<SLUG> BC-AMWEST-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FAA WAIVES AMWEST'S RE MAINING $2.5 MILLION FINE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By PETER CORBETT  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   A year after America West Airlines was hit with a $2.5 million
fine over maintenance violations, the Federal Aviation
Administration waived the remaining $2.5 million penalty.
</P>
<P>
   The FAA agreed Wednesday to forgive the final fine because the
airline complied with terms of a settlement reached last July,
according to FAA spokeswoman Kirsti Dunn.
</P>
<P>
   The fine was the largest in U.S. aviation history, eclipsing a
$1 million penalty paid by now-defunct Eastern Airlines.
</P>
<P>
   America West management declined to comment on the fine waiver.
</P>
<P>
   Union leaders for America West workers reacted with optimism
about the FAA announcement.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm more than happy that that is behind America West,'' said
Bill McGlashen, union president for the company's flight
attendants. ``It's up to the union and FAA to keep vigilant watch
over the airline.''
</P>
<P>
   The fine and FAA scrutiny of America West were good things in
that they forced the Tempe-based carrier to focus more attention on
maintenance issues, McGlashen said.
</P>
<P>
   America West was tagged with a $5 million civil penalty exactly
a year ago to settle violations of aircraft maintenance and
operations regulations.
</P>
<P>
   The FAA agreed last July to accept $2.5 million and suspend the
remaining $2.5 million if America West complied with the terms of
the settlement over the next 12 months.
</P>
<P>
   Aviation consultant Mike Boyd said America West has rebounded
from the bad publicity it received over the FAA fine.
</P>
<P>
   He called the problems minor technical violations of the FAA's
complex rules and said America West never compromised safety.
</P>
<P>
   FAA regulators saw it much differently. America West ``grossly
mismanaged'' its maintenance and operations, according to FAA
documents obtained last year by ''The Arizona Republic.''
</P>
<P>
   The FAA alleged that America West flew 17 Airbus A-320 aircraft
that were overdue for significant structural inspections. The
agency also said that cargo-hold netting was improperly installed
on passenger and cargo flights, and that an aircraft was returned
to service before mechanics properly repaired an elevator actuator,
which controls the tail flap.
</P>
<P>
   ``The attitude of this carrier's management (is) that safety and
regulatory requirements are secondary to the continued movement of
aircraft within the carrier's route system,'' an FAA inspector
wrote in his report last year.
</P>
<P>
   ``This culture, which permeates the carrier, lends credence to
the employees who conduct the day-to-day operations of the carrier
that it is OK to continue an operation even when there may be a
significant factor that could impede safety. This fact alone could
lead to a significant event resulting in a loss of life or
property.''
</P>
<P>
   America West has never had an accident. But its maintenance has
drawn attention since it laid off 500 mechanics in 1995 and began
outsourcing heavy maintenance to outside contractors.
</P>
<P>
   America West is negotiating with the mechanics union to bring
back some of the heavy maintenance, which would create about 125
jobs for mechanics, according to Pat Porter, a spokesman for the
mechanics union.
</P>
<P>
   The company has hired 71 mechanics since last July, an 18
percent increase, according to America West spokeswoman Patty
Nowack.
</P>
<P>
   America West also shook up its management team in the wake of
the FAA fine. The fallout from the agency's action may have been
the beginning of the end for Richard Goodmanson, America West
president and chief executive officer. He resigned in April.
</P>
<P>
   At the time, Goodmanson disputed the FAA conclusions about
America West and said the agency's reports were written by
``apparently junior FAA investigators.''
</P>
<P>
   He also complained that the FAA was being picky and compared it
to a police officer citing a motorist for having a taillight out.
</P>
<P>
   After the FAA fine and continued poor operations over the
summer, Goodmanson fell out of the limelight and virtually
disappeared during the company's contract negotiations with flight
attendants, which averted a threatened strike in March.
</P>
<P>
   America West Chairman William Franke returned as the airline's
president and CEO under the management reorganization announced in
April.
</P>
<P>
   Gilbert Mook, a former top operations executive for Federal
Express Corp., was hired as executive vice president and chief
operating officer to help improve the carrier's day-to-day
operations.
</P>
<P>
   The management changes made since the fine a year ago are
encouraging, according to Donald Steinman, chairman of the Air Line
Pilots Association unit at America West.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think these are steps in the right direction,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   McGlashen agreed and said he would like to see the company move
forward on bringing back more of the outsourced heavy maintenance.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll keep watch from our end over safety-type issues,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   As a part of that, McGlashen said that the Association of Flight
Attendants is lobbying for a whistle-blower protection measure in
Congress for aviation workers.
</P>
<P>
   ``America West and the industry need that because it creates
another level of safety,'' he said. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
