A0636 &Cx1f; tta-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HEALTH-CARE-1STLD-WRI     07-15 1357
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HEALTH-CARE-1STLD-WRITETHRU-ART-(TRIMS)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SENATE REPUBLICANS FLEX THEIR MUSCLE IN SHAPING BILL ON MANAGED
CARE
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Eds: REVISIONS, ADDITIONS throughout.)  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(sw) 
 By ALISON MITCHELL   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Republicans Wednesday showed that they were calling
the shots in the Senate's managed care debate, approving their own
measure on hospitalization for women undergoing mastectomies and
turning back three efforts by Democrats to strengthen the rights of
patients.
</P>
<P>
   In votes almost completely along party lines, the Republicans
defeated the Democrats' second attempt in two days to broaden the
bill to apply to all 161 million Americans with private health
insurance. The Senate also killed a measure to ensure patients'
access to specialists, and it blocked the Democrats' attempt to
require health plans to cover the costs of clinical trials and
drugs. The Democrats argued that clinical trials once paid for by
health insurance are being curtailed because managed-care plans
were no longer paying for the routine patient costs.
</P>
<P>
   The Republican unity presented a sharp contrast to the party's
disarray on gun control earlier this spring, when the majority
party proved powerless to stop Democratic measures. But on the
health care issues, the Republican leaders held their members in
line by making sure that they had put forward their own proposals
on the most emotional issues in the debate, over how to regulate
the managed care companies. That would give Republicans votes they
could point to on matter that the Democrats might raise as campaign
issues next year.
</P>
<P>
   So a day after defeating a broader Democratic amendment on
women's health measures, the Republicans passed, 55 -45, their own
measure to prevent insurance companies from forcing women to have
mastectomies as outpatients.
</P>
<P>
   And the Republicans Wednesday introduced a multipart measure to
guarantee patients emergency room care, as well as access to
specialists and to obstetricians and gynecologists. The action came
after they defeated broader Democratic versions of the same
provisions that would have covered far more people.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're going to come up with a good bill,'' said Sen. Bill
Frist, R-Tenn., attributing the Republicans' success to their
willingness to revisit some issues after defeating Democratic
amendments on those matters. ``It's working,'' he said, ``that's
why we're getting people to stick together.''
</P>
<P>
   The Democrats charged that the Republicans were simply seeking
political protection. Sen. Tom Daschle, the minority leader, said:
``Yesterday they voted wrong. Today they saw what they did, and I
guarantee you they're going to come back today and try to cover
themselves.''
</P>
<P>
   The Senate is pushing to pass a final bill on Thursday night,
but appeared to be on a collision course with President Clinton.
Clinton's aides have said they will recommend that he veto the bill
if the Republican version passes.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no room for compromise between an absolute sham and a
real Patients' Bill of Rights,'' the secretary of Health and Human
Services, Donna Shalala, said in an appearance on Capitol Hill.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats, who had forced the Senate to consider the issue of
regulating managed care, stepped up their efforts to show how their
version of the legislation known as the Patients' Bill of Rights
differed from the rival Republican plan. And they drew support from
various doctors' groups.
</P>
<P>
   The American College of Obstetricians and Gynecologists came out
in opposition to the Republican version of a plan to give women
direct access to obstetricians. It said the Republican amendment
would give direct access in cases of a routine visit but weaken
access to follow-up care.
</P>
<P>
   And the president of the American Medical Association, Dr.
Thomas R. Reardon, appeared at a news conference with a handful of
House Republicans who are doctors and dentists to condemn the
Senate vote on Tuesday night against a Democratic plan to give
doctors, not insurance companies, the say over what treatment is
medically necessary.
</P>
<P>
   Shouting at times on the Senate floor, Sen. Edward M. Kennedy,
D-Mass., said that many of the Republicans' protections were
extended only to the 48 million people who have their insurance
through large companies with self-financed plans. Such plans fall
solely under federal and not state regulation, and are often
older-style fee-for-service plans.
</P>
<P>
   ``These reforms are supposed to protect patients against HMOs
and insurance companies,'' Kennedy said. ``But people with
insurance coverage with HMOs are not covered by the Republican
bill.''
</P>
<P>
   At one point Sen. Charles Schumer, D-N.Y., asked Kennedy how
many New Yorkers would be covered by the Republican bill. ``Four
out of five of the citizens of New York will not be covered under
the Republican program,'' Kennedy replied.
</P>
<P>
   Schumer said: ``That means four out of five would not get
emergency room coverage. Four out of five would not get the right
to specialists. Four out of five would not get the right to sue.''
</P>
<P>
   The Republicans countered that the states were better suited to
regulate insurance companies, not the federal government. ``This is
about arrogance,'' said Sen. Rick Santorum, R-Pa. ``It's about
people thinking we'll decide. We here in Washington think we're
enlightened and know what's best for you.''
</P>
<P>
   By a vote of 52-48 the Senate defeated the Democrats' effort to
broaden the Republican bill to cover all Americans with private
health insurance.
</P>
<P>
   During the debate, Kennedy became so impassioned that Sen. Don
Nickles, the Oklahoman who is the majority whip, said he feared
that Kennedy would have a heart attack and need to call in Frist,
the only doctor who is a member of the Senate. Kennedy shot back,
``We couldn't get Dr. Frist under the access-to-specialists
provisions of the Republican bill.''
</P>
<P>
   In one case Wednesday, that of mastectomies, the Republicans did
agree to extend their bill's protection to all those with private
insurance.
</P>
<P>
   Just a day after voting down a Democratic amendment that would
have given women an array of protections, the Senate turned around
and by a straight party-line vote of 55 -45 approved a provision by
Sen. Olympia Snowe, R- Maine , that would give all women who
undergo a mastectomy the right to stay in the hospital as long as a
doctor considered it medically necessary. ``Leave it to the doctor
and the patient,'' Ms. Snowe said. ``That's what we're asking to do
with patients who have breast cancer.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Snowe's measure also required insurance companies to pay for
a secondary consultation for cancer. But it stopped short of the
assurances that were in the Democrats' provision to give a woman
the right to select an obstetrician-gynecologist as her primary
doctor.
</P>
<P>
   Women's health issues have been a major issue in the debate on
HMO care, as was demonstrated by the passage of the Federal
Newborns' and Mothers' Health Protection Act of 1996, which
requires a minimum hospital stay of 48 hours after a normal vaginal
birth and 96 hours after a Caesarean section, unless the mother and
doctor agree to an earlier discharge. Mastectomies have become an
issue because it has not been rare for women to be discharged
immediately after a procedure. In addition, many women are not
allowed to use obstetrician-gynocologists as their primary care
physician in an HMO, though many states have passed laws allowing
them to do so.
</P>
<P>
   But late in the day, the Republicans introduced a multipart
amendment that would ensure patients access to emergency rooms
outside of an HMO hospital network, allow but not require a health
plan to consider an obstetrician-gynecologist a primary care giver
and give patients more assured access to specialists. In all cases
these protections would apply to 48 million people, not the 161
million the Democrats would cover.
</P>
<P>
   Shortly thereafter, the Republicans voted down the Democrats'
provision on access to specialists.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
