r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LA-GAMEWORKS-LADN     07-15 0963
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LA-GAMEWORKS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GAMEWORKS FLAGSHIP MAY ANCHOR IN L.A.'S VALLEY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
BY DAVE MCNARY  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Sega GameWorks, the ambitious chain of nearly two
dozen arcade-nightclubs backed by Steven Spielberg, is actively
considering building its prime site in the San Fernando Valley.
</P>
<P>
   ``We would definitely like to have a flagship site in a place
like Sherman Oaks or West Los Angeles,'' Bruce Fabel, chief
operating officer at the 3-year-old venture, said during a recent
interview. ``We are actively looking for real estate.''
</P>
<P>
   The executive's comment indicates GameWorks is likely to take a
long look at the legendary Sherman Oaks Galleria, which would give
GameWorks high visibility at a well-known location. It could take
at least a year for such a site to open at the mall, about five
miles to the east of GameWorks headquarters on the Universal
Studios lot.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's nothing solid yet in terms of real estate decisions,''
GameWorks spokeswoman Melissa Schumer said Wednesday. ``At this
point, we see Sherman Oaks and West Los Angeles as viable areas.''
</P>
<P>
   The mall, made famous through Frank and Moon Unit Zappa's song
``Valley Girl'' and its use in the film ``Fast Times at Ridgemont
High,'' has been mostly vacant for several months due to extensive
remodeling in its interior. Galleria owner Douglas Emmett &AMP; Co. has
said it expects the revamping to be finished around October 2000.
</P>
<P>
   Such a decision by GameWorks _ a joint project of Universal
Studios, Sega and Spielberg's DreamWorks SKG _ would underscore its
commitment to stick with the still-evolving concept of
location-based entertainment. The basic idea is to lure
free-spending adults to a high-tech combination of a three-ring
circus of interactive games, food, flashing lights and computer
hardware.
</P>
<P>
   The original concept, launched in Seattle in March 1997, was
designed to attract teen-agers and young adults who wanted more
than video games and would pay for ``play cards'' that could be
used throughout the multilevel facility. The idea was to attract
kids during the day and adults at night and the first locations
were designed to blend the casual feel of a Hollywood studio back
lot with an array of casual-eating options and hundreds of video
games.
</P>
<P>
   The signature attractions at GameWorks include a half-dozen
Zones, such as the Racing Zone, the Carnival Zone and Sports Zone
with one-of-a-kind games such as Two Minute Drill, Wave Runner,
Extreme Powerboat and the Spielberg-designed Vertical Reality game
in which players strap on harnesses and raise and lower themselves
along a 24-foot-high wall in a race against the clock to rid a
skyscraper of criminals.
</P>
<P>
   The idea was to serve as an anchor at a retail center and a lure
for free-spending young adults as a hangout. GameWorks has remained
on the outskirts of the action in Southern California's suburbs
thus far, opening outlets in Irvine, Ontario and Orange.
</P>
<P>
   GameWorks is pushing ahead despite competition from the Dave and
Buster's restaurant chain for adults and Walt Disney Co.'s
DisneyQuest interactive play parks, now open in Chicago and
Orlando, Fla. It will open at least three more GameWorks facilities
next year and will expand the Irvine location from its GameWorks
Studio format to a full-size site.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts give mixed grades so far to the GameWorks concept,
which also has opened in Detroit; Miami; Tempe, Ariz.; Las Vegas;
Fort Lauderdale, Fla.; Chicago; Guam and Grapevine, Texas. Their
major criticism is that the sites are unlikely to attract more
customers than teen-age boys and young adult males.
</P>
<P>
   ``They've got to shift their appeal to something that's more
attractive to other demographics,'' said entertainment analyst
Kevin Skislock of Laguna Research Partners. ``The family
demographic is not going be attracted by multilevel bars. GameWorks
had a very clear goal originally to attract a family-oriented
demographic by re-creating the Hollywood back lot experience in an
enclosed retail environment but it wasn't executed effectively.''
</P>
<P>
   Theme park consultant Dennis Speigel said Spielberg's name
elevates the concept, but he added that insiders haven't been
overly impressed so far with the locations.
</P>
<P>
   GameWorks says more than 15 million people have attended its
dozen full-size sites, most of which occupy more than 30,000 square
feet and its 10 smaller GameWorks Studio sites. It also has been
fine-tuning the concept with the more recent locations by shifting
its appeal more toward adults, particularly females, rather than
teen-age boys, according to Fabel.
</P>
<P>
   ``About 18 months ago, we did a tremendous amount of exit
surveys and guest research and what we found was that adults were
looking for places to go after hours,'' said Fabel. ``We've been
focusing on softening the design to cater towards women so it no
longer has a technical hard feel, but more of a Hollywood feel.''
</P>
<P>
   That's meant adding bar areas on both levels, making the play
Zones more distinct and offering a sit-down grill-style restaurant
much like Houston's or The Cheesecake Factory, Fabel said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The restaurants are not just selling just onion rings and
fries,'' he added. ``We're now offering things like linguine with
shrimp sauce.''
</P>
<P>
   There will continue to be variety from site to site since
GameWorks wants each location to complement the surrounding area.
</P>
<P>
   ``We always try to make concept fit the location,'' Fabel said.
``We're definitely hitting targets as being hometown entertainment
choice in terms of competing with the megaplex and major
restaurants. We're not trying to be a tourist attraction but a
place where locals feel comfortable with coming in once a week.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
