<HEADER>
A0645 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKW-NBA-ALL-STARS-ART     07-15 0708
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKW-NBA-ALL-STARS-ART-1STLD-WRITE-THRU-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AN ALL-DEFENSE, ALL-STAR GAME, ALL FOR THE FANS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Eds: REORGANIZES; ADDS details, quotes)  (ART ADV: A photo is being sent. Non-subscribers can make
individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
(rk) 
 By JERRY BREWER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The first WNBA All-Star game Wednesday night was not
a contest that gave you so many great plays that your eyes wanted
to pop out. It was just hard basketball, lots of fun and too much
defense. But it satisfied the Madison Square Garden sellout crowd
of 18,649, including many youngsters who took part in the
festivities.
</P>
<P>
   The Western Conference All-Stars _ who had the more marquee
players _ held off a surging Eastern Conference team, went on one
final spurt and won, 79-61.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought it was a wonderful game, especially since we won,''
West coach Van Chancellor said. ``Our defense was 300 percent
better than I ever dreamed it would be in an all-star game. We were
switching on screens. We looked like we had been working on defense
for a long time.''
</P>
<P>
   True to the vibe of the league, none of the stars shined too
much. They just blended together, showing their skills when they
got the chance but not forcing it. The game's most valuable player,
Lisa Leslie of the Los Angeles Sparks, had 13 points. Utah Starzz
forward Natalie Williams led all scorers with 14 points, eight of
those coming from the foul line. Every player scored.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really feel honored to have won this award,'' Leslie said.
``A few players could have received this award, and they chose
me.''
</P>
<P>
   From the start, the players seemed more concerned with whether
the fans, especially the children, were enjoying the game.
Throughout the game, children were integrated into the festivities.
And even if the play was not stellar, the screaming youths made the
game worthwhile to the players.
</P>
<P>
   Liberty players Vickie Johnson, Kym Hampton and Teresa
Weatherspoon scored eight , five and three points, respectively.
</P>
<P>
   Heralded rookie Chamique Holdsclaw of the Washington Mystics
left the game midway through the second half with a chip fracture
of her left index finger. Holdsclaw, who had five points, sustained
the injury in the first half while trying to prevent Michele Timms
from stealing a pass from Weatherspoon.
</P>
<P>
   ``The ball just hit me dead on, on the tip of my finger,''
Holdsclaw said. ``Yeah, it hurts, but I took four painkillers so
it's a little better. The initial prognosis is three weeks to heal,
but I think I'll be playing this Saturday.''
</P>
<P>
   From that start, the crowd was teeming with energy and emotion.
Whitney Houston rocked with her rendition of the national anthem.
Celebrities like Tyra Banks, Gregory Hines and Spike Lee, along
with Nets point guard Stephon Marbury and six members of the U.S.
women's soccer team, including Mia Hamm, added to the glamour of
the event.
</P>
<P>
   And the players did their part, too. They raised the roof with
their mock shoulder presses. Some danced a step or two while
waiting to be introduced. But this was more about children's
giddiness than glitz, more about fun than fantasy.
</P>
<P>
   As the starters were introduced, hundreds of children stood at
half court and slapped the hands of the players. Throughout the
timeouts, youngsters dressed as mascots trotted around the court.
The halftime show featured dancing for youths representing their
WNBA teams.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a lot of fun,'' said Houston Comets forward Sheryl
Swoopes, who had eight points. ``I think everyone had a good time.
I think we gave the fans exactly what they wanted to see.''
</P>
<P>
   The basketball was shaky at the start. The East seemingly came
out with jitters and the West jumped out to a 17-2 lead. The East
was able to get back into the game from that point, getting as
close as two, at 31-29, by the four-minute mark.
</P>
<P>
   But the half still had its thrills. Cynthia Cooper went coast to
coast for layups. Swoopes showed her trademark speed, streaking
down the court for easy scores. Weatherspoon threw no-look passes,
but several East players failed to finish.
</P>
<P>
   A dropped pass here, a missed layup there. A few air balls. That
is how it went.
</P>
<P>
   And uncharacteristic defense, too.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
