r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MURDER-SOLVED-LADN     07-15 0855
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MURDER-SOLVED-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FORMER L.A. LAWMAN APPARENTLY TOOK OWN LIFE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
BY LISA VAN PROYEN   AND RICK ORLOV  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ After spending 14 years trying to solve the
killing of Los Angeles County sheriff's Sgt. George Arthur, police
found their prime suspect dead Wednesday in an apparent suicide.
</P>
<P>
   The body of 54-year-old Ted Eugene Kirby was first discovered
Wednesday afternoon by a news reporter and a photographer, a few
blocks away from the Spokane, Wash., home where Kirby moved in 1996
shortly after his retirement from the Los Angeles County Sheriff's
Department.
</P>
<P>
   He was up against a rock outcropping in a pasture, said Deputy
David Reagan, a spokesman for the Spokane County Sheriff's Office.
</P>
<P>
   The body was partially decomposed, indicating Kirby apparently
shot himself to death after learning he was a suspect in the Arthur
killing.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's kind of disappointing,'' said Detective Dennis Kilcoyne
of the Los Angeles Police Department's Robbery-Homicide Division.
``There are some aspects of this investigation that will now never
be answered.''
</P>
<P>
   Kirby used to work with Arthur at the Men's Central Jail in Los
Angeles, and police said he apparently waited in Arthur's van on
the night of June 1, 1985, before the 14-year sheriff's veteran
left work for his Rancho Cucamonga home.
</P>
<P>
   Though police did not provide specifics on the motive for the
fatal shooting, Kilcoyne said it apparently involved a dispute over
a woman. Kirby was divorced at the time and Arthur, 37, was
separated from his wife, Linda Arthur, then a member of the latent
prints section of the Sheriff's Department's crime lab.
</P>
<P>
   ``There appeared to be a misunderstanding on Kirby's part about
this, but everyone involved at the time was young and single and
living on their own,'' Kilcoyne said.
</P>
<P>
   Minutes after taking off in his van, Arthur was shot several
times, causing the vehicle to crash on a concrete divider on the
Mission Road on-ramp to the eastbound San Bernardino Freeway in
Boyle Heights, Kilcoyne said.
</P>
<P>
   Witnesses saw a man crawl from the wreckage and flee.
</P>
<P>
   CHP officials initially thought Arthur died from traffic
collision injuries. It was not until 27 hours later that the
Coroner's Office found Arthur had been shot to death.
</P>
<P>
   Investigators could not find the suspect, and in the past 14
years, the case was reopened at least twice. The story was even
televised on ``America's Most Wanted.''
</P>
<P>
   But Kirby's name did not come up in the case until about three
weeks ago, Kilcoyne said.
</P>
<P>
   Kilcoyne and sheriff's homicide Detective Mike Bumcrot were
assigned to a team looking at older cases.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's something about having fresh eyes look at a case,''
said LAPD Deputy Chief Martin Pomeroy.
</P>
<P>
   Kilcoyne said he and Bumcrot went through nine boxes of
materials and evidence as part of the investigation.
</P>
<P>
   ``We focused on a different direction than prior detectives and
got lucky,'' Kilcoyne said. ``We interviewed people who were close
to Sgt. Arthur and names popped up. We focused on a group that had
closer relations with these guys.''
</P>
<P>
   Kilcoyne added there was no indication that Arthur and Kirby had
been friends.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was no indication that Sgt. Arthur did anything to cause
this to happen,'' Kilcoyne said. ``It appeared Mr. Kirby had been
given some wrong information.''
</P>
<P>
   Authorities had seen Kirby alive the last week of June, when
they got a court order to take a sample of his saliva to test for
DNA. That sample matched evidence at the crime scene 14 years ago,
police said.
</P>
<P>
   But when police returned with an arrest warrant in hand to
Kirby's home July 7, he had vanished.
</P>
<P>
   Soon after police left with the sample, Kirby walked away from
his home armed with a handgun and was described by his wife as
being ``depressed and emotional,'' police said.
</P>
<P>
   On top of the police closing in on him, Kirby also been
terminated June 28 from his job as a bag handler for Horizon Air at
Spokane International Airport, where he was employed part time
since August 1997, said Cheryl Temple, a Horizon spokeswoman.
</P>
<P>
   By the time police left his home, suspicions were high that he
was the wanted man, police said.
</P>
<P>
   ``A red flag went up immediately,'' Kilcoyne said of Kirby's
reaction to the news that detectives were reopening the case and
wanted a saliva sample.
</P>
<P>
   By Tuesday, police had launched a nationwide manhunt.
</P>
<P>
   But in the end, it was an NBC-affiliate news crew who discovered
Kirby dead, Reagan said.
</P>
<P>
   Tom McDonald, a photographer, and Gary Darigol, a reporter, had
heard that Kirby had gone into neighboring woods near his home.
</P>
<P>
   ``So they said, Let's just go back there and check it out,''
Troy McGuire, KHQ-TV's executive producer in Spokane said
Wednesday. ``We weren't expecting that. We were just out looking
around. ... Police said that they were not going out there until a
day later.''
</P>
<P>
   Los Angeles police officials received word of Kirby's death as
Chief Bernard C. Parks was holding his monthly media briefing at
Parker Center.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
