<SLUG> BC-EDIT-VALUJET-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: WHEN A CRASH CAN BE A CRIME 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial on Thursday, July 15:
</P>
<P>
   The filing of state charges of third-degree murder and
manslaughter against the aircraft maintenance company Sabretech for
110 deaths in the 1996 ValuJet crash is highly unusual, and
probably not appropriate in most plane crash cases. Criminal
prosecutions in this context may deter airlines and maintenance
crews from fully cooperating in future accident investigations. But
if there is clear evidence that the accident was caused by gross
negligence that rises to criminal conduct, prosecution may be
justified.
</P>
<P>
   The National Transportation Safety Board found that the ValuJet
crash was probably caused by Sabretech's failure to properly secure
and label oxygen generators that caused a fire in the cargo hold.
But the NTSB also blamed ValuJet and the Federal Aviation
Administration for inadequate oversight.
</P>
<P>
   The Florida prosecutors have singled out Sabretech, concluding
that the actions of the other parties did not rise to criminal
culpability. Sabretech is charged with violating state law in
transporting the generators that caught fire. The felony murder
charges rest on the fact that the deaths were directly caused by
the illegal transportation of hazardous material. The manslaughter
counts are based on criminal negligence. Neither felony murder nor
manslaughter under Florida law requires proof of intent to kill. No
employee or officer of Sabretech, whose assets have been sold, was
charged with the deaths.
</P>
<P>
   But three individuals have been indicted by federal prosecutors
for conspiracy to make false statements to the FAA, falsifying
records about the generators and violating federal regulations on
the handling of dangerous materials. They would be subject to fines
and prison sentences if found guilty of those Federal charges.
</P>
<P>
   The state prosecutors evidently believe they can prove the
deaths were due to criminal conduct, not merely mistakes that can
lead to tragic results. They face a heavy burden of proof, but in
instances where there may be criminal negligence that costs lives,
prosecutors should bring the case to court.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
