<SLUG> BC-WNBA-HOLSCLAW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AN INJURED HOLDSCLAW HAS TO SIT
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 By JERRY BREWER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Chamique Holdsclaw, whose shoulders have been chosen
to carry the future of women's professional basketball, sat on the
bench for most of the second half of Wednesday night's inaugural
WNB A All-Star game. She was the victim of the game's only injury.
</P>
<P>
   Holdsclaw, who finished with five points in 11 minutes, left the
game with a chip fracture of her left index finger. She suffered
the injury early in the game while trying to stop Michele Timms
from stealing a pass. Holdsclaw said the finger was not expected to
fully heal for three weeks, but she hoped to play on Saturday when
her Washington Mystics face the Charlotte Sting.
</P>
<P>
   ``The ball just hit me dead on, on the tip of my finger,'' said
Holdsclaw, whose East team lost to the West, 79-61, at Madison
Square Garden. ``Yeah, it hurts, but I took four pain-killers, so
it's a little better.''
</P>
<P>
   The injury spoiled an all-star homecoming for the Queens native,
who starred at Christ the King High School before attending the
University of Tennessee. Holdsclaw said before the game that she
did not need the game to validate her superstar potential. But she
was disappointed that she got injured.
</P>
<P>
   ``You want to compete, you want to have fun, you want your team
to win,'' Holdsclaw said. ``I got hurt, my team lost, so I'm a
little upset.''
</P>
<P>
   Holdsclaw, whose 18.7 points per game are fourth in the WNBA,
shied away this week from directly responding to criticism that she
is getting too much publicity. Sheryl Swoopes of the Houston Comets
recently said that she thought Holdsclaw's hype was overshadowing
some of the league's other stars.
</P>
<P>
   ``She is one of the finest players in the game,'' the Eastern
Conference coach, Linda Hill-MacDonald of the Cleveland Rockers,
said about Holdsclaw. ``I think she has lived up to everything she
has been billed to be.''
</P>
<P>
   But to prove that point emphatically, Holdsclaw will have to
wait.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-15-99 0030EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
