<DOCNO> NYT19990715.0012 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-15 00:39 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0656 &Cx1f; tth-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-JUICE-UNPASTEURIZED-S     07-15 0738
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JUICE-UNPASTEURIZED-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MOTHER OF SICK YOUNGSTER ASKS COUNTY TO BAN SALE OF UNPASTEURIZED
JUICES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By NEIL MODIE  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ Because of her mom, 2-year-old Abigail Merritt's six
days of misery may help other children avoid her fate: being
poisoned by packaged unpasteurized fruit juice.
</P>
<P>
   Regulatory wheels are grinding because the tot, her sister
Isabella, 4, and their mother, Karen Wolf, shared a fruit
``smoothie'' made with contaminated orange juice.
</P>
<P>
   They slurped it at a World Wrapps restaurant in Seattle on June
18. A few days later, Abigail developed severe diarrhea _ becoming
one of least 36 local cases of salmonella poisoning traced to Sun
Orchard orange juice. With medical care, the youngster recovered
from the potentially fatal illness after nearly a week of pain,
lack of appetite and listlessness.
</P>
<P>
   The day Abigail recovered, Wolf got busy. A senior policy
analyst for King County, she e-mailed her boss, County Executive
Ron Sims, and Dr. Alonzo Plough, the Seattle-King County health
director, urging them to ask the county Board of Health to ban the
sale of unpasteurized, commercially prepared fruit juice in the
county.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday Sims said he will do just that when the board meets
Friday.
</P>
<P>
   If the board agrees, King County may be the nation's first state
or local government to impose such a ban, health officials said.
</P>
<P>
   In her e-mail, Wolf, a vegetarian and avid natural-foods
consumer, wrote: ``I know people will be upset that they can't get
`fresh-squeezed' orange juice, but if they saw how sick my little
girl was, I think they would reconsider their opposition.''
</P>
<P>
   Sims said he prefers a ban, but might consider a warning label
on commercially produced, unpasteurized fruit juices that would be
stricter than now required by the U.S. Food and Drug
Administration.
</P>
<P>
   He said the action is justified because last month's salmonella
epidemic was the second local food poisoning outbreak in three
years involving unpasteurized, prepackaged fruit juice. An outbreak
of E. coli poisoning in 1996 was traced to Odwalla apple juice.
</P>
<P>
   The latest scare may make unpasteurized juice harder to find in
stores and restaurants.
</P>
<P>
   Brad Pettinger, vice president of World Wrapps Northwest, said
his company stopped using unpasteurized juice the day it learned
some of the salmonella cases had been traced to its outlets.
</P>
<P>
   He said World Wrapps now uses only pasteurized products, and its
supplier no longer carries unpasteurized orange juice.
</P>
<P>
   Of Sims' proposed ban, Pettinger said, ``If that's going to
ensure the food safety for all of us, I think it's a great idea.''
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Jeffrey Duchin, the health department's director of
communicable disease control and epidemiology, said consumers don't
always know if the juice they buy is unpasteurized.
</P>
<P>
   The FDA requires commercially produced, unpasteurized fruit
juices to be labeled as such. But it has granted a temporary
exemption to the labeling requirement for citrus juice producers
who achieve a 100,000-fold reduction in pathogens using alternative
technologies instead of pasteurization.
</P>
<P>
   ``The big bugaboo with fresh-squeezed juice is that the
establishment selling the juice doesn't know for sure whether the
juice has been pasteurized or not unless it's been labeled, so the
consumer is really in the dark,'' Duchin said.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of restaurants that advertise `fresh-squeezed' orange
juice may not be the ones that squeezed it,'' Duchin said. ``It may
have been `fresh-squeezed' a thousand miles away a couple of days
ago.''
</P>
<P>
   In the current salmonella outbreak, health authorities have
identified more than 200 cases in 14 states and two Canadian
provinces. Duchin said nearly all the cases have been traced to
unpasteurized orange juice from Sun Orchards, Inc.
</P>
<P>
   The Tempe, Ariz., company has recalled all of its
non-pasteurized orange juice, which was sold to hundreds of
restaurants, including World Wrapps. A class-action lawsuit seeking
unspecified damages from Sun Orchards has been filed in King County
Superior Court.
</P>
<P>
   Requests to Sun Orchards for comment went unanswered Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Wolf said Wednesday she's gratified that some good might come of
the pain her daughter suffered.
</P>
<P>
   ``As I told my husband, I wanted to focus my energies on getting
legislation through,'' she said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
