<HEADLINE>
STARS TO OPEN AGAINST PENGUINS ON OCT. 1
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MIKE HEIKA 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Stars will share the spotlight with Wayne Gretzky on opening
night next season, NHL officials announced yesterday.
</P>
<P>
   The Stars plan to raise their Stanley Cup banner on Oct. 1 at
Reunion Arena before a national television audience on ESPN, when
they play host to the Pittsburgh Penguins and Jaromir Jagr in a
6:30 p.m. game. The only other game scheduled opening night is the
Edmonton Oilers at the New York Rangers in which Wayne Gretzky will
be officially honored for his retirement after 20 years in the
league.
</P>
<P>
   The start of the NHL season has been moved ahead one week to
help the playoffs begin earlier. The league also has added the
Atlanta Thrashers to the schedule. That means the Stars will play
only once against the Penguins, Buffalo Sabres, Boston Bruins,
Montreal Canadiens, Ottawa Senators, and Toronto Maple Leafs to
accommodate the expansion team and an adjusted schedule that offers
extra games against the Chicago Blackhawks and Calgary Flames.
</P>
<P>
   The Stars are scheduled to play 24 games against their Pacific
Division rivals _ six apiece against the Los Angeles Kings, Phoenix
Coyotes, Anaheim Mighty Ducks and San Jose Sharks. They will play
34 games against the other Western Conference teams (four apiece,
except five against Flames and Blackhawks). And they will play 24
times against Eastern Conference teams, twice against nine teams
and once against six others.
</P>
<P>
   The Stars are scheduled to play on New Year's Eve at home and
have a day game scheduled the day after Thanksgiving (Nov. 26 vs.
the Mighty Ducks). They will play eight day games and have 21 of
their home dates scheduled for Fridays, Saturdays or Sundays.
</P>
<P>
   The Stars will play eight of their first 13 games at home and
five of their final seven on the road. In between, their longest
scheduled home stand is six games from Dec. 29 to Jan. 7 and their
longest road trip will be Jan. 11 to Jan. 23.
</P>
<P>
   The Stars should have a stout preseason schedule, getting two
games apiece against the Detroit Red Wings, Colorado Avalanche, St.
Louis Blues and the Blackhawks and one game against the Coyotes.
The Red Wings, Avalanche and Blues each made it to the Western
Conference semifinals.  &LR; subheds:Marshall to file Pat Morris, the
agent for Stars winger Grant Marshall, said Marshall will file for
arbitration rights today. However, Morris said that does not mean
he and the Stars will stop negotiating.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is just one step, one option,'' Morris said. ``You can
sign a deal even during arbitration.''
</P>
<P>
   Marshall, who made $400,000 last season, is hoping for a big
raise after posting career highs of 13 goals and 31 points. Today
is the last day for free agents who have arbitration rights to file
for arbitration. Cases will be scheduled for later in the summer.
</P>
<P>
   Stars defenseman Richard Matvichuk, who also can file for
arbitration, is not expected to exercise his right. Because
Matvichuk had only 12 points during the 1998-99 season, he has
little ammunition for getting a good arbitration settlement. If
Matvichuk and the Stars cannot come to terms on a new contract,
Matvichuk's best strategy is a holdout. \Ntagtop:Mike Heika, (817)
390-7760
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
