<SLUG> BC-BKW-RHODEN-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: A LEAGUE IN SEARCH OF A MOMENT
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 By WILLIAM C. RHODEN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ At midday Wednesday Angela Alfaro was on 33rd Street,
outside Madison Square Garden, contemplating an imposing 7-foot
rim. This was at the Slam Dunk exhibit, one of 12 set up by the
WNBA as a prelude to its inaugural All-Star game Wednesday night,
won by the West, 79-61.
</P>
<P>
   There was a 3-point arc. A consecutive foul-shot challenge. An
obstacle course. But the slam dunk booth, with baskets ranging in
height from 7 to 9 feet, drew the most persistent attention. This
was an intense laboratory of bravado and experimentation. While
male counterparts attempted dunks at a 9-foot rim _ mostly without
success _ the 15-year-old Alfaro readied herself, steadied herself,
measured her steps. Run. Lift. Bam! A dunk.
</P>
<P>
   Could she do it again? Of course. Alfaro measured her steps,
sprinted, rose: Bam.
</P>
<P>
   Jason Katz, who works in the NBA's marketing office, worked the
7-foot basket all day and made his own observations about the
culture of dunking. ``During the course of the day, I sort of
tempted the girls to try,'' Katz said. ``At first they were
tentative. A lot of them wouldn't even try, they just took shots.
After they tried it, they got into it.''
</P>
<P>
   Anastasia Chin, of average height for an 11-year-old, walked
over to the 7-foot rim and measured her steps. Deep breath, run,
rise. Oops. Try again. And again. On her fifth attempt, Anastasia
finally dunked one. She raised her arms in triumph and slapped
palms with her teammates on the 13-and-under New York Angels. ``I'd
like to see more women dunk,'' she said. ``The dunk would turn up
the game a little more, put more excitement in the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``I get tired of people saying what we can't do. Like in soccer,
they said women can't do this, women can't do that. Women proved
that they can do anything if they put their minds to it.''
</P>
<P>
   Nobody has dunked during a WNBA game, and nobody dunked
Wednesday night, either, although Lisa Leslie, the West's
6-foot-5-inch center, dunked during warm-ups. But the moment was
lost in the midst of all the excitement. ``I was surprised nobody
noticed,'' Leslie said. ``Everybody's been asking me to dunk. When
I do it, nobody notices.''
</P>
<P>
   On a fast break during the game, Leslie threw the last pass to
Yolanda Griffith for the basket. ``If Yolanda and I would have
switched places on the break, I could have dunked it,'' Leslie
said.
</P>
<P>
   As women's basketball fights for a toehold in the United States,
some players still react defensively to any suggestion that the
women's game is lacking simply because they do not dunk. ``Men rely
more on their physical talents, women rely more on the technical
game,'' Cynthia Cooper of the Houston Comets, the league's two-time
most valuable player, said Wednesday. ``But it's still
basketball.''
</P>
<P>
   Players and officials in the women's game too often dismiss the
dunk as ``a man's thing,'' the way critics once dismissed it as ``a
black thing.'' Of course, the dunk is no such thing. The dunk
belongs to no race or gender; it has become an intrinsic part of a
global game.
</P>
<P>
   And believe this: the first woman who consistently ``throws it
down,'' who consistently terrifies the opposition with her ability
to thunder dunk at crucial points of a game, will become the WNBA's
first icon. This might chase away some purists who see the WNBA as
more of a movement than a pro sports league. But they'll be
replaced by hard-core fans, eager to see the game played by women
at its highest level.
</P>
<P>
   All Anastasia Chin knows is that she has seen the dunk and she
wants to dunk, too. As the novelty of a women's pro league wears
off, the WNBA must soar to the next level. Dismissing what one
cannot do argues for limitations, and isn't removing limitations
what the WNBA is supposed to be about?
</P>
<P>
   Last Saturday, I was part of a group riveted by the Women's
World Cup championship game. Finally the moment of truth arrived:
the shootout. Goals had been impossible to come by; now, at
point-blank range, the goals seemingly came as easy as pennies.
</P>
<P>
   Just before the third Chinese kicker made her attempt, the
commentator said something about women goalkeepers lacking the
athleticism of men to make the great play. No sooner had the words
been spoken than Briana Scurry, the U. S. goalkeeper, darted to her
left and used instinct, reflexes and ``athleticism'' to make an
incredible save. That save may have been the defining moment of
women's soccer in the United States. A barrier was scraped away,
one more layer of cannot-do removed.
</P>
<P>
   The women's soccer team found its moment. You get the sense that
the women in the WNBA are still looking for theirs.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
