<SLUG> BC-KYL-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DEMOCRATS PAINT BULL'S EYE ON KYL'S SEN ATE SEAT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By CHRIS MOESER  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   National Democrats have painted a bull's eye on the back of Sen.
Jon Kyl, calling Arizona's junior senator the ``most vulnerable
Republican incumbent'' in the nation next year.
</P>
<P>
   The Democratic Senate Campaign Committee released a poll
Wednesday that shows Kyl with a 39 percent favorable rating,
compared with 42 percent for President Clinton, 65 percent for Gov.
Jane Hull and 67 percent for Sen. John McCain.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans quickly countered that Democrats, desperate for a
candidate, are using the poll to scare up a high-profile challenger
to Kyl, a charge that Democrats don't dispute.
</P>
<P>
   The poll is evidence that the Democratic Party is prepared to
make a serious push for a Senate seat in Arizona, if they can find
the right candidate. That effort would include an infusion of
campaign cash that would be needed to offset Kyl's huge
fund-raising advantage.
</P>
<P>
   The last Democratic U.S. senator from Arizona was Dennis
DeConcini, who retired from political office in 1995 and whose seat
Kyl won.
</P>
<P>
   ``(Kyl) is vulnerable because he's been a non-entity in the
Senate,'' said Jim Jordan, the political director for the group
that coordinates Democratic Senate campaigns from Washington.
Jordan said Democratic polling shows that Kyl's poll numbers are
the worst of any GOP Senate incumbent.
</P>
<P>
   ``The poll confirms what we suspected: that Sen. Kyl has made no
impact in Washington or on his constituents in Arizona,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Kyl was elected to his first term in 1994, the year of the
Republican congressional landslide that enabled the GOP to take
control of both the House and the Senate for the first time in
nearly four decades.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans defended Kyl, saying that the Democratic poll was
biased. State GOP Chairman Mike Minnaugh said Kyl already has
raised $1.4 million, giving the incumbent a daunting lead in the
campaign race.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's very strong,'' Minnaugh said, noting that the
Washington-based Cook Political Report lists Kyl's seat as
``solid.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Unfortunately, he has been in the shadow of Senator (John)
McCain,'' Minnaugh said. ``But Jon's record is solid in
Washington.''
</P>
<P>
   Kyl could not be reached for comment. However, his regional
director for southern Arizona, Hank Kenski, ripped the poll: ``This
is a standard poll that parties conduct when they're trying to come
up with opposition.''
</P>
<P>
   Kenski said his boss's poll numbers are reasonable but could be
better.
</P>
<P>
   Arizona State University pollster Bruce Merrill also disputed
the Democrats' contention that Kyl is in trouble. Merrill's May 27
poll showed Kyl with a 42 percent positive rating and a 20 percent
negative rating.
</P>
<P>
   The Democratic poll of 500 Arizona voters, taken from June 29 to
July 1, found Kyl with a 17 percent negative rating. The poll had a
margin of error of 4.4 percentage points. The survey found that 30
percent of those questioned would vote to re-elect Kyl.
</P>
<P>
   Merrill said the fact that the Democratic poll was conducted by
random dialing, and not necessarily of registered voters, may have
skewed the sample.
</P>
<P>
   ``In terms of running someone against him, I would say he's not
very vulnerable,'' Merrill said. ``It's going to take someone with
a name, someone with a ton of money.''
</P>
<P>
   Democrats still haven't come up with a candidate.
</P>
<P>
   The highest-ranking elected Arizona Democrat, Attorney General
Janet Napolitano, has no interest in the race, a spokeswoman said
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   State Democratic Party Chairman Mark Fleisher says he's trying
to convince Terry Goddard, the former Phoenix mayor and two-time
gubernatorial nominee, to run.
</P>
<P>
   Goddard, who now works for Department of Housing and Urban
Development in Phoenix, declined to comment, citing his federal
job.
</P>
<P>
   Fleisher said he asked others to encourage Hattie Babbitt,
acting director of the Agency for International Development, to
consider the race. Babbitt is the wife of Interior Secretary Bruce
Babbitt, who served as Arizona governor from 1978 to 1987.
</P>
<P>
   ``She does not seem real interested in running,'' Fleisher said.
</P>
<P>
   The most likely Democratic candidate so far appears to be Dan
Salcito, an attorney and rancher who spilts time between Scottsdale
and Skull Valley. Salcito said Wednesday that the Democrats asked
him to run and that he was considering the race. If he runs, he
will spend personal wealth on the campaign, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think Arizonans know who the state's second senator
is,'' Salcito said. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
