<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HIV-DRUG-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW, LESS EXPENSIVE DRUG FOUND TO CUT HIV RISK IN INFANTS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By CAROL SMITH  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ A less expensive drug that prevents transmission of
HIV from infected mothers to their newborns could keep about 1,000
babies a day from being born with the virus that causes AIDS,
according to researchers at the Fred Hutchinson Cancer Research
Center in Seattle.
</P>
<P>
   The drug, nevirapine, is somewhat less effective than AZT, the
drug widely used in the United States to prevent transmission from
mother to child, but costs only $3 per dose compared with $1,000 to
$2,000 for a course of AZT.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, nevirapine is only administered once to the mother
during labor and once to the infant shortly after birth _ while AZT
is part of a long course of prenatal therapy.
</P>
<P>
   The new drug could become a standard of care for HIV-infected
women giving birth in developing countries, preventing spread of
the infection, said Dr. Thomas Fleming, lead statistician for the
study.
</P>
<P>
   ``Until now, we've not been able to meaningfully reduce the risk
(of transmission) in countries where risk is the highest,'' he
said. ``Now we think we have a way.''
</P>
<P>
   Fleming, who is chairman of the Department of Biostatistics at
the University of Washington School of Public Health and Community
Medicine, is also a biostatistician for the Hutchinson Center's
Public Health Sciences Division.
</P>
<P>
   The study, which was conducted in Uganda, was done in
collaboration with researchers at Johns Hopkins University in
Baltimore and Makerere University in Kampala, Uganda.
</P>
<P>
   An estimated 1,800 HIV-infected babies are born each day in
developing countries, Fleming said.
</P>
<P>
   The study results, based on the study of 618 women, are being
heralded as a major public health advance for prevention of HIV
infections in infants.
</P>
<P>
   Health and Human Services Secretary Donna Shahala called the
study results ``extraordinary.''
</P>
<P>
   ``American scientists along with our international partners are
committed to developing treatments that not only work, but that are
also feasible in other health care settings,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   In the United States, most pregnant women with the human
immunodeficiency virus are treated with a course of AZT, a powerful
antiretroviral drug. The treatment reduces transmission by between
70 percent and 80 percent, Fleming said. But the treatment requires
extensive prenatal care, which is not available in many parts of
the world.
</P>
<P>
   In contrast, researchers in Uganda found that giving one oral
dose of nevirapine during labor and one follow-up dose to the
infant within three days of birth, reduced transmission of HIV by
about 50 percent. The treatment costs about $3 for the mother and
11 cents for the infant.
</P>
<P>
   With little treatment available, most HIV-infected infants in
developing countries die within two years.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's devastating,'' Fleming said.
</P>
<P>
   The goal of the study was to find a safe, simple, effective way
to prevent babies from being born with HIV.
</P>
<P>
   An estimated 30 percent of women in the urban areas of
sub-Saharan countries, such as Uganda, are infected with HIV, said
Fleming. The majority of those women receive no treatment for HIV,
and about one-third of infected women pass the virus to their
babies, either in utero or through breast-feeding.
</P>
<P>
   ``This study represents the most promising advance to date
toward the goal of finding strategies that can be used worldwide to
prevent the spread of HIV from HIV-infected mothers to their
infants,'' said Dr. Anthony Fauci, director of the National
Institute of Allergy and Infectious Diseases, which funded the
study.
</P>
<P>
   Glaxo-Wellcome, which manufactures AZT, and Boehringer-Ingelheim
Pharmaceuticals, which manufactures nevirapine, provided drugs for
the study.
</P>
<P>
   Originally, the study was designed to use a placebo control
group, but the placebo was dropped after data showed a shorter
course of AZT also reduced transmission of the virus. The
redesigned study tested nevirapine against a short course of AZT.
</P>
<P>
   ``This research provides real hope that we may be able to
protect many of Africa's next generation from the ravages of
AIDS,'' Crispus Kiyonga, Uganda's Minister of Health, said in an
announcement in Kampala Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   While the study showed the risk of transmission could be cut at
birth, the babies of infected mothers are still at risk of
acquiring the virus through breast-feeding.
</P>
<P>
   More research is under way to determine whether continued doses
of nevirapine through the breast-feeding period can cut the risk of
transmission even more, Fleming said.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, scientists are looking at whether nevirapine should
be added to the AZT treatment currently used in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   In Uganda, women were anxious to participate in the study, said
Lynda Emel, protocol operations coordinator for HIVNET, the
federally funded program based at the Hutchinson Center that helped
coordinate the study. Emel helped set up the study.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most of the mothers who know they're HIV-infected would do
anything possible to prevent transmission to their babies,'' she
said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
