<HEADLINE>
DODGERS' MALONE STILL A BELIEVER
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BRIAN DOHN  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Through the heartache of the first three months of
the season, general manager Kevin Malone had a glimmer of hope that
the Dodgers would turn their season around.
</P>
<P>
   It was dim, but it was there. Malone still talks of a long road
to recovery for the Dodgers, but winning the final four games
before the All-Star break has added brightness.
</P>
<P>
   As the Dodgers open the second half of the season with the first
of three games at Anaheim tonight, they will do so with a tangible
optimism absent the last two months. The Dodgers are looking for
their first five-game winning streak since April 27 to May 1.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're optimistic,'' Malone said. ``We showed signs of what
this team is capable of doing in holding a powerful Seattle team
down. It shows we're capable of beating a good team like that.
We're moving in the right direction.''
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers (39-47) entered the break 10 games behind
front-running San Francisco, but also on a four-game winning
streak. They did it by shutting down a Seattle club that led the
league in homers. The Mariners managed only four runs in the
three-game series.
</P>
<P>
   Manager Davey Johnson is hoping that's the beginning to a better
understanding from the reluctant Dodgers, who haven't exactly
conformed to Johnson's methods.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not easy for a talented group of individuals to accept
maybe a different system,'' Johnson said. ``Sometimes things I do
can be misconstrued in their eyes because a different manager did
it a different way. But I have no hidden agendas. I just want to
win games. I've never won a division or a pennant without a team
effort.''
</P>
<P>
   Osuna return delayed: The Dodgers spoke last week of
right-hander Antonio Osuna returning for today's series opener
against the Angels, but that's changed.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson said even though Osuna remains on schedule (he was to
pitch for Single-A San Bernardino on Wednesday), a more realistic
return date would be after the Dodgers return from Pittsburgh on
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``His velocity was at 92, but it fell back to 88, 89,'' Johnson
said. ``We want to see if he can stay in the 90s.''
</P>
<P>
   There's other reasons the Dodgers aren't eager to activate
Osuna. They don't want to bring him back too soon only to have him
re-aggravate his pitching elbow, from which he had a bone spur
removed in May. Also, the Dodgers bullpen hasn't been a problem. If
he's activated, the Dodgers will have to ship someone out.
</P>
<P>
   F.Y.I.: There was talk a few months back that the Dodgers would
put in a bid to host the 2002 All-Star Game, but they decided not
to waste the time, energy or money to explore the option. Dodgers
president and CEO Bob Graziano said he spoke with officials in the
National League office who told him it would be fruitless to bid on
the game because the new ballparks are in line to host. . . . There
is still no word on possible suspensions for Sunday's brawl in
which Dodgers Todd Hundley, Pedro Borbon and coach Rick Dempsey
were ejected.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
