<SLUG> BC-HOUSE-SPEND-1STLD-WRITETHRU-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOUSE NARROWLY DEFEATS INCREASE IN MONEY FOR ARTS AND HUMANITIES
ENDOWMENTS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Eds: RECASTS with votes, details) (rk) 
 By TIM WEINER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The House on Wednesday night narrowly defeated a
move to increase spending on the National Endowment for the Arts
and the National Endowment for the Humanities, whose budgets have
been cut and then frozen for four years.
</P>
<P>
   The vote came as the House debated after midnight a $14 billion
Interior Department spending bill. The bill passed, 377-47, after
conservatives forced across-the-board spending cuts and froze funds
for endowments of the arts and humanities at $98 million and $110.7
million, respectively.
</P>
<P>
   By a 217-207 vote, the House rejected an amendment to increase
spending on the arts and humanities endowments by $10 million
apiece. Twenty-nine Democrats provided the margin of defeat,
joining 188 Republicans opposing the amendment.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a luxury, let's face it,'' Rep. Cliff Stearns, R-Fla.
said of the federal support for arts and humanities. ``Many of us
question whether it should even exist.''
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Lynn Woolsey, D-Calif., said Congress had declared ``a war
on culture'' ever since Republicans took control of Congress in
1994. ``I'm embarrassed for this House of Representatives,'' she
said.
</P>
<P>
   The bill provides about $7 billion for the Interior Department,
more than $4 billion for the Bureau of Indian Affairs and the
Indian Health Service, $1.4 billion for national parks and about
$580 million for cultural heavyweights like the Smithsonian
Institution and the National Gallery of Art.
</P>
<P>
   The House, which had already cut $1.2 billion from the White
House's budget request for the Interior bill, trimmed $140 million
more on Wednesday at the instigation of the Republicans' staunchest
fiscal conservatives, who want to freeze or cut money for all
federal agencies this year.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. David R. Obey of Wis., the ranking Democrat on the House
Appropriations Committee, denounced them as ``a hard core of
right-wing militants'' who ``detest government'' and are engaging
in political power plays.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not a game,'' the leader of fiscal conservatives, Rep.
Tom Coburn, R-Okla., calmly responded. He has largely succeeded in
his threats to delay or derail all spending bills in the House this
year unless the Republican leadership bowed to his demands for
domestic spending cuts that, to date, total nearly $600 million.
</P>
<P>
   The House also voted, 273-151, for an amendment that would
stymie a controversial Senate measure favoring mining companies.
</P>
<P>
   The issue pits environmentalists against miners. The Senate
wants to overturn a five-acre limit for mine waste sites on federal
land. The House amendment would block funds for processing mining
companies' applications for dumps bigger than five acres.
</P>
<P>
   Proponents of the Senate measure say Interior Department lawyers
enforcing the limit threaten the mining industry. Opponents say the
Senate's bill would allow mining companies to dump thousands of
tons of cyanide-tainted waste freely on public land.
</P>
<P>
   The House also rejected, by voice vote, an amendment blocking
the Forest Service from charging fees to hikers, boaters and others
using national parks and forests. The fees pay for maintenance and
improvements. Opponents call them a tax on a pleasure that once was
free.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
