A0683 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SOLIAH-BAIL-LADN     07-15 0834
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOLIAH-BAIL-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FORMER L.A. LAWMAN APPARENTLY TOOK OWN LIFE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
BY JESSE HIESTAND  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ A Superior Court judge set bail at $1 million
Wednesday for ex-Symbionese Liberation Army member Kathleen Soliah
as prosecutors detailed evidence of her alleged plot to blow up two
Los Angeles police cars 25 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Soliah's three teen-age daughters broke down in tears as she was
led from the courtroom back to jail after bail was set. One cried,
``Bye, Mommy.'' Her husband, Dr. Fred Peterson, an emergency room
physician, sat with the girls in the front row of the courtroom and
visited with Soliah at the noon break.
</P>
<P>
   Eight friends from Minnesota came for the hearing. One, Stephen
Yanisch, said they hope bail will be reduced for the woman who grew
up in the Antelope Valley and has lived in Minneapolis for more
than 20 years as Sara Jane Olson, a suburban wife and mother who
attended church regularly and acted in the local theater.
</P>
<P>
   ``The judge was in a tough situation, so I'm hoping we can get
the bail reduced through appeals,'' Yanisch said. ``For people of
ordinary means, raising $1 million is tough.''
</P>
<P>
   Soliah appeared in court for the first time on 1976 charges
that, the previous year, she helped plant pipe bombs under two Los
Angeles Police Department cars.
</P>
<P>
   Judge Larry Fidler called such a crime ``particularly
abhorrent.'' He said a bomb ``is the terrorist's weapon of choice
and has no discretion,'' often harming innocent bystanders.
</P>
<P>
   But he made it clear during the four-hour hearing that the case
against Soliah is far from strong. ``The evidence in this case is
circumstantial, and that is certainly acceptable, but it's not
overwhelming,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors conceded they only have a circumstantial case
against the 52-year-old Soliah.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not a strong case, but it is not a weak case,'' said
Deputy District Attorney Michael A. Latin.
</P>
<P>
   He said bomb-making materials were found in an apartment Soliah
had been sharing in San Francisco at the time two large pipe bombs
were placed under police cruisers Aug. 21, 1975.
</P>
<P>
   Steel nails packed into the bombs and wiring used to trigger
them were identical to nails and wires found in a closet at the
apartment, Latin said. Investigators also found empty holders for
magnets, manufactured in England, of the same size and make as
those used in the bomb triggers, he said.
</P>
<P>
   He said a bomb found in the closet was very similar to those
under the police cars; one bomb malfunctioned and the other was
found later in an emergency search.
</P>
<P>
   Soliah's fingerprints were on a map of Los Angeles that police
found in the car she and an accomplice allegedly used in the plot,
Latin said.
</P>
<P>
   She was charged in February 1976 with conspiracy to commit
murder and multiple counts of possessing bombs.
</P>
<P>
   But defense attorneys called the case against Soliah ``beyond
weak,'' as one worded it. ``She did not attempt to kill Los Angeles
police officers,'' defense lawyer Stuart Hanlon of San Francisco
said after the hearing. ``She will be acquitted if this goes to
trial.''
</P>
<P>
   Defense attorney Susan Jordan of Oakland said the person who
named Soliah as the prime suspect and who identified the car
allegedly used in a bomb plot was fellow SLA member Patricia
Campbell Hearst.
</P>
<P>
   Hearst, a newspaper heiress who was kidnapped by the group but
later joined it, made those claims immediately after she was
convicted of bank robbery in federal court and began cooperating
with the FBI, said Jordan.
</P>
<P>
   Hearst has never been relied on as a witness in court _ and
won't likely be called in this case _ because of severe credibility
problems, Jordan said.
</P>
<P>
   Court records filed by the defense contend that John Marshall,
the only witness who could directly link Soliah to the bomb plots,
has died.
</P>
<P>
   Soliah is due back in court Tuesday for her attorneys to explain
how bail would be posted and who would monitor compliance with the
judge's order that she wear an electronic monitoring device if
released.
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors wanted Soliah held without bail. Defense attorneys
hoped to get bail set at $250,000, an amount supporters already
have raised.
</P>
<P>
   ``Her life is with her children and her husband and also with
those of us in the community,'' said James M. Johnson, a retired
civil engineer who was among supporters who came from Minnesota to
attend the hearing.
</P>
<P>
   A fellow member of Minnehaha United Methodist Church in
Minneapolis, he said she has been a tireless volunteer teaching
English and citizenship skills to immigrants, working on blood
drives and helping the homeless.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson echoed other witnesses who testified Wednesday that
Soliah would not disappear again if granted bail because she would
never willingly give up her family and friends in Minneapolis.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no way she would run from that,'' he said. ``If she
ran from that, she would have no life.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
