<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-15 01:28 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0684 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKL-ALLSTAR-HNS &LR;      07-15 0893
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKL-ALLSTAR-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By W.H. STICKNEY JR.  
 c. 1999, Houston Chronicle  
NEW YORK _ There was a familiar hue to the first WNBA All-Star Game
on Wednesday night.
<TEXT>
<P>
   There was red-hot sizzling energy flowing throughout the event,
which played to a sellout crowd of 18,649 at Madison Square Garden.
There was equally sizzling entertainment in the pre-game and
halftime ceremonies.
</P>
<P>
   And when the game began, the three players clad in Comets red
who have been so dominant through the league's first two-plus years
_ Sheryl Swoopes, Cynthia Cooper and Tina Thompson _ were at it
once again, staking the Western Conference to an early 14-2 lead
that eventually stood up for a 79-61 victory.
</P>
<P>
   As good as the three Comets All-Star starters were, it was the
dominant inside game of Sacramento's Yolanda Griffith, Utah's
Natalie Williams and All-Star Most Valuable Player Lisa Leslie of
the Los Angeles Sparks, along with some of the defense that has
been the Comets' trademark, that ultimately sent the Eastern
Conference to defeat.
</P>
<P>
   The night was predicted to be one filled with fun and
excitement. In that, there was no disappointment.
</P>
<P>
   Or was there?
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm mad. I'm real mad. No, just kidding,'' said East guard
Teresa Weatherspoon of the New York Liberty. ``It was beautiful.''
</P>
<P>
   As much fun as the players had, however, Comets coach Van
Chancellor, the 54-year-old self-described ``child'' who coached
the West squad, had more.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought this was a wonderful night for women's basketball,''
Chancellor said. ``I got here at 3:45 in the afternoon, son, and
I've been soaking in everything that hatched since that moment. I
had my grandchildren, my children here, my wife, my whole family. I
thought about how lucky I was. This is one of my most special
moments in my life. It's the best moment in coaching I've ever
had.''
</P>
<P>
   It was made that way because Cooper, Swoopes and Thompson made
it look like a typical Comets game early, as the West scored five
of its first seven baskets on the fast break while running off to a
17-2 lead.
</P>
<P>
   And it was made that way because the West held in check Nikki
McCray, Vicky Bullett, Kym Hampton and the rest of the East,
limiting them to 35.1 percent shooting and 36 rebounds.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our defense was about 300 percent better than I ever dreamed
it would be in an All-Star Game,'' said Chancellor. ``I thought it
was good. We were switching on screens. We looked like we had been
working on defense for a long time. That was a lot of fun.''
</P>
<P>
   And fun was the operative theme for the full 40 minutes,
especially in the first five minutes when the West jumped to its
big lead.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yeah,'' said Thompson, ``it did kind of feel like a Comets
game, particularly in those first five minutes.''
</P>
<P>
   Cooper had five of her seven points during the opening run,
Thompson had four of her eight points and Swoopes two of her eight
points.
</P>
<P>
   Four more points in the run were scored by Leslie, who came out
of the night with 13 points, five rebounds and a beautiful glass
trophy from Tiffany &AMP; Co.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel like a little kid,'' the 6-5 Sparks center said. ``I am
totally excited to be here and very thankful that the fans are the
ones that put me in that position, as well as the fans here (at
Madison Square Garden). Obviously, a few other players probably had
the opportunity to get it as well. I just thank God for blessing me
to be here, to play.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was able to get in and get some quick shots with Michele
Timms pushing the ball upcourt. I guess basically I'll leave here
believing that I'm going to be a part of history, being the first
MVP.''
</P>
<P>
   There was little of the razzle-dazzle on either side that is
often typical of All-Star affairs.
</P>
<P>
   But the rest of the trimmings were there. Movie director Spike
Lee and supermodel Tyra Banks were among those in the crowd. And
Whitney Houston turned up the electricity during the pre-game
ceremonies, turning in a rendition of the national anthem that left
the entire house on its feet cheering.
</P>
<P>
   The early run by the West served to settle the pro-East throng
back into its seats rather quickly, however. The East eventually
cut a 15-point deficit to 31-29, but Chancellor sent his starters
back in and they built a 43-29 halftime lead. The East never
threatened in the second half.
</P>
<P>
   Coach Linda Hill-MacDonald's squad suffered a huge blow when
heralded rookie Chamique Holdsclaw of the Washington Mystics broke
the index finger on her left hand in the first half and was unable
to play the final 20 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   But Hill-MacDonald said what hurt the East more was not having
the size and wide bodies to cope inside with the likes of Williams
(14 points, eight rebounds), Griffith (10 points, five rebounds)
and Leslie.
</P>
<P>
   ``There wasn't much we could do to combat that when you don't
have size on your bench,'' said Hill-MacDonald. ``The tallest
player on our team was 6-3 (Taj McWilliams of the Orlando Miracle).
The next-tallest after that was 6-2. Next after that was 6-2. We
had three post players; they had five.
</P>
<P>
   ``Kym Hampton (New York Liberty), I was asked to limit her
minutes. I tried to rotate them as best I could, keep people as
healthy as we could.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's not much you can do. You just put them in there, let
them play. And that's what we did.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-15-99 0128EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
