<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-15 01:30 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0685 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-LOPEZ-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      07-15 0841
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-LOPEZ-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
John P.Lopez
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; c. 1999, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
THE skipper returns tonight, but that won't guarantee the ship
steering into clear and smooth waters.
</P>
<P>
   Fans will arrive at the Astrodome tonight wearing their favorite
Hawaiian shirts, in tribute to Astros manager Larry Dierker, whose
recovery from the seizure and ensuing brain surgery of last month
has been nothing short of spectacular.
</P>
<P>
   But that doesn't guarantee the Astros' second half will be just
another cheeseburger in paradise like it was a year ago.
</P>
<P>
   Dierker's return will inspire this team, for sure. His calm and
steady hand is sure to make a difference in the season's second
half. He will keep pitchers happy and understand that experience
and leadership should give the Astros an edge over the hot
Cincinnati Reds.
</P>
<P>
   All in all, it simply will be a welcome sight seeing Dierker's
jersey draped around something other than a hanger. Bring your
Hawaiian shirts, and cheer the man. He's earned it.
</P>
<P>
   But as much as Dierker can do, as seemingly comfortable and
confident as the Astros remain with a 50-37 record and a share of
the division lead at the break, the Astros haven't earned a thing
yet. Margaritaville still can become Nowheresville quickly.
</P>
<P>
   Most notably, three significant issues face Dierker upon his
return to the team as the second half of the season begins tonight
against the Detroit Tigers:
</P>
<P>
   What do you do with the pitching rotation, especially
considering the up-and-down bullpen performances?
</P>
<P>
   Is Derek Bell, who always looks casual and unconcerned, really
casual and unconcerned this time _ simply going through the motions
on the way to another uniform?
</P>
<P>
   And when will the Astros get what they paid for out of Ken
Caminiti?
</P>
<P>
   Sure, other questions need attention, but they all should be
weathered.
</P>
<P>
   Losing Ricky Gutierrez to a broken hand was a tough break, but
Tim Bogar can pick up the defense and Bill Spiers can flat-out
play. This guy needs to get onto the field as often as possible.
</P>
<P>
   Starting the second half with a makeshift lineup of catchers is
no big help, either. But Tony Eusebio should be back to form soon,
and his stick figures to improve. Besides, the Astros never
expected a lot of offense from this position, even when they were
touting Mitch Meluskey as a cross between Johnny Bench, Yogi Berra,
Aquaman and Inspector Gadget.
</P>
<P>
   As for Craig Biggio, he probably could have put up better
first-half numbers, but I wouldn't worry. The way Bidge responded
to being snubbed for the All-Star Game might be a sign of how he
again will lead this team the rest of the way.
</P>
<P>
   The difference will be in the rotation. And between Bell's ears.
And on Caminiti's wheels.
</P>
<P>
   At what point, if ever, will Dierker make the decision to go to
a four-man rotation of Shane Reynolds, Mike Hampton, Jose Lima and
Scott Elarton? It's not always smart to do that too early in a
season, but on this team it might be an option.
</P>
<P>
   He'll have to toss in the occasional start for a fifth arm,
sure. But Astros coaches and management already have given Chris
Holt and Sean Bergman more chances than Hillary has Bill. At some
point, you have to send them to the pen, or elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the bullpen has at times been stifling and figures to
get stronger with the return of Doug Henry. And there's nothing
better in a division chase than having a reliable starter every
time out and an array of relief possibilities sitting out there
ready to enter.
</P>
<P>
   As for Bell, the option facing Dierker might be more touchy in
terms of clubhouse harmony. But it might be necessary nevertheless.
</P>
<P>
   If Moises Alou returns full strength and Bell still hasn't found
whatever it is that ignites his game, it should be Bell who takes a
seat. Not Richard Hidalgo. And certainly not Carl Everett.
</P>
<P>
   Then there is Caminiti _ his problem is he has been sitting far
too long.
</P>
<P>
   It's never a good sign when you've just pulled a calf muscle but
then a couple of weeks later you're still sitting out when your
manager has his head cut open.
</P>
<P>
   And then weeks after that, the guy with the scar across the top
of his head is back in the lineup before you.
</P>
<P>
   The whispers of several weeks ago have turned into outright
cries of speculation across the league: Did the Astros sign a
broken-down player?
</P>
<P>
   There's no doubting Caminiti's heart for the game, so obviously
it is not a lack of desire keeping him out. It might just be a
matter of taking too many wild dives into the dirt for too long. It
might just be too many miles on the treads. Too many turned ankles.
Too many sprained wrists. Too many bangs on the knees.
</P>
<P>
   But if the Astros truly want to make a big run, Caminiti has to
get better. Caminiti has to return to some form of his old self and
contribute his bat and playoff experience. Down the stretch, he
must be in the lineup every day.
</P>
<P>
   Thus, the biggest question of all: Can Dierker perform another
medical miracle, this time on Cammy?
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
