   &UR; NATIONAL _ GENERAL (Moved in ``a'' category) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   SCI-AIDS (Undated) _ In an advance that promises to
significantly reduce the incidence of AIDS in children in
developing countries, American and Ugandan scientists have found a
simple new way to prevent mother-to-child transmission of the AIDS
virus that also is less costly and markedly more effective than the
standard therapy in the Third World. By Lawrence K. Altman.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WASHINGTON _ (Moved in ``w'' category)  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   WORKER-HEALTH _ For the first time, the federal government is
acknowledging that nuclear weapons production during the Cold War
may have caused illnesses in thousands of workers, and the Clinton
administration will announce on Thursday legislation that will
compensate many of them for their medical care and lost wages. By
Matthew L. Wald.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; BUSINESS DAY _ (Moved in ``f'' category)  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Y2K-SERVICE (Phoenix) _ As major corporate customers wrap up
their Y2K computer repair programs, business has been drying up for
vendors of software tools and services aimed at Y2K solutions. Some
smaller companies have disappeared or withered to the point of
having their stock delisted by the Nasdaq exchange. Others have
changed their names along with their focus in an attempt to shake
their year 2000 identities. By Barnaby J. Feder.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Graphic has been sent to NYT graphics clients.)
</P>
<P>
   QUALCOMM-MARKETPLACE (New York) _ This week, a few days after
Standard &AMP; Poor's announced Qualcomm Inc. would be added to the
esteemed list of 500 big-capitalization stocks, Qualcomm said it
would sell up to 4.6 million shares directly to index fund
managers. Over the last year, several other companies have
registered stock for sale to index fund managers, but Qualcomm, a
San Diego-based wireless communications company, appears to be the
first to reap all of the proceeds itself. By Edward Wyatt.
</P>
<P>
   LUXURYCARS-AD-COLUMN (Dearborn, Mich.) _ There was a time when
American car lovers conjured up Cadillac and Lincoln as icons when
they thought of luxury cars. Now, Lincoln is embarking on a new ad
campaign trying to make it so again, but with a twist: it has
designed a car that looks and drives like a European or Japanese
sport sedan, that will be showcased in ads that proclaim ``American
Luxury.'' By Robyn Meredith.
</P>
<P>
   CAPITALGAINS-ECONSCENE (Undated) _ Congress is flirting with
cutting the tax on capital gains by lowering the top rate on
capital gains to 15 percent from 20 percent as part of an $864
billion package of tax cuts spread over 10 years. The goal is to
stimulate savings, investment and economic growth. It's a
nice-sounding theory. But many economists say it lacks credible
evidence. By Michael M. Weinstein.
</P>
