   &UR; HOME (Moved in ``l'' category) &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   HISPANIC-NATIVE-ART (Santa Fe, N.M.) _ Like summer lightning
across the mesas, history seems intimately close here. As Ramon
Jose Lopez, an artist, stands in the family chapel of his home, the
light filtering through windows made of rock crystal onto his
hand-adzed altarpieces, it doesn't seem that long ago when the
foothills here were marked by orchards and cornfields, rather than
condominiums, and farmers exchanged their corn and grain for his
grandfather's hand-carved images of saints, or santos. Lopez and
his family have filled their homemade chapel with their art _
santos, silver reliquaries, exquisite prayer books made from
buffalo hide, altarpieces painted with yellow ocre he gathers from
caves in the Sandia mountains. By Patricia Leigh Brown.
</P>
<P>
   PERFECT-SOFA (Undated) _ Forget happiness, financial security
and a healthy sex life. If you ask people what they're really
looking for these days, ``a perfect sofa'' is what many are likely
to say. By David Colman.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Photo has been sent to NYT photo clients.)
</P>
<P>
   TAJ-MAHAL-GARDENS (Undated) _ Across the river from the Taj
Mahal in Agra, India, there was once an enchanting garden filled
with the fragrance of white, night-blooming flowers and blossoming
trees. For hundreds of years, people were intrigued by the idea of
the existence of the Moonlight Garden, which was documented in
paintings and manuscripts. They knew approximately where it was.
What they did not know were the garden's exact dimensions, how the
fountains worked, where the water courses were and what exactly was
planted in this classic Imperial Mughul garden. By Paula Deitz.
</P>
