<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-15 01:31 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0688 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-DIERKER-HNS &LR;      07-15 0840
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-DIERKER-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ALAN TRUEX  
 c. 1999, Houston Chronicle  
With Larry Dierker returning to the dugout tonight, the Astros are
asking fans to wear Hawaiian shirts _ the favored attire of the
popular manager when he's not in uniform _ to the Astrodome.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Shortly before Dierker spoke to the media Wednesday at the
Astrodome, leis were handed out to reporters. There was a buoyant
atmosphere, which players participating in a voluntary practice
session noticed.
</P>
<P>
   ``It gives you a lift to see him back and having fun again,''
said Derek Bell, one of the players closest to Dierker when he
suffered a grand mal seizure during a game June 13.
</P>
<P>
   Dierker underwent brain surgery, and there are some lingering
symptoms. He has occasional headaches; his sense of time may be
off; he is not allowed to drive an automobile or to engage in a
strenuous workout.
</P>
<P>
   But he is alert and in excellent spirits, and Bell said, ``He's
the same guy except he has a low haircut, like me.''
</P>
<P>
   Third baseman Ken Caminiti said, ``It's a positive thing getting
him back. He is probably the leader of this team.''
</P>
<P>
   Dierker is confident he has regained enough mental faculties to
lead the Astros to a third consecutive National League Central
championship.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't expect to have any difficulties resuming my duties as
manager,'' he said, in anticipation of tonight's game against the
Detroit Tigers. He added, ``I would like to thank the many people
who sent cards and letters and food and flowers. I was totally
overwhelmed.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've heard from a lot of people who've had the same type of
condition I had, and they're living as if they'd never had the
episodes. Those messages have made me very optimistic about a full
recovery. I don't have any fear of this happening again.''
</P>
<P>
   But it may take time before he's 100 percent recovered. Doctors
do not want him driving for another five months, and he said,
``That's the only thing that reminds me daily that something
serious has happened.
</P>
<P>
   ``Looking back, I had headaches for two days preceding the
seizure, and I don't get headaches very often. I have had a few
headaches since I've come home, but if I take a couple of Advils or
aspirins, they go away.''
</P>
<P>
   Dierker said he recently ``had a brain-wave test to determine if
I have what's called a `seizure focus' _ which is a little thing
that tells doctors this is a person who might have a seizure. I
don't have that anymore.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been taking seizure medication, and the doctors want me
to take it through the end of the season. If they do the test again
and it comes out clean, then I'll probably stop taking the
medication.''
</P>
<P>
   Dierker admitted he's lacking energy, but he said, ``I did go
out and play golf several times. One time I played from 10 in the
morning to 6 at night, and that made me feel pretty good about my
endurance.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked if he had any apprehension about managing again, he said,
``Just a little bit. I wonder if I may have lost some sense of
time.''
</P>
<P>
   He recalled: ``The day I had the seizure, I got down to the
dugout late. I remember (Astros pitcher) Mike Hampton coming into
my office and asking me if I was going to watch the game. It was
the bottom of the first inning.
</P>
<P>
   ``Since I've come out of the hospital, I still have some trouble
with time. Yesterday it was four weeks from the surgery, and it
seemed like two weeks to me.''
</P>
<P>
   Even if he suffers an occasional mental lapse, he's confident
that Matt Galante, who filled in for him during his convalescence,
will make sure he doesn't overlook anything.
</P>
<P>
   ``Matt is so experienced as a manager, he's like a prompter for
me in the dugout,'' Dierker said. ``And the same thing with Vern
Ruhle looking after the pitchers. So I'm not fearful of anything
happening that would put us at a competitive disadvantage.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked to assess the Astros as they emerge from the All-Star
break, Dierker said: ``I'm not happy with where we are based on the
team we had coming out of spring training. But I am happy with
where we are based on the circumstances, the injuries.''
</P>
<P>
   Left fielder Moises Alou has not played this season because of a
knee injury, and shortstop Ricky Gutierrez and Caminiti also are on
the disabled list.
</P>
<P>
   ``But when we lose Ricky Gutierrez twice, we have Tim Bogar,''
Dierker pointed out. ``How many teams have a Tim Bogar who can play
everyday shortstop? And I'm not sure Caminiti can play that much
better than Bill Spiers has been playing.''
</P>
<P>
   The Astros enter the second half trailing Cincinnati by one
percentage point.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can tell by watching the games on television that the Reds
have some good chemistry going right now, and it's hard for us to
pull away from them,'' Dierker said. ``But there are so many games
left that I think eventually we will do that.''
</P>
<P>
   As usual, Dierker was focusing more attention on others than on
himself. ``It's great to be back,'' he said, ``but to be honest,
I'd rather have Alou back than myself.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
