<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-15 01:32 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0689 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GLF-BRITISH-ADVANCE-H     07-15 0941
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-BRITISH-ADVANCE-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By EDDIE SEFKO  
 c. 1999, Houston Chronicle  
CARNOUSTIE, Scotland _ When the British Open ends Sunday, the proud
and proper Scots might be departing Carnoustie humming a familiar
refrain.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Yanks for the memories.
</P>
<P>
   Seven decades ago, Walter Hagen and Bobby Jones combined to win
five consecutive British Opens. It stands today as the best run of
success Americans have had in the 128-year history of this
tournament. But by Sunday evening, that legendary duo may have
company.
</P>
<P>
   Starting with John Daly in 1995, Americans have won four
consecutive British Opens, and Tiger Woods teed off this morning
favored to make it five in a row for the U.S.
</P>
<P>
   It is a far cry from the 11 years before '95, during which only
one American _ Mark Calcavecchia in 1989 _ won the tournament.
</P>
<P>
   Now, this suddenly is America's adopted championship. The
invasion from stateside is turning this competition in golf's
homeland into a red, white and blue party.
</P>
<P>
   But nobody, including the man tabbed as the pre-tournament
favorite, is sure why.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really can't point out why we've been so successful,'' Woods
said. ``I know that our tour is very strong, and maybe that's what
it is because we are able to compete at a high level to win in the
States. You can't really play a bad round anymore and still win.
Other than that, maybe it's just blind luck.''
</P>
<P>
   Once is luck. Maybe even twice. But when such diverse American
players like Daly, Tom Lehman, Justin Leonard and Mark O'Meara have
won the British Open, it clearly can be construed as a sign that
knee-high heather, gnarly gorse and bowling-alley fairways don't
intimidate the Americans.
</P>
<P>
   ``The American players who come over here realize this is what
golf is all about,'' said O'Meara, the defending champion. ``It's
one of the greatest championships in the whole world. And it's a
refreshing change for most Americans because a lot of times we play
the same type of golf course day in and day out. I think a lot of
Americans get fired up about coming over here and playing on a
links course.''
</P>
<P>
   Whatever the reason, the Americans again are expected to do well
this week. At local bookmaking establishments, David Duval is the
second betting choice, behind Woods. And half of the players listed
at 40-1 or better odds are Americans.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't understand why,'' Payne Stewart said. ``I was asked
the same question at the U.S. Open. I don't know why they
(Europeans) don't perform well there. I don't have an answer for
that question. There is no reason why they shouldn't.''
</P>
<P>
   The implication is that so many non-Americans don't play in all
the major championships, therefore they have less experience at
dealing with the pressure.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's easy to say that, but take a look at the Masters,''
Ireland's Darren Clarke said. ``Take a look at how many European
winners you have had at the Masters. How long ago is it since we
had a winner here? Five years?
</P>
<P>
   ``It just so happens it's been non-Europeans who have played
better the past five years. Anybody who wins this tournament is a
fantastic player. It just so happens they've been American.''
</P>
<P>
   Whoever prevails this week will have conquered what is expected
to be as difficult an Open Championship golf course as has ever
been played. Carnoustie has teased players during practice rounds.
The wind was docile for two days. But Wednesday, it whipped strong
from the west, and expectations for a Carnoustie carnage wafted
through the ranks of players.
</P>
<P>
   ``There most certainly will be some scores in the 90s,'' said
Colin Montgomerie, one of the favorites among the non-Americans.
</P>
<P>
   What makes Carnoustie so tough is the combination of length
(7,361 yards), narrow fairways, hayfield rough and strategic
bunkering, plus the wind that invariably will blow this week.
</P>
<P>
   But what makes Carnoustie great is the history that abounds,
particularly on Nos. 6 and 16.
</P>
<P>
   The sixth hole is a 578-yard par-5 that will forever be known as
Hogan's Alley. In 1953, when Ben Hogan won with a 282 total at
Carnoustie, he discovered he could shave off some yardage on the
then-shorter hole by knifing his tee shot between a pair of fairway
bunkers and the out-of-bounds fence that runs the length of the
hole on the left side.
</P>
<P>
   Legend has it that on the final day of the Open, when 36 holes
were played, he hit his tee ball perfectly on the first 18 and then
drove it into his exact divot on the second trip around the course,
making birdie both times.
</P>
<P>
   That might be fact or fiction. But what is undeniable is that
Hogan, Tommy D. Armour, Henry Cotton, Gary Player and Tom Watson
are the five who previously have won Opens at Carnoustie, and
whoever prevails this week will step alongside five of the greatest
names in the sport's history.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've never seen a course quite like this before,''
Calcavecchia said. ``There's no question it's tough. Some holes, if
you don't make the perfect tee shot, you're going to make bogey or
worse.
</P>
<P>
   ``If it gets really windy and ugly, then it will be vicious to
play. The average score might be 80. In fact, it probably will be.
So that's pretty silly.''
</P>
<P>
   But the beauty of golf in any circumstance is that it will be
the same golf course for each player, although conditions can
change quickly along the Scottish coast.
</P>
<P>
   ``Regardless of whether you like or dislike the golf course,
they haven't stopped giving out a trophy on Sunday,'' Duval said.
``So whether you think it's fair or unfair or too hard or too easy,
somebody is going to take home the Claret Jug on Sunday night.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
