<P>
   MAYOR-ALLEGATIONS (REEDS SPRING, Mo.) The mayor of Reeds Spring,
Mo., was taken into federal custody Wednesday after a U.S.
magistrate heard evidence that he had offered thousands of dollars
to potential witnesses in his sexual misconduct case. By MARK
MORRIS. Story will move in the ``a'' category. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   PRAIRIE-CHICKENS-2TAKES (TABERVILLE PRAIRIE, Mo.) Purple prairie
coneflowers nod in the wind above the grasses in this ancient
prairie, as they have for centuries. But something is missing as
biologist Norman Murray strolls in the knee-high growth 90 miles
south of Kansas City. It's why he is part of the recently formed
Missouri Grasslands Coalition, an unprecedented public-private
prairie conservation effort. Prairie chickens _ the bird that once
roamed Missouri by the hundreds of thousands _ are not seen on this
hike, or during a subsequent drive across the ridge tops. Greater
prairie chickens, a large member of the grouse family, last year
were added to Missouri's endangered species list. They number less
than 1,000 and are scattered in dangerously small flocks on prairie
remnants. If population trends continue, they will vanish in the
next decade. By BILL GRAHAM. Story will move in the ``a''
category. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   BROWN-RELEASE (KANSAS CITY, Mo.) Sharion Beaver didn't want to
turn her son in to police. She wanted her son, Allen C. Brown, to
get on with his life in Kansas City after he was released July 6
from a Tucson jail. But it turns out Brown, 37, was freed because
of a paperwork foul-up. Arizona authorities suspect Brown of
killing his girlfriend by stabbing her more than 100 times on May
22. And they did not want him released from jail, where he had been
held on a $1 million bond. On Monday, a Tucson detective left a
message with that information at Beaver's midtown home. So even as
Beaver was thrilled that her son was home, she knew what she had to
do: Tell him to surrender. By MATT STEARNS and KEVIN HOFFMANN.
Story will move in the ``a'' category. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ELKS-CONVENTION KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ There are about 10,000 members
of the Benevolent and Protective Order of Elks meeting at their
national convention in Kansas City this week. But it is two women
who want to be members who are garnering some of the spotlight.
Although more women now are Elks and a few are in leadership roles,
protesters think there is still a long way to go. By MARY SANCHEZ.
Story will move in the ``a'' category. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   SCHOOL-BOARD KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ In a 7-2 vote, the Kansas City
school board offered the superintendent's job to Benjamin Demps Jr.
late Wednesday night. After a day of intensive background checking
and a closed-door meeting that ran for nearly an hour, the board
agreed to extend an offer to Demps, 65. He is a retired Federal
Aviation Administration official who served as director of the
Oklahoma Department of Human Services during the early 1990s. He is
now semiretired and operates an aviation consulting business. By
PHILLIP O'CONNOR. Story will move in the ``a'' category. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ For years, Chiefs star Derrick Thomas has
been locally famous not only for his on-field achievements but for
his compassion toward Kansas City's needy children. The
linebacker's Third &AMP; Long Foundation has been particularly
interested in helping children improve their reading skills. So it
seemed a natural step when, nearly two years ago, Thomas pledged
$127,035 to pay the fines for lost and overdue books for more than
4,000 Kansas City children. Paying the fines would allow the
children to borrow books from the library again. In anticipation of
Thomas' check, the library forgave the fines. But so far, Thomas
has paid less than half the money. By MATT STEARNS. Story will move
in the ``a'' category.
</P>
