<HEADLINE>
REEDS SPRINGS MAYOR SENT TO JAIL BEFORE START OF MISCONDUCT TRIAL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARK MORRIS  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   REEDS SPRING, Mo. _ The mayor of Reeds Spring, Mo., was taken
into federal custody Wednesday after a U.S. magistrate heard
evidence that he had offered thousands of dollars to potential
witnesses in his sexual misconduct case.
</P>
<P>
   Joe Dan Dwyer, 68, had been free on bond since his indictment in
January on charges that he had transported a 15-year-old girl from
Kansas to St. Louis to engage in illegal sexual activity.
</P>
<P>
   Early this month, prosecutors added new charges, alleging that
Dwyer offered and, in some cases, paid three women to lie to his
lawyers to help his case or to commit perjury at his upcoming
trial.
</P>
<P>
   At Wednesday's hearing, U.S. Magistrate Judge Sarah Hays heard
FBI agent John R. Smith testify that he interviewed three women who
said Dwyer had offered up to $50,000 for their help in his case.
</P>
<P>
   Dwyer also gave some of the women books to teach them how to lie
convincingly under oath and during interrogations, Smith said.
</P>
<P>
   The mayor's lawyers objected to the testimony, saying it was
based on hearsay and that they could not confront the potential
witnesses.
</P>
<P>
   They characterized some of the women as unreliable small-time
criminals, nude dancers and prostitutes.
</P>
<P>
   Discounting the government's evidence, defense attorney Charles
Rogers said prosecutors hadn't made a good enough case to revoke
Dwyer's bond.
</P>
<P>
   ``(Prosecutors) have a burden to show dangerousness and a flight
risk,'' Rogers said. ``The government has shown neither.''
</P>
<P>
   Rogers said Dwyer has always appeared for court proceedings, and
so would not leave the jurisdiction without permission. Hays,
however, said the evidence was enough to put Dwyer in jail until
trial.
</P>
<P>
   ``The greatest and best predictor of future conduct, I've found,
is past conduct,'' Hays said.
</P>
<P>
   Reeds Spring is in Stone County, about 20 miles northwest of
Branson.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
