<SLUG> BC-PRAIRIE-CHICKENS-2NDTAKE-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PRAIRIE CHICKENS A SYMPTOM OF AN ECOLOGICAL ILL AS GRASSLANDS
DWINDLE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BILL GRAHAM  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The richness comes in part from the grasses, drought-resistant
strains that evolved over millions of years. They sink roots five
to 20 feet deep. When those roots are replaced, the old ones decay
and add organic matter to the soil, creating a fertile loam.
</P>
<P>
   A canopy of vegetation forms over the ground, with space between
stalks and stems. It's ideal for ground-dwelling birds such as
prairie chickens to run and hide in. The grasses turn reddish gold
in autumn and stay upright, helping wildlife stay dry and warm in
winter. The cover provides nesting sites during spring.
</P>
<P>
   Pioneer settlers didn't understand these drought-tolerant
grasses. They fenced livestock onto prairie pastures European
style. When the cattle ate the grass close to the ground and it
didn't grow back, they called it unproductive.
</P>
<P>
   Recent studies show that forage production on prairies is equal
or superior to imported grass if the native grasses are not cut or
grazed too low. But it's expensive to change back to native
grasses.
</P>
<P>
   Homesteaders quickly plowed most prairies to grow corn and wheat
in the rich topsoil, much of which has since eroded away.
</P>
<P>
   Taberville Prairie, like the Flint Hills prairie in Kansas, was
likely spared because of rocky glades that are hard to till.
</P>
<P>
   Some prairie patches survived as hay fields, or for sentimental
reasons.
</P>
<P>
   But much native grass was plowed in the 1970s as crop prices
jumped. Now, many farm families are leaving their lands. New owners
or tenants with no ties to the land are plowing more prairie
fragments.
</P>
<P>
   Thousands of acres have been replanted with native grasses such
as switchgrass or big bluestem under the federal Conservation
Reserve Program.
</P>
<P>
   That helps prairie chickens and has boosted numbers in northwest
Kansas.
</P>
<P>
   But it's a monoculture of grass and not a true prairie with more
than 300 species of plants interwoven by the centuries.
</P>
<P>
   Landowners such as Hand _ with Grassland Coalition help _ are
Missouri prairie chickens' best hope.
</P>
<P>
   Taberville Prairie will be the heart for one of nine prairie
chicken focus areas created by the coalition.
</P>
<P>
   But help from private landowners will be crucial in re-creating
a large-scale prairie landscape. Hand used a federal grant to pay
for tree-cutting on a small prairie he owns near the public land.
He plans more tree removal and native grass replanting on other
land.
</P>
<P>
   ``We weren't talking to our neighbors before,'' Figg said. ``The
prairie chickens were failing, but the neighbors didn't know. Now
we're talking, and so far they're responding positively.''
</P>
<P>
   Some steps are as simple as giving farmers a helping hand in
ridding fence lines of trees. But shrub and weed cover for prairie
chickens and quail will be left.
</P>
<P>
   Biologists believe tree lines draw predators such as red-tailed
hawks or owls and furbearers such as raccoons that eat eggs in
nests.
</P>
<P>
   ``Prairie chickens don't like to fly through or over trees,''
Murray said.
</P>
<P>
   On all sides of Taberville Prairie, he pointed to tree lines
separating pastures and fields. Hand's great-grandfather divided
his land into 80-acre tracts by planting hedgerows of Osage orange.
Trees also spread because fires, once a regular occurrence on
prairies, were suppressed.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we take out the trees, it will open up areas for birds to
use,'' Murray said.
</P>
<P>
   Kansas City lawyer Arthur A. Benson II, coalition co-founder,
and other volunteers from the Missouri Prairie Foundation visited
Taberville Prairie recently to clear trees. Another member bought
an adjoining prairie remnant and will manage it to boost prairie
chickens. A paid crew, hired by the foundation, is working with
farmers this summer.
</P>
<P>
   Some landowners may be offered financial incentives to replant
native grasses or to revitalize surviving prairies with controlled
fires. The coalition hopes to raise $1.5 million for landowner
assistance that can be implemented quickly, free of government red
tape.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, government agencies are communicating more
than ever on prairie restoration techniques, said Sharron Gough, a
Conservation Department grasslands biologist.
</P>
<P>
   All participation is voluntary.
</P>
<P>
   ``If a neighbor (landowner) doesn't want to be part of the
Grassland Coalition effort,'' Figg said, ``it's OK and we'll go
work on other areas.''
</P>
<P>
   No one knows for sure whether these efforts will save prairie
chickens. One flock in northwest Missouri has grown from birds
restocked in Iowa that migrated to the Dunn Ranch and Pawnee
Prairie area.
</P>
<P>
   But elsewhere, Missouri's native prairie chickens must reverse a
long-term downward trend.
</P>
<P>
   At Taberville, Murray hopes flushing a prairie chicken during a
hike becomes common rather than rare.
</P>
<P>
   But history makes biologists cautious.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is trying to figure out what a great panorama is supposed
to look like,'' Gough said, ``when you're only working with a few
small jigsaw puzzle pieces.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
