<HEADER>
A0694 &Cx1f; kan-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PRAIRIE-CHICKENS-2TAK     07-15 0963
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PRAIRIE-CHICKENS-2TAKES-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PRAIRIE CHICKENS A SYMPTOM OF AN ECOLOGICAL ILL AS GRASSLANDS
DWINDLE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BILL GRAHAM  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   TABERVILLE PRAIRIE, Mo. _ Purple prairie coneflowers nod in the
wind above the grasses in this ancient prairie, as they have for
centuries.
</P>
<P>
   But something is missing as biologist Norman Murray strolls in
the knee-high growth 90 miles south of Kansas City. It's why he is
part of the recently formed Missouri Grasslands Coalition, an
unprecedented public-private prairie conservation effort.
</P>
<P>
   Prairie chickens _ the bird that once roamed Missouri by the
hundreds of thousands _ are not seen on this hike, or during a
subsequent drive across the ridge tops.
</P>
<P>
   ``We bought this area in 1959 to save the prairie chicken,''
said Murray, who works for the Missouri Department of Conservation.
``We've found out we need to do more.''
</P>
<P>
   Greater prairie chickens, a large member of the grouse family,
last year were added to Missouri's endangered species list. They
number less than 1,000 and are scattered in dangerously small
flocks on prairie remnants. If population trends continue, they
will vanish in the next decade.
</P>
<P>
   Their thinning numbers are a sign of deeper trouble; in fact,
all grassland bird populations are declining in the Midwest.
Kansas, a prairie stronghold, has seen prairie chicken numbers drop
in the southeast and the southwest. Beyond that, conservationists
say, the region is losing its last shreds of virgin prairie _ and
with it, some of the delicate balances of plant and animal life
that have long been its hallmarks.
</P>
<P>
   ``Prairie chickens are really a banner species for all the
grassland birds and plants,'' said Dennis Figg, a Missouri
Conservation Department naturalist and coalition co-founder. ``Even
commonly seen birds like meadowlarks have declined by 50 percent
over the last three decades in Missouri.''
</P>
<P>
   The Missouri coalition of 13 state, federal and private
conservation agencies will try to reverse the trend by creating
large grassland focus areas, 10,000 acres or more for each area,
with the volunteer help of private landowners.
</P>
<P>
   Within these areas the coalition will re-create the original
open landscape. Trees will be cut, and the coalition will offer
financial incentives to make private pasture and crop field
management-friendly to wildlife.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we can meet the needs of the prairie chicken,'' Figg said,
``then a number of other species should respond, too.''
</P>
<P>
   Pure prairies once dominated as much as half of Missouri's
landscape. Grassy savannas, meadows and glades mixed with trees in
the remainder of the state.
</P>
<P>
   Now, less than 1 percent of the native grassland remains, and
small pockets of virgin prairie continue to be destroyed.
</P>
<P>
   Only in recent decades have scientists begun to study in depth
what was lost and what is left.
</P>
<P>
   Many biologists believe surface and groundwater quality and
quantity dropped when prairie was no longer present to soak up
rainfall. The diversity of prairie plants and their adaptations to
the climate and soils may hold invaluable secrets for agriculture
and medicine. A recent medical conference in Kansas City focused on
the healing qualities of echinacea, made from purple prairie
coneflowers.
</P>
<P>
   Coneflowers evolved in an ecosystem that vanished long before
environmental movements were born and before science understood it.
</P>
<P>
   We know forests because they survived in rocky, hilly or lowland
areas that were difficult to till.
</P>
<P>
   But most Missourians have never walked in the mix of grasses and
flowering forb plants that, over eons, built the rich soils now
cultivated for crops or pastures. And they've never seen the
once-common wild prairie chicken.
</P>
<P>
   Jack Hand remembers hundreds of prairie chickens flying near his
birthplace, on land south of Taberville Prairie that his
great-grandfather homesteaded in the 1870s.
</P>
<P>
   ``They used to be real thick,'' said Hand, 74. ``They'd fly from
the prairie over to the cornfields. I wouldn't let anybody shoot
them. They're unusual, and I enjoy looking at them.''
</P>
<P>
   This spring, observers counted 52 males on the 1,600-acre area's
annual breeding sites, called leks or booming grounds. Those are
the places where the males strut and make a cheek-puffing, drumlike
sound, known as booming, to attract breeding females.
</P>
<P>
   As recently as 1988, almost 200 booming males were counted.
</P>
<P>
   Biologists suspect the prairie chicken is failing because it
needs large, open spaces to thrive. Meanwhile, grassland habitat
has declined. Scientists this year also began testing to see
whether the declines had brought on disease or reproduction
problems.
</P>
<P>
   Taberville Prairie still has ridges and swales rich with flowers
that bloom in a changing pattern from spring to fall. Clear water,
rainfall filtered by the prairie, seeps into a gurgling creek.
</P>
<P>
   Prairie chickens peck bugs from plants such as the
nitrogen-building legume called sensitive briar, which has puffy,
purple flowers. Murray touched its multipetaled leaf, and it closed
like a Venus's-flytrap.
</P>
<P>
   ``Prairie chickens can come here and eat bugs most of the warm
season because there's green vegetation and something's always in
bloom,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   White obedience plant blooms faced east, away from the wind, and
Murray pushed them around on the stem and they held their place. He
fingered the green seed head of gama grass, succulent fodder to
livestock and a relative to corn. Ripe purple dewberries signaled
summer, while nearby a few red Indian paintbrush blooms lingered
from spring.
</P>
<P>
   ``This prairie was bought for prairie chickens,'' Murray said,
``but it's turned out to be very rich for all kinds of prairie
life.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
