<HEADLINE>
MISTAKENLY FREED PRISONER BACK IN POLICE CUSTODY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MATT STEARNS and KEVIN HOFFMANN  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ Sharion Beaver didn't want to turn her son in
to police.
</P>
<P>
   She wanted her son, Allen C. Brown, to get on with his life in
Kansas City after he was released July 6 from a Tucson jail.
</P>
<P>
   But it turns out Brown, 37, was freed because of a paperwork
foul-up. Arizona authorities suspect Brown of killing his
girlfriend by stabbing her more than 100 times on May 22. And they
did not want him released from jail, where he had been held on a $1
million bond.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, a Tucson detective left a message with that
information at Beaver's midtown home.
</P>
<P>
   So even as Beaver was thrilled that her son was home, she knew
what she had to do: Tell him to surrender.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had mixed emotions,'' she said. ``I hated to turn him in.
But at the same time, I knew it was to his advantage.''
</P>
<P>
   Brown had been described in a police bulletin as armed and
dangerous. So when a dozen heavily armed police officers came to
Beaver's home Tuesday, she was ready to help. After talking with
her son's attorney, Beaver led police to a house in the 8500 block
of East Sni-A-Bar Road where Brown was staying.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were able to come to an agreement where they wouldn't
bombard the house,'' Beaver said. ``They let me walk in and out of
the house with him.''
</P>
<P>
   Kansas City Detective Al Devalkenaere said he was pleased with
the way Beaver cooperated with police. He said police assured her
they wanted no harm to come to her son. They just wanted him back
in custody.
</P>
<P>
   ``The last thing we wanted was him out on the run, scared,''
Devalkenaere said.
</P>
<P>
   Police said Brown cooperated when they arrested him.
</P>
<P>
   ``He wanted it known that he was not fleeing from Arizona and
that he was told he was free to go,'' Devalkenaere said.
</P>
<P>
   Brown, who was indicted in Jackson County Court and is being
held in the Jackson County jail, waived extradition Wednesday. He
will remain in Kansas City until Arizona authorities come get him.
</P>
<P>
   Beaver, who believes her son is innocent, said she hopes the
next time he comes home, it will be for good.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm going to keep on doing what I've been doing all along,''
she said. ``And that's pray. I trust in God that justice will be
served.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
