A0697 &Cx1f; kan-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ELKS-CONVENTION-KAN &LR;      07-15 0924
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ELKS-CONVENTION-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PROTESTERS CRITICIZE ELKS CLUB OVER MEMBERSHIP 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARY SANCHEZ  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ There are about 10,000 members of the
Benevolent and Protective Order of Elks meeting at their national
convention in Kansas City this week.
</P>
<P>
   But it is two women who want to be members who are garnering
some of the spotlight.
</P>
<P>
   Georgia Bonacci and Dona Etienne stood outside Bartle Hall on
Tuesday with placards declaring: ``Not All Elks Have Antlers'' and
``We Can Be Elks Too.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite the fraternal organization's decision in 1995 to allow
women as members, the Los Angeles-area women contend that the Elks
roster in the nearby Bellflower, Calif., lodge is still all-male.
</P>
<P>
   And although more women now are Elks and a few are in leadership
roles, the protesters think there is still a long way to go.
</P>
<P>
   Etienne, Bonacci and other women said they have been denied
membership in the Bellflower lodge several times. Both women said
they were tired of being members of the organization's ladies
auxiliary.
</P>
<P>
   ``It made me feel like a second-class citizen, that I wasn't
good enough to be a member of the lodge,'' Bonacci said.
</P>
<P>
   Gloria Allred, an attorney renowned for opening up the all-male
Friar's Club to women, is representing Bonacci and Etienne,
although no lawsuit has been filed to force their acceptance into
the Bellflower lodge.
</P>
<P>
   ``These things don't just happen by evolution, they have to be
fought for,'' Allred said. ``And like in this case, even after laws
are passed, many women still have to fight to make these laws the
reality.''
</P>
<P>
   Efforts to reach a spokesman for that lodge for comment were
unsuccessful.
</P>
<P>
   Elks leaders said the number of lodges that still refuse to
admit women is small, but didn't provide numbers.
</P>
<P>
   ``The majority of our membership has accepted women,'' said
James C. Varenhorst of Ludington, Mich., the grand exalted
ruler-elect for the Elks.
</P>
<P>
   Varenhorst acknowledged that court rulings, diminishing
membership and pressure from within the organization itself are
pushing for the inclusion of more women in the Elks.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is time to embrace all American citizens into our ranks,
male and female alike; if we do not, we will destroy our fraternity
and our proud legacy will become only history,'' Varenhorst said in
his acceptance speech.
</P>
<P>
   But Varenhorst also emphasized that each of the 2,200 lodges are
autonomous. New members are accepted by a two-thirds vote of
current lodge members.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is not my intent to force our lodges to tell them what they
have to do,'' Varenhorst said.
</P>
<P>
   He added: ``I would be a hypocrite if I didn't tell you I
believe God created two species, man and woman. Why should we not
be able to have two societies?''
</P>
<P>
   The Elks are among many service or fraternal organizations that
once excluded women. Others include the Rotary, Lions and Kiwanis
clubs, all with international memberships.
</P>
<P>
   The Elks, a 131-year-old fraternal organization, focuses on a
variety of social service projects, such as disabled children and
drug awareness. Last year, the group's 1.3 million members gave
more than $160 million to charity.
</P>
<P>
   At one time, some Elk lodges formed private clubs to hold their
liquor licenses, Varenhorst said, then transferred members to that
club to keep the right to exclude women.
</P>
<P>
   While many Elks organizations are now accepting women, their
numbers are still small in some areas.
</P>
<P>
   Wes Cunningham, a member of the Cass County Elks Lodge, said
there are no women among its 300 members, but he added that none
have applied.
</P>
<P>
   ``At this convention, I met two women who headed their lodges,''
Cunningham said. ``They couldn't have become president of a lodge
if there is a problem.''
</P>
<P>
   The bylaw change to include women came after the Elks were
challenged in several lawsuits.
</P>
<P>
   A 1987 Supreme Court decision involving Rotary International
clubs in California became the catalyst for many other service
organizations to begin including women.
</P>
<P>
   Most legal challenges to clubs have been against male-only
organizations, with plaintiffs arguing that women needed access to
the business connections that frequently occur behind club doors.
</P>
<P>
   On the same day of the Rotary decision, the executive committee
of the Lions Club International opened its membership to women.
Kiwanis International officially accepted its first women in 1987,
too.
</P>
<P>
   Despite threats that all the men would resign when women joined,
the various groups have only seen memberships soar. And women have
now been in the groups long enough to rise through the ranks to
high profile positions.
</P>
<P>
   This month, the Lions _ with more than 137,000 female members _
elected its first woman board member.
</P>
<P>
   At least 15 percent of the Rotary's 59,300 U.S. members are
women. Of the 29,000 Rotary clubs worldwide, nearly 1,900 had women
presidents in 1997-98.
</P>
<P>
   Those statistics may provide a welcome omen to Jewell M. Weston,
a member of the Elks for nearly three years. On Wednesday, Weston
scouted for other women to enter the room where the Elks' state
presidents and secretaries luncheon was held.
</P>
<P>
   She found none.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have had wholehearted support from the men,'' Weston said.
``I have always felt accepted.''
</P>
<P>
   But Allred said a more meaningful level of inclusion will be
reached when Weston and other women no longer can count their
numbers on their hands.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are still in the area of token firsts,'' Allred said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
