<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCHOOL-BOARD-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KC SCHOOL BOARD OFFERS ANOTHER SUPERINTENDENT CONTRACT OFFER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PHILLIP O'CONNOR  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ In a 7-2 vote, the Kansas City school board
offered the superintendent's job to Benjamin Demps Jr. late
Wednesday night.
</P>
<P>
   After a day of intensive background checking and a closed-door
meeting that ran for nearly an hour, the board agreed to extend an
offer to Demps, 65. He is a retired Federal Aviation Administration
official who served as director of the Oklahoma Department of Human
Services during the early 1990s. He is now semiretired and operates
an aviation consulting business.
</P>
<P>
   Demps is the third person to be offered the district's top job
in three weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Board members Terry Riley, John Rios, Lee Barnes Jr., Connie
Clark, Lance Loewenstein, Sandy Mayer and Helen Ragsdale voted for
Demps. Patricia Kurtz and Fifi Wiedeman voted against.
</P>
<P>
   ``Strong leadership is very paramount to the Kansas City school
district right now,'' Riley said after the vote. ``I think we found
a candidate we can all unite around.''
</P>
<P>
   Riley said of the conversation that led to the vote: ``Everyone
was on the same page. There was no adversarial conversation.''
</P>
<P>
   The deciding factor, he said, was leadership skills.
</P>
<P>
   Demps could not be reached late Wednesday for comment.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier Wednesday, school board members said they had received a
letter Wednesday from Mayor Kay Barnes, saying she wanted to
appoint a community task force to study how the district is
governed. Board member Sandy Mayer said Barnes told her that she
had received many calls from community members concerned about the
direction of the district. Barnes could not be reached for comment
Wednesday night.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday's late-night meeting came after four members, Barnes,
Clark, Ragsdale and Mayer, returned from Oklahoma City, where they
had spent the day interviewing Demps' former employees and
co-workers at the Oklahoma Department of Human Services.
</P>
<P>
   They also met with lawmakers, the administrator overseeing the
state employee's personnel office, and representatives of several
minority groups. In addition, they met with the publisher of a
local minority-owned newspaper, The Ebony Tribune, and with an
Oklahoma City Board of Education member.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was looking for someone who could make tough decisions, not
be compromised by special-interest groups and be an agent of
change,'' Mayer said. ``Based on the interviews conducted, I
believe he may be the perfect fit.''
</P>
<P>
   Those who traveled to Oklahoma said they had learned nothing
during the interviews that caused them concern.
</P>
<P>
   The Oklahoma trip was in addition to what district officials
described as the most exhaustive background investigation ever
conducted on a Kansas City superintendent candidate.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to the Oklahoma City visit, the district's search
firm also ordered a credit report, conducted a criminal background
check and reviewed local, state and federal courts in Oklahoma and
elsewhere for lawsuits involving Demps.
</P>
<P>
   District lawyers also reviewed congressional testimony involving
a training facility that Demps oversaw as a top-ranking FAA
official.
</P>
<P>
   Again, district officials said, they discovered nothing to cause
concern.
</P>
<P>
   The four members returned to the Board of Education building
about 10:40 p.m. and immediately went into the closed-door meeting.
</P>
<P>
   Demps is expected to come to Kansas City later this week to meet
with board members and community groups. Board members hope to
complete negotiations over the weekend.
</P>
<P>
   The school board is under orders from U.S. District Judge Dean
Whipple to reach agreement with a finalist by Monday. Failing that,
the court-appointed Desegregation Monitoring Committee has
recommended that it be allowed to appoint an interim superintendent
while the school board continues its search for someone to fill the
post permanently.
</P>
<P>
   Board members said they expect to offer Demps a two-year
contract that calls for an annual base salary of $140,000. Demps
also would be eligible for $33,800 in incentive pay if he is able
to meet certain performance measures, such as raising test scores.
</P>
<P>
   Demps was one of four finalists identified by a Desegregation
Monitoring Committee-dominated screening committee. The other
three, Jay T. Edwards, Pascal Forgione Jr. and John A. Martin, all
withdrew as candidates.
</P>
<P>
   Supporters said they hoped Demps could bring stability to a
district seemingly in constant turmoil. They also hope he can tame
a bureaucracy that some think is overstaffed and underworked.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
