<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOKS-PROMISE-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TWO YEARS LATER, LIBRARY WAITING ON CHIEFS' STAR TO COMPLETE
PLEDGE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MATT STEARNS  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ For years, Chiefs star Derrick Thomas has
been locally famous not only for his on-field achievements but for
his compassion toward Kansas City's needy children.
</P>
<P>
   The linebacker's Third &AMP; Long Foundation has been particularly
interested in helping children improve their reading skills.
</P>
<P>
   So it seemed a natural step when, nearly two years ago, Thomas
pledged $127,035 to pay the fines for lost and overdue books for
more than 4,000 Kansas City children. Paying the fines would allow
the children to borrow books from the library again.
</P>
<P>
   In anticipation of Thomas' check, the library forgave the fines.
</P>
<P>
   But so far, Thomas has paid less than half the money.
</P>
<P>
   Library officials aren't sure why. Thomas pointed to a familiar
Kansas City nemesis, recently retired Denver Broncos quarterback
John Elway, as the stumbling block. But Elway's supposed
involvement was news to his representatives.
</P>
<P>
   The first check, for $61,231.45, came on April 1, 1998 _ after,
library officials say, several calls to Thomas' spokeswoman, Nancy
Mitchell.
</P>
<P>
   Several calls and more than a year later, the rest of the money
is nowhere in sight.
</P>
<P>
   Teresa Stohs, the library's director of development, said it was
unusual for a donor to take so long making good on a pledge. But
she gives Thomas the benefit of the doubt.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel like it's unfair that the community thinks he's done
this great, wonderful thing,'' Stohs said. ``But he just did half
of a great, wonderful thing. We know he can do the other half.''
</P>
<P>
   Thomas plans to pay the remaining $65,803.55, Mitchell said. She
said he never intended to pay the money out of his own pocket. The
initial check came from grants made to the Third &AMP; Long Foundation,
Thomas' charitable organization, which has raised thousands of
dollars through celebrity sports events.
</P>
<P>
   Thomas' fund-raising plan for most of the rest hasn't worked out
as planned.
</P>
<P>
   The plan: Sell, for $1,000 each, 58 signed footballs _
signifying Thomas' jersey number _ commemorating his 100th career
sack. That's where Elway comes in: He was the victim, so Thomas
wanted him to sign the balls, too.
</P>
<P>
   According to Mitchell, Elway agreed.
</P>
<P>
   But, Mitchell said, Elway hasn't let retirement keep him from
sticking it to Kansas City.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have tried so many different ways, I can't even tell you,''
Mitchell said of her attempts to get Elway to sign. ``I said:
`Derrick, they're going to hang you if you don't get these balls
signed.'...I just don't know what to do.''
</P>
<P>
   Kathy Hatch, Elway's assistant, said Wednesday that she had
never heard of the plan and had never been approached by Mitchell.
Dennis Engel, president of the Elway Foundation, the quarterback's
charitable organization, said the same thing.
</P>
<P>
   ``That is bizarre,'' said Hatch, the gatekeeper for Elway
autograph requests. ``John's very good about that. He does so much
for so many other athletes.''
</P>
<P>
   Thomas' next move, Mitchell said, is to apply for a grant from
the National Football League for the remainder of the pledge
amount. Applications for the grant are due by Aug. 1, and Mitchell
said the grants should be made by late September.
</P>
<P>
   Thomas could write a check for the rest of the money, but he
won't, Mitchell said, because library officials have been rude in
demanding the money.
</P>
<P>
   Mitchell said Thomas did not renege on the deal. ``They knew the
balls were the resource to bring the dollars in,'' she said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
