u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CHINA-BOMB-NYT &LR;      07-15 0861
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHINA-BOMB-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHINA PROCLAIMS IT DESIGNED ITS OWN NEUTRON BOMB 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 By SETH FAISON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BEIJING _ China announced on Thursday that it has successfully
developed the design technology to make neutron bombs and
miniaturized nuclear weapons on its own, the first time it has made
these assertions publicly.
</P>
<P>
   Coming just days after Taiwan shifted its stance toward China,
prompting furious accusations from Beijing that the island it
considers a renegade province was moving toward independence, the
announcement appeared to be timed as a pointed reminder of China's
military capability.
</P>
<P>
   China has always reserved the right to use military force to
achieve its cherished goal of reunification with Taiwan, if
peaceful methods and negotiation fail, and it reiterated that
position again on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   The announcement concerning the neutron bomb came at a news
conference held to deliver a rebuttal to the Cox Committee report,
issued by a congressional committee in May, which accused China of
systematically stealing American nuclear technology.
</P>
<P>
   The Cox Committee accused China of having stolen information on
the designs for the neutron bomb as well as for the W-88, the most
advanced miniaturized warhead.
</P>
<P>
   At the news conference in Beijing on Thursday, a senior
official, Zhao Qi-zheng, spoke at length about why he thought the
Cox report was misleading, full of lies and racist. He did not take
any questions about the neutron bomb, which was mentioned in a
passing reference in a 36-page report _ entitled ``Facts Speak
Louder Than Words and Lies Will Collapse on Themselves'' _ that was
released simultaneously.
</P>
<P>
   Yet in case anyone did not immediately grasp the significance of
the report, the New China News Agency carried a dispatch entitled
``China Masters Neutron Bomb Technology.''
</P>
<P>
   ``China has already mastered the neutron bomb design
technology,'' the dispatch begins, saying that it began work on the
topic in the 1970s, when the United States and the Soviet Union
intensified their arms race. It does not say when China succeeded
in achieving its design technology, and omitted further details
such as whether China had conducted tests, begun production or
deployed the weapon.
</P>
<P>
   ``The neutron bomb seems quite mysterious to ordinary people,''
the report says. ``In fact, it is a special kind of H-bomb. Since
China has already possessed atom bomb and H-bomb technologies, it
is quite logical and natural for it to master the neutron bomb
technology.''
</P>
<P>
   The neutron bomb is designed to kill people with enhanced
radiation while leaving buildings intact. No nation is known to
have deployed a neutron bomb, but the Cox Committee report said
that China had tested the weapon in 1988 after having stolen the
design information in the late 1970s from the Lawrence Livermore
Laboratory.
</P>
<P>
   The neutron bomb, or W-70 warhead, contains elements that may be
used either as a strategic thermonuclear weapon, or as an enhanced
radiation weapon.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday's assertion, a three-sentence reference in a long
rebuttal to the Cox report, was presented as part of a declaration
that China's scientific advances have been made over the years
without the benefit of espionage, as the Cox report alleges.
</P>
<P>
   ``As everyone knows, since the 1950s, China has successfully
overcome a series of technological problems and mastered nuclear
weapon technology within a reasonably short time,'' the report
says, ``by relying on its own forces, on its large number of
talented scientists full of creative spirit and on the energetic
support of the people throughout the country.''
</P>
<P>
   Zhao added that a principal implication of the report is that
``Chinese can't be as smart as Americans, so they must have stolen
the technology,'' which he called a racist allegation.
</P>
<P>
   He also repeated China's position that the Cox report was cooked
up by people whose intention was not to find the truth, but to
slander China and to damage U.S.-China relations.
</P>
<P>
   Asked if he saw some connection between the Cox report and
NATO's bombing of the Chinese Embassy, which many Chinese believe
was deliberate, Zhao said no. But he equated the chances that the
bombing was accidental with rolling triple snake eyes in dice.
</P>
<P>
   Zhao was also asked whether China would hold military exercises
in response to Taiwan's announcement that it will no longer follow
a `one-China' formula in its dealings with the mainland and will
instead call Taiwan and China two separate countries.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is difficult for me to answer this question,'' Zhao said.
</P>
<P>
   Zhao's news conference was held on a day when American officials
began talks with China's Foreign Ministry on how to compensate
Beijing for NATO's bombing of the Chinese Embassy in Belgrade on
May 9, which killed three Chinese journalists.
</P>
<P>
   Washington agencies asked for comment early on Thursday morning
did not return telephone calls.
</P>
<P>
   China has consistently denied the allegations of spying made by
the committee, formally known as the Select Committee on United
States National Security and Military/Commercial Concerns with the
People's Republic of China.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
