<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-MARINERS-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MARINERS TO SPORT NEW LINEUP AT NEW BALLPARK 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By DAN RALEY  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ The wraps come off Safeco Field and Jay Buhner
Thursday night, with both the brand new ballpark and bald right
fielder sure to glisten under the Seattle skyline.
</P>
<P>
   One brings outdoor big-league baseball back to the city after a
30-year absence; the other returns a significant home run bat to
the lineup, one missing for two months.
</P>
<P>
   Yet the ballpark unveiling was tempered a bit Wednesday as the
Mariners, still dealing with residue from Sunday's brawl at Dodger
Stadium, placed outfielders Brian Hunter and Charles Gipson on the
15-day disabled list. The loss of these two players _ Hunter to a
hyperextended left knee, Gipson to a separated right shoulder _
carries serious ramifications.
</P>
<P>
   ``We lost most of our speed we were so proud of in one fell
swoop,'' said Woody Woodward, vice president of baseball
operations.
</P>
<P>
   To find replacements for the 7:05 Safeco opener against San
Diego, the Mariners traded swiftness for power: they activated
Buhner from the DL and recalled outfielder Ozzie Timmons from Class
AAA Tacoma.
</P>
<P>
   ``It looks like the speed part of our club (is gone),'' manager
Lou Piniella said. ``But if the pitching gets better and we catch
the ball well, we should be fine.''
</P>
<P>
   Mariners left-hander Jamie Moyer and San Diego right-hander Andy
Ashby, an All-Star selection, will be the first to trudge around
the mound at Safeco. But not before the $517 million ballpark has
been duly christened.
</P>
<P>
   Pregame ceremonies will include a ``Shoeless Joe'' reading by
Dave Niehaus; Fred Hutchinson's 5-year-old grandson, Joey, running
the bases; symphony music; fireworks; air dancers; and the
ceremonial first pitch by a mystery guest, a person the club
Wednesday still was keeping a closely guarded secret.
</P>
<P>
   The Mariners took batting practice in their new palatial estate
late Wednesday afternoon. They were left noticeably wide-eyed by
their new digs.
</P>
<P>
   Their spacious clubhouse, with its big-screen TV sets, could
have doubled as a sports bar.
</P>
<P>
   ``You want to send someone out around here, he can hide for a
week,'' Piniella wisecracked.
</P>
<P>
   Some players detected a chill while standing on the field. A
welcome chill. Buhner plans to wear long underwear under his
uniform.
</P>
<P>
   Balls flew out of the park with little trouble, too. Both Ken
Griffey Jr. and John Mabry sent drives ricocheting off the Hit It
Here Cafe in right field.
</P>
<P>
   Everyone seemed caught up in the significance of the moment.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a lot of emotion riding on what's going to be going on
here,'' Buhner said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's about as nice as you can get for a ballpark,'' said
reliever Frankie Rodriguez, whose previous big-league tours of duty
had been spent at the Kingdome and Minnesota's Metrodome.
Laughingly, he added, ``This is a little better.''
</P>
<P>
   Now all the Mariners have to do is put on a team on the field
that matches their impressive surroundings. The club, however,
comes off the All-Star break with a five-game losing streak, its
longest of the season.
</P>
<P>
   The fight did nothing to improve matters. Not only did the
Mariners lose two outfielders to injury, Buhner and relievers Jose
Mesa, Jose Paniagua and Damaso Marte are facing fines, suspensions
or both for being ejected from Sunday's brawl.
</P>
<P>
   In their favor, player punishment won't be determined any time
soon. Complicating matters, officials from both leagues will be
involved because the matchup was an interleague contest played in a
National League ballpark. Both sides need to review videotapes, and
the NL office didn't request a copy of the fight footage until
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   NL president Leonard Coleman will mete out the penalties in
consultation with AL president Gene Budig. No more than one player
will be suspended at one time.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's going to put a serious cramp on our roster, no doubt
about that,'' Woodward said.
</P>
<P>
   Said Hunter: ``I'm disappointed by the way it happened. If it
had happened during a game, I probably could explain it.''
</P>
<P>
   There are stiffer penalties for players on the DL who get
involved in on-field unpleasantness. Buhner might be fined as much
as $10,000.
</P>
<P>
   The right fielder, out since May 18 with a severe hamstring
sprain, could find himself returning from his injury only to sit
back down with a suspension. He planned to call Budig this morning
and plead his case _ he was only coming to the aid of an injured
teammate, Gipson, and put Dodgers reliever Pedro Borbon in a
headlock, throwing no punches.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll tell him I'll pay the fine,'' Buhner said. ``I did what
anybody would have done. I'm not going to let a teammate with a
separated shoulder get pummeled. I'd do it again.''
</P>
<P>
   Gipson was expected to return to Seattle Thursday. He had X-rays
taken at a Los Angeles hospital and was still in a lot of pain
early this week, trainer Rick Griffin said.
</P>
<P>
   In sweats, Hunter walked stiff-legged as he entered Safeco Field
and watched batting practice. Looking for a positive, the
Vancouver, Wash., native said he felt lucky to be present even if
he couldn't play.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is so great for the community, for the Northwest,''
Hunter said. ``This is everybody's ballpark.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
