<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-15 02:36 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0723 &Cx1f; tth-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBA-VECSEY-COLUMN-SPI     07-15 0872
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-VECSEY-COLUMN-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KEEP OFF THE GRASS? NOT MARINERS' BUHNER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By LAURA VECSEY  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ Cold weather. Hot weather. Rain or sun. Roof open or
roof closed. Doesn't matter.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm playing, regardless,'' Jay Buhner said Wednesday with a
cat-ate-the-bird grin creeping out from somewhere in the middle of
that famous Buhner goatee.
</P>
<P>
   As if they were going to be able to keep him off the field.
</P>
<P>
   As if there was any chance the Mariners right fielder was going
to stay off the grass.
</P>
<P>
   On the eve of a historic Seattle sporting moment, after two
months on the disabled list with a strained hamstring, Buhner's
marvelous recovery comes just in the nick of time.
</P>
<P>
   This week, in the wake of an on-field brawl that left Mariners
outfielders Charles Gipson and Brian Hunter injured and on the
disabled list, Buhner submitted to two rounds of hail-Mary
acupuncture sessions and says he's fine.
</P>
<P>
   Not 100 percent, but fine.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've got the green light,'' he said. ``I know it would have
been crazy to rush back just to play, but I would have done it
anyway.''
</P>
<P>
   As if there were any chance he was going to say anything else.
</P>
<P>
   ``They stuck needles all down the back of my leg and in my lower
back. It sounds kind of kooky but it works.''
</P>
<P>
   You bet it works. There is more chance that the Public
Facilities District and the Mariners brass will share a beer
Thursday night than that Buhner would be on the bench when the
Mariners take the field in their new park.
</P>
<P>
   Safeco Field was not built for Jay Buhner. Not exactly, anyway.
</P>
<P>
   And we all know that popular wisdom has it that the Mariners'
new ballyard is the house that Griffey built or the house that
Randy Johnson built or the house that everybody built even when
they voted it down by 1,000 votes.
</P>
<P>
   But when the field opens Thursday to the strains of the Seattle
Symphony Orchestra playing the theme from ``2001: A Space Odyssey''
and to the lonesome freight train whistles calling from out behind
right field, the entire festive affair will be a testament to
big-money, state-of-the-art sports palaces.
</P>
<P>
   It will also be a testament to the great outdoors and vistas of
Seattle and to the splendor of grass. Baseball the way it ought to
be.
</P>
<P>
   No one deserves to feel the plush carpet of Kentucky bluegrass
beneath his feet more than Buhner, the veteran Mariner whose
12-year tenure is longer than Ken Griffey's and nearly as long as
that of Edgar Martinez.
</P>
<P>
   All those years pounding away on the turf-covered concrete in
the Kingdome have taken their toll on Buhner. It is only fitting
and only fair that he should be out there where the legs and back
and knees can catch a break.
</P>
<P>
   ``In a nutshell, (playing on turf) knocked some years off my
career. It's almost a given that it will do that to guys,'' Buhner
said. ``So coming onto this grass isn't going to do too much for me
because basically it's too late. But the biggest thing it does for
guys like Junior and A-Rod, it's going to help them before it
sneaks up on them.
</P>
<P>
   ``But grass, that's where the game is supposed to be played.
Period. It's going to be nice to go out there and stand in it.''
</P>
<P>
   Buhner is adamant that he will always miss the Kingdome _ a
place where he and his mates made that unforgettable effort to save
baseball in Seattle.
</P>
<P>
   The Kingdome gave us Buhner Buzz Cut Night and the Buhner Bone
Yard and a place where the power-hitting Buhner became one of only
three players in history to hit 40 home runs in three consecutive
seasons.
</P>
<P>
   You can understand that there is sentimental attachment to the
old concrete dome. But Buhner, perhaps as much as any Mariner, is
ready to let go of the past and embrace the future.
</P>
<P>
   He said the opening night of the new ballpark will affirm
everything that has happened to the Mariners, good and bad and
everything in between.
</P>
<P>
   For all his grousing and attempts at being a tough guy, Buhner
always has a way of putting the big picture in perspective _
especially when it comes to the game and the team he loves.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think this (new) place represents all the hard work over the
years and what we did in '95,'' he said. ``It's going to be
exciting. I think it's going to be real emotional from the
standpoint that there's going to be a lot of stuff going through my
head. I know I'll be thinking about the reason why this all
happened.
</P>
<P>
   ``I mean, from what was going on in this organization when I
first came over to now, what a difference. When I first came here,
it was terrible. You were losing all the time. It was a revolving
door not only for players but for managers and ownership. A big
goal when I first came over was to try and finish above .500,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``But now look at this place. This is unbelievable. To come in
here and have two (American League West championship) banners out
there and a lot more to come. It's going to be a pretty neat
night.''
</P>
<P>
   Here's hoping it's more than one pretty neat night _ for Buhner
and the Mariners and everyone who chooses to be part of whatever is
ahead in the new park filled with light and grass.
</P>
<P>
   Laura Vecsey is a P-I columnist.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-15-99 0236EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
