Drysdale and his favorite, Dodgers outfielder Willie Davis.
</P>
<P>
   But to a kid so smitten with basketball, baseball didn't seem as
exciting.
</P>
<P>
   ``Like a lot of kids, you kind of think baseball's boring,
that's the perception, and as an outfielder you stand around a
lot,'' Gwynn said. ``And really trying to learn all I could about
the game, you began to understand the nuances of the game, and it
became really fun.
</P>
<P>
   ``It became a lot of fun for me to learn about the history of
the game. I heard Pete Rose talking about, `Look in a book, look in
a book.' You know, what book? So finally I went and got one of
those baseball encyclopedias, and you start to read and you start
to understand.''
</P>
<P>
   Gwynn realized he knew more than he thought. The harder he
worked, the faster the fundamentals he'd been taught years before
came back to him. But he also found that baseball was a little like
those Walla Walla onions _ the more layers you peeled, the more
layers you found.
</P>
<P>
   That process of discovery, even at 39 years old, remains Gwynn's
greatest joy. Bochy could name only three players who retained
Gwynn's passion for the game at that age, and all three _ Paul
Molitor, Eddie Murray and Alan Trammell _ are probable Hall of
Famers.
</P>
<P>
   ``When he's not playing, I can pretty much assure you he's
thinking about what he would do in that situation,'' said Trammell,
Detroit Tigers hitting coach and co-owner with Gwynn of the San
Diego School of Baseball. ``Everybody watches, but I wonder
sometimes whether they're really thinking, `What would I have
done?' And they should, because that can help you become a better
ballplayer. That's what I tried to do, and that's what Tony Gwynn
does.''
</P>
<P>
   The best advice Gwynn ever received came from his first manager,
Dick Williams, who emphasized the importance of thinking something
out before doing it. Williams would let players know _ loudly _
when they'd made a mental error, and to Gwynn, there's no worse
feeling.
</P>
<P>
   And there's no better feeling than making the smart play.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you're a position player, they say all it is is swinging a
bat, and there's so much more to it,'' Gwynn said. ``It's defense,
offense, knowing your ballpark, knowing the pitchers, other
hitters, it's a lot. And as you get into it, man, you can really
enjoy this game. This game can be as much fun as anything, because
not only do you need physical ability, you need mental ability,
too.''
</P>
<P>
   (insert copy break)
</P>
<P>
   Gwynn was not a great outfielder when he came to the majors, but
by 1991 he had won five Gold Gloves. There's an excitement in his
voice as he talks about throwing out a runner at home plate
recently _ not because of the achievement, but because it reflected
a drill he had worked on with a coach and two rookies during spring
training.
</P>
<P>
   He's also improved as a hitter, turning on inside pitches better
and using his years of preparation to better predict what pitch
will come next. When a game in Cincinnati was suspended with Gwynn
at the plate last year, Gwynn told coach Tim Flannery that, when
the game was resumed, he would see a slider on the first pitch and
smack a game-tying double to left-center. It happened.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've probably seen 2,000 of his hits, and I've seen them from
every angle,'' said Flannery, also a former teammate. ``And I know
that he's a better hitter today than he's ever been.''
</P>
<P>
   History surrounds Gwynn, and he's trying not to let the hype
distract him. But that's not easy. During a break in a recent
interview, he was approached by a team official with a model of a
bus that will bear Gwynn's likeness and the slogan, ``Next Stop:
Cooperstown.'' Gwynn groaned.
</P>
<P>
   A few days earlier, he had the same reaction when he parked his
car at Qualcomm Stadium, looked up and saw ``TONY 3000'' in giant
placards on a mountain off the side of Friars Road.
</P>
<P>
   The stacks of memorabilia have piled up in his lockers, but
there is room for chairs for the stream of visitors. Mariners
catcher Tom Lampkin, a former teammate, came by a few weeks ago and
chatted with Gwynn at length.
</P>
<P>
   Lampkin had no hits in five games before seeing Gwynn. In his
next five games after they spoke, he had nine hits.
</P>
<P>
   ``It seems like every time I talk to him, he gives me something
else to think about,'' Lampkin said. ``And it may be something I've
heard before, but when Tony says it, it clicks. It's like with my
kids _ I can tell them to do something, but until they hear it from
a Spice Girl or 'N Sync, it's not going to register.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tony has a knack for saying things in a way that people will
understand. He can teach hitting to a 5-year-old or a 40-year-old,
because he knows how to relate to people so well. We talked about
confidence, and he convinced me that I could hit in a matter of
about 20 minutes.''
</P>
<P>
   (insert copy break)
</P>
<P>
   When Trammell mentions Gwynn's name to his pupils on the Tigers,
he has noticed they pay more attention. Gwynn's presence is
invaluable to the young Padres, and when a recent calf strain made
flying difficult, Gwynn drove from San Diego to Phoenix, and then
to Milwaukee, to be with the team.
</P>
<P>
   His effort matched those of some Padres fans, who had bought
tickets to those games in case Gwynn got No. 3,000 on the road.
Gwynn is a civic hero for staying in San Diego and turning down
chances to leave for more money. That loyalty impressed at least
one member of the 3,000-hit club, Hall of Famer Al Kaline, who
recently wrote Gwynn a congratulatory letter.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really admire someone like him,'' said Kaline, who spent his
whole career with Detroit and is one of 21 players with 3,000 hits.
``Money is so, so important to so many athletes today, and he
decided to play where he and his family are happy.''
</P>
<P>
   Gwynn wants to get the 3,000th hit at home, and although he
tries to downplay the significance of the milestone, he knows it
will make him nervous when he gets closer.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm going to try my darndest not to get too hyped about it,
because I know, when you get that close, you're going to be,''
Gwynn said. ``You probably won't be able to sleep at night. Knowing
me, I'll be looking at videotape of the guy starting that night,
all of that.''
</P>
<P>
   In that regard, No. 3,000 will be a lot like No. 1.
</P>
<P>
   Called up from Class AAA Hawaii in July 1982, Gwynn knew his
first game would be against the Philadelphia Phillies. The whole
flight to California, he fretted about the notion of facing future
Hall of Famer Steve Carlton. As soon as he got off the plane, Gwynn
bought a newspaper to check that night's pitchers. Carlton was not
scheduled that night, and Gwynn got his first hit, a double off
reliever Sid Monge.
</P>
<P>
   The stadium scoreboard announced Gwynn's accomplishment, and a
Phillies infielder trailing the play jogged up and offered his
hand.
</P>
<P>
   ``Congratulations,'' said Pete Rose, whose name sits atop the
all-time hits list in a book he inspired Gwynn to buy. ``Don't try
to catch me in one night.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
