<SLUG> BC-FEINSTEIN-ISSUESBOX-SFCHRON(W/FEINSTEIN-VEEP) </SLUG>
  
 FEINSTEIN ON THE ISSUES  &HT;     By MARC SANDALOW 
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
Among the topics Sen. Dianne Feinstein discussed Wednesday with
California reporters in Washington:
<P>
   HEALTH CARE
</P>
<P>
   Feinstein said the Democratic Patients' Bill of Rights Bill is
dead, but added that Republicans will pay a cost in next year's
election for having defeated it. ``I do think a patients' bill of
rights becomes a major campaign issue. A very important issue in
California,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   NUCLEAR LAB SECURITY
</P>
<P>
   Feinstein said she is very concerned about lax security, and
suggested that the lab's relationship with the University of
California should be re-evaluated. ``This is hard for me, because
the University of California is in my state and I am a big fan of
the university, but I question the academic overlay and the
academic administration. There is a whole different culture that
permeates that is not conducive to security,'' Feinstein said. ``We
have to take some vigorous and forceful action to create a new
administrative structure that has a much greater emphasis on
security.''
</P>
<P>
   TAXES
</P>
<P>
   Feinstein said Republican plans to cut more than as much as &LR; 
 &LR; $800 billion in taxes over the next 10 years are too large. She
said she supports a much narrower tax cut that would eliminate the
marriage penalty, make the research and development tax credit
permanent and provide relief for health care and education
expenses.
</P>
<P>
   FUND RAISING
</P>
<P>
   Feinstein, who spent $9 million in her 1992 Senate race and $15
million in 1994, said she has raised a little over $2 million so
far. How much she needs to raise depends on how well financed her
competitor is. ``You raise what you have to raise to be
competitive, and we will do that,'' Feinstein said. ``We'll raise
what we have to raise.''
</P>
<P>
   HILLARY CLINTON'S NEW YORK SENATE CANDIDACY
</P>
<P>
   Feinstein said the first lady will be a formidable candidate but
will face a tough campaign to get elected. President Clinton should
feel free to raise money for his wife, she said, but he ought to
let her campaign on her own. ``He's entitled to campaign for his
wife,'' Feinstein said. ``I'd say do the fund-raisers, but let her
campaign alone.''
</P>
<P>
   VICE PRESIDENT AL GORE
</P>
<P>
   Feinstein said she supports Gore over former Sen. Bill Bradley.
She said reports of Gore's poor campaign skills are overstated, and
that there is plenty of confidence among Democratic senators. ``I
think there is kind of a media thing going on right now that isn't
really the reality,'' Feinstein said. ``The Al Gore that debated
Jack Kemp, the Al Gore that debated Ross Perot, is a formidable
candidate, and I think that is the Al Gore we are going to see on
the stump.''
</P>
</TEXT>
