<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OSTLER-COLUMN-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A SCENE TO WATCH WITH EYES SHUT
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     By SCOTT OSTLER 
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &LR;   &LR;  SAN FRANCISCO _ Here comes the orgy scene!
<P>
   The flower of the city's movie-critic community gathered at
Metreon Wednesday for the press screening of ``Eyes Wide Shut,''
and just before the orgy scene, poof! Screen goes black, sound
continues.
</P>
<P>
   &LR; Tres  &LR; Kubrick, no? Director Stanley Kubrick, forced to re-edit
the orgy scene to achieve an R rating, simply killed the video!
Wow! Sheer genius.
</P>
<P>
   Stanley is simultaneously thumbing his nose at the ratings
people, doing a cosmic riff on the movie title and telling us,
``The imagination is your greatest love tool.'' How, like, deep.
</P>
<P>
   No. It was simply a false fire alarm that played havoc with the
projection system at the world's most technically sophisticated
flick barn.
</P>
<P>
   The critics, perhaps predictably, were critical of the
 &LR; celluloidus interruptus.  &LR; And when the movie was re-started, with
video but no audio, the critics supplied the narration as Kubrick
spun in his grave.
</P>
<P>
   The whole thing was a like a scene from a Stanley Kubrick movie.
</P>
<P>
   IN OTHER cultural news, City Attorney Louise Renne is suing the
owner of a Chestnut Street bar for allowing his customers to smoke.
</P>
<P>
   One smoky San Francisco bar down, 999 to go. Hey, I feel a song
coming on.
</P>
<P>
   If Renne plans to turn this into a crusade, she'd better pack a
lunch for the two city Health Department inspectors who, in their
spare time, handle enforcement of the no-smoking bar law.
</P>
<P>
   No word yet on how the mayor feels about this get-tough policy,
but the usual cloud of cigar smoke coming out of Willie's favorite
smoky bar on Columbus is an indication that he's mulling it over.
</P>
<P>
   STILL SIMMERING (I am) about Florida lawyer Morris Engelberg
trying to tell San Francisco how to honor Joe DiMaggio.
</P>
<P>
   ``Can you believe,'' asks Louisa Arndt, ``this lawyer purporting
to represent the interests of the most low-profile guy in baseball
history wants us to name the airport after DiMaggio? Very unclear
on the concept.''
</P>
<P>
   Solution. Airports are notorious sources of annoyance,
aggravation and noise pollution. So we put DiMaggio's name on North
Beach Playground and rename our airport Morris Engelberg
International.
</P>
<P>
   CHICAGO, of all places, has honored Joe DiMaggio in grand style.
</P>
<P>
   Chicagoans are in the process of converting an entire city block
of Little Italy to Joe DiMaggio Piazza, with large fountains and a
life-size bronze statue of the Yankee Clipper.
</P>
<P>
   Why Chicago? Because Chicago is the home of the National Italian
American Sports Hall of Fame, of which Joe was the first inductee.
</P>
<P>
   We could take a lesson: If you want to honor someone, just do
it, ba-da-bing.
</P>
<P>
   FLORIDA FOLLIES: They're still fine-tuning the execution process
down there in Florida. ``Old Sparky,'' the electric chair, turned
human heads into Roman candles, so they got a new chair, which
caused a nosebleed in Tiny Davis as Tiny was being fried last week.
</P>
<P>
   Tiny was a 344-pounder (and how come tiny guys are never
nicknamed Biggie?) who murdered a woman and her two daughters. You
hate to see a guy like that suffer a bloody nose.
</P>
<P>
   I oppose capital punishment, but not because it stains your
shirt. Getting our terminology straight, then: I'm a bleeding-heart
liberal but not a bleeding-nose liberal.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
