<HEADLINE>
FOR RANGERS, PROGRESS GOES WITH PATIENCE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RANDY GALLOWAY 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ARLINGTON, Texas _ After a Rangers' exhibition in Tampa one
night last March, Doug Melvin was headed for the exits when he
walked up on an intense baseball pow-wow.
</P>
<P>
   It was Yankees general manager Brian Cashman huddled in deep
conversation with a couple of his front-office assistants.
</P>
<P>
   ``What are you guys doing _ plotting how to win 125 games again
this season?'' joked Melvin.
</P>
<P>
   Cashman, who had just watched somebody named Jeff Zimmerman
breeze through the heart of the Yankees' batting order, gave Melvin
one of those looks.
</P>
<P>
   ``Not exactly,'' he told the Rangers GM. ``George
\RSteinbrenner\S saw that Zimmerman kid pitch tonight, and he's
going to want to know where he came from and why we don't have him.
We're trying to get our stories straight. This meeting is about how
to cover our butts.''
</P>
<P>
   Such is life, huh? Nobody gets out of this world alive without
proper butt-coverage.
</P>
<P>
   And now it's Melvin's turn.
</P>
<P>
   Play resumes tonight following the All-Star Game break, and
Melvin, it seems, has two clear-cut options to ponder with the
Rangers.
</P>
<P>
   One, he can be extremely cautious between now and the
major-league trading deadline at the end of July. Do the endless
phone work, gather information on what pitching help might be
available, but at the same time be picky, hesitant and protective
of all top minor-league prospects. Plus, Melvin slams the phone
down on the ear of the next media Einstein who asks if left fielder
Rusty Greer is going to New York for a pitching puzzle named Andy
Pettitte.
</P>
<P>
   Or option No. 2 _ try to impress the new bosses in Arlington,
meaning owner Tom Hicks and team president Jim Lites, by sticking
your neck way out there. Trade Greer, throw in that hot-shot third
base prospect named Lamb at Tulsa, and if necessary, give up the
kid, Mateo. Do anything to get to the World Series this season. Or
get canned trying.
</P>
<P>
   But if successful, what a nice kiss-up move from Melvin to Hicks
_ a World Series in Arlington to go along with Tom's new Stanley
Cup.
</P>
<P>
   The inclination is to think Melvin will sit tight behind door
No. 1, but that means you weren't paying attention last July. A
huge gamble went down at the trading deadline, and St. Louis is
still chuckling over the steal of young third baseman Fernando
Tatis. The only consolation for the Rangers is the trade helped win
the division, and that shortstop Royce Clayton is much better than
what he has shown thus far this season.
</P>
<P>
   Melvin, as we know, is not scared. Which is my point. This is a
season to be more realistic than brave.
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers can win the AL West with what they have. Unless,
however, a surprise deal suddenly pops open, there is no trade out
there to transform the Rangers into a prime World Series contender.
</P>
<P>
   For his part, Hicks is pushing to win by whatever means, but to
his credit has become a huge discipline of long-term growth through
the farm system.
</P>
<P>
   Hicks isn't going to say it publicly, and Melvin certainly
won't, but even with $70 million worth of payroll, the pieces
aren't right yet for a World Series this season.
</P>
<P>
   And as someone who always preached the
win-now-at-any-minor-league-cost philosophy, here's a curveball:
</P>
<P>
   Sit tight, Doug Melvin. Try to tweak the rotation with a
mid-range deal, but wait on 2000.
</P>
<P>
   There are a couple of reasons for my crawfishing. Hicks now
gives the Rangers all the financial muscle they need in the
off-season free-agent market. Granted, the pickings will be slim
this winter (Kenny Rogers, Chuck Finley, Juan Guzman, etc.), but
the Rangers will now always be a strong player in this area. Or in
chasing a high-dollar pitcher another team can't afford.
</P>
<P>
   And the second factor is the Rangers now have a farm system that
is beginning to hum with prospects. The drought is over. It is only
a matter of time.
</P>
<P>
   The farm system has given them a sensation in Zimmerman and a
reliable lefty in Mike Venafro for the bullpen this season. Free
agency brought in Rafael Palmeiro, the best sign of the off-season
by any team.
</P>
<P>
   Melvin flunked on veteran free-agent pitcher Mark Clark, but out
of nowhere, 39-year old Mike Morgan has done what Clark was
supposed to do.
</P>
<P>
   Ruben Mateo arrived a bit sooner than expected, struggled early,
but is beginning to bloom. He's a center-field star waiting to
happen.
</P>
<P>
   For short-term and long-term the Rangers have never been this
well-positioned. After 28 years, why suddenly rush it, or screw it
up?
</P>
<P>
   ``My focus for the trading deadline is on winning now, but my
goal is to also be winning four and five years from now,'' said
Melvin. ``With Mr. Hicks, we will do what's necessary to win. But
he's the first to tell me to do what's right for the future good of
the organization.''
</P>
<P>
   It's coming in Arlington, it's just not there yet. More
patience, please.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
