<SLUG> BC-CAR-MOTORSPORTS-REPORT-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FENDERS ON INDY-CAR DOES NOT FLY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOHN STURBIN 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Anyone who follows motorsports knows that superspeedway
developer Bruton Smith and his right-hand man, H.A. ``Humpy''
Wheeler, are two of the most innovative thinkers in the business.
</P>
<P>
   Their list of pioneering ideas includes racetrack condominiums,
amenities like swank restaurants and health clubs, introduction of
personal seat licenses and taking stock-car racing to Wall Street.
</P>
<P>
   Those initiatives _ every one a home run _ have made Smith and
Wheeler powerful and wealthy men.
</P>
<P>
   But there has been a swing-and-a-miss along the way. Let's not
forget the dual-banking concept that created controversy and havoc
through the 24-degree turns at Texas Motor Speedway before the
racetrack was reconfigured and repaved last summer.
</P>
<P>
   That brings us to Smith's latest ``cause celebre'' _ the
proposed introduction of fenders on Indy-cars as fielded by the Pep
Boys Indy Racing League. In the name of increased spectator safety
_ and greater sponsor visibility _ Smith and Wheeler have submitted
drawings of Indy-cars with fenders to IRL founder Tony George and
Leo Mehl, the organization's executive director.
</P>
<P>
   TMS is home to two of five IRL events run at Smith-owned
facilities in 1999. The IRL season will end in Fort Worth on Oct.
17. Will that be the last Indy Racing League event run at an SMI
facility?
</P>
<P>
   Don't count on it, mainly because both parties need each other
to survive. But in spite of the success the IRL has enjoyed at TMS
since June 1997, TMS executive vice president and general manager
Eddie Gossage has not signed a sanction agreement for 2000.
</P>
<P>
   Smith and Wheeler have been championing the fendered concept
since early May, when a three-car crash at Smith's Lowe's Motor
Speedway in Concord, N.C., sent a wheel and debris flying into the
grandstands. Three spectators were killed and eight injured in that
incident. While SMI's concern for spectator safety is admirable,
the idea of putting fenders on Indy-cars falls into the category of
dual-banking.
</P>
<P>
   It's a swing-and-a-miss.
</P>
<P>
   If you put fenders on open-wheel cars, they obviously are no
longer open-wheel cars and by definition no longer Indy-cars. They
have no connection with racing conducted at the Indianapolis Motor
Speedway since 1911, one of the reasons George founded the IRL in
1994. What Smith and Wheeler envision are cars that resemble Can-Am
cars, which are in museums, or World Sports Car prototypes, which
do not race on ovals, or the Batmobile, of which there is one.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you start closing the fenders in, you're going to run into
other problems,'' said Fort Worth's Johnny Rutherford, a three-time
Indy 500 champion and the IRL's director of special events. ``Did
you see the full-bodied Mercedes take off at LeMans?''
</P>
<P>
   The front end of a closed-coupe Mercedes-Benz prototype lifted
during the 24 Hours of LeMans last month. The car flipped five
times before landing on its roof _ fortunately in a clearing
surrounded by trees.
</P>
<P>
   ``Instead of throwing a wheel into the stands,'' Rutherford
said, ``you could end up throwing the whole car up there.''
</P>
<P>
   Since the Lowe's tragedy, the IRL has mandated installation of a
cable restraint system designed to keep the wheels attached to each
car's tub. Engine horsepower has been cut and will be further
reduced next year. Meanwhile, SMI uniformly has raised the height
of the catch fencing at its tracks that play host to IRL events by
6 feet, from 15 to 21 feet.
</P>
<P>
   If Smith and Wheeler are determined to do away with open-wheel
racing at their tracks, they might want to consider creating a
fendered ``Indy-car'' series of their own.
</P>
<P>
   But there's no need to reinvent open-wheel racing. On this idea,
they have swung-and-missed.
SPOTLIGHT ON...
</P>
<P>
   Terry Labonte envisions new Hendrick team spirit
Perhaps it's time to start referring to Hendrick Motorsports as
Team Turmoil.
</P>
<P>
   Wally Dallenbach, driver of the forever star-crossed No. 25
Budweiser Chevrolet Monte Carlo, reportedly will not be rehired for
the 2000 season.
</P>
<P>
   Terry Labonte, a two-time NASCAR Winston Cup champion, began his
off-week on Tuesday denying rumors that he was headed for Robert
Yates Racing in 2000.
</P>
<P>
   And with each completed race, three-time and reigning Cup
champion Jeff Gordon's hopes for a third consecutive title are
evaporating like Unocal 76 fumes.
</P>
<P>
   The timing of Dallenbach's impending pink slip was interesting,
in light of Labonte's comments during a national teleconference
Tuesday morning.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're really working toward working more together like we used
to,'' said Labonte, driver of the No. 5 Kellogg's Chevy. ``We kind
of went in separate directions a few years ago.''
</P>
<P>
   That was a back-handed reference to the
communication/cooperation gap that opened between Gordon and crew
chief Ray Evernham during their magnificent run the past two years
and the teams fielded for Labonte and Dallenbach. Specifically,
that gap widened during the court-ordered house arrest of team
owner Rick Hendrick, who also has been battling bone cancer since
1997.
</P>
<P>
   Hendrick's leukemia now is in remission, and he is more involved
at the shop. Meanwhile, Gordon and Evernham have proven to be mere
mortals _ as their four DNFs and fifth-place points standing in the
heretofore bulletproof No. 24 DuPont Automotive Finishes Chevy
indicates.
</P>
<P>
   Labonte envisions renewed chemistry developing between the
crews, beginning with more standardized Chevys.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's a good opportunity to do this while we're
building these new cars for next season,'' said Labonte, referring
to the redesigned 2000 Monte Carlo. ``You have to have the whole
package, and actually the cars are built kind of different by the
three teams. So it's hard to go down and say, `Give us your spring
and shock setups' and put it in the car and have it work.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's what we're trying to do for next year. I think we're
stronger when we work together. It's not that we haven't been
working together, but we haven't been working near as well as we
could have been and as well as we're planning on being.''
\Nsubheds:INSIDE THE NUMBERS All for one? NASCAR powerhouse
Hendrick Motorsports has placed two drivers inside the Winston Cup
points top 10 after 18 of 34 races. But even three-time and
reigning champion Jeff Gordon's bid for a record-tying third
consecutive title is fading fast, considering he is nearly 400
points behind series leader Dale Jarrett. A statistical look at
Team Hendrick: Driver Rank Trails leader Poles Wins Top-5s Top-10s
DNFs Jeff Gordon 5th 389 points 6 4 11 12 4 Terry Labonte 9th 741
points 0 1 1 5 2 Wally Dallenbach 20th 1,111 points 0 0 0 2 3
Source: Winston Cup Racing Update
\Nsubheds:QUICK HITS TMS races to ABC The season-ending Pep Boys
Indy Racing League event at Texas Motor Speedway on Oct. 17 has
received a TV upgrade.
</P>
<P>
   Originally scheduled for the Fox Sports Network on a regional
basis, the race instead will be televised nationally by ABC.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are details still left to be worked out, but the race is
going to be on ABC,'' said Eddie Gossage, executive vice president
and general manager of TMS. ``We've been working to upgrade the TV
package, and we're going from a regional series of cable networks
to one of the big four. From the standpoint of reach, that's a big
improvement for TMS and the IRL.''
</P>
<P>
   The race remains scheduled for a 1 p.m. start. But that could
change at the network's suggestion. \Nsubheds:Hill to soldier on
Damon Hill's fifth-place finish Sunday in the British Grand Prix
has rejuvenated his desire to remain in Formula One.
</P>
<P>
   The 1996 World Driving Champion announced yesterday that he
would complete the season with Jordan Formula One. Hill, 38, had
threatened to quit after crashing out of last month's French Grand
Prix.
</P>
<P>
   Hill, who has scored five championship points this season, is
scheduled to rejoin the team for testing at Monza, Italy.
</P>
<P>
   Jordan is third in the constructors' championship. Hill's
teammate, Heinz-Harald Frentzen, is fourth with 26 points and eight
races remaining. \Nsubheds:Stewart apologizes NASCAR rookie
sensation Tony Stewart has apologized for dissing the media after
running out of fuel while leading the Jiffy Lube 300 last Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Stewart, sixth in Cup points, was two laps from winning his
first Winston Cup race when he ran out of fuel. Stewart chugged
home 10th. Rather than meet the media afterward, he remained in his
team's trailer while crew chief Greg Zipadelli explained what went
wrong.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's inexcusable to do what I did,'' said Stewart, driver of
the No. 20 Home Depot Pontiac Grand Prix. ``I apologize to
everybody I inconvenienced. There was a lack of maturity there.
It's something I'm going to work on. It wasn't because I was trying
to be mean to the press. I was real consumed by the emotions. When
you work so hard and lose the way we did, it's hard to deal with
the emotions.
</P>
<P>
   ``By time I got home, I felt bad. We all hope it's going to blow
over.'' \Nsubheds:Last words ``I really believe we can be a
championship contender. We're 30 points out, but that definitely is
within striking distance.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Greg Ray, third in IRL points heading to Atlanta Motor
Speedway this weekend
nn
</P>
