<HEADER>
A0956 &Cx1f; tad-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TEEPEN-COLUMN18-COX     07-15 0542
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEEPEN-COLUMN18-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COMMENTARY: Oh, behave!
 &HT;    By Tom Teepen
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Boy, are we ever in one another's faces these days. There's such
a din of scolding and moral haranguing that the nation sounds less
like a republic going about its civic business than a preaching
contest with the pulpits in a shouting match.
</P>
<P>
   Congress, though itself never one of the recognized shrines of
moral instruction, thinks that whatever ails our kids _ and it is
assumed that much does _ will be cured by having public school
pupils hauled into passing proximity with one or another version of
the Ten Commandments.
</P>
<P>
   As another cure to what adults think is wrong with other
people's children, Louisiana has passed a law requiring students to
refer to their teachers as ``sir'' or ``ma'am.'' And if that
doesn't stop the little thugs from wearing their baseball caps
stupidly backwards, maybe a statute requiring them to curtsy and
bow would do the trick.
</P>
<P>
   Poor Brandi Chastain, in her exuberance at having just converted
the penalty kick that gave the U.S. women the World Cup, whipped
off her jersey and waved it like a flag. This exposed her decidedly
unsexy, no-jiggle sports top _ and exposed the rest of her to some
of the stoutest moral huffing of this indignant season.
</P>
<P>
   Never mind that many women jog similarly attired, to no known
remonstrance. One newspaper editorial sniffed that Chastain is a
poor role model and hero and an offense to soccer moms everywhere.
Oh, grow up.
</P>
<P>
   And as if all that, and more of the same, were not enough, we've
got God pitching us from billboards _ and an insufferably
cutesy-poo God at that.
</P>
<P>
   He's saying, or she is, things like:
</P>
<P>
   ``Keep using my name in vain and I'll make the rush hour
longer.''
</P>
<P>
   ``That `Love Thy Neighbor' thing? I meant it.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Don't make me come down there.''
</P>
<P>
   And ``Have you read my number 1 bestseller? There will be a
test.''
</P>
<P>
   These and more are quips in the ``God Speaks'' campaign, and
although God may, as widely reported, move in mysterious ways, I
hope I shatter no one's faith by telling you this is not really God
speaking.
</P>
<P>
   Actually, this is the Washington, D.C.-based Outdoor Advertising
Association speaking and _ just a hunch _ rather less for God than
for the 900 member companies it lobbies for. It is putting up
10,000 of these billboards in 40 states, seeking innocence by
association.
</P>
<P>
   I'm no theologian, but I doubt that God would speak, as these
billboards do, in the voice of George Burns, who played him in a
couple of movies, or that he would speak in a manner that
notoriously fouls his own creation. God, I'm guessing, is not an
eyesore.
</P>
<P>
   I suppose it's pointless to note that this in-your-face
moralizing is tedious and will get us nowhere and that the same
amount of energy directed to, oh, uplifting the poor, squaring up
Social Security and Medicare, toning down the gunfire and saving
patients from their health insurers might actually spruce up life.
</P>
<P>
   Sorry for the moralizing.
</P>
<P>
   Tom Teepen is national correspondent for Cox Newspapers. He is
based in Atlanta. E-mail: teepencolumn(at)coxnews.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
