r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GLASS-COLUMN-$ADV18-C     07-15 0594
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLASS-COLUMN-$ADV18-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COMMENTARY: SCANNING THE NATION'S HATE CRIME AGENDA
 &HT;    For release Sunday, July 18.
 &HT;    By ANDREW J. GLASS
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Come November, President Clinton plans to convene a
White House conference on hate crimes, which the FBI says have more
than doubled in the past decade. Although that issue touches some
raw nerves, it's unlikely that this gathering will explore them.
</P>
<P>
   Before November, Clinton hopes to sign into law a Hate Crimes
Prevention Act. There's a good chance he'll succeed, since the bill
already enjoys 40 co-sponsors in the Senate and 180 in the House.
</P>
<P>
   Whenever local authorities fail to act, the bill empowers the
Justice Department to prosecute offenses based on race and religion
(already covered under a prior statute) as well as national origin,
gender, sexual orientation or disability. Before it can move, the
attorney general must certify that the prosecution ``is in the
public interest and necessary to secure substantial justice.''
</P>
<P>
   That trigger fails to mollify the Family Research Council, which
sees the bill as a lever to undermine the First Amendment by
punishing ``thought crime'' and making ``name-calling'' a ``federal
case.'' The conservative group also argues that the legislation
would create ``favored classes of victims'' _ gays and lesbians _
contrary to the 14th Amendment.
</P>
<P>
   Benjamin Smith serves as the posthumous poster boy of the hate
crimes bill. Smith, 21, killed himself as police closed in on his
stolen van after he drove through Illinois and Indiana shooting at
blacks, Orthodox Jews and Asians. Two of his victims died after
being shot in the back.
</P>
<P>
   In seeking to root out evil, could the feds bring charges
against the World Church of the Creator, an anti-black,
anti-Christian, anti-Jewish organization? (Before his deadly
rampage, Smith had placed about 2,000 World Church fliers under
windshields in Bloomington, Ind., exalting the ``Great White Race''
and assailing what the group termed ``a deceitful, alien
government, a controlled media, and a suicidal religion.'')
</P>
<P>
   It's possible, but not likely.
</P>
<P>
   Some 30 years ago, the Supreme Court held in Brandenburg v. Ohio
that the government is constitutionally barred from forbidding
``advocacy of the use of force or of law violation'' unless ``such
advocacy is directed toward inciting or producing imminent lawless
action and is likely to incite or produce such action.'' The
Brandenburg ruling raises a constitutional shield over the World
Church's hateful message.
</P>
<P>
   But if hate groups have rights, so should their victims: 1997
saw an 8 percent rise in reported hate crimes based on sexual
orientation alone, making anti-gay crime the third-highest category
reported to the FBI, after race and religion.
</P>
<P>
   Even as those statistics roll in, the Vatican has ordered an
American priest and a nun to end their ministry to gay men and
lesbians, asserting that the pair's long-term work is incompatible
with the church's stance that homosexual activity is immoral.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton could do worse than to ask clerics from the Congregation
for the Doctrine of the Faith, the church body charged with
safeguarding its teaching, to join religious folk, cops and victims
at his upcoming hate crime conference.
</P>
<P>
   It's all part of the same agenda.
</P>
<P>
   Andrew J. Glass is a Washington, D.C.-based columnist for Cox
Newspapers. His e-mail address is aglass(at)coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
