<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-15 10:30 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1010 &Cx1f; taf-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-AUSTIN-POWERS-MOD-REV     07-15 0858
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AUSTIN-POWERS-MOD-REVIVAL-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AUSTIN POWERS: MOD REVIVAL  
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;    (To purchase this special one-shot feature from W magazine _ the
rate is not prohibitive _ contact New York Times Syndicate Sales
Executive DEBRA WEYDERT at (732) 390-4480; fax, 732-390-4697.)
 &HT;    
 &HT;    ---------------------FREE ART!----------------------
 &HT;    ONE B&AMP;W AND ONE COLOR SLIDE are available ELECTRONICALLY by
E-MAIL for FREE. Please specify that you want the art when you
order the article.
 &HT;    ----------------------------------------------------
 &HT;    
 (PLEASE NOTE: This article has been filed into the ``e''
entertainment news and ``l'' lifestyle news files.)  
 &HT;    
 By ANNE D'INNOCENZIO 
 c.1999 Fairchild Publications  
<TEXT>
 &UR; (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &LR;  &QC;
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Critics have blamed Austin Powers for many things,
including an elusive sense of good taste. Now they can add one
more: That international man of mystery, now romping across the
nation's movie screens in one of the summer's blockbuster movies,
might singlehandedly be bringing psychedelia back to fashion.
</P>
<P>
   Groovy, baby.
</P>
<P>
   The way Lloyd Singer, president of ABS Allen Schwartz, sees it,
``Consumers needed the signal.''
</P>
<P>
   Austin Powers, he said, was that signal.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's going to make the '60s Mod looks more mainstream,'' said
Singer, who increased offerings of psychedelic prints from 10 to 30
percent for fall/holiday selling, because of the movie's
popularity.
</P>
<P>
   ABS's other Austin Powers-inspired looks are aqua peasant
blouses and lace pants with bell flares.
</P>
<P>
   Singer isn't alone. Other fashion executives believe that
``Austin Powers: The Spy Who Shagged Me'' just might help raise
hemlines and further push hot pink and bright orange into pop
acceptance.
</P>
<P>
   Fashion observers pointed out that the movie, which features
Heather Graham in such styles as HotPants, over-the-knee boots and
bright pink and orange micromini crocheted dresses, is a refreshing
departure after ``Elizabeth,'' ``Titanic'' and ``Shakespeare in
Love.'' Those films, said retailers, helped spur sales of romantic
styles, such as ruffled shirts, but the fashions were serious.
</P>
<P>
   The new Austin Powers movie is believed by Singer and others to
be much more of a fashion influence than the original film _
``Austin Powers: International Man of Mystery'' _ which came out
two years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Most of that movie was set in the '90s, and the parts that took
place in the '60s were handled differently than those in the
sequel.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was more in the world of pop art,'' said Deena Appel,
costume designer for both movies. ``There was a lot of vinyl.
Fashion was also doing a lot of vinyl.''
</P>
<P>
   Appel said she wanted the sequel to have an explosion of color.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know if you can directly pluck everything out of the
film and wear it on the street, but we are becoming more
comfortable with color,'' Appel said. ``This is certainly the year
of pink.''
</P>
<P>
   Retail executives said they believe their consumers are relating
to the Austin Powers sequel _ at least as far as fashion is
concerned.
</P>
<P>
   ``The best thing about it is the optimism and the freshness that
people haven't seen in a while,'' said James Aguiar, fashion
director for women's ready-to-wear at Bergdorf Goodman.
</P>
<P>
   ``People aren't used to so much color. I think people won't be
as afraid of prints, and they won't be afraid of going around in
microminis. I went to the movie with a friend of mine, and she told
me it made her realize how boring we have become.''
</P>
<P>
   Aguiar said the movie has ``certainly helped'' push sales of
shift dresses by Girlfriend in Pucci-inspired prints and geometric
patterns. The dresses, which retail for $200, are ``blowing out,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   Aguiar added that Voyage's brightly colored camisoles and
scarves, as well as its skirts, are also doing well. In addition,
he believes that the sequel could help push sales of crocheted
dresses.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the movie is definitely helping,'' said Ed Burstell,
general manager at Henri Bendel. ``It will push everything out
there.''
</P>
<P>
   He, too, attributed booming sales of Girlfriend's brightly
colored designs in part to the Austin Powers sequel.
</P>
<P>
   ``It will subliminally push the '60s and '70s trends,'' said
Kalman Ruttenstein, fashion director at Bloomingdale's, adding that
he liked the crochet dresses in the Austin Powers sequel.
</P>
<P>
   ``Short hemlines have been in the wind, and we are starting to
sell short right now,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, J.C. Penney's is working with several of its private
label suppliers to develop a junior line inspired by the film,
according to Robin Schuellein, the junior tops buyer. She said she
wants to develop a line of Hippie Chic clothing and plans to
promote it with images from the movie.
</P>
<P>
   _______ &QC;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (Anne D'Innocenzio is a reporter for Fairchild Publications.) &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   _______ &QC;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (To purchase this special one-shot feature _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ contact New York Times Syndicate Sales Executive
DEBRA WEYDERT at (732) 390-4480; fax, 732-390-4697.) &LR;  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
