<SLUG> BC-BORDERS-COLUMN16-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    One small step for man, and nickels for me
 &HT;    By Gary Borders
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   LUFKIN, Texas _ Thirty years ago, give or take a few days, Neil
Armstrong became the first man to walk on the moon _ and I made
about $10 bucks selling an extra edition of the Longview Daily News
to the folks who were on my paper route near downtown.
</P>
<P>
   Best as I can recall, the paper published three extras while I
was a paperboy, riding my Schwinn Stingray, silver in color with a
banana seat and chopper handlebars, the green-and-white canvas bag
tied between the wrist grips. The first was when Dwight Eisenhower
died; the second when some rednecks trying to stop integration blew
up the school buses at the barn on July 4, 1969, apparently hoping
the popping of fireworks would mask the sound of a few dozen large
vehicles being blown to kingdom come. Bad plan. They were caught
and convicted in no time. I hope they're still in prison. And the
third extra, a few weeks later, was the moon landing.
</P>
<P>
   Extras, rare beasts that they were, meant pure gold for us
paperboys, who usually had to split our take evenly with the
newspaper. An extra sold for a nickel instead of the usual dime,
and the paperboy kept all the money. I had about 200 customers, so
it was a fast sawbuck back when that would keep a 13-year-old
supplied in soft drinks, comics and Reeses Peanut Buttercups _
still my weakness _ for a week, easily.
</P>
<P>
   Besides the cash, which was always paramount to a
lower-middle-class kid with a powerful hankering for the latest
Fantastic Four comic, the next-best part of selling an extra was
getting to yell, (SET ITAL)``Extra! Extra! Read All About It.''(END
ITAL) I did just that, my prepubscent voice cracking horribly. I
believe that is why I'm still in this line of work three decades
later, still waiting for a chance to hit the streets with an issue
that people are just dying to read. At least my voice doesn't crack
anymore.
</P>
<P>
   Extras are all-but-extinct, done in by cable television, which
can bring live reports within seconds of an event happening. Still,
one of these days, before I hang up my green eyeshade, I want to
come out with another extra, and if I get the chance I'll be out
there hawking them with the rest of the crew.
</P>
<P>
   I drove by the downtown fire station in my hometown of Longview
some weeks back and spied the brass pole in the truck bay, still
shiny. I slid down that pole the day Armstrong landed on the moon,
after selling a few extras to the firemen lolling on their bunks in
the thick heat of an East Texas summer, landing lightly on my feet
and bounding out of the station to hit the old Sears store next.
One small step for man, one giant leap down a slippery pole for me.
OSHA, trial lawyers and a societal fear of being sued likely assure
the pole is merely a decoration these days.
</P>
<P>
   After finishing about half my route, I was ready to suck in some
needed air conditioning at Sears and peddle some copies to the
sad-eyed appliance salesmen standing around hoping to sell a window
air-conditioning unit to someone tired of trying to stay cool with
an evaporative cooler.
</P>
<P>
   Kelly Plow was my next big stop, an imposing place that
manufactured farm implements _ a hot, loud and spooky building to
one with an overactive imagination. It's long gone now, a victim of
progress, but in 1969 the foundry reminded me, years later, when I
read Dante, of one of the circles of hell.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, I made my way up Green Street, peddling my product to
the residents of the shotgun houses that hugged Marshall Avenue,
the old Highway 80. I approached an old black woman fanning herself
on the front porch, a normally reliable customer willing to fork
over a dime (regular price) most days for the day's news. I'll call
her Miz Grimes, though her real name is lost to my memory banks.
After 30 years, I'm paraphrasing the conversation.
</P>
<P>
   ``Miz Grimes,'' I said. ``We landed on the moon. I'm selling an
extra edition here for a nickel. Want to buy one?''
</P>
<P>
   She fanned herself furiously with her funeral-home fan, a piece
of cardboard stapled on a popsicle stick.
</P>
<P>
   ``Naw, I don't believe I want to truck with that foolishness.
Ain't no man landed on the moon. They just made that stuff up in
the studio. Trick photography, that's all that is,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   I could not convince her that an American astronaut had landed
on the moon. She never did buy the paper. Exasperated, I tried to
give her the paper, willing to eat the nickel. She pulled back as
if I was trying to hand her the devil's own preamble.
</P>
<P>
   I figure Miz Grimes went to her grave believing the moon shot
was pure fiction. Imagine what she'd think about the Internet, or
all the other new-fangled inventions of the last 30 years. More
trick photography, she'd harrumph.
</P>
<P>
   Heck, I don't know. Sometimes I wonder if she might have been
right.
</P>
<P>
   Gary Borders is editor and publisher of the Lufkin Daily News.
His e-mail address is gborders(at)coxnews.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
