<HEADER>
A1036 &Cx1f; tad-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MCNEELY-COLUMN16-COX     07-15 0716
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MCNEELY-COLUMN16-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Clinton's New York run will hurt Gore
 &HT;    By Dave McNeely
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Hillary Rodham Clinton is running for the U.S.
Senate in New York for the same reason George W. Bush is running
for president: because she can. She has the borrowed name
identification of a president along with the fund-raising ability
that that carries.
</P>
<P>
   When she takes a four-day ``listening'' trip to New York, 200
reporters dog her steps _ more than accompanied her husband on a
simultaneous tour of areas with lots of poverty.
</P>
<P>
   But at some point, the Democrats are going to worry about this.
That includes most of all Vice President Al Gore, who is trying to
get a little distance from the Clinton White House in his effort to
win the job himself next year. Gore has no choice but to pay lip
service to the first lady's race, but it's with an even stiffer
upper lip than usual.
</P>
<P>
   Hillary may win in New York. Even though some Republicans
suspect she's flirting with the race as a means to raise money to
pay for the Clinton's legal bills from the impeachment proceedings
over her hubby's fling with Monica Lewinsky, she wouldn't be this
far down the track unless polling data had shown she had a good
chance.
</P>
<P>
   But while she may be successful in New York's quirky politics,
she hurts the Democrats, and particularly Gore, in various ways.
</P>
<P>
   She reminds American voters ready for what Bill Clinton said
they needed seven years ago _ a change _ that the Clintons are
trying to hang around. While Gore is trying to establish himself in
his own right, she's in the media capital of the world, appearing
constantly in The New York Times, which in turn acts as the
unofficial assignment sheet for the national TV networks.
</P>
<P>
   ``It looks like it deflects attention away from Al Gore's
campaign _ especially at a time when he's having a hard time
attracting support as well as attention,'' said Bruce Buchanan, a
University of Texas at Austin professor whose specialty is
presidential elections. ``And by reminding people nationally, more
so perhaps than in New York, that they're fatigued with Clinton, it
may hurt Gore even more by accentuating his connection to the
Clinton regime.''
</P>
<P>
   Hillary already is making Gore's life more difficult. Former
U.S. Sen. Bill Bradley of New Jersey is raising a surprising amount
of money as the alternative to Gore, and having the Clinton
reminder around helps Bradley in his effort to elbow Gore out of
the nomination.
</P>
<P>
   In an effort to play to the voters of New York, Hillary is
already disagreeing with the president on matters such as Medicare
funding for teaching hospitals and whether the capital of Israel
should be in Jerusalem. Hillary may have disagreed with Bill on any
number of things in the privacy of their home, but this public
disagreement reinforces the suggestion that the Clintons are
opportunistic politicians.
</P>
<P>
   Hillary's stumping may not be a problem with New York voters,
because she'll presumably have the political cash necessary to
respond to negative television ads with ads of her own.
</P>
<P>
   But elsewhere in the country, she won't have that paid podium.
And the continuing Clinton presence could taint the Democrats
outside New York.
</P>
<P>
   But the most serious problem is money, said Greg Hartman, who
has managed statewide campaigns in Texas for former Comptroller
John Sharp and for the Democratic ticket. Many smaller donors only
have so much discretionary money that they're willing to spend on
political candidates, and Hillary is sucking up some of that, he
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those are the kind of people she hurts Gore with,'' Hartman
said.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, one female progressive Democrat in Texas reported
several days ago that she'd been called by a telephone bank boiler
room with a request she send Hillary a check _ days before Hillary
officially filed her exploratory committee.
</P>
<P>
   Who knows? Maybe the Republicans soon will be cheering Hillary's
candidacy even more than the Democrats had hoped former Republican
House Speaker Newt Gingrich would stick around.
</P>
<P>
   Dave McNeely writes about politics for the Austin
American-Statesman. You may contact him at
dmcneely(at)statesman.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
