<HEADER>
A1037 &Cx1f; tad-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-YOUNG-COLUMN16-COX     07-15 0607
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-YOUNG-COLUMN16-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Soccer vs. baseball reminds us of what elevates us over beasts
 &HT;    By John Young
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WACO, Texas _ My friend was remarking on why soccer is weird.
Human beings have these attachments _ hands _ which elevate the
species over others. And we have a game where only two players on
the field can use them.
</P>
<P>
   I don't agree with my friend on everything, but on this he's
right. Soccer is weird.
</P>
<P>
   And frustrating. That's why when Brandi Chastain scored the
winning penalty kick in the Women's World Cup 0-0 final, the first
thing she did was find a use for her hands by stripping off her
jersey _ introducing ``sports bra'' as a household term.
</P>
<P>
   I understand her frustration. Hands do make the sport, if you
ask me. That's why, for instance, the Professional Apple-Bobbers
Tour never made it, despite lining up a contract with ABC, with
Chris Schenkel to announce.
</P>
<P>
   Take baseball. Now, that's a sport that glorifies hands, and man
by extention.
</P>
<P>
   In that regard, Tuesday night's All-Star Game was another
midsummer night's classic. We got to see how the game's greatest
scratch themselves. We got to see digital dialogue from the
coaching box, from the catcher's crouch.
</P>
<P>
   Baseball is a calvalcade of earthy, hand-to-orifice action. See
the pitcher step from the rubber. See him prepare the next
offering. Is there any wonder the batter whiffs?
</P>
<P>
   Baseball is evolution's crowning glory. Consider, for instance,
the fact that man's nostrils have naturally selected a
circumference that's a virtual match for man's forefinger. Just
train the camera on the All-Star dugout and see how it works.
</P>
<P>
   Horses and hyenas cannot do that. They are lesser creatures.
</P>
<P>
   Let's face it. Were it not for our hands, other creatures would
run the planet. I have a collie in the back yard who would have me
walking on her leash every day from sunup to sundown if she had
hands. Instead, she must settle for a paltry but blissful few
minutes walking on my leash every evening.
</P>
<P>
   I have hands. I have command.
</P>
<P>
   My hands can open gates, doorknobs and dog-food sacks. My hands
can master a backyard faucet. My wife thinks I can't do anything
around the house with my hands. My dogs think I'm a regular
Leonardo da Vinci.
</P>
<P>
   And of course those hands can administer the rubdowns and the
surgical scratches of a dog's dreams.
</P>
<P>
   The human form is a good concept. But five out of five dogs
agree: Hands are the best concept.
</P>
<P>
   Hands continue to advance the human species. One misconception
is that we don't work with our hands anymore. That's not true.
</P>
<P>
   It's true that machines do a lot of things that hands used to
do. But to make the machines and to program the computers takes
hands _ hands which can fly over a computer keyboard and work a
mouse like cracking a whip.
</P>
<P>
   It's said that voice-data input will make those keyboarding
skills obsolete one day. Wrong. Some set of hands will have to
program that voice-data gizmo.
</P>
<P>
   In the words of Carl Sagan, billions and billions of flying
fingers will continue to dictate how things work. Hooray for hands.
</P>
<P>
   Now I'm wondering why everyone was cheering _ maybe they were
mocking _ those poor soccer gals as they ran back and forth trying
to make the ball do their bidding without the use of their hands.
We winced to watch them try to knock the ball into the goal with
their noggins.
</P>
<P>
   This is called using your head? I don't think so.
</P>
<P>
   John Young is opinion page editor of the Waco Tribune-Herald.
E-mail: jyoung(at)wacotrib.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
