<HEADLINE>
EDITORS:
</HEADLINE>
  
 Thursday, July 15, 1999      The Hearst News Service will file these stories for Friday and
Sunday. If you have questions, please call Tim Spence at
202-298-6920.  
    (Slugline includes the ``HNS'' tag.)
   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NATIONAL NEWS (``a'' category)
</P>
<P>
   SMUGGLED-PEOPLE (Raymondsville, Texas) _ Whether it was the
take-out order for 200 hamburgers or bulk sales of pre-cooked
chicken and jugs of water, there have long been hints of smugglers
stashing legions of undocumented immigrants here. By DANE SCHILLER.
(Photos on the Wieck Database.)
</P>
<P>
   PESTICIDE-USE (San Francisco) _ California farmers and
professional exterminators sprayed more cancer-causing pesticides
than ever before in 1997, nearly twice the amount used in 1991, a
new state study says. By JANE KAY.
</P>
<P>
   LIFESTYLE/FEATURES (``l'' category)
</P>
<P>
   HIKING-SNACKS (Albany, N.Y.) _ It doesn't matter if you're
taking a day hike, climbing one of the High Peaks or setting off on
a considerably longer journey. Packing the right trail snacks is as
important as choosing proper footwear. By DOUG BLACKBURN.
</P>
<P>
   VIETNAMESE-TEJANO-BAR (Alvin, Texas) _ There's a faraway look in
the eyes of Michael Thanh Lee, a would-be businessman who has the
dull gaze of someone who's just been hit between the eyes with a
two-by-four. The Vietnamese immigrant has spent $70,000 trying to
open up a Tejano bar in this blue-collar town, which is trying to
clamp restrictions on the beer-joint industry. When he hung up a
sign that proclaimed, ``Coming Soon Tejano Night Club,''
neighboring residents went into battle mode. By STEVE OLAFSON (For
weekend release, July 17-18. Photo available on NYT database.)
</P>
<P>
   STRAIGHT-EDGE (Houston) _ To the Fur Breeders Agricultural
Cooperative in Sandy, Utah, Straight Edge is a terrorist group. To
Houston teen-ager Anthony Calleo, it's salvation. The controversial
youth movement has come under attack nationally, but young adults
in Houston like the group's wholesome philosophy: no drinking, no
smoking, no drugs, no promiscuous sex. Houston-area youths say the
national media have blown the exploits of a few out of proportion,
negating the positive impact it has had on thousands. By LISA DAVIS
(For weekend release, July 17-18. Photos available on NYT
database.)
</P>
<P>
   BRAINS-GENDER (Albany, N.Y.) _ Dean Falk's research has put an
age-old sexual controversy to rest. Size, she has concluded,
doesn't matter. In a recent issue of the Journal of Human
Evolution, she outlined her findings that men's brains are larger
on average than women's, but that the discrepancy has no bearing on
general intelligence. By ANDREW BROWNSTEIN.
</P>
<P>
   EVOLUTION-THEORY (Albany, N.Y.) _ Using modern medical
techniques to re-construct ancient fossils, a University at Albany
professor has made a discovery she claims will dramatically alter
the way science views human evolution. The long-accepted theory is
that the genus homo appeared roughly two million years ago in
Africa. Dean Falk's new theory is that homo sapiens, the scientific
name for modern human beings _ may have stemmed directly from an
early ancestor, Australopithecus africanus. By ANDREW BROWNSTEIN.
</P>
<P>
   FOG-HORNS (San Francisco) _ Sailors once listened intently to
the basso chorus of San Francisco Bay's fog horns to find their
way. Today, with global positioning satellite systems (GPS) on
board, mariners look at blips on a screen to find their precise
location on a shifting sea. By HAL WESTON.
</P>
<P>
   FOOD (``d'' category)
</P>
<P>
   FOOD-Q&AMP;A (Albany, N.Y.) _ Q: How do I preserve fresh herbs if I
don't have a dehydrator? Is there another way to dry them? Can I
freeze them? I can't use the pound of cilantro I've gotten out of
my garden all at once! By LISA STEVENS.
</P>
<P>
   BUSINESS/FINANCE (``f'' category)
</P>
<P>
   CHEVRON-REFINERY (San Francisco) _ An explosion at Chevron's
Richmond refinery last weekend will significantly reduce oil
production, raising speculation that already creeping prices at
California's gas pumps will soar even higher. By ANITA WADHWANI.
</P>
<P>
   SF-NEWSPAPERS (San Francisco) _ A San Francisco Board of
Supervisors' committee has urged the city attorney to find out how
the city can help preserve San Francisco's two daily newspapers in
the wake of the anticipated sale of the San Francisco Chronicle. By
GREGORY LEWIS.
</P>
<P>
   ENTERTAINMENT (``e'' category)
</P>
<P>
   INTERNET-MUSIC (San Francisco) _ Despite the accolades, media
hype and revolutionary rhetoric, digital music downloaded from the
Internet is not a ready-for-prime-time player, according to a
recent study of the online music industry. The study, conducted by
the New York Internet analysis firm Jupiter Communications,
concluded that digital music distribution must overcome major
obstacles before becoming a mainstream consumer technology. By
BOBBY McGILL.
</P>
<P>
   FILM-BLAIR-REVIEW (Undated) _ A series of films, from ``The
Haunting'' to ``Lake Placid,'' will open soon, but it's ``The Blair
Witch Project'' that is stirring the most frenzy. The movie is
defiantly original _ and scary. By BRUCE WESTBROOK.
</P>
<P>
   FILM-HORROR-LISTING (Undated) _ A look at all of the fright
films that are opening this summer. By BRUCE WESTBROOK.
</P>
<P>
   FILM-FONDA-PROFILE (Beverly Hills, Calif.) _ Actress Bridget
Fonda wasn't eager to do any in-the-water scenes, but she still had
fun making the big monster project ``Lake Placid'' with co-stars
Bill Pullman and Oliver Platt. The movie opens Friday nationwide.
By LOUIS B. PARKS.
</P>
<P>
   TV-PREVIEWS (Pasadena, Calif.) _ If you're looking for a
metaphor _ and in Hollywood that's a perpetual hunt _ you could
find it in the thick, lung-clenching smog that mixed with the heat
and stupidity and choked this town before the day even began. By
TIM GOODMAN.
</P>
<P>
   COMMENTARY (``k'' category)
</P>
<P>
   MORSE-COLUMN (San Francisco) _ On the way over to Berkeley, I
practiced my chants and slogans. ``Power to the people, right on.''
``Venceremos.'' ``La Lutte Continue.'' ``Hey, hey, ho hum, how
humdrum can radio become?'' The people's struggle for control of
Berkeley's KPFA made for dramatic radio, at least when station
management pulled the plug on reporter Dennis Bernstein and his
program ``Flashpoint.'' By ROB MORSE.
</P>
<P>
   SALTER-COLUMN (San Francisco) _ For someone who's been a
feminist as long as I have, you'd think I'd know by now to check
with Feminism Central before I say or do anything that knocks me
out of lockstep with my millions of sisters around the globe. After
all, as everyone knows _ especially people who take to the airways
or opinion pages to criticize ``The Feminists'' _ we all think and
act exactly alike. By STEPHANIE SALTER.
</P>
