<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-15 11:04 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1041 &Cx1f; tad-z
r t &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HEMINGWAY-HOUSE16-COX     07-15 0884
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HEMINGWAY-HOUSE16-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Hemingway's House a prize catch
 &HT;    By Cheryl Blackerby
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   KEY WEST, Fla. _ This is the point in the tour of Ernest
Hemingway's house that usually gets the biggest chuckle.
</P>
<P>
   The tour guide points to a penny embedded in the concrete by the
pool and begins the story.
</P>
<P>
   Ernest Hemingway's second wife, Pauline, waited until her
husband was out of town to spend $20,000 for a huge saltwater
swimming pool. It was the island's first swimming pool and a luxury
that was the talk of the town.
</P>
<P>
   Pauline wanted the pool to be a surprise for Hemingway, who was
in Spain covering the civil war.
</P>
<P>
   Hemingway was indeed surprised when he saw it and even more
stunned when he saw the bill.
</P>
<P>
   So much so that he pulled a coin out of his pocket and threw it
down on the patio. ``Here,'' he said, ``You might as well take my
last penny.''
</P>
<P>
   That's just one of the stories that make a visit to the
Hemingway House and Museum more interesting than most monuments to
famous people.
</P>
<P>
   Whether or not visitors are fans of the writer, they will
appreciate the intimacy of the house. His manual Royal typewriter
and still sits on the small table in the upstairs studio of a
cottage behind the main house, where he wrote all or parts of A
Farewell to Arms, To Have and Have Not, For Whom the Bell Tolls and
The Snows of Kilimanjaro.
</P>
<P>
   HEMINGWAY'S ROPE BRIDGE
</P>
<P>
   Today, visitors walk up the stairs to see it, but when Hemingway
lived here he had a swaying rope bridge that connected the office
to the second-floor veranda of the house.
</P>
<P>
   In the gift store downstairs, you can buy his books. The one
that is most closely associated with Key West is ``To Have and Have
Not,'' published in 1937. Once you read it, it will be easy to see
the town through his eyes as you walk the narrow lanes.
</P>
<P>
   ``The moon was up now and the trees were dark against it, and he
passed the frame houses with their narrow yards, light coming from
the shuttered windows; the unpaved alleys, with their double rows
of houses; Conch town, where all was starched, well-shuttered,
virtue, failure, grits and boiled grunts . . . ''
</P>
<P>
   On the advice of his friend, John Dos Passos, Hemingway came to
the country's southernmost city to fish and drink, watch the sun
set and get into the occasional fistfight.
</P>
<P>
   You can still drink at Hemingway's favorite bar, Sloppy Joe's,
owned by his friend, Sloppy Joe Russell.
</P>
<P>
   When Russell moved the bar to its present place on Duval Street
in 1937, Hemingway was there for free drinks. He once locked
original manuscripts of ``A Farewell to Arms'' and ``To Have and
Have Not'' and uncashed royalty checks in the back room on his way
to Cuba. They weren't found until 1962.
</P>
<P>
   Another sure chuckle on the tour is the the urinal, porcelain on
cast iron, that Hemingway carried home one night from Sloppy Joe's
bar. Pauline put decorative tiles on it and used it as a drinking
fountain for their 40 or so cats.
</P>
<P>
   HOUSE A NATIONAL LANDMARK
</P>
<P>
   Visitors to the house will be sure to appreciate Hemingway's
anger when Pauline replaced all of the ceiling fans with
chandeliers. She didn't like the fans _ never mind that there was
no air conditioning and that without them the house was, and still
is, hotter than a steam room.
</P>
<P>
   The house is at 907 Whitehead St., one block from Duval, ``the
brightly lit main street . . . three poolrooms, two barbershops,
five beer joints, three ice cream parlors, the five poor and the
one good restaurant, two magazine and paper places . . . '' he
wrote.
</P>
<P>
   The house, a National Historic Landmark, still has his
furniture. The small china figurine of a nude woman playing a flute
was a gift from Marlene Dietrich. There's an 18th-century traveling
desk with secret compartments, a 17th-century walnut bench from a
Spanish monastery, and his king-sized bed with a headboard made of
an old Spanish gate.
</P>
<P>
   A ceramic cat sitting on top of a chest was a gift from Pablo
Picasso. He painted a heart on the cat's chest to symbolize
Hemingway's love of cats.
</P>
<P>
   TO CUBA, BACK TO KEY WEST
</P>
<P>
   Fifty descendants of Hemingway's pride and joy, a tom cat with
six toes on each paw, roam the firstand second-floor verandas and
grounds. Many of them also have six toes.
</P>
<P>
   Hemingway lived at the house from 1931 until 1940 with Pauline.
She divorced him in 1940 and continued to live at the house with
their two sons until she died in 1951. Hemingway moved with his new
wife, Martha, to Cuba but came back to Key West during World War
II.
</P>
<P>
   While covering D-Day in Europe, he met his fourth wife, Mary. He
won the Pulitzer Prize in 1953 for ``Old Man and the Sea'' and the
Nobel Prize for literature in 1954. In 1961, he committed suicide
with a shotgun in Ketchum, Idaho.
</P>
<P>
   The house is one of Key West's oldest. It was built in 1812 for
Asa Tift, a wealthy merchant who lived there until 1889. Tift, who
designed Confederate naval ships during the Civil War, used rock
quarried on the site to build the house and he imported Italian
marble for the fireplaces.
</P>
<P>
   The Hemingway House and Museum: open daily 9 a.m. to 5 p.m.;
(305) 294-1575; admission: adults, $7.50; children 6 to 12, $4.50.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
