A1042 &Cx1f; tad-z
r t &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KEYHARBOR16-COX     07-15 0579
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KEYHARBOR16-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Key West harborfront gets a makeover
 &HT;    By Cheryl Blackerby
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   KEY WEST, Fla. _ The cast of characters who came through this
harbor couldn't be better if you made them up. And Ernest Hemingway
tried.
</P>
<P>
   First, there were the Spaniards who shipwrecked offshore and
made a few treasure hunters very wealthy 400 years later.
</P>
<P>
   Then there were salvagers who made fortunes in the 1800s,
stripping the vessels wrecked on nearby shallow reefs.
</P>
<P>
   And the spongers who came from Greece, and were run off to Tampa
when they became too successful. And the shrimpers who sought
``pink gold.''
</P>
<P>
   And, of course, Henry Flagler, who brought the railroad, and the
moneyed passengers from the north. They took the Key West ferries
to Cuba.
</P>
<P>
   Ernest Hemingway was one of them. He used to walk over to Key
West Bight from Sloppy Joe's Bar at sunset and watch the ferries
come and go.
</P>
<P>
   The ferries stopped when Americans quit going to Cuba and Key
West's seaport became an ugly working port most tourists avoided.
</P>
<P>
   But with the completion of a five-year, $5.4 million
revitalization, Key West's Historic Seaport is now bringing back
tourists. A boardwalk, called Harborwalk, that opened in January
will be officially dedicated next month.
</P>
<P>
   The Harborwalk starts at Grinnell and ends at Front Street. It
connects 100 landand sea-based waterfront businesses including
restaurants, clothing stores, dive shops, a gourmet grocery and
even a wedding chapel.
</P>
<P>
   We docked our boat in one of the Historic Seaport slips, and we
were in impressive and eclectic company _ dive/snorkel catamarans,
Tall Ships and schooners offering sunset cruises, glass-bottom
boats, fishing charters and live-aboard sailing yachts.
</P>
<P>
   The ferries are back, although they don't go to Cuba. Now you
can catch a ferry to the Dry Tortugas National Park and Marco
Island.
</P>
<P>
   The 8.5-acre Historic District stretches along the north end, or
gulf side, of the island along Key West Bight. Near Grinnell is
Lands End Village where the Half Shell Raw Bar and Turtle Kraals
restaurants sit on the sites of the former shrimp docks and Turtle
Cannery. Both outdoor seafood restaurants offer superb views of
million-dollar yachts.
</P>
<P>
   Other restaurants include the Waterfront Market and Schooner
Wharf Bar. At night you can expect live music on the docks.
</P>
<P>
   There's more to come. The Conch Republic Seafood Company, which
recently opened in the former Singleton Fish House building, will
soon expand to include a fish market, botanical park, and a
historic and maritime education center.
</P>
<P>
   Restoration of the Turtle Cannery building continues, aided by a
preservation grant from the state that will also renovate the
historic Thompson Fish House.
</P>
<P>
   Reef Relief, a nonprofit organization working to preserve and
protect the Keys' living coral, has new offices at the Seaport.
</P>
<P>
   The seaport is easy to find. If you're on foot, and on Duval
Street, take Caroline Street east to William or Margaret, turn left
and you'll end up at Land's End. There's plenty of parking here.
There are also lots of bike racks to lock your bike.
</P>
<P>
   Boaters can call Historic Seaport at the Key West Bight at (305)
2938309 to reserve a slip. Dockage includes electricity and water.
There's a 30-foot minimum ($56).
</P>
<P>
   You can't ask for a better spot for sightseeing in Key West.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
