<HEADER>
A1043 &Cx1f; tad-z
r t &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KEYSBYBOAT16-COX     07-15 1361
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KEYSBYBOAT16-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Down the Keys in five days, by boat
 &HT;    By Cheryl Blackerby
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   KEY WEST, Fla. _ Dockmaster Kevin Walsh grinned when I told him
I was staying in a hotel near the Historic Seaport at Key West
Bight.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have money to stay in a hotel, and you have that little
boat?'' he asked.
</P>
<P>
   Our 17-foot fishing boat was the smallest, by at least a dozen
feet, of the 80 or so highly upscale international yachts docked at
the Bight. (We had to pay a 30-foot minimum docking fee since the
slips are not designed for wee little boats.)
</P>
<P>
   Kevin believes, as do most hard-core boaters, that you should
put all your disposable income, as well as indisposable income,
into your boat.
</P>
<P>
   I told Kev that we had come all the way from Key Largo _ 120
miles by sea _ and he was impressed. Any 50-foot yacht can do that,
but a 17-footer?
</P>
<P>
   ONE FINE 17-FOOT BOAT
</P>
<P>
   I set off on this odyssey with Palm Beach Post photographer Paul
Milette, and before Paul gets mad at me, let me say right away that
his boat is one fine 17-foot boat. It doesn't have a cabin, galley,
beds or toilet, but it does have a canopy and space for a cooler.
</P>
<P>
   His 14-year-old daughter, Amy, who took a Coast Guard-approved
safe boating course and has a boating license like her dad, served
as first mate.
</P>
<P>
   The boat had a Global Positioning System, which has satellite
communication that told us our latitude and longitude. This mostly
helped us find restaurants. But it also kept us from ending up in
Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   We also had a depth finder, which is crucial in the shallows on
the gulf side of the Keys. During the five-day round trip, we
rarely got in water over 10 feet deep and a couple of times ended
up in about 18 inches and had to back out into the deep channel.
</P>
<P>
   The water is so clear it's hard to tell the depth by eyeballing
it. You can see sponges, conch and sea urchins on the sandy bottom
as clearly at 10 feet as two. You can admire every stripe on an
angelfish, and you can clearly see the stingrays darting around
like spaceships.
</P>
<P>
   The flats are full of trails made by boat propellers that have
torn up protected grasses and coral.
</P>
<P>
   GO AHEAD, WRECK MY DAY
</P>
<P>
   The early islanders made a living from ships that wrecked on the
oceanside reefs. Legend accuses them of helping the mishaps along
by intentionally misplacing lights, perhaps thinking, well, that's
what outsiders get for intruding into the Keys.
</P>
<P>
   But a boat, especially one that can go in shallow water, is
still the best way to see this string of hundreds of
mangrove-covered islands, which separate the ocean and gulf. By
car, you go over 42 bridges. By boat, you're not bothered with such
manmade inventions.
</P>
<P>
   In a car, we would have missed the stingray jumping out of the
water and staying airborne long enough for us to make the
transition from ``What the heck is that?'' to ``It's a stingray!''
</P>
<P>
   In Marathon, we saw a manatee drinking fresh water from a hose,
its gray whiskered face out of the water as it gulped. (Don't do
this. Manatees shouldn't be encouraged to hang out with people
because they end up getting run over by boats.)
</P>
<P>
   Channel markers for the Intracoastal Waterway, which goes to Key
West, and other channels served as perches for anhingas. Anhingas
can go underwater to search for fish; as our boat neared, they
would shoot from the water like rockets.
</P>
<P>
   REAR VIEW OF MALLORY
</P>
<P>
   In Key West, we got to see the sunset from the water and saw the
backside of the performers at Mallory Dock, literally. The
tightrope walker's tights were so threadbare we almost had to cover
Amy's eyes.
</P>
<P>
   As the sun set, a fleet of chartered clipper ships got smaller
and smaller on the horizon. I imagined the ladies up on the widow's
walks of the houses in Old Town watching their husbands leave in
the last two centuries. And the men _ what were they thinking? A
year out on a wooden boat with no GPS or depth finder, or cooler
full of cold drinks.
</P>
<P>
   We also saw some of the aftermath of Hurricane Georges, which
hit the Keys last year. Huge sailboats that had been thrown on
sandbars were still waiting to be towed. Miles of coastal trees
were brown, burned by saltwater during the storm. A houseboat's
windows had been blown out, but the tattered curtains remained,
billowing in the wind.
</P>
<P>
   The eeriest moment was seeing empty plastic jugs tied together
and floating on the ocean several miles from land. As darkness
descended, the jugs swept by us in the current, and I saw that they
were attached to the bow of a big, upended sailboat. The boat
popped up about a foot out of the ocean as it passed us, like
Carrie's hand coming out of the grave.
</P>
<P>
   During our trip, I watched the colors of water and sky change by
the hour. In the middle of our first day, the gulf was flat and the
same light gray as the sky, making it impossible to distinguish the
horizon.
</P>
<P>
   ROUGH SEAS
</P>
<P>
   On the last two days, the water was dark blue and rough. On the
way to a restaurant in Marathon on our last night, we were drenched
when we broadsided an ocean swell. We sat through dinner wet and
sticky. But what the heck, we were starving.
</P>
<P>
   The nighttime excursions were the best. Skinny, skittish needle
fish, reflecting silver moonlight, jumped out of the water one
night. We stopped the boat and were surrounded by leaping,
splashing fish.
</P>
<P>
   We saw brilliant Venus in the west and red Mars in the east, and
a gazillion stars reflected on the water.
</P>
<P>
   It made me wish Paul's boat at least had a deck to sleep on.
</P>
<P>
   For information about the Keys, call (800) FLA-KEYS.
</P>
<P>
   HOW WE MADE THE TRIP
</P>
<P>
   The journey: We pulled our boat by trailer to Key Largo and
spent five days discovering the Keys.
</P>
<P>
   The boat: A 1996 Key West 17 with a 1996 Johnson 88 SPL outboard
motor. The 17-foot boat has a Bimini top.
</P>
<P>
   The seas: The sea conditions were mainly calm to a light chop.
The roughest water was when we went from the gulf to the Atlantic
at Bahia Honda State Park and traveled through to Key West.
</P>
<P>
   We found much nicer water on the gulf side, but don't be fooled.
The sea conditions can be as treacherous as the ocean.
</P>
<P>
   Equipment: Make sure you have all your Coast Guard approved
safety gear aboard your boat:
</P>
<P>
   Life jackets for all aboard.
</P>
<P>
   At least one throwable PFD (personal floatation device).
</P>
<P>
   A fire extinguisher, some type of whistle or horn, an anchor and
plenty of line.
</P>
<P>
   A VHF radio and a cell phone.
</P>
<P>
   Make sure all your navigation and anchor lights are operating _
you'll be out for sunsets and dinner after dark. Our Global
Positioning System came in handy marking coordinates of snorkeling
spots and for its compass headings.
</P>
<P>
   Tips: Don't assume everything on your charts is accurate. We had
one chart that showed markers through the center of the lower keys,
but when we ventured that way, we could not find any of the channel
markers the map showed. Ask questions at marinas and try to gather
as much local knowledge as possible.
</P>
<P>
   The color of the water is a clue to its depth.
</P>
<P>
   Reef formations and sea grass beds that grow close to the
water's surface will make the water appear brown. Sand bars and
shallow rubble areas appear white. These two water colors should be
avoided in your boat, both for the health of the habitat and the
health of your boat's bottom. Green water usually indicates an area
free of shallow reefs or sea grass beds.
</P>
<P>
   Navigation of small, shallow draft boats in these areas is
generally safe. However, larger, deeper draft boats should exercise
caution.
</P>
<P>
   Information: The National Oceanic Atmosphere Administration
offers charts and navigational information for the Keys and can be
reached at its Charts and Publications Branch at 301-436-6990.
</P>
<P>
   The National Marine Sanctuary Program also has a lot of good
information for traveling the Keys by boat. One such pamphlet,
Keeping Your Bottom Off The Bottom, has valuable tips for water
depth in the Keys.
</P>
<P>
   For more information from the National Marine Sanctuary Program
call (305) 743-2437.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
