</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PIGEONKEY16-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Pigeon Key a fascinating historic site
 &HT;    By Cheryl Blackerby
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   MARATHON, Fla. _ When the train on Henry Flagler's Overseas
Railroad passed Pigeon Key in the spring, it would stop so
passengers could admire the bright orange blossoms of the poinciana
trees.
</P>
<P>
   Our visit was well-timed. The poincianas were blooming.
</P>
<P>
   We pulled our boat up to the dock and set out to explore the
tiny settlement of tin-roofed, wood clapboard buildings _ base of
operations for construction of Flagler's Seven-Mile Bridge.
</P>
<P>
   The island's buildings, constructed in 1908 and 1909, are on the
National Register of Historic Places. Anyone who has driven over
the Seven-Mile Bridge, has seen Pigeon Key, located directly under
Flagler's old bridge.
</P>
<P>
   In 1910, 400 people lived on the island, all employed by
Flagler. There was a post office and a school. A tent city was
inhabited by workers from New York City, and paths between tents
were given names such as 34th Street and Fifth Avenue.
</P>
<P>
   The first building to be restored, a dining hall, was
hand-sanded _ sandblasting is not allowed on historic buildings.
New wooden ``pocket'' windows that slide to the side, identical to
the original windows, were installed.
</P>
<P>
   The buildings were constructed with the same technology used on
Flagler's bridges to withstand hurricanes. Steel rods run from the
roofs into concrete footings.
</P>
<P>
   Architects working on the restoration were excited to find
specks of the original paints. Paint was matched to the specks, and
the buildings are now painted in Flagler's favorite color
combination _ bright yellow with dark green trim.
</P>
<P>
   Tourists weren't allowed to drive down the ramp to Pigeon Key
from 1969 to 1988, when it was used as a marine research center by
the University of Miami.
</P>
<P>
   But the island is now open to visitors. It can be reached by
walking or biking two miles on the old bridge from Knights Key,
just south of Marathon, to Pigeon Key. Cars are not allowed.
</P>
<P>
   But you can take a tram, which runs from the Pigeon Key Visitors
Center, housed in an old train car, on Knights Key. Admission to
Pigeon Key is $7.50 and includes the tram, a short film on
Flagler's life, entrance to Pigeon Key including the museum and a
guided tour. Call (305) 743-5999. Trams run from 10 a.m. to 4 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   Today, the island serves as a base for coral research for Mote
Marine Laboratories and for children's camps.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
