A1046 &Cx1f; tad-z
r t &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TURTLEAID16-COX     07-15 0604
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TURTLEAID16-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Motel helps save ailing sea turtles
 &HT;    By Cheryl Blackerby
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   MARATHON, Fla. _ A half-dozen German travelers gathered around
Lucky, a threatened green sea turtle.
</P>
<P>
   Her name probably should have been Extremely Unlucky, but here
at Hidden Harbor Motel, they tend to be optimistic.
</P>
<P>
   The motel supports the Turtle Hospital next door and guests are
encouraged to learn about sea turtles during their stay. Only motel
guests can see the turtles. They can visit the 150-by-50-foot
saltwater turtle pool and watch Sue Schaf feed the patients, give
medicines and IVs. Patients include all kinds of sea turtles
including several Kemp Ridleys, the rarest in the world. The
Germans had seen a TV documentary about Hidden Harbor and the
turtles and had made sure their Florida vacation included a visit.
</P>
<P>
   Lucky, on the other hand, probably wished she'd never set a fin
in Florida. She had gotten tangled in fishing line and one of her
flippers had been cut to the bone. Unable to swim, she was hit by a
boat. She was dragging a gangrenous fin when she was found.
</P>
<P>
   At the hospital, X-rays showed she also had tumors caused by a
herpes virus. And she was starving. Schaf held her up to show her
underbelly and clearly visible skeleton.
</P>
<P>
   The prognosis was bad, but turtles with severe injuries from
boat accidents and fishing line and illnesses such as tumors and
parasites have healed here.
</P>
<P>
   The Turtle Hospital and Hidden Harbor Motel are owned by Ritchie
Moretti, who ran a Volkswagen repair business in New Jersey before
he sold his business and moved to Marathon in 1980. He bought the
motel, docked his boat and planned to do nothing more than fish.
</P>
<P>
   But his love for fixing ailing cars soon turned to healing sick
turtles in the saltwater pool that came with the motel.
</P>
<P>
   ``Then we discovered the virus, and my interest wasn't casual
anymore,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Today, the hospital has three functions: education _ it hosts
4,000 to 6,000 children from visiting schools a year; research,
conducted with the University of Florida; and hospital care.
</P>
<P>
   The staff includes a veterinarian, two assistants and Moretti,
who has been trained to do diagnostic procedures.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, the sick turtles keep coming. Most have the virus
that is producing tumors that cause blindness and internal organ
failure.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ten years ago, we only saw the virus on green sea turtles, but
now it has spread to other turtles,'' Moretti said. The only common
denominator is that outbreaks always coincide with spikes in
temperatures.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Scientists believe this is one of the first effects of global
warming,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   And if this isn't bad enough turtles have plenty of other
problems.
</P>
<P>
   ``Fishermen put out their nets and put out long lines and take
away the turtles' food source,'' he said. ``And developers are
taking away the nesting beaches.''
</P>
<P>
   But fishermen are becoming more aware of the dangers of fishing
line, Moretti said. The turtles that have had tumors removed appear
to develop immunity to the virus.
</P>
<P>
   A few weeks later, I called to ask about Lucky.
</P>
<P>
   She did indeed have the right name. The tumors were removed and
she has recovered and learned to swim with three fins.
</P>
<P>
   She should be fine in the wild.
</P>
<P>
   Hidden Harbor Motel, 305-743-5376; rates for two people are $65
and $70. You can launch your boat here. Dockage is $10 a night.
From July 25 to Aug. 22, there's a six-night minimum.
</P>
<P>
   Only motel guests are allowed to see the turtles.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
