<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-15 11:06 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1048 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOOK-MILNER16-COX     07-15 0579
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOK-MILNER16-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    `Little Green Men' shines comic light on UFO paranoia
 &HT;    By Jay Milner
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   William F. Buckley Jr., the often inadvertently funny TV and
print pundit and gadfly, has a son named Christopher, who is even
funnier on purpose than his famous father is accidentally.
</P>
<P>
   I am an ardent fan of son, Christopher, particularly after
reading his recent novel, ``Thank You for Smoking,'' which featured
a PR man for the tobacco industry as its hero.
</P>
<P>
   Now, Christopher Buckley had produced another hilarious novel.
It's titled ``Little Green Men'' (Random House) and reveals for us
the truth about all those reports of UFO's, their passengers and
those who have been kidnapped and probed by them.
</P>
<P>
   ``Little Green Men'' is about a snobbish talk show host and
political pundit in Washington, D.C., who has an encounter with a
group of aliens from another planet. Or does he?
</P>
<P>
   What happens to the arrogant pundit after his encounter takes up
the bulk of the book. Suffice to say the aforementioned pundit's
life is altered drastically after he goes public with what he is
convinced has been a real alien kidnapping, complete with perverse
probes.
</P>
<P>
   John Oliver Banion, for that's the pundit's name, finds that he
must choose to either maintain his status as an icon for the
conservative establishment or become recognized as the leader of a
scruffy, fanatical millions who believe in UFO's, a category he has
always regarded as freaks.
</P>
<P>
   Buckley uses this scenario to satirize the people and goings-on
in our nation's capitol district, our duly elected officials and
their henchpersons, just as he did in his hilarious previous novel,
``Thank You for Smoking.''
</P>
<P>
   Banion then launches a campaign to force the government to
``open its files'' on UFO's and the number of his supporters rise
rapidly. He assumes the celebrity of a rock star and finds, to his
surprise, that he loves it.
</P>
<P>
   TV Guide has him on its cover. His talk show sponsor,
Gooey-Lube, is lubricating as fast as it can. ``Millions of
American automobiles hummed frictionlessly along the highways.''
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, many of his former friends and congressional
fans are afraid to identify with him, some even pass him in the
halls without noting his presence. He is confused but determined to
pursue his goal and force the government's ``big secret'' out in
the open.
</P>
<P>
   There are many twists and turns in the plot, most of them more
or less expected once you're into the story, but all-in-all this is
a fun book to read. Buckley has the ability to surprise you with
the obvious, which is a fun talent for a writer to have. Fun, that
is, for his readers. Perhaps fun for the writer, as well.
</P>
<P>
   Buckley even uses his brief biography on the book's jacket to
exercise his apparent obsession for satire. It declares that ``In
1998 he was inducted into the Legion D'honneur by the president of
France... despite the fact that his French is barely sufficient to
order a meal in a restaurant'' adding that ``he has been an adviser
to every president since William Howard Taft, a remarkable
achievement, since he was born in 1952.''
</P>
<P>
   This time of year critics and bookstores are talking about
``beach books.'' This is a perfect example of my idea of good beach
book, whether or not you find yourself on a beach.
</P>
<P>
   Jay Milner writes for Cox Newspapers.
</P>
