<P>
   COXNET BUDGET INFORMATION
</P>
<P>
   So specialty editors won't have to look at every day's budget,
Cox's features budgets have daily themes according tothis schedule:
</P>
<P>
   Monday for Tuesday: Technology
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday for Wednesday: Automotive and personal finance
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday for Thursday: Food, CD reviews, video reviews
</P>
<P>
   TODAY: Movie reviews, travel, books, fashion, and home &AMP; garden
</P>
<P>
   Friday for Saturday: Religion and science &AMP; health
</P>
<P>
   In addition, separate budgets move daily with spot news, sports,
business and commentary.
</P>
<P>
   Stories are moving in the category they're listed under. Stories
moving to duplicate categories are marked. An ETA is given if a
story will move after 8 p.m. Eastern.
</P>
<P>
   If you have questions or need a resend, please call CoxNet, the
Cox News Service, at 404-526-5456.
</P>
<P>
   SAVE TIME: Stories marked as a CoxNet layout are available for
purchase in paginated form: www.nytsyn.com/pageexpress.
</P>
<P>
   LIFESTYLE
</P>
<P>
   SIBLEY-COLUMN _ We had a family emergency. My daughter, who
should have been hoeing the garden or washing the dog, was busy
having a stroke _ the kind of something or other that goes
whindering off to your brain scaring you to death. We packed up
nightgowns and books and television tapes and hurried to the
hospital. She had no business being in precarious health, I told
her. It was my time. So we decided to go in tandem, me in one room,
her just down the hall. (Sibley, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   COXNET TRAVEL PAGE
</P>
<P>
   EDs: This is the CoxNet Travel page for next. This layout will
be available Tuesday by 1 p.m. EDT
</P>
<P>
   COXNET TRAVEL 0717 HEMINGWAY TRAVELS _ A look at Hemingway's
life through visits to Oak Park, Illinois, his birthplace, and his
homes in Key West, Fla. and Cuba. Includes interviews with
Hemingway's son Patrick and the writer's close friends Lillian Ross
and A.E. Hotchner. (Eyman, Palm Beach Post)
</P>
<P>
   WITH
</P>
<P>
   HEMINGWAY-FESTS _ A list of Hemingway festivals. (Eyman, Palm
Beach Post)
</P>
<P>
   HEMINGWAY MUSEUM _ A visit to the Hemingway House and Museum is
more interesting than most monuments to famous people. (Blackerby,
Palm Beach Post)
</P>
<P>
   TRAVEL BRIEFS _ Denmark has proclaimed 1999 its Medieval Year,
highlighting the many archeological digs, burial mounds, churches
and museums of that nation. (Staff, N.Y. Times News Service)
</P>
<P>
   TRAVEL-LONDON-THEATER _ LONDON _ The devoted theater buff can
hardly walk anywhere in London without trodding on some historical
stone or passing some significant door. We visit a whole range of
theaters, lobbies, monuments and oddities of special interest to
such a buff, from the pub where Albert Finney and Peter O'Toole
quaffed mightily after acting class; to the London Theater Museum
where a John Gielgud's Hamlet sololoquy can be enjoyed in a
listening booth. (Hulbert, Atlanta Journal-Constitution) WITH COLOR
PHOTO AND LAYOUT.
</P>
<P>
   Eds: Embargoed for Sunday July 18.
</P>
<P>
   WITH
</P>
<P>
   TRAVEL-LONDONCOVENT _ LONDON _ You could make a case that the
longest-running show in London _ 340 years and counting _ is going
on in front of the Protico of St. Paul's Church, Covent Garden.
Though it has been interrupted quite a few times by rain. It's
street theater.(Hulbert, Atlanta Journal-Constitution) WITH LAYOUT.
</P>
<P>
   Eds: Embargoed for Sunday July 18.
</P>
<P>
   TRAVEL-LONDONTOUR _ LONDON _ Walking tour of historic London
theater sites. (Hulbert, Atlanta Journal-Constitution) WITH LAYOUT.
</P>
<P>
   Eds: Embargoed for Sunday July 18.
</P>
<P>
   TRAVEL-LONDONSAVOY _ LONDON _ Great performances, illicit
rendezvous, theatrical deals struck over caviar _ it's all there
under the stainless steel, art deco marquee that forms the entrance
to London's Savoy Theatre and Savoy Hotel. (Hulbert, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution) WITH LAYOUT.
</P>
<P>
   Eds: Embargoed for Sunday July 18.
</P>
<P>
   TRAVEL-IFYOUGO _ LONDON _ If You Go. . . . to London info box.
(Hulbert, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   Eds: Embargoed for Sunday July 18.
</P>
<P>
   KEYSBYBOAT _ Setting up the tale of a five-day boat trip to the
Florida Keys. (Blackerby, Palm Beach Post) MOVED
</P>
<P>
   HEMINGWAY-HOUSE _ KEY WEST, Fla. _ Whether or not visitors are
fans of Ernest Hemingway, they will appreciate the intimacy of the
house. His manual Royal typewriter and still sits on the small
table in the upstairs studio of a cottage behind the main house,
where he wrote all or parts of A Farewell to Arms, To Have and Have
Not, For Whom the Bell Tolls and The Snows of Kilimanjaro.
(Blackerby, Palm Beach Post) MOVED
</P>
<P>
   PIGEONKEY _ MARATHON, Fla. _ When the train on Henry Flagler's
Overseas Railroad passed Pigeon Key in the spring, it would stop so
passengers could admire the bright orange blossoms of the poinciana
trees. Our visit was well-timed. The poincianas were blooming.
(Blackerby, Palm Beach Post) MOVED
</P>
<P>
   WITH
</P>
<P>
   TURTLEAID _ MARATHON, Fla. _ A half-dozen German travelers
gathered around Lucky, a threatened green sea turtle. Her name
probably should have been Extremely Unlucky, but here at Hidden
Harbor Motel, they tend to be optimistic. The motel supports the
Turtle Hospital next door and guests are encouraged to learn about
sea turtles during their stay. Only motel guests can see the
turtles. They can visit the 150-by-50-foot saltwater turtle pool
and watch Sue Schaf feed the patients, give medicines and IVs.
Patients include all kinds of sea turtles including several Kemp
Ridleys, the rarest in the world. (Blackerby, Palm Beach Post)
MOVED
</P>
<P>
   KEYHARBOR _ KEY WEST, Fla. _ The ferries stopped when Americans
quit going to Cuba and Key West's seaport became an ugly working
port most tourists avoided. But with the completion of a five-year,
$5.4 million revitalization, Key West's Historic Seaport is now
bringing back tourists. A boardwalk, called Harborwalk, that opened
in January will be officially dedicated next month. (Blackerby,
Palm Beach Post) MOVED
</P>
<P>
   ALL STORIES MOVED WITH PHOTOS
</P>
<P>
   GETAWAY _ More than 300 visitors a day flock to Beaufort, S.C. _
the state's second oldest town _ to shop, eat and tour its stately
pre-Revolutionary War and antebellum homes and enjoy the
picturesque waterfront. Getaway feature from Wednesday paper.
(Johnson, Atlanta Journal-Constitution). 35. MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   GETAWAY-FESTIVALS _ Southern happenings. (Thrasher, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   FASHION
</P>
<P>
   (The AJC's fashion page will be available today, embargoed until
Sunday, July 18. The centerpiece follows:)
</P>
<P>
   MULES _ Two years after the mule made a comeback, the slide-on
shoe is still going strong. Men are stepping in style this summer
with looks that team up with women's. Nordstrom's fashion director
says mules will be hotter than ever this fall and winter, with
embroidery, sequins and rhinestones. (Hill, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution) WITH PHOTOS.
</P>
<P>
   HOME AND GARDEN
</P>
<P>
   LAWN-FETISH _ Who are these lawn junkies _ primarily men who
won't let a blade of grass reach one millimeter above its desired
heigfht in summer? We take to Atlantans about what drives their
fescue fetishes _ and yes, we throw in a few tips from the real
experts on turf that works. (Flanders, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution) WITH COLOR PHOTOS .
</P>
<P>
   GARDENING-LIFE _ A weekly column by Lee May. This week:
Horticulture thieves. (May, Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   WORKSHOP-CAULKING _ This is the fourth installment in our summer
workshop series, a step-by-step guide to doing inexpensive weekend
projects for the home or garden. This week: Bathroom caulking.
(Hill, Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   REFINISH _ DAYTON, Ohio _ So you've stumbled across a gorgeous
old coffee table being used to display knickknacks at a neighbor's
garage sale. Or maybe the chest of drawers Grandma Schwartz left
you is starting to show its age. ``Not to worry,'' you think.
``I'll just refinish it.'' Unfortunately, refinishing is rarely an
easy or simple process. It's messy, complicated, sweaty work.
(Dayton Daily News)
</P>
<P>
   NUTS&AMP;BOLTS _ DAYTON, Ohio _ There are few projects you can do
around the house so quickly and inexpensively that have such a
significant impact as outdoor lighting. By working a few hours and
spending less than $100, you can dramatically change the look of
your property and improve its security at the same time. (Cummings,
Dayton Daily News)
</P>
<P>
   ENTERTAINMENT/ARTS
</P>
<P>
   COXNET ENTERTAIN PAGE
</P>
<P>
   EDS: This is the CoxNet ENTERTAIN page for the current week.
This layout is now available.
</P>
<P>
   COXNET ENTERTAINMENT 0715 _ Cartoon Network President Betty
Cohen is the marketing dynamo behind the cable television success
story of the '90s. (Vejnoska, Atlanta Journal-Constitution) Art
includes 5-column color photo of Betty Cohen sitting in her office,
surrounded by cartoon characters.
</P>
<P>
   WITH
</P>
<P>
   AT A GLANCE _ A look at Cartoon Network President Betty Cohen at
a glance. Art includes 1-column full-body photo of Betty Cohen.
</P>
<P>
   COMMENTARY _ How low can television go in behaving badly?
(Holloway, Austin American-Statesman)
</P>
<P>
   VIDEO REVIEWS _ You might approach ``Central Station'' with
caution. Don't. What's remarkable about Walter Salles' film is the
way it subverts expectations and sidesteps easy sentimentality.
Also, reviews of ``A Civil Action,'' ``She's All That'' and ``Waco:
The Rules of Engagement.'' (Staff, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
Art includes 18-pica color photo from ``A Civil Action.''
</P>
<P>
   CD REVIEWS _ Reviews of the new releases from Limp Bizkit, The
Chemical Brothers and Public Enemy. (Staff, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   BOOKS
</P>
<P>
   BOOKS-SUMMER _ Brief reviews of what's new in nonfiction,
including Stephen Fry's ``Moab Is My Washpot,'' Po Bronson's ``The
Nudist on the Late Shift,'' Donald Rawley's ``The View From
Babylon'' and more. (Harrison, Atlanta Journal-Constitution). 35.
</P>
<P>
   EDs: EMBARGOED UNTIL SUNDAY, July 18
</P>
<P>
   PARENTING-BOOK _ DAYTON, Ohio _ If you are sick of reading
parenting books that are peppered with lists and advice, Dr. Kyle
Pruett has a solution. In his latest book, ``Me, Myself and I: How
Children Build Their Sense of Self'' (Goddard Press, $19.95) Pruett
guides parents on how to shape children from 18 months to 36
months. (Rahimi, Dayton Daily News) MOVED SATURDAY
</P>
<P>
   BOOKS-BLOODY-SUNSET _ DAYTONA BEACH, Fla. _ Nancy Powell's
reticence belies the nature of her true-crime story, experienced
nearly firsthand. Powell, once a St. Augustine reporter for the
Florida Times-Union, covered the brutal 1974 murder of Athalia
Lindsley, a prominent personality in the town. Now she's told that
story at length and in detail in ``Bloody Sunset in St. Augustine:
A True Story,'' co-authored with Jim Mast (251 pages, Federal Point
Publishing, $10). (Shashoua, Daytona Beach News-Journal) MOVED
SUNDAY
</P>
<P>
   COXNET BOOKS PAGE
</P>
<P>
   EDS: This is the CoxNet Books page for next week. This layout
will be available Tuesday by 11 a.m. EDT.
</P>
<P>
   COXNET BOOKS 0717 LADY BIRD _ A new biography portrays the
strong political partner who worked at LBJ's side despite personal
affronts and public challenges. (Morris, Austin American-Statesman)
Art includes 3-column color photo of Lady Bird Johnson and 6-pica
color photo of book jacket.
</P>
<P>
   WITH
</P>
<P>
   REVIEW: BEETLE POWER _ Two coffee-table books tell the complete
story of the VW Beetle, the car that became an icon. (Brock, N.Y.
Times News Service) Art includes 2 6-pica color photos of book
jackets and a 2-column color photo of the new VW Beetle.
</P>
<P>
   MANNERS _ In ``A Short History of Rudeness: Manners, Morals and
Misbehavior in Modern America,'' Mark Caldwell dwells on subjects
that seem to fit better in a general social history than a
particular history of manners. (Eder, N.Y. Times News Service) Art
includes 6-pica color photo of book jacket.
</P>
<P>
   SUMMER READING _ Short takes on latest nonfiction releases of
note. (Harrison, Cox News Service)
</P>
<P>
   N.Y. TIMES BEST SELLERS LIST
</P>
<P>
   BOOKS-SYRUP _ Halfway through his satirical novel about a cola
marketing campaign, Australian Max Barry added an X to his name.
Now he's Maxx. It's just the sort of thing a sharp marketing
executive would do. ``It's a joke,'' says Barry, 26, whose
fictional ``Syrup'' (Viking, $23.95) is set in the offices of the
Coca-Cola Co. in Los Angeles. ``Creative types live in mortal fear
of someone forgetting who they are, so they change their names to
make them stand out more.'' In the novel, Scat and a female Coke
marketing executive named 6 pitch the concept of a new cola
product. The soft drink would be sold in a black can with a
four-letter name that's unprintable in a family newspaper.
(O'Briant, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   BOOK-NOTES _ If Eric Jerome Dickey's books seem to have a lot of
humor in them, there's a good reason. The Memphis native is a
former stand-up comic. Described by some as ``a male Terry
McMillan,'' Dickey writes about relationships between black
professionals from a male point of view. One of his books,
``Friends and Lovers,'' has been optioned for the movies by Whitney
Houston. (O'Briant, Atlanta Journal-Constitution) ETA: 6 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   BOOK-MILNER _ Jay Milner's review of a recently released book.
(Milner, Cox News Service) MOVED
</P>
<P>
   HEMINGWAY CENTENNIAL PACKAGE
</P>
