jackets and a 2-column color photo of the new VW Beetle.
</P>
<P>
   MANNERS _ In ``A Short History of Rudeness: Manners, Morals and
Misbehavior in Modern America,'' Mark Caldwell dwells on subjects
that seem to fit better in a general social history than a
particular history of manners. (Eder, N.Y. Times News Service) Art
includes 6-pica color photo of book jacket.
</P>
<P>
   SUMMER READING _ Short takes on latest nonfiction releases of
note. (Harrison, Cox News Service)
</P>
<P>
   N.Y. TIMES BEST SELLERS LIST
</P>
<P>
   BOOKS-SYRUP _ Halfway through his satirical novel about a cola
marketing campaign, Australian Max Barry added an X to his name.
Now he's Maxx. It's just the sort of thing a sharp marketing
executive would do. ``It's a joke,'' says Barry, 26, whose
fictional ``Syrup'' (Viking, $23.95) is set in the offices of the
Coca-Cola Co. in Los Angeles. ``Creative types live in mortal fear
of someone forgetting who they are, so they change their names to
make them stand out more.'' In the novel, Scat and a female Coke
marketing executive named 6 pitch the concept of a new cola
product. The soft drink would be sold in a black can with a
four-letter name that's unprintable in a family newspaper.
(O'Briant, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   BOOK-NOTES _ If Eric Jerome Dickey's books seem to have a lot of
humor in them, there's a good reason. The Memphis native is a
former stand-up comic. Described by some as ``a male Terry
McMillan,'' Dickey writes about relationships between black
professionals from a male point of view. One of his books,
``Friends and Lovers,'' has been optioned for the movies by Whitney
Houston. (O'Briant, Atlanta Journal-Constitution) ETA: 6 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   BOOK-MILNER _ Jay Milner's review of a recently released book.
(Milner, Cox News Service) MOVED
</P>
