   &UR; FUTURE TECH: IMMORTAL CELLS &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; ONE COLOR SLIDE IS AVAILABLE FREE &QL; 
 &UR; (1,000 words) &QL; 
 &UR; By SHANTI MENON &LR;  &QC;
</P>
<P>
   Under normal circumstances, skin cells divide about 50 to 70
times and then quickly wither and stop dividing. But after nearly
two years in a laboratory at Geron, a Menlo Park, Calif., biotech
company, clusters of human skin cells that have been genetically
altered are approaching 400 divisions and still show no signs of
aging. They just keep multiplying. What gives? Shanti Menon reports
on what may very well be the discovery of the fountain of youth.
</P>
<P>
   slugged: BC-CREATING-IMMORTAL-CELLS-NYTSF. Sent to category
codes ``a'' general news and ``l'' lifestyle news.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; CREATURES FROM THE BLEAK LAGOON &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; FOUR COLOR SLIDES ARE AVAILABLE FREE &QL; 
 &UR; (700 words) &QL; 
 &UR; By JOSIE GLAUSIUSZ &LR;  &QC;
</P>
<P>
   When dinosaurs roamed Earth and South America nestled up against
Africa, Araripe Lagoon was a violent sea of death that collected
evidence of ancient life. Over millions of years the changing
climate dried and filled the sea many times. Today it's a
salt-saturated pile of sediment located in the northeast corner of
Brazil. Josie Glausiusz, an associate editor at Discover magazine,
reports on what scientists are finding in its depths.
