<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-15 11:49 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1131 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FILM-BLAIR-REVIEW-HNS     07-15 1442
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-BLAIR-REVIEW-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`THE BLAIR WITCH PROJECT': NEW WRINKLES ON FACE OF FEAR 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By BRUCE WESTBROOK 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   When hearing hype, be afraid _ be very afraid.
</P>
<P>
   After 1996's ``Scream`` scared up $103 million at the box office
by cleverly skewering slasher-flick conventions, many believed it
would push the horror genre to new heights.
</P>
<P>
   Surely ``Scream'' would trigger innovations and originality, not
heaps of creeps in the mindless masked-madman mold it had mocked.
</P>
<P>
   Then reality set in.
</P>
<P>
   From ``Disturbing Behavior'' and ``The Faculty`` to ``I Know
What You Did Last Summer`` to ``I Still Know`` _ well, you know _
filmmakers simply settled for the trite and true, with randy teens
being systematically slaughtered.
</P>
<P>
   But this summer brings a chill. Now _ finally _ we hear bumps in
the night that could signal that a change is looming.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, the buzz is back for horror films, thanks to a spooky
spate of hot-weather fear fests with more on their minds than gore
and more gore.
</P>
<P>
   At least, that's the hype. And hype can be a dangerously
two-sided tool, perhaps not for commercial products like ``The
Haunting,'' opening July 23, or ``Lake Placid,'' opening Friday,
but certainly for horror's most heralded new film, ``The Blair
Witch Project.''
</P>
<P>
   The Sundance Film Festival adored it, and an elaborate Web site
is stirring the frenzy. Some reviews scream that it's the scariest
movie since 1974's ``The Texas Chainsaw Massacre.''
</P>
<P>
   The horror, the horror.
</P>
<P>
   The hype, the hype.
</P>
<P>
   Where is the truth? Are we on the cusp of a horror renaissance
or another grisly letdown?
</P>
<P>
   Judging solely by ``Blair Witch,'' yes and no.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, because the film is defiantly original. No, because its
challenging minimalism will make it a tough sell for a mass
audience.
</P>
<P>
   Go ahead, Hollywood. Pack a theater with fans of ``Chainsaw``
``The Exorcist,`` ``The Omen,`` ``Hellraiser`` and other hard-core
horrors. Tell them ``Blair Witch`` is even scarier.
</P>
<P>
   Then listen as some viewers grumble, impatient with the
home-movie look of this pseudo-documentary about student filmmakers
who set out to probe a witchy legend _ then disappear.
</P>
<P>
   At least ``Blair Witch`` is getting a proper roll-out, first
playing art houses in only 20 markets. This is no shopping-mall
movie.
</P>
<P>
   ``Marketing this film has been a challenge,'' admits Orlando,
Fla.-based Ed Sanchez, who wrote, edited and directed ``Blair
Witch,`` along with partner Dan Myrick.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of people don't know what to make of it. I definitely
think it's not for everybody. But that's the whole point.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you go in with the idea that you're going to see a
conventional horror film with known actors or even good camera
work, you'll be disappointed. If you want blood and guts, this is
not that.''
</P>
<P>
   For a film about a legend, ``Blair Witch'' has generated a
legendry about itself. This stems from a meticulously detailed
back-story, touched upon in opening frames.
</P>
<P>
   For far more, you can trace the tale's origins _ and its
aftermath _ on the official Web site at www.blairwitch.com.
</P>
<P>
   It follows the fictional ``Blair Witch'' legend from a Colonial
woman accused of witchery in 1785 to the 1995 discovery of the
missing students' footage in the woods.
</P>
<P>
   For even more background, catch a one-hour Sci Fi Channel
special, ``Curse of the Blair Witch,'' airing at 7 p.m. CDT Sunday
and 10 p.m. July 22. There's even a tie-in CD, ``Josh's Blair Witch
Mix,'' with chunks of dialogue and sound effects lacing tracks of
music inspired by the film, which isn't scored.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM) &QL; 
 &QL; 
Like the film itself, ``Curse of the Blair Witch`` is fiction
posing as a documentary. Actors portraying the family, friends and
teachers of the missing students are interviewed, and the
fabricated legend is further explored.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(END OPTIONAL TRIM) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   This all seems so real that many who watch the TV special or see
the film ``cold'' may believe the story is true _ just as some who
saw the 1984 mock documentary ``This Is Spinal Tap'' thought Spinal
Tap was a real rock band.
</P>
<P>
   Yet Sanchez and Myrick aren't trying to hide the fact that
``Blair Witch`` is fiction.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a weird line you have to walk,'' Sanchez said. ``We
didn't set out to do a hoax, just to make a film that seemed
completely real.''
</P>
<P>
   They have mixed feelings about how much viewers should know in
advance.
</P>
<P>
   On the one hand, it's important to prepare an audience for the
crude camera shots (often in black-and-white) and a story with no
clear resolution.
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, exposing the movie's process undercuts its
greatest power: a suspension of disbelief.
</P>
<P>
   When the students turn panicky after getting lost, when they
cringe from strange sounds outside their tent at night, and when
their bold leader, Heather, breaks down and tearfully tapes a
farewell message to her parents, the sense of dread and doom is
almost palpable.
</P>
<P>
   ``Blair Witch`` may be as fictional as ``A Nightmare on Elm
Street,'' but it doesn't prop up flimsy fantasies with special
effects. Rather, it immerses the viewer in a darkly disturbing
sense of you-are-there reality.
</P>
<P>
   ``We thought reality was the way to scare people these days,''
Sanchez said, ``to scare the jaded, high-tech, late-'90s audience
that knows everything about filmmaking and computer graphics and
has seen every monster imaginable.''
</P>
<P>
   For their entry into feature films, Sanchez and Myrick made
``Blair Witch`` for ``about the cost of a new Ford Taurus,''
Sanchez said with a laugh. (Reportedly, the budget was $30,000.)
</P>
<P>
   Recognizable stars would have ruined their concept _ not that
Sanchez and Myrick could have afforded them. ``Blair Witch's``
starkness owes as much to financial limits as artistic vision.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, unknown actors _ using their own names on screen _
essentially become the characters.
</P>
<P>
   For most of the eight-day shoot, they lived together in the
woods, sleeping in a tent and emerging in the morning to find the
day's instructions and rations of food left by Sanchez and Myrick.
</P>
<P>
   ``Blair Witch'' is surely the first film completely shot by its
actors. They were given situations, then told to improvise as their
characters recorded the experiences with a 16mm camera and a video
camcorder (later transferred to 35mm film).
</P>
<P>
   The situations included becoming hungry, cold and frightened _
first by being lost, then by being stalked by an unseen menace.
</P>
<P>
   Heather Donahue, Michael Williams and Joshua Leonard were chosen
from among 2,000 actors for their ability to work without a net.
But a little luck didn't hurt, either.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were quite blessed during shooting,'' Sanchez said.
``Nobody broke an ankle or got poked in the eye by a branch. Being
in the woods at night was creepy enough.''
</P>
<P>
   Except for asking the actors to keep the cameras zoomed out,
Sanchez and Myrick left shot compositions up to their cast members.
</P>
<P>
   The actors shot a total of 20 hours' worth of footage, and the
finished film is ``the worst 82 minutes of what they went
through,'' Sanchez said.
</P>
<P>
   The performances are Method acting (fully inhabiting a
character) to an extreme.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were definitely glad to get out of there,'' Sanchez said.
``We even started cutting down their food at the end. It was
tough.''
</P>
<P>
   The actors weren't truly lost _ the Maryland park where they
shot was small _ but being lost was their most terrifying
situation, said Sanchez.
</P>
<P>
   At Sundance, Artisan Entertainment purchased ``Blair Witch'' for
$1.2 million. In the months since, the film has had ``a bootleg
problem,'' Sanchez said, due to preliminary copies sent to film
festivals on video.
</P>
<P>
   ``But that's the old version,'' he said. ``This version adds
cool stuff, and the sound is better.''
</P>
<P>
   Actually, Sanchez is more sanguine about video. Due to its
intimacy, he thinks the film ``will make some money in theaters _
nothing huge _ but where it's almost guaranteed to blossom is on
video.''
</P>
<P>
   Next, he and Myrick plan a comedy.
</P>
<P>
   ``It'll cost more money,'' he said, ``the price of a couple of
Lear jets.''
</P>
<P>
   But for now they plan to stay in Florida, where their Haxan
Films is based and their ``Blair Witch'' vision emerged.
</P>
<P>
   ``The thing about classic horror films _ truly frightening films
_ is they let you picture a lot of the horror in your head,''
Sanchez said. ``That's what we tried to do.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know audiences are conditioned to getting a neat package of
a film wrapped in a bow. But I'm hoping they at least give this one
a chance as something completely new.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
