<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IVOR-RICHARD-GERE-IN-RUNAWAY-BRIDE-ART-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`RUNAWAY' HIT? RICHARD GERE AND JULIA ROBERTS RETURN TO `PRETTY
WOMAN' TURF 
</HEADLINE>
  (This ``separate buy'' article is from this week's Hollywood Stars
entertainment column) 
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or by fax at 732-390-4697.) 
 (She also has information on how to subscribe to Hollywood Stars, a
weekly entertainment column with color and black-and-white art.)
 Includes black-and-white photos and color slides of Richard Gere
with Julia Roberts and with Hector Elizondo in ``Runaway Bride.'' 
 By IVOR DAVIS  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
 &HT;    It took almost a decade, but Richard Gere and Julia Roberts are
back in business as of July 31, hoping to strike box-office gold
again in ``Runaway Bride'' _ their first film since ``Pretty
Woman'' (1990), the smash hit that made Roberts the most bankable
female star in Hollywood.
 &HT;    ``Right after `Pretty Woman' there was a lot of pressure on us
to do a sequel,'' recalls the silver-haired Gere, who will turn 50
on Aug. 29. ``But expectations were so high we all backed away.
There wasn't any script, so it was a moot point anyway.
 &HT;    ``Lightning stuck with that movie,'' he adds, ``and nobody had
any idea that it would. But I think we are all smart enough to know
there couldn't be a sequel. You can't do that twice.''
 &HT;    Still, he's hoping that the Gere-Roberts combo, plus ``Pretty
Woman'' director Garry Marshall and supporting player Hector
Elizondo, will once again prove a winning formula, even with a
story much different from their previous tycoon/hooker odd-couple
love story.
 &HT;    In ``Runaway Bride,'' Roberts operates a small-town hardware
store and has a habit of getting cold feet every time she is about
to marry, leaving a trail of dejected fiances standing at the
altar. Gere is a misogynistic newspaper columnist who investigates
the story and, inevitably, falls for her.
 &HT;    ``The script was very charming and made me laugh out loud,''
Gere says. ``I couldn't help thinking, `This is Julia _ this is
her.' So I called and said, `Look, we've been trying to find
something, and I can't find a reason not to do this.'''
 &HT;    He sent her the script and she quickly called back and told him
it was terrific. Whereupon, Gere admits, he himself began to
equivocate.
 &HT;    ``I told her, `Look, whether I do it or not, it's perfect for
you and it's what people want to see you in,''' he recalls. ``She
said, `I won't do it unless you do it.'''
 &HT;    Thus ``Runaway Bride'' was off and running. But Gere is quick to
note that he's not the same man he was in 1990, and his approach to
acting is different.
 &HT;    ``I enjoy it and it's fun,'' he says. ``When it doesn't become
fun anymore, I won't do it.
 &HT;    ``But these days I don't take acting that seriously,'' he
continues. ``It's a job, it's not my life. Wherever I am, I want to
create a nurturing and comforting environment _ even on film sets.
After over 20 years in this business, I like to find time to think
about my beliefs, about music, photography and other things.''
 &HT;    As a devout Buddhist, Gere strongly supports the Dalai Lama,
which in turn has involved him increasingly in charitable
activities that have taken him around the world.
 &HT;    Shortly after NATO began bombing Yugoslavia, the actor recalls,
he spent a week visiting a Kosovar refugee camp on the Macedonian
border. He had been speaking in Geneva at a human-rights conference
on Tibet when the opportunity to go came up, and he seized the
opportunity.
 &HT;    ``I had been helping Oxfam and Doctors Without Borders and felt
it was a good time to go _ at the beginning of the crisis,'' he
says.
 &HT;    He was impressed with what he saw.
 &HT;    ``Basically we were told the truth of what was happening,'' he
recalls, ``but clearly it wasn't black-and-white. There were no
heroes on any side.
 &HT;    ``I could talk about it for hours,'' Gere says, ``but what it
meant to me was that I could bring a little joy to the people who
were there, because they knew me _ it was part of the whole surreal
experience for them to be in no man's land between Kosovo and
Macedonia, and Richard Gere shows up and talks to them about what's
happening.''
 &HT;    On the personal front Gere, who was married to model Cindy
Crawford from l991 to l995 and of late has been involved with
actress/model Carey Lowell of television's ``Law and Order,'' says
that children aren't on his priority list.
 &HT;    ``I don't have a strong desire to have my own children,'' he
said. ``My voyage in this life is to find and understand myself,
and that's a far too selfish quest to involve children.''
 &HT;    How that statement stands now is open to question, however: At
press time, it was reported that Lowell is expecting a child early
in the new year, a baby who would be Gere's first.
 &HT;    It's the latest twist in a highly unusual life whose early years
were spent on a bucolic farm in upstate New York. Though he dropped
out of college to become an actor, Gere says that all along he was
more interested in studying philosophy and playing in a band _
acting was simply a good way to make money.
 &HT;    That decision, he says, turned him into a completely different
person.
 &HT;    ``I don't lead a normal life,'' he admits. ``I resigned myself
to that years ago.''
 &HT;    Gere made his movie debut in ``Report to the Commissioner''
(l975), and then became something of a sex symbol thanks to dark,
edgy roles such as Diane Keaton's dangerous pickup in ``Looking For
Mr. Goodbar'' (l977) and the lover for hire in ``American Gigolo''
(l980).
 &HT;    True stardom came with ``An Officer and a Gentleman'' (l982),
which cast him opposite Debra Winger as a passionate, confused
young would-be fighter pilot.
 &HT;    ``We were all _ Winger and I _ hungry and energetic and wildly
optimistic about the power of what we were doing,'' he recalls. ``I
saw the movie again last year while surfing TV at 2 in the morning.
I barely recognized myself, and didn't even know who that guy was.
 &HT;    ``I was struck by how unpretentious the film was,'' he adds. ``A
really straightforward, well-told story.''
 &HT;    Since then, however, most of his movies have been dramas, with
``Pretty Woman'' the most noteworthy exception. The pattern
continues with his next film, Joan Chen's ``Autumn in New York,''
in which he plays a womanizing restaurateur who falls for a
terminally ill woman played by Winona Ryder.
 &HT;    Next up is one of Robert Altman's notoriously offbeat
comedy/dramas, ``Dr. T and His Women.''
 &HT;    Given his history as a dramatic actor, it's surprising to hear
that Gere actually prefers comedy to drama. The only reason he
doesn't do more romantic comedies, he says, is that decent scripts
are few and far between.
 &HT;    ``Someone asked me what romantic comedies I've liked in the last
10 years,'' he says, ``and you know, I couldn't think of any. You'd
think there would be millions.
 &HT;    ``It's extremely difficult to write intelligent, adult romantic
comedies that are combative, with smart people engaging in sharp
dialogue,'' he says. ``It's easier to be wet and do a sentimental
piece.''
 &HT;     c.1999 Ivor Davis  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; (Ivor Davis is a Hollywood-based reporter and columnist.) &LR; 
 &UR; EDITOR: For further information on ``Runaway Bride,'' consult the
official Website at www.runawaybridemovie.com. And don't forget to
visit The New York Times Syndicate Web site at
http://www.nytimes.com/syndicate for information on Hollywood Stars
and other features. &QL; 
