A1144 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FILM-FONDA-PROFILE-HN     07-15 1095
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-FONDA-PROFILE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BRIDGET FONDA HAS NO FONDNESS FOR LAKES 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By LOUIS B. PARKS 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BEVERLY HILLS _ When you see Bridget Fonda going into
crocodile-filled water in ``Lake Placid,'' her scared look is not
all acting.
</P>
<P>
   Fonda really didn't want to get into that lake, but the 30-foot,
people-gulping, mechanical ``crocodilus`` was not the reason. She
just doesn't like lakes.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was horrible,'' said Fonda, being humorous about it but
also clearly serious. ``I don't like lakes; I never have _ not
since camp. There's something about when something brushes up
against your leg and you think, `What was it?' and you're thinking
about water moccasins.
</P>
<P>
   ``And lake worms. There's just something stagnant about a lake.
There's something dark, and what grows there kind of ... I don't
know. It's iffy.''
</P>
<P>
   Fonda takes the opportunity to point out that she's also not
fond of jumping out of airplanes and that she's afraid of heights.
</P>
<P>
   ``I won't sky-dive; I'm serious about that,'' she said, giving a
rich, throaty little laugh.
</P>
<P>
   She said she can, however, overcome her fear of lakes, if she
has the proper incentive _ such as a movie to make.
</P>
<P>
   ``But for no reason at all?'' she said. ``Just going to go take
a dip in a lake? That ain't going to happen.''
</P>
<P>
   In ``Lake Placid,'' a big creature feature that's more
tongue-in-cheek than actual monster mash, Fonda plays Kelly Scott,
a nature-phobic paleontologist sent by her museum to find out what
game wardens have discovered _ the hard way _ in a
deep-in-the-Maine-woods lake.
</P>
<P>
   It turns out to be a giant crocodile, which everyone agrees
can't possibly be there but nevertheless is. And it has quite an
appetite, too.
</P>
<P>
   Scott reluctantly teams with a game warden (Bill Pullman), an
eccentric crocodile buff (Oliver Platt) and a local sheriff pretty
disgusted with them all (Irish actor Brendan Gleeson, ``The
General'').
</P>
<P>
   As the film's title hints, the movie is subtly witty, the
product of screenwriter David E. Kelley, creator of the TV series
``Ally McBeal,`` ``Chicago Hope,`` ``Picket Fences`` and ``The
Practice.`` (He's married to Michelle Pfeiffer.) Kelley is the
reason Fonda and the rest of the cast made &UR;  &LR; what is otherwise a
throwback to the drive-in movies of days gone by.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't define David Kelley's style, but it's very real, and
yet it's funny without the gags, without real obvious (comedy)
setups,'' Fonda said. ``I was reading (the script) and I was
laughing out loud. It's kind of poking fun and kind of taking
itself seriously.''
</P>
<P>
   The other thing that attracted Fonda was that Scott is an
annoying character _ at least at first _ with a background. As
Fonda has shown before, in films such as ``A Simple Plan,'' she's
quite willing to play characters who are a tough sell.
</P>
<P>
   ``I love a challenge _ somebody who seems it would be really
hard to gain audience sympathy for. I like that. I find most people
sympathetic. I empathize with most people. I can make all kinds of
excuses for behavior.
</P>
<P>
   ``On top of that, David Kelley is not afraid of people's
annoying habits and having them still be likable. He doesn't need
to make people saccharin. I really respect that because it's a cut
above the regular screenwriting shtick.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Lake Placid`` is the latest in a long line of off-the-beaten
paths taken by the adventurous Fonda in her 10-year career.
</P>
<P>
   While her performances have almost always been applauded by
critics, and she's made a name for herself separate from her
distinguished acting family (she's the granddaughter of Henry
Fonda, niece of Jane Fonda and daughter of Peter Fonda), she
remains somewhat overlooked and underappreciated.
</P>
<P>
   Since her screen debut in 1988 in ``Aria,'' she has not only
overcome the simultaneous crutch/handicap/blessing of a famous name
but also has sustained a steady string of distinctive roles in
unusual pictures.
</P>
<P>
   While many actresses of her generation have disappeared after
playing safe but forgettable ``girlfriend'' roles to male stars in
bigger pictures, Fonda has been the lead or at least her own person
in most of her films.
</P>
<P>
   She's averaged more than three films a year, including major
roles or leads in ``Single White Female,`` ``Point of No Return,``
``Little Buddha,`` ``It Could Happen to You,`` ``City Hall,``
``Jackie Brown`` and ``A Simple Plan.''
</P>
<P>
   She has yet to have the breakthrough role that makes a really
big star _ and at 35, she may not. (She has the youthful looks to
play younger than her age, but she doesn't want such roles. ``It's
lost its appeal,'' she said. ``Young tends to be trendy. I'm not
interested in that.'')
</P>
<P>
   But she's had the kind of career most actors at least say they
would like to have, playing strong roles.
</P>
<P>
   If she has a theory why her career has stayed steady while so
many others have shot up briefly, then crashed just as fast, she
doesn't say.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's the luck of it,'' she said, spreading her extra-long,
elegant fingers on her knee. ``I don't know how much of it is my
power and how much is just the way it goes. And then there's the
other question: How much of it is the _ I guess nepotism doesn't
really cover what I'm talking about, but the fact that I have a
famous, identifiable last name? Maybe that's what's kept me there.
I'll never know exactly.''
</P>
<P>
   After Lake Placid, Fonda has several films coming up. Already
done is ``South of Heaven, West of Hell,`` which she describes as
``a Gothic western with everyone under the sun in it'' (Vince
Vaughn, Billy Bob Thornton, Paul Reubens and her dad, Peter Fonda).
It was written and directed by Dwight Yoakam, with whom Fonda
became involved after her breakup from longtime beau Eric Stoltz.
</P>
<P>
   Currently she is filming ``Monkey Bone,'' in which she plays the
friend of an animator, Brendan Fraser, who is in a coma. It's a
dark comedy with Whoopi Goldberg as Death. Reubens is in this one,
too, playing the voice of Monkey Bone, an animated character that
harasses the illustrator while he's unconscious.
</P>
<P>
   Fonda admits she has concerns about the lack of meaty roles for
women her age and older.
</P>
<P>
   ``I look around, and there are already not many parts for women
as juicy and fun as I like. And I say, thank God for theater,
because there will always be juicy roles in theater. But film is
different.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think, `When it falls apart, what will I do?' Well, I can
sew a little,'' she said with humor in her voice. ``Ya know, that
kind of thing.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
