<HEADER>
A1165 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MOVIE-BLAIR16-COX     07-15 0756
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIE-BLAIR16-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Psychological thriller `Blair Witch Project' trades blood and
gore for less is more
 &HT;    By Steve Murray
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   You might forget to breathe at the end of ``The Blair Witch
Project,'' the Sundance Film Festival favorite that takes the shape
of a spooky campfire tale updated to the hand-held-camcorder age.
</P>
<P>
   It's a film chock-full of grainy and blurred images that leaves
you unnerved, exhausted ... and reluctant to turn off the lights at
bedtime. Not since ``The Vanishing'' (the original French version)
has a movie built such a palpable sense of mortal dread. It does so
without a single computer-generated special effect and only the
tiniest splash of blood. A small masterpiece of filmmaking and
storytelling, it's a reminder that real terror sometimes comes from
what you don't see. It's an exhilarating scare.
</P>
<P>
   Tapping into primal terrors, it's a ``Hansel and Gretel'' for
the end of the millennium, rewritten in favor of the witch. It's
best to experience this movie fresh, free of preconceptions. With
that caveat in mind, here's the setup.
</P>
<P>
   Three University of Maryland students _ portrayed by actors
Heather Donahue, Michael Williams and Joshua Leonard, lending their
own names to the flick _ decide to make a documentary about the
fabled Blair Witch. According to oral legend, this was a
child-killing she-fiend in the 18th-century township of Blair, a
place that continued to be plagued by murders and eerie goings-on
even after the citizens fled and founded another settlement,
Burkittsville.
</P>
<P>
   The students make a pit stop there, quizzing the locals about
the old legends. They hear tales of ``an old woman whose feet never
touched the ground'' and of a 1940s loner responsible for the
ritualistic killing of seven children. Then the students continue
their project, heading into the woods with backpacks and rations
and enough camera batteries to ``fuel a small country for a
month.'' They never return.
</P>
<P>
   Here's the truly clever (and creepy) premise: That ``Blair
Witch'' consists entirely of the video footage shot by the trio in
the woods, capturing on tape what happened to them. It's a
first-person journey into the kind of terror that comes from trying
to glimpse something moving in the shadows just beyond the
campfire.
</P>
<P>
   The movie, a wickedly smart fusion of story, structure and
creative use of limited resources, wrings chills out of the
slightest effects: odd, twiglike contraptions hanging from trees.
An unexpected pile of stones. Strange noises in the night. Like the
1963 version of ``The Haunting,'' its power comes from
psychological intensity.
</P>
<P>
   Writer-directors Daniel Myrick and Eduardo Sanchez were savvy
enough to make it a point of tension for Michael and Joshua that
Heather insists on filming everything. This justifies all the
footage _ even if you personally think the last thing you'd do when
you're running in terror is remember to hit the ``record'' switch.
The movie crackles with the reality of a genuine documentary.
There's a reason for that. The actors endured a sort of boot-camp
experience _ spending eight days in the woods, improvising much of
the script according to notes left by the director-producers, and
subsisting on dwindling food supplies.
</P>
<P>
   They're all terrific, degenerating from sardonic college kids to
panicked wrecks. Their fight scenes are as scary as any of the
nighttime assaults by their unseen tormentors.
</P>
<P>
   But Donahue is the standout. She starts off as the team's
cheerleader, a perkily annoying project director (think of
``Election's'' perfectionist class-president contender Tracy Flick
with a camera). She also does a pitch-perfect parody of
documentary-speak, in shots of the unfinished film-within-the-film.
Finally, she embodies paralyzed terror, delivering an already
famous, up-close video confession near the end of the movie.
</P>
<P>
   Ingenious in its conception, consummate in its you-are-there
execution and unforgettably chilling, ``The Blair Witch Project''
is proof that sometimes simplicity is the most powerful artistic
choice. In a summer of bloated and boring Hollywood spectaculars
like ``Wild Wild West,'' this is one movie that actually lives up
to its buzz.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Blair Witch Project''
</P>
<P>
   Grade: A
</P>
<P>
   Starring Heather Donahue, Joshua Leonard and Michael Williams.
Rated R for language. At Tara. 1 hour, 27 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   The verdict: You may never go camping again.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
