<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIE-MUPPETS16-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Kermit, Miss Piggy and friends take hilarity into space
 &HT;    By Eleanor Ringel Gillespie
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Teletubbies may come and go, but Muppets are forever.
</P>
<P>
   ``Muppets From Space'' is more Muppet madness _ a manic mix of
vaudeville shtick, kid-friendly slapstick and hilarious movie
in-jokes, ranging from ``Close Encounters of the Third Kind'' to
``Field of Dreams.''
</P>
<P>
   The plot, of course, matters little. The Great Gonzo (that
vulture-beaked thingie voiced by David Goelz) is shown literally
missing the boat. No, not the Titanic. The Ark. See, Noah isn't
exactly sure what Gonzo is and won't let him on board. And besides,
there's only one of him.
</P>
<P>
   Skip ahead a few millennia. Gonzo is still hung up on his roots.
His search for family ties takes an extraterrestrial turn, and the
next thing we know he's been kidnapped by a paranoid government
agent (``The Larry Sanders Show's'' superfoil, Jeffrey Tambor).
Meanwhile, Miss Piggy (voiced by Frank Oz), who works for the TV
show ``UFOMania,'' intends to use Gonzo's spaced-out odyssey as a
career springboard from coffee pig to on-air anchor-ham.
</P>
<P>
   As usual, a lot of the jokes zip over the little ones' heads.
But parents will appreciate the many clever touches (check out the
fly-splattered wallpaper in Kermit's room or the Mice Girls poster
that provides a ``Shawshank Redemption'' gag). And the Muppets'
patented, post-1960s style of inherent sweetness and screwball
comedy works as well here as it did for kids 30 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Add a few celebrity cameos _ Andie MacDowell, David Arquette,
Ray Liotta, Rob Schneider, a ``Dawson's Creek'' kid or two _ and
you've got a winning family-film formula.
</P>
<P>
   This is a movie for families who, in theory, may be intrigued by
the much-trumpeted ``South Park: Bigger, Longer &AMP; Uncut'' but
really don't want to risk it. Besides, when it comes to sheer '90s
weirdness, you can read anything you want into this exchange
between Gonzo and his roomie, Rizzo the Rat: A frazzled Gonzo
confesses that he's had ``that dream'' again, and Rizzo sighs,
``Not the one about the dwarf and the jar of peanut butter?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Muppets From Space''
</P>
<P>
   Grade: B
</P>
<P>
   Starring the Great Gonzo, Kermit the Frog and Miss Piggy.
Directed by Tim Hill. Rated G. At metro
</P>
<P>
   theaters. 1 hour, 22 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   The verdict: Beam us up, Gonzo.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
