<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-15 12:31 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1167 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MOVIE-PLACID16-COX     07-15 0377
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIE-PLACID16-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Reptilian hunk best part of `Lake Placid'
 &HT;    By Steve Murray
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   You'll dig the 30-foot crocodile in ``Lake Placid.'' But you'll
want him to eat all the humans, quickly. They include bland game
warden Jack Wells (Bill Pullman), paleontologist Kelly Scott
(Bridget Fonda) and wacko mythology professor Hector Cyr (Oliver
Platt), who've gathered at a remote New England lake to investigate
some strange killings.
</P>
<P>
   Fonda plays the feisty, nature-hating city girl who quips ``I'm
allergic to timber'' and sprays the open air with bug repellent.
You can imagine Calista Flockhart tossing off these lines; they're
the trademark work of glib writer-producer David E. Kelley (``Ally
McBeal''). What seems smart and charming on the small screen plays
precious and tinny on the big one.
</P>
<P>
   In this sometimes watchable, underpopulated ``Jaws'' retread,
the croc attacks are predictable and rudimentary. This is the sort
of movie in which no one but bit players gets their head bitten
off. Pity. The scares aren't scary, the laughs aren't funny and
poor Fonda has to keep falling off moving vehicles (boats, trucks)
directly into the path of the monster croc, like some hapless 1940s
heroine.
</P>
<P>
   Brendan Gleeson, the brilliant star of John Boorman's ``The
General,'' is reduced to pratfalls as a local sheriff. Betty White
is dragged in to do her familiar sweet-old-lady-with-a-foul-mouth
routine. And Pullman is so laconic that he's upstaged by the trees.
</P>
<P>
   Stan Winston's crocodile (animatronic and computer-generated) is
a winner. But you know there's something wrong with the flick when
you're more worried about the fate of an imperiled heifer than any
of the humans.
</P>
<P>
   A weird mixture of thrills, snickers and political correctness,
``Lake Placid'' never hits a remotely believable note. It's the
first ecologically sensitive, feel-good monster movie. Huh?
</P>
<P>
   ``Lake Placid''
</P>
<P>
   Grade: C-
</P>
<P>
   Starring Bill Pullman, Bridget Fonda and Oliver Platt. Rated R
for violent creature attacks and related gore, and for language. At
metro theaters.
</P>
<P>
   1 hour, 22 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   The verdict: A crock of a croc tale.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-15-99 1231EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990715.0119 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-15 12:31 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1168 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MOVIE-WOOD16-COX     07-15 0508
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIE-WOOD16-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Friendship's the focus in `The Wood'
 &HT;    By Steve Murray
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``The Wood'' is so awkwardly structured and meandering that you
might be surprised at how effectively it starts to grow on you.
</P>
<P>
   Writer-director Rick Famuyiwa's autobiographical feature film
debut charts the friendship of three buddies from Inglewood, Calif.
(``the Wood'' for short). We meet them as adults, first Mike (Omar
Epps), who gets the movie off to a very shaky start, addressing the
camera and shoveling exposition at the audience.
</P>
<P>
   He's a groomsman for pal Roland (Taye Diggs), due to be married
any minute now. The only problem is, no one knows where Roland has
gone on this, the morning of his wedding. So it's up to Mike and
fellow groomsman Slim (Richard T. Jones) to track down the wayward
hubby-to-be.
</P>
<P>
   When they find him, he's very, very, very drunk. So the morning
becomes a prolonged dry-out spell, as Slim and Mike drive Roland
around _ and reminisce.
</P>
<P>
   Much of ``The Wood'' takes place in 1986, as young Mike (Sean
Nelson) arrives from North Carolina and learns the SoCal ropes from
young Roland (Trent Cameron) and young Slim (Duane Finley).
``Either you gang-bang or you play ball,'' young Slim explains.
</P>
<P>
   Predictably, they also spend a lot of time thinking about girls,
debating who's hotter, Vanity or Apollonia. They compete to get the
most girls' phone numbers at school dances and place bets on who'll
lose his virginity first.
</P>
<P>
   The main girl in the film is Alicia (Malinda Williams), who is
given the sort of ogling, slow-motion entrance that has become a
cliche in teen movies. She's an idealized creature who's a little
bit of everything: gorgeous, down to earth, refined and
hot-hot-hot.
</P>
<P>
   But as ``The Wood'' gets longer, it also gets deeper. It
graduates from Mike's first boorish grab at Alicia's posterior to a
sex scene distinguished by well-observed humor and the kind of
real-life candor you don't usually find in the movies.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, back in the present, we hang with the adult version
of the boys and see all the ways they've grown up, and haven't.
Epps, Jones and Diggs have such airtight rapport, as they banter
over pizza, that you forget you're watching actors. Their
friendship rings true.
</P>
<P>
   That friendship is what sets ``The Wood'' apart from the usual
genre pigeonholing of African-American movies. It avoids the usual
urban-gangsta, raunchy-comedy niches and becomes something much
more universal. It's a male-bonding flick that transcends issues of
race.
</P>
<P>
   And here's a footnote: In a summer characterized by gross-out
sight gags at the multiplex, the movie holds its own with one
protracted barf scene that's as funny as it is vile.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Wood''
</P>
<P>
   Grade: B
</P>
<P>
   Starring Omar Epps, Taye Diggs and Richard T. Jones. Rated R for
strong language and strong sexuality. 1 hour, 46 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   The verdict: A meandering but affecting tale of friendship.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
