<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VIETNAMESE-TEJANO-BAR-ART-$ADV17-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VIETNAMESE BUSINESSMAN FIGHTS FOR TEJANO BAR IN SMALL TEXAS TOWN 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  (For weekend release, July 17-18) 
(Eds.: Photo available on NYT database) 
 
By STEVE OLAFSON 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALVIN, Texas _ There's a faraway look in the eyes of Michael
Thanh Lee, a would-be businessman who has the dull gaze of someone
who's just been hit between the eyes with a two-by-four.
</P>
<P>
   The Vietnamese immigrant toiled unremarkably in real estate and
insurance before deciding to start a business in a downscale
shopping center in Alvin, which is about 30 miles south of downtown
Houston.
</P>
<P>
   In selecting an enterprise, Lee chose a different path from that
chosen by most of his expatriate countrymen. He decided to open a
Tejano bar.
</P>
<P>
   Big mistake.
</P>
<P>
   Then he made another miscalculation. He chose as his location a
blue-collar town where he soon discovered a budding movement to
clamp restrictions on the beer-joint industry.
</P>
<P>
   Lee's biggest mistake, however, was his decision to promote his
business before the all-important beer license had been signed,
sealed and delivered.
</P>
<P>
   When he hung a big banner outside the 3,000-square-foot space he
leased at the Meadow Park Shopping Center that proclaimed, ``Coming
Soon Tejano Night Club,'' neighboring residents went into battle
mode.
</P>
<P>
   Their displeasure, they insist, has nothing to do with the
Hispanic clientele that would be attracted to a Tejano bar, or that
the proprietor would be of Vietnamese descent.
</P>
<P>
   They're just sick of bars and all the problems they bring, the
neighbors say.
</P>
<P>
   ``Two o'clock, when that thing lets out, it'll be a madhouse,
just like it was before,'' predicted C.B. Jolly, a 68-year-old
farrier who lives across the street from the shopping center.
</P>
<P>
   He and other residents tell stories of drunken men and women
venturing into their yards and driveways after stumbling out of
bars that were located in the shopping center in past years.
</P>
<P>
   Before Lee tried to open his bar, however, no one in Alvin had
ever protested the issuance of a beer license for a watering hole.
</P>
<P>
   The reason for that is simple, say bar opponents. Unlike Lee,
none of the other bar owners ever advertised their plans before
obtaining a license.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's where he screwed up,'' Jolly said.
</P>
<P>
   After Lee's banner went up, nearby residents persuaded the City
Council to sign a letter of protest.
</P>
<P>
   The mayor, police chief, a council member and residents showed
up at a March 31 license hearing convened by Brazoria County Judge
John Willy.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was like walking into a lynch mob,'' said Robert Clements,
an Alvin lawyer who represents Lee.
</P>
<P>
   Even though Lee's application for a beer license met all the
technical requirements of the Texas Alcoholic Beverage Commission,
the judge denied the request, citing ``the general welfare, health,
peace, morals, safety and sense of decency of the people.''
</P>
<P>
   The ruling is being appealed.
</P>
<P>
   While his lawyers pursue that, Lee, 43, said he does little more
than sit around his home in southwest Houston and feel the walls
close in around him. He's broke and his wife is grumpy, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``She's already mentioned divorce,'' he said. ``Every day she
says, `What happened to your club?' I feel terrible. I told her
it's not because of my failure. I try to be a man and support my
family, but they won't let me. It's like I live in a communist
country again.''
</P>
<P>
   Lee, whose business venture was inspired by a friend who owns a
successful Tejano bar in Houston, said he has spent $70,000 to try
to open his bar.
</P>
<P>
   His opponents are not sympathetic, saying he was a fool to
invest money in an enterprise that he knew neighborhood opponents
opposed.
</P>
<P>
   Lee's foes say they also want to clamp down on other beer joints
by restricting them to certain areas of town.
</P>
<P>
   Petitions that urge Alvin to take action are circulating, said
Laura Burton, the leader of the self-styled temperance movement,
who lives across the street from the Tejano bar that has been
stymied.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't intend to give up,'' said Burton, a 45-year-old
bookkeeper. ``I don't think anyone is very happy with the number of
bars in Alvin.''
</P>
<P>
   In a weird way, she has Michael Thanh Lee to thank for the
public interest that has been stirred up over the issue. Without
his Tejano bar venture, no one in Alvin would have had a chance to
stage the city's first protest over a beer license.
</P>
<P>
   Excuse Lee, though, if he doesn't have that same sense of civic
pride as Burton and her supporters.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel terrible,'' he said recently, standing in his empty,
windowless bar amid brand-new bar stools that never have been used.
</P>
<P>
   To make matters worse, Lee added: ``To be honest with you, I
don't know that much about Tejano music.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY XXXX &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
