<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-15 12:55 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1187 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-STRAIGHT-EDGE-ART-2TA     07-15 0914
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STRAIGHT-EDGE-ART-2TAKES-$ADV17-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LIFE ON THE EDGE: YOUTH GROUP SAYS `TERRORIST' IMAGE NOT JUSTIFIED 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  (For weekend release, July 17-18) 
(Attn.: Utah) 
 
(Eds.: Photos available on the NYT database) 
 
By LISA DAVIS 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ To the Fur Breeders Agricultural Cooperative in Sandy,
Utah, Straight Edge is a terrorist group.
</P>
<P>
   To Anthony Calleo, it's salvation.
</P>
<P>
   Calleo, an honors student at the University of St. Thomas in
Houston, said the controversial youth movement saved him from the
life of a junkie.
</P>
<P>
   ``Straight Edge totally isn't a bad thing,'' he said. ``It's a
good thing.''
</P>
<P>
   Members of this small, loosely organized group adhere to a
strict and wholesome philosophy: no drinking, no smoking, no drugs,
no promiscuous sex. Many are vegetarians; some won't even drink
caffeine. Their fondness for body piercings and loud music hardly
seems unconventional these days.
</P>
<P>
   But in recent months, the group also has been under fire
nationally after the arrest of some adherents for attacking smokers
or bombing stores, such as the fur co-op, in the name of animal
rights. In Salt Lake City, two face murder charges after a brawl
between Straight Edgers and members of other gangs.
</P>
<P>
   Calleo and other Houston-area young people who believe in the
movement say the national media have blown the exploits of a few
out of proportion, negating the positive impact it has had on
thousands. Those who take Straight Edge to the point of vigilantism
are known as ``hard-liners.''
</P>
<P>
   ``People ask me why I still associate myself with a movement
that has those kind of people in it and identifying themselves with
it,'' Calleo said recently. ``It's because if I didn't, it'd be
like giving up something that meant so much to me to people I think
are just going to ruin it.''
</P>
<P>
   The Straight Edge scene in Houston involves about 150 young
people, from teens to adults in their late 20s.
</P>
<P>
   Like many of the Straight Edgers, Calleo, 19, is a white male
who has battled drugs and alcohol. His hair is shorn and he keeps a
bandana tied around his forehead. Calleo's arms are covered with
tattoos starting at his shoulders and his ears and lower lip are
pierced. To a recent Straight Edge concert he wore Converse tennis
shoes, baggy pants and a basketball jersey with ``Hatebreed'' on
the front of it.
</P>
<P>
   Before he started claiming Straight Edge, which he described as
a grass-roots movement, Calleo said he was well on his way to
becoming a statistic.
</P>
<P>
   Calleo has a history of alcoholism on both sides of his family,
he said, and by the time he was 12 he had already started drinking
and smoking. That led to marijuana, speed, acid and Ecstacy.
</P>
<P>
   ``Finally I started getting more into punk rock and less into
drugs,'' Calleo said. ``I started listening to it and started
reading the lyrics, and more and more I started to see where doing
drugs was getting me. I didn't like doing them anymore and I didn't
like how it was making me feel. ... I was 16 then and that's when I
went Straight Edge.''
</P>
<P>
   For the next six months, Calleo said, he continued to hang out
with his old friends who were a ``bunch of drunk punk rockers.'' As
he straightened out he realized he needed his friends to be clean,
too.
</P>
<P>
   ``I couldn't just watch them kill themselves anymore,'' Calleo
said. ``It (Straight Edge) is a personal choice to make yourself
better. Before you can change the world you've got to change
yourself.''
</P>
<P>
   His mother, Cynthia Calleo, described his maturation and
decision to go Straight Edge as ``getting his snap.''
</P>
<P>
   ``He found out he could be himself without alcohol, drinking and
doing drugs,'' she said. ``I'm very proud of kids who are Straight
Edge, not just Anthony. There are so many things out there to
influence them, and they just say no and stick to their guns.''
</P>
<P>
   In an era where drugs and alcohol are common among youth, it may
not be surprising that teens turn to a movement such as Straight
Edge to resist peer pressure.
</P>
<P>
   ``The only time I'm going to label myself Straight Edge is when
I'm in a situation where there are alcohol and drugs,'' said Emily
O'Neal, a sophomore at St. Thomas. ``People don't get it when you
say `I don't want any,' but they know not to mess with you if
you're Straight Edge.''
</P>
<P>
   Other teens who have decided to go Straight Edge said it is more
than just the decision to be drug-free. It's a united resistance to
all vices and abuses.
</P>
<P>
   Scott Douglas Smith, 25, wears a beaded necklace that says
``Poison Clan.'' It, like the tattoos and shirts other Straight
Edgers wear, signifies his commitment to the movement.
</P>
<P>
   ``We do take Straight Edge to the point to where it's a
brotherhood,'' said Smith. ``It's not really a gang, it's more like
we back each other up. It's something of a religious thing.''
</P>
<P>
   When Straight Edgers slip from their path of sobriety, they are
said to have ``fallen'' or ``lost their edge.''
</P>
<P>
   ``If one of my friends were to fall, it's not like I would say,
`Hey, you're out. I don't care about you,' because that's not what
friendship is about,'' Smith said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would be right there to help them up and say, `Hey man, you
chose Straight Edge for your life. You didn't want this.'''
</P>
<P>
   Straight Edge originated on the East Coast in the 1980s and
spread throughout the United States through punk and hardcore
music, which espouses the values of Straight Edgers.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(MORE) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Teen-agers old enough to get into clubs often are marked with Xs
to show that they aren't old enough to drink. As the Straight Edge
movement took hold, the X became its symbol because those who claim
it have no intention of drinking. At concerts, Straight Edgers
often mark the backs of their hands with a large X.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Xs are like Christian art,'' O'Neal said. ``They are
symbols there to remind you of who you are and to tell others:
`This is what I stand for.'''
</P>
<P>
   The name Straight Edge came from lyrics in a 1981 song by the
Washington, D.C.-based punk band Minor Threat:
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm a person just like you
</P>
<P>
   But I've got better things to do
</P>
<P>
   Than sit around and smoke dope ...
</P>
<P>
   I've got a straight edge.``
</P>
<P>
   On June 19, the Houston club Fitzgerald's hosted Metalfest III,
with a collection of hardcore and Straight Edge bands. They played
to a crowd of Straight Edgers and hardcore fans alike.
</P>
<P>
   The musical styles are the same, with punk and metal sounds
heavy on guitar riffs and loud drums. The singing is more like
deep, throaty screaming into a microphone. It sent some running for
ear plugs, but it led others into a dancing frenzy.
</P>
<P>
   The difference is the lyrics, with Straight Edge songs focusing
on the movement's values.
</P>
<P>
   As Finer Truth, a local Straight Edge band, started to perform,
Straight Edgers thronged the front of the stage. Calleo was in the
thick of it, thrashing his arms, colliding with people and throwing
kicks.
</P>
<P>
   Security guards stood a few feet away with a watchful eye toward
the crowd, but despite the violent nature of the dancing everyone
seemed at ease. Those who didn't want to get involved simply stood
farther from the stage. Audience members there only for the
hardcore music smoked cigarettes and nursed beers by the bar.
</P>
<P>
   ``All the energy I need to release, as far as negative energy, I
release through dancing. It's not like moshing, it's kick-boxing,''
said Smith.``The music is very angry, but that's how I get my
release.''
</P>
<P>
   Music has been a common thread in Straight Edge since its
beginning, and it is a way to reach others with the message.
</P>
<P>
   ``There could be another 14-year-old kid out there who is just
like me, who gets into Straight Edge and ... for the first time
he's not hearing someone who's a cop, a teacher, a priest, a
parent, an adult ... saying that doing drugs, destroying your body
and hurting other people and getting drunk all the time is wasting
your life,'' Calleo said.
</P>
<P>
   Some teen-agers at the concert said Straight Edgers go too far
trying to persuade others to leave their vices.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a positive movement, but a lot of times they get
overzealous with it, pushing their beliefs over the edge and
getting in fights with friends,'' said Brett Heinselman, 24, who
attended the Metalfest.
</P>
<P>
   Heather Lepine, a recent graduate of Klein High School, said,
``I think it's fine, but I just think people are taking it too far,
like when they are taking it to extremes or hurting other people.''
</P>
<P>
   Several other teens expressed similar concerns, but no one could
actually name anyone who had gotten in a fight with a Straight
Edger over beliefs.
</P>
<P>
   The majority of the negative publicity, including a damning
report on ABC-TV's ``20/20,'' has been based on incidents in the
Salt Lake City area. But even Salt Lake officials said the
spotlight has been focused on Straight Edge unfairly.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't (cooperate with) any stories about Straight Edge
because there has been so much inflammatory, misinformation about
Straight Edge in the past,'' said Lt. Zane Smith, director of the
Salt Lake Area Gang Project. ``We have some problems with Straight
Edge, but comparatively it's minute.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite scattered incidents in other cities, the problems in
Utah have gotten most of the media attention. Houston Straight
Edgers said that means five or 10 hard-liners are giving a bad name
to a movement of several thousand across the nation.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't try to preach to anyone. I tell them who I am and why
I am, but if they don't want to do it, they're not going to do
it,'' said Chris Williams, 19. ``I'm not going to say, `Get away
from me, you're smoking or you're drinking.'''
</P>
<P>
   Adrian Garcia, the Houston Police Department liaison to the
Mayor's Anti-Gang Office, confirmed that there have been no known
problems with Straight Edgers in Houston.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're aware of the Straight Edge phenomena, but ... we haven't
had any incidents with Straight Edge here in Houston,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Police officials in Dallas and Los Angeles also said they were
following the story about Straight Edgers and their alleged
exploits in Utah, but that they have not had any problems with
them, either.
</P>
<P>
   ``Straight Edge is not a popular thing in Houston, Texas.
Straight Edge is not for the masses,'' said Smith. ``I wish I could
be like everyone else, but I'm not. I have this conviction that's
stronger than anything else in my life other than the love for my
daughter.''
</P>
<P>
   Calleo, like Smith, said he agrees it would be easier to be like
everyone else, but he has to do what he believes is right.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can honestly say I'll be Straight Edge until I die. I'm not
going to be 35 years old putting Xs on my hands and going to shows
and dances, but I'll be drug-free and chemical-free with that
mind-set for the rest of my life,'' Calleo said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I do it because it's better for me, it's better for other
people. I also do it because I think no matter what, my actions are
going to affect other people.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
