<DOCNO> NYT19990715.0128 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-15 13:16 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1204 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBA-REDSOX-BOS &LR;      07-15 1455
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-REDSOX-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SECOND HALF WILL SHOW WHAT RED SOX REALLY HAVE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By GORDON EDES  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON -- The party was a blast, but after a day of taking down
the bunting, sweeping out the trash, and tucking Pedro finally to
bed, the season must go on.
</P>
<P>
   The Red Sox resume play with that bane of Jimy Williams's
existence, interleague play, as the Philadelphia Phillies arrive
for a three-game set.
</P>
<P>
   The Sox are 3-9 against their National League cousins, with
three games to follow against the Florida Marlins when the Phillies
leave town.
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, a moment to consider the obvious. The first
half exceeded all expectations. The Sox are on a pace to win 90
games, just two fewer than the total that got them a wild card last
season. They're just four games behind the Yankees in the AL East,
but the gap between second and third place is even smaller, as the
Toronto Blue Jays have crept to within three games.
</P>
<P>
   The Sox have played the best teams in the league very well
head-to-head. In games against the division-leading Yankees,
Indians and Rangers, they're 12-6. Now, in the season's second
half, the schedule would seem to be in their favor. Of their last
74 games, only 23 are against teams with winning records.
</P>
<P>
   All-Star shortstop Nomar Garciaparra will be back in the lineup,
but while Tom Gordon is expected back in town, the jury remains out
on a return date. Pitching coach Joe Kerrigan says the next two
weeks should be a good indicator of whether Gordon will avoid elbow
surgery and reclaim his role as Sox closer.
</P>
<P>
   There are just over two weeks to the July 31 trading deadline,
and general manager Dan Duquette has made it no secret that the Sox
are in the market for a big bat. Last season at this time, Duquette
reacquired Mike Stanley, who hit seven home runs and drove in 32
runs down the stretch. Duquette could be aiming for bigger game
this time.
</P>
<P>
   A look back, and a look ahead:
</P>
<P>
   Good karma: Sox go into October with a pitching rotation of
Pedro Martinez, Bret Saberhagen, and Ramon Martinez, with Tom
Gordon back as closer.
</P>
<P>
   Bad karma: Pedro tires, Saberhagen's shoulder acts up, Ramon
remains in rehab, and Flash never makes it back.
</P>
<P>
   Good karma: Sox pull off maybe the greatest All-Star show ever;
Dan Duquette doesn't have to hide from questions about Mo Vaughn
and Roger Clemens, since neither one were All-Stars, and Jose
Offerman has a great start, then goes into a slump; the other way
around, and critics would have been calling for Duke's head.
</P>
<P>
   Bad karma: Tom Gordon hurts his elbow just as author Stephen
King, who built a best-selling novel around the Sox closer, tells
fans sitting around him, ``I hope I haven't jinxed him.'' King
himself is struck by a van and winds up in the hospital; Bret
Saberhagen cuts his foot on broken glass while hosting a team
party; Sox lose close game to Braves in extra innings when
third-base coach Wendell Kim doesn't see bunt sign from Jimy
Williams.
</P>
<P>
   Good karma: Troy O'Leary. Sox left fielder had a brutal second
half and worse postseason (1 for 16) last year, then puts up Mo
Vaughn numbers (.297, 17 home runs, 58 RBIs) in the first half this
season. He's turned himself into a good Fenway Park outfielder,
too. Sox hope that his .205 average this July is related more to
Nomar Garciaparra's absence than another second-half slump.
</P>
<P>
   Bad karma: Mark Guthrie. Lefty reliever has been a workhorse
when healthy, but the results have been dismal, and now he's on the
DL with a frayed Achilles tendon.
</P>
<P>
   Good karma: Pitching callups from Pawtucket _ John Wasdin, Jin
Ho Cho, Brian Rose, and Juan Pena _ have combined for 15 wins, and
at one point were unbeaten in 14 decisions.
</P>
<P>
   Bad karma: Wasdin has lost three in a row since opening 7-0,
Pena is in the Gulf Coast League trying to come back from a bad
shoulder, and Rose and Cho are a combined 0-4 with a 8.86 earned
run average in their last five starts.
</P>
<P>
   Good karma: Nomar Garciaparra hits two grand slams and drives in
10 runs in one game, bats .394 in June, and takes a 17-game hitting
streak into the All-Star break.
</P>
<P>
   Bad karma: Garciaparra misses last nine games after aggravating
a strained left groin, making a total of 11 games missed because of
the groin, and an additional six games with a hamstring strain
sustained in April.
</P>
<P>
   Good karma: Brian Daubach, Wilton Veras. Rookie Daubach, a punch
line when floated as a possible replacement for Mo Vaughn, has hit
over .300 all season in DH/1B platoon with Mike Stanley and hasn't
gone more than two starts without a hit. Veras, called up from
Double-A Trenton, spends a terrific couple of weeks filling in for
John Valentin, serving notice of becoming the third baseman of the
future.
</P>
<P>
   Bad karma: Chad Fonville, Bob Wolcott. Fonville, summoned as
emergency infield help from Pawtucket, mishandled three consecutive
balls at second base in his only start and was gone two days later.
Wolcott pitched four times in a month and faded away as quietly as
he came.
</P>
<P>
   Good karma: Catcher Jason Varitek, seizing the chance to play
every day when Scott Hatteberg has season-ending elbow surgery,
shows himself to be a masterful handler of pitchers and superb
receiver.
</P>
<P>
   Bad karma: Varitek is charged with five passed balls in five
innings with knuckleballer Tim Wakefield on the mound. Hatteberg
hurts his elbow when he slips in loose sand while making a throw
during spring training. Creighton Gubanich hits a grand slam off
Oakland's Jimmy Haynes for his first major-league hit, then is sent
down to the minors shortly thereafter before being recalled.
</P>
<P>
   Good karma: Jeff Frye returns from a year-long absence due to
knee surgery and reclaims his starting job as second baseman.
</P>
<P>
   Bad karma: Three weeks into the season, Williams replaces Frye
at second base with Offerman, and Frye winds up having more knee
surgery. Offerman, meanwhile, has the second lowest fielding
percentage among AL second basemen.
</P>
<P>
   Good karma: Before he's hurt, Frye and Darren Lewis, slugging
flyweights, hit back-to-back home runs in the bottom of the ninth
for a walkoff win against the Twins.
</P>
<P>
   Bad karma: Sox right fielders have hit four runs and 32 RBIs,
ranking last in the league in both categories. Rookie Trot Nixon
was hitting .136 after a month, but has been batting close to .300
since. Still, the production is lacking.
</P>
<P>
   Good karma: Mo Vaughn, in his much-heralded return to Fenway
Park with the Anaheim Angels, manages one hit in three games.
</P>
<P>
   Bad karma: Sox run production has dropped to 10th in the league
without Vaughn. Last season, they were third in runs. The Sox do
not have a player who ranks in the top 10 in home runs, RBIs, runs
scored, or hits.
</P>
<P>
   Good karma: Williams has the Red Sox just four games behind the
Yankees despite having to rotate No. 3 hitters, losing Gordon,
converting Tim Wakefield to closer, Valentin having an off-year,
Garciaparra out for extended time, Offerman nose diving, and other
assorted minidramas.
</P>
<P>
   Bad karma: On April 22 in Detroit, Williams starts a lineup
which has Lou Merloni at first, Creighton Gubanich catching, Damon
Buford hitting fifth and Donnie Sadler playing left field. Tigers
lefthander Justin Thompson shuts Sox out on one hit through eight
innings; Tigers need just 1 hour 49 minutes to beat the Sox, 1-0.
</P>
<P>
   Good karma: Bret Saberhagen has won his last four starts and has
walked one batter or fewer in nine of his last 10 starts.
</P>
<P>
   Bad karma: Saberhagen won his first two starts, then didn't win
another game until after the summer solstice.
</P>
<P>
   Good karma: Rookie Brian Rose is holding lefthanded hitters to a
.144 average, lowest in the league.
</P>
<P>
   Bad karma: After failing to cover first base in a nationally
televised game, Rose is called an ``embarrassment to everyone in
the uniform'' by pitching coach Joe Kerrigan.
</P>
<P>
   Good karma: For past favors, team in Japan gives Duquette a
little-known pitcher, Tomokazu Ohka. He goes 11-0 in his first pro
season here and starts the Futures Game last Sunday in Fenway Park.
</P>
<P>
   Bad karma: Sox invite John Jaha for a visit this winter, but
take one look at his medical records and decide to pass. Jaha hits
19 home runs for the Athletics and is an All-Star.
</P>
<P>
   Good karma: Mark Portugal, who abruptly quit because he wanted
to spend more time with his family, is persuaded that he can be a
good dad and a working pitcher, too.
</P>
<P>
   Bad karma: The Sox are giving Portugal the worst run support in
the league, 3.82 runs per nine innings.
</P>
<P>
   Do these things all even out in the end? Red Sox fans know
better. But what better time than the last year of the century to
catch a break?
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
