<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WHITE-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MEDITATING YOUR WAY TO A BIGGER BUST 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DIANE WHITE  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The strangest things appear on my desk, most recently the Athena
II Breast Beautification Program. Is someone trying to tell me
something?
</P>
<P>
   It's an impressively packaged box of audiotapes billed as ``A
Healthy, Natural Alternative to Breast Enlargement Surgery.'' It's
also cheaper, although not exactly cheap at $125.
</P>
<P>
   ``Increase your bust size 1 to 3 inches in 2 months.
Guaranteed,'' a line on the the package promises. From her Chicago
office, Amy Radick, the Athena II marketing representative, said
the system uses relaxation techniques and guided imagery to
increase blood flow to the breasts, thus making them bigger.
</P>
<P>
   I told her that sounds preposterous. She conceded that it might
seem ``far-fetched'' to some, but that studies conducted by the
company proved it works. Radick said 60 women had participated in a
two month-long study and all but two had experienced significant
breast enlargement. The average gain was 1 1/2 inches. One woman
added 3 1/2 inches.
</P>
<P>
   The tapes aren't meant to be listened to while driving. This is
not because they might cause the breasts to deploy suddenly,
risking accident, but because total relaxation is required to
meditate upon a larger, firmer bustline. ``Picture the blood flow
increasing to your breasts . . . think about it, imagine it . . .
your breasts are growing bigger, firmer, and more beautiful . . .
relax . . .imagine.''
</P>
<P>
   Imagine indeed. What is it with breasts? Stupid question. I know
what it is with breasts. Still, I continue to be amazed at the
number and variety of things people are able to peddle to women
eager to make more of their bustlines. The back pages of women's
magazines are full of ads for breast enlarging creams, vitamin
supplements and exercise devices. The WonderBra, The Miracle Bra
and Curves, The Invisible Breast Enhancer are more popular than
ever. When the Wonderbra fails to work wonders, there's the ``It's
All You!'' bra, which gathers up any extra flesh on the back,
midriff, waist, wherever, and traps it in a formidable brassiere
that looks like it could have played a persuasive role in the
Inquisition.
</P>
<P>
   Breast enlargement surgery is, of course, the quickest way to
achieve observable results. It's the second most popular plastic
surgery procedure, trailing only liposuction. The surgical bosom
enlargement business is booming, up 302 percent since 1992,
according to the American Society of Plastic and Reconstructive
Surgeons.
</P>
<P>
   There's always something new on the bigger breast front. An
alternative to surgery still in the testing stages, caused a stir
when it was introduced at the May meeting in Dallas of the American
Society for Aesthetic Plastic Surgery. ``It's a contraption that's
difficult to describe, kind of a vest, with a suction pump,'' said
Elliot Jacobs, a New York plastic surgeon who attended a
presentation.
</P>
<P>
   In tests, women who wore the device for 12 hours a day for 10 to
12 weeks had measurable increases, an average of half a cup size,
documented by MRI's and other tests. ``It's based on a sound
scientific principle,'' Jacobs said, ``If you put constant stress
on living tissue it will stretch.''
</P>
<P>
   Will it stretch enough to undermine the breast implant business?
That's unlikely. However, if it does work, it could provide an
alternative for women who don't want to have surgery, to say
nothing of an alternative to questionable methods of breast
enlargement such as the Athena II program.
</P>
<P>
   Listening to those tapes I remembered how we used to joke in
high school gym class: ``We must, we must, we must increase the
bust.'' Could that be marketable? In the bigger bust business,
anything's possible.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Diane White is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
