<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-15 13:19 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1208 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-AUTHOR-CHAPLIN-2TAKES     07-15 1115
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AUTHOR-CHAPLIN-2 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW TEMPEST SWIRLS AROUND `DARK WIND' 
</HEADLINE>
 TAKES-ART-BOS  
 (ART ADV.: A photo is being sent to NYTNS clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchases by calling 212-556-4204 or -1927.)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOSEPH P. KAHN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON -- The storm that took Susan Atkinson's life veered
southward without warning, packing 100-knot winds that turned an
idyllic lagoon in the Marshall Islands into a roiling deathtrap.
Anchored close to shore, Atkinson and her companion, Gordon
Chaplin, elected to ride out the typhoon aboard their 36-foot
sailboat, a foolishly fatal choice. The boat was ultimately driven
aground and splintered by the pounding surf.
</P>
<P>
   Roped together, Atkinson and Chaplin were thrown into the
churning sea. Their life vests were quickly torn away. ``Hold me
up,'' Atkinson implored. And then, according to Chaplin:
</P>
<P>
   (itals)We were underwater again. I opened my eyes and saw her
clearly, as if she were outlined in black fire. There was a little
smile on her lips and her eyes were half closed. Her long hair
spread out in the water. The top of her head was about a foot under
the surface, and when I put my hand under her chin and tried to
push up, another wave was there.(unitals)
</P>
<P>
   Atkinson's body was never recovered. Chaplin stumbled ashore,
battered yet miraculously alive. That was nearly seven years ago,
on Nov. 19, 1992.
</P>
<P>
   Chaplin, a freelance journalist and novelist, has now published
a book about the tragedy, ``Dark Wind: A Survivor's Tale of Love
and Loss'' (Atlantic Monthly Press). It chronicles not only the
series of miscalculations that led to Atkinson's drowning but also
describes, in often harrowing detail, the couple's personal
conflicts and the guilt he still harbors about having survived
while Atkinson did not.
</P>
<P>
   ``I needed to figure out what really happened _ for both of
us,'' explains Chaplin, in an interview conducted at the Weston
home belonging to his ex-wife and daughter. Atkinson was a
Brookline native and author who began her professional life as a
nurse at Massachusetts General Hospital.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't necessarily see it as an accident,'' Chaplin
continues. ``It could have been. But I needed to show what led up
to it and whether something in our lives, or outside our lives, had
led us to do what we did.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Laboring over his manuscript for five years was therapy for him,
says Chaplin. But he also wanted others to know the full story,
especially Atkinson's two adult daughters, Ashley and Page, even
though Atkinson's family had expressed reservations about seeing it
in print.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was the only survivor,'' he says. ``I felt a compulsion to
tell people who cared about Susan what really happened.''
</P>
<P>
   Chaplin dedicates ``Dark Wind'' to Atkinson's daughters and has
arranged for them to receive any profits generated by the book. His
text quotes from letters written by and to members of Atkinson's
family, not all of them flattering to Atkinson's private assessment
of Chaplin. He made the manuscript available to them before
publication, he says, and invited them to suggest changes, which
they acknowledge doing.
</P>
<P>
   Thus it surprises Chaplin to be shown a statement given to the
Globe by Atkinson's daughters. It reads:
</P>
<P>
   ``We made it clear to Gordon Chaplin that we did not want him to
publish this work about our mother, Susan Atkinson. Based on our
knowledge, this book is not an accurate depiction of events as they
occurred. The publication of this work, and its inaccurate
portrayal of our mother, is a continuing unwelcome intrusion into
the lives of our family.''
</P>
<P>
   Chaplin blinks.
</P>
<P>
   ``The part about it not being an accurate depiction bothers me
deeply,'' he says slowly. ``I can see where they might have a
different portrait of their mother than mine. Whether it's their
portrait is something I have no control over.
</P>
<P>
   ``What you've read'' _ he stares into the distance _ ``they gave
me permission to use the material, they signed release forms. This
is very heavy.''
</P>
<P>
   Is it possible that to an extent he had not realized before,
Atkinson's family holds Chaplin responsible for her death?
</P>
<P>
   ``I faced that question when I got back,'' Chaplin replies.
``Her brother Ned believes to this day that both of us caused this
to happen. I don't agree. That was one reason I went over this
story so thoroughly, to satisfy myself that a pattern of
self-destruction didn't exist.''
</P>
<P>
   He smiles wanly. ``I hope they'll grant me that I'm being
accurate to my own picture of Susan,'' he repeats. And then, in
words you don't hear often from touring authors in today's
marketplace, he says, ``If canceling my book tour would make them
more comfortable, tell them I'll do it.''
</P>
<P>
   Reached later, Ned Atkinson, Susan's brother and a Boston
attorney, says the pain Chaplin has stirred up has more to do with
the fact that the book exists at all than with its specific
details.
</P>
<P>
   ``We all have our memories of Susan,'' says Atkinson. ``And no
matter how you read this book, it somehow diminishes them. Her
death has become an event in Gordon's life. He doesn't accept
responsibility for the person he is.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In Hollywood terms, Chaplin's tale combines elements of
real-life adventure sagas like ``A Perfect Storm'' with the
fictional boy-loses-girl pathos of ``Love Story.''
</P>
<P>
   He and Atkinson first met in the 1960s, when she was married to
Chaplin's former college roommate. Both grew up in privileged
circumstances _ Chaplin along Philadelphia's Main Line, Atkinson in
what Chaplin calls ``one of those New England families in which
insanity is passed down along with the Chippendale and the pewter
and the Harvard education.''
</P>
<P>
   By 1980, Atkinson's marriage had ended and Chaplin was literally
sailing away from his. The two began a life together that took them
from a remote Mexican village to rural New York State. It also took
them to sea, as Chaplin described in his book ``The Fever Coast
Log,'' about their adventures in Central America. Chaplin had
sailed all his life; in Atkinson he found a partner willing to set
aside fear of physical risk to master the intricacies of open-ocean
sailing.
</P>
<P>
   What made their relationship special, says Chaplin, was the
supposition that without taking risks, life offers few rewards.
</P>
<P>
   ``Susan believed you should do something every day that you're
not comfortable doing,'' Chaplin says. ``She wasn't a real physical
person, but she was very courageous. If she was more cautious than
I, it was because I'd been diving and sailing all my life. Her
fears had to do more with what might happen to me.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MORE &LR;  &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
