<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-IDENTITY-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KOSOVARS FINDING IT HARD TO RESTORE LEGAL IDENTITIES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SUSAN MILLIGAN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   PEC, Yugoslavia _ It was the ultimate indignity for Kosovo
refugees lucky enough to make it to the border alive, and now it is
shaping up as a bureaucratic nightmare for those who have returned:
the destruction of the ethnic Albanians' personal documents.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the documents have been burned: hundreds of thousands of
identification cards, passports, driver's licenses, automobile
license plates and work records that made up the life history of
the Kosovar Albanians.
</P>
<P>
   Those who made it to Morina Pass in Albania, or to Macedonia,
were forced to hand over all their documents to Serbian police,
reducing the Albanians to officially nameless figures without a
history, either as a people or as individuals.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can't document anything about ourselves now,'' said Ali
Kelmendi, 39. ``It's like you're not a man anymore.
</P>
<P>
   ``Anybody in town knows that I worked for 20 years, but I can't
prove it,'' said Kelmendi, who ran a small business before the war.
``It was all in my burned house.''
</P>
<P>
   In a war full of anonymous massacres, mass burials and unmarked
graves, even the survivors were deprived of their sense of self.
</P>
<P>
   Marched in long columns, packed into buses and trucks like farm
animals, and forced to leave Kosovo, virtually all of the refugees
all were subjected to the same parting shot. A card table was set
up at border stations, refugees say, and a gun-wielding Serb
policeman forced them to empty their pockets.
</P>
<P>
   This, the final step in the Serbs' ethnic ``cleansing campaign''
to drive Albanians from the province where they constituted 90
percent of the population, eradicated any record that the Albanians
had lived, learned, worked and owned property in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   ``They took everything, and they burned everything'' at the
border, said Naser Gjuka, 40. They didn't leave any chance for us
to prove we are Albanians, or even humans.''
</P>
<P>
   The loss of identity papers is personally unsettling for the
returning refugees, and it also presents a massive complication for
a province struggling toward some kind of order and interim
governance.
</P>
<P>
   Without documents, the government-in-the-making cannot determine
who owns what, who worked where and for how long, and who is
eligible to drive or to receive a pension.
</P>
<P>
   International agencies haven't even begun to address the
problem, since they are still concerned with housing and feeding
Kosovars and helping them form an interim civil administration,
said Susan Manuel, a spokeswoman for the United Nations Mission in
Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   Some refugees have registration cards issued at refugee camps in
Macedonia and Albania, but the cards show nothing other than the
fact that the individuals fled and returned to Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   Pristina's City Hall re-opened this week, but it will be weeks
before the provincial administration is at full force, and much
longer before it begins to assess and credential the population.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the documents have been found, and are under protection
by Kosovo Force (KFOR) soldiers, said Ron Redmond, a spokesman for
the United Nations High Commissioner for Refugees.
</P>
<P>
   But in many towns, records were completely destroyed, said
Volker Turk, the refugee agency's legal counsel. The only hope may
be convincing bureaucrats in Belgrade to hand over any duplicate
records they have, Turk said.
</P>
<P>
   But agencies here aren't expecting the Serbian government, which
lost total control of Kosovo when the war ended, to cooperate.
``It's a major problem,'' Redmond said.
</P>
<P>
   International officials are hoping most of the documentation
problem will be solved informally. In villages and small towns,
most Albanians knew each other, and knew where everyone lived _
enough, officials hope, to prevent major disputes over property.
</P>
<P>
   Many ethnic Albanians do not want documents issued from
Belgrade, despite the fact that Kosovo is still part of the
republic of Serbia and the nation of Yugoslavia. Passports, for
example, are typically issued by federal governments _ in this
case, the one centered in Belgrade.
</P>
<P>
   But Kosovar Albanians, who have long hoped for the right to
travel freely and safely, say they would rather stay forever
tethered to Kosovo than to travel abroad on Yugoslav documents.
</P>
<P>
   ``I never want to get a Belgrade passport. Belgrade is dead for
me,'' said Shefkinazo Muhaxniri, 63.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't want anything from those who did this to me,'' said
Gjuka, gesturing toward his burned and looted house in Pec. ``I
don't want their documents now.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
