<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WEST-BANK-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ON WEST BANK, TWO VILLAGES NERVOUSLY AWAIT PEACE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CHARLES M. SENNOTT  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HALHOUL, West Bank _ This Palestinian farming town is tired of
waiting for peace.
</P>
<P>
   Halhoul is supposed to be the next West Bank town from which
Israeli troops withdraw and Palestinian forces take control under
the peace process. But for two years hopes for independence have
been on hold in this community north of Hebron, and its 26,000
people have descended into despair over a crippled economy.
</P>
<P>
   Just across a rocky valley, the neighboring Israeli settlement
of Karmei Tzur has also waited for the next phase of the peace
process and worried about its future.
</P>
<P>
   The laboriously negotiated Wye River accord calls for Israeli
troops to withdraw from land around the 450 religious nationalists
who've staked a claim in houses and trailers ringed with barbed
wire. When the troop pull-out happens, they say, they'll be left
vulnerable to attacks by Palestinian militants. They fear attempts
to remove them from land they believe God granted them.
</P>
<P>
   Both sides of this valley know that when Israel's new prime
minister, Ehud Barak, meets President Clinton in Washington
Thursday the futures of their communities and the fate of the
Middle East peace process hang in the balance. How Barak will weigh
the disillusionment of the Palestinians against the fiery ideology
of the Israeli settlers is anyone's guess. But what's certain is
that he will have to find a solution, and soon.
</P>
<P>
   In a series of meetings Barak will lay out his strategic vision,
and is expected to urge the United States to play a less pronounced
role as a peace broker. He is also intent on convincing Clinton
that some time is needed to implement the Wye River agreement.
Clinton worked tirelesly to get both sides to sign Wye and is said
to be anxious to break the long deadlock that occurred under
Barak's predecessor Benjamin Netanyahu.
</P>
<P>
   Barak needs time, analysts say, in part because of the domestic
political pressure that will come to bear on him from the religious
right and settlers as his new coalition moves toward
implementation. The question is whether the peace process can
survive another delay.
</P>
<P>
   Halhoul's mayor, Mohammed Milhem, insists it can't.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need to see that peace means change,'' said Milhem. ``We
need to see that peace is real, and not an illusion. We've been
waiting a long time. Too long.''
</P>
<P>
   Halhoul has been uniquely frustrated by the stalled peace
process. For two years, it has been on the verge of what
Palestinians call ``liberation'' from the Israeli military control
of the West Bank, which Israel captured in the 1967 Six Day War.
And for two years, it has waited.
</P>
<P>
   Seven months ago, after the signing of the Wye agreemnt, Halhoul
unfurled banners in anticipation of troop withdrawals and a visit
by Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat. He never came. The official
transfer of the land from shared Israeli-Palestinian control to
full Palestinian control never happened. The banners have been
taken down.
</P>
<P>
   On the terraced hillsides of this fertile valley, peach trees
are weighted down with their harvest and grape vines form canopies
over the brown soil that clings to the craggy slopes.
</P>
<P>
   But farmers can't get their produce to market since Israel
restricts travel on the roads and requires expensive permits and
tariffs for any exports. Laborers who illegally sneak into Israel
to scratch out a living on low-paying jobs want official work
permits. Water wells are contaminated and bone dry.
</P>
<P>
   Mayor Milhem, 70, who was born and raised in Halhoul, says that
his community has grown more than just weary of the peace process.
He believes that even when the pull back of Israeli troops happen,
it won't change much in Halhoul.
</P>
<P>
   What he says is most important is the opening of the so-called
``safe passage'' roads which will connect West Bank towns like
Halhoul to the pockets of Palestinian controlled areas throughout
the West Bank and especially in Gaza. The farmers need the broader
markets for export. They also care more about beginning
construction of a commercial port in Gaza, which will open the
market further for international exports. Both of these plans _
safe passage and construction of the port _ were agreed upon under
Wye.
</P>
<P>
   Adnan Heinehan, 39, a Palestinian business man, asks, ``How long
can you wait? The sad truth is that we were economically better off
before the peace process.''
</P>
<P>
   From Halhul, heading north on the wide, paved ``bypass road''
that leads to the Karmei Tzur, the growth of the settlement is
visible. Five trailers placed on a hillside sit next to the first
of 40 new foundations being poured. The work is being done hastily
because ``facts on the ground,'' as the settlements are often
called, matter. Settlement leaders fear in the next redeployment
their community will not only be imperiled but possibly evacuated.
</P>
<P>
   The head of Karmei Tzur's council, Esti Uliel, said, ``There is
a real possibility we will be left surrounded by Palestinians. . .
. The Palestinian Authority does not want peace. . . . The Wye
agreement is wrong, Oslo is wrong. We can only hope that Israel
will wake up to see that.''
</P>
<P>
   Barak has been vague about the further redeployment from roughly
13 percent of West Bank land called for under Wye. Some analysts
believe at least one or two settlements that dot the West Bank
would have to be removed. Palestinians say the settlements are
illegal and that their expansion is a violation of the peace
process. The settlers remain entrenched and defiant.
</P>
<P>
   ``We will never leave,'' says Shlomo Neeman, who came nine years
ago as a new immigrant from Russia. ``We believe in the
righteousness of our path.''
</P>
<P>
   Deep mistrust dwells in the valley between the settlers and
Palestinians. But there is an important piece of the history of the
land that binds Palestinian Muslims and Christians with their
Jewish neighbors. All three faiths embrace the prophet Jonah who,
the bible claims, was buried in Halhoul. Tradition holds that
Jonah's tomb is in the central mosque, where a stone shrine
shrouded in black attracts visitors of all three faiths.
</P>
<P>
   Hassan Abu Yussef, 91, who has delivered the call to prayer at
the mosque for 50 years, recounted the biblical passages referring
to Jonah being swallowed by the whale and cast out only after he
expressed faith in God.
</P>
<P>
   ``Palestine is like Jonah,'' he said. ``It has been swallowed by
the Ottoman empire, the British mandate, Jordanian rule, and the
Israeli army. Now it is about to be cast out to live under its own
government. But it is not the peace process that achieved that, it
is God's promise.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
