<HEADLINE>
O'MEARA FORECASTS SOME ROUGH GOING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOE CONCANNON  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   CARNOUSTIE, Scotland _ There will always be those major
championship flashbacks for Mark O'Meara. There he was, rolling in
a remarkable putt on the 18th green of the Masters in 1998 to win a
championship he coveted. There he was, sitting on a slope at the
British Open at Royal Birkdale watching Brian Watts make a
remarkable sand shot to set up a playoff.
</P>
<P>
   When O'Meara won that four-hole playoff, it made him the oldest
player (41) to win two majors in the same year. They were also his
first two majors, and he hasn't won a tournament since.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a dream come true,'' said O'Meara Wednesday, on the eve
of the 128th British Open at the storied links of Carnoustie Golf
Course in the Angus district on the North Sea. ``The last year has
been a lot of fun. It was disappointing to have to bring the old
Claret Jug back to the R&AMP;S secretary's office earlier this week.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would be nice to come out and have a great week and play
well. The golf course is very tough and very demanding. Of the 14
Opens I've played in, this is by far the toughest set-up I've ever
seen. Not only is the rough extremely deep and very difficult to
play out of, but the golf course is very narrow, too.
</P>
<P>
   ``You throw the wind on top of that with the length (7,361
yards) that this golf course is, it's going to be a heck of a
contest to keep the ball somewhere in either the short grass or the
semi-rough, and try to make pars. On some holes bogey is going to
be a good score because it is a long golf course.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hit a 1-iron on the ninth (a 474-yard hole) and hit a 3-wood
into the green. You're going to see a lot of guys sacrificing
distance for short grass and accuracy, because even though some of
the longer hitters will take out the driver you're going to see
some hitting 1-irons, keeping the ball low and just trying to chase
it down the fairway.''
</P>
<P>
   It has not been the best of years for O'Meara, who has only one
top-10 finish _ third at The Memorial. ``I think a lot of it has to
do with my confidence,'' said O'Meara. ``I could be playing a
little better. I really haven't putted as well this year. It's a
combination of all those things together. Golf is a fickle game.
That's just the way it is.''
</P>
<P>
   Even though Royal Birkdale reared its nasty head in high winds,
O'Meara was up to the challenge. ``The fairways were a little
wider,'' he said, ``and I don't think the rough was quite as deep
as this. But even-par won the championship. It just seems this
course is narrower as any I've ever seen in an Open.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would think here the rough has taken some of the bunkers out
of play. Players are not going to hit driver or 3-wood. They're
going to sacrifice once again the distance to put the ball on the
fairway.''
</P>
<P>
   Some feel his success in 1998 may have taken a toll, but O'Meara
disagrees. ``I had more opportunities out there that presented
themselves of what I did last year,'' he said. ``I've tried to
capitalize on some of them. I've played a lot around the world
since last year. I've enjoyed that. You can say maybe it's taken a
toll. I don't think it has.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are times where you're not playing as well or your
expectations are higher than what you are seeing in your
performance, and then it can be a little frustrating. I took a
little time off after the US Open, and I might take time off after
this championship.''
</P>
<P>
   And as for this championship, O'Meara knows it will be difficult
to turn his year around at Carnoustie.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would like to get out and get a good solid round under my
belt,'' he said. ``I feel I'm starting to putt a little bit better,
and that's a good confidence boost. This is going to be somewhat
like the US Open. You're going to miss a lot of greens out there,
so your short game will have to be good and you're going to have to
make some putts.''
</P>
<P>
   The severeness of Carnoustie, where Tom Watson won the last Open
here in 1975, was evident in Wednesday's final practice round in
brisk, windy conditions. ``It's brutal,'' said Billy Andrade of
Bristol, R.I., after his third practice round. ``It's a brutal
test. The man who wins on Sunday here, in my eyes, will be the
greatest golfer in the world.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's going to test every part of your game. You're going to
have to have the patience. Who knows what's going to win? If it's
windy and it gets wet, I'd say a 295 or 300 would win this
tournament. You've got to keep the ball in the fairway. It's hard
to hit these fairways with no wind, let alone with wind. It's by
far the severest of all the Opens I've played in, US or British. I
love it. That's why I'm here. I think if you just hang in there
this week you've got a chance of winning.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
