<SLUG> BC-GLF-BRITISH-GARCIA-2 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SERGIO GARCIA: NEW NAME IN THE GAME 
</HEADLINE>
 TAKES-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB DUFFY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   CARNOUSTIE, Scotland _ Conseulo Garcia didn't like to bother her
husband at work. After all, they shared the same place of
employment _ she in the clubhouse shop, he as head professional at
the Mediterraneo Golf Club in the seaside town of Bottriol, Spain.
She knew that the members' demands on Victor were incessant, and
right now he was at his busiest, organizing a club tournament.
</P>
<P>
   But she was afraid this matter couldn't wait any longer.
``Victor,'' she told him on the 10th hole, ``I'm having
contractions.''
</P>
<P>
   So much for the tournament. Husband and wife rushed to the
hospital, where they became mother and father to a second son Jan.
9, 1980.
</P>
<P>
   The newborn, Sergio, had no say in the matter, but he certainly
wouldn't have been pleased that his parents dragged him away from
the golf course.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The boundaries of his existence always have been from tee to
green, and now, suddenly, his horizons are planetary. Suddenly, but
hardly surprisingly. For while he seems to be blazing across the
pro golf scene like a comet, he has actually followed a
meticulously plotted course to the constellation. Still, his
emergence is unimaginable to the uninitiated.
</P>
<P>
   He is all of 19 years old, has more use for Clearasil than a
shaver, hasn't qualified for a driver's license, lives at home, and
has a year of high school to go. Yet he already has achieved the
ultimate in recognition _ single-name status _ on every course he
graces. Tiger. Greg. Jack. Arnold. Seve. And now Sergio.
</P>
<P>
   Which was why Wednesday's announcement on the eve of the British
Open _ trumpeted as a blockbuster by his manager, Jose Marquina _
was as extraneous as it was extraordinary: ``If you don't mind, I'd
like you to call me `Sergio' in the media if that is possible,
because I feel much better than (being called) `Garcia' . . . I've
always liked people to call me `Sergio' because it seems more
familiar.''
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps that's an indication of the innocence lurking beneath
the virtuoso talent. His request is a bit like someone asking that
today be called Thursday. Throughout his week of preparation at
Carnoustie Golf Club _ capped by a 2-under-par 69 with no bogeys on
this 7,361-yard behemoth Tuesday _ one word from the galleries has
virtually punctured his eardrums: ``Sergio! Sergio!'' The refrain
has been as constant as it has been universal _ from small
children, teens barely his age, young adults, and senior citizens.
He has become a word in the golf dictionary in near-record time.
</P>
<P>
   The British Open will be his eighth pro tournament, although it
also will mark the third time he has teed off in this major
championship. Having turned pro in April a week after finishing as
the low amateur in the Masters, he got so rattled in his second
event for pay, the Byron Nelson Classic in Dallas, that he
struggled to an opening-round 62 and managed only a third-place
finish. It took him six tournaments to register his first pro win _
in the European Tour's Irish Open at Dublin two weeks ago. So taken
aback was he by that success that in his very next round, at the
Loch Lomond Open outside Glasgow last week, he ballooned to a 62.
And he threatened to make it two wins in a row before bogeying two
of the last three holes and winding up second to Colin Montgomerie.
That lifted him to seventh place in the European Ryder Cup
standings, and he's a shoo-in to be in Brookline, Mass., as part of
the team facing the United States at The Country Club Sept. 26-28.
</P>
<P>
   And the most amazing thing is that none of this is amazing.
Peripheral observers have labeled him the next Tiger and the next
Seve, but they're off the mark. The golf literati know him as the
original Sergio _ and they have for years.
</P>
<P>
   ``He has everything to be a great champion,'' says Seve
Ballesteros, Garcia's homeland idol and unofficial mentor for
several years. ``His game is so strong. I saw it from the beginning
that he was a very special talent.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Three or four years ago, the first time you put eyes on him,
you could see that there was something special about him,'' says
Masters champion Jose Maria Olazabal, the other member of the
Spanish pantheon. ``Maybe the most impressive thing was the mental
attitude. I think that's his strongest part.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's obvious he was ready to come out,'' says US Open winner
Payne Stewart. ``He's just beaming with personality. He's friendly.
He's fun. He's going to be around for a long time.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, they're banking on Garcia to galvanize European golf the
way Woods did the US PGA Tour two years ago. The only factor that
might prevent that is that Garcia belongs to the world _ he'll be
playing in the US and Japan as well as on the Continent. ``This
kid's gonna take me all over the place,'' says his caddie, Jerry
Higginbotham, who has carried the bags of Ben Crenshaw in the '70s,
David Graham in the '80s, and Mark O'Meara in the '90s, and expects
Garcia to be his millennial meal ticket.
</P>
<P>
   Even Woods, now a sage at 23, has no doubt about his impact: ``I
think what he has done is show the world how talented he really
is.'' And Tiger should know.
</P>
<P>
   Where matters of golf are concerned, Garcia _ uh, sorry, Sergio
_ seems to take it all in stride.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I turned pro, I want to get my card and then I said in a
couple of interviews that I wanted to win one tournament or more
before the year end,'' he says. ``I've already won one and now I
try to go for some more.''
</P>
<P>
   Nothing he does can surpass his own expectations. When he turned
pro, he announced that he would shave his head to signal his first
victory. He persuaded his father and Marquina to make a similar
promise. All now sport the skinhead look. Sergio did the honors.
He'd been carrying the razor in his luggage since his pro debut.
</P>
<P>
   But then, what other logical conclusion could there be for a kid
who has been programmed for success, who was placed in a golf test
tube before adolescence?
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MORE &LR;  &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
