<SLUG> BC-BBO-ALLST-RYAN-COL-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FENWAY SHOWED THE CLASS OF BASEBALL'S GRANDE DAME 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB RYAN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON -- It was as if grandma had invited the baseball world
over to her house for dinner.
</P>
<P>
   An All-Star Game at Fenway? With all that old funky furniture?
One bathroom for 33,000 people? The old icebox instead of a modern
fridge with the gargantuan freezer? All those embarrassing
knickknacks?
</P>
<P>
   And _ get this _ no food court!
</P>
<P>
   I mean, grandma's sweet and we love her to death, but is she
really up for it?
</P>
<P>
   Now that it's over, and Fenway Park, the Red Sox, and the city
of Boston put on a phenomenally successful All-Star Game, the
verdict is in: Grandma's got a few good years left. You can put
that number for assisted living back in the desk drawer for the
time being.
</P>
<P>
   Get used to the idea. Fenway is going, and the 1999 Game was
indeed the final such occurrence in this park (figure the 2009 or
2010 game for Dot.Com Field, or whatever they'll be forced to name
the new one when fiscal practicality finally wins out over
romanticism). What we saw Monday and Tuesday night's was the
beginning of the countdown. That's why Larry Walker was smart to
grab that clump of right-field grass he was proudly brandishing to
the media after the game. So what if he is now permanently off Joe
Mooney's Christmas card list? He knows he'll never be back here
again (unless The Duke has something clever up his sleeve).
</P>
<P>
   Speaking of Mooney, the venerable groundskeeper discovered that
his reputation had well preceded him. ``Someone from Major League
Baseball said to me, `Oh, we've heard all about you!' '' he
cackled.
</P>
<P>
   Mooney is part of the Fenway aura, every bit as much as the
ladder, the door, the red seat, or, God bless her, ageless Helen
Robinson, who Wednesday morning was on the job at the Fenway
switchboard, as she has been since 1941.
</P>
<P>
   The Fenway ghosts had better seats than even the swells in the
reprehensible 600 Club for the goings-on. You think they're not
chuckling over the fact that, after 53 years and 27 innings of
play, the National League has yet to hit a baseball over any Fenway
fence, never mind The Wall?
</P>
<P>
   Start feeling sorry for the Atlanta Braves. They've got the 2000
All-Star Game. But that's all they've got. It turns out that the
game _ the last seven innings, anyway _ was by far the least
appetizing tidbit on the Fenway/Boston All-Star platter.
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta will have a Home Run Derby, but it's not going to have
the HOME RUN DERBY we had Monday night. Those Georgians can just
fuhgeddabouttit. Mark McGwire might hit 20 baseballs clear into
South Carolina next year and it won't have the impact those 10 he
knocked over the hallowed 37-foot-high left-field wall and the
23-foot screen perched atop it had in the first round of Monday
night's contest. (He hit two more into the screen and one to
center, giving him a record 13 for the round.) In years to come, no
one will recall that Junior Griffey actually won the contest, not
even Junior. But everyone who was there will take to his or her
grave the memory of McGwire sending baseballs to MIT, the Bunker
Hill Monument, Bell Circle, Bangor, Newfoundland, and Neptune, or
wherever those baseballs landed after they soared over the wall,
over the screen, and off into the balmy July night.
</P>
<P>
   And who's kidding whom? 488 feet? If three or four of those
babies weren't 520-footers, or more, then Ted Williams never hit
.300.
</P>
<P>
   The great thing about what happened before the game Tuesday
night is that no one was remotely prepared for it. All the media
knew was that various members of the Top 100 Players of the Century
list would be introduced. But this is, after all, Boston, the only
city with a 128-year continuous run of major league baseball. The
sport is genetically implanted here, and its traditions are
thoroughly respected. These great players would be appreciated to
some degree anywhere, but in a town that truly understands and
loves how hard it is to play this game well, the greats of the past
are revered, all the more so if they have had a hand in frustrating
these very fans and their elders. The only place Bob Gibson and Lou
Brock would be received so well outside of St. Louis, for example,
is Boston. These men stood between the 1967 Red Sox and the
ultimate fulfillment of the Impossible Dream, and everyone who
follows baseball in Boston knows it.
</P>
<P>
   So it was that the Kevin Costner introduction of the 31 Top 100
representatives who were on hand took on a life of its own. Seeing
these diamond luminaries assembled on the infield was a magical
moment.
</P>
<P>
   And then out from center field came that golf cart carrying
Teddy Ballgame himself.
</P>
<P>
   He waved his cap _ the wrong cap, thanks to his shameless
huckster son, John Henry _ and that was nice enough. Longtime Sox
employee Al Forester pulled the cart in front of the pitcher's
mound, and then the script fell apart. The great stars of the past
and the great stars of the present slowly encircled the Greatest
Living Ballplayer in a deep show of love and respect, and it was
hanky time.
</P>
<P>
   The great Theatre of the Absurd moment came when PA announcer Ed
Brickley was forced to request that the old stars and the new stars
leave the field so that the game could begin. It was as if they
were so much media scum, the difference being that the media must
slink off the field to the jeers of the fans when they are asked to
leave. Stan Musial, Willie Mays, Sammy Sosa, and Cal Ripken don't.
They can do what they damn well please, and who cares if the games
starts a few minutes late?
</P>
<P>
   In fact, at that moment, who cared if they ever played a game?
They could have sent the 34,187 home without drawing a whimper from
anybody.
</P>
<P>
   And yet there was one more business matter to conduct. Pedro
Martinez, grandma's official host pitcher, took the mound and did
unto the great National League stars as he has been doing unto the
lesser folk he sees in regular-season play. Only Matt Williams put
a bat on the ball, and that was a feeble grounder somehow mangled
by normally reliable Roberto Alomar.
</P>
<P>
   Six batters, five strikeouts. Winning pitcher. MVP. All that was
following the script.
</P>
<P>
   In a strict financial sense, this was just another convention.
Hah. We know better. All the doctors, lawyers, accountants, and
software salesmen in the world don't provide one-10th the glamour
and life that these ballplayers, old and new, brought to our
ancient city.
</P>
<P>
   You can say that about all these All-Star Games, but there was
something very special about this one. Grandma Wrigley and Grandma
Fenway, baseball's first cousins, are the only ballparks that can
give us what we had at this All-Star Game.
</P>
<P>
   Hey, Atlanta. Good luck, y'all.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Bob Ryan is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
