<SLUG> BC-MISSING-EDITOR-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BOOK EDITOR MISSING AFTER UNITY CONFERENCE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By KIMBERLY A.C. WILSON  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ Had things gone as planned, Joe Wood would have packed
his bags after a journalism conference last week in Seattle, and
flown home to New York Sunday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   He would have shown up for work this week at a Manhattan
publishing house.
</P>
<P>
   He would be headed on another cross-country trip to visit
friends and meet with some of his Los Angeles-based clients.
</P>
<P>
   But no one has heard from Wood, the 34-year-old, Yale-educated
book editor, since last Thursday. His car was found Wednesday night
at a Longmire parking lot, on the south side of Mount Rainier
National Park. A park-entrance receipt in the rental car showed he
arrived at Mount Rainier a little after noon on Thursday. Rangers
plan to search the area this morning with bloodhounds.
</P>
<P>
   Friends and relatives Wednesday enlisted the help of a Seattle
detective agency.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to know what's happened to him,'' said Wood's longtime
friend, Somini Sengupta.
</P>
<P>
   Sengupta, a New York Times reporter, was in town last week with
Wood to attend UNITY '99, a conference of minority journalists. She
last saw him Wednesday evening at the opening ceremonies for the
convention in downtown Seattle.
</P>
<P>
   When she awoke Thursday, she opened her laptop computer to check
her e-mail. She found a missive from Wood saying he planned an
afternoon hiking trip on Mount Rainier.
</P>
<P>
   ``Since I heard from him on Thursday, no one has,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Wood, a former editor at the Village Voice newspaper who has
edited non-fiction books at the New Press since 1996, never checked
out of his Seattle hotel or returned his rental car. His luggage
remains stowed in an office at the hotel.
</P>
<P>
   Sengupta, Wood's parents and his employers want to know what
happened to Wood. This week, they began flooding the offices of
searchers on Mount Rainier and deluging the voice mailbox of
Seattle missing-persons detective Ray Holm.
</P>
<P>
   But there were few answers as the official investigation bounced
from police jurisdictions on both coasts.
</P>
<P>
   Sengupta, who began calling Seattle police Tuesday to report
Wood missing, learned Wednesday morning that she first needed to
file a missing-person's report in Brooklyn, where he lives.
</P>
<P>
   Then, the New York Police Department's 77th Precinct passed on
the report to the Seattle detective Wednesday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   But while a private eye began searching for Wood on the snowy
foothills where Wood planned to hike and bird-watch last Thursday,
an official search remained on hold until Wednesday when his car
was found.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll begin a full search first thing in the morning,'' said
Maria Gillett, spokeswoman for Mount Rainier National Park.
</P>
<P>
   Wood's white Mercury Marquis rental, with Oregon license plates
WVN-303, was found in the Longmire parking lot late Wednesday. But
there was no sign of Wood.
</P>
<P>
   Dolores Kong, a Boston Globe reporter who also attended UNITY,
had also planned to hike Rainier.
</P>
<P>
   But after a fellow reporter chided her about hiking alone on the
mountain just weeks after a Georgia doctor was lost while
snowboarding, Kong waited until she could hike with a friend.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even then, there was a lot of snow at the parking-lot level at
the Sunrise visitors center,'' Kong recalled.
</P>
<P>
   Friends in New York are anxious. An avid bird-watcher who
eschews cell phones and beepers, Wood usually carries a purple
knapsack and dons a New York Yankees baseball cap while hiking.
</P>
<P>
   Christine Johansen, office manager at the publishing house, said
colleagues were hoping for the best.
</P>
<P>
   ``We all hope he's OK and gets back soon.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
