<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-15 13:30 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1231 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TEN-DAVIS-MARTIN-BOS &LR;      07-15 1253
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEN-DAVIS-MARTIN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SELFLESS MARTIN GIVES ALL FOR THE US 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOE BURRIS  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BROOKLINE, Mass. _ Chances are you've never heard of Jake
Haunty. You probably weren't at Northwestern a decade ago when he
etched his name into off-campus intramural basketball tournament
lore by sinking a 15-foot turnaround jump shot at the buzzer to
lead Delta Tau Delta to the championship. It's safe to say that
beyond the participants and their fraternity brothers, few people
couldn't care less about the game.
</P>
<P>
   Except that Todd Martin makes you wish you were there. He was
there, a 6-foot-6-inch freshman seated on the Delta Tau Delta bench
with tennis skills worthy of leading Northwestern to its first Big
Ten title in 30 years but sorely lacking in basketball prowess.
</P>
<P>
   Still, he was merely pleased to have gotten a good look at the
winning shot. He was among those who soaked up the comraderie
during the team's run and stormed the court in celebration
following the championship.
</P>
<P>
   Martin left Northwestern in 1990 to pursue a career in tennis.
He has filled a resume that includes eight singles titles, four
doubles titles, a current No. 10 ranking in the world, $5,983,016
in prize money, an appearance in the 1994 Australian Open finals
and membership on every Davis Cup team since 1994.
</P>
<P>
   Yet he still considers that moment on the Delta Tau Delta bench
among his greatest achievements in sports.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I made the finals of the Australian Open, I was just one
person when I was out there, and I celebrated by myself,'' said
Martin, the ultimate team player and the primary reason why the US
men's Davis Cup team enters Friday's quarterfinal tie with
Australia with no controversy surrounding who will play singles.
</P>
<P>
   Pete Sampras joined the team in June, two months after the US
beat England, 3-2, in the first round. Many would assume that
Sampras, the third-ranked player in the world, would play singles
in the tie against Australia, but those spots are occupied by
Martin and Jim Courier, the latter of whom won two grueling matches
in England.
</P>
<P>
   But Martin has offered to give up his singles spot so Sampras
could play there. Team captain Tom Gullikson reiterated Wednesday
that Sampras has said he wants only to play doubles and, barring
injury, will do so. Still, Martin's willingness to give up his spot
for the sake of the team has all but smoothed over what could have
been a hot media topic this week.
</P>
<P>
   The thing is, Martin's gesture surprises no one. The player who
won the ATP Tour sportsman award in 1993 and 1994 is widely known
as one of the most amicable players in tennis.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our focus this week is to win as a team. winning as an
individual and being on the court as an individual is secondary,''
said Martin. In a sport in which one often celebrates victory and
endures setbacks alone, he said his most enjoyable triumphs have
been in the Davis Cup.
</P>
<P>
   ``After the Australian Open, I went into the locker room and I
had a coach who said, `Good job,' and then I lost a day or two
later,'' he said. ``It was a little anticlimatic.''
</P>
<P>
   The three-day, best-of-five tie features singles A and B
matches. Saturday features doubles at 1 p.m., and Sunday includes
singles C and D.
</P>
<P>
   Team lineups and order of play for the tie do not need to be
determined until one hour before the Davis Cup draw, which is at
noon Thursday on the Longwood grass courts. Sampras's name would
have to be in the draw pool to be selected for singles.
</P>
<P>
   If it is not, the only way he would be able to play singles is
if the US would clinch the tie by Saturday (Sunday's matches would
be played regardless) or if Courier or Martin would suffer from a
medical condition serious enough to allow Sampras to play.
</P>
<P>
   Unless Gullikson runs counter to what he has maintained since
Sampras joined the team, there won't be any surprises at the draw.
</P>
<P>
   ``Things haven't changed,'' he said Wednesday after the second
of two US practices. ``I talked to Pete and we had a team meeting a
couple of nights ago, and Pete feels strongly that Jim and Todd
should play singles. Unless something happens injury-wise, he
doesn't anticipate playing singles.''
</P>
<P>
   Martin, 29, joined the Davis Cup team in Gullickson's first year
as captain. Gullikson said the team has benefitted from his
team-first attitude.
</P>
<P>
   ``Todd has really matured in one of our best Davis Cup
players,'' said Gullikson. ``He is extremely loyal to the program
and to the team and the country. He's been there virtually every
time for us when he's been asked to play singles or doubles or
both. He is really the ultimate team player. He brings a lot of
good character quality to the team.''
</P>
<P>
   Martin has an 11-4 career singles record at Davis Cup (14-9
overall). He is coming off a 1-1 singles mark in England; he gave
the Americans a 2-0 lead after beating Greg Rusedski, 6-4, 6-4,
6-2.
</P>
<P>
   Yet he knows that defending Wimbledon champ Sampras is playing
at a level worthy of his No. 3 ranking in the world in singles. As
long as he can take the court in victory when the matches are over,
Martin doesn't matter watching the singles from the bench.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want Gully to feel like he could put the best team out on
the court and not feel bad about it,'' said Martin. ``I think Pete
has swallowed enough pride by sayng he would just play doubles and
wants to be a part of it. That's more than enough for me.
</P>
<P>
   ``From there I think we should put the ball in the captains'
hands, and I think we should all mature about it and whoever he
thinks should play should play and we should accept our roles.''
</P>
<P>
   Martin playing singles doesn't necessarily mean advantage
Australia, which is expected to field Patrick Rafter (No. 2 in the
world) and 18-year-old sensation Lleyton Hewitt. A Martin-Rafter
meeting would mark a repeat of this year's Wimbledon quarterfinals,
which Rafter won, 6-3, 6-7, 7-6, 7-6. He beat Rafter in the third
round of the Paris Indoor last year, 5-7, 7-6, 7-6.
</P>
<P>
   Both matches came during Martin's comeback after missing seven
months due to shin and elbow injuries suffered in 1997. He sat out
of this year's French Open due to a right shoulder injury.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've had a week off and this is the second time I've hit since
Wimbledon,'' said Martin, ``and I feel like things are in pretty
good shape. I'm going to constantly work on my strengths this week
to allow things to keep from getting broken down.''
</P>
<P>
   Martin credited teammate Jim Courier's victory over Tim Henman,
a four-hour, five-set thriller, as giving him momentum to beat
Rusedski in straight sets during the tie against England in April.
</P>
<P>
   ``Had Jim not beaten Tim, I think I would have assumed Rusedski
to come out on the court more prepared to play against me,'' he
said, ``and I might not have been able to play as well as I did.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you get out to a 2-0 lead, although we lost the lead,
it's nice to have three opportinities to clinch the match.''
</P>
<P>
   Gullikson said he was pleased with Wednesday's workout, which
ended with Courier and Martin playing an extensive singles match.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're just trying to get a little rhythm going and getting our
game faces on,'' he said. ``(Wednesday) is when you start thinking
about the match a little bit more. Typically the guys have worked
hard on Monday and Tuesday and Wednesday is usually the last day of
hard work. (Thursday) after the draw most of the guys just hit once
and lighten up on their work.''
</P>
</TEXT>
