u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBO-ALLST-TV-COLUMN-B     07-15 0806
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-ALLST-TV-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RATINGS WERE A FALLING STAR 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By HOWARD MANLY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON -- Ratings, schmatings.
</P>
<P>
   The numbers are in and the millenium's last All-Star Game
demonstrated pretty clearly that freedom of choice has choked the
mass appeal of the former national pastime.
</P>
<P>
   Something about this new generation. How in the world does
``Buffy the Vampire Slayer'' even compare to coverage of the
greatest assemblage of living baseball players on the planet?
</P>
<P>
   For the record, the country hasn't gone completely mad. There
are some pockets of baseball fans still standing. A little wobbly,
but holding their own.
</P>
<P>
   Cleveland led the nation with a 27.8 rating and 45 share. It's
no wonder. The All-Star Indians accounted for every American League
run to beat the National League.
</P>
<P>
   Boston was second with a staggering 25.1 and 43 share. It
smashed ``Buffy'' 's 6.4 rating and offered further proof that
Boston is a baseball town. Not even Fox analyst Bob Brenly's quips
could deter the faithful.
</P>
<P>
   Someone had to mention the Red Sox' inability to win a
championship since 1918. That would be Brenly. He was talking about
the autumn-like weather Tuesday night when he took a shot at the
team. ``Boston fans are not used to seeing games played in the
fall,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Brenly didn't stop there. He told the national audience that
Pedro Martinez is known to ``fade'' at the end of the season and
that there was ``no way'' he would finish the season with 30
victories. Brenly failed to mention that Martinez, all praises be
due, might have only 14 or 15 more starts during the second half of
the season.
</P>
<P>
   That's all right. Bostonians are an enduring lot, and baseball
just wouldn't be baseball without a little poke every now and then.
</P>
<P>
   Cleveland and Boston understand the pain. So does St. Louis,
which came in third with a 19.8 rating and 34 share.
</P>
<P>
   Those numbers are all good, but nationally the game took another
hit. The ratings dropped 9 percent from last year to a 12, with a
22 share. It was the second-lowest rating for the game in the last
30 years.
</P>
<P>
   The audience peaked from 9:30-10 p.m. EDT with a 14.1 rating and
stayed above 12.0 until 11 p.m. Once most of the starters were
replaced, the rating dropped to a 9.9 from 11-11:30 p.m., and a 7.7
from 11:30-midnight.
</P>
<P>
   Fox officials weren't overjoyed by the numbers, but pitching
duels are for the purists, not the casual fan seeking games filled
with spectacular highlights. And besides, the real star was the
ballpark. Not one of the All-Stars was able to even hit The Wall,
much less knock one over it. No video could ever replace actually
being at Fenway.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're happy that we were able to provide fans with one of the
most memorable moments in sports history,'' Fox spokesman Dan Bell
said.
</P>
<P>
   No number could ever do justice to the sight of Ted Williams
surrounded by the past and present All-Stars. Willie Mays and Ken
Griffey. Mark McGwire and Stan Musial. Hank Aaron and Sammy Sosa.
</P>
<P>
   The only thing close was the coverage by Fox. By all accounts,
it matched the joy of the night, able to convey the raw emotion of
Williams shedding tears as he threw out the first pitch and the
sheer amazement of Martinez striking out four straight batters,
five in all.
</P>
<P>
   The cameras and microphones caught everything, including the
tacky cap Williams's son gave him to wear promoting his website.
</P>
<P>
   Fox's coverage withstood competition from its cable rival, ESPN.
The self-proclaimed sports leader re-aired the Women's World Cup
championship at 8 p.m., buying advertisements in USA Today touting
the telecast. But ESPN earned slightly lower ratings than what its
programming received last year directly against the All-Star Game.
That programming included shows on cheerleading, bloopers, and
gymnastics.
</P>
<P>
   ``We wanted to show the game again while it was still fresh,''
ESPN spokesman Dave Nagle said. ``It made sense.''
</P>
<P>
   Hmmm. What a cowinkydink, considering the legal spat between
ESPN and Major League Baseball over ESPN giving NFL games more
respect than baseball.
</P>
<P>
   ESPN is not alone. The country isn't giving the sport that much
respect either.
</P>
<P>
   It's a shame.
</P>
<P>
   The All-Star Game was a night of childlike wonderment, a night
of the way things used to be, a night of nostalgia, not a night of
cheap promotion or silly competition.
</P>
<P>
   ``Look at them all, smiling like Little Leaguers,'' Fox
announcer Joe Buck said as the cameras panned the crowded infield
of All-Stars surrounding Williams.
</P>
<P>
   Ah yes, Little Leaguers.
</P>
<P>
   And to think Fox, the zany network oft-criticized for its blue
hockey streaks, was able to make us all remember being kids in the
summer.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Howard Manly covers the sports media for The Boston Globe.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
