u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBO-ALLST-MARTINEZ-BO     07-15 0850
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-ALLST-MARTINEZ-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SHOWING BY MARTINEZ STRIKES HOME 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By LARRY WHITESIDE  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   (itals)``This is very special. But after tomorrow it's all over.
Everybody goes home and I have to go back to work.''(unitals)
</P>
<P>
   _ Pedro Martinez &QL;
</P>
<P>
   BOSTON -- Leave it to the Red Sox ace to put everything into its
proper perspective. The excitement of Tuesday night's 70th All-Star
Game will last only until his next start, which comes Sunday. But
the magic of yet another grand moment in Fenway Park history will
stay with him forever.
</P>
<P>
   Martinez will no doubt be telling his grandchildren of the night
he pitched two scoreless innings during a 4-1 victory by the
American League. The fact that he struck out the game's first four
batters, a record, and five of the six he faced will be mentioned
prominently. It earned him the Most Valuable Player award, which
only two other Red Sox _ Carl Yastrzemski (1970) and Roger Clemens
(1986) _ had previously won.
</P>
<P>
   ``It really means a lot,'' said Martinez shortly after being
named the MVP. ``Not only to myself as an individual, but also for
baseball and for the fans, my people, the hometown, everybody. I
think this one had a little more taste than the previous ones I've
been in. I just glad that it went to my side. I thank God for the
things that have come to me. Especially since I didn't expect it.''
</P>
<P>
   In the last All-Star Game of the 20th century and almost
certainly the last at Fenway Park, Martinez came through as
advertised against a National League lineup that included two of
the game's top power hitters, Mark McGwire and Sammy Sosa. Most of
the sellout crowd of 34,187 were Red Sox fans, and they cheered
every strike by Martinez.
</P>
<P>
   Martinez became the second player ever to win an MVP award in
his home park, and the first pitcher to win at home since Jimmy Key
prevailed in relief at Toronto's Skydome in 1991. The last starter
to win at home was Steve Rogers of Montreal in 1982.
</P>
<P>
   It was only the sixth time that a pitcher born outside the
United States has gotten the win. The others were Juan Marichal
(Dominican Republic) in 1962 and 1964, Charlie Lea (France) in
1984, Dennis Martinez (Nicaragua) in 1991, and Bartolo Colon
(Dominican Republic) in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   After Martinez left the game, he was followed by David Cone,
Mike Mussina, Jose Rosado, Jeff Zimmerman, and Roberto Hernandez.
Cone allowed the only National League run in the third inning,
cutting the AL lead to 2-1. But the NL could get no closer. The
Americans did all their scoring in two innings, getting pairs of
runs in the first and fourth. For the first time since 1990,
neither team hit a home run.
</P>
<P>
   It all came together on a perfect night for baseball. A year
ago, when the Red Sox agreed to replace Milwaukee as All-Star Game
host, skeptics were everywhere. The park, first opened in 1912, had
not hosted since 1961. Given its dimensions, the 13-8 rout by the
AL at Coors Field in Denver last year looked to be a low-scoring
game in comparison. There was nothing to suggest things would turn
out like this.
</P>
<P>
   But they did, thanks to Martinez, who had pitched twice
previously in All-Star competition in relief.
</P>
<P>
   Everything was in place by game time Tuesday night. FanFest,
which drew 105,363 patrons to the Hynes Convention Center over five
days, had ended at 5 p.m. The pregame ceremonies at Fenway included
the introduction of 32 legends nominated for the All-Century team.
Finally, there was the return of Red Sox legend Ted Williams to
Fenway to throw out the first ball.
</P>
<P>
   Then came Pedro. With his 15-3 record and assortment of pitches,
how could he fail?
</P>
<P>
   ``Not everybody gets a chance like this,'' said Martinez. ``And
here in Boston, no one appreciates it better than these fans. They
really understand what it's all about. They really understand their
baseball and their tradition.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was not only the last (All-Star Game) of the century but
also the last one with all those players being there. I never
dreamed in my lifetime in seeing all of them together. I don't
think anybody else is going to do it. It's probably bigger than
just participating.''
</P>
<P>
   If nothing else, Martinez showed a national audience that he is
baseball's best pitcher.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was pumped up and sky high,'' said AL manager Joe Torre.
``I'm glad he's on my side. When you have a guy like like Pedro,
it's like hitting in a darkroom. With his arm speed, it doesn't
matter if he's throwing his fastball or changeup.''
</P>
<P>
   It was the third straight victory by an American League team
since a 6-0 loss in Philadelphia in 1996. Torre also managed the AL
team that posted a 3-1 victory in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you have a chance to pick nine or 10 pitchers from all
over the league, there is a good chance you will wind up with
quality,'' said Torre. ``We had quality tonight. I think you
appreciate a lot of things that went on here. It showed a lot of
class. It's going to mean a lot for me to say I was on the field
for the last All-Star Game of the century.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
