u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GLF-BRITISH-HOGAN-2TA     07-15 0961
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-BRITISH-HOGAN-2 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AT CARNOUSTIE IN '53, HOGAN MADE A MAJOR STATEMENT 
</HEADLINE>
 TAKES-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JIM MCCABE  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   It was a moment of great triumph, and Ben Hogan, in the
aftermath of his fourth US Open championship, had reason to smile.
</P>
<P>
   Until . . .
</P>
<P>
   ``The British Open is the only major title you've never won.
Isn't that so?'' asked a reporter from the back of the crowd. The
locker room at Oakmont Country Club grew silent. Hogan's smile
turned into an icy stare. No one dared say a thing. Finally, Hogan
spoke in a voice that both informed and reprimanded: ``It's the
only one I never tried for.''
</P>
<P>
   After allowing that to sink in, Hogan, favored greatly by the
American golf writers of the day, again smiled and went on with the
locker room celebration. He had just concluded a six-shot win in
the national championship, which, on top of his five-shot triumph
at the Masters, had cemented his lofty position as America's
greatest golfer.
</P>
<P>
   A month later, he would be elevated to legend.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Forty-six years have passed since Ben Hogan made his one and
only appearance in the British Open. Forty-six years since the Wee
Ice Mon was christened amid the heather in golf's birthplace.
Forty-six years since British writer Pat Ward Thomas penned: ``That
was Hogan. We shall never see his like again.''
</P>
<P>
   Years have past, but many would argue that Thomas's words hold
up. The Hogan visit to Carnoustie in 1953 holds that much appeal.
</P>
<P>
   It is a story that will be repeated many times in the next few
days as the 128th British Open is played out over the grueling
links of Carnoustie's Medal Course, just 20 miles north of St.
Andrews.
</P>
<P>
   Carnoustie. The mere mention of it conjures up the image of
Hogan, smoking a cigarette beneath his trademark white cap, staring
straight ahead, his eyes colder than the wind whipping in off the
North Sea. Even if you weren't there, you can picture it. If you
were there . . . well, the memory is special.
</P>
<P>
   ``I played four rounds right behind him,'' said Peter Thomson.
``It was pretty slow behind him. There was a fair amount of waiting
and waiting. So I got to watch him quite a bit.''
</P>
<P>
   Thomson was a 23-year-old Australian playing in his third
British Open, and though he would shoot 72-72-71-71 and threaten
the top spot all three days (in those days, the British Open
concluded with a 36-hole finale), Thomson never entertained
thoughts of a championship. ``I wasn't ready to win. I was still
fiddling with golf clubs,'' he said. There was only one winner in
his mind. ``Hogan. He was recognized as the best player in the US
at the time. We expected him to win.''
</P>
<P>
   There was an awe about Hogan, and the fact he had finally
relented and gone to play the British Open was major news. ``They
kept after him and kept after him and kept after him,'' said Frank
Stranahan, the dominant amateur player of the 1940s and early '50s.
``They kept telling Hogan, `You've gotta win the British Open. It's
the thing you have to do for your career.' ''
</P>
<P>
   They? It has been reported through the years that Walter Hagen,
Tommy Armour, Bobby Jones, and some key business associates were
the most vocal in telling Hogan he needed to play in the British
Open. But Stranahan, who considered Hogan a friend, said the event
would never have unfolded had it not been for Valerie Hogan, who
agreed it would be good for her husband to play. Stranahan was on
the plane that carried the Hogans across the Atlantic.
</P>
<P>
   When Hogan arrived, said Thomson, there was no mistaking his
presence. ``He was friendly with someone from the National Cash
Register Company and stayed at their mansion (11 miles away), not
in Carnoustie,'' Thomson says. ``He lived in comfort; the rest of
us lived in digs _ that's what we called them. He took a big limo
to the course.''
</P>
<P>
   But Hogan in Scotland was no different from Hogan in the US.
Determined. Alone. Unflappable. Stranahan played several practice
rounds with him and continually drove it 25, 30, 40 yards farther.
He tried to talk Hogan into switching to the type of ball he was
hitting, a Dunlop 65 with 100 compression, but Hogan would have
none of it.
</P>
<P>
   ``He stuck to his Acushnet, 90 compression. Hogan said, `Frank,
I want my ball to stay on the green.' If you knew Hogan, you knew
he never changed his mind, never deviated from his plan.''
</P>
<P>
   The trip to Scotland was made in late June to give Hogan a few
weeks to get used to the climate, the time zone, and, of course,
the golf course. It is hard to imagine the Royal &AMP; Ancient or the
US Golf Association forcing Tiger Woods to go through a 36-hole
qualifier, but that is how the opens were conducted back then. Thus
the great Ben Hogan, just a few weeks removed from his fourth US
Open championship in six years and a few months after winning the
Masters for the second time in three years, was treated no
differently from, say, Hassan Hassenein of Egypt. If Hogan wanted a
chance at history, if he wanted to become the first player since
the advent of the Masters in 1934 to win three majors in a season,
if he wanted to prove himself _ as Hagen and Armour had insisted he
do _ one of the game's greatest, then he had to do it the hard way.
</P>
<P>
   A daunting challenge, no doubt, but then again, this was a man
who had escaped death in an awful crash four years earlier. Doctors
had said he would never walk again. Then they said he would never
play golf again. Now they were saying his battered legs would not
be up to the challenge of Carnoustie.
</P>
<P>
   As usual, people underestimated Hogan's will, said Ken Venturi.
``He prepared for that tournament. He felt it was the best time for
him to play the British Open.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MORE &LR;  &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
