<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-15 13:34 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1240 &Cx1f; tth-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BAD-WRITING-SPI &LR;      07-15 0700
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BAD-WRITING-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SEATTLE LAWYER WINS PRIZE FOR HIS PUTRID PROSE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By MIKE BARBER  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ David Hirsch must be a pretty good lawyer _ he
murdered the King's English and got away with it.
</P>
<P>
   The 15-year veteran of the Seattle public defender's office
Tuesday won the Purple Prose award of the coveted and dubious 18th
International Bulwer-Lytton Fiction contest for bad writing. It is
named for the Victorian author who penned the immortal words: ``It
was a dark and stormy night.''
</P>
<P>
   ``There are so many ways of writing badly and I try to cover
them all,'' said Hirsch, speaking with tongue pressed firmly in
cheek. ``I submitted 15 entries; I'm disappointed the other 14
didn't win. But it's made my day, at least marginally.''
</P>
<P>
   Hirsch's Purple Prose award would make a weathercaster weep,
with its projectile vomiting metaphors about the local climate at
its winter worst, said Scott Rice, an English professor at San Jose
State University, where the Bulwer-Lytton Awards were selected from
thousands of paragraphs written worldwide.
</P>
<P>
   It's not exactly ``Purple Rain,'' but Hirsch's prose was
inspired by the same stuff:
</P>
<P>
   ``Rain _ violent torrents of it, rain like fetid water from a
God-sized pot of pasta strained through a sky-wide colander, rain
as Noah knew it, flaying the shuddering trees, whipping the
whitecapped waters, violating the sodden firmament, purging purity
and filth alike from the land, rain without mercy, without
surcease, incontinent rain, turning to intermittent showers
overnight with partial clearing Tuesday.''
</P>
<P>
   Hirsch's paragraph outdistanced all others for the Purple Prose
Prize because, ``like his pasta, it was overdone,'' said Rice.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is an example of metaphors run amok and not knowing when to
quit. The whole range was ludicrous _ shattering, whipping,
violating, purging,'' Rice said, in painful admiration.
</P>
<P>
   Hirsch counts among his artistic experiences membership in the
defunct ``Mazeltones'' band _ ``we played hundreds of weddings.''
</P>
<P>
   But Rice believes Hirsch's legal experience provided him with
the best tools:
</P>
<P>
   ``He's been finding a way of justifying the unjustifiable and
speaking about the unspeakable for a long time,'' the professor
quipped.
</P>
<P>
   Hirsch was outdone only by the Grand Prize winner, Dr. David
Chuter, a 47-year-old government official from London, who became
the first non-American in years to win the perverse competition.
</P>
<P>
   Chuter, who describes himself as ``a rather harmless and obscure
bureaucrat trying to serve the public interest,'' wrote:
</P>
<P>
   ``Through the gathering gloom of a late-October afternoon, along
the greasy, cracked paving-stones slick from the sputum of the sky,
Stanley Ruddlethorp wearily trudged up the hill from the cemetery
where his wife, sister, brother, and three children were all
buried, and forced open the door of his decaying house, blissfully
unaware of the catastrophe that was soon to devastate his life.''
</P>
<P>
   Rice said the awards were conceived both to encourage
unpublished authors who do not have the time to write books, and to
honor the memory of the Victorian novelist Edward George Earl
Bulwer-Lytton.
</P>
<P>
   Bulwer-Lytton's 1830 novel, ``Paul Clifford,'' opened with the
words now timeless and synonymous with wretched writing.
</P>
<P>
   Taking time out to be serious, Rice said it's really encouraging
to see people from all walks of life go to such lengths to be
creatively bad.
</P>
<P>
   ``English teachers are always bemoaning the state of literacy,
but here are people from all walks of life who love to have fun
with words,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   For his efforts, Chuter gets what all winners have gotten, ``a
pittance,'' Rice said.
</P>
<P>
   Hirsch gets less. ``Hey, he'll be a household name, he'll have
groupies, he'll be the envy of his literate friends. Isn't that
enough?'' Rice pleaded.
</P>
<P>
   Asked how he might celebrate the insult and honor with friends
or family, Hirsch said ``leave my family out of this. They're
respectable people.''
</P>
<P>
   And he's already plotting another assault on the language.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm working up to the pittance. Maybe in a few years ... ''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
