NYT-07-15-99 1335EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990715.0145 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-15 13:35 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1242 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CHILDCARE-COLUMN-2ND &LR;      07-15 1091
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHILDCARE-COLUMN-2ND </SLUG>
   TAKE-BOS  
 UNDATED: ... she says.  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   If a TV-14 is accompanied by V, S, L and/or D, expect it to be
very intense, warns Eisenstock, who lectures nationally on the
effects of media on children.
</P>
<P>
   FV is also a problem. Since it stands for ``fantasy violence,''
many parents incorrectly assume it means cartoon violence. Not so.
What it means is that some children may not be able to recognize
that the violence in the show is make-believe.
</P>
<P>
   Secondly, FV is only added to TV-Y7, not to the more general
TV-Y label. That doesn't mean that there won't be mild violence in
TV-Y shows, however. ``Roadrunner,'' for instance, a cartoon,
contains isolated, animated violence but it's rated TV-Y. ``You
can't automatically assume TV-Y is free of violence,'' warns
Eisenstock.
</P>
<P>
   But there are several assumptions you can make when you see
TV-Y7-FV, Montgomery says: ``Violence is central to these shows,
it's presented in an exciting and realistic way, heroes are
justified and valued for their acts of violence, and the
consequences of the violence aren't shown.''
</P>
<P>
   The danger to children under 7 who watch FV programming is well
documented: ``Not only do they imitate the violence and accept it
as an appropriate way to solve conflict, but their tolerance of
aggression gets lower and lower until they accept it as normal,''
says Montgomery. ``When a kid tells you the violence in a
particular show is `no big deal,' that's what's happened.''
</P>
<P>
   --News, commercials, and sports shows are not rated at all.
Because of their inability to tell the difference between what's
real and what's not, preschoolers can be frightened by the news and
even by some sports programming. Commercials can be a problem not
just for inappropriate content but also because they makes young
children vulnerable to sales pitches. ``My 6-year-old only watches
public TV for just that reason,'' says Montgomery.
</P>
<P>
   Here's where the V-chip comes in. Some of the new TVs have an
option that allows blocking of any unrated program.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's a real child-proof cap for the TV,'' says Cantor. She
would be quick to use this for a child who worries about his or her
personal safety or frequently has nightmares.
</P>
<P>
   Normally, the V-chip blocks the level you program it for and
anything higher: If you block TV-PG, you also automatically block
TV-14 and TV-MA. Knowing what you need to block depends on your
child's age, stage of development, gender, emotional maturity, and
ability to separate fantasy from reality. ``If you have a
4-year-old who's getting into trouble on the playground and he's
fascinated by violence on TV, you may want to block anything that's
not TV-Y,'' says Eisenstock.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   VIDEO AND COMPUTER GAMES
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The system:
</P>
<P>
   There are two ratings systems. The Recreational Software
Advisory Council rates on a scale of 1 to 4, for instance: V1,
little or no killing of humans, V4, a lot of killing of humans; S1,
little or no sexual touching or degree of undress, S4, lots of
sexual touching and nudity. The Entertainment Software Rating Board
gives an age demarcation: EC: early childhood; E: for everyone
(older games may be labeled KA, which means ``from Kid to Adult'');
T: teen, 13 and older; M: 17 and older; AO: adults only.
</P>
<P>
   What to be aware of:
</P>
<P>
   --The age ratings give you no clue about content.
</P>
<P>
   --Except for AO, video stores tend not to pay attention to
ratings when children are renting.
</P>
<P>
   --Just because it's a sports game doesn't mean there isn't
violence. Cantor tells of buying her son an NFL video game where
every play ended with players being smashed to the ground and the
commentator gleefully declaring: ``A crushing tackle!'' ``It was
violence, all right,'' she says.
</P>
<P>
   --Violence, sex, etc., tend to escalate at higher levels of each
game. ``Video games at the early levels are pretty benign, but they
get more and more vicious as they go up in level,'' says Cantor.
Her advice: ``Don't just look at a game once and decide it's OK;
have the computer, Nintendo, etc. in a public space in the house,
where you can see what's going on without seeming to be a snoop.
Rent video games before you buy them.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   COMPACT DISCS
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The system:
</P>
<P>
   A CD may contain a ``Parental Advisory'' label, meaning it
contains lyrics that raters consider crude or otherwise offensive.
</P>
<P>
   What to be aware of:
</P>
<P>
   Unless you purchase the CD (or shop in a store where you can
listen before you buy), there's no way to know whether the
offensive lyrics are four-letter words your child hears on the
playground or racist slurs.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(AFTERTHOUGHT _ Recommended: ``Children and Safe Computing: Keep
Your Child RSI-Free'' by Maureen Clancy (Upright Press, 1999,
$9.95), available by calling 1(800)537-1560 or emailing,
upright(at)hamptons.com)
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
TIPS FOR PARENTS  &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   --The V-chip provides built-in opportunities for teaching media
literacy. Use it to talk to your 3- and 4-year-old about why there
are only certain shows she can watch: ``Not everything on
television is good for kids. The V-chip is a way our family keeps
you safe. TV-Y shows are the ones for you.''
</P>
<P>
   --With older children who have had viewing freedom, it's
important not to suddenly become absolute about programming. Even
if you get a set with a V-chip, it doesn't mean you can't override
it: ``There may be some things that are blocked that you want to
see, and we can decide about that together.''
</P>
<P>
   --When you use the V-chip, if you block by content, for instance
TV-PG-V, you will still receive shows with TV-PG-L/S/D, unless you
also block those designations. It's also possible to block
programming for a specific time and channel.
</P>
<P>
   --By January, all new sets will be equipped with V-chips. For
older sets, you can buy a V-chip set-top box.
</P>
<P>
   --For more information on V-chips and ratings, visit the Center
for Media Education Web site, http://www.vchipeducation.org, or
order their free booklet, ``A Parent's Guide to the TV Ratings and
V-Chip'' by calling toll free, 877-282-4478.
</P>
<P>
   --Ratings for TV are voluntary. If you don't agree with them,
write to TV Parental Guidelines Monitoring Board, Box 14097,
Washington, DC 20004.
</P>
<P>
   --For information on Moms Offended by the Media, write to MOM at
Box 402, Southampton, MA 01073.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Barbara F. Meltz's first book, ``Put Yourself in Their Shoes:
Understanding How Your Children See the World'' (Dell), is
available in bookstores. She welcomes letters and comments and can
be reached via e-mail at meltz(at)globe.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
