<HEADLINE>
PROFITABLE POLAROID'S STOCK SINKS, DESPITE COMEBACK 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RONALD ROSENBERG  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Thanks to PopShots, Wall Street is taking fewer pot shots at
Polaroid Corp.
</P>
<P>
   PopShots is the Cambridge, Mass. company's new single-use
disposable instant picture camera that reached the mass market in
February and is largely responsible for the company's first
quarter-to-quarter increase in revenue in three years.
</P>
<P>
   Strong sales of its ``Barbie'' camera, a dressed-up version of
the aging OneStep model, and increased sales of new products in
Japan, pushed Polaroid back to profitability for the first time in
nine months.
</P>
<P>
   But the strong financial results did not stop a sharp drop in
Polaroid's stock price, as the firm warned that in the second half
of the year earnings will be below initial projections because of
anticipated fluctuations in foreign currency markets and further
declines in some of its smaller, noncore businesses.
</P>
<P>
   The forecast sent Polaroid shares into a tailspin Wednesday,
with the stock closing at 23 3/4, down 5 _ the steepest one-day
drop this year and almost half of the gain the company has made
since hitting a 52-week low of 17 1/16 in late January.
</P>
<P>
   The decline is ``a big chunk for Polaroid, but keep in mind that
the noncore stuff has little bearing on the long-term viability of
the company and the dollar fluctuations are beyond the company's
control,'' said B. Alex Henderson, an analyst with Prudential
Securities.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the reversal in Polaroid's results is the first clear
sign that the strategy put in place by chairman Gary T. DiCamillo
when he took over the Cambridge-based company in 1995 _ churning
out dozens of new consumer products _ is working.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are continuing Polaroid's turnaround and the second quarter
profitability was as we expected,'' said DiCamillo, who in the past
three years has cut 3,000 jobs from the 62-year-old company.
Polaroid, the world's biggest instant-photography company, employs
about 9,000 people.
</P>
<P>
   But DiCamillo warned the strong dollar and changes in noncore
businesses such as sunglasses, polarizers, holography, and graphic
arts products would affect third-quarter profits. DiCamillo hopes
to sell off the noncore lines by the end of the year to concentrate
on instant and digital photography.
</P>
<P>
   Henderson said the company's second-quarter results were
``pretty good with solid revenues,'' as new products were ramped up
on schedule. ``But the company is not out of the woods yet,'' he
added.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, there is growing concern that Polaroid's instant film
sales _ the company's main profit center _ are declining in the
markets such as residential real estate and insurance claims
because of digital technology. Filmless digital cameras can capture
images, such as pictures of homes, and save them on personal
computers where the images can be stored, put on the Internet, sent
as electronic mail, and later printed.
</P>
<P>
   Polaroid also reported a second-quarter decline in European
camera and film sales, in
</P>
<P>
   part because some of the newer products that are available in
Japan are just arriving in selected markets.
</P>
<P>
   And while Polaroid will launch two new cameras _ the I-Zone
Instant Pocket Camera and JoyCam, each priced at $24.99 _ in
August, the new film for the Pocket Camera may be in short supply,
DiCamillo told Wall Street analysts.
</P>
<P>
   ``We will not have enough to meet demand,'' in the second half,
DiCamillo warned.
</P>
<P>
   He said the company is building capacity for the new instant
film, which will produce images about the size of postage stamps.
Polaroid is producing the new, smaller film in Mexico for the
Japanese market and is just beginning to expand production in
Waltham.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is increased evidence that DiCamillo's new-product
strategy is working, but we will not know for sure how well until
the end of the year,'' said Ulysses A. Yannas, a longtime Polaroid
watcher at Mercer, Bokert, Buckman &AMP; Reid in New York.
</P>
<P>
   Yannas and others noted Polaroid is making hefty bets on its
pocket camera, which has proven very popular in Japan, where it has
been available for 15 months. He said the firm expects its new
cameras to appeal to US preteens, teenagers, and young adults, many
of whom are new to instant photography.
</P>
<P>
   The new products, which accounted for about $70 million of
Polaroid's revenue in the first half of the year, should rise to
nearly $140 million in the second half, Yannas said. In 2000, the
company's new camera and film products should jump to about $365
million and reach $500 million in 2001, he added.
</P>
<P>
   DiCamillo has said the company is ``on track to deliver
profitable growth in 1999.''
</P>
<P>
   Polaroid reported second-quarter earnings of $14.8 million, or
33 cents per diluted share, compared with $1.34 million, or 3 cents
a share, last year. Worldwide revenue for the quarter ended June 30
rose 5 percent to $487 million, compared with $465 million in the
year-earlier period. US sales accounted for $267 million in
revenue, an increase of 9 percent over the same period in 1998. But
European sales slipped to $107 million from $117 million.
</P>
</TEXT>
