<SLUG> BC-ONBUSINESS-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PRICES FALLING ON TERM LIFE INSURANCE POLICIES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVEN SYRE AND CHARLES STEIN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   For a product that doesn't run on computer chips, term life
insurance keeps getting cheaper at a remarkable pace.
</P>
<P>
   The price of the plain vanilla policies most of us buy has
fallen 60 percent since the beginning of the decade and nearly 20
percent in the past two years, according to published data.
</P>
<P>
   And there's a chance that, between now and the end of the year,
prices may ratchet down again. ``We could see a two-minute drill,''
says Robert Sheridan, president of Savings Bank Life Insurance, a
Woburn, Mass. company and the state's leading writer of term
policies.
</P>
<P>
   Term policies provide insurance for a set period of time,
without the savings and investment features common in other types
of life insurance.
</P>
<P>
   The trigger for this latest round of price cuts, ironically, is
a new government regulation that may raise prices starting next
year. The rule, known as XXX (called Triple X), would require
insurers to boost the reserves they must keep on hand to write term
policies.
</P>
<P>
   As the length of those policies has increased _ some insurers
guarantee flat rates for 30 years _ so have the fears of
regulators. They worry the companies are making promises they won't
be able to honor. Raising the reserve requirement will provide an
extra margin of safety for consumers, according to the National
Association of Insurance Commissioners.
</P>
<P>
   The group endorsed the new rules at its spring meeting and most
states are expected to adopt the regulations, possibly as early as
next January. Massachusetts has yet to take any action on the
measure.
</P>
<P>
   While there is considerable dispute about how much impact XXX
will have, there is an emerging consensus that prices will go up at
least a little and that some of the best deals may disappear.
Industry experts say insurers are likely to use the approaching
deadline as a way to drum up business with the message: Buy now
while the getting is good.
</P>
<P>
   ``You'll see companies try to leapfrog one another with price
cuts,'' predicts James Van Elsen, an industry consultant based in
Iowa. Massachusetts Mutual of Springfield recently announced a cut
in its rates. Savings Bank Life ``is seriously considering'' a cut,
says Sheridan.
</P>
<P>
   For the industry, rate cuts have been the rule, not the
exception, in this decade. ``Rates have gone in only one direction,
down,'' says Milton Brown, who runs Insurance Information Inc., a
Cape Cod firm that compares prices for consumers on term insurance
policies.
</P>
<P>
   In 1991, a healthy 35-year-old man could buy a 20-year, $250,000
term policy for $447.50 a year. Today that same man could get a
policy for as little as $165, says Brown, who tracks prices for 600
different companies.
</P>
<P>
   The fact that we are living longer has a lot to do with the
falling prices, say industry executives. The logic is pretty basic:
The fewer people who die, the less insurers have to pay out in
death benefits.
</P>
<P>
   Increased competition has helped too. Everyone and his brother
sells term insurance today. The rise of the Internet as a shopping
tool has heightened the competition by allowing consumers to make
simple comparisons among policies.
</P>
<P>
   Finally there is one thing the industry doesn't brag about much:
better underwriting. Using blood tests, medical records, and
questionnaires, insurers have become more skilled at separating the
good risks from the bad. Anything from high blood pressure to a
fondness for sky diving can make a consumer ineligible for the
rock-bottom rates that typically are advertised.
</P>
<P>
   ``Will cheap term insurance still be available next year?'' asks
Van Elsen, the consultant. The answer, he says, is yes. But he
expects prices to rise somewhat and he thinks some companies that
now guarantee rates for 20 years, may shorten those guarantees to
five or 10 years.
</P>
<P>
   Kiplinger's Personal Finance Magazine recently quoted an
insurance specialist who predicted rates could rise 10 percent to
40 percent, a range others consider too large.
</P>
<P>
   So should consumers run out and buy policies now to beat the
possible price hikes?
</P>
<P>
   The answer from experts is: maybe. They say that no one should
buy life insurance unless they need it and that the world after XXX
is not likely to be radically different from the world today.
</P>
<P>
   But for consumers who are in the market already, the next few
months may bring some very attractive deals, according to industry
watchers. Says Milton Brown, ``If you need it, this could be a very
good time to buy.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Steven Syre and Charles Stein can be reached by e-mail at
boscap(at)globe.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
