<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WELTNER-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A SAD WAY TO LEARN ABOUT SIDE EFFECTS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By LINDA WELTNER  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   I &UR;  &LR; was watering the new plants in front of the house at dusk,
standing in the deserted street with no company but myself.
</P>
<P>
   My thoughts were unusually dark.
</P>
<P>
   My granddaughter, Jessie, 8, had been rude to me. Having lost an
argument with me the day before, she'd flounced off without saying
goodbye. I felt defeated and unappreciated, as if our unhappy
parting revealed that as far as both my grandkids were concerned,
my only purpose was to indulge them. All the love I'd given them
was pointless in the light of this stunning revelation. I hadn't
built a lasting or reliable relationship with them. I saw that now.
Cross them once and I was off their list.
</P>
<P>
   I was feeling bad, too, that I'd let down my youngest daughter.
No need to go into detail here. In fact, the problem is that I'm
too willing to share information Julie considers no one's business
but her own. As a teenager, she'd once asked, ``Mom, why does
everything I say to you go in one ear and out your mouth?'' I
carefully check out the content of this column, but obviously I
still haven't learned when to keep my mouth shut with friends. She
was right to be angry at me. I was angry at me too. It seemed to me
that the best gift I could give her was to stay away forever.
</P>
<P>
   I was missing her already.
</P>
<P>
   The watering seemed endless, but even if I spent my whole life
watering, I wouldn't miss anything. My relationship with my husband
was nonexistent. He'd had meetings for the last three nights and
hadn't been home for dinner. As the shadows deepened, I felt
terribly lonely, but it was good preparation, I thought, for being
a widow. Jack was destined to die all too soon so I might as well
practice being alone all day and all night. It seemed to me that
once I got used to being estranged from everyone, the total
bleakness of my future wouldn't come as such a shock.
</P>
<P>
   I poured water onto another plant, too sad to cry.
</P>
<P>
   A tiny light flickered in the darkness of my mind like a distant
neon sign: (italsOIt's a bit unusual for you to feel hopelessly and
permanently alienated from everyone you love.(unitals) I've managed
to weather a lifetime of disagreements, a checkered career of
thoughtlessness, and a marriage full of temporary absences. Why did
everything seem so overwhelming now? What had changed?
</P>
<P>
   The answer was my brain chemistry. I was on a new medication.
</P>
<P>
   For the last six weeks, I've been waking up every morning with a
headache. I have pills that cure my migraines once they've started,
but they're to be used sparingly, so I recently went to a
specialist to see if I could prevent them. Several years ago, I
gave up on a drug that left me so devoid of energy that I could
barely get through the day, but I was now trying out another. I'd
been terribly tired and had recently noticed a molasseslike
consistency to my thinking, but I hadn't decided whether these side
effects were reason enough to quit or not.
</P>
<P>
   Now I wondered if the drug had triggered my depressive feelings.
They certainly felt like genuine emotions. It goes against the
grain of my common sense to think of them as chemically caused.
What's so shocking in retrospect is how totally justified they
seemed at the time, such a perfectly appropriate response to actual
events.
</P>
<P>
   That is, until I stopped taking the drug and returned to normal.
In two days, not only did my energy return, but I was sane again.
Jessie was a sweetie who occasionally lost her temper, Julie was
capable of forgiveness, and Jack, home for dinner, no longer had
one foot in the grave.
</P>
<P>
   I never realized how powerful, and dangerous, many commonly
prescribed medications are. If I hadn't made the connection, it
wouldn't have taken long for my personal life to have become a
shambles, perhaps irretrievably so, with no one the wiser as to why
I'd gone off the deep end. None of the information I received from
the pharmacy mentioned depression. I hadn't planned to report the
details to my doctor, but when I called one of the authors of
``Worse Pills, Good Pills: A Consumer's Guide to Avoiding
Drug-Induced Death or Illness,'' written by Public Citizen's Health
Research Group, Larry Sasich suggested I report my adverse effects
to my physician. Depression, it turns out, has been linked with
this medication. Given that this drug had been tested on fewer than
5,000 people, patient feedback is the primary source of knowledge
about side effects.
</P>
<P>
   Thank goodness I didn't learn this lesson the hard way.
</P>
<P>
   I'll never be this naive again.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Health Research Group was cofounded by Ralph Nader to give
consumers more control over their health. For more information,
visit their Web site at http://www.citizen.org/hrg/ or call
202-588-1000.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Linda Weltner's Web site is http://www.shore.net/weltner)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
