<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-15 13:40 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1250 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GARDEN-VERTICAL-BOS &LR;      07-15 0951
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GARDEN-VERTICAL-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VERTICAL GARDENING DISGUISES EYESORES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVE HATCH  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   I've been interested in growing up (we're talking gardening, not
personal maturity) for almost 15 years, ever since we had that row
house in Philadelphia with a gorgeous stone facade on the steps
leading up to the front door. It cried for a vine.
</P>
<P>
   We considered ivies, Boston especially, but finally chose
trumpet vine, Campsis radicans. It grew, attaching to the stone and
mortar, but never flourished, being in too much shade. We returned
to New England before it had a chance to fully adjust.
</P>
<P>
   Here we have no appropriate places to grow trumpet vine (I don't
want it attached to our shingled house or the wooden shed), but we
do grow climbers. I'd like to say we got into climbing plants out
of a deep sense of design, mixing vertical elements in brilliant
and subtle ways to heighten the experience of our gardens.
</P>
<P>
   But it was the chain-link fence that got us going. That would be
the chain-link fence we had to install immediately upon moving to
Marshfield because we had a small pool, and the insurance company
(not to mention the law) insisted on the fence. It marred our back
view. It had to be covered, disguised.
</P>
<P>
   I've been covering it ever since. For annuals, we have used
sweet peas, which I think have the best scent on this planet,
hyacinth beans (Dolichos lablab) for white and purple flowers and
purple beans, and scarlet runner beans (Phaseolus coccineus) for
their scarlet flowers followed by edible beans (not the best, but
the big dog likes them).
</P>
<P>
   We have two roses out there, a pink miniature that has yet to
take off and a Zephirine Drouhin that, despite the drought and
because of extensive watering by me, has decided to flower after
all. There is a hardy kiwi (Actinidia kolomitka), which has mottled
pink, white and green leaves, and two euonymus (Euonymus fortunei
`Emerald Surprise') have grabbed hold, hauled themselves up, and
are going hand-over-hand along the fence top.
</P>
<P>
   Two purple Clematis jackmanii flank the kiwi. One has finished
flowering, its large buds opening to equally large flowers, and the
other is about to, with much smaller buds opening to smaller
flowers (this leads me to believe it is another, mislabeled
cultivar, but I don't care).
</P>
<P>
   Naturally, all this has led to other climbers, and we grow two
other climbing roses, a deep red mystery heirloom that came with
the house and a pinkish hybrid. We also have a honeysuckle
(Lonicera X brownii `Dropmore Scarlet'), whose orange flowers have
scarlet throats and some gold-tinged ivy headed up an oak. There's
also poison ivy and American bittersweet, two undesirables we mean
to deal with some day.
</P>
<P>
   And then there are more clematis. The clematis we have failed at
include `Henryi,' `Ernest Markham,' and `Ville de Lyon,' but this
is because of the hellish site we chose. A deep red `Niobe' is
adjusting, after three years, to the turkey-wire-covered wood fence
post it grows on by the pool, and a tangutica, a small-flowered
species with yellow flowers, is being encouraged near a spirea.
</P>
<P>
   Our best is sweet autumn clematis (Clematis maximowicziana),
which covers the front lamp post and has scrambled into an adjacent
ornamental plum tree, where its green leaves stand out like a cool
stream of green amid the plum's purple leaves. In September, we'll
have showers of small, slightly fragrant white flowers. I love it.
</P>
<P>
   In truth, I love clematis, and I am determined to grow more and
find better ways to do it, too.
</P>
<P>
   Susan Austin, owner of Completely Clematis Specialty Nursery in
Ipswich, Mass., is a fount of information, being an aficionado as
well as a grower.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, they have a reputation for being finicky. ``They do because
of the clematis wilt, which affects the large-flowered hybrids.''
So, either deal with the wilt, which generally doesn't kill the
plant, though it does rob you of your show, or grow wilt-resistant
small-flowered varieties.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think they're terribly easy to grow, and they don't get the
wilt,'' Austin said of the small-flowered clematis. Their foliage
is more attractive, and the seed heads are quite extraordinary,
extending the season of interest. They can be quite fragrant, and
they don't require use of wilt-combating fungicides.
</P>
<P>
   The notion that clematis must have cool roots, while the tops
like the sun, is false, she said. They do like a good, fertile root
run, and Austin recommends planting the crowns 4 inches below the
surface.
</P>
<P>
   Sun, not full sun, is a good idea, but according to Austin,
`Silver Moon,' a whitish large-flowered cultivar, would grow in a
closet and certainly can light up a shady corner.
</P>
<P>
   And they don't all have to go up. ``Some varieties of clematis
make great ground covers,'' she said. C. heracleifolia `Mrs. Robert
Brydon' has masses of small lavender flowers and ``covers every
speck of open space,'' Austin said. The integrifolias, sprawly
nonclimbers, can be ground covers and can make nice border plants.
</P>
<P>
   Her nursery sells more than 135 kinds, including bicolors and
double-flowered cultivars. There are exotics as well as the
standbys, including the vigorous montana group, which can ramble on
for 30 feet and look stunning up trees.
</P>
<P>
   That ability to mix benevolently with neighbors adds to the
versatility of clematis.
</P>
<P>
   ``Just for fun I always plant annual vines, and sometimes I mix
them with clematis,'' Austin said. ``Things like canary creeper (a
yellow-flowered nasturtium cousin). When you have a young clematis,
they look very good. It gives it some fullness.''
</P>
<P>
   Now that's a lovely idea.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-15-99 1340EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990715.0150 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-15 13:42 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1252 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-AUTO-REVIEW-BOS &LR;      07-15 1277
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AUTO-REVIEW-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PORSCHE CARRERA 4 UNDERSTATED _ UNTIL YOU FIRE IT UP 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (l and f coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ROYAL FORD  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Dear Mr. Porsche:
</P>
<P>
   I'm sorry about what happened to your car (but more on that
later).
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, thank you for letting me drive your 911 Carrera
4. I have never driven anything quite like it. It is fast _ wicked
fast and wicked quick _ it is smooth, and it seems the only way you
can lose control of this car is to make a deliberate and crazy
attempt to do so (but more on that later).
</P>
<P>
   It is hard to believe that the car whose prototype you built 51
years ago _ remember those military parts and the leftover
Volkswagen Kubelwagens that went into the 356? _ has evolved into
this quietly elegant but roaring piece of machinery.
</P>
<P>
   In some ways, it looks so benign from the outside. No bulging
fenders-on-steroids. No gaping air intake ports. Just the smooth
lines of a gently rounded wedge. Even the Carrera 4 tag on the back
probably means little to those who don't already know that this is
an all-wheel-drive car.
</P>
<P>
   Inside, the first thing you notice is the dash: so simple, but
again, so elegant. The main gauges wrapped in a soft, stitched,
leather wedge shaped much like the car itself. And I love the way
you took all those gauges and scalloped them one behind the other
from the center out.
</P>
<P>
   There in the middle, as befits a true performance car, is not
the speedometer but the tachometer. At the bottom of this same full
circle is a digital speed readout and the trip computer that tells
you outside temperature, how far you can go before you run out of
gas, what your gas mileage has been, and, if you set it, will warn
you when you exceed your chosen speed limit. To the left, the
semicircles step away as analog speedometer, voltmeter, and
odometer. To the right are the shift indicator (for both the manual
and automatic options) and oil and fuel gauges.
</P>
<P>
   On stems behind the steering wheel are controls for the trip
computer, windshield and headlight washers, cruise controls,
wipers, and light beams. All so simple and so functional.
</P>
<P>
   And so are the climate controls and sound system centered on the
dash. Love the way the display face on the sound system pops open
to reveal a CD slot behind it, and love the CD stacker built into
the dash below.
</P>
<P>
   The leather seats are firm and comfortable, though again, they
are so simple in design they are understated. No bulging sides to
hold the outer thighs; no raised lip at the front for support; seat
flowing continuously into headrest. It all works.
</P>
<P>
   The rear seats, well, there's not much headroom back there, so
four adults on a long trip would be problematic _ but of course
that's not why you buy a car like this. Just as you don't buy it
expecting lots of storage space.
</P>
<P>
   No glove box. Bins with lids set in each door at armrest height,
small slots at the bottoms of the doors, a tiny covered box in the
center console. The trunk up front is a small box, as well _ no
golf clubs or large suitcases up here, though folding down the rear
seats would set two people up nicely for a trip.
</P>
<P>
   So simple, so understated. Until you fire it up and get that
distinctive sound from its twin pipes and look out the windshield
and down the hood, where the front fenders seem to be heading
toward a wedge, a tipped ``V'' that says, ``Point me somewhere and
step on it.''
</P>
<P>
   Step on 296 horsepower, cranking 258 lbs./ft. of torque from a
flat 6 aluminum block, aluminum head engine, and the V seems to
shrink before your eyes; becomes the point of an arrow, or the
sharp, guiding cursor in a video game.
</P>
<P>
   And driving this car _ shifting up and down with both thumbs
using the Triptonic manual shift buttons built into the steering
wheel _ is like being in a video game. Except, as Jake the Snake,
my 9-year-old guide in things electronic, pointed out to me, ``When
you mess up with this, you can't press the reset button.''
</P>
<P>
   Other select-shift transmissions I've driven have still had at
least some ``automatic'' feel to them, a certain lag after each
shift, even when set on manual. Not this one.
</P>
<P>
   Crank through the gears from first to third (0-60 in five
seconds) and each step is smooth but noticeable as you flash
through them. Downshift from fifth to fourth at high speed and give
it gas and you get a race car rumble from the twin exhausts as you
bolt forward. Playing with the car in a heavy way, I got just under
18 miles per gallon in a week of driving.
</P>
<P>
   It's a stiff ride, as it ought to be, and the handling is
impeccable. And for some, that is a problem.
</P>
<P>
   A problem because this Porsche is equipped with what is called
Porsche Stability Management. That means it is as smart as some
airplanes, and some folks don't want their cars helping them out
when it comes to on-the-edge driving.
</P>
<P>
   This new Porsche has sensors that monitor the steering wheel,
yaw of the car, wheels, brake pedal, clutch and gears and throttle
position. Viscous couplers feed torque to nonslipping wheels from
slipping wheels. The sensors can brake individual wheels to regain
stability or alter engine power to recapture control.
</P>
<P>
   In other words, to get this car to oversteer or understeer so
severely you lose control, you have to do something seriously _
perhaps intentionally _ wrong. I tried it. Set the rear wheels on
sand as I entered a 90-degree turn. Goosed the gas. Felt the rear
try to kick out and send me into the World of the Incredible
Shrinking Radius Turn. Couldn't do it. The front wheels grabbed,
pulled the car ahead, and said, ``Oh no you don't.''
</P>
<P>
   So I switched off the PSM (for those moments when you want to
induce terror) and tried the same thing. Nice fishtail, wonderful
understeer. Oh yes, I do. But though I corrected easily, I could
tell that this car, without the computer- assisted stability, could
be dangerous in the wrong hands.
</P>
<P>
   The speedometer goes to 175 miles per hour and though I didn't
take it there, I could tell in short bursts that it would eat up
most of that gauge. The brakes _ 12.5-inch vented discs up front,
11.8-inch vented discs in the rear _ coupled with antilock control,
brought the car to sudden, straight stops from high speeds.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, Mr. Porsche, you have built a beautifully understated,
rip-roaring beast of a car. A car I would love to own.
</P>
<P>
   Now, back to that problem, and I hope you will understand. I
can't find your car. I still have the keys, but it just disappeared
one day when I wasn't looking. Somebody probably hid it in a garage
or an old mine up in New Hampshire where I live. But I figure
you've got lots more and, hey, what's one little Porsche to a guy
like you who has so many. If I do find it, I'll be in touch. And
again, thanks for letting me drive it.
</P>
<P>
   Nice Touches:
</P>
<P>
   --The lateral, telescoping movement of the steering wheel.
</P>
<P>
   --An air conditioning system that kept me chilled right through
the recent sweltering heat wave.
</P>
<P>
   --The easy-to-use trip computer.
</P>
<P>
   Annoyances:
</P>
<P>
   --The danger of speeding tickets. Leave your local post office,
give the car moderate gas, shift 1-2-3, and look down. You are now
doing 50 in a 30. Hello, officer!
</P>
<P>
   --I have to give the car back to Mr. Porsche _ if I ever find
it, that is.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   THE NUMBERS
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
