<HEADLINE>
GOING TOO FAR TO STOP STEALING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By HIAWATHA BRAY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Fans of Apple Computer Inc.'s Macintosh computers like to accuse
Microsoft Corp. of stealing the Mac's graphical user interface for
Microsoft's Windows software. Microsoft defenders respond that
Apple itself stole the idea from Xerox Corp.'s Alto computer.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, they're both right, and thank heaven for it.
Intellectual progress doesn't happen in a vacuum. Nearly every
``new idea'' is based on previous ideas that somebody appropriates
for his own ends.
</P>
<P>
   How many truly original ideas have we seen in computing lately?
The most recent that comes to mind is the spreadsheet, invented by
a couple of Bostonians 20 years ago. Of course the Xerox Alto of
1974 goes on the list. As does Paul Baran's 1964 Rand Corp. paper
in which he thought up packet switching _ the central technology of
the Internet. Most of the other breakthroughs were big or small
improvements on existing ideas. Soaking up information from others,
and then imparting a new spin to it, is about as creative as most
of us will ever get.
</P>
<P>
   Which is why quite a few creative types are up in arms over the
US Congress's latest adventure in intellectual property law. North
Carolina Republican Representative Howard Coble is pushing a bill
that would provide new protections for companies that create
databases of information. The bill, HR 354, would make it harder
for people to use collected data without paying for it. But the
bill's critics seem to regard it as the worst threat to the
nation's intellectual life since Jerry Springer got his own TV
show. And they may have a point.
</P>
<P>
   These days, databases are everywhere. There's your personal
address book, for instance, or a telephone directory, or the
complete computer columns of Hiawatha Bray. These are all
databases. Companies create them by the millions, and a growing
number are available on the Internet _ stock market data, for
instance. Obviously this information is valuable, and it costs
money to assemble it all. No surprise then that big companies like
Reed Elsevier Inc. _ owner of the Lexis-Nexis news and legal
database _ support HR 354, which will impose criminal penalties on
people who steal information.
</P>
<P>
   This sounds like justice. Thanks to computers and the Internet,
it's easy to copy somebody else's database and market it as your
own. Should I be able to go to a sports Web site, download reams of
statistics, then set up my own Web site to compete with the
original source? It hardly seems fair.
</P>
<P>
   But consider the flip side. Those sports scores may be in a
database compiled by someone else. But they're also historical
facts. Draw your database protection bill too broadly, and you
could end up making it illegal for historians to scoop up factual
data from the Net and use it in their next book.
</P>
<P>
   HR 354 prohibits the copying of ``substantial'' parts of a
database _ a fancy way of saying that a violation is whatever the
database owner says it is. Suppose a sports writer is working on a
book about the 1998 Chicago Bulls. Say he visits the National
Basketball Association Web site, collects the lifetime stats for
every member of the team, and includes this data in the book.
That's a pretty substantial chunk of information. Would the writer
have to pay the NBA to use it? Well . . . maybe. The courts would
have to decide.
</P>
<P>
   Now multiply that example by many thousands. Everybody from pulp
novelists to college profs use large and small chunks of other
people's data in their work. The expansive language of HR 354 will
have all these people breaking a sweat. Which is why an
extraordinary array of the nation's top universities are fighting
this proposal, along with the National Writers Union and the
American Library Association. Even Internet firms like Yahoo and
Lycos, which create their own databases and distribute others, say
HR 354 goes too far.
</P>
<P>
   Virginia Republican Tom Bliley has offered up a rival bill, HR
1858, which has been endorsed by many of the same groups that hate
354. The biggest difference is that 1858 simply bans copying of
entire databases in order to sell the stolen data. Supporters of
354 say the Bliley bill still leaves room for info-theft, and
they're right. But we need a few loopholes in our intellectual
property laws _ just enough to encourage the kind of larcenous
creativity that gave us Windows and the Macintosh.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(E-mail Hiawatha Bray at bray(at)globe.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
