</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WOMEN-MARRIAGE-ART-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOR MANY WOMEN, MARRIAGE NOT SO CRUCIAL ANY MORE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ART ADV.: A photo is being sent to NYTNS clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchases by calling 212-556-4204 or -1927.)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KAYCE T. ATAIYERO  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   At 15, Nikolai Loquez has already done a lot of thinking about
marriage.
</P>
<P>
   Sitting cross-legged on the floor at a Massachusetts shopping
mall, the teenager described her vision of the perfect marriage:
``He would be tall and handsome, and he would make good money and
we would live in a big house with a pool and have cute kids and he
would love me,'' she said, her excitement tangling her words as she
peered from underneath a white, wide-brimmed fisherman's hat.
</P>
<P>
   Her friend, 14-year-old Jacqueline Crowley agreed, adding that
love was most important ``because everyone wants someone who loves
them to grow old with. It's what life's about.''
</P>
<P>
   The two girls also agreed that the storybook romance most likely
would end in disappointment and divorce.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to be married to the same person forever but if you
look around, you see that just doesn't happen anymore,'' Loquez
said. ``That's why I am going to have my own money, house, car so
that I will be OK no matter what happens.''
</P>
<P>
   The girls' views echo the findings of a report, ``The State of
Our Unions,'' issued this month by Rutgers University's National
Marriage Project. According to the annual report, which tracks
social indicators of marital health and wellbeing, 70 percent of
graduating high school girls said it was possible to have a full
life without marriage, compared with 61 percent in 1980.
</P>
<P>
   Fifty-three percent of women said having a child without being
married is a worthwhile lifestyle, compared to 33 percent in 1980,
and about 36 percent of teenage girls said they believe their
future marriages are destined to be short-lived, compared to 32
percent in 1980, the report said.
</P>
<P>
   Even though this country's divorce rate is on the decline, the
country's annual marriage rate has dropped to just 49.7 per 1,000
women, the lowest since researchers started to measure it in 1960.
</P>
<P>
   One portion of the study singled out females, saying that while
young men were becoming slightly more optimistic about the prospect
that they will build a happy marriage, young women are losing
faith.
</P>
<P>
   ``These girls are being realistic,'' said David Popenoe,
codirector of the project. ``Some of them have never seen a good
marriage so they naturally plan for the day when theirs comes to
what they see as its inevitable end.''
</P>
<P>
   America's divorce culture has taught a generation that they must
first provide for themselves before they think of a partnership,
Popenoe said.
</P>
<P>
   Crowley said she wants to go to college and find a good job
before she marries in case she gets divorced and is left to fend
for herself.
</P>
<P>
   ``You want to think that things will be cool forever and you can
try to make it work, but it might not,'' she said. ``I don't want
to end up by myself, without any money, and not be able to take
care of myself.''
</P>
<P>
   Marriage is changing as society has moved beyond the day when a
woman was seen first as wife and mother, the study said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Fifty years ago, we were living in much more of a marriage
culture, highly centered around women marrying and marrying
young,'' Popenoe said. ``It was less desirable to be single and
interest in college and a career was not cultivated in young
women.''
</P>
<P>
   But Sharon Chirban, a Cambridge psychologist, said it can be
difficult for women to reconcile their desire to achieve in their
20s with their disinterest in being unmarried at 40.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think that it's tough for more educated women because though
they are progressive and want to be equal partners, they still
think of relationships in traditional ways and expect the man to be
in a better position,'' Chirban said. ``This expectation becomes
more difficult as women acquire and accomplish more.''
</P>
<P>
   Yolanda James, 24, a public relations coordinator, said she
feels torn between her desire to succeed and the pressure to be
married.
</P>
<P>
   ``People start looking at you when you are in your late 20s and
wonder why you aren't married when all of your friends are making
down payments on reception halls,'' said the Roxbury native. ``I
think if I'm not married by 35, it would bother me. It's tough
because the same people who say they are proud of what I have
accomplished then turn around and question my ringless finger.''
</P>
<P>
   James has spent the last six years of her life working toward
her professional goals, putting relationships on the back burner
until just the right time. Now that she is more focused on settling
down in a long-term relationship, she is growing concerned.
</P>
<P>
   ``I see a lot of successful women, older mentors of mine who
have everything but a man and I wonder if I can hope for a better
future for me,'' she said. ``In some ways, I think I am resigned to
it. People ask if I am scared that I will end up alone and I say,
`I got the job, got the house, got the car, what do I have to be
scared of?' ''
</P>
<P>
   Chirban said that while women no longer attach self-worth to
relationships, many still want the fulfillment a marriage can
provide.
</P>
<P>
   ``Women now primarily don't define themselves by marriages so if
they don't get married, it's not a crushing blow to their
self-esteem because they have developed their sense of worth in
other terms,'' she said. ``But for those who do want to get
married, the fact that it hasn't happened can be a huge loss.''
</P>
<P>
   Just as women have begun to claim a more equal position in
society, so they have come to demand more from their marriages than
their mothers did. They are more accomplished than before, and with
increased stature comes greater expectations for equality in their
relationships, and they are less willing to accept the brunt of
household work and rearing children, the study said.
</P>
<P>
   Julie McGovern expects her future marriage to be an equal
partnership. The 19-year-old Salem (Mass.) State College sophomore
said she has laid down the ground rules already with her boyfriend,
who she said she plans to marry after graduation.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to make sure that we are both on the same page and that
we plan to share equally in the responsibility,'' she said. ``We've
talked about finances and raising the kids because I am not
planning to have to do everything myself. He has to meet me
halfway.''
</P>
<P>
   Patty Hudson, a 27-year-old English teacher, said she was
starting to count herself among the disillusioned. She said she was
determined not to end up like her friends, either divorced or
sacrificing their goals to keep their marriages together.
</P>
<P>
   Hudson was in La Reine bridal shop in Brookline, just outside of
Boston, getting fitted for a gown for her Aug. 14 wedding, a day
she thought would never come.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a one-in-a-million thing,'' she said. ``Few women find a
man who is as giving and willing to compromise as I have. I look at
my parents, who have been married for 38 years, and I know how rare
and special that is. I think few women my age will experience
that.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
