<SLUG> BC-TV-MINORITY-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TV NETWORKS UNDER FIRE FOR DIVERSITY GAP 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DON AUCOIN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   By 1984, having been a household name for two decades, Bill
Cosby might reasonably have expected TV networks to embrace his
idea for a new sitcom about a middle-class black family.
</P>
<P>
   But even Cosby was not exempt from television's historic
reluctance to showcase black characters _ an attitude the NAACP
said this week is rearing its ugly head again as the networks
prepare to roll out an overwhelmingly white fall lineup.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Alvin F. Poussaint, a professor of psychiatry at Harvard
Medical School who was a script consultant on ``The Cosby Show,''
recalls that ``some of the networks shied away from it because they
didn't think it would appeal to the white audience.'' When it
became the most popular series of the decade, the same network
executives were ``stunned'' and ``confounded,'' leading Poussaint
to believe that ``the networks were behind the times in judging the
public mood.''
</P>
<P>
   With African-Americans virtually invisible in the two dozen new
dramas and sitcoms slated for the fall TV lineup on the four major
networks, Poussaint sees no reason to change his opinion.
</P>
<P>
   Even supporting roles in the new shows are scarce for black
actors, and Hispanics and Asian-Americans fare no better. But the
fall lineup only puts an exclamation point on a TV schedule that
was hardly the picture of diversity before.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, the NAACP decided it had had enough. NAACP president
Kweisi Mfume, noting that none of the new shows feature ``a
minority in a leading or starring role,'' lashed out at what he
called ``a virtual whitewash in programming'' on television. On
Monday Mfume blasted the fall lineup as ``an outrage and a shameful
display by network executives, who are either clueless, careless,
or both.'' He warned of possible legal action and a possible
boycott of both programs and advertisers.
</P>
<P>
   Mfume also demanded meetings with the heads of ABC, CBS, NBC,
and Fox _ meetings the networks are hastening to arrange. The
networks have released statements defending their overall records
on diversity in casting and programming but, in general, have
acknowledged shortcomings and vowed to do better. As a step in that
direction, several networks are recasting some shows with an eye
toward adding minority characters, though the chance is slim that
any of them will be leading roles.
</P>
<P>
   Even though boycotts have largely not worked for groups lobbying
against sex, violence, or other aspects of television programming
deemed objectionable, the networks appear to be taking the NAACP's
boycott threat seriously. ``Everybody feels they are very serious
about this, that they have the stamina to go the distance,'' said
one network executive who requested anonymity.
</P>
<P>
   Sheila Douglas, a spokeswoman for the NAACP, confirms that
assessment. Douglas said the NAACP's size _ 500,000 members, 1,700
branches _ enhances the chances for a successful boycott if the
organization goes that route. ``It is a top priority for us because
we feel very strongly about this issue,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Though the spotlight on diversity has now grown hotter, there
has been a steady decline in the percentage of ethnic minorities on
prime time since the beginning of this decade. Poor people, the
elderly, and rural residents are also a rare sight on TV, which
seems determined to wear a cosmopolitan, yuppified face in pursuit
of the viewers who flocked to ``Seinfeld'' and other
singles-in-Manhattan shows.
</P>
<P>
   ``Television has always been homogeneous, but it's become even
more homogeneous,'' remarked Steven Stark, author of ``Glued to the
Set.''
</P>
<P>
   Added Poussaint: ``They are sliding backwards. It doesn't make
sense in 1999 to believe you could get away with that, because
every year America becomes more and more diverse. They live in a
make-believe world.''
</P>
<P>
   The problem, according to George Gerbner, a professor of
telecommunications at Temple University in Philadelphia who
specializes in TV demographics, is that television's make-believe
world has destructive fallout in the real world, especially for
minority children who don't see their lives mirrored on TV.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have four or five conglomerates that basically control all
the stories our children grow up with, and the world they present
is a world of mostly white, middle-class consumers,'' said Gerbner.
Nonwhite children are led to believe ``that they're not as good as
anybody else, that they have fewer opportunities, fewer roles, less
potential. I call this growing up damaged.''
</P>
<P>
   Besides, noted Dan Amundson of the Center for Media and Public
Affairs in Washington, ``It's not just getting someone with the
same skin color. It's getting someone who is thinking about their
situation as a black or Latino would think about them.'' For that
to occur, the TV industry would need to bolster its low number of
minority writers, producers, and programming executives.
</P>
<P>
   Among other things, the dispute reflects an inherent tension
between the expectation that television will operate as a force for
social change and the reality that it operates as a bottom-line
business. Advertisers have made clear their preference for
youthful, affluent, and educated viewers.
</P>
<P>
   Critics like Poussaint note that many minority viewers fit all
three categories, but the networks have largely chosen to chase
their target demographic by developing copycat versions of
``Seinfeld'' or ``Friends,'' shows with all-white casts. The Big
Four networks who are the target of the NAACP's ire have
increasingly left black-themed programs to the upstart networks,
UPN and the WB. However, as with Fox, those networks have catered
less to black audiences as they have grown more established.
</P>
<P>
   The dearth of nonwhite characters on prime time now stands in in
sharp contrast to the TV landscape 25 years ago, during the
so-called ``Norman Lear era.'' In the 1974-75 season, noted TV
historian Alex McNeil, six of the Top 10-rated shows either starred
minorities or dealt with racial issues on an ongoing basis (``The
Jeffersons,'' ``Sanford and Son,'' ``Chico and the Man,'' ``All in
the Family,'' ``Maude,'' and ``Good Times''). In the past season,
only two of the Top 10 shows featured minorities in leading roles:
``ER'' and ``Touched by an Angel.''
</P>
<P>
   The visibility of ethnic minorities on American television has
eroded in this decade, even as presence in the US population has
grown. For instance, during the 1992-93 season, a study by the
Center for Media and Public Affairs found that 17 percent of the
characters on television were black. By this year, though
African-Americans make up 13 percent of the US population, the
percentage of black characters on TV had dropped to 10 percent,
according to Amundson.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps in response to the overall underrepresentation of
minorities on television, black viewers have increasingly diverged
from white viewers when it comes to program choices. The racial
divide opened widest in 1997-98, when ``Seinfeld'' was the
top-rated show in white households, but ranked only 50th among
black viewers, while the top-rated show in black households,
``Between Brothers,'' ranked 112th among white viewers.
</P>
<P>
   However, the range of roles available to minority actors has
undeniably broadened. Robert Thompson, head of the Center for the
Study of Popular Television at Syracuse University, noted the
``really good, juicy parts'' played by black actors on such shows
as ``ER,'' the recently canceled ``Homicide,'' and ``Ally McBeal.''
``We have definitely come a long way from where we were before,
though there's still a long way to go,'' said Thompson.
</P>
<P>
   To traverse that distance, Poussaint believes black viewers need
to send a succinct message to the TV industry and the advertisers
who support it: ``If you don't pay attention to us, why should we
pay attention to you? Why should we give you our money if you don't
reflect our lives?''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-15-99 1349EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990715.0156 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-15 13:50 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1261 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-AUTHOR-CHAPLIN-2ND &LR;  &UR; T     07-15 0981
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AUTHOR-CHAPLIN-2ND </SLUG>
   TAKE-ART-BOS  
 BOSTON: ... happen to me.''  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Chaplin is by his own description a compulsive adventurer, a man
who flies airplanes, drives fast cars, and enjoys scuba diving in
challenging locales. Many of the couple's quarrels centered around
safety issues. In ``Fever Coast Log,'' Chaplin describes how he
once pushed Atkinson out of a dinghy when she complained he was
going too fast.
</P>
<P>
   In her diary, from which Chaplin quotes, Atkinson wrote: ``Two
acts of abusive, violent behavior in two weeks which I have
accepted. I am very ashamed I haven't jumped ship, but I really
want to do this trip and if that's the trade-off, I'll accept it.
Another instance of cruelty will be the last. . . . ''
</P>
<P>
   How fearful was Atkinson of Chaplin? And to what extent did
their quarreling over safety precautions reflect deeper conflicts
that may have played a role in Atkinson's death?
</P>
<P>
   Chaplin considers the questions carefully. ``She was very pissed
off about it,'' he finally answers. ``I never thought our
relationship was in jeopardy. But I saw it'' _ the pushing incident
_ ``completely differently. There was no danger where we were. I
saw it as horsing around. Obviously she didn't.''
</P>
<P>
   As to why include the scene, Chaplin replies, ``Because it
happened, that's why. There were editors and agents who invited me
to take that out, I'm sure because they thought I was going to lose
readers. And maybe I did. But I believe the best memoirs are the
ones that tell everything.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Dark Wind'' is a darkly confessional tale, even without
Atkinson around to rebut Chaplin's version of events.
</P>
<P>
   In Belize, the couple returned to a port where Chaplin had once
had a fling with a female scuba diving instructor _ and lied about
it to Atkinson, who unearthed the truth anyway. Chaplin
subsequently returned to the United States for two weeks. Rejoining
Atkinson in Panama, he was told by her that she had slept with
another man while Chaplin was away. Later she confessed that the
sex was not consensual.
</P>
<P>
   The rape would have a profound impact on both of them, according
to Chaplin. Insisting they set sail across the Pacific immediately,
Atkinson seemed to harden in her fears about traveling with
Chaplin. A comically inept confrontation with the rapist only
seemed to worsen matters.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd lost faith in myself,'' writes Chaplin, ``as a man as well
as a sailor.'' Their lovemaking, which he previously described in
rhapsodic terms, all but ceased. Now, he writes, ``she needed to
make the voyage more than I did. . . . In some mysterious way she'd
gained confidence while I'd lost it.''
</P>
<P>
   With this as backdrop, Chaplin and Atkinson finally sailed into
Wotho atoll on Nov. 9, 1992. For 10 days they frolicked in a kind
of earthly paradise. And then along came Typhoon Gay, far more
potent than weather forecasters in the region had predicted.
</P>
<P>
   As the storm intensified, writes Chaplin, a strange feeling of
passivity settled over Atkinson and himself. ``We both seemed slow,
in movement and thought,'' he describes it in the book, ``as if we
were in a dream.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In retrospect Chaplin defends some, though by no means all, of
the decisions preceding Atkinson's death. Sailing to the Marshall
Islands during the tail end of typhoon season was not imprudent, he
argues. Trying to outsail the storm was not a clear-cut option
either. Other choices such as not swimming for shore during the
storm, or Chaplin's electing to hold on to his own life jacket
while Atkinson slipped away, are less defensible, he concedes.
</P>
<P>
   ``If she had asked _ she did not ask to go ashore. I did not
tell her to go ashore, either,'' he says, adding that he would have
never kept her from going. ``The question is, why didn't I make her
go ashore. And the only thing I can say is, because. Because I
didn't make her go ashore. That's why.''
</P>
<P>
   He pauses.
</P>
<P>
   ``I expected in the storm things would be very clear,'' Chaplin
says. ``But they were not clear. The wind was unlike anything I'd
experienced before. Even when the boat blew over, I thought the two
anchors would snag. It never happened.''
</P>
<P>
   According to Chaplin, there was also no reason to anticipate
that the valve on his life vest would malfunction, or that
harnesses on both vests would come apart in the pounding surf.
</P>
<P>
   Could he have saved Atkinson anyway?
</P>
<P>
   Chaplin nods slowly. ``It's a realistic possibility if I had
gotten to her,'' he says, ``I could have held Susan up until we
reached shore _ even though I had no idea where shore was.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just had the feeling she was gone, you know. I thought Susan
was gone.'' Chaplin looks away. ``I hoped she could make it, but I
was almost positive she couldn't. And I was sure I was drowning
too.''
</P>
<P>
   Chaplin writes of coming home to face Atkinson's family _ and
finding if not forgiveness, at least some measure of sympathy and
understanding. Later, he recounts his struggle with depression _ to
the point of contemplating suicide _ and of suffering rejection by
his own sister, his only sibling. The two have not spoken since,
says Chaplin, who blames the rupture on dysfunctional family
dynamics, not Atkinson's death.
</P>
<P>
   ``Dark Wind'' ends on an appropriately uneasy note. Addressing
Atkinson's survivors directly, Chaplin writes that he did his best
on a story he felt compelled to tell. ``This may ring hollow,
coming from someone whose best was not good enough,'' writes
Chaplin, adding, ``still, I had to try.''
</P>
<P>
   Holding in his hands the statement composed by Atkinson's
daughters, Chaplin shakes his head.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm totally floored by this,'' he says as he absorbs the
latest aftershock from the storm that took one life and changed
numerous others. ``If they had told me categorically that they
hated the idea of my doing this book, I'm not sure that I would
have gone ahead and written it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
