<DOCNO> NYT19990715.0157 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-15 13:51 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1262 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CHILDCARE-COLUMN-2TAK     07-15 1226
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHILDCARE-COLUMN-2 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A PARENT'S GUIDE TO TV RATINGS 
</HEADLINE>
 TAKES-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BARBARA F. MELTZ  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   There wasn't much fanfare to mark it, but July 1 was a landmark
date for parents: the first time we can walk into a store and buy a
televi-sion set with the much-touted V-chip. Unfortunately, just
because we finally can protect our children from violence on TV
doesn't mean we're out of the woods yet.
</P>
<P>
   The same parent who cares enough to buy a TV with technology
capable of blocking violent programming is probably also the parent
who pays attention to the movies his children see, the computer and
video games they play, and the CDs they listen to.
</P>
<P>
   And how is that parent rewarded? With rating systems that have
little in common, are difficult to understand, and ignore
children's developmental stages, the most important guideline a
parent has. Indeed, to make ratings work in a child's best
interests is time-consuming and confusing; no wonder many of us
give up in frustration.
</P>
<P>
   Researchers urge us to make the effort.
</P>
<P>
   ``It still isn't easy or simple but at least the V-chip and the
ratings combine to give us tools we didn't have before,'' says
Joanne Cantor, a professor at the University of Wisconsin and one
of the nation's leading TV researchers. She's also a mother who is
vigilant about what her 9-year-old son watches.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think of my efforts as a kind of health insurance for
Alex,'' she says. ``Bad viewing habits are just as bad for kids as
too much junk food.'' Cantor also is the author of `` `Mommy, I'm
Scared': How TV and Movies Frighten Children and What We Can Do to
Protect Them'' (Harcourt Brace, 1998).
</P>
<P>
   Here then is a rundown on the rating systems for various media,
as well as the major pitfalls of each one:
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   MOVIES
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The system:
</P>
<P>
   G: general audience, all ages admitted;
</P>
<P>
   PG: parental guidance suggested; some material may not be
suitable for children;
</P>
<P>
   PG-13: parents strongly cautioned for children under 13;
</P>
<P>
   R: restricted; under 17 requires adult chaperone;
</P>
<P>
   NC-17: no one under 17 admitted.
</P>
<P>
   What to be aware of:
</P>
<P>
   --Movie ratings ignore developmental differences. Although they
divide children chronologically into three groups _ 0 to 13, 13 to
17, over 17 _ there is no allowance for the huge differences among
preteens and no help at all with children under 7. In other words,
the PG-13 movie that one 11-year-old can tolerate may cause
nightmares for her best friend, the PG movie that an 8-year-old can
handle may be overwhelming for a 6-year-old, and nothing about the
ratings gives you clues to this beforehand.
</P>
<P>
   Jacqui Sears, a mother in Southampton, experienced several years
ago how meaningless ratings can be when she took the G rating on
the ``Beauty and the Beast'' video at face value. Her daughter,
then 3, was so badly frightened by the scene where the dogs chase
Belle that she continues to have bad dreams about it, even five
years later. Sears formed MOM (Mothers Offended by the Media) and
has been lobbying the ratings board of the Motion Picture
Association of America ever since, trying to get it to adopt a G-6
rating to indicate a movie is inappropriate for under 7.
</P>
<P>
   Educators agree 7 is a critical age.
</P>
<P>
   ``Younger children typically aren't yet able to distinguish
between what's real and what's not,'' says early childhood educator
Diane Levin of Wheelock College.
</P>
<P>
   Children under 7 also are only able to take in the most obvious
feature of what's on the screen. All too frequently, that's what is
violent or grotesque, says Bobbie Eisenstock, a professor of
communication at California State University who specializes in the
psychological effects of media on children. ``They then become
frightened because they are cognitively unable to handle the
material,'' she says.
</P>
<P>
   --Toy tie-ins to movies mislead children and some parents to
think a movie is for them. In addition, the toy typically
capitalizes on the grotesque or violent aspect of the movie that
probably earned it the PG-13 rating in the first place.
</P>
<P>
   A current summer movie release, ``Mummy,'' for instance, is
rated PG-13 but has toys marketed for 4-year-olds who are not yet
developmentally capable of understanding how the body works: A
4-year-old typically wants a bandage because he worries his body
will ooze out; when he has a broken arm he doesn't
compartmentalize, ``My arm is broken,'' he thinks, ``I am broken.''
Yet one ``Mummy'' action figure is the ``Impaled Mummy with
piercing action: Impale the mummy, watch as his intestines fall out
of his chest.''
</P>
<P>
   Levin finds this appalling: ``The toy feeds into a child's
vulnerability by taking a developmental issue he's trying to
understand and making it scary and complicated.'' She urges parents
to be wary of all movie tie-in toys and to bear in mind that most
toy ratings are based on how safe they are for a young child, not
on a child's cognitive ability to handle the toy or whether the toy
offers good play potential for a child that age. Levin is
nationally recognized for her research on the impact of media
violence on children and is author of ``Remote Control Childhood?
Combating the Hazards of Media Culture'' (NAEYC Press).
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   TELEVISION
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The system:
</P>
<P>
   TV-Y: programming specifically made for young children of all
ages;
</P>
<P>
   TV-Y7: made for children 7 or older;
</P>
<P>
   TV-Y7-FV: contains fantasy violence intended for children 7 or
older;
</P>
<P>
   TV-G: made for general audiences;
</P>
<P>
   TV-PG: for general audiences, but contains mild to moderate
violence, sex, crude language, or sexual dialogue; parental
guidance suggested;
</P>
<P>
   TV-14: contains moderate to intense violence, sex, language, or
sexual dialogue; parents strongly cautioned against viewing by
children under 14;
</P>
<P>
   TV-MA: not suitable for children under 17.
</P>
<P>
   V (violence), S (sexual situations), L (crude langauge), or D
(dialogue about sex) may accompany a TV-PG or TV-14 rating so it
looks like this: TV-14-SL. This ups the ante on the rating. TV-14
already means there's some sex, violence, etc. SL tells you that
the sex and language are even more intense than usual.
</P>
<P>
   What to be aware of:
</P>
<P>
   --Ratings are not used universally or always easy to find. BET
(Black Entertainment Television) does not rate programs at all; NBC
does not add the content descriptors. Some newspapers, including
the Globe, print content ratings; some do not. When the rating is
shown, it's displayed in the upper left-hand corner of the screen
for the first 15 seconds of the show. ``If you aren't there to see
it, you've missed it,'' says Kathryn Montgomery, president of the
Center for Media Education, a public interest group based in
Washington, D.C. She urges parents to ask stations to flash the
rating now and then during a program.
</P>
<P>
   --You can't trust ratings to be complete. TV-G never has content
ratings, so even if there is mild violence, etc., there's no
warning. TV-PG by definition includes mild to moderate violence,
sex, bad language or sexual dialogue.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most parents don't realize that,'' says Montgomery.
</P>
<P>
   Eisenstock says this is a particular problem with TV-PG because
the contents can vary so much from show to show. ``One TV-PG may
not be a problem but another one is,'' she says.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MORE &LR;  &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
