<SLUG> BC-WALKER-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EQUAL RIGHT TO BARE ALL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ADRIAN WALKER  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   It wasn't anything men playing soccer don't do all the time.
</P>
<P>
   By now, you've seen the shot on television, in the Sunday paper,
adorning the covers of Newsweek and Sports Illustrated: defender
Brandi Chastain shirtless, in a sports bra, celebrating her winning
penalty kick against China, triceps rippling, sweat pouring off her
exhausted body from which she had ripped her jersey moments before.
</P>
<P>
   It was the kind of thing previously reserved for male sports
heroes, often prone to acts of partial disrobement at the height of
battle. It was something Dennis Rodman would do, or Latrell
Sprewell. It was a moment of true equality, the right of both sexes
to celebrate victory unencumbered.
</P>
<P>
   ``A moment of temporary insanity'' was the way Chastain
described her World Cup moment after the game.
</P>
<P>
   Not everyone was convinced it was purely spontaneous. After all,
this is a woman who has posed in the buff (crouching behind a
soccer ball) for Gear magazine and a Nike ad, and whose teammates
nicknamed her ``Hollywood'' for her flamboyant personality. It
seemed in character.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm proud of my body,'' she said a few weeks ago. ``I have
bigger biceps and shoulders than my dad. I'm not going to hide
it.''
</P>
<P>
   Then again, who cares why she did it? She captured the emotion
of the moment. She gave almost everyone with abdominal muscles
something to aspire to. She looked strong and sexy _ and any man
who tells you he didn't notice it thinks you're an idiot.
</P>
<P>
   Actually, pulling up your jersey to celebrate a goal is common
both in men's soccer and, increasingly, in women's soccer. It's
like spiking a football after a touchdown.
</P>
<P>
   Even so, the Women's World Cup prompted a predictable,
politically correct debate over whether ``sexuality'' was being
used to sell the event, sullying its pristine perfection as a
stairway to heaven for suburban teenage girls arriving at soccer
games with their faces painted red, white and blue.
</P>
<P>
   Never mind that there was less exposed flesh than you could see
this weekend at Singing Beach, or even at the finish line of the
Boston Marathon. But, it was enough to make some people uneasy.
</P>
<P>
   Almost immediately, there was howling that Chastain's move was a
marketing ploy for the ubiquitous Nike, which she represents. Or
that it was in some other way calculated as an act of
self-promotion. (Nike officials admit to salivating when they
realized the bra was one of their ``Inner Actives,'' due to hit
stores later this month.)
</P>
<P>
   For Chastain, the goal was the culmination of a tournament in
which she had most attracted attention for kicking a ball into her
own net in a quarterfinal match against West Germany. She courted
disaster by firing a pass for goaltender Briana Scurry past her and
into the US net. She later scored the tying goal in the game, which
the right side won, 3-2.
</P>
<P>
   But for all the historic appeal of the team, especially to
girls, the sexual subtext was ever present, as it always is in
sports. David Letterman led the way, displaying a picture of the
team in long T-shirts, and apparently nothing else, for most of the
tournament.
</P>
<P>
   People magazine did its part by naming superstar Mia Hamm one of
the 50 most beautiful people in the world. Julie Foudy posed for
Sports Illustrated in a bikini, playing soccer on a beach with her
husband.
</P>
<P>
   All along, there were some naysayers, even among the athletes
themselves. ``I am a bit uncomfortable with Brandi's deal,''
midfielder Michelle Akers told the New York Times after Chastain's
spread in Gear appeared. ``You don't want something like that to
detract from the excellence of this team and the message that we're
striving to put out.''
</P>
<P>
   Fair enough. But sports and sex appeal have always been linked
and always will be. How many of Michael Jordan's fans were as drawn
to his physique as his basketball? Why do so many men cheer for
tennis player Anna Kournikova? And why did one of my friend's
girlfriend borrow his binoculars at Fenway only between innings in
the 1980s? (So she could leer at Dwight Evans' butt as he ran on
and off the field.)
</P>
<P>
   Title IX was passed a generation ago to bring parity to men's
and women's sports. Slowly it has. We found out Saturday just how
far down the road to equality men and women have come. All of a
sudden, we can all cheer the athletes, even as we ogle the bodies
underneath.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Adrian Walker's e-mail address is walker(at)globe.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
