<SLUG> BC-ELLIS-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TECHNOLOGY'S CHANGING PICTURE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOHN ELLIS  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   In about six or nine months, Lexmark is planning to bring to
market a new printer. What's remarkable about this printer is that
it has a chip in it that can publish Kodak-quality photographs
directly from a digital camera, in any size or shape you wish.
</P>
<P>
   All you have to do is plug the camera into the printer. If you
want a contact sheet, it'll do that. If you want to print out two
3x5s, it will do that. If you want one big picture on one sheet of
paper, it'll do that too.
</P>
<P>
   Today, you can print out digital photographs on any color
printer, but you have to go through a personal computer to do so.
That's easily done, once you get the hang of it, but it's daunting
for beginners and anything other than one picture per page is
equally daunting for experts. Since specialty paper sells for
anywhere from 80 cents to $1.20 per sheet, one picture per page is
cost ineffective.
</P>
<P>
   But these problems will soon disappear. And, probably, in two or
three years, the Lexmark printers with the smart chip for
``developing'' digital photographs will cost no more than the one
you can buy over the Internet today (which is to say $219). In
addition, the specialty paper will become a commodity and like
every other commodity see its price cut in half.
</P>
<P>
   Once the price issue is moot, the larger issue of immediacy and
convenience takes over. Here the Lexmark printer wins, hands down.
It could not be more immediate. It couldn't be more convenient. No
more film, no more Photo-quick on your lunch hour; it's not even
close. Especially when you remember that the digital technology
will only get better, faster, and smarter.
</P>
<P>
   Everywhere you turn these days, convergence is changing the
landscape. Five years ago, the notion that a company that
manufactures low-end printers could spell doom for the Eastman
Kodak Company would have seemed almost inconceivable. Kodak, after
all, is virtually synonymous with the business of photography. But
five years later, here we are.
</P>
<P>
   The impact of converging technologies is being felt in virtually
every business category. In New York, there's a fellow going around
Wall Street selling software that wakes up your computer, turns on
your printer, dials up your Internet service provider and builds
you a personalized newspaper. You tell it what you want (and from
which newspapers) and it goes out and gets it.
</P>
<P>
   You have your personalized op-ed page, your personalized sports
page, your personalized business section, your hometown metro
coverage, your national and international news, weather reports,
stock quotes, what have you.
</P>
<P>
   Once the hunting is done, the software informs your computer to
print it out in the order you wish to receive it. By the time you
roll out of bed, it's sitting there waiting for you, with
advertisements about products and services that you request. If you
don't want ads, then there are no ads.
</P>
<P>
   I have no idea if this software actually works, but I suspect
that if it doesn't, someone out there will invent software very
much like it that will work just fine. And when that happens,
that's the end of your local newspaper as you know it. Because when
that happens, every newspaper will become your local newspaper. You
just have to decide which parts of which paper you want printed
out.
</P>
<P>
   Five years ago, this newspaper competed with The Boston Herald
in the Boston media market. Today, The Boston Globe competes with
every newspaper on the Internet, including the newspaper company
that owns it, The New York Times.
</P>
<P>
   This competitive set will only intensify as bandwidth and
Internet technologies advance. In five years, connection speeds to
the Internet will be 8 to 15 times faster than they are today.
Computers will be dirt cheap. Internet access will likely be
commodity priced at $10 per month and could well be free.
Organizations like AARP will bring millions of new users onto the
Web. And everybody who has information worth selling will be in the
``newspaper'' business on the Web.
</P>
<P>
   The task of navigating these waters at the Globe now falls to
Richard H. Gilman, who Monday replaced Benjamin Taylor as
publisher. The end of the Taylor era at the Globe was on some level
inevitable; new owners always move in to properties they purchase.
But on another level, Gilman's appointment marked the end of the
Boston Globe as a newspaper company and embarked it once and for
all on the uncharted waters of convergence.
</P>
<P>
   What's remarkable is that the effects of converging technologies
are just beginning to be felt. The pace of change will only
accelerate. Gilman's task is to insure that The Boston Globe does
not go the way of Kodak. It's a tough task and one wishes him well.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(John Ellis is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
