<SLUG> BC-BOOK-RESSURECTION-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BOSTON SURVIVES POSTWAR THRILLER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOHN KOCH  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
RESURRECTION DAY 
By Brendan DuBois 
Putnam, 389 pp., $23.95 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``The stories appearing in today's Boston Globe have been
cleared by the U.S. Army under the provisions of the Martial Law
Declaration of 1962 and the National Emergency Declaration of
1963.''
</P>
<P>
   Such is the state of American journalism, and the US at large,
in the what-if scenario spun by Brendan DuBois in his
post-apocalyptic thriller, ``Resurrection Day.'' What if the Cuban
missile crisis had boiled over into a catastrophic Soviet-US
nuclear war that wiped out half a dozen major American cities and
rendered the USSR a medieval wasteland?
</P>
<P>
   That's DuBois's premise, and in his grim, reeling post-war US of
1972, Boston _ one of the major American cities spared in the
attack _ is the main stage for an often entertaining but
hyperactive story. The Globe, realistically situated in Dorchester,
but with an Army censor on the staff imposing daily control on the
paper's contents, figures prominently in the overheated plot.
</P>
<P>
   The hero is a proverbially dogged reporter, Carl Landry, a
laconic Special Forces vet who was an adviser in Vietnam until the
'62 nuclear outbreak nipped that little misadventure in the bud.
Landry is called back from Indochina to serve in California. There
he resettles nuclear refugees and, more sinisterly, helps put down
mini-insurrections by Americans hostile to what looks curiously
like military rule, despite President Romney's lip service to
democratic values. John F. Kennedy, his family, and numerous
Washington-based politicians and officials perished in the bomb
blasts _ though graffiti nationwide eerily insist that ``He
Lives.''
</P>
<P>
   Landry is rewarded for his military service with a job at the
Globe, where he sinks his teeth into a mundane-sounding but
increasingly mysterious East Boston murder story that he never
surrenders for the nearly 400 pages of DuBois's book. Despite dire
warnings from his editor and the censor, Landry pulls on the loose
strings of the suppressed story, which lead him toward the center
of a plot involving a resurgently predatory British Empire and a
homegrown revolution stewing in the bowels of depopulated Manhattan
and, of course, a pretty love interest (an ambitious ivory-skinned
reporter from The Times of London).
</P>
<P>
   ``Resurrection Day'' has a lot to recommend it, especially a
level of hypothetical-historical detail that gives the better parts
of the novel a nightmarish authenticity. ``Orphie'' gangs of
rootless, hardened teens roam the night streets of Boston; food is
available but hardly plentiful; and the rundown city barely
functions as the country slowly, uncertainly decontaminates
lingering nuclear hotspots and haltingly rebuilds.
</P>
<P>
   And DuBois's evocation of an overarching US military, its long
reach extended through the brutal, fascistic Zed Force, generates
some scary action and an effectively cautionary message. He
knowledgeably takes our national penchant for violence and history
of atomic assaults and covert operations to their darkest
conclusion, a world so blighted by American power that US military
personnel are subject to arrest as war criminals in Europe.
</P>
<P>
   But DuBois has difficulty sustaining our belief in the universe
he manufactures. The mechanics of his illusion-making can be
embarrassingly obtrusive. His dialogue, for example, often sounds
less like natural conversation than like stilted history lessons.
And his graceless and occasionally painfully cliched prose
trivializes the book's more serious intentions. Listen to Landry,
inspired by his lovely girlfriend Sandy to rediscover purpose in
his life and work: ``He remembered their special night together and
the energy that sparked something inside of him. . . . Sandy was
making him care again.'' True, that's as bad as it gets, but it
gets that way too often.
</P>
<P>
   And then there's Landry himself: too decent, too clever, and,
finally, too almost comically heroic to be true. Suffice it to say
that he has a Houdini-like gift for escaping mortal danger and the
combined journalistic skills of Woodward and Bernstein. As much as
DuBois (a New Hampshire mystery novelist) appears to admire George
Orwell and Anthony Burgess, he finally sounds more like a fan of
Hollywood's ``Die Hard'' extravaganzas and their stylishly
blood-streaked, bullet-proof centerpiece, Bruce Willis.
</P>
<P>
   For all its flaws, ``Resurrection Day'' is a fairly good read _
but I'll bet the movie, if there is one, will be far better.
Indeed, the novel reads as if DuBois himself made this same
discovery in the process of writing, and turned his attention from
crafting a book to imagining the weekend grosses of the screen
version.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-15-99 1355EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
