<SLUG> BC-HANDYMAN-HOTTON-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHEN BEETLES KNOCK ON THE DOOR 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PETER C. HOTTON  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q. I am finding little black beetles in a wood door. What are
they and how can I get rid of them?
</P>
<P>
   AMY BUCKLAND, Brookline, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   A. They could be powder post beetles or old house borers. Yep,
that is what they are called, and there are many kinds of each,
although powder post beetles generally attack only hardwoods. They
all tunnel in the wood, but you can usually see little holes where
they have entered. Mostly, they don't eat the wood, but extract the
starch from it, and they sure do tunnel!
</P>
<P>
   Your first step is to identify the bug; in most cases this is
done by an exterminator.
</P>
<P>
   But there are things you can do yourself, if you are willing to
take the time, and if the infestation is not severe. If the beetle
is the type that does not reinfest wood and you saw them outside
the door, there is nothing you have to do because they will not
return to the wood. You need an identification to determine if the
critters are nonreinfesters.
</P>
<P>
   They tend to come and go; sometimes you may have them and then
you don't. Your main concern is to make sure they don't go
elsewhere in the house.
</P>
<P>
   One treatment is to squirt bleach or paint thinner into the
holes, kill any escapees, and hope for the best. Insecticides to
use are borax-based products such as TIM-Bor or Bora-Care, and
pyrethrin/silica aerogel.
</P>
<P>
   Other methods are high heat (120 degrees) and an electrical
current in the wood. These can be expensive and so can fumigation;
they should be done if the infestation is severe, and it's a job
for an exterminator.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. I am regluing my kitchen chairs, but in one chair, the rung
doesn't come out so I can glue it. Is there any trick to separating
those rungs?
</P>
<P>
   FRANK McKINNON, Saugus, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   A. Not really a trick, but what you ran into is a nail that is
driven into the leg that holds the rung and through the rung
itself. It's the only thing that is keeping the chair from
collapsing completely. You should be able to worry the rung out,
either bending or breaking the nail, which is not very big. This
was a common practice in building wood chairs with rungs. Once you
have the rung out, pull the nail. When you reglue, drive another
similar nail to complete the repair.
</P>
<P>
   And, if the hole is too big for the rung to glue properly, you
can decrease the size of the hole with Mr. Grip. This is a little
strip of aluminum perforated to look like a cheese grater; the
perforation holes retain small barbs that do the holding. Insert
one or more into the hole; usually you can fold one end-to-end and
stick it in. Then the rung will be tight when you push it in, but
you will still have to glue it. Mr. Grip is sold in hardware and
building supply stores.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. I fished a fine old sideboard from a dump fire in Maine,
where I have a camp. It must date to the late 1800s or early 1900s.
I refinished it and it looks wonderful, except it needs hardware.
Where can I find old hardware appropriate for such an oak veneer
sideboard? I remember there was a shop in Boston that handled old
hardware, but I can't think of its name.
</P>
<P>
   LESTER PITCHER, Naples, Fla.
</P>
<P>
   A. You may be thinking of Restoration Resources, a retail store
whose address is 31 Thayer St., Boston, MA 02118; telephone
617-542-3033.
</P>
<P>
   There are a number of catalogs out there, too, where you might
find what you are looking for. Van Dykes' Restoration products is
one (800-843-3320). Renovator's Supply (800-659-2211) is another.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. The wide floorboards in my 1800 house are really nice but the
nails tend to work themselves loose and pop up, causing a hazard to
walkers. I nail them back, but that only lasts a few months. How
can I keep them in place? The boards are random width rock maple.
</P>
<P>
   MARVIN KRIMS, Newton, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. It's a simple matter, really. The nail holes are too big,
after many years of expansion and contraction of the boards. There
are several cures, and since the boards are face-nailed (the nail
heads are showing), the fix is relatively easy. You have three
choices:
</P>
<P>
   --Buy hot-zinc-dipped galvanized box nails a size or two bigger
than the up-popping nails. Drive them in place of the old nails and
countersink. There is no need to fill the holes unless you really
want to. Such wide boards are rather informal anwyay. The handyman
used such nails to secure his wide pine boards 25 years ago, and
they are still holding strong. The galvanizing process makes the
nails hold well, and there are little barbs on the shafts that help
hold even better.
</P>
<P>
   --Pull the maverick nails and substitute solid brass screws of a
bigger size, countersink, and leave them, or fill the holes with
wood plugs.
</P>
<P>
   --Replace the old nails with screw nails, although this may not
be practical if you cannot find a screw nail bigger than the old
nail.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Globe Handyman on Call Peter Hotton will answer reader questions.
Write him at the Boston Globe, Boston, Mass., 02107.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-15-99 1357EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990715.0162 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-15 13:58 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1275 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GLF-BRITISH-GARCIA-2N     07-15 0959
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-BRITISH-GARCIA-2ND </SLUG>
   TAKE-BOS  
 CARNOUSTIE, Scotland: ... before adolescence?  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   While he claims that he once dreamed of being a soccer star _
``I was thinking, `Ah, you can see me in the Bernabeau with Real
Madrid' '' _ golf has been Garcia's milieu since the gestation
stage. He would follow his mother around the pro shop in his
stroller as an infant. At age 2, he began swinging a duster like a
golf club. He started playing the game for real at age 3, and his
competitive career was launched at 6 when he would ask members who
made the mistake of wandering past him, ``You want to play three
holes for a Coke?''
</P>
<P>
   ``He became the biggest Coke consumer in the province of
Castellon,'' says Marquina.
</P>
<P>
   Garcia got his first adult clubs at age 9, and his father was
his tutor, both concerning the game and the price it required.
Victor had been a professional caddie as a young adult. Forbidden
to swing clubs on the course, he had taught himself the game with a
jerry-rigged olive branch. He had worked his way up to this club
job, and he instilled that ethic in his son.
</P>
<P>
   By 12, Garcia was the club champion. By 13, he was a scratch
golfer. And at that point, he became the end product of a unique
assembly line.
</P>
<P>
   Marquina, an international business liasion who had known the
family since he began taking lessons from Victor when Sergio was 5
or 6, recognized the prodigious potential and decided that it must
be properly nurtured.
</P>
<P>
   Six years ago, with Victor's and Consuelo's blessing, Marquina
set up what he calls Team Sergio. It seemingly left nothing about
Garcia the golfer _ and golfing commodity _ to chance.
</P>
<P>
   The team now numbers seven or eight people, by Marquina's
estimation. From the time Garcia was 13, he worked with an English
teacher whose curriculum included mock press conferences; judging
by many of his responses, he earned an A-plus in cliches. There was
a physical therapist to strengthen his back, generally the most
vulnerable part of a golfer's anatomy. He would run every day for
10-15 minutes to develop cardiovascular strength. The key was
elasticity, and that extended to the golf itself. Twice a month,
Garcia would play lefthanded to facilitate swing balance; he has
shot as low as 42 for nine holes from that side and Wednesday
played a lefty shot out of Carnoustie's rough.
</P>
<P>
   The dividends were immediate. Garcia won an estimated 70 amateur
events. At 15, he became the youngest European Amateur champion
ever, and later he added the British Amateur crown, both titles
earning him automatic entry into the British Open. But more
remarkable was his advanced placement work.
</P>
<P>
   Marquina already was brainstorming _ and scrambling _ in an
effort to hone Garcia's game on a grander scale. He approached
Garcia's father and said, ``Let's take Sergio to the US. It's a
different language, different courses. It will be good for him.''
</P>
<P>
   Victor agreed, which left only one problem: How to get there?
</P>
<P>
   Marquina approached a friend who worked for an airline and tried
to cadge a couple of trans-Atlantic tickets.
</P>
<P>
   ``You must be kidding,'' the friend said.
</P>
<P>
   Marquina told him, ``He's going to be the greatest golfer in the
world.''
</P>
<P>
   The airline executive was sold and the tickets were donated.
Garcia went to Miami at age 14, entered a 16-and-under tournament,
and won it by 14 strokes.
</P>
<P>
   But that was nothing compared to Marquina's other avenue of
development. The best way for Garcia to prepare for life as a pro,
he figured, was to play as a pro. Some of his amateur victories
earned him exemptions to European Tour events. Marquina got him
into others by begging and cajoling tournament directors. In all,
Garcia played 28 Tour events as an amateur. He made the cut 21
times. At 14, he became the youngest player ever to make a European
Tour cut, in the Turespana Open. At 17, he won a local pro event,
the Catalonia Open.
</P>
<P>
   ``At the beginning, maybe when I was about 14, 15 years old, I
was a little nervous,'' says Garcia. ``But that helped me. That's
why I'm not afraid to be here. I've always said when I was an
amateur that I was playig all those many pro events because I
didn't want to be afraid now.''
</P>
<P>
   And he's not, because he was a veteran before he became a
rookie.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's been almost like a pro for the past few years,'' says
Vijay Singh. ``He's a good player who's going to get better.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   But not necessarily cynical. If Marquina's grand game plan seems
manipulative on the surface, there are restraints. At his advisers'
insistence, Garcia will finish high school next year ``to get him
away from golf and keep him grounded,'' says Marquina. His
endorsement deals are limited to a pair, with Acushnet and Adidas,
``so he's not stretched too thin,'' says Marquina. ``The key for me
is for him to be comfortable, not to worry about having to make
money while he's standing over a putt.''
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps that's why there's still a bit of the boy in the old
pro. When Marquina signed the Adidas deal, Garcia cared only about
two things: meeting fellow client Anna Kournikova and getting a
Real Madrid jersey. After he won the Irish Open, he immediately
demanded an appearance fee for next year _ a PlayStation and 10
video games.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a straightforward kid,'' says Marquina. ``What you see is
what you get.''
</P>
<P>
   He expects to get much more, this composite of naivete and
savvy, though he realizes it won't always be a snap.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know if I keep playing well, the expectations are going to
be high,'' says Garcia. ``I'd like you to be happy with me, but you
have to know sometimes that the sport is not as easy as it looks.''
</P>
<P>
   Obviously, he doesn't know any better. It only looks easy to
prodigies like Garcia. Oops, Sergio.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
