<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; FOR FRIDAY AMs
</P>
<P>
   &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Here are today's top news stories from The New York Times News
Service for AMs of Friday, July 16:
</P>
<P>
   &UR; INTERNATIONAL &LR;  (``i'' code)
</P>
<P>
   NIRELAND-PEACE (Belfast, Ireland) _ What was to have been the
most important day in the Northern Ireland peace effort broke down
in chaos and recriminations as a top Catholic official in the new
Northern Ireland government quit after the main Protestant party
boycotted Thursday's discussions. By Warren Hoge.
</P>
<P>
   ISRAEL-U.S. (Washington) _ On the meeting between Israeli Prime
Minister Ehud Barak and President Clinton in Washington Thursday
afternoon. By Jane Perlez and John M. Broder.
</P>
<P>
   IRAN-PROTESTS (Islamshar, Iran) _ In a working-class suburb of
Teheran where the government put down an economic protest a few
years ago, people clamor for jobs, not press freedom, and they're
just as disgruntled as the pro-democracy demonstrators. By Elaine
Sciolino.
</P>
<P>
   CHINA-NUKE (Washington) _ Reaction from Congress and the
administration to a Chinese announcement that China built its own
neutron bomb and didn't steal plans from the United States. By Eric
Schmitt
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-RUGOVA (Pristina, Yugoslavia) _ Ibrahim Rugova, head of
the Kosovo Democratic League and a political leader of Kosovar
Albanians, returned to Kosovo after a two-month absence;
difficulties in administering Kosovo persisted as Albanians, Serbs
and KLA representatives argued over setting up provincial and town
governments. By John Kifner.
</P>
<P>
   INDIA-TELEVISED-WAR (Mokhra, India) _ India has fought three
larger wars with Pakistan, in 1947, 1965 and 1971, but the past two
months of fighting in the Himalayan land of Kashmir that lies
between the two countries have produced its first televised war. In
1971, less than 1 percent of Indian households had televisions.
Now, more than 30 percent of households own a television. By Celia
W. Dugger.
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIA-NOSTALGIA (Moscow) _ A Moscow journal on Russians'
increasing nostalgia for the Soviet era. A patina of nostalgia, or
at least kitsch, has spread over that gray world of communal
apartments, chronic shortages, propaganda slogans, controlled
newspapers and political taboos. By Serge Schmemann.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WASHINGTON &LR;  (``w'' code)
</P>
<P>
   HEALTH-CARE (Washington) _ On the Senate vote expected late
Thursday on the Republican version of the Patients' Bill of Rights.
By Alison Mitchell.
</P>
<P>
   HOUSE-RELIGION (Washington) _ On the House debate and expected
vote on whether religious liberty or civil rights should take
precedence when the two principles come into conflict. By David E.
Rosenbaum. With photo.
</P>
<P>
   CAMPAIGN-FINANCE (Washington) _ Presidential candidates'
second-quarter finance reports reveal which donors have switched
candidates and which candidates face financial difficulties. By Don
Van Natta Jr.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NATIONAL GENERAL &LR;  (``a'' code)
</P>
<P>
   COURT-SETTLEMENTS (Undated) _ More than a decade after states
began enacting laws to cut back big jury awards and curtail injury
lawsuits, state courts across the country are overturning one
measure after another, concluding that Americans have a powerful
right to settle their disputes in court. By William Glaberson.
</P>
<P>
   AFFIRMATIVE-ACTION (Atlanta) _ Atlanta's mayor, Bill Campbell,
is scheduled to hold a rally at city hall Thursday night in support
of the city's 24-year-old affirmative action program.
</P>
<P>
   DENVER-INTERNATIONALIZE (Denver) _ Japan has opened a consulate
here. China's prime minister has visited. The mayor will play host
to African leaders for a meeting on development and democracy.
Experts say the rapid internationalization of this city, 1,000
miles from the nearest seaport, is perhaps the highest profile
example of a larger trend: the increasing integration of the
nation's interior into the world economy. By James Brooke.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-VACCINE-SUSPEND (Undated) _ Federal health officials on
Thursday called for immediate suspension of a vaccine against
rotavirus that is now recommended for all infants in this country.
Developed at the National Institutes of Health and licensed less
than a year ago to Wyeth-Ayerst, the vaccine is suspected of
causing serious cases of bowel obstruction. By Lawrence K. Altman. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   NY-SENATE-CAMPAIGN (Undated) _ New campgain finance filings for
the New York Senate race. By David M. Herszenhorn.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; BIZDAY &LR;  (``f'' code)
</P>
<P>
   FASTER-COMPUTERS (Palo Alto, Calif.) _ A team of researchers
from Hewlett Packard Co. and the University of California at Los
Angeles have fashioned simple computing components no thicker than
a single molecule and are speaking openly about the possibility of
computers that are 100 billion times faster than today's fastest
personal computers. They envision a world in which supercomputing
power is so pervasive and inexpensive that it literally becomes an
integral part of of every man-made object. By John Markoff. With
photo and graphic.
</P>
<P>
   WARNER-BROTHERS (Undated) _ The co-chairmen of Warner Brothers,
Robert A. Daly and Terry Semel, the longest serving studio heads in
Hollywood, will leave by year-end. By Geraldine Fabrikant and
Bernard Weinraub.
</P>
<P>
   CONSUMER-PRICES (Undated) _ Consumer prices held steady in June
as energy costs fell for a second straight month after surging in
April. The Consumer Price Index was unchanged in June, as it was in
May. The last time the index registered two straight unchanged
readings was November-December 1962, the government said. Analysts
had expected an increase of 0.1 percent in the June Consumer Price
Index. By Sylvia Nasar. With graphic.
</P>
<P>
   CORPORATE-SPONSORS (Portland, Ore.) _ The recent Portland Rose
Festival was kicked off by events like the Starlight Parade.
Actually, make that the ``Portland General Electric/Solv Starlight
Parade Presented by Southwest Airlines.'' Corporate sponsorship of
all manner of events is not a new phenomenon. But these days you
can barely find the event for the sponsors. By Edwin McDowell.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; COMMENTARY &LR;  (``k'' code)
</P>
<P>
   SAFIRE-COLUMN (Undated) _ Details to come.
</P>
<P>
   Thomas L. Friedman and A.M. Rosenthal are on vacation.
</P>
