<HEADER>
A1288 &Cx1f; tad-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-JOEMURRAY-COLUMN16-CO     07-15 0608
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JOEMURRAY-COLUMN16-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    TALL TALES AND SHORT STORIES: A follower of Hemingway in Paris
 &HT;    By Joe Murray
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   PARIS _ Be careful what you let your daughter read. Otherwise
she might turn out like Noel Riley Fitch, devoting herself to the
bohemian lifestyle of Paris.
</P>
<P>
   If only she'd never read the Ladies Home Journal.
</P>
<P>
   That's how it started, in the mid-1960s when she was a graduate
student at Washington State University and her mother, ``concerned
that I was neglecting my domestic skills,'' sent her a copy of the
ladies magazine.
</P>
<P>
   Noel, however, skipping over items on the joys of housekeeping,
settled instead on an article by author Katherine Anne Porter, all
about the writers and artists who made Paris their home in the
1920s _ and made Sylvia Beach's Shakespeare and Co. bookstore their
second home.
</P>
<P>
   ``The description was so real, from the books on the shelves to
the fire in the fireplace,'' she said. ``It was where I wanted to
be.''
</P>
<P>
   One way or another, she's been there ever since _ as a professor
and author, making the Paris life of Ernest Hemingway and others of
that era her life's work. A Ph.D. who has a striking resemblance to
Ann-Margaret, she divides her time between Los Angeles and Paris,
teaching at USC and the American University.
</P>
<P>
   I first had met her through her book, ``Sylvia Beach and the
Lost Generation,'' which is used as a text at the Sorbonne for a
course in American writers and artists of the 1920s.
</P>
<P>
   When I met her in person in Paris for an interview _ the
centennial of Hemingway's birth is July 21 _ it was at her favorite
cafe, Cafe Francois Coppe on the rue du Monparnasse, not a place
Papa had frequented.
</P>
<P>
   Noel Riley Fitch will tell you that ``no one had a better sense
of place that carried over into his passion for his art'' than did
Hemingway.
</P>
<P>
   But place is a matter of individual choice. So it is with cafes
in Paris, as much for her as it was for Hemingway.
</P>
<P>
   ``You want a cafe that is near your home, one that is convenient
to buses and Metro service,'' she said. ``This is my neighborhood.
This is my cafe.''
</P>
<P>
   The ones to avoid are those that have become famous. ``On the
menus, they may have printed, `Intellectuals meet here,' '' she
said, not so different from ``Rotary meets here.''
</P>
<P>
   But if you are looking for Hemingway's Paris, best that you look
for one of Noel Riley Fitch's guidebooks, ``Walks in Hemingway's
Paris'' and ``The Literary Cafes of Paris.''
</P>
<P>
   She particularly recommends the Deux-Magots, a literary cafe
since 1875, which Hemingway preferred for ``serious talks.'' It is
now much as it was then.
</P>
<P>
   Or visit the home where he and Hadley, his first wife, lived
when they moved to Paris in 1921, up the hill from the Sorbonne in
rue du Cardinal-Lemoine.
</P>
<P>
   You can read about it in the opening scene of Hemingway's
memoir, ``A Moveable Feast,'' or on the plaque on the building,
erected jointly by the Hemingway Society and the F. Scott
Fitzgerald Society.
</P>
<P>
   But that's not the first Hemingway home that Noel Riley Fitch
was acquainted with.
</P>
<P>
   ``I grew up in Idaho. My family camped out in the Sawtooth
Mountains. On the way, we would pass by Hemingway's house in
Ketchum. That was in the 1950s.''
</P>
<P>
   I had to ask. ``But you never stopped.''
</P>
<P>
   ``No,'' she said, shaking her head, ``and he was probably at
home.''
</P>
<P>
   (Joe Murray, editor-publisher emeritus of the Lufkin Daily News,
is senior writer for Cox Newspapers. Address: P.O. Box 151108,
Lufkin, Texas, 75904; e-mail, jmurray(at)lcc.net.)
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
