<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-15 14:20 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1290 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TEACHING-HOSPITALS-$A     07-15 1077
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEACHING-HOSPITALS-$ADV18-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HILLARY CAMPAIGN PUTS SPOTLIGHT ON PLIGHT OF TEACHING HOSPITALS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For release Sunday, July 18)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By DAN FREEDMAN  
 c.1999 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ With a boost from First Lady Hillary Rodham
Clinton, the plight of the nation's 400 teaching hospitals is
becoming a hot-button issue not only in her New York campaign for
the Senate but also in Congress as lawmakers debate the future of
Medicare.
</P>
<P>
   In her ``listening tour'' of the Empire State, Clinton has heard
many complaints about how lawmakers' past cuts in Medicare are
starving the hospitals, which hone the skills of interns and
resident doctors in treating the sick.
</P>
<P>
   Picking up the beat, Clinton is calling the medical
college-affiliated hospitals the ``the crown jewels'' of the state
and saying that teaching hospitals everywhere ``are a particular
concern, and should be to a concern to everyone who cares about
health care.''
</P>
<P>
   Such hospitals are all over the country. New York has 49, 28 of
them in New York City alone. California has 26, four of them in San
Francisco. Texas has 17.
</P>
<P>
   The issue of funding these hospitals is another early test of
how independent of her husband Mrs. Clinton intends to be. She has
already taken more liberal positions on gun control, health
insurance and the status of Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
   Teaching hospital advocates point to the 1997 Balanced Budget
Act, agreed to by President Clinton and the Republican-controlled
Congress, as the main source of their troubles.
</P>
<P>
   The advocates say that when the act stripped $71 billion in
federal reimbursements to all hospitals for treatment of Medicare
patients, teaching hospitals were hurt most because they have a
higher percentage of poor and seriously ill patients.
</P>
<P>
   Bill Clinton's proposal to overhaul Medicare last month would do
little to pump new financial blood into teaching hospitals, these
advocates say. But Hillary Clinton has given them hope.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're very pleased she chose to speak out on this issue,''
said Dr. Jordan Cohen, president of the Association of American
Medical Colleges (AAMC). ``Clearly this is an opportunity for the
country to hear a prominent voice, someone who people can
understand.''
</P>
<P>
   The controversy over teaching hospitals comes at a time of great
uncertainty over Medicare, the 34-year-old medical insurance
program for the elderly that serves about 39 million people. With
the 70-million-member baby boom generation set to begin retiring in
the next decade or so, the system's trustees predict Medicare will
lack sufficient funds to pay all its bills starting in 2015.
</P>
<P>
   As originally conceived by President Lyndon B. Johnson, Medicare
was a pay-as-you-go medical insurance plan as well as an
entitlement that, like its sister, Social Security, would in time
lift many senior citizens out of poverty.
</P>
<P>
   For the first 18 years of its existence Medicare was a boon to
teaching hospitals, which have costs that regular hospitals don't
incur. Besides instructing young doctors and absorbing the costs of
treating sicker and poorer patients, they must pay for
state-of-the-art medical technology.
</P>
<P>
   So teaching hospitals built a portion of these costs into the
bills they sent to Medicare for treating elderly patients. And
through a complicated formula, the federal government paid them.
</P>
<P>
   ``The teaching hospitals argued that training interns and
residents is part of their operating costs, that it's good for
society _ and Congress agreed,'' said Stuart Guterman, a Medicare
expert at the Urban Institute, a Washington think tank.
</P>
<P>
   But as the cost of Medicare skyrocketed through the 1970s and
into the 1980s, Congress looked for ways to economize. In 1983 it
came up with the prospective payment system _ PPS _ whereby
Medicare would pay hospitals a set amount up front for treating
each Medicare patient.
</P>
<P>
   If the hospital's cost per patient was less, then it made money.
If not, the hospital ate the loss.
</P>
<P>
   But Congress also set up a plan to reimburse teaching hospitals
for their special tasks of training doctors and caring for the very
sick and the indigent.
</P>
<P>
   As competition for patients among hospitals stiffened with the
advent of cost-conscious managed care health plans in the early
1990s, the added payments were a lifesaver to teaching hospitals.
In 1997, these payments totaled $9 billion, according to Guterman.
</P>
<P>
   But in forging the 1997 budget agreement, lawmakers were looking
for ways to drastically reduce federal spending, and Medicare
proved a ripe target. In an effort to slow the growth of Medicare
spending, Congress cut into the subsidies provided to teaching
hospitals.
</P>
<P>
   Such funds are slated to decline by 28 percent through 2002,
according to Cohen of the AAMC.
</P>
<P>
   The cuts took effect last year, and Cohen says their impact is
devastating. According to a study for the American Hospital
Association survey, 61 percent of the nation's 5,000 hospitals
(teaching and non-teaching alike) now are paying more for Medicare
patients than they are receiving from Washington.
</P>
<P>
   A study commissioned by the Association of American Medical
Colleges estimates that 40 percent of the nation's teaching
hospitals will be losing money by 2002.
</P>
<P>
   Some Capitol Hill lawmakers are skeptical of the medical
profession's cries of woe. Rep. William Thomas, R-Calif., chairman
of the House Ways and Means subcommittee that oversees Medicare,
says the subsidies should be funded elsewhere in the federal budget
_ where they can scrutinized year by year. Or if they are dropped,
he says, the hospitals should compensate for their loss through
fundraising.
</P>
<P>
   But Cohen insists teaching hospitals are too stretched already
and can be saved only by a recalculation of reimbursement formulas.
``The view that these institutions could absorb cuts is
unfortunate, because our data suggests the opposite,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The medical college association opened a lobbying effort in
April to persuade Congress to change the Medicare formulas so that
some of the money would flow back to teaching hospitals.
</P>
<P>
   And Sen. Patrick Moynihan, D-N.Y., has introduced legislation to
block further cuts and to levy fees on health insurance premiums
that would go into a graduate medical education trust fund that
teaching hospitals could draw on.
</P>
<P>
   (Dan Freedman can be reached at 202-298-6920 and, by e-mail, at
dan(at)hearstdc.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
