<HEADLINE>
EVERY HIKE SHOULD START WITH THE RIGHT TRAIL MIX 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By DOUG BLACKBURN  
 c.1999 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ It doesn't matter if you're taking a day hike,
climbing one of the High Peaks or setting off on a considerably
longer journey. Packing the right trail snacks is as important as
choosing proper footwear.
</P>
<P>
   Just ask Jay ``Diz'' Dizacomo, a licensed New York state guide
from Latham who, when he's not overseeing white water rafting
trips, likes to head for the Appalachian Trail. He has thus far
hiked 1,800 of the historic 2,160-mile trail, from Springer
Mountain, Ga., to Rutland, Vt., and says he might complete the
final stretch later this summer.
</P>
<P>
   ``I ate snacks the entire time I was on the trail,'' said Diz,
who advocates eating early and often when hiking. ``You're going to
be burning a lot of calories when you're out there, and you want to
replenish those calories. You don't want to deplete yourself
water-wise or calorie-wise.''
</P>
<P>
   The best trail snacks, according to Diz, are dried fruit. He has
actually built a dehydrator and prepares his own dried fruit,
eschewing the sugar-laden dried fruit found in most supermarkets.
</P>
<P>
   But it's easy enough to buy unsweetened dried banana and
pineapple and other fruits. Most natural food stores and food
co-ops routinely stock these.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, no backpack is complete without trail mix, usually
referred to as gorp. A combination of nuts, dried fruit, raisins
and chocolate, gorp is as personal as homemade barbecue sauce. Diz,
for instance, prefers to use M&AMP;Ms and Goldfish crackers. Others
won't set out for even a short walk without including sunflower
seeds.
</P>
<P>
   ``The more you make a trail mix, the more you fine-tune it,'' he
explained. ``There is no right or wrong trail mix. Everyone has
their own variation, and a lot of times it depends on what you have
at hand.
</P>
<P>
   ``Power bars and those types of things are good to pack
separately, but Fig Newtons are not too far away from the more
expensive energy bars,'' Diz said. ``You can spend a lot on the
energy bars or you can get a nutritious cookie like a Fig Newton.
</P>
<P>
   ``You want to stay away from things that will melt or get
sticky. You can bring a few candy bars but don't make them a big
staple. If you do bring candy bars, bag them separately in case
they do melt.''
</P>
<P>
   Rose Rivezzi and David Trithart, authors of ``Kids on the Trail!
Hiking with Children in the Adirondacks'' (Adirondack Mountain
Club, 1997), recommend packing foods that will satisfy the
children's hunger and they will like.
</P>
<P>
   And if the kids get cranky, they offer a ``miracle'' cure: ``Our
all-time favorite motivator is the `power pill,' a piece of candy
for times when energy runs low. `It looks like we need some energy,
power pills are coming out at the next big rock.' Off they go to
await the treat. Candy should not be used to alleviate hunger, but
as that little extra we all love.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
