<SLUG> BC-BRAINS-GENDER-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW EVIDENCE THAT SIZE DOESN'T MATTER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ANDREW BROWNSTEIN  
 c.1999 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ Dean Falk's research has put an age-old gender
debate to rest.
</P>
<P>
   Size, she has concluded, doesn't matter.
</P>
<P>
   In a recent issue of the Journal of Human Evolution, she
outlined her findings that men's brains are larger on average than
women's, but that the discrepancy has no bearing on general
intelligence.
</P>
<P>
   For Falk, a world-renowned paleoanthropologist, the discovery
meant overcoming politically correct views in her field that kept
the issue on the academic sidelines.
</P>
<P>
   ``The fear is well motivated,'' she said. ``People have misused
data on sex and race to form prejudices. But I'm interested in
knowing the truth. If I want to know something, I go after it.''
</P>
<P>
   Falk's research grew out of a 1996 graduate seminar at the State
University of New York at Albany. One of her students, Nicholee
Froese, wanted to delve into the hotly contested area of brain size
differences between the sexes. Science showed that on average,
men's brains are 10 percent larger than women's. The consensus was
that this was due to men's generally larger body size.
</P>
<P>
   But what if men and women were the same size? Would their brains
be the same size, too? Scientific opinion was split.
</P>
<P>
   To Falk's surprise, Froese discovered that even when controlled
for body size, men's brains are larger by eight percent.
</P>
<P>
   ``Once I recovered, I wanted to know why,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   A survey of rhesus monkeys found similar results, suggesting
that whatever accounted for male's larger brains was not a trait
unique to humans _ like reasoning, intellectual curiosity or
well-developed language.
</P>
<P>
   From rhesus monkeys, she turned to small rodents. An earlier
study showed that polygamous male voles performed better in mazes
than their female counterparts.
</P>
<P>
   But in gibbon societies, where the males are monogamous and the
females are roughly the same size, there is no difference in the
weight of the brain.
</P>
<P>
   Putting all of these factors _ brain size, gender, and polygamy
_ together, Falk arrived at an intriguing hypothesis: The larger
size of the male brain stemmed from the ancient necessity of
propagating the species; males needed bigger brains in order to
wander to different mates. From philandering rodents, she
speculates, arose the ability for men to score higher on the
spacial-visual portions of IQ tests.
</P>
<P>
   ``My impression of that other species I sometimes drive to work
with is that they don't have to ask for directions,'' Falk said.
``Men have an intuitive sense of where they're going. I want to
know I have to go up 3 blocks, stop at the stoplight, make a left
and so on.''
</P>
<P>
   Though she acknowledges that spatial relations play a role in
intelligence, she balks at the idea that a bigger brain makes men
smarter. Intelligence entails a whole range of factors including
verbal and written skills, she said.
</P>
<P>
   At a recent conference in Salt Lake City, Falk dramatically made
her point with two slides. The first showed an early computer _ one
of the huge, lumbering machines that could occupy an entire room.
The other was a sleek, modern-day laptop underneath a woman's foot.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you're going to do heavy-duty computing, which would you
rather use?'' she asked the audience.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-15-99 1423EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
