<DOCNO> NYT19990715.0172 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-15 14:24 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1299 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-EVOLUTION-THEORY-HNS &LR;      07-15 1074
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EVOLUTION-THEORY-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FINDINGS RAISE RUCKUS OVER HUMAN ORIGINS 
</HEADLINE>
   (ATTN: Missouri, Ohio; note optional trim)  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ANDREW BROWNSTEIN  
 c.1999 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ Using modern medical techniques to re-construct
ancient fossils, a researcher has made a discovery she claims will
dramatically alter the way science views human evolution.
</P>
<P>
   The long-accepted theory is that the genus homo appeared roughly
two million years ago in Africa.
</P>
<P>
   Dean Falk, a paleoanthropologist at the State University of New
York at Albany, has rattled the bones of controversy with her
findings that homo _ including home sapiens, the scientific name
for modern human beings _ may have stemmed directly from an early
ancestor, Australopithecus africanus.
</P>
<P>
   In this scenario, the tiny australopithecines were already
showing human traits in their chimp-sized brains and evolved slowly
into homo over the course of three million years.
</P>
<P>
   If proven, Falk's theories would also deal a blow to ``Lucy,''
the 3-million-year-old pre-human fossil that was hailed as the
mother of humankind following its discovery in Ethiopia in 1974. In
the revisionist view, Lucy (Australopithecus afarensis) becomes an
evolutionary dead-end.
</P>
<P>
   The findings put Falk in the middle of one of the most heated
pursuits of the 20th century: the search for humankind's ancestors.
The so-called ``missing link'' between humans and the apes ranks
with splitting the atom as one of the great prizes of science.
</P>
<P>
   ``The field of paleoanthropology is notoriously contentious,''
said P.V. Tobias, a retired professor at Witwatersrand Medical
School in Johannesburg, South Africa, one of the world's leading
authorities on prehuman fossils.
</P>
<P>
   ``We feel threatened by studies that impinge on our own,'' he
said. ``When it comes to those that are close to humans, and
particularly the minds of such specimens, I think there is a
tendency for scientists to have an enormous emotional investment in
their findings.''
</P>
<P>
   With so much at stake, scholarship can turn ugly.
</P>
<P>
   At a recent conference in Columbus, Ohio, where Falk outlined
her findings, a rival anthropologist ended a talk critical of her
work by showing two slides: One was a milkmaid pouring milk; the
other showed a witch dripping poison into an upside-down skull. The
professor then asked the audience which one they trusted. To many
present, he seemed to be asking, ``Which one is Dean Falk?''
</P>
<P>
   She and a team of six co-authors are trying to have a lengthy
article on their findings published in the Journal of Human
Evolution. ``I have never in my years encountered so much
resistance,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Falk, 55, is best known as the author of the 1992
``Braindance,'' a popular treatment of her ``radiator'' theory of
brain evolution. She contends that the brains of our ancestors grew
as they began to stand erect and develop cranial veins that cooled
the brain. Those blood vessels control brain temperature much in
the same way a radiator cools a car engine, allowing for higher
cognitive functions.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The current debate began last summer, when she was asked by the
journal Science to comment on a paper by Glen Conroy, a professor
of anthropology at the Washington University School of Medicine in
St. Louis. Using a CAT scanner, Conroy made 3-D images of the skull
capacity of a 2.8-million-year-old hominid.
</P>
<P>
   The results were troubling. The skull was one of the largest
examples of Australopithecus africanus in existence; yet its brain
size was less than other specimens with much smaller skulls.
</P>
<P>
   ``It got me thinking that many of the brain reconstructions,
which were mostly done in the 1970s without the benefit of recent
finds and better technology, were wrong,'' Conroy said.
</P>
<P>
   For the past year, he and Falk have been re-measuring the brains
of a host of the most precious ancient fossils. Falk and
SUNY-Albany graduate student John Guyer use brain endocasts made of
plaster and silicon; Conroy makes sophisticated virtual images
generated by computer.
</P>
<P>
   Their findings are twofold. First, they claim that
Australopithecus robustus, long thought to be an evolutionary
cousin to homo, has a small brain _ similar in size to africanus.
But there the similarities end. While the robust brains were pointy
and beak-shaped like those of modern apes, Falk believes the
africanus samples show the early signs of human brain features such
as those used for abstract planning and naming.
</P>
<P>
   The differences between the robust and africanus brains were so
stark, Falk said, that a group of bystanders in her building were
able to correctly separate a dozen specimens into two distinct
piles.
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, the findings raised eyebrows among anthropologists
who question whether human traits can be found in a fossil so old.
They also complain about the limited number of africanus samples
and the incompleteness of those that do exist in museum and
university collections around the world.
</P>
<P>
   Not surprisingly, the most vociferous critic is the one who made
some of the original measurements Falk and Conroy are challenging.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was flabbergasted at some of the calculations,'' said Ralph
Holloway of Columbia University. ``They were much less than what I
had come up with.''
</P>
<P>
   Holloway felt attacked by Falk for comments she made to The New
York Times attributing the earlier measurements to ``unconscious
bias on the part of various investigators.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The implication seems to be that I artificially inflated the
numbers to make them look closer to human beings,'' he said. He
unabashedly owned up to making the offending slide presentation in
at the conference in Columbus, claiming that Falk had
misrepresented his work.
</P>
<P>
   Others traced it to their professional rivalry. ``This is a
long-standing clash of arms between two very fine scholars,''
Tobias said.
</P>
<P>
   Tobias said he is ``overjoyed'' at new evidence linking
africanus to humans _ other factors being their canine teeth and
use of stone tools.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Falk eagerly awaits the publication of her research,
funded with a $20,000 grant from the National Science Foundation.
It will undoubtedly be met with a fresh wave of controversy.
</P>
<P>
   ``The whole field has been controversial for most of the
century,'' Holloway said. ``Thank goodness. It's given us all
jobs.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
