<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FOG-HORNS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOG HORNS PLAY A SYMPHONY BY THE BAY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By HAL WESTON  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Sailors once listened intently to the basso
chorus of the San Francisco Bay's fog horns to find their way.
Today, with global positioning satellite systems (GPS) on board,
mariners look at blips on a screen to find their precise location
on a shifting sea.
</P>
<P>
   Those of us on shore listen to the fog horns for the echoes of
San Francisco's past, sonic ghosts we perceive only when all is
obscured. Once there were 91 fog horns in the Bay; now only 31
remain, of which 18 are in or near San Francisco. Fog horns on land
and bridges, and bells and clappers on buoys make the racket of the
Bay. These aids to navigation help ships find their way through
channels and around rocks, bridges and the shore.
</P>
<P>
   There are two horns on Alcatraz, ``The Rock'' (one on the north
side and one on the south), two on the Golden Gate Bridge (at
mid-span and on the south tower), several on the Oakland Bay Bridge
towers and one at Point Bonita, at the Bay's entrance. Other
navigation aids include lights on shore (such as lighthouses) and
on buoys, and radar reflecting buoys, called RACON, that identify
themselves on a ship's radar screen.
</P>
<P>
   The big ships rely on GPS and radar in bad weather, but still
use fog horns and other reliable old aids as backup, says Pete
Sturges, a former second officer in the merchant marine and now a
lawyer in San Francisco. If the electronic navigation system goes
out, the captain will stop the ship and the watchman will ``get out
on deck and identify all the fog horns and ship's whistles you can
hear _ right away,'' he said. Smaller ships without sophisticated
navigation equipment are more dependent on the horns and lights.
</P>
<P>
   The old horns were diaphones, which made two tones _ a long
sound followed by a sort of grunt that could be heard five to 12
miles away, according to Colin McKenzie of the Nautical Research
Center in Petaluma. The horn on the Golden Gate Bridge at midspan
is one of the remaining diaphones.
</P>
<P>
   Almost all the horns now are electronic and have one pitch that
travels only about a mile.
</P>
<P>
   For sailors, the horns are aids. But for those of us on land,
the horns can be a sort of music _ an orderly cacophony at night,
sounding most raucously at 4 in the morning when the fog settles
around the shore.
</P>
<P>
   Each horn enters when the downbeat of the fog triggers its
sensor; each horn repeats its slow, bleeping canon until the fog
lifts. The horns around the San Francisco shore usually wail until
sunrise, like exhausted late-night blues players. Those on the
Golden Gate Bridge and Alcatraz may moan in the mist, day and
night, during the foggy season.
</P>
<P>
   The Coast Guard's light list shows the location of navigation
aids, including the horns, with the pattern of sound and silence
for each horn. For example, the horn on the south tower of the
Golden Gate Bridge has a 2-second blast followed by 18 seconds of
silence.
</P>
<P>
   As for the pitches of the horns, no one seems to know the score.
No one at the Maritime Library nor McKenzie knew the pitches. The
San Francisco Almanac lists a few, and R. Wiley Evans, a local
composer, identified some for a piece he wrote.
</P>
<P>
   The Coast Guard doesn't list any because the Coast Guard doesn't
know. (Perhaps it's time to call in the Marines; their band plays
at the White House.) The old diaphones were mostly in the keys of F
and C. Music students will recognize this as tonic and dominant.
Probably a coincidence, but a nice touch: As the dominant resolves
to the tonic at the end of a phrase, so did the sounds of the horns
end a journey.
</P>
<P>
   The horns today don't seem to have any such tonal relationship,
which may reflect our modern society. A, G and C seem the most
prevalent _ a harmonic relationship (an A minor seventh) that
doesn't settle anything. The pitches may vary a little depending on
where you're standing and the way the fog is blowing. In all, it's
a band that can't toot straight. The most interesting fog horn is
Alcatraz South, which sounds like an Andrew Lloyd Webber chord.
You'll hear it as a C but it's probably an A minor chord in the
first inversion.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;
</P>
<P>
   (Hal Weston lives in San Francisco. He studied piano as a
child.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
