<HEADLINE>
CITY QUESTIONS POSSIBLE SALE OF SAN FRANCISCO CHRONICLE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By GREGORY LEWIS  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ A committee of the Board of Supervisors wants to
find out how the city can help preserve San Francisco's two daily
newspapers.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to protect the free flow of ideas,'' said Board of
Supervisors President Tom Ammiano. ``In a one-newspaper town, we'd
be beholden to monopolistic influences rather than democratic
influences.''
</P>
<P>
   The Finance and Labor Committee directed the city attorney's
office to examine the potential anti-trust implications of the
expected sale of the 134-year-old San Francisco Chronicle.
</P>
<P>
   Chronicle Publishing Co.'s board of directors announced last
month that its media properties would be sold. The privately-held
company is owned by descendants of Chronicle founder Michael H. de
Young.
</P>
<P>
   The company owns three newspapers, the Chronicle, the
Bloomington Pantagraph in Illinois and the Worcester Telegram and
Gazette in Massachusetts; three television stations, KRON in San
Francisco, KAKE in Wichita, Kan., and WOWT in Omaha, Neb.; a cable
television station; two book publishing companies; and an on-line
information service. The company employs 3,200 people nationwide.
</P>
<P>
   Donaldson, Lufkin &AMP; Jenrette, a New York investment firm
managing the sale, has presented the company's board with a list of
prospective suitors for the Chronicle, including the Hearst Corp.,
owner of the San Francisco Examiner, the city's afternoon
newspaper.
</P>
<P>
   Since 1965, the Chronicle and Examiner have shared all business
costs and split revenues while maintaining separate editorial
operations, under a joint operating agreement commonly referred to
as a JOA.
</P>
<P>
   The legal underpinning of the JOA was articulated in a
subsequent federal law, the Newspaper Preservation Act, which
provides exemptions to anti-trust law when the purpose of such
business arrangements is to preserve and foster editorial diversity
in cities.
</P>
<P>
   The JOA gives Hearst the first shot at buying the Chronicle.
</P>
<P>
   At the city hearing, nine speakers, including two representing
newspaper unions, argued that a sale of the Chronicle to the Hearst
Corp. would ``mean virtually, certainly, San Francisco will be a
one-newspaper city,'' said syndicated columnist and author Norman
Solomon.
</P>
<P>
   Solomon bemoaned that no public outcry had arisen to save the
Chronicle and the Examiner as separate papers, as had happened in
the early 1990s when the San Francisco Giants baseball team seemed
certain to be sold and moved to St. Petersburg, Fla.
</P>
<P>
   Steven Barnett, a law professor at the University of California
at Berkeley and a specialist in anti-trust law, said the city
should prepare a lawsuit to head off the shutdown of one of the
newspapers. Barnett also urged the city demand to be notified
immediately if there are plans to close one of the newspapers and
require, instead, that the owners search for a new buyer rather
than close.
</P>
<P>
   Supervisor Mark Leno said he was concerned about the importance
of two editorial voices and the potential loss of jobs that had
been seen in other cities after newspaper sales.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-15-99 1427EDT &QL; 
