<HEADLINE>
$ADV26 
 INSIDE TREK &AMP; SCI-FI 
 TALL ORDER: `IRON GIANT' AND THE NEW FACE OF ANIMATION 
</HEADLINE>
  (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or by fax at 732-390-4697.) 
 (She also has information on how to subscribe to Inside Trek, a
weekly science-fiction column with color and black-and-white art.)
 (Includes a color slide and a black-and-white photo of a scene from
``The iron Giant.'') 
 By IAN SPELLING  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
 &HT;    Coming from nowhere with incredibly positive buzz, but with no
toys, bed sheets or Happy Meals to boost awareness, ``The Iron
Giant'' just might conquer the planet anyway, when it stomps into
theaters on Aug. 4.
 &HT;    ``I wish we had a few more tie-ins than we have,'' says Brad
Bird, who directed the animated adventure about a 9-year-old boy
(Eli Marienthal) and his new pal, a 50-foot robot (Vin Diesel).
``On the other hand, I think it's wonderful to sneak up on people.
 &HT;    ``So many things are overhyped these days. Hopefully, we'll cut
through all of that and get people to see us.
 &HT;    ``If we can just get people into the theaters and into the
seats, I think they'll be happy.''
 &HT;    Audiences that give ``Iron Giant'' a shot may be in for a
surprise. The PG-rated film delivers its share of intense moments
and a few mild swear words, and its story _ the boy tries to hide
the robot from the increasingly fearful denizens of Rockwell, Maine
_ unfolds at an unhurried pace.
 &HT;    Bird suggests that kids as young as 6 can handle the action, and
he promises that parents won't be bored to tears.
 &HT;    ``My goal was to make it more adult-friendly than animation
usually is,'' he says by telephone from his production office in
Burbank, Calif. ``Too often it's been defined by lowbrow humor and
not more intelligent and sophisticated storytelling.
 &HT;    ``I've been saying for years that I think there's a larger
audience for animation than is currently being served.''
 &HT;    Bird pauses to gather his thoughts. When he speaks again, he
does so in a serious tone.
 &HT;    ``My career in animation has been a ``Sophie's Choice'' between
fresh material and great execution,'' says the Montana-born Bird,
who was mentored by Disney animation legend Milt Kahl and toiled on
``King of the Hill'' and nearly 200 episodes of ``The Simpsons.''
 &HT;    ``In other words, if you get to do a high quality of work and
refined animation, you usually have to take a pretty worn-out story
and put five Broadway tunes to it, and, if you're going to do
something that's different and new, you have to do it for $1.98 and
in two hours.
 &HT;    ``One of the many pleasures on this film has been being able to
do something a little bit different and being able to do it on a
high-quality level,'' Bird says. ``Warner Brothers gave us an
unusual amount of freedom on this.
 &HT;    ``That's very rare in Hollywood, especially in feature
animation, which tends to be micromanaged. Once Warners was
convinced that we'd make `Iron Giant' responsibly and come in on
time and on budget, they gave us a lot of leeway.
 &HT;    ``If the film is special, that's one of the primary reasons.
They truly let us make our movie.''
 &HT;    Fair enough. But now to the big Bird question: What precisely
does the director of an animated film do?
 &HT;    ``You're really doing exactly the same thing that you'd do on a
live-action film,'' says Bird, who plans to take a long rest after
``Iron Giant'' opens. ``It's just that the methods for doing it are
a little bit different.
 &HT;    ``You're still directing performances, first of the vocal actors
(which include Jennifer Aniston, Harry Connick, Jr., John Mahoney
and Cloris Leachman) and then of the animators. I suppose that it's
different in that the duties are broken up more, meaning that the
vocal is only the start of the performance.
 &HT;    ``You then direct the animators through the visual aspects of
the performance. But you're still dealing with timing, cutting,
camera angles, rhythm and the balance between comedy and drama.
You're still dealing with questions like, `Do we know who this
character is?' and `Are these scenes playing well?'''
 &HT;    Do we? Are they?
 &HT;    ``Oh, we have a few shots here and there that I'd love to tweak,
but I think we did remarkably well,'' Bird says. ``There are always
things you want to tweak, but I'll be just as glad to see it in a
theater as I hope the eventual audience for it will be.'' 
 -0- 
 NEXT WEEK  
 &HT;    Frank Oz, director, muppeteer and the man behind Yoda, talks
about ``Star Wars: The Phantom Menace.''
 SIDEBAR: CONVENTION CALENDAR  
 &HT;    August 7: Creation Convention at the Masonic Center in San
Francisco, Calif., featuring Brent Spiner, Grace Lee Whitney and
Kenny Baker. For information, call (818) 409-0960.
 -0- 
 c.1999 Ian Spelling  
