<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-15 14:54 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1335 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOOK-NOTES16-COX     07-15 0659
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOK-NOTES16-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Women follow male author into minds of men
 &HT;    By Don O'Briant
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Some have referred to Eric Jerome Dickey as ``a male Terry
McMillan,'' but the former computer programmer and stand-up comic
has a style all his own.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, he explores some of the same territory as McMillan, but
Dickey writes about relationships between young black professionals
with a generous helping of humor and a distinctly male viewpoint.
</P>
<P>
   ``No one ever cries `victim' in my books,'' says Dickey, a
Memphis native who turned to writing after he was downsized out of
the aerospace industry.
</P>
<P>
   After taking writing classes at UCLA, Dickey sold his first
novel, ``Sister, Sister,'' in 1996. The story of three young black
women in Los Angeles quickly soared to the top of the Blackboard
Bestsellers List in Essence magazine. He followed ``Sister,
Sister'' a year later with ``Friends and Lovers,'' a comedic story
of two couples' roller coaster relationships. Then, in 1998, he
dealt with the problems of interracial dating in ``Milk in My
Coffee.'' Both were best sellers, and Whitney Houston optioned
``Friends and Lovers'' for a feature film.
</P>
<P>
   Now on tour for his new novel, ``Cheaters'' (Dutton, $24.95),
Dickey has attracted a loyal following of women readers.
</P>
<P>
   ``They say they like my books because they help them understand
men better,'' he says. ``There are some women who say they can
write about men characters better than male writers, who think they
know what guys think. Any guy who reads their books will tell them,
`I don't think so.' We feel things, just like women. We just don't
articulate it as well.''
</P>
<P>
   Dickey will sign his books from 6:30 to 8 p.m. today at Shrine
of the Black Madonna, 946 Abernathy Blvd., 404-752-6125, and from 6
to 7:30 p.m. Friday at Medu Bookstore, 2841 Greenbriar Parkway,
404-346-3263.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Literary gossip: Before they were published authors, Margaret
Mitchell and Frances Newman were gossip columnists for The Atlanta
Journal Magazine. In a fascinating article in the spring/summer
issue of The Southern Quarterly literary magazine, Lithonia writer
Reginald Abbott explores Newman's influence on Mitchell's career.
Both wrote a series of conversational anecdotes under the pseudonym
of Elizabeth Bennet _ taken from a Jane Austen heroine. There
apparently was little gossip _ mainly accounts of who wore what to
which party. According to Abbott, some observers believe Newman's
scandalous success with ``The Hard-Boiled Virgin'' in 1926 goaded
Mitchell into writing ``Gone With the Wind.''
</P>
<P>
   Also featured in this issue are articles on novelist Kate Chopin
(``The Awakening'') and Georgia State University professor, poet
and novelist David Bottoms (``Easter Weekend'').
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Tangled web: Seventeen-year-old author Katie Tarbox has sold
her first book, ``Girl.com,'' to Dutton after a three-day auction.
The book is a true account of Tarbox's experiences as the target of
a stalker who pursued her through Internet chat rooms. She was 13
when it began. The man ultimately was prosecuted for sexual
harassment of a minor.
</P>
<P>
   Tarbox's agent, Laurie Chittenden, told Publishers Weekly the
story is a cautionary tale about the dangers of the Internet.
``It's something many young girls can identify with, a search for
someone who understands them and gives them affection, but it can
also lead them into some dark, scary places.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Girl.com'' will be published next spring.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  More L'Amour: Author Louis L'Amour is dead, but that doesn't
keep him from making the best-seller lists. ``Beyond the Great Snow
Mountains'' (Bantam, $16.95), a collection of 10 stories first
published in magazines in the 1940s and '50s, is in its fourth
printing with 260,000 copies.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  E-mail: dobriant(at)ajc.com
</P>
<P>
   Don O'Briant writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
