<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-15 14:54 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1336 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOOKS-SUMMER18-COX     07-15 1161
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOKS-SUMMER18-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Summer reading: New nonfiction of note
 &HT;    Eds: Embargoed for Sunday, July 18.
 &HT;    By Shane Harrison
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QR;  Moab Is My Washpot by Stephen Fry (Random House, $24).
</P>
<P>
   Writing an autobiography requires a certain amount of ego, and
many take the occasion to make themselves pitiable, persecuted or
larger than life. Actor-comedian-writer Stephen Fry certainly
possesses the necessary ego, but he's never less than painfully
honest. When describing his theft of money from a friend's
grandmother, Fry calls it a ``shameful act.'' ``There are few
crimes lower,'' he continues, in obvious distress, ``and nothing I
write in this paragraph will mitigate, deaden or palliate the pain
and fury it must have caused that family.''
</P>
<P>
   Most of the book takes a more lighthearted approach. He turns an
often caustic wit on his life, chuckling at adolescent angst from
the perspective of midlife. Readers of his first novel, ``The
Liar,'' will recognize large chunks of this book. His debut novel
was transparently autobiographical, but truth is not only stranger
than fiction, it's also more poignant.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  The Invisible Stranger: The Patten, Maine, Photographs of
Arturo Patten by Russell Banks and Arturo Patten (Harper Collins,
$32.50).
</P>
<P>
   Before his death in March, photographer Arturo Patten captured
these 37 remarkable portraits of the folks who live in Patten,
Maine. These haunting images have a radiant quality, each
containing enough character to fill a novel. Novelist Banks
(``Cloudsplitter,'' ``Affliction,'' ``The Sweet Hereafter'')
surrounded himself with these images in his Adirondack cabin and
recorded his impressions. His style is a perfect fit _ these people
could have sprung directly from the pages of one of Banks' novels.
The people of the northern reaches of our country, Banks writes,
``squeezed between the vast Canadian Arctic and the more temperate,
densely populated tier of American states below, are shaped by the
same strict forces as the land, and thus in many ways they have
come to resemble it. They are tough, unyielding and stoical.'' It
is a testament to Patten's artistry that these words, though a
welcome addition, are not even necessary. The photographs convey it
all.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  The Nudist on the Late Shift by Po Bronson (Random House,
$25).
</P>
<P>
   Po knows Silicon Valley. Novelist and Wired magazine writer
Bronson (``The First $20 Million Is Always the Hardest'') has spent
several years investigating the inner workings of the technology
business in California's Silicon Valley. Entrepreneurs,
programmers, venture capitalists and salespeople feed Bronson's
inexhaustible quest for knowledge. He gets at the heart of a
business that too often gives the impression that it doesn't have
one, finding the soul beneath the cold technology and ruthless
deal-making. Bronson's vivid description of the home of programmers
Kevin Hester and Mark ``Max'' Maxham, dubbed ``Geekhaus,'' is
typical of his smart, observant style: ``Every bedroom of the house
looks to have been decorated by an earthquake: clothes, books,
sporting goods strewn on the floor,'' Bronson writes. ``The
occupants seem not quite to have gotten the concept that certain
things, such as artworks, may be hung from the walls rather than
just leaned against them.''
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  The View From Babylon: The Notes of a Hollywood Voyeur by
Donald Rawley (Warner Books, $23).
</P>
<P>
   The late Donald Rawley, author of ``The Night Bird Cantata'' and
a former editor at Los Angeles' Buzz magazine, takes aim at a
rather easy target: the denizens of Hollywood. It's a shallow place
where, Rawley writes, ``world poverty and racism are meaningless,
but the fluctuation in real estate values is not.'' His pithy,
no-nonsense tone strikes just the right balance of world-weariness
and stinging sarcasm. He skewers celebrities and studio honchos,
sometimes in thinly veiled references to Oscar-winning actresses,
but often simply naming names. Were he still alive, Rawley, like
fellow Hollywood observer Julia Phillips, would probably never eat
lunch in that town again.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  QUICK HITS: Detroit music critic Dan Sicko's ``Techno Rebels:
The Renegades of Electronic Funk'' (Billboard Books, $16.95
paperback) is an excellent American answer to last year's
``Generation Ecstasy,'' Simon Reynolds' Anglo-centric look at dance
music and culture. Sicko is based in Detroit, the birthplace of
techno, the precursor to every dance music genre emanating from DJ
booths and radios today. ...
</P>
<P>
   ``The Embrace: A True Vampire Story'' (Pocket Books, $23) by
journalist Aphrodite Jones (``The FBI Killer'') investigates black
magic and Satanism among a group of bored, disenfranchised
teenagers, including 16-year-old Roderick Farrell. The
self-proclaimed leader of a vampire cult is on death row for the
bludgeoning death of a rural Florida couple. ...
</P>
<P>
   Bill Gates doesn't fare very well in the new ``South Park''
movie, and he takes even more knocks in a couple of new books.
``How the Web Was Won: The Inside Story of How Bill Gates and his
Band of Internet Idealists Transformed a Software Empire''
(Broadway, $27.50) by Paul Andrews and Gary Rivlin's ``The Plot to
Get Bill Gates'' (Times Books, $25) prove that the rabble on the
information highway is still looking to make roadkill out of the
power elite. ...
</P>
<P>
   ``All the Daring of the
</P>
<P>
   Soldier: Women of the Civil War Armies'' (Norton, $27.95) by
Colby College, Maine, professor Elizabeth D. Leonard adds important
and fascinating information to Civil War scholarship. Leonard's
research indicates that many women disguised themselves as men to
serve on the battlefields, while others did duty as spies. She
spins engaging tales of valor, patriotism and dedication through
letters and contemporary accounts. ...
</P>
<P>
   Susan Bordo casts a feminine eye on ``The Male Body'' (Farrar,
Straus &AMP; Giroux, $25) with her penetrating examination of all
things physically masculine. It's a frank and very personal tour
that takes in the author's relationships with the opposite sex. ...
</P>
<P>
   Leslie Stainton delves into the conflicted, peripatetic life of
Spanish playwright and poet Federico Garcia Lorca in ``Lorca: A
Dream of Life'' (Farrar, Straus &AMP; Giroux, $35). From his birth in
1898 in Andalusian Spain to his death at the hands of Franco
supporters in 1936, Stainton's meticulous research and skilled
writing draw a thrilling portrait of a fascinating life. ...
</P>
<P>
   In ``Forever England'' (Carroll &AMP; Graf, $22), lauded British
novelist Beryl Bainbridge examines her country's great North/South
divide. Through interviews with three families from England's
industrial North and three from the agricultural South, Bainbridge
reveals the facts and myths that have divided the regions, and
searches for what binds them together.
</P>
<P>
   Shane Harrison writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
