<HEADER>
A1339 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SCARY-MOVIES18-COX     07-15 1979
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCARY-MOVIES18-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    In the spirit of genuine psychological horror, two films
heighten Hollywood's chill factor
 &HT;    Eds: Embargoed for Sunday July 18.
 &HT;    By Bob Longino
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Terror is playing mind games at the movies this summer.
</P>
<P>
   There's a distinct absence of teen slasher films on the big
screen. You know, the blade-wielding craziness of the ``Scream''
flicks, the ever-stalking bogeyman of ``I Still Know What You Did
Last Summer,'' the bloodletting ferocity of ``Urban Legend.''
</P>
<P>
   Fresh-meat horror is taking a holiday. And in its place comes
psychological trepidation _ terrible things that go bump in the
night, unseen or mere glimpses of monsters, panic, disorientation
and primal fears moviegoers likely haven't felt in years.
</P>
<P>
   Hollywood's latest horror is a return to the spine-tingling
suspense of Alfred Hitchcock, the eerie shadows of ``Nosferatu''
and the wicked, wondrous mind manipulations in the first half of
``The Exorcist.''
</P>
<P>
   Already playing at the Tara in Atlanta is ``The Blair Witch
Project,'' a chilling, seat-of-the-pants ``mockumentary'' about
three young filmmakers terrorized while documenting a centuries-old
horror tale.
</P>
<P>
   And coming Friday is ``The Haunting,'' a remake of Robert Wise's
1963 creepy thriller directed by Jan De Bont (``Speed,''
``Twister''). Based on Shirley Jackson's story, the new
``Haunting'' is the tale of a group of insomniacs enticed by a
scientist (Liam Neeson) to unwittingly spend freaked-out nights in
a mansion that turns out to be haunted.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a refreshing change to be completely scared, and it come
from something other than somebody with a knife slashing people,''
says Atlanta moviegoer Phil Dutra, 33, who saw ``Blair Witch'' at a
recent early screening.
</P>
<P>
   Molly Baroco, 27, of Atlanta has also seen ``Blair Witch'' and
can't seem to stop talking about it to her friends.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know if I necessarily believed the whole premise of
the movie, but I bought it,'' she says. ``I thought it was really
scary. We walked out of the theater, and we were all weak-kneed.
The psychological stuff is what scares the hell out of me.''
</P>
<P>
   Made for a mere $20,000 by a
</P>
<P>
   quintet of University of Central Florida graduates and
distributed by Artisan Entertainment, ``Blair Witch'' is likely the
freshest approach to the horror genre in decades.
</P>
<P>
   It stars three unknown actors as a trio of young filmmakers
making a documentary for a college class project about horrific
tales of child murders, curses, disembowelments and ghost
sightings, stemming from a 1785 witchcraft case in the Maryland
township of Blair.
</P>
<P>
   Its unique turn is that while ``Blair Witch'' is fiction, it is
presented to moviegoers as fact. The three on-screen filmmakers
vanish in the Maryland woods in the midst of making their
documentary. And what audiences see is their found film, displayed
in real time with all its raw graininess, blurry visions and weird
sounds recorded from the moment they set out to begin filming until
their mysterious disappearance.
</P>
<P>
   It's like MTV's ``The Real World'' meets ``Let's Scare Jessica
to Death.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We wanted to create a very realistic movie that transports you
into an incredibly real world,'' says ``Blair Witch'' producer
Robin Cowie, 27, a graduate of Cobb County's (Ga.) Walton High
School and one of the film's five creative partners. ``What is
really unique about the movie is that it takes the trappings of
low-budget filmmaking and makes them a part of the story.''
</P>
<P>
   All the film's footage and sound recordings were made by the
actors _ Heather Donahue, Joshua Leonard and Michael Williams;
their real names are also the names of their ``Blair Witch''
characters.
</P>
<P>
   They were sent into the forests of Seneca Creek State Park in
Maryland for eight days with a 16mm camera, a video camera, sound
equipment, camping gear and a mere outline of the movie and told to
improvise their search for the witch story.
</P>
<P>
   Waiting in the woods were the ``Blair Witch'' creators,
including co-directors/writers Dan Myrick and Eduardo Sanchez and
producer Gregg Hale. Dressed in camouflage and armed with
night-vision goggles, they orchestrated the actors' march through
terror, leaving script notes under orange flags, rousing them with
middle-of-the-night spook invasions and, ultimately, lowering the
group's food rations to heighten their psychological breakdowns.
</P>
<P>
   ``The idea kind of came from a combination of Dan and Ed wanting
this hyperrealism and Gregg having spent some time in military
intelligence,'' Cowie says. ``One of the things Gregg did while in
Special Forces was prisoner-of-war camp. Participants would be
blindfolded and led through the woods, and they'd do everything to
them but kill them. They'd wig 'em out. Gregg thought even though
(our actors) would know it's not real, they'd end up being
petrified.''
</P>
<P>
   One of the movie's key scenes involves a late-night taped
confession by a wildly frightened Heather, the on-screen trio's
leader. ``I just want to apologize to Mike's mom and Josh's mom and
my mom,'' she wheezes while shaking and staring wide-eyed into a
video camera, a single tear hanging just under her right eye.
``Because it is my fault. Because it was my project. I am ... so
... scared.''
</P>
<P>
   Many who've watched ``Blair Witch'' like what they see. Pulitzer
Prize-winning film critic Roger Eber is a fan. The movie was a
late-night thriller at the recent Sundance Film Festival, and it
won the Prix de La Jeunesse (Youth Prize) at Cannes in May.
</P>
<P>
   The film ``appears to be the next evolutionary step (in horror),
not in the same spirit as `Night of the Living Dead,' but really,
in reverse and to the left,'' says Greg Dean Schmitz of the
Internet's upcomingmovies.com. ``Though both films seem to be based
in the horror of the real ... `The Blair Witch Project' is said to
utilize the sense of danger and threat more than any
special-effects intensive bogeyman thrills.''
</P>
<P>
   The movie's creators say they were influenced by such unsettling
films as ``The Exorcist'' and ``The Legend of Boggy Creek'' and,
especially, old TV shows such as ``In Search of'' with its blurry
visuals of purported Loch Ness monsters, ghosts and an apelike
Bigfoot.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our movie makes the viewer really invest in the sense of
watching to decipher what's going on,'' ``Blair Witch'' co-director
Myrick says.
</P>
<P>
   And he's right. During the dead of night when the actors are
awakened by chilling cries from the forest, they scramble to grab
video equipment and race into the woods, the camera often swinging
wildly as they point toward weird sounds emanating from different
places. ``When you work hard to see that _ like when you look at
some grainy photograph _ you carry that with you.''
</P>
<P>
   The power of suggestion is also at the heart of De Bont's remake
of ``The Haunting.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Horror is at its best when things are barely seen or just
imagined,'' De Bont says. ``We're not going to show everything.''
</P>
<P>
   With its big Hollywood budget, ``The Haunting,'' however, will
naturally show a bit more than ``Blair Witch.''
</P>
<P>
   Special effects, especially those employed in the film's trailer
showing stone cherubs and statues moving to face the mansion's
unlucky occupants, will be much more in evidence than in Robert
Wise's original spooky masterpiece.
</P>
<P>
   But De Bont says only 120 special effects shots are used, and
some are quite delicately perceived. ``It's very much a
psychological horror film,'' he says. ``Basically, the house will
come alive. It's not like huge, silly monsters. It's very subtle.''
</P>
<P>
   De Bont also developed and recorded the house's unnerving sounds
before shooting began so that his actors, including Neeson,
Catherine Zeta-Jones and Lili Taylor, could react to something
authentic.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's nothing worse (for an actor) to hear than, `Now here's
where we'll add this and this sound,' and they never hear what is
supposed to be scaring them,'' De Bont says. ``During shooting we
had speakers in the right spots to have sounds audible, like the
creaks, so they not only react but get scared.''
</P>
<P>
   And he says ``The Haunting'' is very different from his most
well-known films such as ``Speed'' and ``Twister,'' in which the
story was propelled by the action sequences. ``In this movie, it is
character-driven and then things are happening. The suspense is
slowly built and maintained. Like in `The Shining,' it is like
those characters and how the house starts to play with their
minds.''
</P>
<P>
   The creators of ``Blair Witch'' have gone beyond the film itself
to fiendishly toy with their audience's brains.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, an hourlong ``Blair Witch'' special aired on the
Sci-Fi Channel that presented the film's made-up story line as
fact. And just three months ago, they launched a Web site _
blairwitch.com _ that outlines back stories for the main
characters, the fictional town and the ages-old witch tale.
</P>
<P>
   The ``Blair Witch'' crew also has a comic book in the works,
plans for an extensive ``Making of ...'' to be included on DVD, has
secured the film's interactive and gaming rights and has first dibs
with Artisan Entertainment at a sequel.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've really tried to maintain the mythology,'' ``Blair
Witch'' producer Cowie says. ``Anything that creeps us out, we go
with it.''
</P>
<P>
   HORROR CLASSICS
</P>
<P>
   Who needs Freddy Krueger? There are plenty of videos that up the
horror quotient with style instead of steel blades and buckets of
blood. Here are 10 to consider:
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``Nosferatu'' (1922) _ As beautiful a film as it is chilling,
F.W. Murnau's silent classic, the tale of a particularly
wicked-looking bloodsucker (Max Schreck) inspired by Bram Stoker's
novel ``Dracula,'' demonstrates the director's brilliance with
subtlety and visual imagery.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``The Old Dark House'' (1932) _ James Whale, the director Ian
McKellen portrayed in ``Gods and Monsters,'' made this movie in
between ``Frankenstein'' and ``Bride of Frankenstein.'' It involves
insanity and disturbing shadows in a Welsh mountain retreat. Among
those in the impressive cast: Boris Karloff, Melvyn Douglas, Gloria
Stuart (``Titanic'') and Charles Laughton.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``Cat People'' (1942) _ What you don't see is what gets you in
Jaues Tourneur's weird psychological tale of women who turn into
panthers.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``The Uninvited'' (1944) _ Ray Milland and Ruth Hussey play a
brother and sister who slowly discover ghosts inhabit their new
home.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``The Spiral Staircase'' (1946) _ The camera does most of the
work generating spine-tingling suspense in a gripping tale of a
mute maid (Dorothy McGuire) who ultimately comes face to face with
a serial killer.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``Diabolique'' (1955) _ Just pass on by the Sharon Stone
version and reach for director Henri-Georges Clouzot's original
with Simone Signoret. It's not so much a horror film as a
suspenseful tale of apparent murder, complete with dark hallways
and creaking doors.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``Curse of the Demon'' (1958) _ The occult is front and center
in another Tourneur film, this one the riveting tale of an American
(Dana Andrews) trying to expose a devil's cult in London.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``Scream of Fear'' (1961) _ Susan Strasberg plays a woman in a
wheelchair subjected to weird happenings _ and startling death
images _ when she travels to her father's European mansion.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``The Haunting'' (1963) _ Robert Wise's depiction of Shirley
Jackson's horror tale involves a large New England home, a history
of mysterious deaths, repeated disturbing nighttime sounds and what
must be creepy-crawling ghosts. Julie Harris stars.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``Repulsion'' (1965) _ Is it all in the mind? Catherine
Deneuve plays a woman suffering from repeated hallucinations in
Roman Polanski's chilling drama.
</P>
<P>
   _Bob Longino writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
