<HEADLINE>
WASHOUTS? LET 'EM FLOAT ALONE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By E.J. MONTINI  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - Why do we save these people?
</P>
<P>
   In the middle of raging thunderstorm, someone drives his truck
or minivan or Ford Pinto into an obviously flooded wash, drifts
downstream until getting tangled up in downed trees, broken
guardrails or other debris, and we send out squadrons of police
cars, firetrucks, helicopters and whatever else it takes to pluck
him from certain embarrassment and possible death in the swift,
murky water.
</P>
<P>
   I'm wondering _ why?
</P>
<P>
   Do we have some special affection for drivers with no judgment?
</P>
<P>
   Is there some secret ``Knucklehead Lobby'' I haven't heard about
but which has a stranglehold on the government?
</P>
<P>
   This happens every summer. Usually, several times.
</P>
<P>
   It's gone on year after year for generations.
</P>
<P>
   And no one ever seems to question the extremes to which local
authorities will go to rescue these people.
</P>
<P>
   Passing the ``stupid motorist'' law, as Arizona did a few years
back, isn't nearly enough. All that does is to allow the state to
pass on the cost of rescues to the nincompoops who make them
necessary.
</P>
<P>
   Only it rarely happens.
</P>
<P>
   And besides, that's after the fact.
</P>
<P>
   The question we should be asking ourselves is: Why bother in the
first place?
</P>
<P>
   (at)j  &QL; 
NOT-TOO-SWIFT CURRENTS
</P>
<P>
   (at)j  &QL; 
We live in a state that has shown no real interest in spending the
money necessary to rescue thousands of children from dangerous or
abusive households, but will spend any amount necessary to pull a
motorist from the flooding cab of his El Camino.
</P>
<P>
   We won't spend the money necessary to provide adequate housing
for poor people or lifesaving medical care for those who need it,
yet we'll launch our own version of Operation Desert Storm every
time some urban cowboy gets his Toyoto Land Cruiser tilted sideways
in a gutter.
</P>
<P>
   Do you think, maybe, there might be a correlation between the
simpletons driving on our rain-soaked streets and the pathetically
small amount of cash the Legislature has been willing to put toward
improving our public schools?
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday, just after the local TV stations had spent the better
part of an hour with their helicopters hovering over Simple Simons
who had driven their vehicles into waist-high storm water, they
focused their cameras on a dog.
</P>
<P>
   It appeared to be a German shepherd that the storm had spooked,
causing him to wander out into the desert and in the path of an
oncoming flash flood.
</P>
<P>
   While cameras from the helicopters rolled, the dog did something
truly extraordinary, at least for this part of the country:
</P>
<P>
   He got out of the way.
</P>
<P>
   He moved.
</P>
<P>
   That's it.
</P>
<P>
   The animal trotted away from the banks of the wash, and the
floodwater moved past him. That was that.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, such a scene isn't nearly as entertaining as watching
some ninny drive headlong into a gully washer, then cry and moan
and wave his arms until rescuers manage to rig some contraption to
haul him out of the sinister deluge.
</P>
<P>
   Raging water looks great on TV.
</P>
<P>
   (at)j  &QL; 
CAUGHT UP IN THE UNDERTOW
</P>
<P>
   (at)j  &QL; 
And you can't help but cheer for the swift-water rescue workers or
the helicopter pilots who swoop in to save people.
</P>
<P>
   Besides, it's better than watching summer reruns. Or worse, the
Major League Baseball All-Star game. Or even worse, the WNBA
All-Star game.
</P>
<P>
   Nor should we assume that every motorist who ends up trapped in
a flash flood is brainless. Intelligent people sometimes make
mistakes. And they should be saved.
</P>
<P>
   But with every monsoon storm that strikes our city, there is a
great untapped potential for idiot cleansing.
</P>
<P>
   We could take the money we spend on rescuing numbskulls (as well
as the money we spend on news coverage of numbskulls being rescued)
and put it to better use.
</P>
<P>
   But we haven't, so far, and we won't.
</P>
<P>
   You can't change human nature. You can't beat showbiz. You can't
use a helicopter to rescue a kid from an abusive home. &QL; 
 &QL; 
E.J. Montini can be reached at (602) 444-8978 or at
ed.montini(at)pni.com via e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
