<SLUG> BC-MORSE-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TUNE INTO THE REVOLUTION 
</HEADLINE>
   Commentary  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ROB MORSE  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   BERKELEY, Calif. _ On my way over to Berkeley, I practiced my
chants and slogans.
</P>
<P>
   ``Power to the people, right on.'' ``Venceremos.'' ``La Lutte
Continue.'' ``Hey, hey, ho hum, how humdrum can radio become?''
</P>
<P>
   The people's struggle for control of Berkeley's public radio
station, KPFA, made for dramatic radio, at least when station
management pulled the plug on reporter Dennis Bernstein and his
program ``Flashpoint.''
</P>
<P>
   On television, it seemed like a bad '60s movie. But talk about
police brutality. It looked like the cops sprayed half the
demonstrators with gray paint and cellulite instead of Mace.
</P>
<P>
   So I had to go over Wednesday and see 1969 in 1999 for myself.
I'd read about the hundreds of protesters and the 52 arrests at the
station Tuesday night, but as we know from the '60s, crowd counts
always are biased.
</P>
<P>
   For one thing, they don't count how interesting the people are
in the crowd.
</P>
<P>
   There was Susan Stone, who, until locked out by management, was
the station's programmer for drama and literature. ``Now I call it
`trauma and liturgy,''' she said.
</P>
<P>
   She still had a big smile, and put the situation at KPFA nicely
and with no radical cant, saying, ``It's a pickle we're in here.''
</P>
<P>
   Lavarne Williams, who violated every '60s stereotype with her
black business attire and cell phone, said, ``I worked in
fund-raising. Now I'm hell-raising.''
</P>
<P>
   Particularly galling to KPFA staffers locked out by the parent
Pacifica Foundation is the fact that the station has been playing
best-of-KPFA tapes _ interviews and stories they taped themselves.
After the police bust, the station played an old interview with
radical Angela Davis.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wonder what Angela would think about that,'' said KPFA
loyalist Wayne Linse. ``It was a good interview, and I felt guilty
listening to it.''
</P>
<P>
   ``They were trying to make it seem as if they are KPFA,'' said
longtime radio commentator and Sovietologist Bill Mandel, who left
the 50-year-old station six years ago ``in the first purge,'' as he
put it.
</P>
<P>
   Mandel and I talked about the days when he was called before the
House Un-American Activities Committee, and the even older days
when he left the Hoover Institution after opposing the Truman
Doctrine.
</P>
<P>
   Don't worry, all you progressive youth who support KPFA. You
won't be tested. Even most of the graying radicals in front of KPFA
don't know what the Truman Doctrine is.
</P>
<P>
   It's not a Jim Carrey movie.
</P>
<P>
   People came and went in front of KPFA for the two hours I was
there. Here are few counts besides crowd counts: When I arrived,
five young staffers and friends were sitting in an old car
listening to Michael Krasny on KQED radio interview some of the
locked-out staffers. They listened with total intensity, as if this
was the last signal from Radio Free Berserkley.
</P>
<P>
   I heard two mentions of a possible CIA interest in buying the
station. No, not the Culinary Institute of America, although that
might make sense in Berkeley.
</P>
<P>
   I saw one young guy make the sign of the revolutionary fist. I
didn't know any young people knew how to do that anymore without
putting up one finger.
</P>
<P>
   I heard one reference to ``cyberfascism,'' although I forget
what that has to do with radio.
</P>
<P>
   I heard a guy playing ``We Shall Overcome'' on one of those
baritone horns played by the Salvation Army.
</P>
<P>
   A simple crowd count didn't do justice to this crowd.
</P>
<P>
   But the thing that got me wasn't the Berkeleyness of it all, or
how old, white and gray I suddenly felt.
</P>
<P>
   What got me was the look on people's faces. One woman, with a
beautiful face just starting to show wrinkles, was on the edge of
tears as the speakers talked seriously of free speech and
solidarity.
</P>
<P>
   I knew that look. She was someone who had lost a home, of sorts.
It was as if an earthquake had hit Berkeley, and left it
free-speechless and her speechless.
</P>
<P>
   Reporter Dennis Bernstein was still shaking with anger and
feelings of betrayal after getting the boot from management. He
said he hadn't slept since then.
</P>
<P>
   ``You leave on Friday, and you get to your office on Monday and
find armed guards. It's unbelievable,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Yeah, and in Berkeley, I said. ``In Berkeley?'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Anywhere.''
</P>
<P>
   Afterward, I called Vini Beachem, a friend who had been taping
his own radio plays with his company, Pagliacci's Fools, when the
station imploded. These remarkable plays are the perfect blend of
the old and the new.
</P>
<P>
   Beachem, a former member of the KPFA board, said he has to
protect his people and his project and probably will move his
shows, taped before live audiences, to the Oakland Museum.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe that's the point of KPFA now,'' he said, ``taking the
spirit of the station and doing it elsewhere, taking it to the
museums, the streets and the parking lots.''
</P>
<P>
   That sounds very '60s, but I think what he's really saying is
you have to protect yourself, your friends and your project in the
corporate '90s.
</P>
<P>
   By the way, don't forget taking it to the Internet, the
revolution that succeeded. Free speech is under threat there, too.
</P>
<P>
   Beachem doesn't have time to wait for KPFA to solve its
problems. ``If it comes down to litigation and lawsuits, how long
does that take?'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   A lot longer than the revolution has taken so far.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Rob Morse is a columnist for the San Francisco Examiner, P.O.
Box 7260, San Francisco, CA 94120.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
