<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PESTICIDE-USE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STUDY SAYS PESTICIDE USE RISES DRAMATICALLY IN CALIFORNIA 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JANE KAY  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Farmers and professional exterminators sprayed
more cancer- causing pesticides than ever before in 1997, nearly
twice the amount used in 1991, according to a new California study.
</P>
<P>
   Overall, the pesticide use increased to 204 million pounds in
1997, up by 3.5 percent from 1996, according to the annual study by
the California Department of Pesticide Regulation, released
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Growers applied 93 percent of the total amount, pest control
operators sprayed 3 percent, landscapers used 1 percent and all
others, 3 percent.
</P>
<P>
   The study doesn't include pesticides used in homes, gardens,
schools, hospitals and other buildings where no certified
professional is involved. Experts say that use would raise the
total number of pounds by another 15 percent.
</P>
<P>
   For the first time, the state Department of Pesticide Regulation
reported pesticide use by the following categories: carcinogens,
reproductive toxins, air contaminants, threats to groundwater and
others. The Legislature asked for the information in the most
recent budget language.
</P>
<P>
   Environmental groups objected to the continuous increase of
pesticide use, particularly the carcinogens, reproductive toxins
and nerve toxins.
</P>
<P>
   ``We should be trying to reduce the use of chemicals that cause
birth defects, sterility and cancer,'' said environmental chemist
Susan Kegley, staff scientist at the Pesticide Action Network.
``Alternatives to these toxic pesticides are available. The state
needs to provide incentives and support to growers to reduce the
pesticide use.''
</P>
<P>
   Veda Federighi, a spokeswoman for the Department of Pesticide
Regulation, said, the agency offers programs aimed at reducing the
use of hazardous chemicals.
</P>
<P>
   The use of oils as pesticides, Federighi said, contributed to
the high volume of carcinogens. Using oils can be a less toxic
alternative, she said. The oils are used in the winter on barren
trees, which reduces the need for certain toxic chemicals during
the growing season.
</P>
<P>
   The department granted $750,000 in 1999 to growers and others
for developing ways to control insects without pesticides. The
grants since 1996 total $4.5 million, Federighi said.
</P>
<P>
   But Kegley responded that $750,000 a year out of an operating
budget of $40 million to $50 million is a very small portion.
``They need to allocate more resources to hit this problem hard,''
she said.
</P>
<P>
   According to the study:
</P>
<P>
   _ Carcinogenic pesticides, known to cause cancer in lab animals,
increased by 81 percent from 31.2 million pounds in 1991 to 56.5
million pounds in 1997. Most widely used were petroleum and other
oils. Next most highly used were two soil fumigants, Telone and
metam sodium, which spilled during a train wreck in 1991 and killed
fish in miles of the Sacramento River.
</P>
<P>
   _ Reproductive toxins increased by 34 percent from 24.3 million
pounds in 1991 to 32.6 million pounds in 1997. They can cause birth
defects, miscarriages and infertility. Most frequently used were
metam sodium and methyl bromide, a fumigant used on strawberries,
grapes and nursery crops.
</P>
<P>
   _ The family of organophosphates and carbamates, both nerve
toxins, rose by 17 percent from 13.8 million pounds in 1991 to 16.1
million pounds in 1997. Chlorpyrifos and aldicarb, both used on
cotton, are the top chemicals. Chlorpyrifos, a component in Raid,
is commonly used around homes as an insecticide.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (The 1997 Pesticide Use Report is available at
www.cdpr.ca.gov/whatnew.htm)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
