<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-15 15:34 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1388 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBO-RYAN-MAIN-HNS &LR;      07-15 2473
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-RYAN-MAIN-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
Ryan winds up with 27 seasons of memories
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; By MICKEY HERSKOWITZ &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; c. 1999, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   It didn't have to end this way
</P>
<P>
   No, we don't mean the induction of Nolan Ryan into the Hall of
Fame. Cooperstown is clearly the last station where this train
stops, this Ryan Express.
</P>
<P>
   But it turns out that Nolan kept a little something to himself
on his way to baseball's holy tabernacle. That is, he could have
pitched again _ and thought about it _ the season after he retired
in 1993. He might be pitching even now, for crying out loud, if the
only factor was the condition of his right arm, which Pete Rose
called ``the greatest arm that ever lived.''
</P>
<P>
   We _ the fans, the media _ had assumed that Nolan had blown out
his elbow when he threw the last pitch of his storied career in
Seattle on Sept. 22, 1993. He left the field with his arm limp at
his side, while a crowd of strangers gave him a standing ovation.
</P>
<P>
   ``It wasn't really a career-ending injury,'' Ryan said. ``That's
what people thought. I had announced before the season that this
would be my last one, and there was only a week or so left, and
everybody pretty much accepted that this was the final blow. I
never said anything differently. Nobody really asked me. I was
walking away from the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had a partial tear and it healed with rest. By the next
spring, I was throwing batting practice to the TCU kids and my arm
was sound. I know I could have pitched.''
</P>
<P>
   He might have been tempted, but the calendar told him he was 47,
and logic told him no. He didn't want to be one of those athletes
who retired and kept coming back.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't think it would be fair to the club,'' Ryan said.
``The recovery time from the nagging injuries that I knew I'd face,
that was hanging over me. But I guess what surprises me even now is
that I still have that desire to pitch and to perform on that
level. That competitive edge, I've never lost it. Physically, I
think I could have continued to pitch if I really, truly had wanted
to do it.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, if he had changed his mind and tried to go another
season, or two, this Hall of Fame weekend would have been
considerably less attractive. The King of Swing (and Miss) has made
many a choice over the years, and you don't recall many that turned
out badly. No matter how much money he earned, or banks and ranches
and homes he owned, he always returned to Alvin, and the small-town
values he never lost.
</P>
<P>
   He married Ruth Holdorff, school beauty and a state tennis
champion, in 1967. He wanted to quit that winter, having drawn a
cool $7,000 from the Mets. She convinced him to stick it out,
telling him that if he gave up now, he would always wonder if he
might have made it. Nolan had to take out a loan to support them
during the next spring training.
</P>
<P>
   Everybody knows about Nolan, so wholesome that at 50-plus he
still looks like the poster boy for Future Farmers of America. He
became a special kind of sports treasure because he achieved big
things, and he did them without vanity or deceit or scandal.
Through it all, Ruth was more than the pretty blonde who lived with
Nolan's arm. They have made a splendid team, and when he retired
Ruth wrote her own story of life in the fast(ball) lane. The title
was Covering Home.
</P>
<P>
   The Ryans raised three handsome kids, Reid, Reese and Wendy. Now
they truly have a family business, a minor-league team in Round
Rock called _ what else? _ the Express, soon to move into a new,
town-supported ballpark.
</P>
<P>
   The outline of Nolan's story ought to be as familiar to the
devout baseball fan as the ingredients of an apple pie. How the
Mets worried that he would never find the strike zone, although he
helped them win a World Series in 1969, known as the Miracle of
Flushing Meadow. Then they traded him to the Angels, where he
blossomed as a strikeout artist and no-hit genius. Then the Angels
thought he was winding down, and they let him get away to Houston,
where he could drive his pickup truck from Alvin to the Astrodome
in less than 30 minutes. And how the fans all but burned down the
stadium when John McMullen tried to lowball him and cut his salary.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I had known then what I know now, I would never have let
him go,'' McMullen said later. ``But if I had known then what I
know now, I would never have voted for Nixon.''
</P>
<P>
   All of which led to one last move _ to the Texas Rangers, where
he seemed to set or extend a record every time he pitched.
</P>
<P>
   Now we spin the calendar backward to the first day of May 1991,
when Nolan delivered a performance so compelling that it seemed to
distill his entire career.
</P>
<P>
   He pitched his record seventh no-hitter over the Toronto Blue
Jays, a 3-0 victory, in front of a crowd that kept growing at
Arlington Stadium, even as cable television flashed the game across
the land.
</P>
<P>
   His son Reid, then a freshman at Texas, dropped a report he was
writing on a Louis L'Amour novel to watch his father pitch the last
two innings. At Shea Stadium, the San Diego Padres and the New York
Mets put their postgame buffets on hold and crowded around the TV
sets in the clubhouses.
</P>
<P>
   And at the ballpark in Kansas City, while the Royals were
playing the Tigers, they picked up Ryan's no-hitter in progress on
the Diamond Vision screen in center field. Let the strangeness of
this sink in: The fans in Kansas City were ignoring a game they had
paid to see, taking place on the field in front of them, to watch
the telecast of a game being played almost 600 miles away.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, in Arlington, a scene both dramatic and eerily
symbolic was unfolding. From the press box, from the sixth inning
on, you could see the headlights of cars backed up for miles,
threading their way to the ballpark. Anyone who saw Field of Dreams
would have recognized the scene. Fans were desperate to buy a
ticket to a game that was nearly over, hoping to grab at least a
concluding glimpse of Ryan pitching one more hitless gem.
</P>
<P>
   Nolan's final out was Roberto Alomar. When Ryan pitched his
first no-hitter for the California Angels 18 years earlier, his
second baseman was Sandy Alomar, Roberto's father. ``I've known
that kid since he was a toddler,'' said Ryan. ``He wanted to be a
pitcher.'' But Nolan showed him no mercy. He struck him out, his
16th of the game, and the seventh no-hitter was his.
</P>
<P>
   At that instant, in Kansas City, the fans gave a standing
ovation to the television screen, which showed a close-up of a
smiling Ryan, his right arm punching the air as his teammates
swarmed the mound. They hoisted him onto their shoulders and
carried him off.
</P>
<P>
   In Austin, Reid Ryan crushed a Coke can and jumped up and down.
In Arlington, Nolan's wife, Ruth, left her seat in the stands to
wait for her husband outside the clubhouse. She had arrived at the
stadium just before the first pitch, deciding at the last minute to
accept a ride on a private plane owned by an Alvin neighbor.
</P>
<P>
   He was young and restless in New York, celebrated in Anaheim and
idolized in Houston. But Ryan discovered the meaning of life in
Arlington. ``The secret,'' he said, ``is knowing that there is no
secret.'' There was just raw talent, refined by hard work and
humility.
</P>
<P>
   Even after his seventh no-hitter, with the reporters jockeying
for position around his locker and still lobbing questions at him,
he politely excused himself and walked over to the stationary bike.
He did his 45 minutes, already preparing for his next start.
</P>
<P>
   Nolan called that no-hitter his most meaningful, partly because
``it was a reflection of me as a complete pitcher,'' and partly
because it happened in Arlington, in front of the Rangers fans
``who have been so good to me.''
</P>
<P>
   This was one of the keys to Ryan's long and spectacular career.
This was how he could join a new club in 1989, adjust to new
teammates and new surroundings, and finish the season with 16 wins
and a major league-leading 301 strikeouts, all at the age of 42.
</P>
<P>
   Unless androids eventually take up baseball, no one will ever
duplicate his endurance: He played 27 seasons, still holds 48
major-league records, including walks and wild pitches, and his
most famous _ 5,714 batters who connected only with air, in 5,386
innings. He struck out eight father-and-son combinations, 12 sets
of brothers and 27 members of the Hall of Fame, among them two of
the newest, George Brett and Robin Yount.
</P>
<P>
   Over the years, the fans felt an attachment to Ryan that reached
far deeper than his statistics. It had to do with the fact that
this was one of the best human beings ever to play ball. The job
was temporary, and he understood this better than most.
</P>
<P>
   Are other examples in order?
</P>
<P>
   He pitched his sixth no-hitter in Oakland, against the
power-hitting Athletics, on June 11, 1990. He did it despite a
stress fracture in his lower back. His son, Reese, then 14, was on
the trip and in the dugout, working as a ballboy. Between innings,
he rubbed his father's back. After the last of the eighth, he
assured his father, ``We only need three more (outs).''
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers' manager, Bobby Valentine, who had played center
field for the Angels in Ryan's first no-hitter, said, ``It was a
Norman Rockwell scene.''
</P>
<P>
   He was a no-hit pitcher who too often labored for no-hit teams.
The pitchers on the 1919 Black Sox got better run support from
players trying to dump the Series.
</P>
<P>
   A lot of athletes seize on a modest amount of success to flaunt
their importance. Not Ryan. With remarkable patience, he mapped his
campaign over the years. He was his own coach, his own trainer, his
own chaperone. No one has ever heard of Nolan Ryan knocking a
manager or a teammate.
</P>
<P>
   He pitched in four cities under 10 managers without becoming
confused as a person. By the end of his career, he was the only
player who was a member of the FDIC, having purchased the Danbury
State Bank, 10 miles from Alvin.
</P>
<P>
   I covered his first start (a loss) and his first win for the
Mets, both occurring in the Astrodome before his family and
friends. Writing about him has been a source of unending
satisfaction. He made our jobs easier because success didn't change
him, not as a person and not as a competitor. He never saw himself
as a matinee idol or a showman. He is what he seems. If you search
for more, you risk missing the very essence of him.
</P>
<P>
   Yet writers always had to exercise particular care when it came
to Ryan because they tended to lose their critical faculties. I
remember when the Astros commissioned LeRoy Neiman to paint Nolan's
portrait. The finished work showed him halfway into his delivery,
with the flag visible behind him in center field.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was how I saw him,'' said Neiman. ``I had at my disposal
a pitcher of such idealism that it was impossible to present him as
anything other than the All-American baseball player.'' You can
evoke all the rhythm and flavor and texture of the sport with one
freeze-frame of Ryan blowing a strike past a big hitter.
</P>
<P>
   In more than 100 years, only six pitchers ever held more than
two teams hitless. The others were Sandy Koufax with four, and Jim
Maloney, Bob Feller, Cy Young and Larry Corcoran with three each.
Young retired in 1908. You may not remember Corcoran. His big year
was 1880, when he started 60 games, completed 57 and won 43. This
is the company Ryan keeps.
</P>
<P>
   Like an old man whittling wood, pitchers keep shaving their
thoughts until their philosophy is as smooth and fine as they can
shape it. Nolan studied the science of other pitchers, and this
helped him mature. Lew Burdette of the Braves put it simply: ``I
exploit the greed of all hitters.''
</P>
<P>
   There was this advice from Satchel Paige: ``Just take the ball
and throw it where you want. Throw strikes. Home plate don't
move.''
</P>
<P>
   Nolan was still learning to pitch when he finally walked off the
job, with 324 wins and a list of strikeout records as long as his
arm. He was a very proud fellow, with a work ethic that was off the
charts. His humor was dry and often playful.
</P>
<P>
   So my favorite memory of Ryan isn't his classic duel with Rose
in 1981, when he allowed the single that tied Pete with Stan Musial
for the most career hits in the National League. It wasn't his
fifth no-hitter, over the Dodgers, in the Astrodome. It wasn't the
time he pitched against Ruth in a Fantasy Camp game and buzzed her
with a fastball high and inside, almost knocking her down. (I
jumped him about that. ``You jammed her? Your own wife?'' ``Had
to,'' he said. ``She was digging in on me.'')
</P>
<P>
   My personal favorite is his 4,000th strikeout, an odd pick, I
concede. He was 12 short of that mark in 1985 when he started for
the Astros against the Mets. Running in the outfield before the
game, he passed Danny Heep, an ex-teammate who had been traded for
Mike Scott.
</P>
<P>
   As they crossed, Heep cried out a warning: ``You're not getting
me for 4,000, not me, not tonight!'' Nolan just laughed. ``That's
OK,'' he said. ``I don't figure it will be you, either.''
</P>
<P>
   As the innings rolled along, the strikeouts began to pile up.
After his total reached 11, Nolan glanced at the on-deck circle.
Guess who was stepping up to the plate. Yeah, Danny Heep. ``He just
stared at me,'' said Ryan, ``and he was shaking his head. It was
all over his face. I could see him thinking, Why didn't I just keep
my mouth shut?
</P>
<P>
   ``I started him off with a fastball, and he took it on the
outside corner for a strike. I threw him another over the plate and
he fouled it back to the screen: 0-and-2. I threw him a curve, down
and in, a tough pitch for a hitter to lay off. He swung and missed
and was gone on three pitches.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1989, after he moved to the Rangers and Heep had joined the
Red Sox, they met at a restaurant in Arlington. Heep said, ``I wish
you would hurry up and get your 5,000th strikeout, so people would
quit talking about me being No. 4,000.''
</P>
<P>
   Said Nolan: ``I didn't have the heart to tell him he was always
going to be No. 4,000. He just wasn't going to be talked about as
much.'' (Rickey Henderson, of Oakland, turned out to be No. 5,000.)
</P>
<P>
   ``What I really miss most about the game is the competition,''
said Ryan. ``I miss the routine of working out on a daily basis _
I'm probably one of the few guys who really enjoyed that. I miss
the camaraderie of the guys in the clubhouse, being a member of a
team. You don't replace that with anything else I know of.
</P>
<P>
   ``I haven't been in a clubhouse since the last time I took off
my uniform. Once you're not on the team, you're an outsider. I
don't care what you've done or what you contributed to the game.
You don't really belong there; it's not your clubhouse.''
</P>
<P>
   So this weekend, Lynn Nolan Ryan joins the most elite team of
all _ the one at Cooperstown. The train stops there.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
