<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-15 15:45 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1403 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TV-COMMENT-SFCHRON &LR;      07-15 0843
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-COMMENT-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NETWORKS DELIVER AN ALL-WHITE PICTURE 
</HEADLINE>
   By JOHN CARMAN  
 c.1999, San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   So the networks are willing to do lunch with NAACP President
Kweisi Mfume to smooth over this race issue.
</P>
<P>
   Race issue as in oops, only one race on all the new fall shows.
Big surprise, the race is white.
</P>
<P>
   Even the space aliens are white. And by the way, there are more
of them in starring roles than blacks. Or Latinos. Or Asians.
</P>
<P>
   The implicit message is that as the networks figure it, white
viewers are more comfortable watching space aliens than watching
black people.
</P>
<P>
   I can spare Mfume the indigestion that would be sure to follow
his meal with network suits.
</P>
<P>
   With the utmost sincerity, the network execs would look Mfume
straight in the eye and tell him that nothing is more important to
them than rectifying the embarrassing shortage of minorities in
lead roles.
</P>
<P>
   They would also point out the ethnic diversity in their
supporting casts _ doesn't every white cop on TV get chewed out by
a black boss? _ and ABC might add that it features Nick Turturro on
``NYPD Blue.''
</P>
<P>
   Nick Turturro? Last summer, critics were pelting Stu Bloomberg,
ABC Entertainment chairman, and Jamie Tarses, ABC Entertainment
president, over the absence of ethnic minorities on ABC's new
programs.
</P>
<P>
   Well, said Tarses, there was Jeffrey Sams in ``Cupid,'' which
has since been canceled. Bloomberg interjected, ``And Nick
Turturro.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Yeah,'' Tarses chirped. ``and Nick Turturro in `NYPD Blue.'''
</P>
<P>
   And you wonder why the networks are in trouble.
</P>
<P>
   Scott Sassa, NBC's top executive on the West Coast, was enduring
a similar grilling earlier this year. Sassa himself is Asian
American.
</P>
<P>
   ``In terms of ethnic diversity,'' he said, ``I think we need to
make sure that the shows we have on air accurately reflect the
composition of the audience that we're serving.''
</P>
<P>
   That was six months ago. And now, with the fall shows about to
drop from the shelf onto the air, Sassa seems to have met his
mandate _ provided that the audience NBC is serving is all white,
because Mfume won't find his own race reflected at the top of NBC's
shows.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking at the NAACP's annual convention this week in New York,
Mfume noted that there isn't a minority lead in any of the major
networks' 27 new shows. True; you have to slide down to UPN, with
its ``Moesha'' spin-off and new Jaleel White comedy, to find
minority stars.
</P>
<P>
   In a sense, TV was more amenable to black stars in 1951, when
``Beulah'' was on ABC and ``The Amos and Andy Show'' was on CBS.
</P>
<P>
   What the networks dare not say publicly is that they're
apparently convinced that black stars are anathema to ratings.
</P>
<P>
   Never mind that ``The Cosby Show'' was TV's smash hit of the
previous decade. Maybe Bill Cosby was unique in attracting a
crossover audience or maybe racial attitudes have hardened in the
1990s.
</P>
<P>
   Half a century into network TV, we're still awaiting the first
successful drama carried by a black lead. None, in 50-plus years.
</P>
<P>
   Blacks have fared better in comedy. But the 1999-2000 television
season figures to be a scant year for sitcoms.
</P>
<P>
   Mfume's complaint relates to a broader change in the television
business. The big networks, which are becoming smaller networks,
aren't in the practice of serving anyone well these days, except
for white urban viewers between the ages of 18 and 49.
</P>
<P>
   You could even argue that the networks are programming for a
minority. Their prime demographic is just that _ less than half of
the national population. But still, it's the group advertisers
crave.
</P>
<P>
   In other years, network programmers might have felt a moral
obligation to serve an audience that included blacks, older
viewers, children and rural Americans.
</P>
<P>
   After all, broadcasters use a public resource, the airwaves, to
operate for the interest, convenience and necessity of all
Americans.
</P>
<P>
   But TV is far more lightly regulated today, and the networks
have been taken over by bigger corporations with a bottom-line
obsession.
</P>
<P>
   Buckling under the pressure from cable and other competitors,
the broadcast networks have never been less interested in their
public obligations.
</P>
<P>
   Huge profits are no longer assured; the era of noblesse oblige
is over. Networks scrapping for survival are apt to postpone their
societal responsibilities. You'll sooner see people torn to pieces
by wild animals than a successful black family drama.
</P>
<P>
   Network behavior can be explained easily enough. It's
self-serving and loathsome almost by rote. But should the networks
have to force-feed shows to viewers that they apparently don't want
to watch? And sooner or later, doesn't the question shift from the
networks to the audience?
</P>
<P>
   That question is: Why won't sufficient numbers of white viewers
watch black TV stars, especially on TV dramas?
</P>
<P>
   On that topic, Mfume doesn't really need a candid exchange of
ideas with network executives.
</P>
<P>
   In one sore word, the reason is racism.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service clients) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-15-99 1545EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990715.0195 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-15 15:46 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1405 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBO-RYAN-EARLYDAYS-HN     07-15 1621
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-RYAN-EARLY </SLUG>
 DAYS-HNS  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
Solid roots in hometown become foundation for success
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; By JODY GOLDSTEIN &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; c. 1999, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   It all began at Shroeder Field.
</P>
<P>
   That was as close as you got to nirvana as a kid in Alvin, a
real Little League field with a real pitcher's mound, dugouts,
bleachers and even lights.
</P>
<P>
   Or maybe it began at Alvin Hardware, that day in 1954 when Nolan
Ryan was 7 years old and his father took him to buy his first
baseball glove.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was one of my favorite memories,'' Ryan said. ``Getting
to go with my dad down to Alvin Hardware and being the last of six
kids and getting to pick out, for the first time, anything new for
myself and it not being a hand-me-down. That was a new
experience.''
</P>
<P>
   It was what kids in Alvin waited for and dreamed of _ being old
enough to move off the vacant lot and onto a real baseball field,
being old enough to play organized ball, to experience the
camaraderie of a team, the thrill of competition.
</P>
<P>
   ``As youngsters, the one thing the kids looked forward to was
getting old enough to play baseball in one of the youth league
teams,'' Ryan said. ``That was the highest thing you could look
forward to as a kid growing up in a small, rural town like that. To
go out to tryouts and stuff. That was a big event in your life.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some of my fondest memories of baseball were playing in the
youth leagues, playing the game for no other reason than for the
enjoyment of playing and feeling no pressure whatsoever.''
</P>
<P>
   Ryan can still remember the pride of putting on that uniform and
knowing that he belonged.
</P>
<P>
   ``As a kid, to get your hat to start with, and you're on a team
for the first time '' Ryan said. ``And then the game rolls around
after practicing for two or three weeks and it seems like you'll
never get there. All kids probably get their uniforms on six hours
before the game, then beg their parents to get to the ballpark
three or four hours before they're supposed to. It's that
anticipation and excitement, and I still remember that.''
</P>
<P>
   Ryan pitched and played shortstop. There was no trip to
Williamsport, Pa., for the Little League World Series, no scouts
watching, no agents calling. It was simply a Little League
experience similar to that of millions of other kids, except that
his glove now hangs in a museum in Alvin.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's so old you can't even read the numbers on it,'' Ryan
said. ``But you can read my name on it where I burned it in there
with a woodburning set to make sure nobody got it away from me.''
</P>
<P>
   It was only a few years later that Ryan went on his first date
with Ruth Holdorff, who would later become his wife. She was 13. He
was 15. He picked her up in his fire-engine-red 1952 Chevy (at the
time, Texas allowed teen-agers to get their license at 14). They
went to the movies, then on to DairyLand, Alvin's only fast-food
joint.
</P>
<P>
   ``I still remember him asking,'' Ruth said. ``He came up to me
and said, `Do you think your mom would let you go to a movie?' He'd
had a girlfriend, but they'd just broken up. She bet he wouldn't
ask me. I guess he got stuck.''
</P>
<P>
   They'd known each other forever. Ruth's sister Lynn was in
Nolan's class. After their first date, their fates were sealed.
</P>
<P>
   ``She was just so definite; we knew,'' said Ingrid Holdorff,
Ruth's mom. ``But he was such a gentleman. You couldn't ask for
someone to be nicer to your daughter. She was very popular. I'm
sure there were lots of guys interested, but she was quite
definite.''
</P>
<P>
   The Most Handsome guy always dates the Most Beautiful girl in
the movies, but for Nolan and Ruth, that was real life as well.
Those were the tags given Nolan his sophomore year and Ruth as a
freshman by their Alvin High School classmates.
</P>
<P>
   ``We love to tease them about that,'' said their son Reese. ``We
always tell them there must not have been much to choose from.''
</P>
<P>
   They were two of the most popular as well. Nolan was an
all-around athlete, also excelling on the basketball court. Ruth
was the 1965 Class 3A state doubles tennis champion, a member of
the student council and a cheerleader.
</P>
<P>
   But all of Nolan's school-day memories aren't fond. Though a
leader on the field or court, he retreated in the classroom. As an
adult, it was discovered that he had dyslexia. But as a kid, he
simply felt stupid.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was really quiet,'' Ruth said. ``He struggled so much in
school because of the learning disability. One teacher thought he
was stupid and wanted to fail him. He was a C student, with a
couple of D's and F's mixed in. The hardest thing for him was
spelling. He also had a slight lisp, and as a result, he was shy in
the classroom.''
</P>
<P>
   By Ryan's sophomore year, most of his free time was spent
playing baseball. By his junior year, he was unstoppable.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sophomore year, I didn't know he was that good,'' said former
Alvin High School baseball coach Jim Watson. ``He was real skinny.
He didn't have a whole lot of physical strength at the time. But he
threw harder than any other kid I'd seen. He was a good hitter, so
we used him in a lot of spots. He'd come up through Pony League,
and a lot of those coaches told me he was a pretty good pitcher but
a better outfielder.''
</P>
<P>
   He worked mainly in relief that first year. In his first start,
against Deer Park on March 15, 1963, he pitched 3 innings and gave
up seven hits and two walks. He struck out four, hit one batter and
came away without a decision in a 4-3 loss.
</P>
<P>
   He got his first victory two weeks later, striking out 11 in 4
innings as Alvin beat Dickinson 2-1 on March 28.
</P>
<P>
   Ryan threw hard, but he was a bit wild. There was one game where
he hit four batters, another where he nailed three. But there were
just as many one- and two-hitters as Ryan began establishing
himself as one of the area's best pitchers.
</P>
<P>
   ``I swear, that ball jumped six to eight inches when it reached
the plate,'' Watson said. ``And he was wild. There were problems
with catchers who were afraid to catch him or couldn't hold onto
his ball.''
</P>
<P>
   George Pugh, a long-time neighbor and friend, was among those
who tried.
</P>
<P>
   ``You couldn't blink and catch it, I'll tell you that,'' Pugh
said. ``You couldn't sit back and relax. If it wasn't right down
the middle, you were going to have to move to get it.''
</P>
<P>
   Ryan went 7-2 his junior year, catching the eye of Mets scout
Red Murff, who first saw him play against Deer Park in a tournament
on March 21, 1964. Ryan gave up eight hits and three walks in 4
innings as Alvin lost 6-1. Four days later, Ryan pitched his first
complete game, allowing only three hits and striking out 12 as
Alvin beat West Columbia.
</P>
<P>
   ``Red Murff told me that Nolan had one of the top 10 arms in the
U.S., but I thought for sure he was exaggerating,'' Watson said.
``We didn't have a radar gun back then. I don't think I really
believed it until one afternoon when Nolan pitched a two-hitter.
Then my wife and I went to the Astrodome where Larry Dierker was
pitching against Jim Maloney. They were the two fireballers back
then. And I thought to myself, Nolan can throw faster than that.
That was the first indication that I had.''
</P>
<P>
   By Ryan's senior year, his fastball was becoming legendary
around small-town Texas. Alvin had only one .300 hitter on the team
that year, but it went to the state final on the strength of Ryan's
arm.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nolan didn't have any idea where the ball was going, but he
didn't have to thread the needle either,'' Watson said. ``Those
kids were so scared, they'd swing at anything just to get out of
there.''
</P>
<P>
   He went 6-0 to begin the season and didn't lose until his 10th
appearance. That 2-1 loss to Wharton on April 9, 1965, would be his
last in high school.
</P>
<P>
   On June 10, Ryan faced Brenham for the second time in the
regional playoffs. Three days earlier, he threw a complete game,
striking out 16 and allowing only six hits for a 2-1 victory in the
first of a three-game series. Brenham, the preseason favorite to
win the state title, tied the series by winning Game 2.
</P>
<P>
   As Game 3 started, Ryan clearly had his stuff. Alvin gave up a
run on an error, but Ryan got stronger as the innings passed,
striking out 12 and throwing his first official no-hitter in a 3-1
victory.
</P>
<P>
   ``Brenham had five guys off that team sign pro contracts,''
Watson said. ``They could hit. But I knew in the first inning that
Nolan was going to be awesome that night. He'd thrown a lot of
one-, two-hitters and taken a lot of no-hitters into the sixth or
seventh (they only played seven innings in high school), but this
was special. There was so much on the line and he knew we weren't
going to score a lot. He was just awesome.''
</P>
<P>
   He got one more win in high school, sending Alvin to the state
final. The Yellowjackets lost the title 6-3 to Waxahachie, with
Ryan getting a no-decision.
</P>
<P>
   And then the Mets came calling. Their call came late, as New
York selected Ryan 295th overall in the spring 1965 draft. To Ryan,
that was a sign that he should take some college classes and have a
backup plan.
</P>
<P>
   With the goal of transferring to Texas A&AMP;M and studying to
become a veterinarian, Ryan enrolled in Alvin Community College and
took a few courses during the baseball offseason. It quickly became
apparent that school would have to wait.
</P>
<P>
   Ruth recently was cleaning out some mementos when she came
across a notebook. For one of his courses, Ryan had been assigned
to write five future goals.
</P>
<P>
   ``Three of them were to own his own ranch (he now owns several),
to have his own cattle (he has herds) and to be able to play
major-league baseball,'' Ruth said. ``I think these were all things
he thought he'd never reach.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
