<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-15 15:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1411 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBO-RYAN-METS-HNS &LR;      07-15 1367
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-RYAN-METS-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
New York doesn't become apple of young pitcher's eye
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; By NEIL HOHLFELD &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; c. 1999, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Of all the places he could have landed to start his major-league
career in the late 1960s, New York City seemed the least desirable
for Nolan Ryan, a young country boy from Alvin, Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Ryan was the square peg. The Big Apple was the round hole. The
match just wasn't there. He was used to wide-open spaces and
friendly folks, commodities in short supply in New York.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hated that place,'' Ryan once said of his days in New York.
``I'd get cabin fever, sitting around the house. Then you'd drive
to the ballpark and, no matter what time you went, there would be
traffic and people getting in fights, honking, flipping people off,
yelling.''
</P>
<P>
   He wasn't in Alvin anymore, that was for sure.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to the culture shock, Ryan's formative years were
spent with an organization that was loaded with pitching talent,
another major factor in his 29-38 record over parts of five
seasons.
</P>
<P>
   Each time Ryan's control deserted him, or he developed those
persistent blisters on his right thumb and middle finger, or he had
to fulfill his military obligation by attending reserve camp during
the season, he slid farther down the depth chart.
</P>
<P>
   Led by farm director Whitey Herzog, the Mets had stockpiled
pitching. In addition to Tom Seaver, Jerry Koosman and Gary Gentry,
they had layers of pitchers underneath their upper crust.
</P>
<P>
   When the Mets gathered for the 1967 Instructional League, they
had 14 pitchers on their roster. Within one year, 11 of them had
made it to majors. It was easy for a pitcher with even Ryan's vast
potential to get pushed aside.
</P>
<P>
   There was little room for missteps by a young, untamed pitcher
whose ability was far from being harnessed. As much an outcast as
he was living in Queens, Ryan was equally on the outside in the
Mets' pitching scheme.
</P>
<P>
   Ryan had only one winning season, going 6-3 in 1969. In addition
to his well-documented blisters, Ryan had reserve duty and a groin
injury that kept him out of the mix for parts of that season.
</P>
<P>
   ``Looking back, it turned out to be one of those situations
where things just didn't match up,'' Ryan said. ``The combination
of how many good, young pitchers there were and my military
obligations, that made for some problems.''
</P>
<P>
   When Ryan was traded to the California Angels on Dec. 10, 1971,
he was hungry for the chance to escape New York. Frustrated by the
lack of clarity concerning his role and his own lack of success,
Ryan said he was close to quitting baseball in the summer of 1970
and again in '71. Only the persistence of his wife, Ruth, prevented
Ryan from returning to Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Ryan's career in the Mets organization started out much
brighter. In 1965, the first year of baseball's amateur draft, Ryan
was selected in the 10th round. In Ryan's first full season in
professional baseball, he was 17-2 with 272 strikeouts in 183
innings at Class A Greenville.
</P>
<P>
   To get a first-hand look at their latest pitching phenom, the
Mets called up Ryan late in the '66 season. After pitching once in
relief against Atlanta, Ryan made his first major-league start at
age 19 on Sept. 18, 1966, at the Astrodome, but it was hardly
memorable. Ryan lasted only one inning, striking out three batters
but walking three and allowing four runs in a 9-2 loss.
</P>
<P>
   Ryan was back in the minors at the start of the 1967 season, but
the first in a series of injuries set back his progress. While
warming up for a game at Class AA Jacksonville, Ryan felt a twinge
in his right forearm and was finished for the rest of the season.
</P>
<P>
   In those days, there was no such thing as exploratory surgery.
Ryan was sent home and told to report for the Instructional League
in October. His arm had improved by spring training in 1968, but
the Mets had a new manager in Gil Hodges and a pitching staff that
included Seaver, Koosman, Don Cardwell, Cal Koonce, Al Jackson,
Dick Selma and a host of young prospects.
</P>
<P>
   Ryan made his first start that season on Easter Sunday (April
14) in the Astrodome. This time, he was overpowering, striking out
seven of the first 10 batters he faced and earning his first
major-league victory, 4-0 over the Astros and Larry Dierker.
</P>
<P>
   Ryan, however, had to leave that game in the seventh inning when
he developed blisters on the middle finger of his right hand.
During the 1968 season, he twice spent time on the disabled list.
</P>
<P>
   The combination of the blisters and a stint in the reserves
interrupted what had started out as a good season. He was 6-5 on
June 23 but did not win a game the rest of the season, finishing
6-9 with 133 strikeouts and 75 walks in 134 innings.
</P>
<P>
   In 1969, the Mets pulled off an amazing turnaround by winning
the National League pennant over Atlanta and then shocking heavily
favored Baltimore in the World Series.
</P>
<P>
   For Ryan, it was a bittersweet season. He made only 10 starts,
slowed by military obligations and the depth of the Mets' staff. He
was used in relief 15 times, and at times it seemed the Mets were
leaning toward using him as a reliever despite his wildness.
</P>
<P>
   Hodges showed surprising faith in Ryan during the Mets'
clinching game of the National League Championship Series against
Atlanta. With runners on second and third, no one out and Rico
Carty at the plate, Ryan was brought in to relieve Gentry. He
struck out Carty, got out of the inning unscathed and allowed only
three hits the rest of the way in a 7-4 win that gave the Mets the
pennant.
</P>
<P>
   In the World Series, Ryan was bypassed as a starter and relieved
once. This time, he took over in Game 3 with the bases loaded and
two out in the seventh and gave up what looked to be an extra-base
hit to Paul Blair. A leaping catch by Tommie Agee in right-center
saved the day for the Mets, who went on to win 5-0, with Ryan
saving the win for Gentry. The Mets won the next two games and beat
the Orioles 4-1 in the Series.
</P>
<P>
   After coming through in the postseason pressure, Ryan seemed on
his way to stardom with the Mets early in the 1970 season. He
struck out 15 in a one-hit win over Philadelphia in April. In his
first 27 innings that season, Ryan allowed only six hits and struck
out 28 batters.
</P>
<P>
   But Ryan never sustained that pace. He finished the season at
7-11 and set a team record with 97 walks. The death of Ryan's
father at age 63 in Alvin hung over Nolan throughout the summer,
causing him again to consider quitting baseball.
</P>
<P>
   By 1971, it was clear that Ryan was no longer considered a
phenom by the Mets. They had Seaver, Koosman, Gentry and Jim
McAndrew as their top four in the starting rotation, meaning Ryan
was the fifth starter and his turn was skipped when the schedule _
and his military obligation _ dictated.
</P>
<P>
   Near the end of the season, Ryan went to Mets general manager
Bob Scheffing and asked to be traded. The Mets had a chance to
acquire veteran infielder Jim Fregosi from California and included
Ryan as part of a four-player package.
</P>
<P>
   Fregosi lasted little more than one season in New York and was
Ryan's manager in California in the late 1970s. Ryan, meanwhile,
initially was not overjoyed when he learned where he was headed.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd gone in to Bob Scheffing in September and told him I
thought it might be better for both of us if they had an
opportunity to move me to go ahead,'' Ryan said. ``That December,
the last day of the winter meetings, I had told Ruth that this
might be the day it happens.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was just walking out the door to go to class at Alvin
Community College when Ruth said it was Bob Scheffing on the phone.
He told me I was going to sunny California. I thought, all right,
I'm going to the Dodgers. I'd never even thought that it might be
the Angels. I didn't know much about them. But it worked out.
</P>
<P>
   ``I went to a team that was in the building stages and I got to
pitch every fourth day. My military obligation was over that year,
and I went from pitching 130 innings with the Mets to 300-plus
innings each year with the Angels. At that point in my career,
really, that's all I was looking for.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
