<DOCNO> NYT19990715.0197 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-15 15:52 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1415 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBO-RYAN-ASTROS-HNS &LR;      07-15 1597
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-RYAN-ASTROS-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
With stakes high, contract dispute forces a final move
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; By NEIL HOHLFELD &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; c. 1999, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   When Nolan Ryan signed as a free agent with the Astros on Nov.
19, 1979, money was no object. Astros owner John J. McMullen made
Ryan the highest-paid athlete in history by signing him to a
four-year contract worth approximately $4.4 million.
</P>
<P>
   Nine years later, when Ryan left the Astros to sign with the
Texas Rangers in December 1988, the relationship between McMullen
and Ryan had soured to the point where $300,000 prevented Ryan from
finishing his career in Houston.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought the contract I signed (in 1979) would be my last
one,'' said Ryan. ``I'd be 37 when that contract was up, and I
figured that would be it. I thought I'd pitch (in Houston) till
that contract was up and I'd finish my career with the Astros.''
</P>
<P>
   Instead, Ryan lasted until 1988 with the Astros and wanted to
pitch at least one more season. The day Ryan signed with the
Rangers was one of the darkest in Houston sports history.
</P>
<P>
   McMullen, who started out the decade of the 1980s as one of
baseball's free spenders, had become fiscally conservative by 1988.
He drew his line in the sand with Ryan, wanting the all-time
strikeout leader to take a 20 percent cut in his base salary of
$1.4 million.
</P>
<P>
   Incentives based on the number of starts could have made the
contract roughly equal to what Ryan made in 1988, but the way in
which the negotiations were handled turned McMullen into public
enemy No. 1 in Houston.
</P>
<P>
   Had the Astros offered Ryan the same amount of guaranteed money
in 1989, Ryan likely would have stayed. As negotiations unfolded,
Ryan quickly knew the Astros had no intention of keeping him, and
he was incensed that McMullen wanted him to take a pay cut.
</P>
<P>
   Astros fans were aghast when Ryan signed with the Rangers, who
gave him a two-year contract worth a total of $3.2 million before
re-signing him after the 1990 season. The publicity nightmare in
Houston lasted until McMullen sold the club to Drayton McLane Jr.
in 1992.
</P>
<P>
   ``That plane ride home from Atlanta (where the 1988 winter
meetings were held) was one of the low moments in my career,'' Ryan
said. ``I had thought all along that I'd finish my career with the
Astros. Instead of living at home, I was going to have to go
elsewhere. I wasn't sure what to expect.''
</P>
<P>
   As it turned out, Ryan went to the Rangers and found the
national attention that had eluded him during his time in Houston.
After pitching well into his 40s _ throwing two more no-hitters and
leading the American League in strikeouts twice _ Ryan was able to
reflect on his stormy relationship with McMullen.
</P>
<P>
   ``You know, I can look at my relationship now with John as a
positive,'' said Ryan. ``He brought me to Houston and gave me the
opportunity to pitch in my hometown for nine years. When things
didn't work out, I went to Texas for another five years. What I
thought was a negative turned out to be a positive.''
</P>
<P>
   Nine years earlier, Ryan had to overcome some negatives after
becoming the highest-paid professional athlete.
</P>
<P>
   In effect, it seemed McMullen bid against himself in 1979,
raising the price for Ryan to make a splash by cracking the $1
million mark. Ryan, uncomfortable with the attention of being the
highest-paid player in history, tried to shrug off the contract as
a sign of the times.
</P>
<P>
   In 1980, his first season with the Astros, the pressure was on
Ryan to deliver the team to its first division title. The Astros
started the season with a remarkable starting rotation, teaming
flamethrowers Ryan and J.R. Richard with knuckleballer Joe Niekro.
</P>
<P>
   In July, Richard suffered a stroke that ended his career. The
Astros let a big lead in the NL West over Los Angeles slip away in
the final weekend and had to win a one-game playoff for the
division title.
</P>
<P>
   They led Philadelphia two games to one in the best-of-five NL
Championship Series but lost the next two games in extra innings.
In Game 5, Ryan was on the mound with a 5-2 lead in the eighth
inning but failed to hold it. The Astros lost 8-7 in 10 innings.
</P>
<P>
   Before that game, Ryan was 112-3 with three no-decisions since
1972 when he had a lead after seven innings. The sudden and
unsuccessful finish to his first season in Houston remains with him
to this date.
</P>
<P>
   ``You get that close and don't make it, that stays with you a
long time,'' Ryan said. ``The same thing happened later (in 1986)
but that one stung, because we felt we were in good position to get
to the World Series. By then, I had played long enough to realize
what a unique opportunity it is to get there.''
</P>
<P>
   After going 11-10 in 1980, Ryan was dominant in the
strike-shortened 1981 season. He was 11-5 with a league-low 1.69
ERA. In 149 innings, he allowed only two home runs. On Sept. 26,
1981, Ryan pitched the fifth no-hitter of his career, passing Sandy
Koufax as the all-time leader.
</P>
<P>
   The 5-0 win over Los Angeles came as the Astros were on their
way to winning the second-half title in the NL West. They took a
2-0 lead over the Dodgers in the best-of-five first round of the
playoffs but once again failed to advance.
</P>
<P>
   Los Angeles won three straight games at Dodger Stadium. Ryan,
who won Game 1 on a two-hitter, was the losing pitcher in Game 5,
falling 4-0 to Jerry Reuss and the Dodgers, who went on to win the
World Series.
</P>
<P>
   From 1982 to 1985, the Astros were a bland team that finished 10
or more games out of first place three times in four seasons.
Attendance in the Astrodome dropped from 1.6 million in 1982 to 1.1
million in 1985.
</P>
<P>
   Ryan provided most of the few highlights during those years. In
1983, he became baseball's all-time strikeout leader, passing the
mark of 3,508 held by Walter Johnson. However, Ryan was a combined
52-44 in those four seasons, which were the hallmark of mediocrity.
</P>
<P>
   In 1985, Ryan was 10-12, his first losing season since 1978. He
had a 3.80 ERA, the highest since 1971, his final season with the
Mets. He was using a changeup more often and with greater
effectiveness by the end of the season, something that would allow
him to pitch longer than he ever dreamed he'd be able.
</P>
<P>
   To his surprise, he had not lost much off his fastball. Nor had
he lost any of the competitive fire. Though he was closing in on 40
years old, Ryan agreed to two contract extensions that he thought
would surely keep him in Houston for the rest of his career.
</P>
<P>
   He figured time was running out for him to return to a World
Series, where he had not been since 1969. In 1986, the Astros were
picked by one national sports publication to lose 100 games.
Instead, the Astros went 96-66 and won the NL West by 10 games.
</P>
<P>
   The top two starters in the Astros' rotation were Mike Scott,
who won the Cy Young Award, and lefthander Bob Knepper. Ryan twice
was put on the disabled list because of an elbow injury, and a
decision was made by Astros medical personnel to limit his pitches
to 100 in an attempt to spare his elbow from getting worse. He was
12-8 in 30 starts.
</P>
<P>
   Ryan was hardly ready for the old folks' home, though. The night
before Scott clinched the division title with a no-hitter over San
Francisco, Ryan struck out 16 Giants in eight innings and had a
no-hitter through 6 innings. He struck out 10 of the last 12
batters he faced, including five in a row.
</P>
<P>
   For the third time in Ryan's first seven seasons in Houston, the
Astros made it to the postseason. Once again, they failed to make
the World Series, losing one of the most memorable playoff series
ever in six games to the Mets.
</P>
<P>
   Ryan lost Game 2 of the series in the Astrodome and had no
decision in Game 5, when he hooked up against Dwight Gooden for a
1-1 tie through nine innings. Ryan pitched most of the game despite
suffering a hairline fracture in his left ankle while sliding into
second base.
</P>
<P>
   Ryan struck out eight of the first 12 batters he faced. He gave
up two hits in nine innings, walked one and struck out 12. The only
run he allowed was a home run by Darryl Strawberry in the fifth.
The Mets scored off the Astros' bullpen in the bottom of the 12th
for a 2-1 win and 3-2 edge in the series.
</P>
<P>
   ``I probably wanted to win that game more than any game I'd
pitched,'' Ryan said afterward.
</P>
<P>
   The Astros blew a 3-0 lead in the ninth inning of Game 6 the
next afternoon and eventually lost 7-6 in 16 innings. Once again,
Ryan was denied a chance for a World Series.
</P>
<P>
   In 1987, still working under a limit of 100 to 125 pitches that
he grew to despise, Ryan had a truly unbelievable season. He led
the league with a 2.76 ERA and 270 strikeouts in 211 innings.
However, he was 8-16, as the Astros averaged 3.35 runs in his 34
starts. In his 16 losses, Houston scored 13 runs while he was still
in the game. He went 0-5 in July but had a 2.36 ERA that month.
</P>
<P>
   One year later, it became clear that McMullen was going to dump
Ryan. There were many theories as to what happened between the men.
But whatever mad logic went into the thought process, the Astros
and their fans were the losers in this confrontation. Ryan,
meanwhile, went on to greater glory with the Rangers.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've always been a firm believer that things happen for a
reason,'' Ryan said. ``I was able to pitch in my hometown for nine
seasons because of John, and then I was able to move on to the
Rangers and have that great experience because of him, too.
</P>
<P>
   ``You look back on it, and I guess things worked out the way
they were supposed to work out.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-15-99 1552EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990715.0198 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-15 15:52 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1416 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBO-RYAN-ANGELS-HNS &LR;      07-15 1342
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-RYAN-ANGELS-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
Despite some shaky moments, California strikes gold
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; By BILL SULLIVAN &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; c. 1999, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   When the trade came down, folks in Southern California figured
it was the steal of the century.
</P>
<P>
   Trouble was, most worried that they were on the wrong end of the
heist.
</P>
<P>
   Some kid named Nolan Ryan was coming to the Angels. Big arm, no
clue where the ball was going, tepid results in parts of five
seasons with the New York Mets.
</P>
<P>
   And for this, the Angels had parted with Mr. Angel, the great
Jim Fregosi.
</P>
<P>
   Small wonder, then, that the transition from one coast to the
other and from National to American Leagues had its rocky moments _
all magnified by the arrival of son Reid and the specter of a
strike that threatened to delay the start of the season, and a
much-needed paycheck.
</P>
<P>
   Years later, Ryan would describe his eight years in Anaheim as
``the foundation of my career.'' It began, however, with more
moments in which he considered packing up and going home than ones
spent pondering the text for his acceptance speech in Cooperstown.
</P>
<P>
   For starters, the looming strike threatened to make Ryan a
rancher. That first spring training camp, the Ryans lived in a
borrowed trailer in Holtville, Calif. When the team moved on to
Palm Springs, Nolan made a daily 180-mile round trip commute in a
borrowed Volkswagen Beetle.
</P>
<P>
   Things were so tight that Ryan borrowed $1,500 to rent a house
in Anaheim for the season to come. Had the strike lasted very long
_ ultimately, opening day was delayed and eight games lost _ the
family would have been packing up and heading back to Alvin.
</P>
<P>
   Early on, some Angels fans probably wished he had done just
that. Ryan had what he termed ``a horrible spring,'' and it
continued with a 2-4 start in which he failed to last beyond the
fifth inning five times, rendering hearts all the fonder about the
departed Fregosi.
</P>
<P>
   Pitching coach Tom Morgan, who in time would become a close
friend, worked on streamlining Ryan's delivery. In late May, they
began to get results as Ryan won nine of 10 decisions, pitching
five consecutive complete games in the process.
</P>
<P>
   The run culminated with a one-hitter in which he struck out
eight straight batters and fanned the side on the minimum nine
pitches.
</P>
<P>
   By the time the smoke cleared, few were lamenting Fregosi, who
went on to become another in a long line of failed third-base
candidates with the Mets. After going 29-38 in New York, Ryan
finished that '72 season with a 19-16 record, leading the league in
strikeouts (329) and walks (157) while completing 20 games and
compiling a 2.28 earned-run average.
</P>
<P>
   Tom Grieve, then an outfielder with the first-year Texas
Rangers, says those numbers don't begin to tell the story.
</P>
<P>
   ``Back then, they didn't keep pitch counts,'' Grieve said. ``And
he's walking nine or 10 guys in some of those games. There were
probably a lot of times when he was throwing 200 pitches a game
when he was 22, 23 years old.''
</P>
<P>
   Grieve, later a Rangers general manager and now a television
announcer for the club, laughs at the notion.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have a guy throwing 200 pitches now, you'll be taken in
front of a judge for child abuse. The agent will get into it. The
league will investigate.''
</P>
<P>
   Ryan threw plenty of pitches the next two seasons, starting a
total of 83 games and finishing with records of 21-16 and 22-16. He
struck out a major-league record 383 hitters in '73 and 367 the
following year.
</P>
<P>
   In each of those seasons, the Angels scored a paltry 22 runs in
the 16 losses. Undaunted, Ryan posted ERAs of 2.87 and 2.89 and
threw a total of 52 complete games.
</P>
<P>
   He tossed the first of his seven no-hitters on May 15, 1973, at
Kansas City. His second came two months later at Detroit. No. 3
would follow on Sept. 28, 1974, at home against Minnesota.
</P>
<P>
   In one particularly gritty performance, Ryan threw 235 pitches
in a 13-inning outing against Boston and got a no-decision.
</P>
<P>
   A quarter-century later, Grieve vividly recounts the ``thrill''
of stepping to the plate against a young Nolan Ryan.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was the only pitcher I faced _ other than J.R. Richard in
Oklahoma City, where you couldn't see because of the lights _ that
fear entered into the at-bat,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was throwing so hard, and he was wild, and you knew he was
mean. He'd knock you down, and you never knew whether it was on
purpose or not.
</P>
<P>
   ``He had a curveball that he threw so hard, and it broke so
much. It started up around your head, and if you couldn't recognize
it and it turned out to be a fastball, you were going to get hit.''
</P>
<P>
   What to do?
</P>
<P>
   ``I backed off the plate a little bit. I backed up in the box a
little bit. Instead of being nice and relaxed up there, every part
of your body was alert.''
</P>
<P>
   Those years would showcase Ryan at his most dominant. In August
of '74, his fastball was clocked at 100.9 miles an hour, though
Ryan believes he has thrown harder than that.
</P>
<P>
   All that effort, however, would begin to exact a toll.
</P>
<P>
   In 1975, Ryan started the season 10-3 with five shutouts, seven
complete games and an ERA of 2.24. On June 1, he produced his
fourth no-hitter.
</P>
<P>
   Trouble, however, was on the way.
</P>
<P>
   Ryan's elbow had been hurting for months. After one mid-April
start, he awoke to discover that he could not fully extend his arm.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Frank Jobe, the noted orthopedist, prescribed ice and
whirlpool treatments, but the pain persisted. In August, after
losing nine of 13 decisions (eight straight at one point), Ryan
finally told the club he could go on no longer.
</P>
<P>
   Calcium deposits were removed. Once again, Ryan pondered the
question of whether he would pitch again.
</P>
<P>
   ``If my arm wasn't better the next spring,'' he said, ``I was
going to retire.''
</P>
<P>
   That wouldn't be necessary, though Ryan was up-and-down in 1976.
He pitched in 39 games and struck out 327 hitters but went 17-18
with a 3.36 ERA.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the issues were mental. Some of the trouble was because
of stiffness, and the elbow occasionally would catch. In trying to
compensate, Ryan fell into bad habits as well.
</P>
<P>
   He lost five straight in May but came back to win seven of his
last eight decisions and finished with 21 complete games, seven of
them shutouts. The following year, he went 19-16 with 341
strikeouts and a 2.77 ERA, , with 22 complete games and four
shutouts.
</P>
<P>
   But the good times in Anaheim were coming to an end.
</P>
<P>
   In 1978, Buzzie Bavasi arrived as executive vice president. A
month later, GM Harry Dalton left after Bavasi accused him of
running a ``country club.''
</P>
<P>
   Ryan didn't like Bavasi or his ways, and physical problems added
to the pitcher's misery.
</P>
<P>
   A pulled hamstring put Ryan on the disabled list from June 14 to
July 5. Later, a rib separation landed him on the DL from Aug. 20
to Sept. 6.
</P>
<P>
   In the end, a 10-13 season and a 3.71 ERA had Bavasi eyeing the
bottom line as Ryan eyed the door.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wouldn't have come back as long as he was the general
manger,'' Ryan said.
</P>
<P>
   His contract, however, ran one more season, and it would be an
eventful one.
</P>
<P>
   Reid, then 7, was struck by a car, eventually losing his spleen
and a kidney. As his son endured a lengthy hospital stay, Nolan was
helping the Angels win the American League West for the first time.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the distractions, Ryan finished 16-14 with a 3.59 ERA
and 17 complete games. His contract was up, and agent Dick Moss
approached the Angels with an incentive-heavy proposal that could
have made Ryan the game's first $1 million player.
</P>
<P>
   Bavasi scoffed at the offer. In one particularly colorful
moment, he indicated he could replace Ryan with two 8-7 pitchers.
</P>
<P>
   Thirteen years later, that comment echoed when, in June 1992,
the Angels retired Ryan's number while he was still pitching in the
major leagues. And while Nolan speaks fondly of the California
years, life once again was changing.
</P>
<P>
   Bavasi would save his money. The Ryans were on their way back to
Houston.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
