<DOCNO> NYT19990715.0200 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-15 15:54 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1419 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBO-RYAN-HOHITTERS-HN     07-15 1368
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-RYAN-HOHITTERS-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
Chances of topping no-hitter mark far-flug
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; By BILL SULLIVAN &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; c. 1999, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ARLINGTON _ Some of the numbers were inevitable. Pitch 27
seasons, throw 95 miles per hour _ or better _ for more than a
quarter-century, and certain things are likely to come a fellow's
way.
</P>
<P>
   Those 324 wins, for instance, represent a relatively modest 12
per year. The 5,714 strikeouts, impressive as they are, remain at
least partly a product of longevity as well.
</P>
<P>
   Magic moments, however, are a very different matter. There is no
grinding them out. They arrive, instead, as a by-product of
personal brilliance, of a rare sense of history and theater, and no
one enjoyed more of them along the way than Lynn Nolan Ryan.
</P>
<P>
   Those seven no-hitters tell part of the story, but only part.
</P>
<P>
   ``There were a lot of other ones that were real close,'' he
said. ``You tend to forget them.''
</P>
<P>
   Baseball _ the ultimate numbers game _ does not forget. Delve
into the record books a little, and the true extent of Nolan Ryan's
dominance becomes even more apparent.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to the magnificent seven, Ryan pitched 12
one-hitters between 1970 and 1990. He also had 19 two-hitters, 31
three-hitters and 27 four-hit games in the course of his career.
</P>
<P>
   Those may be the truest measure of 27 years of throwing heat. It
is those seven times Ryan walked off the mound with a ``0'' under
the ``H,'' though, that are at the heart of the legend.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nolan threw it down the strike zone harder than any human
being I ever saw,'' said Jeff Torborg, who caught Ryan's first
no-hitter on May 15, 1973. ``In 1973, against the Red Sox, he threw
a pitch a little up and over my left shoulder.
</P>
<P>
   ``I reached up for it, and it tore a hole in the webbing of my
glove and hit the backstop at Fenway Park.''
</P>
<P>
   Certainly, Ryan was throwing hard enough when he overpowered the
Kansas City Royals 3-0 for no-hitter No. 1. He struck out 12 and
walked only three, and the lone close call came when shortstop Rudy
Meoli made an over-the-shoulder catch of a popup into short left
center.
</P>
<P>
   Two months later, Ryan would do it again, becoming the fifth
pitcher in history to throw two no-hitters in a season.
</P>
<P>
   This time, he would make it look even easier.
</P>
<P>
   Against the Tigers in Detroit, he struck out 17, with 16 of
those coming in the first seven innings. His arm stiffened a bit in
the course of the Angels' five-run eighth inning but he had enough
left to close the deal.
</P>
<P>
   Ryan was quick, and tricky as well.
</P>
<P>
   ``He had an excellent curveball, too,'' catcher Art Kusnyer
said. ``He'd throw the curve 88 to 90 miles an hour. Guys would
swing straight down at it. I couldn't believe it.''
</P>
<P>
   The Tigers' Norm Cash evidently couldn't, either. Late in the
game, Cash came to the plate with a table leg instead of a bat,
telling home-plate umpire Ron Luciano that it would make no
difference.
</P>
<P>
   Ryan nearly made it back-to-back no-hitters his next time out,
taking a no-hitter into the eighth, and he added a one-hitter in
August of that same season.
</P>
<P>
   The following year, he would save his best for last. On Sept.
24, in his final start of the season, Ryan turned in no-hitter No.
3 in a 4-0 win over the Twins in Anaheim.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nolan definitely had it that day,'' said Tom Egan, who caught
Ryan's third no-no. ``It was like driving a powerful sports car. It
was fun going along for that ride.''
</P>
<P>
   Meoli again was a big part of the game, making two tough plays
on grounders in a game in which Ryan walked eight.
</P>
<P>
   No. 4 _ the one that tied Sandy Koufax for most ever _ took
shape on June 1, 1975, again in Anaheim. It also came as something
of a surprise to catcher Ellie Rodriguez, who feared trouble as the
two warmed up.
</P>
<P>
   ``He didn't have his good stuff at all,'' Rodriguez said later.
``He was having a tough time.''
</P>
<P>
   Unbeknownst to Rodriguez or anyone else on the team, Ryan was
having elbow problems. He gradually found his fastball as the game
went on, but his choice for the concluding pitch spoke of trouble.
</P>
<P>
   With Bobby Grich at the plate and a 2-2 count, Rodriguez called
for another fastball. Ryan shook him off and went for a changeup,
which a stunned Grich took for a called third strike.
</P>
<P>
   ``I threw very few changeups in those days,'' Ryan said. ``But I
knew if I threw one and got it over the plate, I had him.
</P>
<P>
   ``And I did.''
</P>
<P>
   It would be six years, and another change of leagues, before he
would add to the total and his legend. The record would become
Ryan's alone on Sept. 26, 1981, when he pitched at home for the
Astros against the Los Angeles Dodgers.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was the one thing I wanted,'' he said later. ``I'd had a
shot at it for a long time, but because of my age (then 34), I
thought I wouldn't get it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't have the stamina I used to have, but that day I
really had my curveball working and I got ahead of the hitters.''
</P>
<P>
   With Alan Ashby behind the plate, Ryan struck out 11 and walked
just three. Dusty Baker grounded to Art Howe at third for the final
out of a 5-0 game.
</P>
<P>
   That last pitch, Ashby recalls, flirted with disaster. It was a
high curve, but Baker _ looking for a fastball _ got too far out
front and hit the ball on the ground.
</P>
<P>
   ``To be able to catch that one, the one that broke the record,
was a mind-boggling experience,'' Ashby said.
</P>
<P>
   For Ryan, it was meaningful in another way.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was home,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Ryan would not be done boggling minds, though it would be a long
wait between no-hitters _ so long, in fact, that he had just about
given up on the idea.
</P>
<P>
   Certainly, June 11, 1990, didn't seem to be his day.
</P>
<P>
   His back hurt so much that he had an appointment scheduled with
a specialist the next day. In his previous five starts, he was 0-3
with an earned-run average of 8.86. In the course of the game
against the A's in Oakland, 14-year-old Reese sat next to his
father in the dugout, rubbing his back.
</P>
<P>
   Ryan also was working for the first time with John Russell, a
journeyman catcher the Rangers had called up in the wake of
injuries to Mike Stanley and Geno Petralli.
</P>
<P>
   ``He had some trouble with his back early,'' Russell said that
night. ``But then he started getting stronger.''
</P>
<P>
   Ryan needed 132 pitches to record No. 6, and 93 of those were
fastballs. He struck out 14 and was helped by the fact that the A's
were without regulars Jose Canseco (bad back), Carney Lansford
(bicep) and Mark McGwire, who had struck out against Ryan three
times the previous week.
</P>
<P>
   As he had done in his second no-hitter 17 years earlier, Ryan
called his own pitches.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was his game,'' Russell said. ``He had that look, unlike
anything I'd ever seen. He smelled it.''
</P>
<P>
   Less than a year later, Ryan would pick up the scent one more
time. It would be perhaps the most memorable night in Rangers
history, and the man at the center of the excitement once more
displayed a keen sense of the moment, even at age 44.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not saying he pitched that no-hitter because it was
Arlington Appreciation Night,'' Rangers broadcaster Tom Grieve
recalled with a smile. ``But he knew it was.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a big crowd, and he was probably giving them something
a little extra. Once he realized it, he was going for it.''
</P>
<P>
   Pitching on three days' rest in order to appear on the special
occasion, Ryan was overpowering. He retired 27 of 29 batters,
walking Kelly Gruber in the first and Joe Carter in the seventh. He
tied his club record with 16 strikeouts, the last of those ending
the game when he got Roberto Alomar with his 122nd pitch.
</P>
<P>
   The identity of the victim underscored just how long this no-hit
business had been going on: Alomar's father, Sandy, was a Ryan
teammate with the Angels in the 1970s.
</P>
<P>
   Now, Nolan was picking on a second generation.
</P>
<P>
   ``He taught me how to pitch when I was a little kid,'' Roberto
Alomar said. ``And I got my first major-league hit off him.
</P>
<P>
   ``I guess this was his way of repaying me.''
</P>
<P>
   In doing so, Ryan made the younger Alomar a footnote to history
_ the last out of the last no-hitter in a record that may never be
approached, much less broken.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
