<HEADER>
A1422 &Cx1f; tab-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-`VIRTUAL'-WALLETS-WOR     07-15 0831
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-`VIRTUAL'-WALLETS-WORTH-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE BILLFOLD OF THE FUTURE FOR INTERNET SHOPPERS  
 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Personal-Finance and Lifestyle Editors)   (This ``separate buy'' 625-word personal-finance story is from
``WORTH'' magazine. To publish this article, it must be purchased
from the New York Times Syndicate's sales representative DEBRA
WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or fax her at 732-390-4697. Her e-mail
address is Debra/Weydert/CORPHQ/NYTIMES. If unable to reach Ms.
Weydert, please call 800-444-0267, or fax us at 816-822-1444.)  
  
 (PLEASE NOTE: This article has been filed into the ``f'' financial
news, ``a'' domestic/general news and ``l'' lifestyle news
files.)  
  
 By ALLAN HOFFMAN  
 c.1999 Worth Magazine  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Just 1.6 percent of visits to online merchants result in a
purchase, according to a study by the Boston Consulting Group for
Shop.org, an industry organization for Web retailers.
</P>
<P>
   Why? After security and privacy concerns, consumers cite the
need to reenter personal data at different merchants as one of the
main drawbacks of shopping online, says David Pecaut, head of the
E-commerce practice at Boston Consulting.
</P>
<P>
   ``The wallet,'' he says, ``has the potential to make things much
simpler.''
</P>
<P>
   What's a virtual wallet? Simply a standardized form into which
you enter your name, address, and credit-card number. Every time
you make a purchase online, the affiliated merchant gets access to
your billing and mailing data from the wallet.
</P>
<P>
   A boon for cyber-shoppers? It promises to be, but it isn't yet.
</P>
<P>
   The assortment of wallets is likely to confuse even hard-core
techies. Expect to encounter pitches for virtual wallets from
online stores, Web portal sites like Yahoo and Excite, and banks.
</P>
<P>
   ``We will have a chaotic period,'' says Denis Yaro, executive
vice-president of CyberCash, an electronic-commerce company in
Reston, Va.
</P>
<P>
   The CyberCash solution, InstaBuy, lets you sign up for a wallet
at a participating merchant and use it to shop at other InstaBuy
retailers.
</P>
<P>
   Through partnerships with SkyMall and the Impulse Buy Network,
InstaBuy customers have access to more than 150 stores, including
such high-end retailers as Calyx &AMP; Corolla and Sharper Image.
</P>
<P>
   InstaBuy is a ``server-based'' solution: It stores your personal
data on a remote computer. Obviously aware of consumers' concerns
about hackers, CyberCash is teaming up with financial institutions,
such as First USA, to secure shoppers' financial information.
</P>
<P>
   America Online has a wallet of its own, enabling consumers to
shop at affiliated merchants without reentering personal data.
</P>
<P>
   AOL's Quick Checkout lets members store information for up to 10
credit cards and 50 shipping addresses; the data is kept on AOL's
servers. For security reasons, the full credit-card number is never
displayed.
</P>
<P>
   Yet another option is eWallet, a software application that can
be downloaded (at www.ewallet.com). EWallet stores your personal
data on your computer, which may be more secure, but this also
requires you to install and maintain the software yourself.
</P>
<P>
   EWallet works at nearly all Web stores; when you're ready to
make a purchase, eWallet helps you with the forms. During the
holiday season, about 250,000 copies of eWallet were downloaded.
</P>
<P>
   For all the uncertainty over the eventual standard-bearer, one
thing is certain: Not all of these wallets will be in use a year
from now.
</P>
<P>
   In the standard-less interim, choose a wallet with care. Don't
try them all, or you may find yourself with multiple accounts at
some merchants. Consider the stores connected with the wallet; for
now, selection is probably the deciding factor.
</P>
<P>
   If you're a regular at just one or two online shops, don't
bother with a wallet. As with much that involves consumer
technology, you won't miss a lot by waiting.
</P>
<P>
   Eventually, one or more of these systems will achieve that magic
combo of convenience and ubiquity. Until then, America Online and
the portal sites have an edge, largely because they have the
attention of millions of consumers.
</P>
<P>
   The ultimate winner will let you buy from any store on the Web,
or close to it, without downloading software to your PC. By then,
the wallet will help you find the best prices for your items of
choice.
</P>
<P>
   The wallet may even suggest, based on your past purchases, what
wines or books you might like to buy. Sort of scary, but
convenient, too. ``Chaos doesn't reign very long,'' says Yaro. ``It
won't be tolerated.'' &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; _______ &QC;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (To publish this 625-word ``WORTH'' magazine article, it must
be purchased from the New York Times Syndicate's sales
representative DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or fax her at
732-390-4697. Her e-mail address is Debra/Weydert/CORPHQ/NYTIMES.
If unable to reach Ms. Weydert, please call 800-444-0267, or fax us
at 816-822-1444.) &LR;  &QL;
</P>
