<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-15 15:55 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1430 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBO-RYAN-RANGERS-HNS &LR;      07-15 1305
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-RYAN-RANGERS-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
Arlington fans get hospitality repaid during five-year stay
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; By BILL SULLIVAN &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; c. 1999, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ARLINGTON _ Baseball's winter meetings were in Atlanta that
year, and Tom Grieve had no idea what a big splash either he or the
Texas Rangers would make at the annual press-and-peddle-the-flesh
gathering.
</P>
<P>
   Coming off a tepid 1988 season, the Rangers were generally
regarded as a second-rate organization, an image fostered by 17
pennant-free seasons since the former Washington Senators arrived
in North Texas in 1972. Playing at Arlington Stadium _ a converted
minor-league facility that very much looked the part _ didn't do
much to enhance the profile, either.
</P>
<P>
   All of that would change with a few unexpected strokes of the
pen.
</P>
<P>
   ``We didn't have any idea that Nolan was going to leave
Houston,'' Grieve, then the Rangers' general manager, said. ``I
think everybody in baseball assumed he was going to stay with the
Astros.
</P>
<P>
   ``When it became apparent that things weren't working out in
Houston, I called Dick Moss, who was Nolan's agent, and told Dick
that if Nolan didn't go back to Houston, that the Rangers would
have a lot of interest.''
</P>
<P>
   So did the Angels, Nolan Ryan's old team. The San Francisco
Giants, who would go on to the World Series that year, made
inquiries, too.
</P>
<P>
   But Ryan already had done California. He would have preferred to
stay in Houston, but owner John McMullen was trying to cut costs,
and a pitcher who had won just 20 of 47 decisions the previous two
years seemed _ to McMullen, at least _ like a good place to start
trimming.
</P>
<P>
   The wheels were turning for one final change of venue in Ryan's
remarkable career.
</P>
<P>
   ``Eddie Chiles, who owned the team at the time, said to do
whatever it takes,'' Grieve said. ``So we pretty much gave Nolan a
blank contract, told him to fill in the blanks and signed our names
to it.''
</P>
<P>
   A club with a long history of bad trades and ill-fated
free-agent signings never made a better investment. Not only did
Ryan bring instant credibility to a sad-sack franchise, but he
brought an added bonus:
</P>
<P>
   He could still pitch.
</P>
<P>
   In his first season as a Ranger, Ryan won 16 games, struck out
301 batters (his highest total since 1977) and pitched six complete
games, two of them shutouts. That would be his most productive
season of the five he spent in Arlington, but it would not be the
end of memorable moments as Ryan put the finishing touches on his
Hall of Fame credentials.
</P>
<P>
   He pitched his sixth and seventh no-hitters. He registered his
300th win and his 5,000th strikeout.
</P>
<P>
   ``One reason his impact was so great was that no one expected
him to pitch more than two years,'' says Gov. George W. Bush, who
headed an ownership group that took over the club soon after Ryan
was signed. ``We thought he'd be a two-year wonder, and he pitched
a lot longer than that.''
</P>
<P>
   Other images further enhanced the legend.
</P>
<P>
   There was, for instance, the time he stayed in the game after a
shot off the bat of Bo Jackson bloodied his lip and stained the
front of his jersey. Even more memorable was the sight of Ryan
corralling a mound-charging Robin Ventura in a headlock and
proceeding to give the younger player a Texas-style whupping.
</P>
<P>
   After the bench-emptying brawl subsided, Ryan went on to pitch
seven innings, allowing one earned run in a 5-2 Rangers victory.
</P>
<P>
   Those images underscored Ryan's toughness and competitiveness.
Off the field, his folksy manner charmed fans (and advertising
executives) as the one-time boy wonder became a timeless, ageless
wonder.
</P>
<P>
   ``The years I spent with the Rangers were the ones that put me
over the top,'' Ryan said, explaining why he will enter the Hall of
Fame as a Ranger.
</P>
<P>
   Suddenly, everything old was new again.
</P>
<P>
   New league.
</P>
<P>
   New team.
</P>
<P>
   New image.
</P>
<P>
   All of it, though, was based on something very much the same.
</P>
<P>
   ``If he couldn't pitch anymore, he would have been just another
guy,'' Grieve says now. ``Because of his personality, the fans
accepted him a lot more easily, but if Nolan was the world's
biggest jerk and pitched the way he did, he would have reached the
same heights.''
</P>
<P>
   His first three years as a Ranger, Ryan won 41 games while
losing just 25. Those years were even more memorable for the
milestones passed and indelible memories made.
</P>
<P>
   On Aug. 22, 1989, Oakland's Rickey Henderson become Ryan's
5,000th strikeout victim, the record Ryan says he cherishes most.
</P>
<P>
   ``It represented that many innings pitched and being able to
maintain that style of pitching my entire career,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   That same year, Ryan twice took no-hitters into the ninth before
falling short.
</P>
<P>
   No-hitter No. 6 finally came on June 11, 1990, at the Oakland
Coliseum at the age of 43 years, 4 months, 12 days, making him the
oldest pitcher to accomplish the feat. On July 31 of that same
year, he won his 300th game, beating the Brewers in Milwaukee.
</P>
<P>
   A seventh and final no-hitter followed on May 1, 1991, in
Arlington.
</P>
<P>
   Others have won 300, of course, and Ryan already had set the
mark for most no-hitters when he produced No. 5 as an Astro on
Sept. 26, 1981, breaking a tie with Sandy Koufax.
</P>
<P>
   It was the Rangers years, though, that enabled Ryan to push
those records virtually out of reach.
</P>
<P>
   His 5,714 strikeouts virtually lap the field, and it is the
record that may never be approached, much less threatened.
</P>
<P>
   Steve Carlton, No. 2 on the all-time list, trails by 1,578.
Fellow Texan Roger Clemens, the only active player in the all-time
top 10, entered the current season with 3,153 career strikeouts and
would need to average nearly 260 strikeouts for 10 seasons to catch
Ryan.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nolan's record is so far out there it isn't even worth
thinking about,'' Clemens said this spring.
</P>
<P>
   Clemens will turn 37 in August, making a run at the record all
the more unlikely.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's tough to get motivated,'' Grieve said. ``If you're good
enough to be considered to break those records, you're making a ton
of money.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now you've got a family. You've got kids. Is a guy like Roger
going to be able to stay motivated to pitch at that level until
he's 45 years old? Probably not.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nolan was. Don't ask me how. That was the most amazing thing
about Nolan Ryan, to me, to stay focused and maintain that edge for
27 years.''
</P>
<P>
   To the end, a big part of the Ryan mythology was that he
remained accessible to the public throughout that career. In an era
of outrageous salaries and testy stars, Ryan became all the more
extraordinary by being ordinary. At spring training, he would stand
in the sun for hours, signing balls, caps, jerseys, you name it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nolan was a hero who didn't let you down,'' Bush said. ``In
this day and age, you have heroes who let you down by the decisions
they make in life.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nolan never let us down.''
</P>
<P>
   Ryan's career ended a little earlier than he had planned when he
injured his elbow in the first inning of a Sept. 22, 1993, start in
Seattle's Kingdome. His last appearance in a Rangers uniform came
on Oct. 3, when he exchanged lineup cards with Kansas City's George
Brett, who was playing his final game for the Royals.
</P>
<P>
   The two will be linked again in Cooperstown.
</P>
<P>
   &QC;
</P>
<P>
   Just inside the second base entrance at the Ballpark in
Arlington _ which opened the season after Ryan retired _ a likeness
of the most famous figure ever to grace a Rangers uniform greets
fans as they enter the team's state-of-the-art home.
</P>
<P>
   The first time he saw the statue, the honoree _ still very much
alive and well, thank you _ allowed himself a nod of approval.
</P>
<P>
   ``They did a nice job,'' he said in typical low-key fashion.
</P>
<P>
   So did Lynn Nolan Ryan, though there was hardly anything low-key
about it.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
