<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-15 15:55 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1426 &Cx1f; tab-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BEWARE-JOB-CONTRACTS!     07-15 1433
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BEWARE-JOB-CONTRACTS!-WORTH-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOW TO SAFELY NEGOTIATE THE EMPLOYMENT-CONTRACT MINEFIELD  
 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Business Editors)   (This useful ``separate buy'' financial/career-oriented story is
from ``WORTH'' magazine. To publish this article, it must be
purchased from the New York Times Syndicate's sales representative
DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or fax her at 732-390-4697. Her
e-mail address is Debra/Weydert/CORPHQ/NYTIMES. If unable to reach
Ms. Weydert, please call 800-444-0267, or fax us at
816-822-1444.)  
  
 (ATTN. EDITORS: FOR THOSE DESIRING A SHORTER VERSION, THIS
USER-FRIENDLY ARTICLE OFFERS A 175-WORD OPTIONAL TRIM AT 675. TOTAL
UNCUT VERSION IS 1,150 WORDS.)  
  
 (PLEASE NOTE: This article has been filed into the ``f'' financial
news, ``a'' domestic/general news and ``l'' lifestyle news
files.)  
  
 By STEPHEN M. POLLAN  
 c.1999 Worth Magazine  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Sought after though they have become, employment contracts are
fraught with pitfalls for executives.
</P>
<P>
   Their status as status symbol is, of itself, a danger. Managers
often are so flattered to have one they don't realize what they've
signed away to get it.
</P>
<P>
   What's more, even the most seemingly innocuous provisions _ such
as the basic job description _ can have unexpected consequences.
Boss to employee: ``It says here you agreed to work anywhere in the
U.S. I'm sure you'll just love your new assignment in Hammond,
Indiana.''
</P>
<P>
   Look at it this way: Your employer undoubtedly has negotiated a
lot more of these deals than you ever will (or at least let's hope
that's the case). So who's more likely to gain the upper hand?
</P>
<P>
   To help even the odds, here's a provision-by-provision guide to
the modern employment contract, along with some pointers.
</P>
<P>
   1. TERM: This section defines the length of the contract _ one
year, two years, etc. Its inclusion is more than a formality. In
most states, employers can fire an employee for any reason at any
time and without further compensation (unless civil-rights or
discrimination laws apply).
</P>
<P>
   However, if your contract specifies the term of employment,
you're entitled to receive the balance due if you're canned without
cause (as defined in Section 5 of this article).
</P>
<P>
   2. DUTIES: Many employment contracts are far too vague or
sketchy when it comes to defining the job itself. There's nothing
wrong with flexibility, of course _ so long as everyone's happy.
But if the relationship sours, latitude makes it possible for an
employer to dream up loathsome or even humiliating work assignments
_ perhaps in a deliberate effort to persuade the employee to quit.
</P>
<P>
   Remember, you and your employer can always agree to make changes
in a contract. So if your pride can't stand emptying the trash or
having your desk moved to the stairwell, make sure your contract
says something about what you'll be doing and where you will be
doing it. (One client of mine got a clause that allowed him to work
one month each year in Vail, Colo.).
</P>
<P>
   Get as specific a description of your duties and
responsibilities as you can. If that's not possible, at least make
sure this section of your contract says that your duties will be
restricted to those that are ``reasonable and customary'' for the
position you hold.
</P>
<P>
   3. COMPENSATION: The rule here: If it ain't written down, it
ain't going to end up in your pocket.
</P>
<P>
   Everything that can be remotely considered compensation _ from
vacation days and perks to salary and stock options _ should be
detailed in this section. (This is where you can ask for a rabbi
trust or a paid-for vacation home in the Hamptons, as clients of
mine have done.)
</P>
<P>
   Unless you don't expect a raise during the time period covered
by the agreement, this section should also spell out the procedure
for determining pay increases.
</P>
<P>
   4. EXCLUSIVE EMPLOYMENT: Many companies today offer employment
contracts precisely because they want their charges to sign a
document that restricts their ability to jump ship _ or take
proprietary information with them when they do.
</P>
<P>
   The covenants contained in this section are where employers seek
to obtain this protection. In other words: Watch your flanks. Your
objective should be to give yourself as much career flexibility as
possible.
</P>
<P>
   Employers like to push for extreme limits on whom you can work
for and when. In a sense, they'd just as soon have you drop off the
face of the earth if you're not going to be toiling for them.
</P>
<P>
   In examining the validity of the exclusions contained in this
section, courts weigh the employer's legitimate business interests
against the ability of an employee to earn a livelihood.
</P>
<P>
   For instance, a court might agree to bar the employee of a
children's TV program on cable television from working for another
show with a similar audience. But the court might let the employee
work for a cable-TV show about monster trucks. &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (175-WORD OPTIONAL TRIM BEGINS HERE AT 675) &LR;  &QC; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   While there's no requirement for employers to offer employees
compensation for these covenants, such payments have sometimes
helped courts overcome their problems with employee livelihood.
</P>
<P>
   In other words, if you can't eliminate or soften restrictions on
where you can earn a living, try to shorten the period and/or get
compensation for them.
</P>
<P>
   You can also work to subtly undermine exclusions you can't
negotiate away through your choice of the law governing the
agreement (see Section 7. Governing Law. Jurisdiction).
</P>
<P>
   Companies understandably try to keep all internal information
confidential. Nevertheless, courts have ruled that there are limits
to confidentiality. Client lists, for instance, are protected only
if the information can't be obtained elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
   Similarly, publicly known or previously published contracts,
pricing policies, and buying habits aren't protected. That doesn't
mean the provisions don't have some teeth: Courts have held
employees liable for the disclosure of confidential information
whether or not the disclosure was willful. &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (END OF OPTIONAL TRIM) &LR;  &QC; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   5. REASONS FOR TERMINATION: A paragraph should be added that
provides for a ``cure period'' during which, after a warning, you
are given a chance to address your employer's complaints about your
work. This should apply to performance issues _ a failure to
produce promised results _ instead of, say, a conviction for
insider trading.
</P>
<P>
   If your employer balks at such language, explain that the firm
will benefit by having its potential exposure to litigation
limited.
</P>
<P>
   An additional reason for termination is ``change of control or
ownership.'' This should be specifically listed here so that it can
be discussed in the subsequent section.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, wording should be included that calls or ample notice
(such as six months) if your contract isn't going to be renewed.
</P>
<P>
   6. RESULTS OF TERMINATION: Ask for full payment of your
contracted salary if you're terminated without cause or if your
employer breaches the agreement. But be prepared to cut a deal. By
expanding the reasons for termination in the previous section, you
can include language here outlining your severance rights after a
change in management or ownership.
</P>
<P>
   7. GOVERNING LAW. JURISDICTION: This may seem like neutral
boilerplate. It's not. The common-law obligations of employers and
employees vary from state to state. So, too, does the way local
courts interpret and enforce the covenants outlined in Section 4.
</P>
<P>
   The choice of governing law and jurisdiction in the agreement
will ultimately determine what elements of Section 4 can be
enforced and how strenuously they will be enforced.
</P>
<P>
   Use the state law most beneficial to you. If, for example, you
work in the California office of a corporation headquartered in
Alabama, your employer will want Alabama law to govern the
contract, since it's considered employer-friendly. But California
law is employee-friendly. &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (EDITOR'S NOTE: Stephen M. Pollan writes about career-related
issues for WORTH with his co-author Mark Levine.) &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; _______ &QC;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (To publish this 1,150-word ``WORTH'' magazine article, it must
be purchased from the New York Times Syndicate's sales
representative DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or fax her at
732-390-4697. Her e-mail address is Debra/Weydert/CORPHQ/NYTIMES.
If unable to reach Ms. Weydert, please call 800-444-0267, or fax us
at 816-822-1444.) &LR;  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
