<DOCNO> NYT19990715.0209 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-15 15:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1432 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBO-RYAN-STRIKEOUTS-H     07-15 1434
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-RYAN-STRIKEOUTS-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
Fastball helps blaze the way for record performance
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; By NEIL HOHLFELD &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; c. 1999, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Of all the records and accomplishments in Nolan Ryan's career,
this one could be the most telling:
</P>
<P>
   Ryan finished with 5,714 career strikeouts, which puts him 1,578
ahead of Steve Carlton, who had 4,136 and is second on the all-time
list. That is the largest percentage difference between first and
second in any major statistical category in baseball.
</P>
<P>
   Think of it this way. If a pitcher made his major-league debut
today and finished a few years later with 1,578 strikeouts, people
would say he had a nice career. Ryan finished his career with that
many more strikeouts than any other pitcher in the history of
baseball.
</P>
<P>
   If a pitcher broke in this season and had designs on overtaking
Ryan for the all-time strikeout lead, he would need to average 200
strikeouts for more than 28 seasons. If he averaged 250 strikeouts,
it would take nearly 23 seasons to catch Ryan. Averaging 300
strikeouts, he would need 19 seasons.
</P>
<P>
   ``People talk about records that won't be broken,'' said Astros
coach Matt Galante, ``but Nolan's strikeout record is right near
the top. You have to have the combination of high strikeout totals
and longevity. Those are two things that don't often go together.
</P>
<P>
   ``Pitchers with a lot of strikeouts, for a lot of reasons, don't
last that long. To do what Nolan did and keep doing it for as long
as he did _ you won't see that again.''
</P>
<P>
   From Pat Jarvis (No. 1 in 1966) to Greg Myers (No. 5,714 in
1993), from Hall of Famer Henry Aaron to bit player Paul Zuvella,
Ryan's strikeouts went on and on and on. He struck out a total of
1,176 players, including eight father-and-son combinations, 12 sets
of brothers and 27 members of Baseball's Hall of Fame _ including
1999 fellow inductees George Brett (18 times) and Robin Yount (16).
</P>
<P>
   Throughout his career, Ryan's signature was his blazing
fastball. And while that pitch had much to do with his abundant
strikeout totals, he never would have reached the remarkable
figures without another pitch. One fallacy of Ryan's career is that
he was all smoke and no finesse.
</P>
<P>
   After he was traded from the New York Mets to the California
Angels in 1971, Ryan developed a devastating curveball. When
prodded, he admits he ``probably had as good a curveball as there
was in the league.''
</P>
<P>
   Ryan's strikeout numbers indicate a pitcher who was able to set
up hitters and blow them away for a remarkable 27 seasons. Some
strikeout highlights:
</P>
<P>
   Ryan struck out 383 batters in 1973, the most in modern history.
In a three-year span with California from 1972-74, Ryan struck out
1,079 batters (329, 383, 367.)
</P>
<P>
   Ryan had 10 or more strikeouts in a game 215 times. Entering the
1999 season, the second-highest total was 102 by Arizona's Randy
Johnson. In 1973 with the Angels, Ryan struck out 10 or more
batters a record 23 times.
</P>
<P>
   Ryan led the American League in strikeouts seven times in eight
seasons with California from 1972-79 and then twice with Texas in
1989-90. When he did so in 1990 at age 43, he became the oldest
player to lead the AL in a major statistical category.
</P>
<P>
   Ryan led the National League with the Astros in 1987-88, his
final two seasons in Houston. When he led the league in 1988, he
became the oldest pitcher to lead the NL in strikeouts at age 41.
</P>
<P>
   Ryan had six seasons of 300 or more strikeouts, 15 seasons of
200 or more strikeouts and had 100 or more strikeouts 24 times,
including 23 consecutive seasons from 1970-92.
</P>
<P>
   Ryan has special memories of the milestone strikeouts in his
career. Obviously, he had no way of knowing the strikeout of
Jarvis, a pitcher for the Atlanta Braves, would be the first of
5,714. In that game, he also struck out Denis Menke, who later was
a coach on the Astros teams Ryan played on in the 1980s, and Hall
of Fame third baseman Eddie Mathews.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really don't remember anything special about that
strikeout,'' said Ryan. ``What I remember was coming into that game
and feeling very nervous. I was just 19 years old and had been in
high school the year before.
</P>
<P>
   ``There I was facing Henry Aaron and Eddie Mathews and Felipe
Alou and Joe Torre and Rico Carty. It was very intimidating. A
couple years prior to that, I'd had all their baseball cards and
here I was on the mound facing them.''
</P>
<P>
   Ryan's strikeouts didn't start to pile up until he left the Mets
after the 1971 season. He had 493 strikeouts for New York _ a total
he exceeded in less than 1{ seasons with the Angels.
</P>
<P>
   Ryan recorded his 500th, 1,000th and 1,500th strikeouts in just
more than two seasons from 1972-74. In August 1976, he notched No.
2,000 against Detroit's Ron LeFlore, who struck out 22 times in his
career against Ryan. Less than two years later, Ryan got his
2,500th strikeout against Buddy Bell, who was with Cleveland at the
time but finished his career as Ryan's teammate in Houston in 1988.
</P>
<P>
   What Ryan remembers most about the 3,000th strikeout of his
career was that there wasn't much attention given to the feat. In
his first season with the Astros, Ryan struck out Cesar Geronimo at
Riverfront Stadium in Cincinnati. After the game, there was so
little fanfare that a reporter from a Houston paper had a
one-on-one session with Ryan _ in the empty team bus outside the
Astros' clubhouse.
</P>
<P>
   ``In those days, there wasn't any ESPN or as much TV coverage,
so it just kind of came and went,'' Ryan said. ``It really didn't
seem like such a big deal.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1983, Ryan and Carlton were locked in a battle to see which
pitcher would be the first to pass Walter Johnson's all-time
strikeout record of 3,508. Ryan entered the season needing 14
strikeouts to eclipse Johnson, while Carlton needed 60.
</P>
<P>
   Ryan went past Johnson in his third start of the 1983 season on
April 27. He struck out Tim Blackwell in the eighth inning to tie
the mark and threw a 1-2 curveball that froze Brad Mills, the next
hitter, who stared at strike three.
</P>
<P>
   ``Once I got that strikeout, I was just relieved it was over,''
said Ryan. ``There were several pitchers who could pass that
number. I just wanted to be the one to do it first. Once I did, I
knew I could sit back and relax and get more satisfaction from
it.''
</P>
<P>
   Even 16 years later, Ryan still seems to be stung by the fact
that the baseball commissioner's office did not have a
representative on hand for the historic game.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just thought it was a little strange that someone was
breaking a 60-year old record, and nobody from the league was
there,'' said Ryan. ``They didn't make much of a deal out of it,
that's for sure.''
</P>
<P>
   When Ryan struck out Danny Heep of the New York Mets on an 0-2
curveball for strikeout No. 4,000 in 1985 _ a figure previously
thought out of reach _ he says the Astros did not have a photo of
the event. The only picture he received was from a free-lance
photographer who took an out-of-focus shot from the screened-in
area behind home plate at the Astrodome.
</P>
<P>
   That was not the case when Ryan reached the 5,000 strikeout
plateau with the Rangers in 1989. He says the buildup of that event
remains one of his biggest thrills in baseball.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I drove up to the park (Arlington Stadium) that night,
the attitude of the fans and the electricity in the air was
something that overwhelmed me,'' said Ryan. ``It was a good four
hours before the game, but people were lining up for tickets.
Sensing the excitement as it built that night, and to see how much
the fans got into that, it was very memorable.''
</P>
<P>
   Ryan delivered, striking out Rickey Henderson of the Oakland A's
for No. 5,000. Ryan said the 5,000th strikeout represents the
accomplishment of which he is most proud.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would say that because of the longevity involved. It
represented that many innings pitched and being able to maintain
that style of pitching my entire career.''
</P>
<P>
   Like the first strikeout of his career, the last one was
memorable only after the fact. Ryan struck out Anaheim catcher
Myers in the fifth inning of a game at Anaheim on Sept. 17, 1993.
Ryan had announced his retirement earlier that season, but he
suffered an elbow injury in the first inning of a game at Seattle
on Sept. 22 and did not pitch again.
</P>
<P>
   ``I vaguely remember that he chased a high fastball,'' Ryan
said. ``In my mind, I never thought that was going to be my last
one. I thought I'd have two more starts and get it at some point in
the final game. You can't predict everything, I guess.''
</P>
</TEXT>
