<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-15 15:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1434 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HILLARY-CLINTON-HNS &LR;      07-15 0970
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HILLARY-CLINTON-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MRS. CLINTON'S SUMMIT MEETING WITH ISRAELI MAY HELP HER IN N.Y. 
</HEADLINE>
   (EDS: For release at 7:30 p.m. EDT)  
 (EDS: Filed in ``w'' and ``p'' categories)  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By STEWART M. POWELL  
 c.1999 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ First Lady Hillary Rodham Clinton, vowing to
``learn how I can be helpful'' in the Middle East peace process,
hosted Israeli Prime Minister Ehud Barak at an intimate dinner for
four at Camp David late Thursday _ a summit that could prove useful
in her New York Senate campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Clinton joined President Clinton, the Israeli prime
minister and his wife, Nava Barak, for dinner and an overnight
visit at the remote presidential retreat in the Catoctin Mountains
of Maryland about 60 miles north of the nation's capital.
</P>
<P>
   Marsha Berry, Mrs. Clinton's White House press secretary, said
the first lady looked forward to the informal get-together with the
Baraks before an official White House dinner on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   ``The White House setting provides an incredible historic
perspective and that is important,'' Berry said. ``Camp David is a
very comfortable environment and there's definitely a sense of
uniqueness about it. It's nice to blend both on a visit like
this.''
</P>
<P>
   White House Press Secretary Joe Lockhart said the Clintons chose
Camp David as the setting for their first get-together with the
Baraks since Israeli voters chose the former Israeli military
officer as the nation's new prime minister.
</P>
<P>
   ``Camp David is a place where they'll have a chance to talk
privately in a more relaxed, informal setting,'' Lockhart said.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton and Barak met earlier at the White House to discuss the
U.S. insistence that Israel fulfill an agreement to relinquish 13.1
percent of additional West Bank territory as part of a
comprehensive land-for-peace deal.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton told Barak that ``America will walk with you'' as Israel
presses ahead with a renewed quest for peace.
</P>
<P>
   Barak vowed to ``inject new momentum into the peace process and
to put it back on all tracks.'' But the Israeli underscored his
government's independence, telling Clinton that the United States
can bolster the peace process ``more as a facilitator than as a
kind of policeman.''
</P>
<P>
   Barak later met privately with Vice President Al Gore, who is
seeking the Democratic nomination in 2000 to succeed Clinton as
chief executive.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Clinton, who has been courting New York voters on two
campaign-style visits to the Empire State in the last two weeks,
said in a letter to a prominent Jewish American leader that she
looked forward to her first meeting with Barak.
</P>
<P>
   ``Today, a new prime minister of Israel is preparing to come to
the United States to discuss his own plans to move the peace
process forward,'' Mrs. Clinton wrote Mandell I. Ganchrow, head of
the Orthodox Union that represents about 750 orthodox Jewish
synagogues across the United States. Her campaign aides released
the letter to reporters.
</P>
<P>
   ``The president and I look forward to hosting Prime Minister and
Mrs. Barak on their first official visit, and I am personally eager
to learn how I can be helpful in this important effort,'' Mrs.
Clinton added.
</P>
<P>
   In her letter, Mrs. Clinton vowed that if she seeks the Senate
seat of retiring Sen. Daniel Patrick Moynihan, D-N.Y., she would be
``an active, committed advocate for a strong and secure Israel.''
</P>
<P>
   She also broke with White House policy and announced her support
of Israel's position that Jerusalem is the ``eternal and
indivisible capital of Israel.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton administration policy calls for the status of Jerusalem
to be negotiated between Israel and the Palestinians as part of
``final status'' talks to resolve disputes over borders, refugees
and Jewish settlements on the West Bank. Meanwhile, the city of Tel
Aviv continues to be the capital of Israel.
</P>
<P>
   Jews are an active political constituency in New York politics,
where they make up 9.1 percent of the state's total population of
more than 18 million.
</P>
<P>
   Jewish voters were 12 percent of the electorate that cast
ballots in the bitter 1998 Senate contest in New York between
then-Rep. Charles Schumer, D-N.Y., and Sen. Alfonse D'Amato, R-N.Y.
Schumer swept 76 percent of the Jewish vote, helping him oust the
conservative Republican, according to exit polls.
</P>
<P>
   Berry, Mrs. Clinton's White House spokeswoman, said the first
lady would visit Israel ``this fall,'' adding: ``We have no
specific time set at this point but it will be after September.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE -- OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Camp David has afforded privacy for first families since
President Franklin D. Roosevelt began using the wooded retreat at
the outset of World War II. Roosevelt called the retreat ``Shangri
La.''
</P>
<P>
   President Dwight D. Eisenhower renamed it for his grandson
David.
</P>
<P>
   President Jimmy Carter chose the isolated setting for an 11-day
summit in 1978 to foster the first Arab-Israeli peace agreement
between Israeli Prime Minister Menahem Begin and Egyptian President
Anwar Sadat.
</P>
<P>
   Carter later said that ``it was necessary (that) we be
completely isolated so that neither Begin nor Sadat nor their
representatives would feel constrained one or more times every day
to'' consult with their own varies constituencies to ``explain what
modifications were being made to previous promises or
commitments.''
</P>
<P>
   Lockhart ducked a question Thursday on whether the Clintons had
chosen Camp David as a way to recall the spirit of peace accords
that began the Middle East peace process in 1978.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll let everybody else decide that,'' Lockhart said. ``I'll
let everyone else speculate on that.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; --- &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Stewart M. Powell can be reached at 202-298-6920 and via
e-mail: stewart(at)hearstdc.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
