<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-15 15:58 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1436 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-E-MAIL-TAX16-COX     07-15 0311
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-E-MAIL-TAX16-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    E-MAIL TAX: AN IDEA THAT WON'T DIE
 &HT;    Moving in (w) Washington and (f) financial categories.
 &HT;    By MARILYN GEEWAX
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ This spring, e-mails bombarded many Internet users,
warning them that the U.S. Postal Service planned to impose a tax
on electronic messages.
</P>
<P>
   Business owners complained loudly about the new burden
government was about to place upon them, and members of Congress
were flooded with inquiries.
</P>
<P>
   But the tax talk was absolute nonsense, the Postal Service said.
It issued a press release reminding the gullible that the ``Postal
Service has no authority to surcharge e-mail messages sent over the
Internet, nor would it support such legislation.''
</P>
<P>
   Case closed.
</P>
<P>
   But not exactly.
</P>
<P>
   The rumor mill can start grinding again, because the United
Nations Development Program this week urged governments around the
world to tax e-mails to raise money to help the underdeveloped
world get on line.
</P>
<P>
   A tax rate of one U.S. cent on every 100 e-mails would have
raised $70 billion had it been in place in 1996, according to a
U.N. economist. Given how quickly the Internet is growing, vast
sums could be raised each year to help poor countries purchase
telecommunications equipment to catch up with the wealthy world.
</P>
<P>
   Word of the U.N. recommendation quickly spread over the
Internet, prompting many to post comments.
</P>
<P>
   ``Never should the government be allowed to control anything
that happens over the Internet!'' one would-be Patrick Henry said
on the Web site called slashdot.org.
</P>
<P>
   But before the rumors grow too thick about a U.N. tax to support
black helicopters hovering over our homes, e-mailers should note
that the United Nations has no power to tax.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-15-99 1558EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990715.0212 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-15 15:58 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1437 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-E-MAIL-TAX16-COX     07-15 0311
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-E-MAIL-TAX16-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    E-MAIL TAX: AN IDEA THAT WON'T DIE
 &HT;    Moving in (w) Washington and (f) financial categories.
 &HT;    By MARILYN GEEWAX
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ This spring, e-mails bombarded many Internet users,
warning them that the U.S. Postal Service planned to impose a tax
on electronic messages.
</P>
<P>
   Business owners complained loudly about the new burden
government was about to place upon them, and members of Congress
were flooded with inquiries.
</P>
