It issued a press release reminding the gullible that the ``Postal
Service has no authority to surcharge e-mail messages sent over the
Internet, nor would it support such legislation.''
</P>
<P>
   Case closed.
</P>
<P>
   But not exactly.
</P>
<P>
   The rumor mill can start grinding again, because the United
Nations Development Program this week urged governments around the
world to tax e-mails to raise money to help the underdeveloped
world get on line.
</P>
