<DOCNO> NYT19990715.0213 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-15 15:58 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1438 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBO-RYAN-FAMILY-HNS &LR;      07-15 1646
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-RYAN-FAMILY-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
Ruthian effort helped keep the `team' running smoothly
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; By JODY GOLDSTEIN &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; c. 1999, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ALVIN _ Ruth Ryan could have been a professional photographer.
</P>
<P>
   She can't begin to count the number of times a stranger has
sidled up to her famous husband, handed her a camera and pleaded
with her to snap a quick photo.
</P>
<P>
   She could have been a professional mover.
</P>
<P>
   For 24 years, she packed a house and eventually three kids three
times every year as the Ryans moved from Alvin to their spring
training site to their major-league town, then home again.
</P>
<P>
   She could have been a nurse, a teacher, a referee _ all jobs
baseball wives must perform when they spend half the year, or at
least half the season, as single parents.
</P>
<P>
   ``My oldest brother once said that if the Ryans are a team, mom
is our quarterback,'' said 22-year-old Wendy Ryan, the youngest of
the three kids.
</P>
<P>
   Ruth also has served as fan, bullpen catcher and confidant for
Nolan from his Little League career at Shroeder Field in Alvin in
1959 to his Hall of Fame career in the majors. She was there for
his first major-league pitch for the New York Mets. She was there
when he threw that final fastball to Dave Magadan of the Mariners
toward the end of 1993, knowing instinctively it would be his last
pitch.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every spring before spring training would start, we'd long
toss in the yard every day, just throwing to each other,'' Ruth
said. ``During spring training if Nolan didn't make a trip, we'd go
out to the field and play. My job was usually to shag balls while
the boys would practice hitting. I probably got a lot more involved
with his career than a lot of wives, but I love baseball and wanted
to be a part of it.''
</P>
<P>
   Baseball wasn't Nolan's job, it was the Ryan family business.
</P>
<P>
   Reid, the oldest son and now 27, pitched at TCU, then played two
seasons of minor-league baseball with the Rangers organization
before retiring to begin a joint venture with his father to bring a
minor-league team to Round Rock. The Astros' Class AA team begins
play there in spring 2000.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've done a lot of bonding through baseball,'' Reid said.
``We have this connection through baseball. When I was in the minor
leagues, I really got a chance to see what he and my mom went
through their first few years.''
</P>
<P>
   Both Nolan and Ruth grew up in moderate circumstances, without a
lot of luxuries and with parents who sometimes worked two jobs to
support their families. Budgeting, scrimping and saving had been
ways of life forever, so the Ryans never looked at it as doing
without.
</P>
<P>
   But they certainly had to. That $6,000-a-year salary his first
year with the Mets didn't go very far in New York. The $1,000
raises each of the next two years still left them without much in
savings when they moved to California in 1972.
</P>
<P>
   And when they got there, with one child in tow, the Ryans found
the Angels had a rule prohibiting children in their spring training
hotel. If they wished to be together, they had to rent a home. And
even though he was making $12,000 _ twice his original major-league
salary _ Nolan and Ruth couldn't find a home or hotel room they
could afford for the six-week training period the team split
between Holtville, Calif., and Palm Springs.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nolan's sister Mary Lou lent us a trailer and we lived in
that,'' Ruth said. ``It didn't have air conditioning, and we were
in the desert. It was fine at night, but it was 100 degrees during
the day. I had a child and no car, so I just sat in a lawn chair
outside the trailer all day long. It seems bizarre now, but that's
what we had to do to be together as a family.''
</P>
<P>
   There were more financial problems soon after when the players
went on strike for the first eight games of the season. With no
money coming in, Ruth and Nolan had to borrow $1,500 against their
1971 tax refund to survive.
</P>
<P>
   But money wouldn't be a problem much longer. In 1973, Ryan
pitched his first two no-hitters and recorded his 1,000th career
strikeout. He broke Sandy Koufax's single-season record with 383
strikeouts and pitched 26 complete games. And at the end of that
year, he was rewarded with a six-figure salary.
</P>
<P>
   By the time Reese, now 23, entered the picture in 1976, Nolan
had pitched four no-hitters and the Ryans could afford to rent a
home during spring training.
</P>
<P>
   Wendy came only a year later, and Ruth found herself with three
kids and a couple of households to manage.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe if I was a more organized person it might have been
different, but it seemed like every few months, life turned upside
down,'' Ruth said. ``I felt completely unorganized. The entire
baseball existence is extremely nerve-wracking for a mother. It
starts with spring training when you pack the car, pack the kids,
take them out of school and turn their lives upside down.''
</P>
<P>
   For this baseball family to survive, life pretty much had to
revolve around the ballpark.
</P>
<P>
   ``From February to October, your husband's job requires so much
focus, concentration,'' Ruth said. ``You have to eat at certain
times, sleep at certain times. The whole day is spent getting ready
to go to the ballpark. There were years when Nolan was getting home
at midnight and you'd have a toddler who was getting up at 6 a.m.
and a baby who was getting up during the night. I didn't sleep
much, but luckily back then I was young and I could get by on five
hours of uninterrupted sleep.''
</P>
<P>
   Through it all, Alvin was the steadying force. In the town in
which they grew up, the Ryans could shop, dine and go to school
without being hassled. Nolan wasn't the resident millionaire, he
was just a local boy done good. The kids went to public school, and
Nolan never felt the need to trade in his pickup truck for a
sportier vehicle.
</P>
<P>
   Even today, Nolan prefers his pickup. Ruth enjoys her Suburban.
</P>
<P>
   Although it was only five years at the end of Nolan's career,
the Ryan family's favorite times start and end with the Rangers.
Texas was the most family-friendly of his four major-league teams,
allowing kids on the field before the game and letting the boys go
in the locker room and sit on the bench.
</P>
<P>
   It was from this vantage point that Reese, then 14, watched
Nolan's sixth no-hitter on June 11, 1990, in Oakland. As the
cameras followed Nolan in the dugout between innings, Reese could
be seen rubbing his dad's back and offering encouragement.
</P>
<P>
   ``His arm was tightening up, so I rubbed it and his back,''
Reese said. ``It was really neat to be a part of that.''
</P>
<P>
   While with the Rangers, Ryan topped the 5,000 career strikeouts
mark (Aug. 22, 1991), posted his 300th career win (against the
Brewers on July 31, 1990), and recorded his seventh no-hitter (May
1, 1991 against Toronto).
</P>
<P>
   He also pitched against his son Reid when the Rangers faced the
University of Texas in an exhibition game in March 1991. Reid
allowed four runs in two innings. Nolan allowed one hit in three
innings. Reid transferred to TCU at the end of that season.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought it would be totally draining for me, but once the
game got going, everything changed,'' Ruth wrote in her book,
Covering Home: My Life With Nolan Ryan. ``Suddenly I had the
proudest feeling I had ever known. It was hard to believe I was old
enough to be watching my husband and son on the same field.''
</P>
<P>
   And suddenly it was all over.
</P>
<P>
   There would be only the one World Series ring, earned in 1969 as
a young member of the New York Mets.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nolan didn't get to pitch much that year, but he won the third
game of the playoffs against Atlanta that sent them to the World
Series and he saved one game in the World Series,'' Ruth said. ``I
never knew baseball fans could be like that. It was unbelievable.''
</P>
<P>
   Even in retirement, he'll never stop being Nolan Ryan, and it
took until each child was a teen-ager to really understand just
what that means.
</P>
<P>
   ``For the longest time, I just thought I was growing up
normal,'' Wendy said. ``I didn't realize just how incredible he is
at what he does. The older you get, the more you can appreciate it.
But I have to give them so much credit for keeping our lives as
normal as they could.''
</P>
<P>
   Family activities have always centered around ranch life and
cattle (the Ryans own ranches in South Texas and near Gonzalez),
with hunting and fishing being particular favorites. And then
there's the sports. Backyard volleyball and tennis tournaments have
long been the norm. The newest craze, however, is golf (Nolan can't
play tennis anymore because of a bad knee). And no, he's not a
natural at it, with scores reportedly around 100.
</P>
<P>
   For all of Nolan's fame and accomplishments, some of the best
anecdotes about him occurred when he was not recognized.
</P>
<P>
   Nolan and Ruth were up at their Gonzalez ranch recently when
they decided to head out to the nine-hole golf course nearby. On
the first hole, Nolan teed it up while the starter, a retired
football coach, watched. He took a big swing and the ball went
about three feet.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was real aggravated and he started stomping around,'' Ruth
said. ``So the little man came over and told him, `Just relax.
Sports are all about having fun.' Nolan just looked at him and hit
the ball. When we drove off, the guys in the clubhouse said, `Do
you know who you were talking to? That was Nolan Ryan.' He was so
embarrassed.''
</P>
<P>
   Being part of the Ryan household has meant growing up in the
spotlight. But it also has meant seeing different sides of the
legend _ a dad who can be a strict disciplinarian, a prankster who
loves a practical joke, and a man who always puts his family first.
</P>
<P>
   ``What's it like to be Nolan Ryan's son? That's a tough question
to answer,'' Reese said. ``I grew up always being Nolan Ryan's son,
so I guess I don't know what it's like to be a normal kid.''
</P>
</TEXT>
