<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-15 16:06 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1443 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GARDENING-LIFE16-COX     07-15 0793
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GARDENING-LIFE16-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Horticultural horror: Landscapers did it
 &HT;    By Lee May
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ It's a gardener's nightmare: After enjoying your
morning stroll in the garden you built with a huge investment of
time, money and energy, you leave home, returning that evening to
discover many of the plants you collected are gone, ripped from the
ground.
</P>
<P>
   That's what happened to Lucia Duncan-Harrison, who gardens in
the north Atlanta neighborhood of Nancy Creek Heights.
</P>
<P>
   Now, I've heard of thieves snatching people's plants (despite
the fact that most gardeners wouldn't dream of stealing from a
kindred spirit). But that wasn't the way it went in Lucia's garden.
</P>
<P>
   This was the horticultural equivalent of friendly fire in a war:
The landscapers did it.
</P>
<P>
   Seems laborers working in her garden somehow ``exceeded what
they were told to do,'' digging out desirable plants as if they
were common weeds, including many of Lucia's prized natives.
</P>
<P>
   Recently, as we walked through her 1/3-acre space, surrounded by
big old trees, Lucia relived that day last summer. As happens with
anyone, her eyes saw what her mind expected when she first arrived
home. ``I didn't really notice anything missing,'' she recalls,
adding that she looked beyond her garden to focus on her next-door
neighbor.
</P>
<P>
   ``All of a sudden, it hit me. Omigod! I still get goose bumps.''
</P>
<P>
   On our afternoon walk, Lucia pointed to the land, describing
what had happened where. Here, grew birdfoot's-violet, she says,
adding that she had placed rocks around the two perennials, but the
workers ``moved the rocks, dug them up and put the rocks back.'' Go
figure. Right over there, was hepatica. And, in this spot,
bloodroot. And, nearby, five types of trillium. Ginger, iris,
phlox, sedum all were missing. Even four azaleas were uprooted.
</P>
<P>
   Recalling the day her plants were dug out, Lucia said, ``I've
just got to tell somebody,'' so she telephoned her parents in
Athens, Wilbur and Marion Duncan, widely respected experts on
wildflowers and authors of several books, including their latest,
the beautifully informative ``Wildflowers of the Eastern United
States.'' (Her parents inscribed Lucia's copy to their ``late-
</P>
<P>
   blooming botanist.'') ``They were horrified about my collection,
too,'' says Lucia. And helpful. ``They said, `Calm down; we'll help
you replace it.'''
</P>
<P>
   As shock wore into determination, Lucia, who is a lawyer, began
compiling a meticulous list of the plants she had lost, contacting
sources, including nature centers and nurseries in the region to
find out which plants were available and how much they would cost.
At the same time, she combed through a pile of worker-discarded
plants, rescuing a few, including one of the four azaleas.
</P>
<P>
   After some discussion, the owner of the landscaping company
``remembered that he had insurance,'' and he and Lucia reached an
amicable settlement.
</P>
<P>
   Still, some of the plants cannot be replaced, she says,
mentioning Georgia mint, hepatica and a dwarf iris as examples of
those that are not sold.
</P>
<P>
   Lucia's uprooted garden is a reminder that what is lost in such
situations is more than unusual plants, of course. Gone is the
experience of collecting them or receiving them as gifts.
Replacement money cannot pay for this, just as it cannot make up
for property losses suffered in floods, tornadoes and other
disasters.
</P>
<P>
   Experiences and connections are lost forever, not restored by
bringing in new plants _ or sofas, chairs, carpets. And, with trees
and shrubs, there's a distinctiveness about each one that is
impossible to replace; every plant is unique. You can replace that
prized azalea that you lost, but you won't be able to find one with
the same little curve in the main trunk. And, no matter how hard
you try, you can't train another spicebush to produce above-ground
roots that put the plant on curved stilts, walking it through the
garden.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, we all suffer our losses, pick up the pieces and
move on.
</P>
<P>
   So it is with Lucia Duncan-Harrison. The other day, even as she
still felt the goose bumps from her chilling loss, she was warmed
by hopes of her plants' resilience.
</P>
<P>
   ``The nature of nature means my plants are doing better than I
expected,'' says Lucia, taking heart in seeing a fraction of her
five dozen bloodroot plants peeping up this year.
Lily-of-the-valley and shamrock, which grew profusely in Lucia's
garden, may one day do it again.
</P>
<P>
   For now, however, she's looking at a lot of empty spaces, filled
with anticipation.
</P>
<P>
   Lee May writes a weekly column on gardening lifestyles. E-mail
him at leemay
</P>
<P>
   (at)bellsouth.net.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
