<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-15 16:06 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1445 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LAWN-FETISH16-COX     07-15 1646
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LAWN-FETISH16-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Each weekend, Atlantans hooked on green take to their yards
 &HT;    By Danny C. Flanders
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALTANTA _ David and Bobbi Kelly avoid travel on Saturday. It's
not a religious holiday or flying phobia that keeps them home.
</P>
<P>
   It's their yard.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've gone on vacation before and left on Sunday so he could
be here on Saturday to do the lawn,'' Bobbi says.
</P>
<P>
   That's the day her husband whips out the Weed Whacker, revs up
the blower, yanks on the mower and steadies the edger for a
half-day ritual aimed at maintaining a look as manicured as a
Marine recruit.
</P>
<P>
   ``I do the angle cuts, you betcha, trying to get it to look like
Turner Field, and I mow in different directions,'' Kelly says.
</P>
<P>
   ``The children call them `Daddy's lines,''' Bobbi says.
</P>
<P>
   Kelly can't help it. Like many of the 53 million Americans with
lawns, the northwest Atlanta resident is consumed by the blade.
</P>
<P>
   When the sun rises high enough for neighbors to safely create a
racket, when the scent of freshly severed growth suddenly fills the
air, when property lines become defined by a half-inch-high
difference in turf, lawn junkies have to have their fix.
</P>
<P>
   Forget the gardening stuff. Maintaining a thick, solid carpet of
green is a guy thing _ a means for marking their territory, for
chipping in to improve the environment and, yes, for keeping up
with those blasted Joneses. Lawns unite neighbors to commiserate
about nematodes, to share fertilizer formulas and to help each
other survive those dreary days of winter after coming down from a
summer of lawn bliss.
</P>
<P>
   ``The lawn works in mysterious ways. It calls to men with a
thick and seductive voice,'' Warren Schultz writes in ``A Man's
Turf: The Perfect Lawn'' (Clarkson Potter, $35). ``It takes our
time during the weekend and occupies our thoughts during the week.
It pulls us up out of the easy chair and away from the television
to tend it. We pamper it, fuss over it, and curse at it. ... And we
expect it to always look its best. We wring our hands when it turns
brown or develops bare patches. We puff out our chests when it
turns rich emerald green in the spring. And, yes, we mow it every
weekend, whether it needs it or not.''
</P>
<P>
   Setting an example: So what drives men to become die-hard
pushers?
</P>
<P>
   ``The object of lawn care is not to encourage rampant growth and
flowering but to control it,'' Schultz says. ``Our goal is not to
encourage _ heck, not to tolerate _ change, development and
diversity but to maintain order and sameness. Lawn care is an
exercise in control, bordering on domination.''
</P>
<P>
   For Kelly, nurturing a blanket of fescue allows him to weed out
the stress of a hectic workweek in wine sales.
</P>
<P>
   He also maintains the entrance to his Hanover West subdivision
because he knows landscaping improves property values. ``We're big
into curb appeal here,'' he says. ``We're the first yard that
people see when they turn into our neighborhood.''
</P>
<P>
   Like Kelly, Wesley Levy sets the standard on his Lithonia
street. Every seven days, the retired carpenter spends about five
hours mowing, edging and mulching his Bermuda grass.
</P>
<P>
   ``He also sits on a bench and pulls the roots of weeds up, one
by one, using (the claw of) a hammer,'' his wife, Carmen, says.
</P>
<P>
   Her husband believes that by setting an example, others will
follow. And they have.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just do whatever Mr. Levy does,'' says next-door neighbor
Rudy Germain. ``I try to make mine perfect, but his _ his is always
perfect.''
</P>
<P>
   The two do their best to encourage a homogenous look along Great
Oaks Drive, Levy says. ``When we mow, we both cut our lawns up to
our neighbor's driveways to keep it all even.''
</P>
<P>
   Obsession or dedication? Once, while Levy traveled abroad for
two weeks, Germain mowed his neighbor's lawn three times, and ``he
wouldn't take a penny,'' Levy recalls.
</P>
<P>
   Paul Dickinson and Pat Apps can identify. The two live across a
cul-de-sac from each other in Alpharetta's Medlock Bridge, where
they exchange plenty of sod stories.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes, Paul's wife feels like a weed widow.
</P>
<P>
   ``My husband's a lawn fanatic,'' Linda Dickinson says. ``His
idea of relaxation is 1) working on the lawn/landscaping, 2)
admiring the lawn/landscaping, 3) watching the sprinkler system
water the lawn/landscaping. It bothers him when people don't take
care of their yards. I agree that our yard looks great, and I
appreciate all of his hard work, but he is only 36 years old.
Shouldn't there be another topic of conversation that takes
precedence over lawn care?''
</P>
<P>
   Dickinson, a technical manager at Lucent Technologies, downplays
his commitment and says he spends less than two hours mowing and
edging every Saturday. He relies on an irrigation system for
watering ``twice a week, 40 minutes per zone, 5 to 7 a.m.'' _ to
the tune every other month in summer of $350.
</P>
<P>
   ``It takes a lot of work, but I like the exercise and getting
outside, especially in the evenings,'' says his neighbor Apps, a
product engineer. ``I try to mow and edge mine every five days, but
that's hard to do.''
</P>
<P>
   Big Lawn Brother. Apps' lawn is like Dickinson's _ Bermuda in
front, fescue in back. ``I think the neighborhood requires it,''
Apps says.
</P>
<P>
   Community restrictions have become commonplace. Schultz, one of
the nation's foremost experts on natural lawn care, considers the
lawn a symbol of suburban conformity.
</P>
<P>
   ``It signals others that we conform to the unspoken rules of the
neighborhood design. (Sometimes these rules are not so subtle. In
certain communities, homeowners are required to keep 75 percent of
their lots in turf grass. In other communities, homeowners must
keep the lawn at a height under 3 inches.) Why? Anything else is
subversive, un-American. There might be communists hiding in the
weeds.''
</P>
<P>
   And in an age when fewer and fewer know their neighbors, lawn
conformity also satisfies a need to belong. ``Through the lawn, we
can join others without having to deal with the unpleasantness of
actually talking to them,'' Schultz says.
</P>
<P>
   But others see it differently; some lawns brings neighbors
together.
</P>
<P>
   From Tupperware to sod. Steve Arthur has spent nearly 40 years
transforming his Buckhead lawn into what at first glance resembles
a small golf course.
</P>
<P>
   The secret to a beautiful fescue lawn, he says, is mowing it
high, 3 to 4 inches. The large yard requires a tractor mower, which
often leaves tracks. ``By the time the grass stands back up, it's
time to mow it again,'' Arthur says.
</P>
<P>
   The job takes about a half day, but at least fescue doesn't
require as much edging and trimming as other grasses. ``It gets
overwhelming sometimes, but I enjoy it,'' says the 81-year-old
retiree.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have a lot of people stop by and ask me about it. We end up
pulling up a chair and visiting for 15 minutes or so.''
</P>
<P>
   For Mark Lieberman, sod became an instrument for meeting his
neighbors after moving into his Alpharetta neighborhood 13 years
ago. ``We had a sod party because we laid it on about the same
day,'' he recalls.
</P>
<P>
   Since then, his zoysia has spread over a bare spot in his
neighbor's yard, and Lieberman mows it.
</P>
<P>
   Got to love it. Twice, he's laid sod _ 5,000 square feet in the
front and 5,000 in back _ and finally he's achieved a thick, dense
carpet. Lieberman, a vice-president for sales at G E Capital,
attributes part of his success to his recent purchase of a $1,000
reel mower, which he says gives a cleaner, finer cut than a
rotary-powered one.
</P>
<P>
   Although zoysia is a slow grower, he mows it every week. ``When
it has that clean cut, it has a whole different feel _ that golf
course look,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   The maintenance begins in February when he dethatches, followed
by applying a pre-emergent to prevent weeds. In late April, he
scalps the lawn to force new growth, then cuts it weekly to about
3/4- inches. During the growing season, he fertilizes every other
month and in November submits soil samples to the County Extension
Service to identify his lawn's needs.
</P>
<P>
   ``My wife says to hire someone for all of this, but I really
like doing it,'' Lieberman says. ``It's like people who wax their
cars.''
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes, his dedication surprises even himself. ``Twenty years
ago, I couldn't have had a conversation about grass because I
couldn't have cared less,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   ``But when you buy a house, everything changes.''
</P>
<P>
   LUSH LAWN SECRETS
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Steve Arthur, Atlanta: Mow fescue high in summer, no lower
than 3 to 4 inches.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Pat Apps, Alpharetta (Ga.): If you mow once a week, fertilize
more often, in his case, three times in summer.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Paul Dickinson, Alpharetta: Water 40 minutes twice a week in
early morning, during the heat of summer.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  David Kelly, northwest Atlanta: Mow in opposite directions and
in overlapping, angle cuts.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Wesley Levy, Lithonia (Ga.): Spread mulched Bermuda clippings
on the grass.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Mark Lieberman, Alpharetta: Mow zoysia low to promote
spreading.
</P>
<P>
   TURF TRIVIA
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Number of roots on a single grass plant: 13 million
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Miles of roots on a single grass plant: 300
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Number of grass plants in a 1,000-square-foot lawn: 850,000
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Miles of grass roots under a 1,000-square-foot lawn: 300
million
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Average number of hours American households spend annually
tending lawns: 40
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Annual cost per acre of maintaining a home lawn: $327
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Annual cost per acre of maintaining a golf course: $2,000
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Total dollars spent annually by Americans on lawn-care
equipment, products: $5.4 million
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Pounds of chemicals applied annually to American turf : 70
million
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Gallons of water needed to cover a 1-acre lawn with an
inch-thick blanket of water: 27,144
</P>
<P>
   Source: Warren Schultz's ``A Man's Turf: The Perfect Lawn''
(Clarkson Potter, $35)
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
