<HEADER>
A1446 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-WORKSHOP-CAULKING16-C     07-15 0283
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WORKSHOP-CAULKING16-COX </SLUG>

<TEXT>
<P>
   Good caulk job can last for years
</P>
<P>
   By Alma E. Hill
</P>
<P>
   Photos by William Berryc. 1999 Cox News Service
</P>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ If you're planning to spruce up your digs this summer,
you'll want to add bathroom caulking to your to-do list.
</P>
<P>
   This is a job you can pay a plumber or contractor to do, but if
you're handy, the task is pretty easy.
</P>
<P>
   And how long will the caulking last?
</P>
<P>
   ``If you use a good, 50-year silicone, it's going to stay good
indefinitely,'' said John Adivari, district trainer for Lowe's Home
Center in Woodstock (Ga.).
</P>
<P>
   ``Homeowners are far more particular than contractors. I try to
train homeowners to be particular, but to take shortcuts'' to get
the job done, he added.
</P>
<P>
   Supplies:
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  100 percent pure silicone caulk
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Plastic putty knife or caulk remover tool
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Rubbing or denatured alcohol
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  2-inch wide quick release masking tape
</P>
<P>
   Step one: Remove old caulk with a putty knife or caulk remover
tool. With alcohol, clean the area where new caulk will be applied.
</P>
<P>
   Step two: Place masking tape above and below the area to be
caulked. Step three: Snip tip of caulk tube at an angle, so caulk
comes out with proper application edge.
</P>
<P>
   Step four: Apply caulk in a thin, straight line between taped
areas.
</P>
<P>
   Step five: Moisten fingertip and spread caulk until it is
smooth. Immediately remove tape before caulk dries. Wipe up any
excess with alcohol. Allow caulk to dry overnight.
</P>
<P>
   The finished product: Newly applied caulk in the bathroom.
</P>
<P>
   Alama E. Hill writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
