<SLUG> BC-LOSING-FILM-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`I'M LOSING YOU': WHAT CAN YOU DO AT DEATH'S DOOR? YOU CAN LAUGH 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds: Production notes are at end of review) 
(af) 
 By JANET MASLIN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Although ``I'm Losing You'' was adapted from Bruce Wagner's
scabrous, razor-sharp Hollywood novel by Wagner himself, it bears
surprisingly slender resemblance to his book.
</P>
<P>
   Acerbic as it is, Wagner's first film is still very much the
watered-down version. That ought to be enough, since on film, ``I'm
Losing You'' unfolds in a doom-tinged, AIDS-minded milieu where the
sardonic quips fly like tennis balls.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am death warmed over,'' says Buck Henry, as an AIDS patient,
to Frank Langella's character, a television mogul newly diagnosed
with lung cancer. ``You're death warming up.''
</P>
<P>
   But ``I'm Losing You'' was a busy, convoluted book, a nearly
unfilmable one. And it loses some of its cumulatively mordant
atmosphere when pared down this way. The cast is good, particularly
Langella as the big kahuna behind a ``Star Trek''-like franchise,
and Rosanna Arquette as a woman acutely sensitive to the grim
tidings all around her.
</P>
<P>
   And the production is archly evocative, noting some of the finer
nuances to be found along the Hollywood food chain. If the film
doesn't quite hang together, it does capture the black humor and
mournful angst at the heart of the material.
</P>
<P>
   Virtually everyone in the film is somehow chicly entwined with
death, like a woman with AIDS (Elizabeth Perkins) who emerges from
a bathroom reciting Emily Dickinson and adding: ``You're free to
wash up now. I'm finished vomiting.''
</P>
<P>
   It is the mogul's son, played by Andrew McCarthy, whom she first
encounters this way, in a film full of dysfunctional relationships
and mounting dread. With a debt to the California anomie of ``Play
It As It Lays,'' this is a film in which a dying character develops
an interest in expensive watches as a means of dealing with
mortality.
</P>
<P>
   The film's obsession with tainted blood also carries Ms.
Arquette's character into the realm of Jewish ritual cleansing, the
kind of thing that calls for a more delicate introduction than the
film can provide.
</P>
<P>
   Wagner successfully echoes his book's bleak resonance, but his
straightforward ability with a camera is no match for what he can
do on the page. He does give the film a cool, calculated look that
preserves its discreet mournfulness and saves it from emotional
overkill.
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCTION NOTES: &QL;
</P>
<P>
   `I'M LOSING YOU' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Directed by Bruce Wagner; written by Wagner, based on his novel;
director of photography, Rob Sweeney; edited by Janice Hampton;
music by Daniel Catan; production designer, Richard Sherman;
produced by Christine Vachon and Pamela Koffler; released by Strand
Releasing. Running time: 102 minutes. This film is not rated.
</P>
<P>
   With: Andrew McCarthy (Bertie Krohn), Rosanna Arquette (Rachel
Krohn), Frank Langella (Perry Needham Krohn), Buck Henry (Philip
Dragom), Elizabeth Perkins (Aubrey), Gina Gershon (Lidia), Amanda
Donohoe (Mona Deware), Salome Jens (Diantha Krohn), Aria Noelle
Curzon (Tiffany) and Laraine Newman (casting person). &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-15-99 1612EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
