<DOCNO> NYT19990715.0224 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-15 16:15 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1463 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-WOOD-FILM-REVIEW-NYT &LR;      07-15 0759
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WOOD-FILM-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`THE WOOD': WHEN LOSS OF VIRGINITY IS THE BIRTH OF LOVE 
</HEADLINE>
  (jt) 
 By STEPHEN HOLDEN    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Late in ``The Wood,'' a savvy, good-natured comedy that follows
the 13-year friendship of three black friends who met in junior
high school in Inglewood, Calif., there is a flashback in which the
three boys, Mike (Sean Nelson), Slim (Duane Finley) and Roland
(Trent Cameron) pool their change into a kitty and swear a pact.
Whoever is the first to lose his virginity will be the recipient of
the accumulated cash.
</P>
<P>
   If the notion of virginal high school boys goading each other
into a sexual contest is similar to the central conceit of the hit
teen-age comedy ``American Pie,'' ``The Wood'' doesn't use it as a
hook on which to string a succession of sniggering gross-out jokes.
Nor does it view its adolescent characters as dirty young men
plotting and scheming to trick girls into sleeping with them.
</P>
<P>
   The contest's winner turns out to be so enamored of the girl who
initiates him into sex that he doesn't boast about his conquest.
The scenes of that initiation in the girl's bedroom find a lovely
balance between ardent passion, comic bumbling, joy (his) and
silent disappointment (hers). The bumbling involves a defective
condom, the boy's anatomical ignorance and the unexpected return to
the house of a family member.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Wood,'' which ricochets back and forth in time between the
late 1980s and the present, is narrated by Mike, who in 1986 moves
with his mother from Winston-Salem, N.C., to a middle-class black
neighborhood in Inglewood. The movie is narrated by the grown-up
Mike (Omar Epps), who occasionally turns to speak directly to the
camera. Different actors also play the grown-up Slim (Richard T.
Jones) and Roland (Taye Diggs). And the physical continuity between
the characters as adolescents and their older selves requires some
suspension of disbelief.
</P>
<P>
   But the movie's rapid transitions back and forth in time are
handled smoothly, and each character is fairly well defined. As it
follows the friends from junior to senior high school, then leaps
back to the present, the film, written and directed by Rick
Famuyiwa, pays close, expert attention to changing hairstyles,
fashions and music. Famuyiwa's dialogue is easygoing and witty, and
the warmhearted comic performances mesh beautifully.
</P>
<P>
   The story begins in the present, just hours before the wedding
of Roland, who has fled in a last-minute panic to an
ex-girlfriend's house where he has become falling-down drunk. Mike
and Slim ply the groom-to-be with coffee and manage to get him into
a car whereupon he gets sick all over them. Some of the film's
funniest scenes follow the three as they cope with this crisis,
dousing themselves with a garden hose in the former girlfriend's
backyard, then entreating a reluctant dry cleaner to have their
clothes ready within an hour.
</P>
<P>
   The desperate last-minute cleanup resonates with the threesome's
adolescent adventures, none especially harrowing. They include
being stopped by the police in a car in which one person is
carrying a gun, finding themselves in the back of a grocery store
while it's being robbed and of course, pitching inept lines at
girls who adamantly stand their ground.
</P>
<P>
   What gives the film its emotional center is Nelson's poignant
performance as the shy, hormonally overloaded Mike, whose
girl-chasing adventures begin on the wrong foot when he accepts his
new friends' bet that he won't have the nerve to grab a girl in the
schoolyard. Malinda Williams plays the girl, Alicia, with just the
right mixture of sweetness and sass. In the tenderhearted world of
``The Wood'' (the nickname for Inglewood), that rude prank doesn't
preclude the possibility of a later, blossoming romance. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCTION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   `THE WOOD'
</P>
<P>
   Written and directed by Rick Famuyiwa; based on a story by
Famuyiwa and Todd Boyle; director of photography, Steven Bernstein;
edited by John Carter; music by Pilar McCurry; production
designers, Roger Fortune and Maxine Shepard; produced by Albert
Berger, Ron Yerxa and David Gale; released by Paramount Pictures.
Running time: 106 minutes. This film is rated R (under 17 requires
accompanying parent or adult guardian). It includes a lot of sex
talk and several fairly explicit sexual scenes.
</P>
<P>
   Cast: Sean Nelson (Young Mike), Duane Finley (Young Slim), Trent
Cameron (Young Roland), Omar Epps (Mike), Richard T. Jones (Slim),
Taye Diggs (Roland), Malinda Williams (Young Alicia).
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-15-99 1615EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990715.0225 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-15 16:17 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1465 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KIDMAN-EYES-LADN &LR;      07-15 1364
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KIDMAN-EYES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Q&AMP;A WITH NICOLE  KIDMAN  ON  `EYES WIDE SHUT`
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients)  
By BOB STRAUSS 
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Having devoted close to three years of her and her
husband Tom Cruise's working lives to Stanley Kubrick's
secrecy-shrouded final film, Nicole Kidman is as excited as anyone
that ``Eyes Wide Shut'' finally is about to be seen.
</P>
<P>
   While it's been anticipated for many different reasons, the
late, legendary director's first work in a dozen years represents
another major professional step for Kidman. Born in Hawaii and
raised in a progressive, academic household in Sydney, she had made
an impressive mark in Australian film and television circles before
meeting Cruise on the set of ``Days of Thunder'' 10 years ago and,
soon after, marrying the megastar.
</P>
<P>
   Unfamiliar to Hollywood, it took the 6-foot-tall redhead a
number of years to convince American producers and audiences that
she had more to offer than statuesque beauty. But a series of
provocative and accomplished projects _ the black comedy ``To Die
For,'' the difficult Henry James adaptation ``The Portrait of a
Lady,'' last year's sellout run of David Hare's stage play ``The
Blue Room'' _ recently have established her as one of the world's
most interesting actresses.
</P>
<P>
   Though paired with Cruise, with whom she has two adopted
children, in ``Eyes,'' she cuts a memorably distinctive figure in
the sexually charged psychological study. In a wide-ranging
interview, the friendly, funny and fiercely intelligent Kidman
addressed, among other tough subjects, the most unique and
rewarding job of her life.
</P>
<P>
   Daily News: ``Eyes Wide Shut'' is certainly not your average
Hollywood, nor even your average independent, production. Does it
feel like just another movie to you, or is it something more than
that?
</P>
<P>
   Kidman: Because of all the things that are attached to this
film, it's certainly the most personal thing that I've ever done.
</P>
<P>
   Partly, it's because we spent so long doing it. Also then, the
subject matter, and making it with the person that I live with. And
with one of the people who I admired most in the world and loved
most in the world, who then died ... There are just so many things
in relation to it that take it away from just being another film.
</P>
<P>
   Q: When you say ``Eyes Wide Shut'' is so personal, you realize
that it's going to fuel speculation over what it might reveal about
your and Tom's much-speculated-on marriage.
</P>
<P>
   Kidman: I doubt people are going to think that the characters in
this movie are us. And I know what we are. We really know each
other, we're very committed to each other and we have a great, deep
love, which, I think, will see us through anything.
</P>
<P>
   Q: There must have been some uncomfortable moments while you
were developing these characters, though. Their problems with each
other stem from very intimate, honest places.
</P>
<P>
   Kidman: Well, in a rehearsal room, I'm very honest. You feel
protected by the four walls, that you can say whatever you want and
it's not going to be repeated or put down. That was a pact between
Tom, Stanley and me: Everything that was said was private and would
be kept secret from that time on.
</P>
<P>
   But it was, at times, quite difficult, because I'd hear things
that I maybe didn't want to hear and, I think, Tom would hear
things that he didn't want to hear. It wasn't like therapy, because
you didn't have anyone say, `And how do you feel about that?' It
was honest, and brutally honest at times. But that's why it was so
extraordinary to make it with my partner. If we had made this a
year into our marriage, I don't think we would have gotten through
it. When you've been married for seven years, which we had when we
started this, you've reached a stage in the relationship when you
want to dig a little deeper anyway.
</P>
<P>
   Q: And Kubrick, the director of such sensitive relationship
studies as ``The Shining,'' ``A Clockwork Orange'' and ``Lolita,''
guided you through all of this?
</P>
<P>
   Kidman: We talked about marriage and commitment and all of those
things. He wasn't judgmental, but he did have strong views.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Kubrick had a reputation for not caring much about actors,
yet you and Tom apparently loved and trusted him like few other
directors.
</P>
<P>
   Kidman: Well, Stanley's extraordinary confidence and belief in
his own intelligence and talent was the strongest factor about him.
He would listen to actors, though. Ultimately, the decisions were
all his, but he would pull things from you, he would watch. He was
a great observer of life and a great thinker.
</P>
<P>
   Q: What about the time element? The main photography lasted
nearly a year, there were about two more years' worth of
involvement before and after that, many shots required 35 takes,
some substantially more ...
</P>
<P>
   Kidman: There was something quite beautiful about that. In this
day and age, you have everybody wanting to make film after film
and, quick, get it out in time for summer or for Christmas.
Sometimes, the wonderful aspect of filmmaking or any sort of
artistic experience gets lost in that pressure to just have it
done. Stanley would not buy into that.
</P>
<P>
   It's something that I would have no qualms about doing again.
The only thing you miss out on is other roles, but if you're
working with a great director and a great script, well, what more
could you wish for?
</P>
<P>
   Q: You had just seen the director's cut of ``Eyes Wide Shut''
when Kubrick died unexpectedly last March. After such an intense
collaboration, it must have been devastating.
</P>
<P>
   Kidman: I'm 32, and it was probably the biggest shock that I've
had in my life. I didn't believe it, I wouldn't believe it. I'd
never had to deal with the finality of death, the loss of somebody
you cannot call on the phone anymore.
</P>
<P>
   Q: There must have been another jolt when that posthumously
released trailer he wanted of you and Tom making out in the nude
came out.
</P>
<P>
   Kidman: I was shocked when I first saw it. (Earlier on) I said
to Stanley, ``You cannot release this as the trailer,'' he said,
``Why?'' and I said ``Because I'm naked, Stanley!'' But what I want
or don't want ... I have no say in the marketing of this film.
(laughs) I did the scene, but I was thinking, ``Oh, gosh, this is
going to be so embarrassing.''
</P>
<P>
   Q: Understandable, yet you seem to be so uninhibited. You
undress in the first shot of ``Eyes Wide Shut,'' You took off your
clothes every night when you appeared in ``The Blue Room'' in
London and on Broadway last year ...
</P>
<P>
   Kidman: It's actually not part of my makeup. I was not the girl
in Australia who was topless on the beach; all of my friends were,
but I was not. It's just that you get lost in a character and then
you have to deal with all of the other things that surround doing
nudity. But the one thing you do have is a character to hide
behind. And particularly with this film, I had the protection of
Stanley. I did not feel that I was being exploited.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Speaking of not being exploited, you and Tom are fighting
back against the tabloids and winning.
</P>
<P>
   Kidman: Well, people want to say things that aren't true. Yes,
you're meant to turn the other cheek and ignore it. But I also
think that there's a time when you have to stand up and say,
``We're willing to fight this battle.'' You can't do it on every
one and you shouldn't do it on every one. But I think that when
somebody calls you a liar or says that (your marriage) is a sham or
any of those sort of things, you have to fight them because that's
not true.
</P>
<P>
   Q: You've been back home in Sydney, where Tom is shooting
``Mission: Impossible 2,'' since the beginning of the year.
</P>
<P>
   Kidman: Yeah. My sister lives up the road, and my mom's nearby.
The kids are in school.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Does that, and the fact that the kids are getting older, make
you feel more like settling down in one place now?
</P>
<P>
   Kidman: I think we've got another couple of years we're going to
travel, and, then, we'll settle. But just in terms of being actors,
part of your existence is moving around. And we're very lucky
because both of us love to keep moving. I love the change, the
unpredictable. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
