<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PLOT-BOOK-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`THIS BLESSED PLOT' : THE VIEW ACROSS THE CHANNEL 
</HEADLINE>
  (Publication notes appear at end of review.) 
(DW) 
 By SAMUEL HYNES   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   In the last 50 years of British politics, no other issue has
been as important, as divisive and as stubbornly irresolvable as
the struggle to turn Britain into a European country. ``Europe''
has dominated British foreign policy, split political parties,
rattled the economy, determined elections and overthrown a powerful
prime minister. It continues to be a determining factor in British
politics: in last month's elections for the European Parliament,
the Tories, a party that has been in intensive care since the 1997
elections, won more seats than the ruling Labor Party, with no more
platform than its intransigent opposition to a single European
currency.
</P>
<P>
   On the Continent during those 50 years, the European Union
slowly but steadily took form, expanding from an agreement on coal
and steel to an Economic Community, extending into international
law, moving toward a common social policy, a common defense policy
and eventually political union. While that steady evolution toward
union proceeded, politicians across the Channel in Britain jittered
uncertainly, like children at the edge of a cold sea: one step
forward, one step back, a plunge in at the wrong time, then a quick
withdrawal from the shock of contact. For Britain it was a
half-century of stumbling national embarrassment; and the story is
still unfinished.
</P>
<P>
   No British writer is better qualified to tell that story than
Hugo Young. As political editor of The Sunday Times, political
columnist for The Guardian and biographer of Margaret Thatcher, he
has been for more than 30 years as close to the political
playmakers of Westminster as one could get without entering the
game.
</P>
<P>
   On the question of union with Europe, he is neither a Europhile
nor Europhobe, but a Euro-realist. In his view, union has been
Britain's destiny from the beginning; ``Europe'' was going to
happen, and British leaders should have recognized that truth and
joined in at the start. They didn't. They rejected the Schuman
Plan, stayed away from the Messina Conference, declined to sign the
Treaty of Rome, agreed to monetary union only tardily and
reluctantly (and then withdrew) and opted out of important clauses
of the Maastricht Treaty.
</P>
<P>
   Young is impatient with this battle against the tide: ``British
perversity,'' he calls it. During the years when the European
Community was evolving, opportunities arose that Britain should
have seized at once, he says; but time passed, nothing was done,
and the opportunities were lost. The moral is clear: a nation that
denies its destiny will get it anyway, but on worse terms.
</P>
<P>
   The history of Britain's stumbling course toward union is not a
story of party against party; both Labor and the Conservatives have
split on the issue. For Labor's Old Left, union has sometimes
seemed a capitalist conspiracy and sometimes a socialist
opportunity, while for Tony Blair's New Labor it has simply been
the future, as easy to accept as next year's calendar. Conservative
moderates like Edward Heath have urged entry into Europe as an
economic necessity, but to Tories on his right, union in all its
stages has seemed a monster that would devour British sovereignty
and separate the nation from its two great alliances, with the
Commonwealth and with the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Young's title comes from Shakespeare's ``Richard II,'' in which
the dying John of Gaunt mourns the decline of England, ``this
blessed plot, this earth, this realm, this England,'' Young's book
is a political drama with a cast of characters taken from what he
calls ``the political class,'' the elected members of British
governments and their advisers.
</P>
<P>
   Young has little good to say about them. He finds the class as a
whole guilty of ``incompetence and bad faith,'' ``vacillating
torpor,'' ``helpless ambivalence'' and ``evasion and duplicity.''
These seem to be peculiarly British political failings; the
political class in Europe works well enough, by Young's account.
</P>
<P>
   He compares himself at one point to a scientist, ``curious to
map the pathology'' of his specimens. But when the heat of the
drama rises, the specimens become individuals with their own
complex and memorable identities, often fixed in a vivid phrase.
</P>
<P>
   The stars are of course the prime ministers: Winston Churchill
at Zurich in 1946, the ``grandiloquent map maker'' breathing out
rhetorical promises; Harold Macmillan, ``besotted and ensnared by
the past'' and no match for Charles de Gaulle; Harold Wilson, whose
mastery of ambiguity amounted to genius; Margaret Thatcher, who
cried ``No!'' while she took Britain further into Europe and in the
end was undone by what she had done; poor John Major,
underqualified and overshadowed, whose photo in the book is
captioned, ``My hesitation is final.''
</P>
<P>
   Two are the heroes of the story: Edward Heath, the most faithful
and courageous of British Europeans, and Tony Blair, left at the
book's end confronting the completion of the job: a common
currency, a common defense and ultimately political union: a United
States of Europe.
</P>
<P>
   Prime ministers are the stars, but there are many other strong
characters: the would-be prime ministers, Hugh Gaitskill and Rab
Butler and Roy Jenkins; the Continental players, de Gaulle, Jean
Monnet, Paul-Henri Spaak and Helmut Kohl, and a supporting cast of
minor figures, middle-level Whitehall officials whose names we
don't recognize, who understood the future and tried to move
Britain toward it but were impeded by the incompetence and
duplicity of their bosses. Young is a brilliant portraitist, a just
historian of this huge cast and a lucid teller of their complicated
story.
</P>
<P>
   Near the beginning of the book he quotes from the writing of Sir
John Tizard in 1949 when he was chief scientific adviser to the
Ministry of Defense: ``We persist in regarding ourselves as a Great
Power, capable of everything and only temporarily handicapped by
economic difficulties. We are not a Great Power and never will be
again. We are a great nation, but if we continue to behave like a
Great Power, we shall soon cease to be a great nation.''
</P>
<P>
   That was the year of the first meeting of the European Assembly.
It was wise advice then, and it is wise now, but it has not yet
been learned by all the members of the political class or by all
the people. Britain _ not ``Great'' Britain any longer _ is a small
nation on the edge of Europe, burdened by history and by memory,
still learning the difference between power and lower-case
greatness.
</P>
<P>
   PUBLICATION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   `THIS BLESSED PLOT: BRITAIN AND EUROPE FROM CHURCHILL TO BLAIR1'
</P>
<P>
   By Hugo Young
</P>
<P>
   Illustrated. 558 pages. Overlook Press. $39.95.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
