<BODY>
 AM-PAGE1-CONSIDER-NYT 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Here are the stories New York Times editors are considering for
Page 1, Friday, July 16. The N.Y. Times News Service Night
Supervisor is Lynn Hoogenboom; phone: (888) 346-9867; e-mail:
lhooge(at)nytimes.com.
</P>
<P>
   INTERNATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in ``i'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   NIRELAND-PEACE (Belfast, Ireland) _ What was to have been the
most important day in the Northern Ireland peace effort broke down
in chaos and recriminations as a top Catholic official in the new
Northern Ireland government quit after the main Protestant party
boycotted Thursday's discussions. By Warren Hoge.
</P>
<P>
   ISRAEL-U.S. (Washington) _ On the meeting between Israeli Prime
Minister Ehud Barak and President Clinton in Washington Thursday
afternoon. By Jane Perlez and John M. Broder.
</P>
<P>
   IRAN-PROTESTS (Islamshar, Iran) _ In a working-class suburb of
Tehran where the government put down an economic protest a few
years ago, people clamor for jobs, not press freedom, and they're
just as disgruntled as the pro-democracy demonstrators. By Elaine
Sciolino.
</P>
<P>
   INDIA-TELEVISED-WAR (Mokhra, India) _ India has fought three
larger wars with Pakistan, in 1947, 1965 and 1971, but the past two
months of fighting in the Himalayan land of Kashmir that lies
between the two countries have produced its first televised war. In
1971, less than 1 percent of Indian households had televisions.
Now, more than 30 percent of households own a television. By Celia
W. Dugger.
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in ``w'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   HEALTH-CARE (Washington) _ On the Senate vote expected late
Thursday on the Republican version of the Patients' Bill of Rights.
(Vote may come as late as 11 p.m. ET.) By Alison Mitchell.
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL-GENERAL
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in ``a'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   EDS: These two national stories will be held if they do not make
Page One.
</P>
<P>
   COURT-SETTLEMENTS (Undated) _ More than a decade after states
began enacting laws to cut back big jury awards and curtail injury
lawsuits, state courts across the country are overturning one
measure after another, concluding that Americans have a powerful
right to settle their disputes in court. By William Glaberson.
</P>
<P>
   RECYCLED-CLOTHES (Providence, R.I.) _ Rising prosperity has
shaken the ways that Americans view and use clothing, so much so
that cast-off clothes have become the flotsam of
turn-of-the-century affluence. In 1998 Americans bought 17.2
billion articles of clothing and gave the Salvation Army alone
several hundred million pieces, well over 100,000 tons. The glut is
a boon to the many charities like the Salvation Army that sort and
sell old clothes. While clothes have become relatively cheap, the
greatest spur to shopping and shedding may be fast-changing
fashions. By Peter Kilborn. (With photo.)
</P>
<P>
   FINANCIAL
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in ``f'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   FASTER-COMPUTERS (Palo Alto, Calif.) _ Plunging deeply into a
Liliputian world that promises ultrafast, low-power computers, a
team of Hewlett Packard Co. and UCLA researchers have for the first
time fashioned simple computing components no thicker than a single
molecule. By John Markoff. (With photo and graphic.)
</P>
