<HEADER>
A1507 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TUNA16-COX     07-15 0407
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TUNA16-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    HOUSE MEMBERS CRITICIZE NEW LIMITS ON TUNA CATCH
 &HT;    By JONATHAN HALL
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ House members Thursday criticized a new federal
rule limiting recreational fishermen to three yellowfin tuna a day.
</P>
<P>
   At a hearing of a House Resources subcommittee, Rep. Jim Saxton,
R-N.J., called the rule issued by the National Marine Fisheries
Service ``premature.'' Prior to the new limit, ``the recreational
yellowfin tuna fishery had been successfully self-regulated,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Yellowfin tuna are a highly migratory fish species that inhabit
the Atlantic. In the United States, they are most commonly found
off the coasts of eastern Atlantic states.
</P>
<P>
   The rule, which became effective July 1, is part of the
Fisheries Service's final fish management plan for Atlantic tuna,
swordfish and sharks. The plan was released in April and was
required by the 1996 amendments of the Magnuson-Stevens Act, which
requires the rebuilding and maintaining of overfished areas.
</P>
<P>
   ``These management measures are consistent with Magnuson-Stevens
Act requirements to prevent overfishing before it occurs,'' said
Dr. Gary Matlock, the service's director of sustainable fisheries.
``If this stock becomes overfished, fishermen would have to face
more stringent management measures in order to rebuild.''
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Frank Pallone, D-N.J., said that with the limit, U.S.
recreational fishermen will lose their desire to fish for yellowfin
tuna. ``The bottom line is that there's an incentive for people if
they know that they can catch more than three. If that incentive
isn't there, even if they don't catch them, it's a disincentive.''
</P>
<P>
   Committee members also asked why the service obtains its
scientific information on Atlantic tuna stock through ICATT, the
international commission for tuna conservation.
</P>
<P>
   They said it would have been more appropriate to use scientific
information provided by the states when developing a rule that
affects the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Bruce Freeman, a research scientist at the New Jersey Department
of Environmental Protection, agreed that the service isn't using
the best scientific information possible. Instead of limiting the
number of fish that can be caught, the service instead should
recommend minimum size regulations to prevent overharvesting, he
said.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
