<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-15 16:36 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1508 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-AGING-ART-REVIEW-2TAK     07-15 0853
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AGING-ART-REVIEW-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW MUSEUM OF CONTEMPORARY ART: AN ODE TO OLD AGE, LIFE'S GIFT 
</HEADLINE>
  (yn) 
 By ROBERTA SMITH   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ At the age of 59, Marcia Tucker is bidding farewell
to the New Museum of Contemporary Art in her usual style. Her swan
song at the museum she single-handedly founded 22 years ago is
``The Time of Our Lives,'' an exhibition that is characteristically
personal, topical, rough around the edges and intent on raising
consciousness.
</P>
<P>
   Alternately sappy and insightful, this exhibition ignores most
esthetic issues and instead brings together a broad array of art
and artifacts _ from paintings to television commercials _
pertaining to a complex human and social theme: growing old. The
result is less an art exhibition than a multifaceted learning
experience; therein lie its weaknesses as well as its intermittent
strengths.
</P>
<P>
   Aging is a condition from which no one who is lucky enough to
live so long escapes, a condition that many, American women in
particular, view with sometimes crippling, self-negating, if
self-indulgent despair. With increased life expectancy and the
graying of the immense baby boomer generation, aging is an ever
more visible fact of American life, a subject of study on many
fronts and an economic factor as well.
</P>
<P>
   Geriatric specialists are on the rise in the medical profession.
``Age theory'' has become a subject for scholars and cultural
critics who are dovetailing it with existing theories about race,
gender and identity. Aging is more and more a subject of television
specials, talk shows and articles in fashion magazines; a spur to
the cosmetics and health industries and the building of both
retirement communities and ``old age'' residences.
</P>
<P>
   Despite these developments, however, ours is a profoundly
youth-oriented culture that often seems to believe that the aged
should be neither seen nor heard. Ageism, as Ms. Tucker points out
in her spirited catalog essay, is a prejudice like any other. It
permeates our lives from birth, affecting everything from
government policy to popular culture and the media. Youth is
equated with beauty, aging with death.
</P>
<P>
   As a crude measure of how society views aging, we have only to
consider the rather short professional life of the Hollywood
actress, the paradigm of youth and beauty, and the interesting
actresses on the far side of 40 who have not appeared in a movie in
years. Ms. Tucker means for her exhibition to take a look at all
this and in particular how society's notions about age affect
women's views of themselves.
</P>
<P>
   The works of art, film and video on view here mostly confront
the joys or sorrows of aging head-on; others address the obsession
with youth or the passage of time itself. Also on view on different
monitors throughout the show are pertinent television commercials
and sitcoms, including the famous 1972 segments of ``Maude,'' in
which the 47-year-old Maude (Bea Arthur) discovers to her horror
that she is pregnant; and ``When You're Hot, You're Hot'' and
``Edith's Problem,'' segments from ``Cybill'' and ``All in the
Family,'' respectively, in which lead characters confront
menopause.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the museum's ground-floor galleries are devoted to a
display of 35 works by 21 artists, some well known and some less
familiar, two-thirds of whom are women. Images of the aging female
body, usually nude, predominate.
</P>
<P>
   The show opens with Jeff Wall's glowing Duratran-box image of
the interior of a modern library into which he has digitally
inserted the colossal image of a naked older woman who towers over
the library visitors.
</P>
<P>
   She stands on the landing of a sleekly 20th-century double
staircase, much the way an idealized statue of a Greek god might
occupy a landing on the marble staircase of a library at an old,
established men's college _ a symbol of pride, beauty and cultural
accomplishment so thoroughly taken for granted that no one bothers
to look at it anymore.
</P>
<P>
   Across the way is Lisa Yuskavage's ``Manifest Destiny,'' a
characteristically ambiguous image featuring one of the artist's
libidinous vixens, shown here in the shadow of a tall, icy,
columnlike woman, an idealized female who has in effect become her
own pedestal. Next to it is Marina Abramovic's ``Cleaning the
Mirror II,'' a vanitas image in video that consists of a close-up
of the artist lying naked beneath a human skeleton that shifts,
coming ever so slightly to life, when she breathes.
</P>
<P>
   Other works include a series of four photographs from Consuelo
Castaneda's ``Speed-Split'' series in which the artist is seen from
above lying beside her mother, their naked bodies tenderly curled
together in a pose that is both fetal and suggestive of the
``spooning'' of lovers; Nancy Burson's heartrending photographs of
children suffering from progeria, a rare genetic disorder that ages
them prematurely; and ``70 + 1,'' a startlingly three-dimensional
full-length hologram self-portrait by Harriet Casdin-Silver, in
which the 71-year-old artist stands tall (balanced on one foot),
while cupping her breasts.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-15-99 1636EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990715.0237 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-15 16:36 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1509 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  AGING-ART-REVIEW-2NDTAKE     07-15 0820
</HEADER>
<BODY>
 AGING-ART-REVIEW-2NDTAKE-NYT  
 NEW YORK: her breasts.  
<TEXT>
<P>
   One of Cindy Sherman's best-known ``Sex'' series images further
reminds us that desire is not the exclusive domain of youth. It
shows an old hag, constructed from prosthetic body parts, giving
birth to a string of sausages, a mad, toothless grin on her face.
Jacqueline Hayden makes a similar point in a large untitled black
and white photograph from her ``Figure Model'' series, which quotes
the pose of Venus and Cupid _ he pinches her nipple _ from
Bronzino's ``Venus, Cupid, Folly and Time,'' recasting them as a
dignified elderly man and woman.
</P>
<P>
   Like many photographs and portraits of elderly people, these
images suggest that spirit and flesh are separate entities, with
their own distinct time lines. But the scale and nakedness of the
figures here give the notion a visceral force. This is nowhere more
apparent than in the large black and white photographs from Manabu
Yamanaka's ``Gyahtei'' series at the end of the exhibition.
</P>
<P>
   Each is a life-size image of an elderly nude Japanese woman
whose shriveled, shrunken body makes the ravages of time shockingly
palpable. But in each case the eye is drawn to their open, animated
faces. These images also reflect the great respect accorded old
people in Asian cultures, which in China and Japan in particular
include frequent artistic portrayals of ancient beings in a host of
roles, as sages, ancestors, beggars and mischievous spirits.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Tucker is not above a cheerful heavy-handedness when it
comes to tweaking the details of her show to reflect its theme. The
exhibition's seating consists entirely of thickly cushioned
glider-rocking chairs, ghastly to look at but heavenly to sit in.
(Literally, you'll feel airborne.) Throughout her long
acknowledgments and in the requisite lists of the museum's staff
members and board of trustees in the catalog, the names are almost
always followed by their ages, her own included.
</P>
<P>
   The catalog also includes comments about aging excerpted from
Ms. Tucker's diary, starting at age 15. And just in case we haven't
grasped society's distorted views of the old, adjacent to
Yamanaka's photographs hangs a full-length mirror in which visitors
can see their own reflections. The primary weakness here, as in
most subject-driven shows, is that regardless of quality, the art
on view almost inevitably functions as mere illustration of the
larger theme. You could say that everything here is either part of
the problem or part of the solution, and either way subsumed within
the larger mood of piousness, public service and pedagogy.
</P>
<P>
   The works that elude this condition tend to be found in the
exhibition's video and film portions.
</P>
<P>
   It is only amid moving images accompanied by spoken words or
music that the richness of the subject of aging comes truly to
life. Worthwhile works include Carol Halstead's ``Why,'' a mostly
computer-animated collage that recounts her life's story in 16
action-packed minutes, and Gail Noonan's playfully caustic,
beautifully drawn animated short film, ``Your Name in Cellulite.''
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes the films have the egalitarian, thrown-together feel
of the show itself. A prime example is ``Whisper, the Waves, the
Wind,'' by Suzanne Lacy, a California artist known for organizing
and filming participatory performance pieces. This particular work,
best described as a living Christo with Felliniesque undertones,
involved 150 women between the ages of 60 and 99, who dressed in
the white garments of their choice and converged on a beach near La
Jolla.
</P>
<P>
   There, they gathered at white tables and talked about their
lives, creating a ready-made grass-roots documentary full of vivid
glimpses of personalities, lives and hard-won wisdom.
</P>
<P>
   But the film program also includes impeccably thought-through
and structured works of art, like Yvonne Rainer's 1990
``Privilege,'' which shows Ms. Rainer's resonant style _ a
slow-moving but riveting mixture of paradocumentary and popular
film clips, theory and humorous self-reference, dramatic flashbacks
and quiet conversation _ at its best.
</P>
<P>
   The subject here is menopause, but the film weaves its theme
into an intricate transparent web that probes racism of the most
subtle sort (between women of different races, for example), the
role of racial prejudice and class in sexual attraction, and
women's ambivalence about being objectified. Throughout, a string
of medical authorities, seen in old documentaries, demonstrate
their pathetic ignorance of menopause, women and aging.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Tucker's exhibition provides a kind of aerial view of the
changing landscape of thought about aging that tells us repeatedly
that this condition is not a burden, but a gift to be savored and
appreciated to the benefit of all. It does this in ways that veer
from simplistic to complex. As Ms. Rainer's film confirms, complex
is better.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
