A1513 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ALBUM-OF-THE-WEEK-NYT     07-15 0291
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ALBUM-OF-THE-WEEK-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`MONSTER BALLADS' 
</HEADLINE>
  (jt) 
 By ANN POWERS    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   VARIOUS ARTISTS: ``Monster Ballads'' (Razor and Tie). In a
startling demonstration of just how strong warped memories can be,
the 16-song retail version of this 1980s pop-metal anthology (also
available as a double disk through television and Internet
promotions) recently made its debut at No. 29 in the Billboard Top
200. Thousands are revisiting the pinnacles of schmaltz reached by
the androgynous demigods of Winger, Whitesnake, Poison and Extreme.
This once-shunned oeuvre is being reclaimed as great pop theater
that outclasses today's stupid kid stuff.
</P>
<P>
   Why? Partly because such music really is fun, especially when
it's history instead of the only thing on the radio. ``Monster
Ballads'' satisfies myriad sugar cravings, whether for earnestly
generic love ballads, sing-alongs by hunks relaxing, the socially
conscious musings of great dudes, operatic exercises in which
singers endanger their vocal cords, or mind-numbing collections of
musical and lyrical cliches. Every song is an excuse for onstage
fireworks yet somehow deeply sincere.
</P>
<P>
   There's another reason folks now long for these wildly
sentimental tirades. Pop's current division between ``soft''
teen-age bands and ``hard'' rappers or heavy rockers leaves little
room for epic romanticism. Although ``Monster Ballads'' overlooks
some greats, like Jon Bon Jovi, it recaptures that glorious moment
when tough guys enjoyed baring their hearts. ``Every bad boy has a
soft side'' the album's promotional campaign announces, but now
pop's bad boys fear softness, and its soft boys lack emotional
muscle. Nostalgic retreats like this one remedy that lack.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-15-99 1638EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990715.0240 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-15 16:40 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1516 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SMUGGLED-PEOPLE-HNS &LR;      07-15 1194
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SMUGGLED-PEOPLE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FEDS TRY TO SLAM DOOR ON PERVASIVE SMUGGLING TRADE 
</HEADLINE>
   (EDs: Photo available on Wieck database)  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By DANE SCHILLER  
 c.1999 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   RAYMONDVILLE, Texas _ Whether it was the take-out order for 200
hamburgers or bulk sales of pre-cooked chicken and jugs of water,
there have long been hints of smugglers stashing legions of illegal
immigrants here.
</P>
<P>
   But few residents openly spoke of the covert industry before a
dozen people, including a former city commissioner and six members
of his family, recently pleaded guilty to roles in a ring that
allegedly smuggled thousands of people over a 15-year period.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a two-horse town where everybody knows everybody, and
there are no secrets,'' said George Pitts, as he took a break from
reading the Bible in his discount store.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody and their grandmother knew they were smuggling and
had been for years,'' said Pitts, a former missionary, who concedes
he smuggled a few immigrants in his younger years.
</P>
<P>
   Even so, few outsiders knew the extent of the underground
network that pumps through this South Texas town of 9,400 people,
50 miles north of Brownsville and the Rio Grande.
</P>
<P>
   Raymondville, located on the northern edge of the Rio Grande
Valley, is seen as ``choke point'' for all foot and vehicle traffic
headed out of the Valley and a prime place to plot evading a U.S.
Border Patrol checkpoint 40 miles up U.S. 77.
</P>
<P>
   The patrol got its first taste of Raymondville's open secret in
January 1997 when agents discovered 356 would-be immigrants stuffed
in shacks owned by a local family.
</P>
<P>
   ``People were everywhere,'' recalled Rick Aguirre, head of the
Border Patrol's anti-smuggling operations. ``It was wild.''
</P>
<P>
   Agent Javier McClain added: ``We'd knock on a door, and there
were a hundred eyes staring at you.''
</P>
<P>
   In dingy, musty-smelling rooms with soiled mattresses,
immigrants would spend up to a week waiting to move north. Dirty
windows were often nailed shut, and boards were placed across doors
to keep them closed.
</P>
<P>
   It was a place where immigrants could hook up with smugglers,
also known as ``coyotes,'' or where smugglers could trade off
immigrants depending on where they were headed or how much they
could pay for passage.
</P>
<P>
   Although officials could not estimate how much money was
collected over the 15 years of smuggling operations, they said an
illegal immigrant could pay up to $500 to reach Houston.
</P>
<P>
   ``Just about everybody in town knew what was going on but would
never do anything about it,'' said a resident who asked not to be
named publicly.
</P>
<P>
   The 1997 raid resulted in what the Border Patrol called
``Operation Snake Pit.''
</P>
<P>
   Under the initiative, the patrol infiltrated this town, which
had become a major staging ground for those preparing to sneak
across ranchlands that separate the Rio Grande Valley from the rest
of the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Some agents openly patrolled the streets, while others set up an
office in a mobile home and sought tips from cooperative residents.
</P>
<P>
   Among the leads they gathered were about masses of food being
passed into vacant buildings and about shoppers buying in large
quantities at downtown groceries.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, a handful of Hispanic officers posed as
``coyotes'' and would-be immigrants headed for Houston.
</P>
<P>
   The immigrants pay to be smuggled into the United States to
search for jobs. Most of the time they are sent back to Mexico
voluntarily.
</P>
<P>
   During the first two months of the operation, agents apprehended
more than 6,900 illegal immigrants here, along U.S. 77 and the
surrounding brushlands, and more than 150 people were charged with
transporting or assisting them, Aguirre said.
</P>
<P>
   Agents would sweep past motels, looking for excessive window
condensation caused when rooms are abnormally packed.
</P>
<P>
   The would also sniff the openings of doors for excessive body
odor left by large numbers of rugged travelers who had not bathed
in days or weeks.
</P>
<P>
   ``The smell of success,'' Aguirre called it.
</P>
<P>
   The new pressure was a change of pace for a town that had been
all but immune to a patrol already stretched trying to keep agents
along the Rio Grande, an hour's drive south of here.
</P>
<P>
   Rene Martin, Raymondville's chief of police, said he passed on
information to the patrol because his officers were powerless to
make arrests for violations of federal law.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our concerns are everything from dog bites to killings,''
Martin said.
</P>
<P>
   Still, he was surprised by what agents discovered during that
initial raid.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had no idea of the magnitude of the situation. The day they
arrested three hundred people, my jaw was on the floor,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``We went in there full force, hit it with everything we had,
and created havoc in the town,'' Aguirre said of Operation Snake
Pit when the first indictments were returned by a federal grand
jury in February.
</P>
<P>
   Twelve people, including seven members of the Contreras family,
pleaded guilty to numerous charges in federal court in Brownsville
late last week.
</P>
<P>
   Abel Contreras Sr., the 61-year-old former city commissioner,
declined to discuss the charges, but he said their lives have been
turned upside down.
</P>
<P>
   All are free on bond, face sentencing in October and could spend
up to three years in prison.
</P>
<P>
   ``It has been hard. I sold groceries here for thirty years,''
Contreras said solemnly as he stood in his all-but-empty store that
was a combination grocery, restaurant and bar.
</P>
<P>
   With his guilty plea, he can no longer sell alcohol, and with
mounting legal bills and declining numbers of customers, he's even
had to sell his pool tables.
</P>
<P>
   As part of the plea bargain, the National Guard will bulldoze
several pieces of property that housed illegal immigrants,
including a house, two small apartment buildings and a small motel,
all owned by the Contrerases.
</P>
<P>
   ``God knows why these things are happening. There is a reason
and a purpose,'' said his daughter, Yolanda Hernandez, 37, who also
pleaded guilty.
</P>
<P>
   ``God has always been good to me. He has always been my
provider,'' said Hernandez, who stands to lose the Los Milagros
Apartments, a six-room complex across the street from the grocery
store her family has operated for three decades.
</P>
<P>
   About two miles away at the Rock Courts Motel and Lounge, which
is also set to be bulldozed, her brother David Contreras, 41, said
he doesn't know what the future holds.
</P>
<P>
   Standing on a wood floor in his bar which is thick with
mementos, including posters of Marilyn Monroe, Malcom X and a host
of ``Star Trek'' models, Contreras said it will hard to watch the
bulldozers.
</P>
<P>
   ``It did not hit me right away,'' he said of the thought of
losing his place. ``The most important thing is I still have my
family. I just want to put this behind me and get on with my
life.''
</P>
<P>
   The Border Patrol says Operation Snake Pit threw smuggling
efforts into disarray, but they are quick to say someone else
already has filled the vacuum.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like any other business,'' Aguirre said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
