<HEADER>
A1537 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HOME-VIDEO-NYT &LR;      07-15 1325
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOME-VIDEO-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOME VIDEO NOTES AND NEWS 
</HEADLINE>
  (jt) 
 By PETER M. NICHOLS    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Perfect Timing For Kubrick Set
</P>
<P>
   Adept at the commemorative tie-in, video scored impressively on
June 29 with the Stanley Kubrick collection, 10 films released
collaboratively on videocassette and digital video disk by Warner,
Columbia Tri-Star and MGM/UA. A boxed set of seven of the films on
DVD, priced at $149.92, is already on best-seller lists, with
interest fanned by Kubrick's death in March and the opening Friday
of his last film, ``Eyes Wide Shut.''
</P>
<P>
   For a box of good movies from a single director it's hard to
beat the Kubrick seven: ``Lolita'' (1962), ``Dr. Strangelove''
(1964), ``2001: A Space Odyssey'' (1968), ``A Clockwork Orange''
(1971), ``Barry Lyndon'' (1975), ``The Shining'' (1980) and ``Full
Metal Jacket'' (1987). ``Dr. Strangelove'' is from Columbia
Tri-Star. All the others are from Warner.
</P>
<P>
   Three more Kubrick films _ ``Killer's Kiss'' (1955), ``The
Killing'' (1956) and ``Paths of Glory'' (1957) _ have been released
separately by MGM/UA but are not included in the set. Why not?
David Miller, the marketing manager, said that their inclusion
would have made the boxed collection too unwieldy. ``It was pushing
it as it was with seven disks,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Still, in their slender jackets the DVD set takes up less than
3{ inches on the shelf. Warren Lieberfarb, president of Warner Home
Video and the liaison with Kubrick on the series, expressed
disappointment that the earlier MGM/UA films weren't included.
``Stanley wanted `Paths of Glory' in the collection, but he didn't
have the kind of contractual rights to impose that on MGM,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Lieberfarb, a principal backer of DVD, said that he had talked
with Kubrick about the format for seven years. But while Kubrick
was attracted to DVD's superior image and sound, he didn't involve
himself with the extra features that are plentiful on many disks
but decidedly on the light side throughout this set.
</P>
<P>
   ``The production and post-production of `Eyes Wide Shut' limited
the time that he had to create and research the extra content,''
Lieberfarb said. Warner, he added, didn't presume to add material
on its own, though other elements could be stirred into future
releases.
</P>
<P>
   Only two of the films have interviews or documentaries. ``2001:
A Space Odyssey'' includes an after-lunch talk by Arthur C. Clarke,
on whose novel the film is based. ``The Shining'' has an excellent
documentary by Kubrick's daughter Vivian about the making of the
film.
</P>
<P>
   It is Kubrick's sole appearance. At the start, Jack Nicholson,
who plays a writer gone murderously berserk, brushes his teeth
before a late-night shoot. Nicholson says he always brushes in
consideration of his fellow actors. ``It's grueling enough without
a face full of lamb cutlets,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   On the set Kubrick is civil but aloof. Stress is palpable.
``Stanley doesn't relate to it,'' Nicholson says, ``because he's
doing exactly what he thinks he should be doing.'' That's all right
with Nicholson. ``I want to be out of control as an actor,'' he
says. ``I want him to have control.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NEW RELEASES &LR;
</P>
<P>
   `The General'
</P>
<P>
   Having actually broken into the home of the director John
Boorman some years ago, the Irish master thief Martin Cahill makes
ideal grist for Boorman's canny, elegant film. More mischievous
than malicious, Cahill (played by Brendan Gleeson, left) kept his
face from public view, maintained two-household domestic
arrangements with his wife and her sister and kept one step ahead
of his police nemesis, Inspector Ned Kenny (Jon Voight), until his
death in 1994. Presented with the chance, Boorman, Janet Maslin
wrote in The New York Times, ``tells this tale of an Irish
underworld original with an unerring instinct for the captivating
detail.''
</P>
<P>
   _1998. Columbia Tri-Star. $99.36. 123 minutes. R. Release date:
July 20.
</P>
<P>
   `Down in the Delta'
</P>
<P>
   When the Chicago inner-city environment imperils her drug-prone
daughter (Alfre Woodard) and grandchildren (Mpho Koaho and Kulani
Hassen), Rosa Lynn (Mary Alice) packs them off for the summer to
her brother, Earl (Al Freeman Jr.), who lives in the family
homestead in Mississippi. All families should have an Uncle Earl,
whose concern and patience begins to melt his relatives' Chicago
shell and who introduces them to the nurturing strength of loving
care and family heritage. Maya Angelou's film ``may be an
impossible dream, a cinematic Hallmark card of familial
togetherness, but the vision it offers is still a dream worth
dreaming'' (Stephen Holden).
</P>
<P>
   _1998. Miramax. $104.16. 111 minutes. Closed captioned. PG-13.
Release date: July 20.
</P>
<P>
   `Eight Millimeter'
</P>
<P>
   A sedate widow asks Tom Welles (Nicolas Cage), a private
detective and family man, to look at film belonging to her late
husband that appears to depict the authentic slaughter of a
teen-age girl. It's enough to set even the violence-hardened Cage
to wincing and cringing. On the trail of the apparent victim and
killer, Tom finds himself in the sleaziest precincts of Los
Angeles, where he gets some help from a porn-shop clerk (Joaquin
Phoenix) and runs into suitably sinister characters. But Tom
remains pretty much a bore. Supposedly discovering the darker side
to a buttoned-down character, Joel Schumacher's film ``barely makes
his reactions apparent'' (Maslin).
</P>
<P>
   _1999. Columbia Tri-Star. $106.77. 119 minutes. Closed
captioned. R. Release date: July 20.
</P>
<P>
   `Virus'
</P>
<P>
   Described as ``lightning that can think _ a new life form,'' the
threat is really the latest gimmick from the ``Alien'' school. This
time it comes in the form of robots who regard humans as the virus
and threaten a tugboat crew captained by a greedy wacko (Donald
Sutherland) and navigated by an admiral's daughter (Jamie Lee
Curtis). Fortunately, the director, John Bruno, ``knows enough to
keep the drivel flowing too quickly for anyone to slump unconscious
over their popcorn and sticky soda with a bad case of deja vu''
(Lawrence Van Gelder).
</P>
<P>
   _1999. Universal. $107.37. 100 minutes. Closed captioned. R.
Release date: July 20.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Other new titles of interest, some of which may have had a
theater release at one time, appeared on television or been on
videocassette in earlier editions.  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   `FOR EVER MOZART'  &UR;  &LR; An extended meditation on the relation
between movies and life, Jean-Luc Godard's film follows an aging
French director and a group of actors to the former Yugoslavia,
where they hope to stage and film an Alfred de Musset comedy, ``One
Must Not Play at Love.'' In Bosnia, the actors are caught up in the
war, arrested and shot. So much for the pretensions of cultural
literati who think that injecting a little intellectual largess
into a far-off hot spot will make a difference. But then, the
director, who slipped away before the executions, retreats to make
a political film. At this point, Stephen Holden wrote in The New
York Times, `` `For Ever Mozart' sharpens its focus and becomes a
melancholy, exquisitely beautiful elegy to the dream of movies as
high art.'' 1996. New Yorker. $89.95. 85 minutes. French with
English subtitles.
</P>
<P>
   `MY NAME IS JOE' &UR;  &LR; In Ken Loach's film, a middle-aged recovering
alcoholic (Peter Mullan) with a wild past tries to restart his life
with the help of a health worker (Louise Goodall). 1998. Artisan.
$105.77. 105 minutes. R.
</P>
<P>
   `GUIMBA'  &UR;  &LR; A wandering griot describes the evil ruler Guimba as
a ``tyrant in his own time,'' but mainly the malevolence in this
movie is directed at meddling in other people's lives for the sake
of matchmaking. Directed by Cheick Oumar Sissoko, who is from Mali,
the film, Janet Maslin wrote in the New York Times, is ``less
interesting for its parable about tyranny than for the fairy-tale
look Sissoko gives its props and settings.'' 1996. Kino. $79.95. 93
minutes. In Bambara and Peul with English subtitles. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-15-99 1653EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
