<DOCNO> NYT19990715.0248 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-15 16:53 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1541 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GOD-BILLBOARDS-$ADV18     07-15 0741
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GOD-BILLBOARDS-$ADV18-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GOD IS SPEAKING FROM BILLBOARDS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For release Sunday, July 18)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ERIC ROSENBERG  
 c.1999 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ God is speaking to motorists.
</P>
<P>
   From billboards and posters, along highways and in bus shelters
across the nation, the Lord is delivering short messages with
Madison Avenue flair designed to amuse _ and prod the fallen back
to their pews.
</P>
<P>
   In large white letters against a stark field of black, one
poster in Ft. Lauderdale, Fla., asks, ``You think it's hot here?''
A billboard in Baltimore says, ``We need to talk,'' while another
in Dallas says, ``Keep using my name in vain, and I'll make rush
hour longer.''
</P>
<P>
   Still another says, ``Big Bang Theory? You've got to be
kidding.''
</P>
<P>
   All are black with white lettering, and all are signed simply
``God.''
</P>
<P>
   The signs _ there are 18 different versions _ are part of a
public service campaign to promote a return to religious values. It
is sponsored by the Washington, D.C.-based Outdoor Advertising
Association of America, which represents 900 companies specializing
in billboard and outdoor advertising.
</P>
<P>
   The so-called God Speaks campaign, which began as a one-time
effort in Florida last year, is expected to reach 281 markets in 40
states on 10,000 billboards and other outdoor advertising venues,
says Sheila Hayes, a spokeswoman for the trade group.
</P>
<P>
   It all began last summer when an individual walked into the
offices of the Smith Agency advertising agency in Ft. Lauderdale,
wrote out a check for $150,000 and asked the firm to devise a
non-denominational ad campaign promoting a return to God. The ad
agency is honoring the client's request to remain anonymous.
</P>
<P>
   Charlie Robb, an agency vice president, ended up writing most of
the one-liners.
</P>
<P>
   By last September, messages from ``God'' began appearing on bus
posters and billboards around Ft. Lauderdale. They included, ``What
part of `Thou shalt not' didn't you understand?'' and ``Let's meet
at my house Sunday before the game.''
</P>
<P>
   Robb says his favorite is, ``Don't make me come down there.''
</P>
<P>
   The signs were an instant hit among many different religions.
For example, the Catholic Archdiocese of Miami praised them, while
a Florida rabbi asked the agency for permission to reprint them for
his flock.
</P>
<P>
   Not all responses, however, were positive. The atheists, for
example, were unhappy. They gripe that the ads ``are promoting what
they consider a mythical being,'' Robb says. ``And once in a while,
we get a call from someone who considers the signs blasphemy,'' he
adds.
</P>
<P>
   Following the generally positive reception in Florida, the
advertising trade group in January asked its members if they would
take the campaign national as a public service.
</P>
<P>
   ``The response was phenomenal,'' Hayes says, with members
pledging $15 million in advertising space and materials.
</P>
<P>
   The national effort began in Dallas in March and has steadily
expanded to other markets.
</P>
<P>
   Some cities where the signs have already appeared or are
scheduled to appear include Baltimore, Boston, Chicago, Houston,
Los Angeles, New York, San Diego and Washington, D.C.
</P>
<P>
   The messages appear on any of three types of outdoor advertising
media: large billboards (14 feet by 48 feet); medium-sized
billboards (12 feet by 25 feet); and posters (six feet by 12 feet).
</P>
<P>
   Hayes says that the popularity of the campaign is comparable
only to two others _ Smokey the Bear and the Vince and Larry
seat-belt dummies.
</P>
<P>
   Adds Robb, ``I've worked on a lot of ad campaigns in 20 years,
and in my experience for something to take off like this, it's
really unusual.''
</P>
<P>
   Hayes believes that the signs strike a special chord following
the shock and tragedy after several deadly schoolyard shootings,
such as the gun rampage at Columbine High School in Littleton,
Colo.
</P>
<P>
   ``Littleton was a reminder of the violence going on in the world
and why it's the right time for messages like this,'' she says.
</P>
<P>
   People find the signs refreshing, Robb says, after being
inundated for a year with news stories of President Clinton's
sexual escapades with a White House intern and his attempts to
conceal the affair.
</P>
<P>
   ``People are thinking a lot about morality after Clinton,'' he
says. ``These are friendly messages.''
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Eric Rosenberg can be reached at 202-298-6920 and at the email
address eric(at)hearstdc.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
