<HEADLINE>
OF A MASTER FIEND AND A GUY UNDERCOVER IN A BROTHEL 
</HEADLINE>
  (af) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   `WILD WILD WEST'
</P>
<P>
   Will Smith, Kevin Kline, Kenneth Branagh, Salma Hayek, Ted
Levine
</P>
<P>
   Directed by Barry Sonnenfeld
</P>
<P>
   PG 107 minutes &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Sporting with a woman in a water tank, the United States marshal
James T. West (Smith) peers through a knothole and spies a bunch of
boys associated with the former Civil War general Bloodbath McGrath
(Levine).
</P>
<P>
   After the tank tips over, West spills into the town brothel,
where he encounters McGrath (the one with the ear trumpet implanted
in his head), and another marshal dressed in drag, Artemus Gordon
(Kline), who is working undercover as a lady of the house and
ducking assignments by pleading tonsilitis.
</P>
<P>
   Gordon, really a polished gadgeteer who rolls around in his
lavish railroad car playing with gizmos and knitting bullet-proof
vests, and West are assigned by President Ulysses S. Grant to
apprehend Bloodbath's boss, a master fiend who has been kidnapping
the country's scientists. They have a week.
</P>
<P>
   Grant then hikes himself off to Promontory Point, Utah, where he
is to open the transcontinental railroad. But the journey plays
into the hands of the embittered and brilliant Dr. Arliss Loveless
(Branagh), a dandified mechanical genius of Southern extraction.
</P>
<P>
   Or half a genius. Having lost his body from the waist down,
Loveless propels himself about in a steam-powered wheelchair
devising mad schemes of revenge. As it evolves, he has also made
off with the scientists, who have been employed to build a gigantic
mechanical spider with which to abscond with the president and put
the Loveless stamp on the nation's destiny.
</P>
<P>
   Violence: People are shot point-blank and Loveless tests a
weapon by luring a band of McGrath's men into a designated space
and slaughtering them. Battles claim many victims, unmistakably if
not gorily.
</P>
<P>
   Sex: Many situations and references, from the bordello onward,
and double-entendres fly.
</P>
<P>
   Profanity: Now and then the air turns bluish.
</P>
<P>
   FOR WHICH CHILDREN?
</P>
<P>
   Ages 3-6: Too big and loud, too profane, too violent. Leave the
littlest ones at home.
</P>
<P>
   Ages 7-9: One could reasonably wonder why the PG rating wasn't
stepped up to a PG-13 in this instance. In any event, PG stands for
parental guidance, which will fall where it may. Much in this film
isn't for young children, though no great harm would be done.
</P>
<P>
   Ages 10-12: By this age group, the coast is clear, or relatively
so, depending on individual standards. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   `MUPPETS FROM SPACE'
</P>
<P>
   Gonzo, Kermit the Frog, Miss Piggy, Rizzo the Rat, Fozzie Bear
and the rest of the Muppets, with cameo appearances by Andie
MacDowell, F. Murray Abraham, David Arquette, Ray Liotta, others.
</P>
<P>
   Directed by Tim Hill
</P>
<P>
   G 82 minutes
</P>
<P>
   A cross between a turkey and a chicken, Gonzo gets shut out of
Noah's ark when he can't come up with a similar being to embark
with two-by-two (Noah does toss him an umbrella). That only
increases his frustrations over his identity and roots, which seem
to extend to another planet. Then at breakfast in the Muppet
boarding house, the alphabet cereal suddenly spells a message:
watch the sky.
</P>
<P>
   At a space center disguised as a cement factory, aliens are
spotted headed this way. Grabbing a chance to be a media star, the
never-retiring Miss Piggy fills in for Shelly Snipes (Ms.
MacDowell) as anchor of the ``UFOmania Show.''
</P>
<P>
   Gonzo and friends infiltrate the installation, where Rizzo gets
caught and locked up in the basement with other rats, who are
testing caffeine substitutes.
</P>
<P>
   Gonzo is scheduled to have his brain removed by a Dr. Van
Neuter. The aliens are to land at Cape Doom at midnight but are so
late all the space freaks go home. Finally they appear for a
``Close Encounters of the Third Kind'' landing. On board are many
Gonzos. Now this Gonzo has to decide whether to go off with them or
stay with the Muppets. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Violence: None.
</P>
<P>
   Sex: None (though sex, or the suggestion of it, is always an
arrow in Miss Piggy's quiver).
</P>
<P>
   Profanity: None.
</P>
<P>
   FOR WHICH CHILDREN?
</P>
<P>
   Ages 3-5: They love the Muppets, of course, but the film is
talky and they could get squirmy. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Ages 6-8: This is a sweet little movie, if slow in places. All
told, they should enjoy it. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   `AMERICAN PIE`
</P>
<P>
   Jason Biggs, Chris Klein, Thomas Ian Nicholas, Eddie Kaye
Thomas, Alyson Hannigan, Natasha Lyonne, Tara Reid, Mena Suvari,
Shannon Elizabeth, Jennifer Coolidge
</P>
<P>
   Directed by Paul Weitz
</P>
<P>
   R 100 minutes
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not a space shuttle launch; it's sex,'' says a student to
a friend at East Great Falls High School. Maybe so but sex is a
last frontier to four male seniors who pledge to lose their
virginity by the time diplomas are handed out.
</P>
<P>
   Kevin (Nicholas) is practically already in bed with his
girlfriend (Ms. Reid), but the three others have hurdles ahead. Jim
(Biggs) is prey to all the social and physical embarrassments of
late adolescence, as are most of his schoolmates, and why shouldn't
they be? (Given their toilet habits, some of them belong in
diapers.)
</P>
<P>
   Finch (Thomas) feels it necessary to pay the sexually active
Jessica (Ms. Lyonne) $200 to spread word of his prowess (as yet
untested). Oz (Klein), a lacrosse star, thinks seduction means
driving a girl to a deserted spot and naming his pleasure.
</P>
<P>
   In other words, these are children _ all with a peculiarly '50s
outlook for the late '90s _ slouching none too confidently toward a
rite of passage. Condoms are procured; Web sites are baited with
come-ons (no takers).
</P>
<P>
   Jim lures a great-looking exchange student (Ms. Elizabeth) into
his bedroom and then botches it. Oz studies flower arranging and
takes up singing to attract Heather (Ms. Suvari).
</P>
<P>
   Of girls, ``Ask them questions and listen to what they have to
say,'' Kevin advises.
</P>
<P>
   Success is achieved, sometimes in unexpected ways. Thinking he's
landed a geekish flute player (Ms. Hannigan), Jim finds himself
with a wild dominatrix. Shunned by his peers, Finch scores with a
latter-day Mrs. Robinson (Ms. Coolidge). On to college. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Violence: None.
</P>
<P>
   Sex: Since this is a film about sex, there is a representative
sampling, including standard intercourse, masturbation and oral
sex. The many allusions spread to related body parts and functions,
and incidental sexual references take in pornography and other
topics.
</P>
<P>
   Profanity: Much obscenity and a flood of bathroom activity and
talk.
</P>
<P>
   FOR WHICH CHILDREN?
</P>
<P>
   Ages 15-17: Not to belabor individual parental standards, but
another R-rated movie about students who are around the age of 17
will attract many viewers who are younger. Going by the book, that
will require the presence of a parent or guardian. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
