<SLUG> BC-TV-WEEKEND-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`SMALL VICES' 
</HEADLINE>
  (EDS: Program notes are at end of review. Time, channel are for New
York area. Please check local listings.) 
(af) 
 By WALTER GOODMAN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Not only is Spenser the toughest private eye who ever broke
another tough guy's nose with the flick of a knuckle, but he's
quick with a quotation, whether from Matthew Arnold or Rhett
Butler.
</P>
<P>
   His main problem in Sunday's zesty A&AMP;E adaptation of ``Small
Vices,'' Robert B. Parker's 24th novel, is another tough guy, known
as ``the Gray Man,'' who's out to kill Spenser. Nothing personal,
unless you happen to be on the receiving end of the Gray Man's
sharpshooting.
</P>
<P>
   Joe Mantegna makes a likable and businesslike detective who is
not embarrassed about doing on his cooking in a frilly apron. And
viewers are assured that despite a dire beginning that finds him
underwater, he will manage to dry off, get back in shape and meet
the Gray Man (Eugene Lipinski) under more satisfactory
circumstances.
</P>
<P>
   Spenser has been hired to look into the case of Ellis Alves, a
black youth who has been convicted or framed for the rape and
murder of a young white woman from an affluent family. There are
intimations here of a class struggle, but don't take it too
seriously.
</P>
<P>
   Fans of the Spenser casebook will recognize his wisecracking pal
Hawk (Shiek Mahmud-Bey) and his smart-aleck girlfriend, Susan
Silverman (Marcia Gay Harden).
</P>
<P>
   There are also several inept tough guys who pop in and out so
that they can have their noses and other body parts damaged by
Spenser or, in one acrobatic episode, by involvement in a hockey
game.
</P>
<P>
   The rudimentary plot should strain no fan's attention. There are
enough cryptic encounters between bad guys and good ones to keep
the insults perking, and the dialogue is wry if a little stiff:
``You are an odd combination of violence and concern for violence.
I would not have you change.''
</P>
<P>
   And incidentally, that ex-CIA agent who turns up so handily is
played by Parker himself. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   PROGRAM NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   `SMALL VICES'
</P>
<P>
   A&AMP;E, Sunday night at 8
</P>
<P>
   Written by Robert B. Parker and directed by Robert Markowitz.
Michael Brandman, executive producer; David Coatsworth, producer;
Delia Fine, executive producer for A&AMP;E. Produced by A&AMP;E in
association with Jaffe/Braunstein Films Ltd. and Pebble Hut
Productions.
</P>
<P>
   With: Joe Mantegna (Spenser), Marcia Gay Harden (Susan
Silverman), Shiek Mahmud-Bey (Hawk), Eugene Lipinski (Gray Man) and
Robert B. Parker (Ives).
</P>
</TEXT>
