<HEADLINE>
MUSIC OFF THE INTERNET POSES ISSUES OF PIRACY AND TECHNOLOGY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By BOBBY McGILL  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Despite the accolades, media hype and
revolutionary rhetoric, digital music downloaded from the Internet
is not a ready-for-prime-time player, according to a recent study
of the online music industry.
</P>
<P>
   The study, conducted by the Internet analysis firm Jupiter
Communications, concluded that digital music distribution must
overcome major obstacles before becoming a mainstream consumer
technology.
</P>
<P>
   Lucas Graves, lead analyst on the Jupiter study, explained what
he sees as a less-than-stellar future for digital downloads.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not that it isn't as significant as people say. It's just
that it is going to take a lot longer than they say it will,'' said
Graves.
</P>
<P>
   The study, in addressing digital music's ``riveting hold on the
media and the recording industry,'' found that its problems revolve
around the established recording industry's fear of piracy, coupled
with the consumer's lack of familiarity with finding, downloading
and playing digital music.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's hardly a consumer-friendly technology,'' Graves said,
referring to the MP3 compression technology commonly used to make
audio files small enough to download. ``It's for Net-savvy people
at this point. You have to know your way around the Net. It's not
something that Joe and Jean Music Buyer are going to be doing.''
</P>
<P>
   Paul Smith, a business appraiser in San Francisco and a frequent
downloader of digital music, agreed. ``If I am looking for the
latest hit single, it's hard to find,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The report predicted that by 2003, only 3 percent of online
consumers in the United States would buy digitally downloaded
music, compared with less than 1 percent buying downloaded music
this year.
</P>
<P>
   What makes the number significant is that by the time 2003 rolls
around, most major music labels should have much of their content
available online.
</P>
<P>
   However, finding content on the Net is a problem, according to
the Jupiter study. Even if surfers do find the latest hit single
for download, chances are it is an illegal post, and thus an
illegal download, said Graves.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE -- OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   While the digital downloading of music has gained much attention
in recent months, the record industry's fear of piracy threatens
the evolution of Web sites that specialize in music distribution.
</P>
<P>
   The situation bears a striking resemblance to the decades-old
problem with cassette tapes. On the Internet, as with cassettes,
people can easily make copies of music and distribute them for free
or for profit without the artists or the labels receiving a dime.
Neither are too crazy about that idea.
</P>
<P>
   Realizing the potential to make _ or lose _ money, major labels
have been working to embrace and control the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, a 110-member coalition made up of the major U.S.
record labels and their counterparts in the technology industry
agreed on a preliminary set of security guidelines. The Secure
Digital Music Initiative (SDMI) essentially seeks to imprint a
digital watermark on digitally distributed music. This code is an
attempt to prevent copying.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
