<SLUG> BC-BBA-TORRE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ALL-STAR FEVER HAS RECUPERATIVE EFFECT ON TORRE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By TIM REYNOLDS  
 c.1999 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Days after he was diagnosed with prostate cancer in
March, Joe Torre was asked if he thought he would be healthy in
time to manage the All-Star Game.
</P>
<P>
   At the time, the question seemed trivial. Soon, though, the
chance to be part of a historic night helped fuel Torre's
aggressive recuperation.
</P>
<P>
   ``To be a participant is most important,'' Torre said. ``In
March, I have to say, this was the last thing on my mind. But once
I was feeling better I was looking forward to it. It's going to
mean a lot to me to have been on the field for the last All-Star
Game of the century.''
</P>
<P>
   Torre managed the American League All-Star team for the second
time in three years Tuesday night, guiding the club to a 4-1 win in
the 70th edition of the contest.
</P>
<P>
   The honor of guiding the All-Star team goes to the manager of
each league's reigning champion. Torre, the 24th man to both manage
and play in the midsummer classic, became the sixth manager to win
his first two All-Star attempts.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't know a few months ago where I was going to be at this
point and time,'' Torre said. ``But once I started feeling well, I
looked forward to this with great anticipation.''
</P>
<P>
   For all his managerial success over the past three-plus seasons
_ two World Series championships, a record-setting 125 total wins
last year, twice being named American League Manager of the Year by
the Baseball Writers Association of America _ it's difficult to
imagine Torre was a man without a job as recently as 1995.
</P>
<P>
   But Torre remembers those days, and that's why he relishes every
chance he has to bask in baseball's spotlight. It was a long time
coming.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a great honor,'' Torre said. ``These are the best players
in the world on both sides of the field. To be able to say that and
to know that I'm writing the lineup down and making the changes ...
you know, if you tell me in 1995 when I was fired as manager of the
Cardinals that a couple of short years later I'd have this kind of
power and this kind of memory, I'd find it hard to believe.''
</P>
<P>
   Torre played in nine All-Star Games, was the National League
Most Valuable Player in 1971 and won the NL Gold Glove as a catcher
in 1965.
</P>
<P>
   He played or managed in 4,268 games before getting to the World
Series in 1996, when he led the Yankees over Atlanta. Torre has
been larger than life in New York City ever since, but he takes
everything in stride.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a nice memory for me to take back,'' Torre said. ``I
think the best part about these few days that you have off is you
don't have to mess with the scrambled eggs in your head, thinking
how we're going to win. You see the names of the players on my
lineup card, you can't make a mistake.''
</P>
<P>
   Fenway has been filled with those nice memories for Torre this
season. He rejoined the Yankees there on May 18, having missed the
first 36 games of the season while recovering from the prostate
surgery.
</P>
<P>
   Torre was prodded by Yankees bench coach Don Zimmer to take the
lineup card to home plate that day. The result was a standing
ovation from a near-capacity crowd at Fenway, all applauding a man
who was wearing the colors of the hated Yankees.
</P>
<P>
   ``I managed my first game back from my recuperation here and had
such a wonderful, warm reception, there was no question I was
looking forward to coming back here _ when they were going to pull
for our ballclub,'' Torre said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was looking forward to this. I had no question I would be
able to do this, unless for some reason I was totally exhausted, or
if my stamina wasn't back. Boston and Fenway Park, you love coming
in here. ... It couldn't have been better in my mind.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
