<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BEACHES-0716-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;    DESPITE IMPROVED MONITORING, AMERICA'S BEACHES REMAIN
THREATENED, REPORT SAYS
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    By RAVEN HILL
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Sun, sand and. . .pollution?
</P>
<P>
   That's the picture at many of America's beaches, according to a
study released Thursday by an environmental action group.
</P>
<P>
   Though more states and localities are adopting monitoring and
public notification programs to warn visitors about polluted
beaches, there are still record numbers of swimming advisories and
closings, said the Natural Resources Defense Council in ``Testing
the Waters,'' its ninth annual vacation beach quality guide.
</P>
<P>
   The group found there were 7,253 closings or advisories
nationwide last year, a 75 percent increase over 1997.
</P>
<P>
   The jump was due partly to storms that hit Southern California
in 1998 caused by the weather phenomenon known as El Nino, the
group said. Advisories and beach closings in California jumped to
3,273 in 1998 from 1,141 in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   However, the group noted, the nationwide rise in closings and
advisories also is partially due to the increased beach monitoring
by state and local authorities.
</P>
<P>
   ``Although we're pleased to be getting more information, the
number of advisories and closings indicate that too little is being
done to prevent pollution _ especially from sources such as storm
water and sewage,'' said Sarah Chasis, and NRDC senior attorney who
was project director for the beach report.
</P>
<P>
   The NRDC advocates effective monitoring and public notification
programs as the first step in eliminating beach water pollution.
</P>
<P>
   Four states _ Alabama, Louisiana, Oregon and Washington _ were
labeled ``beach bums'' this year for lacking regular monitoring or
notification programs. The NRDC said only nine states _
Connecticut, Delaware, Illinois Indiana, New Hampshire, New Jersey,
North Caroline, Ohio and Pennsylvania _ ``comprehensively monitor
most or all of their beaches and notify the public when health
hazards exist.''
</P>
<P>
   The group added that beach quality could be improved through
stronger action by the U.S. Environmental Protection Agency and
state governments.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need to make people aware that when there is no monitoring,
we don't know whether the waters are polluted or not,'' Chasis
said. ``Our feeling is that people should be able to go to the
beach and not worry.''
</P>
<P>
   Mississippi, Puerto Rico and Texas do not have public
notification procedures.
</P>
<P>
   In the past, the NRDC report has been criticized for not
recognizing distinctions among states with beaches. State officials
in Washington, for instance, have pointed out that their beaches
are used far less for swimming and surfing than beaches in states
like Florida, New Jersey and California.
</P>
<P>
   (The Associated Press contributed to this report).
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
