<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990715.0258 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-15 17:15 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1603 &Cx1f; tad-z
u p &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-INTERNET-POLITICS16-C     07-15 0643
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INTERNET-POLITICS16-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    FEC ASKED TO ADD FUND-RAISING SIZZLE TO CAMPAIGN WEB SITES
 &HT;    Moving in (w) Washington and (f) financial categories.
 &HT;    By ANDREW J. GLASS
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The Federal Election Commission is under bipartisan
pressure to make it easier to raise money on the Internet for the
2000 presidential campaign.
</P>
<P>
   While candidates have found fund raising on the Internet to be a
highly efficient undertaking, the flow still remains a trickle
compared to the steady stream of contributions pouring in through
more traditional methods.
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday, for example, the Democratic presidential campaign
of former Sen. Bill Bradley of New Jersey announced it had raised
$240,000 in the year's second quarter through its Web site. This
amounted to only 2 percent of its overall contributions, and other
campaigns have reported similar meager results.
</P>
<P>
   A visit to cyberspace reveals that both presidential
front-runners, Vice President Al Gore and Gov. George W. Bush of
Texas, are hazy about the federal rules that govern fund raising on
their Web sites.
</P>
<P>
   To complete Gore's online contribution form, donors must include
their occupation and employer's name. But federal regulations
require such data only for political contributions of $200 or more.
</P>
<P>
   Bush requires the same information on his site. In addition,
donors are erroneously told that credit card contributions aren't
eligible for federal matching funds.
</P>
<P>
   Last month, the commission voted unanimously to allow Internet
credit card contributions to presidential primary candidates to
qualify for matching funds. ``We recognize the reality that the
Internet is here and a big part of our life,'' FEC Chairman Scott
Thomas said after the 6-0 vote. ``We need to let it be used
freely.''
</P>
<P>
   Both parties are taking the FEC at its word.
</P>
<P>
   Law partners Joseph Sandler and Neil Reiff, former officials of
the Democratic National Committee, said in a joint article in the
July issue of Campaigns &AMP; Elections magazine that Congress should
amend the campaign finance laws so that candidates can ``facilitate
use of the Internet for grassroots political communication.''
</P>
<P>
   Similarly, Bush's campaign is seeking an FEC advisory opinion
that could make life easier for candidates in the fast Internet
lane.
</P>
<P>
   The FEC's June ruling allows campaigns for the first time to
collect and store contributor data solely in electronic form. To
take advantage of this change, however, candidates must ask a
series of screening questions online.
</P>
<P>
   The Gore campaign site, for example, asks donors to attest,
among other statements, that:
</P>
<P>
   _ ``The funds I am contributing are my own personal funds and
not those of another.''
</P>
<P>
   _ ``I am not a foreign national who lacks permanent resident
status in the United States.''
</P>
<P>
   The wrong answer (or no answer) to any item instantly blocks the
transaction from going through. By contrast, campaigns that solicit
through traditional means enjoy a 30-day grace period in which they
can keep the money while seeking to resolve any potential legal
problems.
</P>
<P>
   The Bush campaign says the commission's rulings ``do not in all
cases take into account the new ways a campaign may now utilize
this virtually cost-free means of mass communications.''
</P>
<P>
   In his request for a more relaxed approach, Benjamin Ginsberg,
the campaign's national counsel, has asked the commission to review
a series of ``cutting-edge issues, all of which are designed to use
the Internet and other emerging technologies to increase
participation and interest in campaigns at a time when citizen
involvement seems to be diminishing rather than increasing.''
</P>
<P>
   The commission has until Aug. 7 to respond to Bush's request.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
