<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-15 17:18 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1611 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ANTIQUES-COLUMN-NYT &LR;      07-15 1175
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ANTIQUES-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE RUINS OF EMPIRES CAST A SPELL 
</HEADLINE>
  (af) 
 By WENDY MOONAN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Vestiges of the ancients are cropping up all over.
</P>
<P>
   Sotheby's sale of antiquities in New York on June 5 added up to
a whopping $6.4 million, with 85 percent of the lots sold. The
buyers were responding to the quality of the works and the
impeccable provenances.
</P>
<P>
   A Hellenistic bronze sculpture of Alexander the Great of the
third century B.C., from the collection of the late Ian Woodner,
sold for $244,500, more than twice the high estimate.
</P>
<P>
   A pair of Roman Imperial bronze hunting hounds, circa the first
century, from the estate of Mrs. John Hay Whitney went for an
amazing amount, $211,500; their estimate was $80,000 to $120,000.
And Mrs. Whitney's bronze Greek statue of a horse from the
Geometric period (eighth century B.C.) sold for $189,500, compared
with an estimate of $40,000 to $60,000.
</P>
<P>
   The results were almost as good at Christie's, whose antiquities
sales on June 3 and 4 netted a respectable $3.7 million, although
only 66 percent of the lots sold.
</P>
<P>
   Even beyond the salesrooms, interest in ancient art is
increasing.
</P>
<P>
   Elyse Topalian, a spokeswoman for the Metropolitan Museum of
Art, said 10,000 to 15,000 people a day visited the new ancient
Greek galleries in the first two weeks after they opened on April
20.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, in Rome, preparations for the Holy Year of 2000
include a thorough renovation of the Capitoline Museum, which first
opened in 1471 and boasts one of the great collections of
antiquities in the world. Unlike the Met, the Louvre or the British
Museum, the ancient sculptures in the Capitoline Museum are not
from Greece, Iran or Turkey; they were all discovered in Rome.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Greek originals and Egyptian works conserved in the
museum, all excavated in the city area, confirm Rome's commercial,
political and cultural contacts with the major centers of the
Mediterranean,'' wrote Anna Mura Sommella in ``Masterpieces of the
Capitoline Museum.''
</P>
<P>
   While the Capitoline is closed, its ancient sculptures are in an
unlikely temporary setting: the Centrale Montemartini, a
decommissioned 1912 power plant on the edge of the city. The
building, which looks like a Magritte painting come to life, has
been transformed into a stunning exhibition hall by the Roman
architect Francesco Stefanori.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike the Tate at Bankside in London, another power plant being
turned into a museum, the Centrale retains its immense black
turbines and massive carcasses of cast-iron machinery. They now
form the striking backdrop for ancient white marble sculptures of
the Capitoline Venus, the Omphalos Apollo and a row of busts of
famous and infamous ancients like Homer, Socrates, Trajan and Nero.
</P>
<P>
   Stefanori's installation is as spare and modern as any to be
seen in SoHo and is twice as effective as that of the Musee d'Orsay
in Paris, a former train station that has lost most vestiges of its
former life. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   --- &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   On July 1, ``Visions of Ruin: An Exhibition of Architectural
Fantasies and Designs for Garden Follies'' opened at Sir John
Soane's Museum in London.
</P>
<P>
   Soane, who lived from 1753 to 1837, was appointed architect for
the Bank of England in 1788. Ten years earlier, like other educated
young Englishmen of the time, he went to Rome to study and draw
ancient sites and buildings. But unlike his friends in the gentry,
Soane went there on a traveling scholarship awarded by King George
III.
</P>
<P>
   When Soane returned to London, he amassed a remarkable private
collection of some 3,000 objects, including Greek, Roman and
Egyptian antiquities, plaster casts, antique vases, marble
fragments and a large cast of the Apollo Belvedere that had once
belonged to Lord Burlington. (The original is in the Vatican
Museum.)
</P>
<P>
   Eventually Soane bequeathed his house and its contents to the
nation, stipulating in 1833 that the arrangements of his many
objets d'art be kept as they were at the time of his death. And
they have been.
</P>
<P>
   The museum's deputy curator, Helen Dorey, said: ``What Soane saw
in Rome made an unbelievable impression on him. Ruins were always
in his mind. He wanted viewers of his house to think about it in
conjunction with the noble ruins of Rome.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, the impact of Rome on the many 18th-century tourists
taking the grand tour is going to be part of the Philadelphia
Museum of Art's exhibition on 18th-century Rome, scheduled for
February 2000.
</P>
<P>
   In 1830 Soane commissioned the English watercolorist Joseph
Gandy to do ``A Bird's-Eye View of the Bank of England'' as it
might look as a ruin. ``He wanted his bank to be compared to
ancient Rome,'' Ms. Dorey said. ``The painting makes it look as
grand as the Baths of Caracalla.''
</P>
<P>
   But Soane's immense rotunda for the bank, which was inspired by
the Pantheon, was dismantled in 1925. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Visions of Ruin,'' which runs through Aug. 20, includes both
the Gandy painting and a sad 1925 photograph from The Times of
London showing men dismantling the rotunda, stone by stone. The
exhibition also includes Piranesi engravings of the ruins of
Hadrian's villa outside Rome; fine Robert Adam watercolors of Roman
temple fragments, and pen and ink gouaches of the Roman Forum by
Charles-Louis Clerisseau, a French artist who gave drawing lessons
to several English architects who went to Rome.
</P>
<P>
   ``There would be no England if there were no Italy,'' said
Joseph Rishel, the senior curator at the Philadelphia Museum of
Art. ``Rome was the target of all 18th-century artists and
architects.''
</P>
<P>
   Soane bought 20 paintings by Clerisseau, who also influenced
Thomas Jefferson. Next to these in the show are 18th-century
drawings for proposed garden temples for English estates, in
effect, mock ruins.
</P>
<P>
   ``Architects were very interested in presenting their designs as
ruins then,'' said Margaret Richardson, curator of the Soane
Museum. ``William Chambers, Robert Adam and John Soane were
speaking to a sophisticated audience who understood what they were
doing. People were fascinated with the idea of ruins, because ruins
implied that a great building on the site had fallen into decay.''
</P>
<P>
   Christopher Woodward, the curator of the exhibition, explained
that the English commissioned mock ruins for their country estates
as a ``souvenir of Rome.''
</P>
<P>
   ``These are elite buildings to amuse a small circle of friends
who shared a nostalgia for Rome,'' he said. He continued:
``Architects, who try to build for eternity, are brought back to
reality by the sight of ruins. They represent the transitory nature
of life. The architects had their own fears. They knew that every
building, like every person, had an end. For them, a ruin is a
nightmare come true.''
</P>
<P>
   As David Watkin explained in the exhibition catalog, ``The
Romans had a strong sense of being the heirs to ruined empires,
such as Troy and Carthage.'' And 18th-century England, which
dominated the globe, had a passion for Roman ruins. So why
shouldn't America, the world power of today?
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-15-99 1718EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990715.0261 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-15 17:19 </DATE_TIME>
