A1616 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CAR-NASCAR-STEWART-NY     07-15 0577
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAR-NASCAR-STEWART-NYTR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STEWART, THE ROOKIE, COMES CLOSE TO A WIN  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By PATRICK ZIER   Lakeland (Fla.) Ledger   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Stewart is doing everything it takes to win, but he still hasn't
won
</P>
<P>
   It did not come at the end of May in Charlotte, and it did not
come Sunday in New Hampshire, either, but it will come. Almost
anybody in Winston Cup will tell you that.
</P>
<P>
   Tony Stewart, they say, is almost certain to win a race, even
though he is a rookie and even though the majority of his
experience is in open-wheel cars.
</P>
<P>
   Sunday, leading the Jiffy Lube 300 and driving what eventual
winner Jeff Burton admitted was the best car on the track, Stewart
saw a win within his grasp disappear when his car died from lack of
fuel two laps from the finish.
</P>
<P>
   At the Coca Cola 600 at Charlotte on May 30, a physically
drained Stewart, who had earlier in the day run the Indy 500, did
not have the stamina to keep his car up front late in the race and
fell back to fourth.
</P>
<P>
   But the 28-year-old Stewart, who jumped to Winston Cup from the
Indy Racing League this season, is doing the things it takes to
win, and if you keep putting yourself in position to win,
eventually, you usually do.
</P>
<P>
   While a frustrated Stewart left the track quickly Sunday after a
10th-place finish in his Joe Gibbs Pontiac, he continues to look at
the big picture and not how he fares in individual races.
</P>
<P>
   ``This series is all about consistency,'' said Stewart. At the
New Hampshire International Speedway he recorded his 10th top 10.
</P>
<P>
   ``We obviously want to win every week, but as far as the way we
look at it for a rookie season, if we can just be consistent, then
you can worry about winning races.
</P>
<P>
   ``It means more to me to finish in the top five for three or
four weeks in a row than it does to win one week and finish 30th
the next week and crash the week after that,'' Stewart said.
</P>
<P>
   People have high expectations. Not since Jeff Gordon came along
in 1993 has a rookie created such a stir. Even if he doesn't win,
Stewart is virtually certain to top Gordon's performance his first
year.
</P>
<P>
   In 1993, Gordon had 11 top 10s. Stewart needs just two more top
10s to better that.
</P>
<P>
   You have to go back to Dale Earnhardt's first full season in
1979 to find a more impressive performance. Earnhardt won a race
and rang up 17 top 10s as a rookie.
</P>
<P>
   Stewart said he is looking forward to the second half of the
season when the circuit returns to tracks that he has already run
on this year.
</P>
<P>
   ``Then you fine-tune to the different part of the season where
the tracks are a lot warmer and conditions change a little bit,''
Stewart said.
</P>
<P>
   For his part, Stewart says he doesn't know whether he'll win
this year.
</P>
<P>
   ``If it happens, it happens and if it doesn't, it doesn't,'' he
said. ``If I knew what the future was I'd probably be doing
something other than driving race cars because I'd be making a lot
of money if I could predict the future.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm just worried about learning as much as possible and
finishing races and just trying to be consistent,'' Stewart said.
</P>
<P>
   His approach has impressed veterans like Earnhardt, who scoffs
at the idea Stewart's car must still carry the yellow stripe
signifying a rookie driver.
</P>
<P>
   While Stewart missed grabbing the checkered flag last Sunday, he
is coming closer every week.
</P>
<P>
   (The Ledger in Lakeland, Fla., is part of the New York Times
Regional Newspaper Group.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
