<SLUG> BC-CAR-NASCAR-GARAGES-NYTR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NASCAR NEEDS TO TAKE BACK THE GARAGES 
</HEADLINE>
  (See also CAR-NASCAR-STEWART) 
(DW) 
 By PATRICK ZIER   Lakeland (Fla.) Ledger   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   In NASCAR, the garage area is the equivalent of a locker room in
most sports, a restricted area where the teams get ready to race.
It should have limited access, be available only to those who have
a need to be there.
</P>
<P>
   In recent years, though, the NASCAR garage has become more and
more crowded to the point where the teams and others who work there
are finding it increasingly difficult to go about their business.
</P>
<P>
   The influx is primarily made up of fans, who somehow obtain a
pass and then put the teams and drivers under siege for autographs
and pictures.
</P>
<P>
   As a commentary in Winston Cup Scene pointed out, the fans are
not to blame for this.
</P>
<P>
   If you are a fan and you can get in the garage, you are going to
try and get all the autographs and pictures you can.
</P>
<P>
   The blame falls entirely on NASCAR, which controls the garage
and should recognize that while it is making a few fans happy, it
is causing problems for everyone else.
</P>
<P>
   It addition to being the place where the teams get ready to
race, the garage is also a primary work area for the media.
</P>
<P>
   In a perfect world, every fan would have access to the garage
and be able to get whatever information he or she wanted first
hand. Obviously, though, that's impossible, in racing or any other
sport.
</P>
<P>
   It is the media's job to represent the fans, to talk to the
participants and tell their stories so everyone can be informed.
</P>
<P>
   But this is becoming more and more difficult in NASCAR, because
the drivers are no longer accessible in the garage.
</P>
<P>
   The working areas of ``name'' drivers are now surrounded by
fans, as are their haulers.
</P>
<P>
   So the drivers have retreated to private motor homes parked
adjacent to the garage. Usually, they spend only as much time in
the garage as it takes to walk from their motor homes to the car or
the hauler.
</P>
<P>
   NASCAR drivers and participants are the most obliging athletes
in sports. They never charge for autographs, willingly pose for
pictures and in general do whatever they can to accommodate the
fans.
</P>
<P>
   But they can't satisfy everyone, in part because the sport has
grown so much it's impossible to take care of everybody.
</P>
<P>
   They need some privacy, and the media needs to be able to
converse with them without their being mobbed by well-meaning fans
to the point where they simply feel they can't stop to talk with
anybody.
</P>
<P>
   At some point, NASCAR is going to have to take back the garage
and restore order.
</P>
<P>
   Because there is no order now.
</P>
<P>
   (The Ledger in Lakeland, Fla., is part of the New York Times
Regional Newspaper Group.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
