<HEADER>
A1657 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MAINE-LANDSCAPES-3TAK     07-15 0985
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MAINE-LANDSCAPES-3TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ON MAINE'S COAST, VISTAS ARE CAST IN STONE 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By PAULA DEITZ   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Like the grandeur of the West, the mountainous coast of Maine
was viewed in the 19th century as a vast, untouched wilderness,
even though the lands had been well trodden and shaped by Indian
populations. Leading ultimately to the creation of the national
parks, this perception _ call it the American picturesque _
consisted of an appreciation of natural forms of scenery that
overwhelmed scattered travelers and government expeditions by its
ruggedness and austerity. Artists and chroniclers found these views
particularly uplifting when enhanced by the dramatic rhythms of
rough surf and spectacular sunsets.
 &UR;  &LR;  This summer, weekend visitors to Maine have the unusual prospect
of absorbing the 19th-century experience through a fine exhibition
of landscape paintings in Rockland and of then continuing up the
coast to view the same majestic land formations as preserved in
Acadia National Park on Mount Desert Island. Along the way, it is
also possible to see man-made landscapes and gardens that draw on
the traditions of Maine and enrich local community life.
</P>
<P>
   Flying into Rockland over the coastline, one observes the long
fingers of water emptying into inlets along the irregular shoreline
and the isolated villages on the extreme points of the peninsulas,
their white church steeples marking the terrain. Maine is a rural
state, and even the meadows along the airstrip are filled with
weedy wildflowers.
</P>
<P>
   This summer into early fall, a special quest for Maine scenery
begins in Rockland at the Farnsworth Art Museum, which specializes
in American art. In an exhibition titled ``Inventing Acadia:
Artists and Tourists at Mount Desert,'' the curator, Pamela
Belanger, shows how the work of pioneer landscape painters from the
1830s on attracted urban dwellers to explore these majestic regions
on their own.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, summer colonies later in the century grew to such a
proportion, threatening the idyllic views, that wealthy summer
residents took measures to preserve the landscape by establishing
the 35,000-acre Acadia National Park in 1919. It incorporates most
of the landmark mountainous silhouettes or ``sleeping giants''
recorded by the artists.
</P>
<P>
   In the catalog, Ms. Belanger and other essayists treat the works
in their social and cultural as well as esthetic context, reminding
readers that the early ``artist-explorers,'' as professor J. Gray
Sweeney of Arizona State University calls them in his essay,
provided a kind of salon entertainment in cities where the large
canvases were viewed as vicarious travel experiences.
</P>
<P>
   While the artists often manipulated scenes by adding symbolic
traces of human settlement _ deserted houses or abandoned boats _
to place the viewer within the frame, on the whole they accurately
portrayed the lone lighthouses, the islands scattered across the
bay and the steep mountains falling away to the sea under
violet-streaked skies. Then as now, a patient gaze was required to
capture the subtle and transitory atmospheric changes that altered
one's perception of the landscape.
 &UR;  &LR; Thomas Cole and, later, his student Frederic Church were leaders
among the artists who made expeditions to the island, building on
their reputations as Hudson River School painters. The exhibition
offers the opportunity to compare their paintings of the same
scene, as in Cole's 1844 ``Sandy Beach, Mount Desert Island, Me.,''
and Church's circa 1850 ``Coast at Mount Desert Island (Sand
Beach),'' both of which capture the edge between smooth sand and
jutting boulders of pink granite.
</P>
<P>
   Cole's 1845 scenes of waves crashing against rocks in
Frenchman's Bay and Church's 1850s sunset paintings, one including
an imaginary distant view of Mount Katahdin inland, are all
testaments to the extraordinary artistic response to the variety
and inspiration offered by Mount Desert Island.
</P>
<P>
   Cadillac Mountain, the highest on the island, figured
prominently among the painters' subjects, and Sanford Robinson
Gifford even places an artist sketching from a rocky perch at the
summit, looking out on the horizon. In 1896 Childe Hassam portrayed
the mountain in an Impressionistic haze from the vantage of
Frenchman's Bay.
</P>
<P>
   While most artists worked from the land, Fitz Hugh Lane painted
and sketched from ship deck, capturing the statuesque masted sails
and the effect of light on water. His 1852 ``Entrance of Somes
Sound From Southwest Harbor'' depicts the deep channel of water
that is the only fjord on the Atlantic Coast and the location in
the 1770s of the first permanent Colonial settlement on the island.
Very little had changed when Richard Estes painted ``A View of
Somes Sound'' in 1995, and that is a major point of the show: The
scenic experience of Maine has been preserved.
</P>
<P>
   This view is substantiated after a morning's visit by walking
into the museum's new gardens. In recent years, when the Farnsworth
converted the white church across the street into a center to
showcase the Maine work of the Wyeth family of artists, the
decision was also made to build an extension to the main building
and reorganize the grounds into a campus that includes the 1850
Farnsworth Homestead and carriage house.
</P>
<P>
   Now enclosed on the street sides by a white wooden fence with
tall posts and plantings of white rugosa roses, the entire property
has been given the domestic scale of a series of village gardens by
the landscape architect Clara Couric Batchelor. Separated by
winding paths, low stone walls, a semicircular hornbeam hedge and
tree plantings of gnarled crab apple and white birch, Ms. Batchelor
has planted mixed borders of home-grown plants like black-eyed
Susans, creeping phlox and Joe Pye weed. She also saved two
specimen lilacs on the grassy slope by the carriage house.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
