<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-15 17:32 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1658 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TV-PREVIEWS-HNS &LR;      07-15 1128
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-PREVIEWS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DAZETIME TELEVISION 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By TIM GOODMAN  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PASADENA, Calif. _ If you're looking for a metaphor _ and in
Hollywood that's a perpetual hunt _ you could find it in the thick,
lung-clenching smog that mixed with the heat and stupidity and
choked this town before the day even began.
</P>
<P>
   What an apt _ albeit strange _ introduction to the first day of
the Television Critic's Association summer press tour, at which a
nebulous group called Synditel (that's a conglomeration of
syndicated television shows) started the day with Richard Simmons
pouring everyone orange juice, then detoured through Louie Anderson
swearing and sweating about the new ``Family Feud'' game show he'll
host, careened around a weird ``National Enquirer'' lunch and then,
well, became increasingly more boring along the way.
</P>
<P>
   Syndicated television, if you haven't guessed, is the dregs of
the industry. Sure, there's a handful of talk shows such as
``Oprah'' and ``Rosie'' or an action show such as ``Xena: Warrior
Princess'' to guide the way to respectability, but mostly
syndication is home to shows too cheap, dumb or embarrassing to be
created by the networks, which really ought to tell you something.
</P>
<P>
   Most of what is available in the mornings and afternoons on
television is all syndicated product _ from egregiously bad
talk-show smut to silly game shows. Then, after a break for the
local news, there's a block of time known in the industry as
``early fringe,'' which is from 7 to 8 p.m., an hour reserved
almost exclusively for syndicated fare. So, you can see, these are
space-filler shows that local stations gobble up with their own
money _ not tapping the network till.
</P>
<P>
   And because local stations don't have much to spend after paying
those blow-dried TV anchors, the syndicated fare has to be
affordable. Now, affordable in Hollywood means quick and dirty, and
often disastrous, but sometimes oddly addictive, such as ``Wheel of
Fortune.''
</P>
<P>
   So when you're getting pitched the next wave of syndication,
it's not unlike being approached on a street by a man who opens a
trench coat to reveal 60 plastic watches.
</P>
<P>
   The trick, really, is to go with it. Take Simmons, for example,
a man who is without question larger than life, above derision, a
master illusionist in the costume drama of Hollywood.
</P>
<P>
   How can you make fun of Simmons when he does it himself on David
Letterman?
</P>
<P>
   Plus, and this comes as a frustration to those of us looking for
a quick beat down, Simmons is a really nice man. And he's funnier
than he gets credit for. He's here pitching a show called ``Richard
Simmons' Dream Maker,'' which is like playing T-ball for most
critics _ an easy McGwire-like bash into the upper decks of
sneering sarcasm.
</P>
<P>
   But ``Dream Maker'' is one of those sad TV shows with echoes of
``Queen for a Day'' and ``This Is Your Life'' that flirts with
cheese and sensationalism but ultimately plays out like a Hallmark
special _ and you're just a big jerk if you make fun of it. Because
Simmons is trying to help people get their wishes _ whether it's a
reunion, make-over, celebrity introduction, new car to get to a
much-needed job or life-saving surgery.
</P>
<P>
   And, considering the field, Simmons seems like one man trying to
do something positive for daytime TV _ and for people _ rather than
bloodying their noses or surprising them with the fact that their
sister is married to a goat, the way Jerry Springer and his ilk
tend to do.
</P>
<P>
   Compare that with ``Leeza,'' which is a syndicated show and is
trying to distance itself from the ugly combativeness of Springer
or the freak shows of Ricki Lake and Jenny Jones. But Leeza Gibbons
is no different, really, and possibly worse in that she masks her
exploitation behind a veneer of false caring, perfectly captured by
the cameras as some victims of Littleton, Colo., or other
headline-making event let it all out on national television while
Leeza rubs their backs understandingly.
</P>
<P>
   Clearly, the world doesn't need another talk show but it's
getting one in ``The Dr. Joy Browne Show,'' on which the popular
psychologist gives you answers to your woes. To her credit, Browne
is infinitely more tolerable than the loathsome Dr. Laura and is
self-deprecating and wise about her role: ``I'm a teacher, I'm a
psychologist, I'm a nudger _ but I don't give therapy. ... I give
people choices.''
</P>
<P>
   Fine, if you need them. But does anyone need ``The Martin Short
Show''? Isn't it enough that Roseanne and Howie Mandel tried this
talk thing, and now we need Ed Grimley chatting with Billy Crystal?
We're getting it, though Short _ cursed with the comic's need to be
perpetually ``on'' _ couldn't really encapsulate what the show will
be about or why we all wouldn't just watch Rosie O'Donnell instead.
</P>
<P>
   Then there's ``Family Feud,'' which doesn't have Richard Dawson,
unfortunately, but does have Louie Anderson, who acted as though he
never wanted the job but liked the money so he signed on.
</P>
<P>
   Anderson's TV-friendly comedy has had all the rough edges rubbed
down, but when the camera is not on him he can swear and grouse
hilariously.
</P>
<P>
   One of the most uproarious offerings at Synditel was ``Battle
Dome,'' an obvious rip-off of ``American Gladiators'' even though
the producers say it isn't. Just to make sure all bases are touched
while seeking that young male demographic, the ``warriors'' who
battle contestants look as if they came out of a WWF molding
machine.
</P>
<P>
   Although they had no videotape of the alleged sports battle, one
event _ honest to God _ has contestants holding on to a platform
that spins around at 50 mph until one falls off. If that's not
enough _ and clearly it's not these days _ the warriors will throw
medicine balls at the whirling dervishes.
</P>
<P>
   Then there's the ``National Enquirer'' show, which really needs
no introduction other than to say the nation's largest newspaper is
on a mission to brag about its journalistic credibility on one
hand, then proudly continue its tabloid ways on the other. At the
very least, maybe it'll kill ``Inside Edition.''
</P>
<P>
   And so it goes in the land of syndication. There's another
reincarnation of ``Divorce Court,'' a show called ``Blind Date''
because there aren't enough dating shows and then a strange
paleontologist's dream lineup of such shows as ``Relic Hunter''
with Tia Carrere, ``Peter Benchley's Amazon'' and ``Sir Arthur
Conan Doyle's The Lost World.''
</P>
<P>
   Maybe they'll replace syndicated television's last awful trend:
judge shows.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Tim Goodman is the television critic for the San Francisco
Examiner, P.O. Box 7260, San Francisco, CA 94120. His electronic
mail address is goodman(at)examiner.com).
</P>
