<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990715.0268 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-15 17:33 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1659 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MAINE-LANDSCAPES-2NDT     07-15 1212
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MAINE-LANDSCAPES-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 UNDATED: carriage house. 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   On an afternoon drive up the coast to Mount Desert, the visitor
can stop in nearby Rockport at Avena's Herb Gardens, where a
remarkable woman, Deb Soule, has created an apothecary garden. Here
the leaves and colorful blossoms are harvested and dried for
tinctures, teas, salves and oils: organic compounds that are known
for their wide-ranging healing effects and that are sold by
catalog.
</P>
<P>
   In a Maine tradition of female herbalists that goes back to the
Indians, Ms. Soule has planted an ornamental garden that also
benefits her rural neighbors. A split-rail fence and a row of
sunflowers barely contain massive beds of Calendula officinalis and
Echinacea purpurea planted around a thyme-covered central circle
with radiating paths, one passing beneath a cedar pergola draped in
hops vines and hardy kiwi. All of the flowers and herbs are
botanically labeled.
</P>
<P>
   Passing next through the coastal town of Camden with its
pristine summer cottages and lawns, and a village green designed by
the Olmsted firm, the visitor should pause at the bend in the road
next to the Camden Library for a view of the horseshoe amphitheater
designed about 1930 by Fletcher Steele.
</P>
<P>
   To get the full impact of this powerful plan, which takes
advantage of local mineral and plant materials, one should leave
the library through the children's area at the lower level and turn
immediately left. With tiers upon tiers of granite steps
interspersed by grass and boulder ledges, clumps of hydrangeas and
the strong vertical lines of white birch trees _ a Steele signature
_ this steep outdoor theater has been beautifully maintained for
community events like concerts, plays and graduations. The
permanent show takes place in the active harbor beyond; and at
night tall classical wrought-iron tripod light fixtures, each with
a slight variation, cast a soft glow over the landscape.
</P>
<P>
   From there the drive is a straight run to Mount Desert Island,
the 12-by-14-mile island connected to the mainland by a causeway.
When the navigator Samuel Champlain charted the coastline in 1604,
he called it l'isle des Monts-deserts (the Island of Barren
Mountains) for its multiple peaks sloping down to prominent
headlands. The name of Acadia National Park itself suggests the
earlier French presence in the area extending to Canada.
 &UR;  &LR; The sweep of the Ocean Drive, a segment of the circular park road
that begins just outside the town of Bar Harbor, offers immediate
access to the landscapes that figured prominently among the
19th-century artists.
</P>
<P>
   The sand beach of Cole and Church is the only one on the island;
and though it is vastly peopled with bathers on a good day, one can
still appreciate the curved outcropping of granite that remains the
same and the nearby chasms in the rocks that invite crashing waves.
The road passes by Otter Creek, where Church painted a lone figure
on a rocky beach, and proceeds along coves and inlets opening out
to the glittering sea before coming under cover of woodland. The
best view of Frenchman's Bay and the Porcupine Islands is from the
Shore Path, the public walkway along the coast back in Bar Harbor.
</P>
<P>
   All of the park roads lead to Mount Cadillac, which still offers
expansive views of the sea and the distant hills as well as the
island's rock formations, which derive from its complex geological
origins.
</P>
<P>
   There is nothing more hopeful of future possibilities than a
Maine sunrise seen from its peak when the first gleam of light
pours over a watery horizon and turns the world briefly into a
blush of pink. In that quiet moment under a streaked sky, time
appears to expand into timelessness and with it an understanding of
the paintings that made palpable the wonders of the Maine
landscape.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  Here is information about visiting the Mount Desert Island
and Rockland areas of Maine:
 &UR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR; Attractions
 &UR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR; FARNSWORTH ART MUSEUM, 356 Main St &UR; . &LR; , Rockland, (207)
596-6457. ``Inventing Acadia: Artists and Tourists at Mount
Desert,'' through Oct. 24. The permanent collection surveys
American art from the Colonial period to the present. In addition
to the Wyeth Center the museum also has sculpture by Louise
Nevelson, who grew up in Rockland. Hours: 9 a.m. to 5 p.m. daily
through Columbus Day; then Tuesdays through Saturdays, 10 a.m. to 5
p.m, and Sundays, 1 p.m. to 5 p.m.. Admission: $9; $8 for the
elderly; $5 for students 18 and older; free for those 17 and
younger.
 &UR;  &LR;  ABBE MUSEUM, at Sieur de Monts Spring in Acadia National Park,
P.O. Box 286, Bar Harbor, (207) 288-3519. ``Beads, Bones and
Ancient Stones: 70 Years Collecting, 10,000 Years of History,''
artifacts documenting Maine's Indian cultures from the Stone Age to
the present, through Oct. 24. Hours: 9 a.m. to 5 p.m. daily in July
and August; 10 a.m. to 4 p.m. daily from Sept. 1 through Oct. 24.
Admission: $2; 50 cents for children under 12.
 &UR;  &LR;  ETHEL H. BLUM GALLERY, College of the Atlantic, 105 Eden St &UR; . &LR; ,
Bar Harbor, (207) 288-5015. ``From Paradise to Eden: Gauguin in
Tahiti,'' watercolors, drawings and prints of Gauguin's work in
Tahiti from a private collection. Opens on Aug. 10 and runs through
Sept. 11. Hours: 9 a.m. to 5 p.m., Tuesdays through Saturdays.
Free.
</P>
<P>
   ACADIA NATIONAL PARK, Bar Harbor, (207) 288-3338. Hulls Cove
Visitor Center on Route 3 provides information and maps. Entrance
fee: $10 a car for seven days.
 &UR;  &LR;  AVENA'S HERB GARDENS, 219 Mill St &UR; . &LR; , Rockport, (207) 594-0694.
Hours: Wednesdays through Saturdays, 2 to 6 p.m.; there are
occasional Friday closings, so call ahead. Admission is free.
Directions: Take Route 90 off Route 1 in Rockport and continue
through traffic light juncture at Route 17; turn left onto Mill
Street at the end of the mill pond on the left. There is a sign for
Avena's on the right about a mile down the road.
</P>
<P>
   Where to Eat
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   SECOND READ, 528 Main St &UR; . &LR; , Rockland, (207) 594-4123. Down the
street from the Farnsworth Art Museum, this charming second-hand
bookstore-cum-restaurant serves a variety of lunchtime sandwiches,
soups and salads with a selection of coffees and teas ($2.75 to
$5.95).
 &UR;  &LR; ATLANTICA RESTAURANT, 3 Sharps Wharf, Camden, (207) 236-6011. In a
gray cedar-shingled building overlooking the pier, the restaurant
specializes in Hawaiian cuisine and seafood. Entrees, $13.95 to
$18.95.
 &UR;  &LR; GALYN'S, 17 Main St &UR; . &LR; , Bar Harbor, (207) 288-9706. In an 1880s
storefront structure with a front porch, this restaurant
specializes in local seafood and prime ribs. Entrees, $8.95 to
$30.95.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; JORDAN POND HOUSE, Acadia National Park, (207) 276-3316. This
airy indoor-outdoor restaurant in the park is surrounded by gardens
and lawns and features popovers at lunch, dinner and afternoon tea.
Entrees, $13 to $18.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; THE PORCUPINE GRILL, 123 Cottage St &UR; . &LR; , Bar Harbor, (207)
288-3884. In a turn-of-the-century commercial building, this
restaurant features quietly elegant dining. Entrees, $17 to $24.
 &UR;  &LR; THE BURNING TREE, Route 3, Otter Creek, (207) 288-9331. An old
house in a  &UR; r &LR; ural setting with three dining rooms, one a screened
porch. It serves fresh seafood from local boats and and vegetarian
entrees with organic produce from its own vegetable garden.
Entrees, $16 to $22.
</P>
