<HEADER>
A1663 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-THEATER-NOTES-ART-NYT     07-15 1037
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-THEATER-NOTES-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEWS OF THE GREAT WHITE WAY 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(jt) 
 By JAMES McKINLEY    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON _ Since April fans have been flocking from Eton, from
Essex, from Cornwall, and probably Cornball, too, all seeking a fix
from that most palindromic and hummable of Europop groups, Abba.
</P>
<P>
   The draw is ``Mamma Mia,'' the $4.5 million all-Abba musical
developed by Benny Andersson and Bjorn Ulvaeus, former members of
the group, with a book by Catherine Johnson.
</P>
<P>
   Lines for unclaimed tickets form outside the Prince Edward
Theater in the West End hours before curtain time, and the British
press has reported that scalpers get hundreds of pounds (i.e.,
hundreds of dollars) for prime tickets. ``Mamma Mia'' has sold out
its 1,650-seat theater through Sept. 11, with tickets on sale
through March 2000.
</P>
<P>
   Judy Craymer, the show's producer, said on Tuesday that a deal
was in place to bring it to the Royal Alexandra Theater in Toronto
in May. Then a tour is very likely, she said, and perhaps a trip to
Broadway. ``I don't think anybody anticipated how well we would be
received,'' she said. ``We're really just taking one step at a
time. But Broadway is obviously a dream that everyone would like to
achieve.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Mamma Mia'' is the story of a young woman, Sophie,
incorporating the music of Abba, the Swedish disco quartet, which
has sold about 350 million albums worldwide. Sophie, the only child
of a single mother, is getting married at her mother's taverna on
an unnamed Mediterranean island. Seeking her father's identity,
Sophie invites the three most likely candidates to the wedding,
unbeknownst to her mother. (Mamma mia!) There are men in scuba gear
and women in capri pants and, in the end, much rejoicing.
</P>
<P>
   The London press gave the musical mixed to positive reviews,
with many critics tying themselves in knots to explain its appeal.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are certain predilections to which one does not lightly
confess,'' wrote Alastair Macaulay in The Financial Times,
mentioning his soft spot for Shirley Temple. ``Now it is joined _
herewith vanishes my social life _ by the fact I actually enjoyed
`Mamma Mia.'''
</P>
<P>
   One element cited by several critics is the creators' ingenuity
in fitting 21 Abba songs, none written as show tunes, into the
plot. For example, ``Chiquitita,'' that epic ballad of
cross-cultural romance, becomes a rallying song for a middle-aged
woman with man problems. (Don't ask how.)
</P>
<P>
   The biggest potential problem for a New York transfer seems to
be that the group was never as big in the United States as it was
in Europe. Ms. Craymer said this was a legitimate concern but added
that she suspected that there were more fans than one might think.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think almost anyone of a certain age has `Abba Gold,''' she
said, referring to the band's greatest-hits album. ``And what we've
discovered, and I think this is true in America, is that the
younger generation thinks they've just discovered them.''
</P>
<P>
   THE REAL FLAP
</P>
<P>
   Another hot ticket here is ``The Real Thing,'' a revival of Tom
Stoppard's drama about a playwright, the insularity of passion and
an infidelity or two. (No scuba suits are involved.)
</P>
<P>
   The nine-week run at the Donmar Warehouse has been sold out
since critics trumpeted the production, particularly the
performances of Stephen Dillane and Jennifer Ehle in the play's
central roles. Broadway audiences may remember Jeremy Irons and
Glenn Close in those parts from the 1984 production.
</P>
<P>
   The strong notices have led to talk of a New York run. Anita
Waxman, who has a deal to bring work from the Donmar to Broadway,
said an early spring run in New York would ideally include the
entire British company. But Actors Equity must approve any
arrangement for foreign actors to perform on Broadway. Ms. Waxman
said that preliminary talks with the union had begun but that it
was too early to comment.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this year the union denied Cameron Mackintosh permission
to bring his production of ``Oklahoma!'' to Broadway with the
British cast. The move has been delayed indefinitely. Here, more
than 300 British actors signed a petition last month decrying what
they said was an onslaught of Yankee thespians on their stages.
</P>
<P>
   At least one actor in ``The Real Thing'' might have no problem
performing in the United States: Ms. Ehle, whose mother is the
actress Rosemary Harris, already has a green card.
</P>
<P>
   ROSE'S TURN
</P>
<P>
   One other potential springtime entry for Broadway is ``Rose,'' a
one-woman play by Martin Sherman that follows a Jewish woman from
her girlhood in a tiny village in Ukraine through her bohemian days
in prewar Warsaw to the Holocaust and on to her postwar life in
America. The play, at the Royal National Theater, stars Olympia
Dukakis, making her British stage debut.
</P>
<P>
   The show has already drawn the attention of several major
Broadway producers, including Robert Fox (``Amy's View,'' ``The
Blue Room''), Margo Lion (``Triumph of Love,'' ``Jelly's Last
Jam'') and Stuart Thompson (``Not About Nightingales''). Beyond the
sizable appeal of Ms. Dukakis and the lasting fascination with the
Jewish diaspora, another draw may be the show's compact (read
inexpensive) scale. The set is essentially a wooden bench, and
lighting effects are minimal.
</P>
<P>
   Still, as Fox said, ``even one person is not inexpensive on
Broadway.''
</P>
<P>
   `NOT TOP SECRET' &UR;  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   An opening of note on Friday night's schedule: the world
premiere of ``Home Body/Kabul,'' by Tony Kushner (``Angels in
America''). The piece, like ``Rose,'' is a woman's monologue,
involving a restless upper-class British housewife who imagines
herself in Afghanistan.
</P>
<P>
   The play, written last year, is having a low-key opening at a
90-seat theater in the Chelsea district.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not top secret,'' said the director, David Esbjornson.
``It's just a smaller piece.'' He added: ``It's funny though. We
had a lot of Americans here last night.'' Representatives of the
Manhattan Theater Club and the New York Theater Workshop are
already scheduled to see the piece this month.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
