<SLUG> BC-RODGERS-QANDA-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A CONVERSATION, OF SORTS, WITH BAD COMPANY'S PAUL RODGERS
</HEADLINE>
 
(For use by NYTimes News Service Clients) By MALCOLM MAYHEW 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   There was a time, about 20 years ago, when Bad Company was one
of the biggest rock bands in the world. To this day, Feel Like
Makin' Love is still one of the best make-out songs. Ever.
</P>
<P>
   After making a bunch of money, singer Paul Rodgers left to
pursue other projects, including The Firm with Led Zeppelin
guitarist Jimmy Page. Rest of the band continued, filling Rodgers'
spot with no-namers.
</P>
<P>
   Touting a new best-of-and-then-some collection, The `Original'
Bad Company Anthology, the group has re-formed for a 30-date tour,
which rolls into Dallas' Reunion Arrena on Saturday. All the
original members, too: Rodgers, Mick Ralphs, Simon Kirke and Boz
Burrell. And opening for them ... David Lee Roth.
</P>
<P>
   Rodgers, 49, spews (via telephone):
</P>
<P>
   Q: Why'd you rejoin the band? I thought you hated everyone.
</P>
<P>
   A: Yes I do, and we beat the (deleted) out of each other every
day. No, there have been some frustrations, but most of those were
due to staying on the road too long. For me, it was getting too
unreal, so I tried a lot of different things. We're not really
``back together.''
</P>
<P>
   Q: Oh, man, so it's not permanent?
</P>
<P>
   A: No, this is probably that belated farewell tour we should
have done years ago. We're recording a live album but this is as
far as it goes. I just finished mixing my sixth solo CD and I'm
doing a little tour with the British Rock Symphony. I've got other
things going on.
</P>
<P>
   Q: What's a Bad Company song that you're proud of that doesn't
get a whole lot of airplay?
</P>
<P>
   A: I'm proud of all of them in one way or another. Every song
you write, you think this is IT, the ultimate song. But I really
like Crazy Circles. Now which album is that on? Hmmm.... pretty sad
when you forget that kind of stuff. You'll have to check for me.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Why that song?
</P>
<P>
   A: The lyrics, ``To all the world you're living like a king. ...
but you're just a puppet on a broken string,'' create and express a
mood. That's one of the things I learned listening to blues. They
painted a picture of life that one could identify with, and I've
always tried to do that. I'm still trying.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Who goes to your concerts now?
</P>
<P>
   A: We get a great deal of fans from the old days, but we also
get young kids, too, and they're bringing their kids. It's a
beautiful thing, like the music is coming of age. I respect that,
but I also want to move forward with new songs. That's why we put
four new tracks on the anthology. We were looking for ways to make
this interesting.
</P>
<P>
   Q: You guys still trash hotel rooms and stuff?
</P>
<P>
   A: I live very clean now. I like to stay fit and go down to the
gym and work out every day. I don't think I could handle the
intensity of this without being fit. That's the buzz for me. We did
mess around, went the usual route, but I found it a little bit
pointless. It's always been about the music. It keeps me young and
alive and vibrant. Cynthia wants to have a word with you.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Uh, OK.
</P>
<P>
   A: (Rodgers' manager/girlfriend Cynthia Kereluk gets on the
phone) I just wanted to let you know that Paul works out every day
from 6 to 8 a.m.
</P>
<P>
   Q: So he doesn't get bombed anymore?
</P>
<P>
   A: I think we all know that drugs and alcohol are full of empty
promises.
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
