<HEADLINE>
WEATHER 
</HEADLINE>
  (Editors: The following text accompanies the weather map for
Friday, July 16, sent to computer graphics clients of The New York
Times News Service. For information call: 888-603-1036.) 
(rk) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   NATIONAL FORECAST &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Hot and humid air will spread from the Great Lakes and Ohio
Valley into the Northeast as winds from the west increase. Sunshine
will be plentiful throughout these regions, although some puffy
cumulus clouds will form in the afternoon especially over the
Appalachians. Afternoon temperatures will be in the low to middle
90s.
</P>
<P>
   Patchy clouds and scattered showers will persist from the
Carolinas to the southern Appalachians. There will be more sunshine
than in recent days at the coast, but sunshine will be limited near
the mountains. Thunderstorms will erupt during the afternoon in
Florida and near the central Gulf of Mexico coast as sea breezes
help to lift the sultry air.
</P>
<P>
   A broken band of thunderstorms will precede a weakening cool
front from the western Great Lakes to the central Plains. A jet
stream disturbance will promote some stronger thunderstorms as it
moves across the southern Missouri Valley. In the wake of the
front, less humid air and ample sunshine will prevail in most of
the northern Plains. A second surge of chilly air will produce
clouds and patchy rain near the Canadian border.
</P>
<P>
   The slow-moving afternoon thundershowers that have caused areas
of flash flooding from southern California to Nevada and Arizona
will shift toward southern Colorado and New Mexico. Otherwise, the
Southwest will be sunny with seasonal heat.
</P>
<P>
   Low pressure over the interior Northwest will promote low clouds
near the coast and a few potent thunderstorms over the mountains
from the Cascades to the Bitterroots. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Focus: Southeastern Simmer
</P>
<P>
   The summer has not been as steamy as usual over a large part of
the Southeast. In Birmingham, the 90-degree temperature threshold
has been reached on only 11 days. By mid-July, the Alabama capital
typically has had 23 days with temperatures of 90 degrees or
higher. A permanent weather system known as the Bermuda high has a
strong influence on summer weather in the East. This year the high
pressure zone has been stronger and farther north than usual. As a
result, the hottest air has migrated across the northern states
where heat and drought have been prevalent.
</P>
</TEXT>
