<HEADLINE>
AVERT YOUR EYES: KUBRICK'S FINAL OPUS LESS THAN A WORK OF ART
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service Clients) 
By ELVIS MITCHELL 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The trailers for Stanley Kubrick's movies are malicious teases,
working audiences into a lather like the work of no other major
director.
</P>
<P>
   Probably the only coming-attractions clip to generate more
excitement than Kubrick's adaptation of ``The Shining'' _ in which
a torrent of blood gushed out of an elevator in lewd slow motion
and slammed into the camera _ is the trailer for the director's
last movie, ``Eyes Wide Shut,'' where the biggest star in the
world, Tom Cruise, lunges into a nas-tay clench with his wife,
Nicole Kidman.
</P>
<P>
   (The trailer for ``Eyes,'' though, makes the movie look like the
kind of picture that even Showtime has the nerve to run only at 4
a.m., one of those ``erotic thrillers'' starring Shannon Tweed that
barely gets shelf space at the more reputable video stores. And
there are as many bared breasts in ``Eyes'' as you'd see in any of
those Joe Bob Briggs spectaculars.)
</P>
<P>
   But the trailers promise a wave of humidity that Kubrick has
either never been able to, or wanted to, deliver. In his best work,
he casts a cold, glittering spell over the material, be it ``2001;,
A Clockwork Orange;'' or ``Lolita.'' ``(Paths of Glory'' and
``Spartacus'' are puffed out from Kirk Douglas' enjoyably
melodramatic flexing, which gives them a spiritedness not seen
since Kubrick's early thrillers, which Kubrick essentially disowned
as juvenilia.)
</P>
<P>
   The glitter dances across ice _ which is not to say that the
chilliness doesn't have an odd zeal, or affection. In this
adaptation of Arthur Schnitzler's ``Traumnovelle,'' Kubrick uses as
his source a story that, with its streak of pettiness and
old-school vanity, has a tweedy mustiness that needs airing out _
an airing out that it doesn't get.
</P>
<P>
   Cruise is Dr. Bill Harford, and Kidman is his wife, Alice. With
his hearty straightforwardness, Cruise is interesting to watch as
another side of him comes to life after the exhaustion of nine
years of marriage. Cruise tends to work from the outside _ he's so
chipper that even his hair doesn't seem to age _ and Kubrick's
frigid eminence gives the actor a remarkable showcase. Bill's not
unhappy, but he's clearly looking for something else to stimulate
him. He circles chances for sex outside marriage with an odd
combination of wholesomeness and diligence, determined to do a lot
of comparison shopping before making a commitment.
</P>
<P>
   Even his flirting with a pair of lush models at a party has a
well-scrubbed earnestness. Cruise has learned to use his go-getter
movie-star presence well. Even his tendency to indicate what he's
about to do, so that no one misses what he's up to, works in this
context.
</P>
<P>
   Kubrick is far less successful with Kidman, who seems to be
turning into Kelly Preston, tilting her head and coquettishly
gazing at the camera. In a scene that should be ``Eyes''' first big
emotional climax _ when the couple's stoned argument turns into a
series of confessions that sends a huge fault through their
marriage _ Kidman appears to working through an acting exercise,
like she's auditioning for ``Felicity.''
</P>
<P>
   This is a crucial moment _ when we see how their ability to find
each other's soft spots turns into something abominable _ a truth
that all couples could recognize. But we're thrown out of the
moment because of Kidman's actressy gestures. All the potential she
showed early in her career is dwindling fast; who'd have thought
that Cruise would turn out to be more believable than Kidman?
</P>
<P>
   There are potent performances from other actors. Sydney Pollack,
who hovers around Bill's life as the friend who leads the life Bill
might like, is alert and savvy. He's up for anything, slug-souled
and avuncular. Alan Cummings comes through in a brief bit as a
hotel clerk who takes to the shine in Bill's eyes.
</P>
<P>
   Kubrick must have been attracted to the vein of voyeurism and
self-delusion in Schnitzler's tale of a married couple who toy with
affairs, both in the real world (he) and the dream world (she). It
opens a psychological Pandora's box that the literary set may have
found exciting and new after Freud's theories came into vogue.
Schnitzler exposes his own relationship with Sigmund Freud, since
the women in the story are smudged versions of Schnitzler's wife in
different guises.
</P>
<P>
   Kubrick and writer Frederic Raphael's updating of
``Traumnovelle'' seems to have brought it only up to the 1940s,
even though it's set in contemporary Manhattan; the movie is almost
quaint in its squareness. This squareness extends to the underuse
of the women, who are almost objectified like women in pornography;
they seem to be either homemakers or hookers. (The overreliance on
female nudity definitely hints at a double standard at the MPAA
Ratings Board.)
</P>
<P>
   The movie looks astonishing, suffused with a sepia graininess
that functions as a weird photographic pointilism that takes some
getting used to, a unique visual signature that's both fluid and
rough-hewn. But it fails to properly show the kinky undercurrents
that are supposed to pull Bill into pursuing pleasure at any cost.
</P>
<P>
   This movie is so overly worked out that there's no room for
enjoyment _ we don't sense the tension from a man who's aching to
lose control and savor a wild moment. When Cruise strolls through a
secret pleasure palace where powerful men assemble to have
anonymous sex _ everyone wears cloaks and masks that look like
costumes from a high-school staging of ``Phantom of the Opera'' _
it looks like he's wandered into one of those badly dubbed
soft-core pictures that turn up on pay-per-view. Except that
``Eyes'' lacks the seedy lustiness of those films. It's a rarefied
soft-core porn picture, the worst of both worlds.
</P>
<P>
   What's incredible is that Cruise and Kidman sacrificed more than
a year and a half of their careers _ his longtime absence from the
market may account for the recession the movie industry has
proclaimed _ to surrender themselves to Kubrick's vision. (A more
successful version of this movie is Nicolas Roeg's ``Don't Look
Now,'' an erotic thriller that dramatizes the loving warmth of a
married couple _ it still sends a chill.)
</P>
<P>
   Although the movie can be faulted for its shortage of emotional
voluptuousness, ``Eyes'' shows some daring. Rather, it shows an
interest in being daring. It tries to get at the fissures in a
relationship that are just waiting to split. It strains to bring
some of the lurid, ground-breaking sexiness of movies from the
period when ``Last Tango in Paris,'' ``Midnight Cowboy'' and
Kubrick's own ``Clockwork Orange'' were released. But Kubrick and
Raphael couldn't be more out of touch. In his last picture, Kubrick
will have to get by with a shallow mastery of craft.
</P>
<P>
   ``Eyes Wide Shut'' is rated R for adult content, nudity,
profanity and drug use.
</P>
<P>
   Eyes Wide Shut _ 2 starts (on a scale of 5) Director: Stanley
Kubrick Stars: Tom Cruise, Nicole Kidman Length: 155 min. Rated: R
</P>
<P>
   (Elvis Mitchell is film critic for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram.
Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com) .MDBU/ nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-15-99 1739EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
