r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-STEAMY-MOVIES-TEX     07-15 0367
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STEAMY-MOVIES-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VIEW TO A THRILL: THE STEAMIEST MOVIES
</HEADLINE>
 (Accompanies BC-EYESWIDESHUT-ATTITUDE) 
(For use by NYTimes News Service Clients) 
By ROBERT PHILPOT 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Trying to make a list of the hottest movies ever made is just
asking for trouble, because sexual heat is in the eye of the
beholder. Here are some movies provocative enough to keep your eyes
wide open:
--The Blue Angel: Although this was released in 1930, it still
holds up as a portrayal of sexual obsession, with Marlene Dietrich
as a sultry singer who leads to Professor Emil Jannings' downfall.
--Gilda: Rita Hayworth is at her sexiest in this 1946 film, as a
woman who comes between casino owner George McCready and his
second-in-command, Glenn Ford. Hayworth makes merely taking off a
glove unbelievably hot. Michelle Pfeiffer could never have done her
Fabulous Baker Boys bit without this. --To Have and Have Not: Not
only does Lauren Bacall ask Humphrey Bogart if he knows how to
whistle in this 1946 entry, she also says _ after they kiss a
second time _ ``It's even better when you help.'' This may be the
sexiest performance in screen history. --From Here to Eternity:
This 1953 movie, with its torrid Burt Lancaster-Deborah Kerr
affair, inspired the editors of Videohound's Golden Movie Retriever
to write, ``Still has the best waves-on-the-beach love scene in
filmdom.'' --Body Heat: A throwback to 1940s noir, but with a 1980s
attitude, as Kathleen Turner brings dopey lawyer William Hurt to a
fever pitch. Line: ``You're not too smart. I like that in a man.''
--The Unbearable Lightness of Being: In which Lena Olin
demonstrates that all you need to be sexy is a good hat _ although
it helps to be Lena Olin. --Mississippi Masala: Masala is a
collection of hot and colorful spices, and spicy is the word for
the relationship between Sarita Choudhury and Denzel Washington in
this 1992 movie about a mixed-race affair. --Desperado: Yeah, so
maybe this 1995 movie is more violent than sexy, but it features a
love scene with Antonio Banderas and Salma Hayek. You can't get
much hotter than that.
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
