<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-15 17:39 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1673 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MEANS-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      07-15 0890
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEANS-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE LIBRARY DILEMMA 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARIANNE MEANS  
 c.1999 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ When GOP presidential hopeful Elizabeth Dole
visited Washington state recently, she held a news conference at a
Seattle-area library to demand that federal funding be withheld
from public libraries that lack anti-pornography filters for their
computers.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's about our values,'' she intoned gravely. She was making a
pitch for mechanically protecting children against sex and violence
on the Internet in an apparent effort to appeal to the female
voters she is trying to attract.
</P>
<P>
   Just one small problem. Librarians were appalled. Dole was doing
politics; they do reading. She didn't know the difference between
the cultural ideal of squeaky clean cyberspace and technical
reality.
</P>
<P>
   No matter what Bill Gates says, the software systems designed to
block naughty stuff are not up to assuming the broad responsibility
of substituting for human judgment. Although several kinds of
filters are on the market, ``all filtering software stinks,''
according to the impressive young computer genius in my family.
</P>
<P>
   This, of course, did not matter to the irresponsible House when
it recently passed a measure that would do just what Dole favors,
forcing libraries to rely on ineptly programmed, non-thinking
machines to screen out obscene material.
</P>
<P>
   The Senate Commerce Committee has approved a similar bill
sponsored by its chairman, Sen. John McCain, R-Ariz., who is smart
enough to know better but is caught up in GOP presidential
politics. The Senate bill gives more flexibility to local libraries
than the House version does, although it is still symbolic
nonsense.
</P>
<P>
   But, by golly, the politicians went on record against smut _ and
isn't that wonderful! It took no bravery; if there are thundering
herds of voters clamoring to corrupt our innocent kids with dirty
thoughts, nobody has found them.
</P>
<P>
   Yet rooting out universally despised pornography in a land that
reveres freedom of expression has never been simple. Conceding an
inability to form a coherent test for obscenity, Supreme Court
Justice Potter Stewart opined sourly in 1964 that he couldn't
define it ``but I know it when I see it.''
</P>
<P>
   A filtering system can't define it either, which can result in
the blocking of legitimate literature.
</P>
<P>
   At its clumsiest, the system represents unconstitutional
censorship. It makes librarians tear their hair. At its most
incompetent, it allows so many easy evasions that the filters are
useless against determined viewers of any age.
</P>
<P>
   Some systems cancel out words merely thought too suggestive,
such as ``breast,'' which eliminates medical discussions of breast
cancer and recipes for chicken breast. In an attempt to block
pictorial nudity, some systems filter out images that simply show
too much flesh, which would include bathing scenes and Brandi
Chastain's exuberant shirt-removal at the winning climax of the
Women's World Cup Soccer championship.
</P>
<P>
   The competing filter manufacturers guard as a trade secret the
way they determine what's OK so that libraries have no basis upon
which to examine their decisions. The names of prohibited sites are
hidden from the librarians _ the on-scene guardians of those
youngsters the prohibitions are supposed to protect.
</P>
<P>
   The American Library Association is officially opposed to a
federal mandate compelling public libraries and schools to use
filtering software. The organization does not oppose the idea that
parents might use filters in their home computers, viewing that as
a matter for individual parental discretion.
</P>
<P>
   And it favors leaving the issue to local community standards,
allowing libraries to make their own decisions about filtering. It
also favors privacy screens which allow adults to watch marginal
material without being visible to others who may pass by.
</P>
<P>
   What really upsets the librarians is having mechanical
one-size-fits-all censorship imposed by Washington.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's frustrating that Congress thinks it can come in and do a
better job than we librarians do every day,'' one insulted veteran
told me.
</P>
<P>
   Oddly, we once thought conservatives were for local rather than
federal controls, particularly when it came to schoolchildren. But
somehow we must have gotten that wrong.
</P>
<P>
   Librarians are in the business of expanding access to books, not
limiting their content. The right to read is their mantra, and a
glorious one it is. They think illiteracy is a greater threat to
the republic than a few dirty cyberspace words or photos whose
access can be denied a child on the spot by an alert librarian.
</P>
<P>
   But the political anti-smut patrol is in high dungeon, flaunting
moral superiority and arousing purists to do war against civil
libertarians and other corrupt folk who kind of like the idea of
free speech. The library association has taken some lumps as
sounding too permissive and insufficiently on patrol against sinful
contamination of innocent young minds.
</P>
<P>
   Oh, dear. Once again Congress is setting up work for the Supreme
Court to do in defense of the First Amendment. The librarians may
be no match for congressional momentum but thankfully the high
bench is.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; --- &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Marianne Means may be reached by e-mail at
means(at)hearstdc.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
