A1677 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-EYESWIDESHUT-ATTITUDE     07-15 0682
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EYESWIDESHUT-ATTITUDE-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN `EYES,' NICOLE KIDMAN PROVES THAT THERE'S MORE TO SENSUALITY
THAN SKIN
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service Clients) 
By ROBERT PHILPOT 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   In the past few weeks, Nicole Kidman has appeared nude on so
many magazine covers _ sometimes with also-nude husband Tom Cruise
_ that the couple appear to have renounced their fame and given
their clothing to charity. This isn't the case, of course; it's
merely naked hype for the new ``Eyes Wide Shut,'' in which Kidman
displays her full backside during the very first shot.
</P>
<P>
   But don't let Kidman's body-baring fool you. Although ``Eyes''
is filled with so much nudity and sexual content that it should've
been rated NC-17, it isn't a very sexy movie _ nor is it intended
to be. If anything, this film _ the last directed by the late
Stanley Kubrick _ plays on any pangs of sexual guilt you might
have, with Cruise's character taking a dark journey through an
ever-weirder erotic Wonderland.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, despite all the nudity, the hottest moment in the movie
comes when Kidman is fully clothed, doing homework with her
onscreen daughter. She's in the classic movie-librarian get-up _
hair up, glasses on _ and she's giving the camera such a seductive
look it's a wonder that the cinematographer was able to
concentrate. Mona Lisa smile on her face, chin on her playful right
hand, Kidman looks like she's giving someone that
head-to-heel-and-back-again lust scan, and she makes you feel like
that someone is you.
</P>
<P>
   Somewhere along the line, attitude-generated sexiness like this
slipped away from the movies, and it's a bit of a cosmic joke that
the less puritanical Hollywood has become about movies, the more
anti-erotic they've become. Back when movies were under the
watchful eyes of such censorious groups as the Hays Office, which
kept nudity and explicit sexual content out of U.S. movies for
several decades, they had to rely on chemistry, dialogue and
subtext to bring things to a boil.
</P>
<P>
   Once the Motion Picture Association of America put its ratings
system in place in the late '60s, movies began to be more explicit,
although there's a big difference between the explicitness of, say,
``Last Tango in Paris'' and a hard-core porn film such as ``Deep
Throat.'' And practically every year since then, another film has
come along to challenge the ratings board, with the board
compromising more every year, allowing more explicit material to
break through. The first NC-17 movie, 1991's ``Henry and June,''
looks positively tame compared with something like this year's
R-rated ``Summer of Sam'' _ or even the PG-13-rated sniggering and
grossness of the Austin Powers sequel. And as more explicit
material has made its way into films, audiences _ and filmmakers _
have had to use their imaginations less and less.
</P>
<P>
   As imagination has decreased, so, in many ways, has the
attitude. Nobody smolders like Valentino anymore, although Antonio
Banderas came close in last year's ``The Mask of Zorro,'' with
considerable help from Catherine Zeta-Jones (although she couldn't
bring Sean Connery to a simmer in this year's ``Entrapment'').
Nobody crackles like Bogey and Bacall, who had to use words more
than pictures to smoke up ``The Big Sleep'' and ``To Have and Have
Not'' (Bacall's ``You know how to whistle'' speech in the latter
may be the sexiest line of dialogue in any movie). Nobody can make
the ocean roil like Burt Lancaster and Deborah Kerr did in their
famous beachside love scene in ``From Here to Eternity.''
</P>
<P>
   In these movies, what was left out mattered as much as or more
than what was left in. Now, what is left out amounts to the
director-approved (albeit reluctantly) digital alteration of Eyes'
orgy scene, protecting American audiences from peeks at some
actors' genitals. Although Eyes frequently succeeds as ``art,'' it
doesn't succeed as erotica _ in fact, it's ultimately anti-erotic.
If you're looking for its most sexy element, Kidman's eyes have it.
(Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
