<HEADER>
A1693 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TIGER-THEATER-REVIEW-     07-15 0659
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TIGER-THEATER-REVIEW-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`TIGER TAIL': BEAUTY AND BEASTS IN THE RURAL SOUTH 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: A photo is being sent. Non-subscribers can make
individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
(DW) 
 By D.J.R. BRUCKNER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ It is unlikely that Tennessee Williams ever thought
of ``Tiger Tail'' as a viable theatrical work, and the production
mounted at the Harold Clurman Theater by Randy Becker and
Middleschmertz Productions suggests it isn't. The text is simply a
stage reduction of the script Williams wrote for the 1956 film
``Baby Doll,'' and that script in turn was cobbled together from
two one-act plays, ``The Unsatisfactory Supper'' and ``27 Wagons
Full of Cotton.'' ``Tiger Tail'' was simply meant to bring in some
extra cash for the playwright after the film became a success.
</P>
<P>
   Williams was so inattentive to his cobbling that the movie has
two plots only occasionally tacked together. But he was lucky. Elia
Kazan's brilliant directing made the film about a moral sinkhole in
rural Mississippi much bigger and deeper than the script. Karl
Malden's redneck was sloppy and evil, but in anguish, and Eli
Wallach as his antagonist embodied an intelligent malice that made
him attractive and dangerous.
</P>
<P>
   Williams' idea was that Baby Doll would be a fat, ridiculous
woman, but Kazan's casting of Carroll Baker transformed Baby Doll
into a sex bomb who brought the wrath of many censorship groups
down on the film. So, anyone staging ``Tiger Tail'' has formidable
competition.
</P>
<P>
   The two best reasons for seeing the current effort are Shae
D'lyn as Baby Doll and Jane Cecil as Aunt Rose Comfort McCorkle.
Stage and television audiences know well that Ms. D'lyn can look
alluring enough to make it seem downright indecent for any man who
sees her not to try to seduce her, and here she also captures
enough of the somewhat brainless sense of injury of the teen-age
bride of a middle-aged brute to make her escape from him through
sex with his enemy a nice revenge.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Cecil has few equals at creating dotty women who can throw a
whole plot into chaos with a word and reduce male control freaks to
impotent rage with a smile.
</P>
<P>
   Joseph Whipp as Archie Lee, Baby Doll's gross husband, is
certainly as violent, mean and coarse as he is meant to be, but
this Archie lacks any vulnerability, and without that the black
humor Williams intended degenerates into a crude snicker. Silas
Weir Mitchell as Vacarro, whose seduction of Baby Doll is part of a
plan to pay back Archie Lee for having torched Vacarro's cotton
gin, makes the character so intent on stripping her and unbuttoning
himself that he betrays little of the cruel will to destroy a man
that made this role so powerful in Eli Wallach's hands.
</P>
<P>
   Overall, the fissures in Williams' text are made even more
obvious here than they are on the page. Harry Mastrogeorge, the
director, seems to let the story just trudge along; instead of
building up to an explosive climax of grim, comic comeuppance, it
simply ends with an incoherent, drunk boobie hauled off to the
slammer utterly puzzled by what he has brought down on himself.
That may stir emotions, but it is not dramatic.
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCTION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   `TIGER TAIL'
</P>
<P>
   By Tennessee Williams; directed by Harry Mastrogeorge; sets by
George Xenos; lighting by Greg Macpherson; costumes by Melanie
Wehrmacher; sound by Rob Gould; production stage manager, Kelly
Varley; assistant director, Tineka Becker; scenic assistant, Irene
Strang. Presented by Randy Becker and Middleschmertz Productions,
Tom Hein and Gabriella Mirabelli, assistants to the producer. At
the Harold Clurman Theater.
</P>
<P>
   With: Matthew Burnett (deputy), Jane Cecil (Aunt Rose Comfort
McCorkle), Glenn J. Cohen (Sheriff Coglan), Shae D'lyn (Baby Doll),
Silas Weir Mitchell (Silva Vacarrao), Jay Veduccio (Rock), Sybyl
Walker (Ruby Lightfoot) and Joseph Whipp (Archie Lee Meighan).
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
