<HEADER>
A1700 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-IMMIGRATION-AGENCY-HN     07-15 0702
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IMMIGRATION-AGENCY-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CONGRESS SEEKS OVERHAUL OF INS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By MARK HELM  
 c.1999 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Three congressmen gave the Immigration and
Naturalization Service a failing grade Thursday and called for
abolishing the agency and replacing it with two divisions within
the Justice Department.
</P>
<P>
   ``The INS is a broken-down wreck that can't be fixed,'' Rep.
Lamar Smith, R-Texas, said in announcing a bill that would split
the immigration service into two new bureaus.
</P>
<P>
   Smith, chairman of a House Judiciary Committee immigration
panel, was joined by the two co-sponsors of the bill, Rep.
Silvestre Reyes, D-Texas, and Rep. Harold Rogers, R-Ky., who also
condemned the agency's performance.
</P>
<P>
   ``The INS has simply failed to do its job, and a major reason
for that is that it's trying to do too many things at once,'' said
Reyes, a former Border Patrol sector chief in Texas.
</P>
<P>
   While acknowledging that the INS has problems, Attorney General
Janet Reno said the House bill goes too far.
</P>
<P>
   ``The agency should work on being the best it can be, but it's
important to have it under one roof,'' Reno said when asked about
the legislation.
</P>
<P>
   Under the legislation, a Bureau of Immigration Services would
process applications for visas, citizenship, asylum and refugee
status. A separate Bureau of Immigration Enforcement would oversee
the Border Patrol, inspections at airports and other entry points,
investigations, detentions and deportations.
</P>
<P>
   ``With its record of monumental failures, the agency has proven
that it cannot carry out both missions,'' said Rogers, chairman of
the House Appropriations Committee's Commerce, Justice, State and
Judiciary panel, which has jurisdiction over the INS.
</P>
<P>
   The INS _ which is part of the Justice Department _ has a
backlog of 1.8 million legal immigrants waiting for their
citizenship applications to be processed. The average processing
times is more than two years.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's outrageous that a legal immigrant who has paid the $220
processing fee must wait that long,'' Rogers said.
</P>
<P>
   In part to prevent its own demise, the INS has proposed a
reorganization plan that would establish separate structures to
administer benefits and enforcement, but keep them as part of the
INS.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think that the issues between enforcement and service are so
intertwined that it will be important to have a single head of the
agency,'' Reno said.
</P>
<P>
   However, Reno said she was willing to work with Congress to
reach an agreement.
</P>
<P>
   Immigration groups also oppose breaking up the INS, which has
more than 31,000 employees.
</P>
<P>
   Jeanne Butterfield, executive director of the American
Immigration Lawyers Association, a Washington-based group that
provides legal and social services to immigrants, said that while
the INS was in need of change, the bipartisan bill would do more
harm than good.
</P>
<P>
   Frank Sharry, director of the National Immigration Forum, a
Washington-based immigration advocacy group, said the bill would
create ``dueling bureaucracies'' that would cripple immigration
services and weaken enforcement.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody is frustrated with the INS, but this isn't the way
to fix it,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But the sponsors of the bill said that because of the failure of
past INS restructuring plans, they believe the agency must be
abolished.
</P>
<P>
   ``Since 1983, I've been watching the INS say again and again
that it was `changing this' and `restructuring that' and nothing
ever changes,'' Rogers said.
</P>
<P>
   Although there is no comparable Senate bill, Smith said his
legislation already has the support of more than 70 House member
and has a strong chance of passing.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is just such widespread agreement that something is
wrong with this agency,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The House bill also would:
</P>
<P>
   _ Require the directors of the two new bureaus to report to a
deputy attorney general.
</P>
<P>
   _ Install ``chief financial officers'' in each bureau to ensure
that funds are properly spent.
</P>
<P>
   _ Transfer the INS detention operation to the U.S. Bureau of
Prisons within four years.
</P>
<P>
   (Mark Helm can be reached at 202-298-6920 or at the e-mail
address mark(at)hearstdc.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
