<P>
   COKE-SUIT _ Attorneys for Coca-Cola and plaintiffs in a racial
discrimination lawsuit against the soft drink company will be in
court today to argue a key element in the case _ whether plaintiffs
should be able to pursue a class action against the company.
(Unger, Atlanta Journal-Constitution). 30.
</P>
<P>
   E-MAIL-TAX _ WASHINGTON _ Last month, the U.S. Postal Service
took pains to deny a rumor being circulated on the Internet that it
planned to tax e-mail. But now, an agency of the United Nations is
proposing just such a tax in order to help underdeveloped nations
pay for computers and online services. (Geewax, Cox News Service).
8.
</P>
<P>
   EDs: Moving in (f) financial and (w) Washington categories.
</P>
<P>
   COKE-EARNINGS _ ATLANTA _ Coca-Cola Co. said second-quarter
profit fell 21 percent because of slowing demand in Asia and a
health scare in Europe that cut into sales. Net income at the
world's largest soft-drink company dropped for the third straight
quarter to $942 million, or 38 cents a share, from $1.19 billion,
or 48 cents, a year earlier. It met recently reduced estimates of
analysts polled by First Call Corp. (Unger, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   DELTA-EARNINGS _ ATLANTA _ Delta Air Lines reports second
quarter earnings. There have already been warnings from big
competitors like United that earnings will be lower than expected.
(Thurston, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   GA-GASDEREG _ ATLANTA _ Apartment owners and managers have
rushed to sign up with natural gas marketers, tha latest being
today's announcement that Lane Co. has chosen Shell Energy. The
landlords are anxious to lock in a supplier who will provide
continuous service when units are vacant. But tenants are signing
away their rights to choose theis own marketers in Georgia's
deregulated gas market. (Quinn, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   ALTA-VISTA _ AltaVista, still owned by Compaq announces plans to
offer free dia-up internet access to AltaVista customers through a
company called FirstUp. The service won't be ready for several
weeks, and has nothing to do with new buyer CMGI. (Katz, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
