<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-15 18:19 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1714 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FILM-WITCHHUNT-REVIEW     07-15 0790
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-WITCHHUNT-REVIEW-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WITCH HUNT TURNS UP SOME SCARY HYPE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service Clients) 
By ELVIS MITCHELL 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Few pictures sent the kind of excitement through this year's
Sundance Film Festival like the low-tech, no-budget psychological
thriller ``The Blair Witch Project.'' And ``Blair Witch'' now is
jolting the larger landscape with a similar kind of buzz.
</P>
<P>
   Three college students pack video equipment, and enough
cigarettes to satisfy an entire prison population, into the
Maryland woods. Their aim: to make a documentary about the spooky
goings-on in the area. As they begin their journey, they're
patronizing toward the people they interview for their doc _
regular backwoods folks who eagerly, and maybe a little too
intensely, recount stories about the Blair witch legend.
</P>
<P>
   It's here that ``Blair Witch'' is best, in its setup. Heather, a
fast talker who bulldozes her way in the lead, drags her crew along
with her. Her determination sets things in motion. Tramping through
the woods with their spoiled, well-fed obliviousness, they joke and
gripe about how little they manage to turn up.
</P>
<P>
   Heather's All-American contempt for slacker Michael, as
good-natured Joshua jogs along behind them, gives ``Blair Witch'' a
head of steam. Their attempt to find their subject takes a wrong
turn, and the mounting evidence indicates that they're now the game
instead of the hunters. Suddenly, they're trapped in an urban
legend: a story about a group of kids who go into the woods looking
for a monster and find far more than they bargained for.
</P>
<P>
   Filmmakers Eduardo Sanchez and Daniel Myrick have used a process
they call method filmmaking, in which they plunged their cast of
unknowns into a series of grim improvisations. And as the crew's
sense of entitlement dissipates, and they realize they're lost and
stalked by the danger they came to document, ``Blair Witch'' is
doused with sweat and dread. (This movie will do extremely well in
Europe, as the tiny cast is shorn of its bourgeois arrogance.)
</P>
<P>
   The unease is cranked up by the hand-held cameras _ the movie
was shot on video for roughly $20,000 _ and the unsteady-cam
videography adds to the realism.
</P>
<P>
   Part of the enjoyment you may experience in responding to the
material may be a sense of relief. In ``Blair Witch,'' there's none
of the honeyed nihilism and self-mocking cheap irony found in
``Scream'' and its imitators. Nor is there a river of blood and
dismembered body parts. Instead, ``Blair Witch'' gets its shivers
the subtle, old-fashioned way, by creating a scenario that seems
familiar and pulling the rug from under us.
</P>
<P>
   The bleached-poor quality of the visuals and the crew of unknown
actors are a no-nonsense horror treat. For the first 45 minutes or
so, ``Blair Witch'' is a prickly joy, disorienting and disturbing,
a combination of ``The Real World'' and ``Night of the Living
Dead,'' the granddaddy of low-budget, come-from-nowhere thrillers.
</P>
<P>
   But as the movie grinds on, the limited resources become
tiresome. The actors eventually descend into a series of screaming
matches, tearfully bellowing obscenities at each other: The Actors
Studio of the Living Dead. And the ineptitude of the filmmaking,
which had a ragged charm at the outset, is wearing, too.
</P>
<P>
   In George Romero's ``Living Dead,'' the unwieldy filmmaking and
barely tolerable acting gave the movie the off-putting and
mesmerizing quality of a nightmare _ that's why you're afraid to go
to sleep after you've seen ``Living Dead;'' you feel like you've
dreamt it before. For audiences who haven't seen a lot of movies _
and, apparently, the press members who are calling this one of the
most original movies of all time _ ``Blair Witch'' may have that
kind of effect.
</P>
<P>
   So some will find it easy to overlook the inconsistencies, such
as why over the course of five days the trio never runs out of
battery power, or that the sound is consistently well-recorded
throughout the picture; you might think that people fearing for
their lives have things to do other than check the recording
levels.
</P>
<P>
   But the first half is likable, a breath of fresh air that
explains why the hype is so thick around ``The Blair Witch
Project.'' Other than that, though, the scariest thing about
``Blair Witch'' may be the hype.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Blair Witch Project'' is rated R for language and
violence.
</P>
<P>
   The Blair Witch Project _ 3 stars (on a scale of 5) Directors:
Daniel Myrick, Eduardo Sanchez Stars: Heather Donahue, Michael
Williams, Joshua Leonard Length: 87 min. Rated: R
</P>
<P>
   (Elvis Mitchell is film critic for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram.
Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
