<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-15 18:28 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1720 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MOVIES-IN-BRIEF-2TAKE     07-15 1218
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIES-IN-BRIEF-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW AND NOTEWORTHY MOVIES 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Here is a selective listing by critics of The New York Times of
new or noteworthy movies currently playing in theaters. Running
times and ratings of films are in parentheses.
</P>
<P>
   `AMERICAN PIE,' starring Jason Biggs, Chris Klein, Natasha
Lyonne, Thomas Ian Nicholas, Tara Reid, Mena Suvari and Eugene
Levy. Directed by Paul Weitz (R, 100 minutes). The snickering
teen-age comedy about four boys, all seniors in the same Michigan
high school, who swear a pact to lose their virginity by the end of
the school year, serves up a new gross-out joke every five minutes.
</P>
<P>
   The movie obviously wants to outdo ``There's Something About
Mary'' in raunchy guffaws, but it lacks the antic spirit of its
forerunner. More like an upper-middle-class ``Porky's,'' it parades
its dirty jokes as crassly as an old-time burlesque show (Stephen
Holden).
</P>
<P>
   `ARLINGTON ROAD,' starring Jeff Bridges, Tim Robbins, Hope
Davis, Robert Gossett and Joan Cusack. Directed by Mark Pellington
(R, 117 minutes). In a smart, stylish thriller that recalls the
paranoid classics of the '70s, Bridges plays a history professor
who begins to suspect that his smiling suburban neighbors are not
what they seem.
</P>
<P>
   Tracking down clues to an anti-government terrorist network, he
also engages in a battle of wits with Robbins' cryptic character,
and these fine actors square off to gripping effect. Swift and
pulse-quickening, this thriller has more than its share of
surprising twists, including a whopper at the finale. All in all, a
welcome change of pace from the season's dopey blockbusters (Janet
Maslin).
</P>
<P>
   `AUSTIN POWERS: THE SPY WHO SHAGGED ME,' starring Mike Myers,
Heather Graham and Elizabeth Hurley. Directed by Jay Roach (PG-13,
95 minutes). There may come a time when even Austin Powers tires of
the words ``Oh, behave!'' But it isn't here yet.
</P>
<P>
   Although the sequel with the fab title is several love beads
short of its predecessor and more than a few scenes play like
outtakes, this is still a crafty, intermittently hilarious comedy.
Myers' neo-Sellers multiple-personality act is fine even when the
material is less so, and this sequel makes the most of Dr. Evil,
his most inspired creation. A scatological Scotsman, the film's
walking id and bathroom joke, is more of an acquired taste.
</P>
<P>
   Costumes and pop references are still a hoot, as is the adorably
benighted Austin. Ms. Graham makes terrific eye candy but doesn't
share Ms. Hurley's quick-witted air of being in on the joke
(Maslin).
</P>
<P>
   `AUTUMN TALE,' starring Beatrice Romand, Marie Riviere, Didier
Sandre, Alain Libolt and Alexia Portal. Directed by Eric Rohmer
(PG, 110 minutes; in French with English subtitles). The final
chapter of the director's ``Tales of the Four Seasons'' is as
sublimely warming an experience as the autumn sun that shines
benevolently on the Rhone Valley vineyard owned by the central
character, Magali (Ms. Romand).
</P>
<P>
   The movie follows the adventures of this wiry and vital but
lonely widowed mother of two after she allows two friends to play
matchmaker. The film's plot, like that of other Rohmer movies, is
mathematically schematic as the characters indulge in exquisitely
verbalized soul-searching. As sensuously gratifying as it is
civilized, with a wonderful central performance by Ms. Romand, it
reaches a happy ending that feels entirely earned (Holden). &QL;
</P>
<P>
   `BIG DADDY,' starring Adam Sandler, Cole and Dylan Sprouse and
Joey Lauren Adams. Directed by Dennis Dugan (PG-13, 95 minutes).
It's awfully early in the career of Adam Sandler to find him
sharing the screen with a scene-stealing 6-year-old (actually the
Sprouse twins).
</P>
<P>
   Besides, the cute kid in Sandler's movies is usually the star
himself. But he's in a position to do whatever he likes, even if
it's a flimsy sentimental comedy with more product plugs and fewer
laughs than might have been hoped for. Having greatly expanded his
following with the romantic comedy and '80s kitsch of ``The Wedding
Singer,'' not to mention the inspired rustic lunacy of ``The
Waterboy,'' he falls back on much less inventive material this
time. And the barrage of brand-name junk food is enough to make
skin break out in the audience (Maslin).
</P>
<P>
   `THE GENERAL'S DAUGHTER,' starring John Travolta, Madeleine
Stowe, James Cromwell, Timothy Hutton and James Woods. Directed by
Simon West (R, 118 minutes). Murder on a military base was once
enough of a pretext for a detective thriller, but nowadays it takes
more. The prevailing sleaze quotient calls for kinks, and this
galling adaptation of a Nelson DeMille best seller is happy to
oblige.
</P>
<P>
   So the title character, a pretty young officer who the film
thinks has no place in the military, is the victim of a lurid
crime. Travolta and Ms. Stowe affably investigate whodunit, though
the unraveling of the crime is laughably arbitrary. The real point
of their ponderous investigation is that the victim asked for what
she got (Maslin).
</P>
<P>
   `AN IDEAL HUSBAND,' starring Cate Blanchett, Minnie Driver,
Rupert Everett, Julianne Moore and Jeremy Northam. Written and
directed by Oliver Parker (PG-13, 97 minutes). The best thing about
Parker's likable but diluted screen adaptation of Oscar Wilde's
1895 comedy of politics and Victorian morality is Everett's
portrayal of Wilde's elegantly epigrammatic alter ego Lord Arthur
Goring.
</P>
<P>
   In underplaying this seemingly incorrigible (but actually wise,
witty and caring) rake, Everett makes him all the more charming.
Northam and Ms. Blanchett are well cast as a politician and his
priggish wife, but Ms. Moore and Ms. Driver miss hitting the right
notes in a screenplay that streamlines Wilde into a
quasi-contemporary style, keeping some but not all of the
playwright's scintillating bons mots. The settings are so lavish
they're almost edible (Holden). &QL;
</P>
<P>
   `NOTTING HILL,' starring Julia Roberts and Hugh Grant. Directed
by Roger Michell (PG-13, 105 minutes). The most romantic notion
here may be that a Hollywood star as famous as Ms. Roberts might be
out, unassisted, browsing for a book. But it's enough to bring her
together with Grant's bashful bookseller and let two
extraordinarily charming actors play out an intelligent flirtation.
</P>
<P>
   As written by Richard Curtis with frequent wit and welcome
echoes of his ``Four Weddings and a Funeral,'' this is a bright,
winsome romantic comedy that's as teasing as the characters
themselves, inviting the audience to ponder the movie star's
burdens of being world famous and desperately attractive (Maslin).
</P>
<P>
   `THE RED VIOLIN,' starring Samuel L. Jackson, Jason Flemying,
Greta Scacchi and Don McKellar. Directed by Francois Girard (not
rated, 130 minutes). ``The Red Violin'' follows the colorful
300-plus-year journey of a priceless violin from its construction
in an Italian workshop in 1681 to a contemporary auction in
Montreal.
</P>
<P>
   As it makes its way from Vienna to England to China, the
instrument becomes the inspiration for some richly photographed
historical tableaux. If the movie's narrative energy is undermined
by a plodding screenplay and wooden acting, the music, composed by
John Corigliano and played by Joshua Bell and the London
Philharmonia Orchestra, is sublime (Holden).
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   `SOUTH PARK: BIGGER, LONGER AND UNCUT,' with the voices of Trey
Parker, Matt Stone and Mary Kay Bergman. Directed by Parker (R, 88
minutes). The movie spinoff from the outrageous Comedy Central
cartoon series following the adventures of some potty-mouthed
third-grade boys in the Colorado town of South Park is extremely
funny and jubilantly obscene, with several sewers' worth of
bathroom humor.
</P>
<P>
   It is also a smart, pointed satire that demolishes the hypocrisy
of a conservative culture that allows almost unlimited violence and
gore in movies and on television but goes ballistic at the prospect
of children being exposed to dirty language and sexual
explicitness. When a group of tykes sneak into a Canadian movie
filled with obscenities and come home spewing smut, their parents
raise such a ruckus that the United States declares war on Canada.
</P>
<P>
   Armageddon looms when the Devil, who has been having a troubled
affair with the recently deceased Saddam Hussein, decides to put in
an appearance. Contributing to the madness are 15 clever songs
spoofing everything from Rodgers and Hammerstein to ``Les
Miserables'' (Holden).
</P>
<P>
   `SUMMER OF SAM,' starring John Leguizamo, Adrien Brody and Mira
Sorvino. Directed by Spike Lee (R, 145 minutes). This raw,
enthralling evocation of a Bronx neighborhood gone mad in 1977
plunges its audience headlong into a pre-AIDS libidinous frenzy. It
also summons an atmosphere of macho posturing and mounting
prejudice reminiscent of ``Do the Right Thing'' a decade ago,
though the locals this time are white Italian-Americans.
</P>
<P>
   The killing spree of David Berkowitz is used as a catalyst,
joining disco, punk, drugs, a heat wave and the Yankees to summon
the crazed spirit of that time. The characters are thin, but a fine
cast brings them to life. Leguizamo (in high ``Saturday Night
Fever'' style) and Brody (with hair in spikes) are outstanding as
the film's two most visible signs of the times (Maslin).
</P>
<P>
   `STAR WARS: EPISODE I _ THE PHANTOM MENACE,' starring Liam
Neeson, Ewan McGregor, Natalie Portman and Jake Lloyd. Directed by
George Lucas (PG-13, 132 minutes). Stripped of hype and breathless
expectations, Lucas' first installment offers a happy surprise:
it's up to snuff. It sustains the gee-whiz spirit of the series and
offers a swashbuckling extra-galactic getaway, creating illusions
that are even more plausible than the kitchen-raiding raptors of
``Jurassic Park.''
</P>
<P>
   While the human stars here are indeed reduced to playing action
figures, they are upstaged by amazing backdrops and hordes of
crazily lifelike space beings as the Lewis Carroll in Lucas is
given free rein. The ``Star Wars'' franchise was funnier and
scrappier when it was new. But it simply wasn't capable of this
(Maslin).
</P>
<P>
   `TARZAN,' with the voices of Tony Goldwyn, Minnie Driver, Rosie
O'Donnell and Nigel Hawthorne. Directed by Kevin Lima and Chris
Buck (G, 88 minutes). No need to wonder how this animated Tarzan
movie could improve on the 47 others that preceded it.
</P>
<P>
   Disney animation turns the hero into a supple, long-haired hunk,
lets the apes talk to him and whooshes through lush jungle settings
with exultant agility. This ``Tarzan'' is sprightly and likable in
ways that are hard to resist, with lively vocal performances,
excitingly kinetic animation and Phil Collins singing tunefully in
the background. Parents will stay awake, and children will be
charmed (Maslin).
</P>
<P>
   `WILD WILD WEST,' starring Will Smith, Kevin Kline, Kenneth
Branagh and Salma Hayek. Directed by Barry Sonnenfeld (PG, 107
minutes). Another big, lavish movie with no there there. This
post-Civil War James Bondish contraption-happy sci-fi film is hard
to categorize, a quality not to be confused with originality.
</P>
<P>
   Directed by Sonnenfeld without the deadpan-alien sensibility
that worked for ``Men in Black,'' this stylistic grab bag is
similarly kinky but a lot more chaotic, however heroically Smith,
as a newly hunky and debonair action hero, tries to save the day.
Good-looking but dopey, with an emphasis on toylike but vaguely
ghoulish special effects. A movie with that much potential kiddie
appeal didn't have to start in a bordello, either (Maslin).
</P>
<P>
   `THE WINSLOW BOY,' starring Nigel Hawthorne, Rebecca Pidgeon and
Jeremy Northam. Written and directed by David Mamet (G, 110
minutes). Terence Rattigan's play about the 1910 schoolboy's trial
that created a furor in England has been artfully pared down to its
essentials in this stately and deliberate adaptation.
</P>
<P>
   Played with unusually effective restraint by a fine, meticulous
cast, it works as a precisely calibrated war of nerves in which the
family of a cadet accused of theft is quietly staggered by the
consequences of that accusation. Benoit Delhomme's cinematography
is beautifully lucid and painterly. Ms. Pidgeon's defiantly arch
acting style sets the film's tone and gives her suffragist
character a sharp edge (Maslin). &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Film Series &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   `UNIVERSAL SIRK.' After he left Nazi Germany in 1937 and finally
re-established himself as a filmmaker in Hollywood, Douglas Sirk
(1900-1987) became known for lavish and commercially successful
Technicolor melodramas of the 1950s whose cars, costumes and
flowers seemed superficially to fulfill a vision of the American
Dream. But in the decades that followed, film theorists began to
discern in Sirk's mainstream films for Universal Studios a sardonic
social consciousness that commented on America in the Eisenhower
era. In a series at the Film Forum, an opportunity is at hand to
examine some of Sirk's classics.
</P>
<P>
   From Friday through Sunday, the attraction is ``Imitation of
Life'' (1959), Sirk's final Hollywood film. This remake of a 1934
hit based on a Fannie Hurst novel stars Lana Turner as an ambitious
actress, Juanita Moore as her black maid and Susan Kohner as the
maid's daughter who passes for white. The series continues through
July 22 at New York City's Film Forum. Screening schedule and
information: (212) 727-8110 (Lawrence Van Gelder).
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
