<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WINE-PATRIARCH-NYTR-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WINE PATRIARCH TO PRODUCE PREMIUM LABEL 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Calif.)  (mk) 
 By MIKE GENIELLA   
 The Santa Rosa (Calif.) Press Democrat   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   UKIAH, Calif. _ Ending a forced retirement, legendary Mendocino
County winemaker John Parducci at age 81 has purchased the bankrupt
Zellerbach Winery.
</P>
<P>
   Parducci said that while the Zellerbach label will continue, he
plans to introduce his own premium line of ``John Parducci
Signature Wines.''
</P>
<P>
   The Zellerbach winery, located south of Ukiah, has an annual
production capacity of 200,000 gallons.
</P>
<P>
   In mid-1997, Zellerbach Winery, under the ownership of William
Baccala's Vintage Funding, filed for bankruptcy protection.
Parducci said Wednesday his purchase of the winery, for a price
industry sources put at $2.1 million, was approved last week by a
federal bankruptcy judge overseeing the proposed reorganization of
Vintage Funding.
</P>
<P>
   Parducci said he plans to upgrade the quality of the current
line of Zellerbach wines, while also doing custom crushing and
wine-making for private label operators. ``Making good wines is
what I know best. I'm eager to get back to it,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Parducci has earned a national reputation for producing fine red
wines at reasonable prices. He said he intends to stick to the
winemaking basics that he first learned working at his father's
side in the 1930s.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a large number of wine drinkers who appreciate the red
wines made by John Parducci over the years. It's almost like a cult
following,'' said Don Sebastiani, president of Sebastiani Vineyards
of Sonoma.
</P>
<P>
   For Parducci, the new winery venture means a new lease on life.
Since late 1994, Parducci has mourned the loss of Parducci Wine
Cellars, a landmark Ukiah Valley winery his father founded.
</P>
<P>
   Parducci was ousted five years ago as that winery's general
manager following a celebrated struggle with Teachers Management
and Investment Corp., a Southern California investment group. In
1973, the Parducci family sold a controlling interest in the winery
to the Teachers group, but John Parducci continued on as winemaker
and general manager.
</P>
<P>
   For years, Parducci and TMI enjoyed a bountiful relationship. He
and his family ran the winery as their own, and TMI dished out big
dividends to hundreds of retired California teachers. But by the
late 1980s, TMI's big statewide real estate ventures were
collapsing. In 1994, tensions over management of the Parducci
winery, by then TMI's only profitable business, reached the boiling
point.
</P>
<P>
   In the end, Parducci was locked out of a winery where he had
worked all of his life.
</P>
<P>
   Parducci Wine Cellars was purchased in 1996 by Chicago venture
capitalist Carl Thoma, and Napa Valley vintner William Hill. Thoma
has since acquired total ownership of the 350,000-case winery.
</P>
<P>
   Parducci said the new winery operation will be ready for this
fall's grape crush. ``Everything we need is already here. All we
have to do is start making some really good wines,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   (The Santa Rosa (Calif.) Press Democrat is part of the New York
Times Regional Newspaper Group.)
</P>
</TEXT>
