<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-15 18:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1732 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-AT-THE-MOVIES-2TAKES-     07-15 0931
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AT-THE-MOVIES-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KUBRICK, EDITED; MASTROIANNI ON HIMSELF; A TWO-WAY BRIDGE
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Canada, Colo., Conn., Mass.)  (rk) 
 By BERNARD WEINRAUB   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOLLYWOOD _ Stanley Kubrick's last film, ``Eyes Wide Shut,''
will be shown in the United States with several sex scenes altered
so it can carry an R rating instead of the far more restrictive
NC-17.
</P>
<P>
   An NC-17 version _ no one under 17 admitted _ will be shown
across Europe. The R version _ anyone under 17 must be accompanied
by an adult _ was made because a portion of one scene, an orgy
among masked couples in a mansion on Long Island, depicted various
sexual couplings.
</P>
<P>
   In the R version, the masked couples are visible but are partly
shielded by computer-generated figures who represent orgygoers
watching them. There are no shielded figures in the NC-17 version.
In both versions, the scenes in question last 65 seconds.
</P>
<P>
   In the last week, Warner Brothers has finally shown the film,
perhaps the most anticipated, or hyped, of the year , to critics
and journalists. The screenings were of the NC-17 version, although
at the end Warner showed the scenes that were altered to give the
movie its R rating.
</P>
<P>
   Pat Kingsley, the publicity agent who represents Tom Cruise and
Nicole Kidman, the stars of the film, said both versions were shown
``because everyone wanted to see the difference.'' Ms. Kingsley
added: ``Not a frame was cut. This was Stanley's intention in the
first place.''
</P>
<P>
   The film was written by Kubrick and Frederic Raphael and
inspired by ``Traumnovelle'' (``Dream Story'') by Arthur
Schnitzler. It deals with an upper-class Manhattan doctor and his
wife whose sexual fantasies and dreams lead them on a strange and
protracted odyssey. During the 18-minute orgy sequence, the Cruise
character sees masked couples engaged in sex.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Kingsley said Kubrick, who died in March, had expected his
film to be released with an R rating. But after showing the movie
to top Warner Brothers executives and discussing it, he realized
that an NC-17 rating was inevitable. Studios avoid releasing movies
rated NC-17 because some theater and video chains shy away from
them.
</P>
<P>
   So Kubrick decided to place the computer-generated figures _
mostly caped and hooded individuals _ in front of the couples at
three different points. The editing was completed after his death.
</P>
<P>
   ``He thought he could get away with an `R,''' Ms. Kingsley said.
``Then he realized he couldn't do it.''
</P>
<P>
   Jan Harlan, executive producer of the film and Kubrick's
brother-in-law, said no portion of the scenes was eliminated.
</P>
<P>
   The Motion Picture Association of America, which oversees
ratings for films, has consistently maintained that it views
violence in movies as seriously as sex. But film critics, taking
note of the Kubrick film, seem to think otherwise.
</P>
<P>
   Todd McCarthy, the film critic for Variety, wrote the other day
that watching the two versions back to back provided a vivid
insight into the workings of the association.
</P>
<P>
   ``Seeing what the MPAA considers NC-17 worthy makes the org's
nit-picking seem absurd, especially given the gruesomely graphic
violence to which it routinely applies R ratings,'' he wrote.
</P>
<P>
   Janet Maslin of The New York Times called the changes made to
the film ``a joke,'' and said, ``The meaning and effect of the acts
witnessed remain the same.''
</P>
<P>
   Mastroianni on Himself
</P>
<P>
   Anna Maria Tato was Marcello Mastroianni's companion for the
last 22 years of his life.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were so different _ the differences made for the appeal,''
said Ms. Tato, who had written books about film when she first met
and interviewed the Italian star.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was 34,'' she said. ``He was 49. I was from the south of
Italy, very passionate. Like a bull. He was a humanist. Very
cultivated. Very kind. Always respectful. He respected women. I was
beautiful and young. And he was so beautiful.''
</P>
<P>
   Before his death in 1996 at the age of 72, of pancreatic cancer,
Mastroianni reluctantly at first and then enthusiastically began to
cooperate with Ms. Tato, discussing his life while being filmed.
The result is the documentary ``Marcello Mastroianni, I Remember,''
which has opened in Italy, France, Spain and London to strong
reviews. The film will open in Manhattan on Aug. 17 at Lincoln
Plaza Cinemas and in other large cities in the week after that.
</P>
<P>
   In the documentary, Mastroianni, who was arguably the most
popular Italian male film star for three decades, gently and
affectionately describes his background (his father was a
carpenter); his working years in the theater; his recollections of
Garbo, Fellini and Visconti, and the stereotyping of him as an
irresistible Latin lover. What emerges from the film is a portrait
of a star who is both surprisingly modest and deeply intelligent.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was aware of being a star but he always tried to live a
normal life,'' Ms. Tato said. ``He always said you can never really
hide what you really are when you are on the screen. Everything of
your inside comes out on the screen. The screen reveals it. The
audience knows.''
</P>
<P>
   He made 170 films, a remarkable number for any actor. Ms. Tato
said that before she met Mastroianni, she thought he was just
another ``bourgeois'' actor. ``I felt so stupid afterwards, so
narrow-minded,'' she said. ``I criticized myself.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I loved his intelligence, the fact that he had such a sense of
irony; he was a great storyteller too,'' she said. ``He had great
qualities.'' She laughed. ``The defects I will not tell you.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   A Two-Way Bridge
</P>
<P>
   Over the years, directors of television shows have used the
medium as a springboard to feature films. Upon embarking on a movie
career, the television directors rarely look back.
</P>
<P>
   Not Steve Miner.
</P>
<P>
   In a highly unusual trajectory, Miner, 50, veers easily between
television and movies, focusing on both almost simultaneously.
</P>
<P>
   ``You go where the work is,'' said Miner , whose newest film,
``Lake Placid,'' an offbeat comedy-thriller about a threatening
crocodile in Maine, starring Bill Pullman, Bridget Fonda and Oliver
Platt, opens on Friday .
</P>
<P>
   The movie was written by David E. Kelley, the television
writer-producer and a longtime friend of Miner's, who has directed
episodes of Kelley's series ``Chicago Hope'' and ``The Practice.''
</P>
<P>
   Miner's features include ``Soul Man,'' ``Forever Young,'' ``My
Father, the Hero,'' ``House,'' ``Friday the 13th, Part 2'' and
``Halloween: H20.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Television used to be a serious stigma for film actors'' Miner
said. ``You couldn't be on a television show on a weekly basis and
still be a movie star. That's completely changed now. But for
directors, it's still very difficult to go back and forth. Why? I
don't know. You either do one or the other.''
</P>
<P>
   He added: ``One of the problems in features now is, of course,
there's a finite number of jobs and there are thousands of
qualified directors. You have to work somewhere.''
</P>
<P>
   What makes Miner unusual is that in television, he has focused
on making the pilot of a series and then not directed later
episodes. Pilots he has made include those for ``The Wonder
Years,'' ``Dawson's Creek'' and an upcoming ABC series,
``Wasteland,'' written by Kevin Williamson, who also wrote
``Dawson's Creek.''
</P>
<P>
   ``If you get a good script for a pilot, you get to set the tone
of the show, you set the look, you cast it,'' Miner said. ``You
have an impact on that show.'' There was one other advantage to
television, he said: ``A pilot takes a month and a half, it's over.
A movie takes more than a year and a big chunk out of your life.''
</P>
<P>
   Miner grew up in Westport, Conn., dropped out of college to work
at a ski resort in Colorado and after seeing the 1969 comedy
``Putney Swope'' decided that he wanted to try to make movies. He
returned home to Westport and began working as an assistant on
various industrial films in New York and Connecticut.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, a Westport neighbor, Sean Cunningham, became the
producer of a horror film, ``Last House on the Left,'' which was
made in his family's backyard; Miner worked as a $15-a-week
assistant on the movie. The film, made in 1973, was the directing
debut of Wes Craven, now one of Hollywood's foremost horror
directors.
</P>
<P>
   Soon, Miner and Cunningham began producing low budget horror
films. The unexpected success of ``Friday the 13th,'' which was
financed by some Boston theater exhibitors, led them to ask Miner
to produce the sequel.
</P>
<P>
   ``I said, `I'll produce it if you let me direct it,''' Miner
said. ``I don't think they understood the difference between a
producer and director. They said, `OK'''
</P>
<P>
   Miner moved to Los Angeles in the late 1970s but couldn't get a
job in films. He met the writing team Carol Black and Neal Marlens;
they asked him to direct the pilot episode of ``The Wonder Years.''
The success of that show led to Miner's Hollywood film career.
</P>
<P>
   He is now completing a film in Calgary, Alberta. Called ``Texas
Ranger,'' it is an action movie starring, among others, Dylan
McDermott (``The Practice'') and James Van Der Beek (``Dawson's
Creek''). Miner has worked with both on their television shows.
</P>
<P>
   The director said that upon completing that film, he hopes to
return to television and take on another pilot episode. Does he
know which one?
</P>
<P>
   ``Not a clue,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
