<HEADER>
A1738 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NY-VIDEO-FESTIVAL-ART     07-15 2189
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-VIDEO-FESTIVAL-ART-1250(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A THEMATIC FEAST OF AVANT-GARDE VIDEOS 
</HEADLINE>
 (Eds: 2nd take is a schedule of screenings for the coming week.) 
(Eds.: The spelling of Armond in the 6th graf is correct. Also, two
dashes after the video title `Ape__' under the 5:45 p.m. lineup for
SATURDAY in the screenings schedule represents a title that is
unprintable in full.) 
(ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036. 
(yn) 
 By STEPHEN HOLDEN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Of the many unsettling images to be seen in the New
York Video Festival, a weeklong series that begins Friday at the
Walter Reade Theater, none is more provocative than the actress
Kate Valk as the title character in the Wooster Group's production
of Eugene O'Neill's play ``The Emperor Jones.'' Wearing blackface
and a Kabuki costume, rolling her eyes and writhing before the
camera like a voodoo apparition in Asian theatrical drag, the
Caucasian actress adopts a cartoonishly oratorical drawl to intone
the character's ravingly paranoid dialogue. Layer upon layer of
calculated artifice combine to create a clashing theatrical
dissonance that is further complicated by the raw emotional power
erupting behind these multiple facades.
</P>
<P>
   The 45-minute work will be shown Friday evening at 9 at the
Video Festival, part of Lincoln Center Festival '99. It will be
followed by a panel discussion with Ms. Valk, the Wooster Group
director Elizabeth LeCompte, the video maker Chris Kondek and the
film critic David Sterritt. The piece is the company's video
adaptation of its acclaimed 1998 stage production of the 1921
O'Neill play. Its central character, Brutus Jones (Ms. Valk), is an
exiled black railroad porter who proclaims himself emperor of a
West Indian island. When the inhabitants rise up in revolt, he
flees into the jungle with his evil Cockney sidekick Smithers
(Willem Dafoe).
</P>
<P>
   The group's production of ``The Emperor Jones'' last year at the
Performing Garage treated the drama as a bold extension of the
playwright's fascination with masks, using blackface and Kabuki
costume and even language itself (the exaggerated black dialect) as
theatrical masks. What is being shown this evening is not a
videotaped version of the stage production but a video
re-conception of the play with digital sets, overlapping images,
Kabuki-influenced dances and sound effects that compress the action
into something that resembles a long-form music video. The finished
work is an explosive, beat-driven, in-your-face confrontation with
the characters whose faces sometimes appear videographically gouged
out (another form of mask) to suggest horror-movie zombies. Like it
or loathe it, ``The Emperor Jones,'' once seen, is unforgettable.
</P>
<P>
   With its experimental video technology and bold collisions of
theatrical style, ``The Emperor Jones'' fits right into a festival
that is unabashedly avant-garde in spirit. Many of the shorter
films are intriguing if often impenetrable collages that explore
the outer limits of video technology and quirky personal
expression.
</P>
<P>
   The closing night performance on July 22 is the elliptical
``Love Diamond,'' an extended performance piece by Miranda July and
Zac Love that mixes dialogues between characters (all performed by
Ms. July) with exchanges between technologies (video and film) to
evoke a kind of communications circuitry between humans and
machines. The work even involves some audience participation.
Although Ms. July lacks the wit and showmanship of Laurie Anderson,
who explores many of the same themes, ``Love Diamond'' belongs
squarely to the tradition of the experimental one-person
Gesamtkunstwerk (total work of art) that Ms. Anderson and other
technologically adventurous performance artists developed in the
1970s and '80s.
</P>
<P>
   Aside from two other special programs, one a videographic
journey by the Russian filmmaker Alexander Sokurov, the other an
analysis of contemporary music videos chosen by the critic Armond
White, the rest of the festival is divided into nine thematic
programs exploring everything from the family (``Family Matters''),
to the relationship between people and animals (``Only Human''), to
the relationship between humans and technology (``Ghosts in the
Machine'').
</P>
<P>
   A good deal of the work this year is problematic. Although video
art is a young form, the genre has already developed its own
cliches. One of the most glaring is digital repetition, a technique
that became a musical cliche in the early years of hip-hop music.
When applied to video, it allows the artist to deconstruct a scene
by replaying it frame by frame, then painstakingly moving it
forward to illuminate its presumed (usually ominous) psychological
subtext.
</P>
<P>
   A number of the artists represented in the festival also wrongly
assume that the portability of video and its ability to visit
places larger cameras cannot go will automatically insure a certain
intimacy. In Don Bernier's video ``Zoo: A Melancholy Bestiary,''
for instance, shots of animals in captivity are introduced by
ominous alphabetically sequential one-word titles. The images of
various zoo animals meant to illustrate these negative concepts are
too bland to have any resonance.
</P>
<P>
   Altogether, the festival is showcasing the work of 40
videomakers from the United States and abroad. The following are
some of the better, more substantial works.
</P>
<P>
   Theresa Duncan's animated video ``The History of Glamour'' is a
gentle, very funny pseudo-documentary of the fashion world that
tells the story of Charlie Valentine, a girl from Antler, Ohio, who
moves to New York City, becomes a supermodel and eventually a
Madonna-like pop star. The film imagines a chic little society
where Chanel No. 5 is served as a cocktail in restaurants with
names like De Rigueur. One of the narrators (played by Mary Louise
Wilson doing her best Diana Vreeland impersonation) is a fashion
maven named Grace Greenberg, who runs the definitive fashion rag
Ooh La La Magazine.
</P>
<P>
   Ken Kobland's ``Transit Riders of the Earth Arise! Walk Dog Eat
Donut'' is a melancholy, semi-abstract video poem made up largely
of blurred images shot from moving subway and elevated cars in New
York City and Berlin. Woven into the film are fragments of a diary
(despairing epigrams like ``all meaning evaporates'') and a Russian
ballad. Repetitive without becoming monotonous, the video evokes an
urban sadness that is so insistent it becomes a whole philosophy of
loss and resignation.
</P>
<P>
   Chris Petit's ``Negative Space'' is a portrait of the retired
film critic and painter Manny Farber, who guides us through some of
his favorite moments in Hollywood movies. He loves pointing out
background details that would have gone unnoticed without his
observation. The one movie most alluded to is Rossellini's 1953
film ``Voyage to Italy,'' from which there are several clips.
Farber has profound things to say about the relation of American
films and the behavior of Americans in relation to the landscape,
especially to the highways and the open spaces of the West.
</P>
<P>
   Christopher Wilcha's ``Target Shoots First'' is his on-location
record of his experience working for the Columbia House record club
in New York City. Hired for an entry-level marketing job just at
the moment when Nirvana was leading an onslaught of alternative
rock, Wilcha, an avid fan and collector of the music, helped
develop a hip alternative-rock magazine for the company to send to
its subscribers. The video delicately explores corporate politics,
the concept of selling out and ageism, among other topics.
</P>
<P>
   Kelly Reichardt's ``Ode'' is yet another update of the legend of
Billie Joe McAllister made famous by Bobbie Gentry's 1967 hit song
about the mystery suicide of a boy in the Mississippi Delta. This
version, filmed in Super 8 and transferred to video, roughly
follows the same course as the 1976 movie version starring Robby
Benson. But it is far more intimate and realistic. Starring Kevin
Poole and Heather Gottlieb as gropingly inarticulate working-class
teen-age sweethearts, the movie is steeped in an almost suffocating
Southern languor.
</P>
<P>
   Of all the works in the series, it could be said few if any
constitute what we think of as television. They belong to an
alternative tradition, obstinate (sometimes maddeningly so) in its
insistence on the value of the quirky, the personal and the
indirect.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &UR; NY-VIDEO-FESTIVAL-2NDTAKE-NYT &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; NEW YORK: the indirect. &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The New York Video Festival, part of Lincoln Center Festival
'99, runs through Thursday at the Walter Reade Theater at Lincoln
Center. Each program includes several videos, many of which will be
introduced by the video makers. Unless noted, the videos were
released this year and either are in English or have no dialogue.
The Video Festival also features a special screening Friday of
``The Emperor Jones'' presented by the Wooster Group, followed by a
panel discussion. Tickets for most programs are $8.50 ($5 for
members of the Film Society of Lincoln Center and the Association
of Independent Video and Filmmakers); there is a special $12 ticket
($10 for society members) for ``Love Diamond,'' a performance piece
that closes the festival on Thursday. Video information: (212)
875-5600. Here is a schedule of screenings:
</P>
<P>
   Friday
</P>
<P>
   ``SOCIETY OF SPECTACLE,'' with ``Johnny Take a Dive'' (United
States), directed by Jennifer Reeder; ``Small Lies, Big Truth''
(United States), by Shelly Silver; ``Evil and Pop Culture'' (Italy,
1998), by Cane Capo Volto; ``The History of Glamour'' (United
States), by Theresa Duncan, 4 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   ``OUTER AND INNER SPACE,'' with ``Moorings'' (United States), by
Michael Ginsburg; ``In.side.out'' (United States), by Scott Stark;
``A Tropical Story'' (United States), by Alfred Guzzetti; ``Transit
Riders of the Earth Arise! Walk Dog Eat Donut'' (United States), by
Ken Kobland; ``Amber City'' (United States), by Jem Cohen, 6:15
p.m.
</P>
<P>
   ``THE EMPEROR JONES'' (United States), by Chris Kondek. A
screening of a documentary about the Wooster Group production of
the Eugene O'Neill work, followed by a panel discussion with
Elizabeth LeCompte, director of the Wooster Group production; Mr.
Kondek; Kate Valk, an actress in the video, and David Sterritt, a
film critic, 9 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   Saturday
</P>
<P>
   ``FAMILY MATTERS,'' with ``Spank'' (United States, 1998), by
Diane Nerwen; ``My Parents Read Dreams I've Had About Them''
(United States, 1998), by Neil Goldberg; ``No Concept But Good
Sense'' (United States, 1998), by Pilar Wiley; ``2 into 1''
(Britain, 1997), by Gillian Wearing; ``Generation Loss'' (United
States), by Sean Bokenkamp; ``A Part of Me'' (Britain, 1998), by
Carl Callam; ``Shifting Positions'' (United States), by Kathy High,
1 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   ``THEY DON'T MAKE 'EM LIKE THEY USED TO,'' with ``Mark Roth''
and ``Marbles'' (both United States), by Animal Charm; ``All Smiles
and Sadness'' (United States), by Anne McGuire; ``2 Spellbound''
(United States), by Les Leveque; ``Ode'' (United States), by Kelly
Reichardt, 3:30 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   ``ONLY HUMAN,'' with ``Rabbit, Rabbit, Rabbit'' (United States),
by Stuart Hawkins; ``Bird Watching'' (United States, 1998), by
David Kareken; ``Spiritual Animal Kingdom'' (Canada, 1998), by
Steve Reinke; ``Ape__'' (United States), by Leah Gilliam; ``Zoo: A
Melancholy Bestiary'' (United States, 1998), by Don Bernier, 5:45
p.m.
</P>
<P>
   ``AFTER IMAGES,'' with ``Wonder Spider'' (United States, 1998),
by Pan Optic; ``Eklipsis'' (United States, 1998), by Tran T.
Kim-Trang; ``F for Fake: The Black Hole Sun'' (Italy, 1997), by
Cane Capo Volto; ``Dead Weight of a Quarrel Hangs'' (United States,
1998), by Walid Raad; ``The Warm Place'' (Argentina, 1998), by
Marcello Mercado, 10:15 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   Sunday
</P>
<P>
   ``CONFESSION,'' (Russia, 1998), a four-and-a-half-hour
documentary by Alexander Sokurov inspired by the diary of a
submarine captain, 1 p.m. In Russian with English subtitles.
</P>
<P>
   ``FAMILY MATTERS,'' 6 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   ``AFTER IMAGES,'' 8:15 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   Monday
</P>
