<DOCNO> NYT19990715.0308 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-15 18:52 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1743 &Cx1f; ttg-z
a l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SWARTZ-COLUMN-$ADV22-     07-15 0853
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SWARTZ-COLUMN-$ADV22-NYTR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMMENTARY: THE LUMPS SHE TAKES WILL BE HER OWN 
</HEADLINE>
  (For release Thursday, July 22.) 
(jt) 
 By SUSAN SWARTZ    
 Santa Rosa (Calif.) Press Democrat   
 c. 1999 The New York Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   She has wider first name identification than Cher. She's always
somewhere on the lists of most admired American women. She's been
on the cover of Vogue.
</P>
<P>
   She's also been scorned, mocked, betrayed, pitied, burned in
effigy and abused by late night boy comedians.
</P>
<P>
   It's amazing, then, that so many everyday women relate to
Hillary, but we do. And so, on the matter of her running for the
U.S. Senate from New York, we may be saying ``go, girl'' for
reasons only slightly connected to what she might do to improve the
life of those in Syracuse and the Bronx.
</P>
<P>
   Were she not the first lady, her situation wouldn't be that much
different from other wives who get to a point in their lives when
it's time to figure out the second half. The babies are raised. The
husband's career is either going to fly or die, no matter whom she
invites to dinner. Now it's her turn to see what else she can do.
</P>
<P>
   In a way, Hillary Rodham Clinton is typical of many women of her
generation who struggled with combining family and career, trying
to be both dutiful, according to the old ways, and independent,
according to the new, and who at middle age have this wild desire
to run for office, go to grad school or start an herb farm.
</P>
<P>
   As we embark on the millennium, Hillary's attempts to do
something very bold or very rash, depending on your point of view,
will be watched by women and more than a few men. We don't know her
motives for wanting to switch careers and enter a field that means
a giant pay cut and which will pit her against an opponent with
large canine teeth and before a press busily making mud pies. But
there are reasons to admire her for marching into the arena.
</P>
<P>
   She's uncomfortable in the role of poor wronged wife. By putting
herself out there she's saying, ``Don't pity me. Vote for me.''
That the woman has aspirations is no surprise. Nor that she seeks
power and influence. Many do. When you have power, maybe they don't
worry so much about how you wear your hair.
</P>
<P>
   She's like so many uppity women who are resented for their
confidence, exuberance and intelligence. And for challenging the
uppity men's club. Many want her to run for the Senate just because
others think she shouldn't. They think she should do something a
little more behind the scenes and gracious. We think she's been
gracious long enough.
</P>
<P>
   Besides, a picture of her in a victory photo would finally make
up for that bathing suit shot.
</P>
<P>
   Of course many of us do not live in New York and are not moved
to debate the carpetbagger issue or worry about gridlock in
Westchester County. Those are New York's problems and New Yorkers
will be the ones who ultimately decide if it's a good idea for her
to run. I talked to a Westchester Democrat who said her objection
to Hillary is that she's become disillusioned with both Hillary and
her husband and she wishes her state could have come up with a
local candidate. But, she said, ``I think it's neat that she's the
first first lady to run for office.''
</P>
<P>
   It's easy to understand why, given the choice of New York or
Arkansas to go home to on Fridays, there'd be no choice for
Hillary. New York has better museums and restaurants, and they were
never very nice to her in Arkansas.
</P>
<P>
   If she becomes a senator, she won't be able to make any outside
money, no astronomical lecture fees. He'll have to work to pay off
the legal bills, which seems only fair since she had to dip into
her money to pay on his Paula Jones account.
</P>
<P>
   A lot of people are still pretty mad at her husband. We'd like
her to run just to say, ``It's not my fault he was a jerk.''
</P>
<P>
   If it were us, we might rather run to a beach far away and sit
on the sand and think about it for a year. But if it were us, we
would have thrown his bags and his stupid copy of ``Leaves of
Grass'' into the driveway and moved to Paris.
</P>
<P>
   It would be interesting to see what Hillary the politician can
do when she's not in her husband's shadow or under his black cloud.
</P>
<P>
   It would also be a welcome opportunity to ask for her thoughts
on issues like welfare and dealing with crime and improving the
schools. Could we get back to the subject of universal health care?
</P>
<P>
   People complain, ``Why does she want to bring all that muck up
again?'' But it's not her muck and it's not her choice to bring it
up again.
</P>
<P>
   It's her choice and her right to run for public office. She's
already proven she cares about her country. If she didn't, the bags
would have been in the driveway, the president would be trying to
find a saxophone gig and the stock market would not be a happy
place.
</P>
<P>
   She stayed. Now she can run.
</P>
<P>
   And if she does and she loses, then she can consider her other
options. Become an ambassador. A university lecturer. A foundation
head. Or the herb farm.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (The Press Democrat in Santa Rosa, Calif., is part of the New
York Times Regional Newspaper Group.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
