<SLUG> BC-CREDIT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INVESTORS BUY UP $1.6 BILLION OF CALIFORNIA HIGHWAY BONDS 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By ROBERT HURTADO   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Municipal bond investors stole center stage in bond
trading Thursday as they quickly bought up $1.6 billion of
tax-exempt bonds backed by toll revenue from a Southern California
highway.
</P>
<P>
   In the largest tax-free bond offering this year, underwriters
led by Salomon Smith Barney handled the sale by Foothill/Eastern
Transportation Agency and had good demand from institutional
buyers, including mutual funds.
</P>
<P>
   The sale included $831.3 million of straight interest-bearing
bonds as well as the more scarce zero coupon bonds, which provide
no income in the interim but pay out all of the tax-exempt interest
in a lump sum at maturity. Some bonds are rated triple-A because
the interest and principal are insured, while uninsured portions
are rated Baa-3 by Moody's Investors Service and BBB by Standard &AMP;
Poor's Corp.
</P>
<P>
   Market participants said the straight bonds were tentatively
priced to yield 4.55 percent for an issue due in 2004 and to yield
5.25 percent for one due in 2016. A bond due in 2019 was priced to
yield 5.35 percent and the longest, due in 2040, was priced to
yield 5.80 percent. The zero coupon bonds were priced to yield from
5.85 percent to 6.125 percent, with maturities ranging from 2020 to
2038.
</P>
<P>
   Another issue priced Thursday was the $138 million offering of
general obligations bonds by Nassau County, N.Y. The county,
recently stung by several cuts in its bond rating by both Moody's
and S&AMP;P, bought insurance that gave the bonds a triple-A rating.
</P>
<P>
   Paine Webber won the issue in competitive bidding and resold the
bonds at prices to yield 4.30 percent for an issue due 2003, and
5.35 percent in 2019.
</P>
<P>
   Treasury securities were little changed after a report that the
Consumer Price Index was unchanged in June for the second
consecutive month, indicating tame inflation.
</P>
<P>
   The yield of the benchmark 30-year bond was unchanged at 5.91
percent while its price, which moves in the opposite direction,
fell 1/32, to 90 25/32.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
