<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FAIR-THEATER-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`AFTER THE FAIR': MUSICAL ROMANCE WITH A DIRGE IN ITS HEART 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds: Production notes are at end of review.) 
(yn) 
 By PETER MARKS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ After the strange doings of Stephen Sondheim and
James Lapine's ``Passion,'' no romance could be too eccentric for
the musical theater, and certainly not that in ``After the Fair,''
a chamber musical adapted from a Thomas Hardy short story about a
frustrated Englishwoman who plays Cyrano de Bergerac to an
illiterate serving girl and the educated man they both love.
</P>
<P>
   This joyless little tale, with book and lyrics by Stephen Cole
and music by Matthew Ward, might have provided a few piquant
moments. But the authors and the director, Travis L. Stockley, are
in no mood for levity. The stunted emotional scale of ``After the
Fair'' starts at mournful and rises in solemn increments to
something like clinical sobriety. Even from a writer as morose as
Hardy, this is a show that might be well advised to start a regimen
of antidepressants.
</P>
<P>
   Though the musical, which opened Thursday night at the Theater
at St. Peter's Church, is new to New York, it can't actually be
called new, having been staged many times in workshops and regional
theaters since 1988. The professional sheen is unmistakable. But
perhaps its creators have fretted too much over the project,
because ``After the Fair'' has had all the life squeezed out of it.
</P>
<P>
   The chief attraction of the production, presented by the York
Theater Company, is Michele Pawk, whose Fraulein Kost, a prostitute
in Fraulein Schneider's rooming house, was one of the glories of
Sam Mendes' Tony-winning revival of ``Cabaret.'' If one were to
pick Fraulein Kost's polar opposite, it would be the character she
plays, Edith Harnham, the prim and corseted lady of the house.
</P>
<P>
   Edith is a repressed country gentlewoman of late Victorian
England, unhappily married to a mumbling bore named Arthur (David
Staller). Her housemaid Anna (Jennifer Piech), ambitious if
unschooled, sets her sights on Charles (James Ludwig), a young
barrister she meets at the local fair. Smitten, Charles asks Anna
to write to him in London. Anna enlists the lonely Edith to be her
epistolary proxy, and an ill-starred love triangle is forged.
</P>
<P>
   One could imagine a score of some charm to leaven the deception;
Cole and Ward have a more prosaic plan. Their songs, a series of
breathlessly earnest ballads, can be pretty but linger in the
memory about as long as a spritz of room deodorizer. The
sensibility lies somewhere on the spectrum between ``The
Fantasticks'' and ``I Do! I Do!'' The two best numbers, ``Between
the Lines'' and ``There's a Woman/What is Real,'' have some oomph,
although one has to tiptoe through a lot of buttercups to get to
them.
</P>
<P>
   Stockley offers his actors little help. Ms. Pawk maintains
unassailable diction and a constant look of contained panic. If she
were any more bottled up, she would require the Heimlich maneuver.
Ms. Piech, who played one of the trio of Kates in the musical
``Titanic,'' garners sympathy chiefly because the story is stacked
so heavily against Anna. The men are just sort of drippy. One
consolation: the lavish period costumes by Michael Bottari and
Ronald Case.
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCTION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   `AFTER THE FAIR'
</P>
<P>
   Book and lyrics by Stephen Cole; music by Matthew Ward; based on
the short story ``On the Western Circuit'' by Thomas Hardy;
directed by Travis L. Stockley; set by James Morgan; costumes by
Michael Bottari and Ronald Case; lighting by Michael Lincoln;
orchestrations by David Siegel; additional orchestrations by
Georgia Stitt; production stage manager, Michael J. Chudinski.
Presented by the York Theater Company; James Morgan, artistic
director; Robert A. Buckley, managing director. At the Theater at
St. Peter's Church, Citicorp Center, Lexington Avenue at 54th
Street.
</P>
<P>
   With: Michele Pawk (Edith Harnham), Jennifer Piech (Anna), James
Ludwig (Charles Bradford) and David Staller (Arthur Harnham). &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-15-99 1856EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
