<P>
   SCHOOL-TESTS (Los Angeles) _ Amid the report of yet another
problem with the state's latest round of standardized tests, the
state Board of Education indicated Thursday it may seek up to $10
million in penalties against the publisher of the problem-plagued
Stanford 9 exam taken by 4.2 million California school children. By
Terri Hardy. (Will move in the ``n'' California news file.)
</P>
<P>
   LA-NINA (Los Angeles) _ Southern California could face another
dry winter and a longer fire season courtesy of La Nina, scientists
said Thursday. The same weather phenomenon that cut the area's
average rainfall in half last winter could return in the next few
months, possibly extending a fire season already expected to be
severe. By David Baker. (Will move in the ``n'' California news
file.)
</P>
<P>
   LA-HARBOR-CITY (Los Angeles) _ The San Pedro-Wilmington
secession movement is poised to join the Valley cityhood study, yet
its leadership has become bitterly divided. The factions clashed at
the Local Agency Formation Commission meeting this week and were
told to settle their differences in court. The dispute doesn't
affect the Valley study, but if it's not settled in the next two
years it could hurt a Valley secession bid when a citywide election
is held. By Michael Coit. (Will move in the ``n'' California news
file.)
</P>
<P>
   WARNER-RESIGN (Los Angeles) _ Shock rolled through Hollywood on
Thursday as the co-chiefs of Warner Brothers, Robert A. Daly and
Terry Semel, announced their co-resignations after two decades of
running the industry's top studio.
</P>
<P>
   Daly and Semel, who have been both the longest-serving and most
consistently successful executives in Hollywood, said they would
leave by the end of the year to pursue unspecified ``new
opportunities.'' By Dave McNary. (Will move in the ``f'' financial
news file.)
</P>
<P>
   SUPERIOR-EARNINGS (Los Angeles) _ Superior Industries
International posted a 56 percent gain in quarterly profits _ the
most profitable second quarter in the history of the wheel maker
and well ahead of analysts' expectations. By Enrique Rivero. (Will
move in the ``f'' financial news file.)
