<SLUG> BC-FILM-BLAIR-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SUM TOTAL OF `BLAIR WITCH PROJECT' IS RATHER SCARY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By WILLIAM ARNOLD  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   It's such a low-low-budget endeavor that ``The Blair Witch
Project'' is bound to disappoint some of the expectations aroused
by its tremendous pre-release buzz. But it's still a clever little
ghost story that generates some authentic chills.
</P>
<P>
   The film is a ``mockumentary'' about a trio of young filmmakers
who have disappeared off the face of the Earth while on an
expedition in the Maryland woods to make a documentary about a
local witch legend. One year later, an opening title card tells us,
their cameras were found.
</P>
<P>
   So what we supposedly see is their film _ their personal account
of the ill-fated quest _ starting with a lengthy sequence in which
they set out on the journey (with an ample supply of liquor and
attitude) and interview some of the locals.
</P>
<P>
   As they trek deeper into the woods where several mysterious
disappearances and murders have taken place over the years, they
gradually get lost, then someone or something seems to be following
them, then one of their number disappears, and then ... well, you
know how it ends.
</P>
<P>
   Be warned that this is not an easy movie to follow. In fact,
it's not a movie at all _ it's a video (with a few sequences of
16mm thrown in), and a significant portion of it is about as much
fun and as dramatically compelling as your neighbors' trip to
Yosemite.
</P>
<P>
   For what seems about half the movie, the video camera is pointed
at the ground, and we have to stare at a shaky blur of images that
mean nothing. I found this so dizzying and headache-inducing that I
finally had to shut my eyes for long passages of time.
</P>
<P>
   Furthermore, the characters are not a bit appealing, the actors
who play them are lackluster at best, and the performances are
thoroughly pretentious _ like what you tend to find in the
least-accomplished student films. (And, technically, ``Blair
Witch'' is very much a student film).
</P>
<P>
   Still, as amateurish and fumbling as it is in every department,
the sum total of the movie is pretty darn scary. We leave it
feeling strangely unsettled in a way we almost never do after one
of Hollywood's $100 million, special-effects-heavy fright fests.
</P>
<P>
   Realizing they couldn't come up with anything visual that hadn't
been done a thousand times before, the young filmmakers opted to
not show any explicit horror.
</P>
<P>
   The film merely suggests some eerie possibilities, and then lets
the audience scare itself with its own imagination. It's an old and
simple idea, but in this era of effects-overkill and total visual
saturation, it seems original, even brilliant.
</P>
<P>
   The Blair Witch Project. Directed, written and edited by Daniel
Myrick and Eduardo Sanchez. Cast: Heather Donahue, Michael Williams
and Joshua Leonard. Artisan Entertainment. 87 minutes. Rated R for
language and horror-movie situations.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: B
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-15-99 1914EDT &QL; 
