</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-PLACID-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`LAKE PLACID' NOT TERRIBLE, JUST TERRIBLY MEDIOCRE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By WILLIAM ARNOLD  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Like most Hollywood movies these days, ``Lake Placid'' tries to
be more than just one thing. It's a comedy, a romantic star
vehicle, a thriller, a horror movie and a quasi-environmental
parable that's calculated to appeal to all demographic groups.
</P>
<P>
   Also, like most Hollywood movies these days, it's not enough of
any one of these things to be particularly engaging. It's not
terrible, just terribly mediocre. You leave the theater not so much
irritated or offended as feeling you've wasted your time.
</P>
<P>
   The action is set on a remote Maine lake that's being victimized
by some giant water creature that, in the opening teaser, bites a
police scuba diver in half. (Yes, the title is ironic.)
</P>
<P>
   In no time, an investigating task force is formed and includes a
high-strung New York museum paleontologist (Bridget Fonda), a smug
fish and game warden (Bill Pullman) and an eccentric mythology
professor (Oliver Platt) who is fascinated by crocodiles.
</P>
<P>
   The team quickly determines that the culprit is, indeed, a
crocodile _ a gigantic, 30-foot, Guinness Book of World Records
crocodile that somehow ended up in a place where his species does
not exist.
</P>
<P>
   As this unlikely group does battle with the leviathan and the
movie turns into a goofy version of ``Jaws,'' both Platt and
Brendan Gleeson (as a small-town sheriff) have their moments, and
effects whiz Stan Winston's animatronic crocodile is quite
convincing.
</P>
<P>
   But, for the most part, the film is acted and directed (by Steve
Miner) with no special flair or inspired B-movie campiness, and it
produces what must be the worst star chemistry of any movie so far
in 1999. Individually and as a couple, Fonda and Pullman could not
be less ingratiating.
</P>
<P>
   As a comedy, the movie also is agonizingly flat. A few nervous
laughs are generated here and there, but most of the character
shtick consistently misses, especially several offensive scenes
with Betty White as a foul-mouth senior citizen who lives as a
hermit on the edge of the lake.
</P>
<P>
   As a horror-thriller, it also has its moments, but it's all
formula _ overworked visual cliches that have no impact anymore.
(``Placid'' also has the misfortune of being released on the same
day as ``The Blair Witch Project,'' which for all its fumbling
amateurishness, is original and scary.)
</P>
<P>
   The script was written by David E. Kelley (who also
co-produced), which is surprising and disappointing, given his
status as the reigning genius of network television (he's the
creator of ``Chicago Hope,'' ``Picket Fences,'' ``The Practice''
and ``Ally McBeal'').
</P>
<P>
   Like his first, dreadful movie script for ``Mystery, Alaska''
(which was screened for critics months ago and keeps getting kicked
down Disney's release schedule), this one is poorly conceived and
thought out and derivative of a dozen better movies.
</P>
<P>
   Lake Placid. Directed by Steve Miner. Written by David E.
Kelley. Cast: Bill Pullman, Bridget Fonda, Oliver Platt, Betty
White. 82 minutes. Rated R for horror violence.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: C
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
