<SLUG> BC-FILM-WOOD-SPI </SLUG>
  
 `THE WOOD' IS A COMIC, AFFECTIONATE GLIMPSE OF THE '80s  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By PAULA NECHAK  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``The Wood'' refers to Inglewood, Calif., a smoggy middle-class
suburb of Los Angeles. It's here 14-year-old Mike (Sean Nelson)
moves from North Carolina with his family in 1986, and where he
meets the two boys who will become his friends for life.
</P>
<P>
   Slim (Duane Finley) and Roland (Trent Cameron) welcome Mike into
their tight team because, if anything, he's more innocently
wide-eyed and clumsy than they are.
</P>
<P>
   But as the years pass, all three grow closer and ruminate
together over everything from girls and the mysteries of sex to
their futures. They ward off gangs and guns and concentrate on
school and what to do with life after graduation.
</P>
<P>
   All of this is relayed through humorous flashback some 13 years
later. It's a big day for Roland (Taye Diggs), who is about to be
married to his sweetheart, Lisa (Lisaraye). The boys are finally
men and soon will be breaking apart and moving in different
directions with their lives, though Mike (Omar Epps) and Slim
(Richard T. Jones) are having second thoughts about Roland's
maturity level.
</P>
<P>
   It's three hours to the wedding and Roland's gone AWOL. Lisa is
upset and wants to call off the wedding. It's up to Mike and Slim
to find their best friend, reel him in and get him to the ceremony
on time.
</P>
<P>
   They share what ostensibly will be their last big adventure
together as they carom through the day, with Mike acting as
narrator and guide through episodes from their youth.
</P>
<P>
   Director and writer Rick Famuyiwa wanted to depict some of his
rites of passage and also has pushed hard to change the way young
black men are portrayed in movies. ```The Wood' represents a shift
in the marketplace toward new representation of African American
life,'' he says in the film's press notes.
</P>
<P>
   He's done exactly what he set out to do. His film is a comic,
loving, affectionate glimpse of the '80s, its music and fashions,
and most of all at that hard-to-find thing called true friendship.
These guys are absolutely devoted to each other and a way of life
that is fading into memory. But while big-name actors Diggs, Epps
and Jones receive top billing, the film really belongs to their
boyhood incarnations _ Nelson, Finley and Cameron _ who, in their
awkwardness and naivete take a rose-colored, sentimental premise
that we've seen many times before and make it seem much fresher and
funnier than it is.
</P>
<P>
   The Wood. Directed and written by Rick Famuyiwa. Cast: Taye
Diggs, Omar Epps, Richard T. Jones, Sean Nelson. Paramount. 106
minutes. Rated R for language, sex, nudity.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: B-
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
