<HEADLINE>
DELAY IN F-22 PRODUCTION WOULD RAISE COSTS BY BILLIONS, AIR FORCE
SAYS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service Clients) 
By MICHAEL D. TOWLE 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ |A key House subcommittee's move to halt initial
production plans for the Lockheed Martin F-22 would delay the
program at least two years, cost taxpayers $6.5 billion and
increase the risk American pilots will face in the years ahead, Air
Force officials said on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are very concerned that without the F-22, we will mortgage
the future of our air dominance capability while we fund the
systems that we currently have and that we think will not be as
capable as they need to be in the future,'' said Lt. Gen. Greg
Martin, principal deputy assistant secretary for Air Force
acquisition.
</P>
<P>
   A House Appropriations subcommittee that oversees military
spending recommended earlier this week that the Air Force
reevaluate its plans for the $70 billion F-22 program and that $1.8
billion in the Pentagon's 2000 budget intended to produce the first
six Raptors be slashed. The committee left in $1.2 billion for
continued development.
</P>
<P>
   Lawmakers on the subcommittee, who voted unanimously in favor of
the move, said readiness, personnel issues, and other problems
within the Air Force are not being addressed properly because the
service is putting a huge portion of its budget into production
plans for the Raptor.
</P>
<P>
   Martin said he met on Thursday with several subcommittee
members, including its chairman, Rep. Jerry Lewis, R-Calif.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think that we will be able to convince people we need it,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   Lewis could not be reached for comment on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   The subcommittee's suggestion that the program, which has
already cost taxpayers $20 billion, be delayed was a shock to many
at the Pentagon, since three other congressional panels had
approved production spending for the airplane.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's astonishingly short-sighted and it just goes to show that
it is all about pork,'' said Richard Aboulafia, an industry analyst
with the Teal Group, a Fairfax, Va. based company that follows
aerospace programs.
</P>
<P>
   The subcommittee's budget improved Clinton administration
proposals to order current generations aircraft, such as the Fort
Worth-made F-16 and St. Louis-made F-15, a plane that, without much
international interest, has teetered on the edge of extinction for
several years.
</P>
<P>
   The full House Appropriations Committee will meet today to vote
on the subcommittee's proposed budget, including its plans for the
F-22. Members are expected to pass the measure setting up a fight
on the House floor next week.
</P>
<P>
   If approved on the House floor, the issue would be tested later
this year when members from the House and Senate meet to iron out
differences in their bills.
</P>
<P>
   Some on Capitol Hill expect the issue to die in conference,
others say it will be hard for joint panels to ignore a House floor
vote in favor of the move.
</P>
<P>
   Martin said that if the delay goes through the Air Force would
have to spend $6.5 billion more on the program. About $1.2 billion
would go to upgrade two test aircraft so they could be used in more
stringent operational tests. The remainder would go to bring
contractors and suppliers back to the program once initial
production plans are rescheduled. The Air Force hopes to ultimately
buy 339 F-22s, down from earlier plans for more than 700.
</P>
<P>
   He said the Air Force also would have to consider upgrading
current aircraft to fight against more advanced aircraft expected
to be flown by enemy air forces in the early part of the next
century, including French and Russian fighters.
</P>
<P>
   The F-22 is being developed to counter lethal threats posed by
advanced surface-to-air missile systems and next-generation
fighters equipped with sophisticated missiles.
</P>
<P>
   About 1,900 of the 11,500 workers at Lockheed Martin Tactical
Aircraft Systems in Fort Worth, are assigned to the F-22 program.
That number is projected to grow to 4,000 by 2005.
</P>
<P>
   The Fort Worth operation produces the middle part of fuselage of
the fighter. The remaining portions are to be produced at a
Lockheed plant in Marietta, Ga. and a Boeing facility in Seattle,
Wash.
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
