<SLUG> BC-CARS-SAFETY-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A NEW APPROACH TO SEAT BELTS 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(mk) 
 By MATTHEW L. WALD   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Early next year, some new cars will come with seat
belts that act somewhat like bungee cords, which could lower the
cost of safety-belt assemblies and improve passenger protection in
crashes that include multiple impacts.
</P>
<P>
   The original idea behind seat belts was to hold occupants
firmly, so that if the front of a car moving at 35 mph hit a brick
wall and instantly stopped, the driver or passenger would not
continue moving forward at 35 mph until striking the dashboard or
windshield.
</P>
<P>
   But if the belt is completely firm, a person can die of injuries
caused by the belt as it suddenly stops the body. Automakers used
to use a device that locked up the belt completely when the car
suddenly and forcefully decelerated, but they now incorporate a
``constant force retractor,'' a mechanical device that spreads out
the strain of deceleration by locking up the belt but then playing
out a little bit of it at the moment of peak strain. The retractor
acts like a fisherman who plays out his line to keep a hooked fish
from breaking it.
</P>
<P>
   The car, though, is faster than the fisherman; the whole crash
can take as little as 120 milliseconds, with the peak load coming
about halfway through that, at 60 milliseconds, or six-hundredths
of a second. The constant-force retractor can cut the peak load
from 50 G's _ or 50 times the force of gravity _to as little as 20
G's.
</P>
<P>
   Allied Signal Corp., which makes various car parts, will begin
shipping a material in August that takes a new approach. The
company will market fibers that are slightly stretchier than the
polyester now used in belts. The new material is only a bit more
elastic; the belt cannot play out too much or a person in the front
seat will be too close to a deploying air bag.
</P>
<P>
   The standard belt is about 9 feet long, counting the part that
goes over the lap and across the torso, and then up into a reel in
the car's center pillar or in the seat. The new material, which the
company calls Securus, will allow the torso to move forward about
9.2 inches in a severe crash, compared with 7.2 inches for a
standard system with a constant-force retractor.
</P>
<P>
   Such a retractor kicks in at 1,000 to 1,200 pounds of pressure
on the belt, said Gregory Rogowski, marketing manager for the new
product, which begins to stretch at about 400 pounds, he said.
Standard belts made of polyester can withstand 6,000 pounds _ a
level of force far beyond what the human torso can handle.
</P>
<P>
   Rogowski said that seat-belt assemblies using the stretchy fiber
would cost $10 to $15 less than those with constant-force
retractors, but that the belts would have a safety benefit as well.
The constant force retractor works only once, but in a
multiple-impact crash the stretchy belt would repeatedly help to
protect its wearer.
</P>
<P>
   Rogowski predicted that automakers would use Securus first in
back seats, because the regulations governing those belts are less
strict and government approval would be likely to come faster. And
because of consumer interest, he said, automakers are paying more
attention to rear-seat safety, especially in minivans.
</P>
<P>
   The new belts will show up around the middle of the 2000 model
year, he said, meaning in March or April.
</P>
<P>
   Dangerous Conversations
</P>
<P>
   Accident data gathered by police still do not make clear the
risk posed by cellular telephones, according to a new study by the
National Highway Traffic Safety Administration, but some factors
are clear: More than 85 percent of cellular phone customers say
they sometimes use the phones while driving, and 27 percent use
them on more than half of their trips. By next year there will be
80 million users, the agency said.
</P>
<P>
   So many cellular users call police when they see highway crashes
that seven states are beefing up ``911'' systems to handle the
increased call volume, even though the number of crashes has not
changed.
</P>
<P>
   Limited data from crashes in several states suggest that it is
conversation, not dialing, that causes crashes. Dialing requires
drivers to take their eyes off the road, but they tend to
compensate, often by driving slower, the report said. ``Contrary to
expectations, the majority of drivers were talking on their
telephones rather than dialing at the time of the crash,'' it said.
``A few drivers also were startled when their cellular telephones
rang and, as they reached for their phones, they ran off the
road.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The overwhelming majority of cellular telephone users were in
the striking vehicle, and struck cars or other large objects that
were in clear view,'' the agency found.
</P>
<P>
   Explorer vs. Sable. Explorer Wins.
</P>
<P>
   The bumpers of some sport utility vehicles have fared badly in
low-speed insurance industry tests using poles or immovable
barriers, but the bumper of a 1997 Ford Explorer did very nicely in
a real-world exercise recently in Rockville, Md., when matched
against the back end of a 1992 Mercury Sable station wagon. It
wasn't bumper-to-bumper, but bumper-to-tail-light, as the Explorer
spared the wagon's bumper almost entirely by striking above it.
</P>
<P>
   As a result of the mismatch, the left rear corner of the car
ended up moving one foot toward the hood. It would probably have
gone forward farther, but the Sable's spare tire, stored upright in
a compartment on the left side, served as a sort of bumper,
transferring some of the impact force to the sheet metal in front
of it. The tailpipe and muffler, undamaged, were clearly visible
from above, where the liftgate used to be.
</P>
<P>
   The Sable was mine, and my insurance company said repairs would
cost a bit more than $5,000, which was the approximate value of the
car, which had 80,000 miles on the odometer. I was not present at
the time of the accident, on a quiet residential street with a 25
mph speed limit, but witnesses said the Ford had only modest
damage.
</P>
<P>
   The outcome would have been considerably worse if anyone had
been sitting in the wagon's rear-facing third seat.
</P>
<P>
   Statistics show that injuries and deaths are more frequent in
car-truck accidents _ the truck category includes sport utility
vehicles like the Explorer _ than in collisions between cars. But
the insurance industry does not keep separate statistics on damage
costs in such collisions. Last year, though, the Insurance
Institute for Highway Safety did measure collision damage against
liability damage (which will apply in my crash if I can collect
from the other driver's insurance company). It shows that 1995-97
models of midsize cars like the Sable had average collision damage
of $250 a vehicle a year, and average liability costs of $73.
Midsize sport utilities like the Explorer had collision damage of
$212, or 15 percent less, but liability costs of $94, or 29 percent
more.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you look at the collision damage, they do pretty well
compared to cars,'' said Julie Rochman, a spokeswoman for the
insurance institute. ``But they're inflicting harm on the vehicles
they're hitting.''
</P>
</TEXT>
