<SLUG> BC-FILM-LIFE-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`AFTER LIFE' WEARS OUT ITS WELCOME 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By PAULA NECHAK  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   British director Nicolas Roeg once told me that in order to make
a good film one must ``cut one's little darlings'' in editing if
the ``darling'' doesn't move the story along. If only Japanese
director Hirokazu Koreeda (and several other filmmakers as well)
would learn that lesson.
</P>
<P>
   ``After Life,'' Koreeda's initially loving, lovely and oddly
honorable homage to life, death, documentary and memory certainly
starts with promise. A group of the recently deceased arrive at a
way station.
</P>
<P>
   Each is assigned a caseworker and given a task. They have a mere
three days to muster up their single favorite memory from life. It
will be re-enacted and filmed and then taken to the next level of
the journey where the person will live it through eternity.
</P>
<P>
   ``After Life,'' like so many movies these days, has several
endings and it wears out its welcome.
</P>
<P>
   Had ``After Life'' been cut by 20 minutes, its graceful
metaphysical message would have hit just the right key. But Koreeda
drones on with his script, introducing a love story late in the
film that is supposed to be a climactic note. Instead, it's
anticlimactic. A more succinct ending has already preceded it.
</P>
<P>
   That said, Koreeda has an eye for the sensual and visual and
creates an illusory world. This is a place where theater,
choreography, image and the act of making a favorite remembrance
from life is important. ``After Life'' gives these notions both
humorous and gentle treatment.
</P>
<P>
   But by the time the film ends, we feel like we've endured a
thousand or more lives by watching an endless meditation on regret
and rebirth and wonder why an accomplished director like Koreeda _
he also directed ``Maborosi'' _ would be so overly expositional
with such ethereal, risky material.
</P>
<P>
   After Life. Directed and written by Hirokazu Koreeda. Cast:
Arata, Erika Oda, Susumu Terajima. Artistic License Films. 118
minutes. Unrated. In Japanese with English subtitles.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: B-
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-15-99 1931EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
