<HEADLINE>
ONLY TWO LARGE CITIES NOW READY FOR Y2K, REPORTS GAO 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  (Attn: El Paso, San Antonio) 
 
By JOHN C. HENRY 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Only two of the nation's 21 largest cities _ Dallas
and Boston _ are fully prepared to deal with anticipated year 2000
computer glitches, according to the General Accounting Office, the
audit arm of Congress.
</P>
<P>
   Houston is among nine cities scheduled to be validated as
Y2K-compliant by the end of September, a margin of three months
before critical systems could begin failing with the dawn of 2000.
</P>
<P>
   Ten other cities _ including El Paso, San Antonio and Washington
_ reported to the GAO that all their computer systems would be
ready for the historic date change by the end of December, timing
that raised concerns among lawmakers and GAO staff members.
</P>
<P>
   ``Completing Y2K activities in the last months of the year
increases the risk that key services will not be Y2K-ready in time
for 2000 because there will not be enough time to deal with
unanticipated complications,'' warned Joel Williamssen, head of the
GAO team that monitors information systems.
</P>
<P>
   Officials are concerned that some computers will crash or render
data unusable by misreading 2000 as 1900, a programming
characteristic originally intended to save space by reducing the
year-date to two digits.
</P>
<P>
   For local governments, the loss of computers could mean
disruptions in emergency services _ such as police, fire and
ambulance _ transportation, and water and wastewater treatment
facilities.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In Houston, city officials earlier this month declared their
various computer systems ready for the arrival of 2000. Mayor Lee
Brown had set June 30 as date for the city's systems to be ready
``and that deadline has been met,'' said his press secretary Lauri
Fickman.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the city is awaiting the arrival of new computer
hardware and software that will make the Aviation, Public Works and
Engineering, Fire, Housing and Community Development, Parks &AMP;
Recreation departments and the Library fully Y2K compliant. Also, a
private consultant currently is verifying that all the city
computer systems are free of the so-called millenium bug, and the
tests are expected to be finished by Sept. 30.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(END OPTIONAL TRIM) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In testimony before the Senate's Special Committee on Y2K
issues, Williamssen reported that telephone surveys of the nation's
largest cities early this month found that 45 percent of their
various computer-reliant systems have been prepared and tested for
the date-switch.
</P>
<P>
   In Dallas and Boston, all municipal computer systems have been
converted and validated. The nine cities whose systems are expected
to be verified as ready by Sept. 30 are Houston, Indianapolis,
Jacksonville, Fla., Memphis, Tenn., Milwaukee, New York,
Philadelphia, San Diego and San Jose, Calif.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, Williamssen said, nine states _ Alabama,
California, Colorado, Hawaii, Louisiana, New Mexico, New Hampshire,
Ohio and Wyoming _ were found to have addressed the problem in less
than 70 percent of their most important computer systems.
</P>
<P>
   Considering how much work remains to be done, Williamssen said,
``contingency plans are critical to ensure that cities will
continue to provide key services through the year 2000 date
change.''
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Robert Bennett, a Utah Republican who heads the special Y2K
committee, said he feared that many state and local governments
were ``leaving little room for testing, contingency planning and
unexpected problems.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
