u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ASIA-DANCE-REVIEW-NYT     07-15 0548
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ASIA-DANCE-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OF GRIEF AND TIANANMEN SQUARE 
</HEADLINE>
  (dw) 
 By JENNIFER DUNNING   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ One of the most interesting aspects of the
Asia-Pacific Contemporary Dance Festival at Kaye Playhouse here has
been the stories of how each of the four modern-dance troupes was
founded. The Taipei Crossover Dance Company of Taiwan, which
performed on Wednesday night, was founded in 1994 by a leading
Taiwanese lighting designer, Lin Keh-hua, and four veteran members
of the Cloud Gate Dance Theater. Cloud Gate, one of the oldest
modern-dance companies in Asia, was created by Lin Hwai-min, a
writer who became enamored with American modern dance as a student
in New York.
</P>
<P>
   Martha Graham was his inspiration. Graham's appetite for large
themes was an evident influence in Lin's ``Requiem,'' performed to
a score by Franz Liszt, whose emphatic simplicity gave it the sound
of an early modern-dance score by Louis Horst. Dedicated to the
victims of the Tiananmen Square massacre, the solo places a woman
at the center of the stage. The dance never lets her stray far from
that spot as she dips and rises, her columnar body and fluting dark
dress a leashed centripetal force. Only her arms and hands pry
loose to claw and ascend in supplication.
</P>
<P>
   A tour de force of performing, ``Requiem'' was danced with a
majestic grandeur by Lo Man-fei. The handsome costume was designed
by Lin Ching-Ju.
</P>
<P>
   The program opened with ``A Wanderer's Autumn Grief,'' a savvy
but long-winded piece by Helen Lai to an old Chinese song.
According to program notes, Ms. Lai used the many fans in the piece
to capture the song's nostalgic mood. The quartet seems,
intriguingly, to be a modernist's comment on cultural tradition and
its ramifications, as two men and two women respond to a fan in
ways that ranged from intense longing to rage. That sense of past
and present was embodied in the skittering, agonized performing of
Wu Su-chun in the central role. Taurus Wah designed the subtly
colored, flowing costumes.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Lo's 1998 ``Dark Side of the Moon,'' which completed the
program, is set to music by Lin Huei-ling that mixes the old and
new to vivid effect. The choreography does, too, in this adaptation
of ``Rashomon.'' Each of the four versions of the story about a
rape and a murder takes too long to unfold, however, making it hard
to connect them. But the stylized look of the work was handsome, as
were the costumes, designed by Yip Kam Tim. Zhang Xiao Xiong stood
out as the tireless punk provocateur of the dance.
</P>
<P>
   The three works were greeted with cheers by the audience. One
man rose to his feet in homage to ``Requiem,'' crying ``Stand up!
Stand up!'' to his fellow audience members as he applauded. But all
three dances had a puzzling emotional cool or distance that could
not be attributed to the physically and dramatically expressive
dancers. They also included the sweet-faced Chen Shu-gi and the
elegant Yeh Tai-chu, founders of the troupe with Ms. Lo and Ms. Wu.
The evening's lighting was by Lin Keh-hua and Chang Tsan-tao.
</P>
<P>
   The festival, produced by Kaye Playhouse and Arts Promotion
Asia, ends with performances Saturday night and Sunday afternoon by
the Son Mu Ga-zen Dance Company from Korea at Kaye Playhouse.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
