<SLUG> BC-LUCENT-SPECTRAN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LUCENT EXTENDS MASSACHUSETTS HOLDINGS, ACQUIRES SPECTRAN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PETER J. HOWE  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Lucent Technologies Inc., the world's biggest telecommunications
manufacturer, continued its Massachusetts shopping spree Thursday,
announcing plans to grab a specialty cable maker for $99 million.
</P>
<P>
   SpecTran Corp., which makes custom fiber-optic products for
telephone and cable television and special applications such as
surgery, oil exploration and fighter-jet gyroscopes, would join a
half-dozen other Bay State high-tech companies that have become
part of Lucent in the last two years.
</P>
<P>
   However, Lucent may face trouble persuading SpecTran owners to
sell because its proposed purchase price of $9 a share is 22
percent below SpecTran's Wednesday closing price. SpecTran shares
tumbled 2 5/8 Thursday to 8 7/8 on heavy Nasdaq volume of 576,500
shares.
</P>
<P>
   SpecTran chief executive Charles B. Harrison said it was the
most favorable purchase offer the 18-year-old Sturbridge company
had received. Given SpecTran's large debt load, small customer base
and fierce competition, he said he doubted a better deal would come
along and noted that SpecTran's average stock price over the last
six months has been $6.50 a share.
</P>
<P>
   But one major shareholder, Martin Whitman, the co-manager of the
Third Avenue Small Cap Value Fund in New York, told Bloomberg
Business News the deal ``doesn't make any sense'' and he will not
sell his fund's 7 percent stake in SpecTran.
</P>
<P>
   Adding SpecTran's 500 employees would bring Lucent's
Massachusetts employment roster to well over 7,000 workers,
including more than 5,500 who work at its Andover, Mass. cable
manufacturing plant, the state's biggest factory.
</P>
<P>
   Lucent said it will open a 20-day tender offer for Spectran's
outstanding stock at $9 a share starting July 21, and if it fails
to get 90 percent of the shares, will reconsider the deal. It would
also assume $35 million in SpecTran debt.
</P>
<P>
   Helped by a soaring stock price, Lucent has been bulking up in
recent months _ including a $900 million stock purchase of Nexabit
Networks Inc. of Marlborough, Mass. announced last month _ in hopes
of better challenging industry giant Cisco Systems Inc. for the
fast-data transmission market.
</P>
<P>
   Lucent was interested in SpecTran because it ``broadens our
portfolio and moves us into new niches'' where it now has no
product offerings, said company spokesman Bill Price.
</P>
<P>
   Besides selling to telecommunications and cable television
businesses, SpecTran markets speciality products such as cables
that link manufacturing equipment and devices that aid deep-well
oil and gas exploration, laser surgery and gyroscopes on military
aircraft.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to Nexabit, which has developed a switch that can
move 1 trillion bits of data a second, in the last 2 1/2 years
Lucent has bought or announced plans to buy in Massaachusetts:
Agile Networks of Boxborough, Cambridge software developer Kenan
Systems Inc. and, in December 1997, Prominet Corp. of Marlborough.
The $200 million Prominet deal came just 20 months after its
founding and seven weeks after Prominet shipped its first
high-speed data switching product.
</P>
<P>
   The former Cascade Communications of Westford, Mass. and Stratus
Computer Inc. of Marlboro are also joining the Lucent stable
through Lucent's $20 billion stock acquisition of Ascend
Communications announced earlier this year. Cascade and Stratus
were both taken over by Ascend.
</P>
<P>
   Spectran has 500 employees working in two divisions: SpecTran
Communication Fiber Technologies in Sturbridge and SpecTran
Specialty Optics Company, in Avon, Conn.
</P>
<P>
   Lucent has had a close relationship with SpecTran for several
years, both as a major customer and through a patent licensing
agreement signed last year.
</P>
<P>
   Bill Spivey, president of Lucent's Network Products Group, said
buying SpecTran will give Lucent ``new fiber products, additional
expertise and new market niches within the optical fiber
industry.''
</P>
<P>
   Lucent, a descendant of the Bell System's Western Electric unit,
has 13 fiber and cable manufacturing businesses and joint ventures
around the world, including China, Denmark and Russia. Its Bell
Labs unit holds over 1,600 optical networking patents.
</P>
<P>
   Harrison, Spectran's president, said he will stay with Lucent
for an unspecified transition period. Lucent shares rose 2 5/8 to
77 5/8.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
