<SLUG> BC-CAMPAIGN-FINANCE-REPORT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AGENCIES FAULTED IN PROBE OF CHINA'S ROLE IN U.S. ELECTIONS
</HEADLINE>
   (jw) 
 By DAVID JOHNSTON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ An internal Justice Department report has found
that the FBI and federal prosecutors mishandled highly classified
intelligence on allegations that China improperly attempted to
influence American elections.
</P>
<P>
   An unclassified summary of the inspector general's 569-page
report, which was released Wednesday, found that FBI officials were
at first reluctant to share raw intelligence with campaign finance
prosecutors, senior Justice Department officials and lawmakers who
demanded the information as part their own investigations.
</P>
<P>
   Later, the report said, Justice Department officials provided
too much unverified intelligence to lawmakers, fearing that
Attorney General Janet Reno and her subordinates could be
criticized by Republicans if they failed to turn over information
that might be considered relevant to a congressional inquiry.
</P>
<P>
   The inspector general's report found that none of the missteps
amounted to an intentional effort to mislead or interfere with any
investigation. Instead, it said, the failures stemmed from
institutional inertia, poor communication and a reluctance to share
classified information with criminal prosecutors for fear of
compromising intelligence sources.
</P>
<P>
   Reno said Thursday that she was reading the report, but added
that she had found no evidence that the Justice Department campaign
finance investigation had been damaged by the problems uncovered by
the inspector general's review. ``Anytime something is delayed, you
can call that bungling,'' she said. ``But the investigation itself
was not impaired in the end.''
</P>
<P>
   Michael Bromwich, the inspector general, concluded that the
actions of the FBI and the Justice Department reflected an absence
of clear-cut standards about how much information to supply to
outsiders. In the case of the Justice Department, the distribution
of sensitive information ``of dubious quality'' potentially
endangered criminal investigations and could have violated the
constitutional rights of people under scrutiny, the report said.
</P>
<P>
   The report drew no conclusions about whether the problems in
handling classified information had any impact on investigations
conducted by the Justice Department or Congress. The inquiries
examined allegations that Beijing had a plan to influence American
elections in 1996, when Asian-American fund-raisers engaged in
intensive efforts to find contributors for the Clinton-Gore
re-election.
</P>
<P>
   Subsequent investigations have found that some contributions
were secretly made by Chinese officials associated with military
and intelligence agencies. But so far little evidence has emerged
to show definitively that Beijing conducted a coordinated attempt
to buy influence in the United States.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-15-99 1938EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990715.0335 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-15 19:38 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1777 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GLF-BRITISH-GARCIA-BO     07-15 0568
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-BRITISH-GARCIA-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GARCIA'S FIRST ROUND LANDS IN THE ROUGH 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB DUFFY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   CARNOUSTIE, Scotland _ It wasn't the aggregate score for Team
Sergio, though it could have been mistaken as such.
</P>
<P>
   Sergio Garcia shot 89 in the first round of the British Open
Thursday all by himself, without a shred of help from his council
of seven advisers/employees. If they truly had his best interests
at heart, his handlers would have removed the clubs from his hands
and all sharp objects from his reach.
</P>
<P>
   The 19-year-old wunderkind _ a pro for two months, a phenom for
five years, and a sensation for two weeks _ played like a child
trapped in an alley. And Carnoustie Golf Club played the role of
neighborhood bully.
</P>
<P>
   As a heralded amateur, Garcia finished 29th in last year's
British Open. As a hapless professional, he won't finish this
year's British Open.
</P>
<P>
   He came here off a victory in the Irish Open two weeks ago and a
second place in the Loch Lomond Open last week, and there was talk
around the clubhouse, even among his veteran colleagues, that he
might duplicate Tiger Woods's feat in the 1997 Masters by winning
his first major championship in which a paycheck was at stake. But
Thursday Evelyn Woods could have outplayed him.
</P>
<P>
   Two days after firing a bogey-free 2-under-par 69 in a practice
round, Garcia opened with a 7. That will win you a bundle in Las
Vegas, but it's not too impressive on a par 4.
</P>
<P>
   Sages had cautioned that the key to survival on this 7,361-yard
goliath was not to dwell on a double bogey. Garcia didn't. He
didn't have time. He just kept piling them up _ five doubles or
worse, including three in a four-hole stretch from the ninth to the
12th. When he registered his lone birdie, on the par-5, 515-yard
14th, he probably didn't recognize what it was.
</P>
<P>
   After the round, the player who the day before had requested
that the media refer to him only by his first name preferred to be
anonymous. He initially refused interview requests, though three
hours later, he relented and assessed the disaster.
</P>
<P>
   ``Things started going badly with that 7,'' he said, showing
wisdom beyond his years. ``I was suffering.''
</P>
<P>
   If it's any consolation, he was hardly alone. The 89 didn't even
win the day's ghoul medal. That honor went to Prayad Marksaeng with
a nifty 20-over-par 91. And Tom Gillis also nosed out Garcia in
ineptitude with a 90. In all, 56 of the 156 golfers who teed off
shot 80 or above. The victims included defending champion Mark
O'Meara, who won't have to worry about packing the claret jug in
his luggage after his 83.
</P>
<P>
   But such is the regard for Garcia's precociousness that his
misery was considered a watershed. Advised of the 89, Colin
Montgomerie, who was thrilled to escape with a 74, said, ``There
you go. It proves it is very difficult.''
</P>
<P>
   Garcia insisted that great expectations were not his downfall.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't put too much pressure on myself,'' he said. ``What I
don't understand is that people complain about the US Open, and
they put the rough so high and the greens so hard (here). I
couldn't do anything. I couldn't swing the club, and on the 12th, I
almost popped it up. I don't think it was a case of coming down
from the clouds. I didn't need to _ I haven't been on any cloud.''
</P>
<P>
   Maybe not. But his score was sky-high.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
