<SLUG> BC-TEN-DAVIS-US-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
US SINGLES SQUAD ANNOUNCED AND SAMPRAS ISN'T ON IT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL MADDEN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BROOKLINE, Mass. _ Pete Sampras spoke noble words of being true
to his word and sensitive words of not wanting to step on any
American egos, while Tom Gullikson spoke a captain's words of team
spirit, of all for one and one for all.
</P>
<P>
   John Newcombe was a tad more blunt, Aussie blunt.
</P>
<P>
   ``No,'' said the captain of the Australian Davis Cup team, he
would not have made the decision the Americans did. ``And I
probably wouldn't like to be in (Gullikson's) shoes if we win,
either.''
</P>
<P>
   Eyebrows all across the tennis world were raised moments after
noon Thursday when umpire Stefan Fransson stood in front of the
ancient and majestic clubhouse of the Longwood Cricket Club and
announced the names of the competitors for Friday's opening singles
matches and those Sunday. Pete Sampras's name was not among them.
</P>
<P>
   Sampras will play only doubles, a rare diversion for him (his
world doubles ranking is 774th). Pedro Martinez volunteering for
middle relief in the World Series or Michael Jordan offering to be
sixth man in the NBA Finals or John Elway choosing to play just the
third quarter in the Super Bowl _ these scenarios only hint at the
magnitude of Sampras's decision.
</P>
<P>
   It was his decision, wasn't it? ``That's correct,'' said
Sampras.
</P>
<P>
   ``Pete and I privately talked about it,'' said Gullikson, ``and
we had a team meeting (at which) we had a lot of feedback from
everyone and everyone told me how they felt. It was a consensus.''
</P>
<P>
   Sampras's status had been lobbed back and forth the last five
weeks like a frayed practice ball. Would America's best play
singles? No, said Sampras time and again, doubles only because he
had watched from the comfort of home while Jim Courier and Todd
Martin were battling in England in the last round. Despite his
denials, however, the sentiment was that Sampras would end up
playing singles anyway. Sampras has to play singles, many figured,
as Sampras playing singles would be best for the US team. Time will
tell, was all Gullikson would say.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just didn't feel comfortable jumping on the bandwagon and
carrying the flag here,'' Sampras said Thursday when time finally
arrived to reveal to the tennis world his final decision. ``It's
Todd's show and Jim's show. They won an unbelievable tie (match) in
England; I don't think it was right for me to come here and play
singles.''
</P>
<P>
   So Sampras will be watching as Martin opens competition at noon
against rookie Lleyton Hewitt. Patrick Rafter, Australia's best,
then will meet Courier, who revels in Davis Cup competition.
</P>
<P>
   On Sunday, Martin is scheduled to meet Rafter and Courier to
take on Hewitt. Skeptical Aussies, though, openly suggest that it
might be Sampras, not Martin, meeting Rafter if the US is down
after Saturday's doubles. In that match, Sampras will pair with
Alex O'Brien against Sandon Stolle and Mark Woodforde.
</P>
<P>
   Though the first game of the first set is not until noon, the
gamesmanship is well under way. Newcombe and Rafter, for instance,
said they had believed until Wednesday that Sampras would be
playing singles but changed their minds at a Davis Cup dinner that
night, said Newcombe, ``when we got a feeling that he wasn't going
to.''
</P>
<P>
   How so?
</P>
<P>
   Because Sampras looked so relaxed.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was just the attitude they had,'' said Newcombe. ``You can
sort of tell if someone's going to play _ they have a nervous air
about them. But Pete looked very relaxed. And then I had some
inside information, but you'll have to kill me before you get it
out of me.''
</P>
<P>
   More gamesmanship.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the most important thing about playing doubles is that
I don't think Pete (Sampras) is as comfortable with playing
doubles,'' said Stolle. ``Obviously, he's a great player, but going
in, I mean, I much prefer to see him across the net in doubles than
in singles. I just can't see how he can walk out there and believe
he can play good doubles.''
</P>
<P>
   Added Woodforde: ``The fact that Pete is not a regular doubles
player could go against him.''
</P>
<P>
   Sampras is 3-1 in Davis Cup doubles.
</P>
<P>
   And even more gamesmanship.
</P>
<P>
   Both captains claimed to be pleased with the draw, which
determined that anxious rookie Hewitt (``I think I am too nervous
at the moment'') would be the Aussie representative in the first
match.
</P>
<P>
   Gullikson said the Hewitt-Martin matchup gives the US an ideal
chance for a quick jump, and added that the prospect of having
Courier go against the rookie in the fifth _ and possibly deciding
_ match is a pleasant one for the home side.
</P>
<P>
   Ridiculous, countered Newcombe. The Americans know they have to
win the first match, he said, ``and that puts a tremendous amound
of pressure on Todd (Martin). And knowing that he is playing and
Pete is not playing, and knowing that he is playing Lleyton _ on
paper he's supposed to beat him. So there will be some very anxious
moments for them in that first match. If we lose the first match
(with Rafter still to play), we are not going to be as worried as
they will be if they lose the first match.''
</P>
<P>
   Said Martin: ``I have played Lleyton once this year (in Sydney)
and it was a close match (a 6-3, 6-7, 6-4 Martin victory). In
Hewitt's opinion, the key to the match ``is that I am going to have
to be returning very well against Todd.''
</P>
<P>
   The spotlight, of course, will be on the Courier-Rafter match.
Rafter said his kick serve ``is working pretty well'' on the hard
court at Longwood. ``I had been trying it on the grass and
sometimes it worked and sometimes it didn't,'' he said. ``But I
know every time I do it on the hard court you get a good reaction,
and this court really takes it nicely.''
</P>
<P>
   Kick serve on or not, ``the one thing about Jim Courier is he
puts in 100 percent every single match he plays,'' said Rafter.
``Some guys deal with the pressure of Davis Cup play very well, and
Jim is one of those guys. He loves the whole thing of the Davis
Cup, and he is someone who is able to handle it better than anyone
else.''
</P>
<P>
   Courier is No. 41 and Rafter No. 2 in the latest world rankings.
But Courier said, ``Pat and I haven't played for a while, but I've
had good success against him.''
</P>
<P>
   Most of all, though, Courier wants Davis Cup play _ his pride
and joy _ to begin and distracting questions about Pete Sampras
playing singles to end.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
