<SLUG> BC-HOUSE-INS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOUSE LAWMAKERS SEEK TO REORGANIZE INS 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By JOHN C. HENRY 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ A bipartisan group of House members has revived
legislation designed to break up the Immigration and Naturalization
Service and assign its two major responsibilities to two new
bureaus within the Justice Department.
</P>
<P>
   Emboldened by reports that the Border Patrol apprehended and
released suspected killer Angel Maturino Resendez eight times in
the past 18 months, the lawmakers are recruiting co-sponsors for
the bill overhauling the 31,000-employee agency.
</P>
<P>
   The release of Maturino ``is just the latest outrage that's a
direct result of an agency at war with itself,'' said Rep.
Sylvestre Reyes, an El Paso Democrat and former Border Patrol
division chief who is among the legislation's co-sponsors.
</P>
<P>
   Maturino, one of the FBI's 10 Most Wanted, is a Mexican national
who went by the alias Rafael Resendez-Ramirez. He surrendered
Tuesday and is being held in the Harris County Jail in Houston in
connection with nine slayings beginning in August 1997.
</P>
<P>
   The INS-reorganization bill would create a Bureau of Immigration
Services within the Justice Department to process applications for
citizenship, visas, asylum and refugee status. A separate Bureau of
Immigration Enforcement would coordinate the Border Patrol,
port-of-entry inspections, detentions and deportations.
</P>
<P>
   ``This bill is about ensuring that our immigration system has
the infrastructure and record system in place to avoid another
Resendez-Ramirez case,'' Reyes said. ``Mismanagement has got us
into this situation, and we need to ensure that this never happens
again.''
</P>
<P>
   Similar legislation sponsored last year by Reyes and Rep. Harold
Rogers, R-Ky., got shoved aside by a Republican Congress bent on
impeaching President Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the INS, which is a part of the Justice Department,
has proposed its own reorganization, including separate offices to
administer immigration services and law enforcement. However, the
plan would keep the agency intact.
</P>
<P>
   Attorney General Janet Reno agreed that the INS has problems,
but agency officials are dealing with them. The reorganization bill
goes too far, she said. ``It's important to have it under one
roof,'' Reno said.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Lamar Smith, a San Antonio Republican and frequent critic
of the immigration agency, disagreed.
</P>
<P>
   ``The current INS resembles a car stranded by the side of the
road,'' said Smith, who chairs the House immigration subcommittee.
``Money intended for necessary repairs was spent to make it (the
INS) look shiny and new, but new paint can't hide the fact it is a
broken-down wreck.''
</P>
<P>
   Congress earmarked about $437 million for the agency this year
to catch up on a backlog of citizenship applications. A little over
a year ago, more than 2 million applications were awaiting INS
action. In the six months ending March 31, the agency has processed
461,543 naturalization applications, up 91 percent from the same
period a year earlier. The backlog currently is about 1.8 million.
</P>
<P>
   INS officials predict that by the end of September, the wait for
citizenship processing _ from the day an application is submitted
until the swearing-in ceremony _ will be cut from 23 months to
about 12. The goal is six months by September 2000. The number of
citizenship applications increased from 543,000 in 1994 to a record
1.57 million in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Smith has scheduled a hearing on the bill, which has no
comparable measure in the Senate, for June 29. He said more than 70
House members are co-sponsoring the INS reorganization bill.
</P>
<P>
   Another INS critic _ the American Immigration Lawyers
Association _ said the reorganization bill fails to address major
problems at the agency and would hinder enforcement and
adjudication of pending cases.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are concerned that under this scheme enforcement (functions
such as the Border Patrol) would receive funds allocated by
Congress, but adjudication would be forced to rely solely on user
fees,'' said Jeanne Butterfield, the organization's executive
director. ``That's how the INS wound up with its current
naturalization backlog of 1.8 million people and its nearly
three-year backlog in processing green-card applications.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
