<HEADLINE>
ANDERSON LOOKING GOOD AS DIERCKXSENS TAKES 11TH STAGE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Dierckxsens is cq)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SUSAN BICKELHAUPT  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAINT-ETIENNE, France _ Tyler Hamilton of Brookline, Mass.,
looks every bit like a casualty of the Tour de France.
</P>
<P>
   A bandage and bruise under his right eye is a reminder of the
crash he and three dozen other racers were in last Monday.
</P>
<P>
   He has fishnet bandages on his left knee and elbow from a spill
he and teammate Kevin Livingston took three days ago.
</P>
<P>
   But Hamilton insists that all is well, despite his
``souvenirs.''
</P>
<P>
   And why shouldn't it be? He's been riding strongly, and his US
Postal Service teammate Lance Armstrong has a firm lead and will
likely wear the winner's yellow jersey on the podium in Paris.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now I feel really good,'' said Hamilton, acknowledging that
the crash in the Tour's second stage, where he lost six minutes in
the standings after just two stages, hit him hard. He's now 19th,
more than 19 minutes behind Armstrong.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yeah, it mattered, it was pretty hard,'' said Hamilton, 28.
``But to be honest with you, we're focused on one rider. I could be
second right now and it wouldn't matter.''
</P>
<P>
   Armstrong has been saying all week that the winning spot isn't
locked up, and Hamilton agrees.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh, we've got a long way to go,'' he said. ``Things look good,
for now.''
</P>
<P>
   Things continued to look good for Armstrong in the 11th stage
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Belgian rider Ludo Dierckxsens won the 124-mile race in 4 hours
34 minutes 3 seconds, and Armstrong and the rest of his teammates,
as well as the rest of the leaders, rolled in more than 22 minutes
later.
</P>
<P>
   But that didn't make any difference in the standings. The Texan
held on to his lead of 7 minutes 47 seconds and for the fourth
stage in a row donned a fresh yellow jersey.
</P>
<P>
   The riders said goodbye to the mountains _ temporarily _ as they
started from the foot of Alpe d'Huez in the village of Le Bourg
d'Oisans to Saint-Etienne, once considered the French capital of
the bicycle industry.
</P>
<P>
   More hilly days are in store until the day off Monday, but it
will be nothing compared with what the riders face next week in the
Pyrenees.
</P>
<P>
   So the riders weren't inclined to exert themselves very much in
the final climb of the race 15 miles from the finish.
</P>
<P>
   Several riders set off at a fast speed of 32 miles per hour to
win a sprint for points 20 miles into the race, with the green
sprinter's jersey at stake.
</P>
<P>
   Australian Stuart O'Grady and German rider Erik Zabel are first
and second in the sprint standings, but it was Belgian Tom Steels
who surged ahead to capture the winner's six points.
</P>
<P>
   The rest of the race was left to the riders who are lower in the
standings to battle it out, while the bulk of the competitors were
content to stay back and stay together. Still, Armstrong and his
teammates rode near the front of the pack, to be ready to attack if
anyone initiated a break.
</P>
<P>
   It never happened. Seven riders built a lead of 2 minutes, then
14 minutes, then 17 minutes. But to show why Armstrong was so
blase, consider that the highest-placed rider of the group,
Kazakhstan's Alexandre Vinokourov, was 43 minutes behind Armstrong
in the standings.
</P>
<P>
   Dierckxsens escaped the small group on the final descent into
town and cruised over the finish line almost a minute and a half
ahead of Russian Dmitri Konyshev.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
