<SLUG> BC-US-BARAK-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BARAK SEEKS `NEW MOMENTUM' IN MIDEAST PEACE PROCESS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOHN DONNELLY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Saying it was time to ``inject new momentum'' into
the Middle East peace process, Ehud Barak Thursday made his
much-anticipated debut in America as Israel's new prime minister,
telling President Clinton he was ready to move ``on all tracks.''
</P>
<P>
   Barak, appearing in the White House Rose Garden with Clinton,
also said he wanted to move to a comprehensive settlement with the
Palestinians while signalling a tough line on the future of
existing Israeli settlements.
</P>
<P>
   In their private talk, Barak told Clinton, ``We are approaching
the moment of truth,'' according to a senior Israeli official.
Barak also was quoted as saying he was prepared for a ``painful
compromise'' with Syria over the Golan Heights, which Syria lost to
Israel in the 1967 war. ``Serious efforts'' to restart talks with
Syria would made in coming weeks, the Israeli official said.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton, according to a senior American official, called the
talks ``very, very positive'' and said he found Barak ``serious and
also reflective . . . a leader who will be scrupulous in living up
to his obligations.''
</P>
<P>
   In the Rose Garden, Clinton vowed to Barak that ``America will
walk with you, ready to help in any way we can'' in future peace
talks. But Barak said the Americans could take more of a back seat
now.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think that the United States can contribute to the process
more as facilitator than as kind of policemen, judge and arbitrator
at the same time,'' Barak said. ``This was the tradition when
Yitzhak Rabin was leading the peace process.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton said it was perhaps natural for the United States to
take a less active role. In a pointed remark directed toward
Barak's predecessor, Clinton said that tenure of Prime Minister
Benjamin Netanyahu ``the bonds of trust and the lines of
communication had become so frayed that we were in danger of losing
the peace process.''
</P>
<P>
   Now, Clinton said, direct contacts can begin again. Reflecting
the administration's strong optimism toward prospects for Middle
East peace, Clinton said:
</P>
<P>
   ``As we have seen before here at this house, as Israelis,
Palestinians, Egyptians and Jordanians have come together, what at
first seems unlikely, even impossible, can actually become reality
when the will for peace is strong.''
</P>
<P>
   Barak's opening of private talks with Clinton, which continued
with a dinner Thursday night at Camp David, was seen by the
administration as a way of going back to the past when Rabin struck
historic deals with the Palestinans and Jordanians.
</P>
<P>
   In their opening statements, Clinton and Barak both invoked the
name of the late Israeli leader, who was gunned down in November
1995 by a Jewish religious extremist, an assassination that led to
the crippling of peace talks.
</P>
<P>
   Rabin was Barak's mentor and Clinton's friend, a warrior who
turned peacemaker, a gruff sort who came to the White House in
September 1993 and signed the historic Oslo accords with
Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat. At that signing also came the
defining symbol of new hope when Arafat outstretched his hand, and
Rabin, with Clinton holding his elbow, shook it.
</P>
<P>
   ``If your mentor, Yitzhak Rabin, were here today,'' Clinton said
to Barak, ``I believe he would be very gratified seeing the
leadership of his cherished nation in your most capable hands.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton and his seasoned Middle East team know Barak well as an
aide to Rabin. But Barak as leader is something else entirely, and
there is apprehension he will balk at fulfilling Israel's
commitments in a deal made last fall at the Wye Plantation in
Maryland.
</P>
<P>
   The Americans also know little of the handful of advisers who
surround Barak, with the notable exception of ex-Mossad spymaster
Danny Yatom, who met with Clinton's aides while the two leaders
talked.
</P>
<P>
   The Wye peace deal involves a series of land-for-security
arrangements with the Palestinians. The Palestinians want the deal
upheld, which would end with them in control of 40 percent of the
West Bank and Gaza.
</P>
<P>
   Barak Thursday indicated he would move ahead on the Wye deal,
but slowly.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is the need to combine the implementation of Wye with
the moving forward of the permanent status agreement,'' Barak said.
``It could be this way: first Wye, then final status. It could be
this way, but only through an agreement with Arafat after mutual,
open, frank, and direct discussions.''
</P>
<P>
   Barak, who in his first week in office met with Arafat, Egyptian
President Hosni Mubarak, Jordan's King Abdullah and Turkey's
president, Suleyman Demirel, said he was open to the idea of
meeting Syrian President Hafez Assad.
</P>
<P>
   Barak wants to withdraw Israeli troops from southern Lebanon, a
deal that would require Syrian, and perhaps Iranian, agreement to
rein in Hezbollah fighters in Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
   On meeting Assad, Barak said, ``I hope we will be able to meet.
It takes two to tango. I am ready, the arena is ready, maybe the
dancing instructor is ready. We have to find opportunity and
begin.''
</P>
<P>
   Barak also addressed the contentious issue of Jewish
settlements, fortified communities in the midst of Palestinian
society in the West Bank.
</P>
<P>
   He said the issue of the settlements will be wrapped into the
final status talks with the Palestinians, but he said that most
settlers would remain in their homes in any deal.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not going to build new ones,'' the Israeli leader said.
``I'm not going to dismantle any one of them. Israeli citizens are
living in them. They came to these places, almost all of them,
through an approval of the Israeli government; we are responsible
for them.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
