<HEADER>
A1793 &Cx1f; tth-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TV-GVSE-SPI &LR;      07-15 0532
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-GVSE-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`GVSE' STARS BATTLE BAD GUYS, BAD SCRIPT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JOHN LEVESQUE  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Early in the premiere episode of ``GvsE,'' Richard Brooks'
character says, ``There's a fine line between cool and stupid.''
</P>
<P>
   How very true. Strangely ironic, then, that ``GvsE'' should
cross the line without even slowing for the speed bump. It ends up
so far inside the stupid zone that it'll take all the king's horses
and all the king's Mensas to bring it back.
</P>
<P>
   The betting here is that co-creators Jonas and Josh Pate pulled
a few muscles, or at the very least suffered severe cramping,
trying so hard to be cool. Better if they had spent less time
mimicking the dark humor of ``Pulp Fiction'' and more time focusing
on story development. We all might feel less cool, but the show,
premiering Sunday on USA Network, would probably make more sense.
</P>
<P>
   ``GvsE'' means good vs. evil. Brooks, who played Brian Robinette
in the first season of ``Law &AMP; Order,'' plays Henry McNeil, a dead
guy who has been given his life back as long as he agrees to work
for the Almighty Corps in its battle against the devil and his
disciples.
</P>
<P>
   If he's rotten to the Corps or breaks any of its rules _ no
contact with family members, no sex, no Faustian deals _ the game
is over. Further complicating matters is the overwhelming mortality
of the Corps' recruits: They have no superpowers, so if any of them
were to go one on one with, say, a crosstown bus, the bus would
win.
</P>
<P>
   The bad guys, who have made deals with the devil, seem to be
better equipped. They have little horns and are called morlocks,
which strikes the ear as ``more lox,'' suggesting the devil is in
the details of a Jewish deli. Alas, morlocks cannot be subdued by
cream cheese alone. It takes a sharp knife specifically designed
for dispatching demons, but which also looks ideal for slicing
bagels.
</P>
<P>
   McNeil's partner in this morlock-hunting expedition is Chandler
Smythe (Clayton Rohner), a recently dead reporter who learns that
working for the Corps is the only way he'll ever make it
``upstairs.'' Who knew the penance of purgatory involved bounty
hunting?
</P>
<P>
   Smythe and McNeil, of course, are oddball partners from the
get-go, but the story moves so quickly _ as if edited by MTV _ that
the viewer never gets to develop an attachment. Quick cuts and
humorous asides dominate, rendering the enthusiastic performances
of Brooks and Rohner a disjointed chain of recitations.
Intermittent narration by football great Deacon Jones is supposed
to add a sarcastic touch, but it's more helpful as a primer on the
rules of this bizarre game.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, no one explains the scene in which Smythe and
McNeil allow an old woman to choke to death for no apparent reason.
What's up with that? If these are the good guys, this Corps may
have a devil of a time keeping its recruits semper fi.
</P>
<P>
   GvsE. One-hour comedy/thriller series about two undercover
agents working for good against the forces of evil. Starring
Richard Brooks and Clayton Rohner. Premieres Sunday at 8 p.m., USA
Network. Parental guideline rating: TV-PG.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: C
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
