<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-BRUINS-TAYLOR-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TAYLOR CASHES IN WITH RANGERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By NANCY L. MARRAPESE  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON -- During his time here, Tim Taylor gave an honest effort
during every shift, every period, and every game. Thursday, he gave
an honest assessment of why he's no longer a Bruin.
</P>
<P>
   Taylor, who agreed to terms on a four-year, $5.8 million deal
with the New York Rangers, said his reason for leaving Boston was
simple.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some players will lie and say it's not about money but it is
about money,'' said the 30-year-old center who played two seasons
here. ``I understand I can't play forever. I played a few years in
the minors, where I felt I missed out on an opportunity to make
some money, so obviously I came where the money was being
offered.''
</P>
<P>
   Taylor, an unrestricted free agent, said there were other teams
that were interested but wasn't one of them. He said he never
received an offer from the Bruins, who paid the center a base
salary of $675,000 last season.
</P>
<P>
   ``When it came down to it, I think the Rangers were the ones,''
he said during a conference call. ``There were a lot of things that
come into it but obviously money was the biggest one. I wanted an
Original Six team and I wanted to stay in the Eastern Conference. I
saw the team was building and they're going to have a big future,
and I'm hoping to be a big part of it. It comes down to money, and
I owed it to myself and my family to take the best offer. My
decision was made for me.''
</P>
<P>
   In his first year with Boston, after being plucked off waivers
from the Detroit Red Wings, with whom he won a Stanley Cup, Taylor
was a strong presence on the Bruins' top checking line with right
wing Rob DiMaio and then-rookie P.J. Axelsson. He scored 20 goals
and 31 points in 79 games and was effective at shutting down
opposing teams' top lines.
</P>
<P>
   Last season, Taylor was hindered by injuries, especially a balky
ankle, and was limited to 49 games. He said his time with DiMaio
and Axelsson and the significant role given to him by coach Pat
Burns helped him reach the financial status he has attained with
the Rangers.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a huge steppingstone for me,'' he said. ``Those guys
meant a great deal to me. They're two great players and obviously
the system we played benefited me as well.''
</P>
<P>
   Taylor said he felt as early as the end of the year that he
wouldn't be in Boston anymore. Despite the Bruins not offering him
a new deal, he doesn't harbor any ill will. He said it's just a
business decision.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wasn't disappointed in the organization,'' Taylor said. ``I
was happy with them. I don't feel they owe me anything. I felt this
was a good situation for me. I wanted to maybe come to a team
that's going to really contend for the Cup.''
</P>
<P>
   Bruins assistant general manager Mike O'Connell seemed resigned
that Taylor was going to be offered more money and that Boston, as
was true with Dave Reid and Dave Poulin before Taylor, just wasn't
prepared to go that far. In addition, management believes another
player _ such as Joe Thornton or a prospect from Providence _ could
step into the role.
</P>
<P>
   ``I figured that just for the fact that we never received one
offer,'' said Taylor. ``I think maybe they thought it was going to
be out of their range and they thought they could move someone else
into that role for a cheaper price.''
</P>
<P>
   DiMaio spoke with Taylor and wished him the best, but couldn't
help being upset at losing his friend and linemate. When DiMaio
gave up his chance at unrestricted free agency to sign a new
three-year deal with the Bruins last summer, he was assured the
club would do its level best to keep the core of young talent
together. DiMaio said he finds the Taylor signing a tough pill to
swallow.
</P>
<P>
   ``Timmy is a good friend and I felt, a real big part of this
hockey team,'' said DiMaio. ``They might think it's very easy to
replace him but it's not. You can put another body there, but the
grit and determination he brings and playing in pain like he did in
the playoffs, you don't replace that kind of thing. I'm very
disappointed he's gone.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously, they have their own idea of where they want to go
in the organization and I don't know if Timmy was part of that. I
thought he was going to be a big part of it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
