<SLUG> BC-BOMBING-PUERTO-RICO-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NAVY DEFENDS PRACTICE BOMBING OF ISLAND OFF PUERTO RICO 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By STEWART M. POWELL  
 c.1999 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The Navy and Marine Corps launched a campaign
Thursday to persuade President Clinton to permit resumption of
live-fire training on the Puerto Rican island of Vieques, three
months after a bombing accident killed a civilian employed by the
Navy.
</P>
<P>
   The accident has inflamed pro-independence sentiment across the
U.S. commonwealth and prompted several dozen protesters to occupy
the bombing range, located 8 miles east of Puerto Rico.
</P>
<P>
   Navy Secretary Richard Danzig released an inch-thick report
justifying the need for continued training on Vieques, where the
Navy and Marines have prepared for every major U.S. military
operation since World War II, including the Persian Gulf War and
the bombing campaign against Serbia.
</P>
<P>
   ``From my standpoint, the main message of today is from a
national security standpoint this is an important and not a
replaceable site,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Danzig released the report on the eve of a meeting by a
four-member Pentagon review panel appointed at the request of the
president to review the need for continued live-fire training on
the 22-mile-long island and to explore possible alternative sites.
</P>
<P>
   The panel is due to report to the president by Aug. 2.
</P>
<P>
   Carlos Romero-Barcelo, Puerto Rico's non-voting representative
to Congress, and Rep. Jose E. Serrano, D-N.Y., the most senior
member of Congress born in Puerto Rico, plan to urge the
four-member panel on Friday to permanently end Navy operations on
the island and turn it over to the Puerto Rican government.
</P>
<P>
   The island has 9,300 residents living at least 10 miles from the
bomb and artillery ``impact site'' at the eastern end of the
island.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are telling you what we genuinely think without regard to
politics,'' Danzig told a Pentagon news conference in releasing the
report.
</P>
<P>
   Danzig said the Navy study examined 18 other sites for
comparable training and concluded that training must continue at
the 24,000-acre range on Vieques. The study was compiled by Navy
Vice Adm. William Fallon, commander of the Atlantic fleet, and
Marine Lt. Gen. Peter Pace, commander of 92,000 Marines assigned to
Atlantic operations.
</P>
<P>
   Danzig suspended live-fire training on April 19 after a Marine
Corps' FA-18 pilot mistakenly dropped two 500-pound bombs about a
mile off-target during night training, killing security guard David
Sanes Rodriguez, 35, a civilian employee of the Navy.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The military officers told the news conference that Vieques
offered the lone site on the East Coast to enable combined arms
training involving naval gunfire, aerial bombardment, artillery
fire and maneuvers by Marine troops.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have an obligation to our nation and to our people to train
them to be most effective if they are called upon to go into
combat,'' Fallon said. ``If we don't do this, we put our people at
personal risk.''
</P>
<P>
   Pace declared: ``My responsibility to their mothers and fathers
is to ensure that when we send them overseas, I have given them the
best training I can.''
</P>
<P>
   The officials signaled some flexibility as the Navy and Marines
try to allay the political firestorm in Puerto Rico and the
political pressure being brought to bear on the White House.
</P>
<P>
   Puerto Rico, with a population of 3.8 million, came under U.S.
jurisdiction during the Spanish-American War in 1898.
</P>
<P>
   The president is due to make a decision after receiving the
report from the four-member Pentagon review panel that includes
only one non-defense official _ retired Rep. Lee Hamilton, D-Ind.,
a former chairman of the House Foreign Relations Committee.
</P>
<P>
   Danzig said the Navy is holding out the prospect of a ``stronger
partnership'' with Puerto Rico to bolster the economic fortunes of
Vieques by helping to lower ferry costs, improving the island
airstrip and pier and freeing government property for economic
development.
</P>
<P>
   Fallon said carrier-based combat air wings that ordinarily drop
about 350 bombs on Vieques to prepare for overseas deployment could
shift a greater share of the bombing to a range at Fallon, Nev.
</P>
<P>
   Pace said the combat-ready Marine Expeditionary Unit of about
2,500 Marines that accompanies an 12-ship combat battle group
assembled around an aircraft carrier usually fires 600 rounds of
artillery and 500 mortar rounds to prepare for overseas operations.
Pace said the Marines would see if the number of rounds could be
reduced.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Stewart Powell can be reached via e-mail at
stewart(at)hearstdc.com.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
