<SLUG> BC-TIMESCO-ABUZZ-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TIMES CO. BUYS ABUZZ'S BEEHIVE PRODUCT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By HIAWATHA BRAY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Everybody's an expert in something. Now The New York Times Co.
is hoping to tap this vast store of knowledge, by purchasing a
Cambridge, Mass. firm whose software creates on-line communities of
expertise.
</P>
<P>
   The Times will pay an undisclosed sum to acquire Abuzz
Technologies Inc., makers of a knowledge management system called
Beehive. The product is used by businesses to create profiles of
workers that reveal each person's areas of expertise. It then
fields e-mail queries, forwarding each message to the worker most
likely to know the answer.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we are hoping to do is to bring this to the Internet,''
said Times spokeswoman Lisa Carparelli.
</P>
<P>
   Recently, The Times Co., which owns The Boston Globe, merged all
its on-line properties, including the Boston.com Web site, into a
new business entity called Times Company Digital. The company plans
to use the Beehive technology on its various sites to turn readers
into a community of experts, freely sharing their knowledge with
all comers.
</P>
<P>
   Such free exchange of information is routine on the Internet,
where chat rooms and message boards are crammed with visitors
seeking advice. But finding someone who really knows the answers
can be a frustrating, hit-or-miss exercise. The Beehive technology
aims to improve results by targeting queries directly to the right
people.
</P>
<P>
   ``The appeal of Abuzz is it's very user-friendly,'' said
Marianne Hedin, a research manager at International Data Corp. in
Framingham. ``You can use it through e-mail, which everybody uses.
You don't have to learn an additional tool.''
</P>
<P>
   The Times plans to take advantage of its large base of
knowledgeable, upscale readers.
</P>
<P>
   ``The New York Times has such an incredible community,'' said
Patty Purcell, vice president of strategic marketing and customer
operations for Abuzz. ``They've described it to us as the best of
the best.''
</P>
<P>
   It's not clear how many visitors to the various Times Web sites
will want to take part in the system as experts. They'd have to
provide a good deal of information about themselves to the Beehive
system. This will enable it to identify likely experts, but it will
also mean experts give up a measure of privacy.
</P>
<P>
   Still, if the Times can persuade enough of its Web readers to
take part in the system, the Abuzz technology could provide users
with an on-line source of instant expertise.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
