A1806 &Cx1f; tad-z
r t &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TRAVEL-LONDONCOVENT18     07-15 0401
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-LONDONCOVENT18-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Lively Covent Garden pillar of community
 &HT;    EDS: Embargoed for Sunday, July 18.
 &HT;    By Dan Hulbert
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON _ You could make a case that the longest-running show in
London _ 340 years and counting _ is going on in front of the
portico of St. Paul's Church, Covent Garden. Though it has been
interrupted quite a few times by rain.
</P>
<P>
   It's street theater. On a recent afternoon, a man juggled three
flaming batons on the cobblestones while cracking jokes, cheered by
crowds on the overhanging deck of a nearby beer garden. Behind him,
on the wall of the 1798 edifice (which anchors the west side of the
Covent Garden marketplace), a plaque marks the point where the
puppet Punch was first observed in England by diarist Samuel Pepys
in 1662, thwacking everyone who tried to share his open-air stage.
Today the Garden's annual Maye Faire is awash with puppet shows.
</P>
<P>
   Chances are that St. Paul's massive Tuscan columns, now smudged
by soot and graffiti, will look familiar if you've ever seen ``My
Fair Lady'' on stage or screen. The opening scene of the musical
and its source play, Shaw's ``Pygmalion'' (1913), is set here. As
flower girl Eliza Doolittle bawls her sales pitch, Professor Henry
Higgins peers around a column, jotting her Cockney elocutions
before he teaches her to speak ``like an English lady.''
</P>
<P>
   A farmers market in the 19th century, Covent Garden is now a
great cobblestoned hive of boutiques _ one specializing in
beautiful Victorian toys _ craft stalls and cafes. The squawks of
poultry and vendors have been replaced by the sounds of music (on a
recent afternoon, an elegant Peruvian band) and various buskers.
Though American chain stores have squeezed in a few tentacles
(inflatable batting cages are the rage!), the square, or piazza, is
surrounded by such handsome old buildings that its character is not
in danger.
</P>
<P>
   Shaw developed his socialist sympathies from encounters with
struggling workers here. He'd be dumbfounded by the gentrification
(a store called Accessorize), but would still approve of the
ever-roisterous spirit. Backpacking college students sprawl against
Eliza's old pillar at St. Paul's, soaking up the scene.
</P>
<P>
   _ Dan Hulbert writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-15-99 2004EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990715.0352 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-15 20:04 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1807 &Cx1f; tad-z
r t &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TRAVEL-LONDONSAVOY18-     07-15 0417
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-LONDONSAVOY18-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Theater and hotel were ground zero for theatrical adventure
 &HT;    Eds: Embargoed for Sunday, July 18.
 &HT;    By Dan Hulbert
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON _ Great performances, illicit rendezvous, theatrical
deals struck over caviar _ it's all there under the stainless
steel, art deco marquee that forms the entrance to the Savoy
Theatre and Savoy Hotel.
</P>
<P>
   The original theater (the first to use electric lights) was
built in 1881, and the hotel in 1903, by producer Richard D'Oyly
Carte with profits from the operettas of W.S. Gilbert and Arthur
Sullivan. A bronze bust of the latter stands in the Embankment
Gardens between the hotel and the Thames. Actor Edward Petherbridge
(``Lord Peter Wimsey'' on PBS' ``Mystery!''), who leads occasional
theater tours for London Walks, informs, ``The topless woman at
Sullivan's feet is his muse. The Victorians would never have
allowed a pose of such abandon if she were a mere mortal.''
</P>
<P>
   If you look up at the hotel from the bust (Sullivan's, that is),
you can see the windows of Noel Coward's old suite, second floor
center.
</P>
<P>
   The Gilbert &AMP; Sullivan run continued until 1907. A struggling
actor named Laurence Olivier turned down a 1929 ``Journey's End''
role that instead made a star of Colin Clive, better known now as
the mad doc (``It's a ... liiiiiiiive!'') in the movie
``Frankenstein.'' The theater got the deco makeover in 1930 and
thrives today.
</P>
<P>
   It was in the hotel's predecessor, the Savoy Palace, that editor
Frank Harris gathered some of Oscar Wilde's friends for an 1895
dinner that would today be called an intervention. Their mission:
to persuade Wilde to be discreet in his relationships, and back off
the libel suit that further exposed his homosexuality and brought
his downfall. Harris writes in his Wilde biography that the
playwright was unmoved, so merry that he coined the epigram, ``Work
is the curse of the drinking classes.''
</P>
<P>
   Stepping down from the hotel's outer lobby of red-and-beige
veined marble, into the luxuriously sprawling lounge of moss green
and dusty rose (sofas set back into discreet nooks), you feel as if
you're making an entrance in a Coward play. You sense the need for
a martini as hand prop, and no wonder: The cocktail was reportedly
invented in the American Bar that you just passed on the left.
</P>
<P>
   _ Dan Hulbert writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
