<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Southern happenings
 &HT;    By Paula Crouch Thrasher
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QR;  Philadephia, Miss. _ The 50th annual Choctaw Indian Fair,
today through Saturday on the Choctaw Pearl River Reservation,
includes cultural foods, dancing, arts and crafts and stickball
games. 601-650-1537.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Key West, Fla. _ Hemingway Days Festival Friday through July
25, honoring the American author, includes a look-alike contest,
writers workshop and conference and fishing clinics. 305-294-2918
or www.hemingwaydays.com.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Kennedy Space Center _ The 30th anniversary of the Apollo 11
mission, America's first moon landing, will be celebrated Saturday
at the Kennedy Space Center Visitor Complex. Events include ``A
Look Back at Apollo'' with astronauts Buzz Aldrin, Wally Schirra,
Walt Cunningham, Charlie Duke and Gene Cernan and a '60s concert
featuring bands of the launch era, including the Supremes and the
Byrds. Also, unveiling of the U.S. Postal Service's ``Moon Walks on
the Moon'' stamp. 407-452-2121 or www.KennedySpaceCenter.com.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Daytona Beach, Fla. _ The Florida International Festival July
23-Aug. 14 features six concerts by the internationally renowned
London Symphony Orchestra along with 60 other events by top names
in jazz, dance, comedy and theater. The series opens July 23 with
Hal Holbrook performing ``Mark Twain Tonight!''; his wife, Dixie
Carter, presents ``An Evening of Cabaret'' July 24-25. Also
upcoming: Michael Doucet and Beausoleil, July 28; Clarence
``Gatemouth'' Brown, July 29; and Martha Graham Dance Ensemble,
Aug. 3-4. 904-257-7790
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Boone, N.C. _ The Appalachian Summer Festival, through July,
includes nearly 30 music, dance and theater performances at
Appalachian State University. An outdoor concert with fireworks
Saturday will feature Mary Chapin Carpenter. Also upcoming: The
Paul Taylor Dance Company, July 20; Celtic Music Celebration, July
21; and Nnenna Freelon and her Quartet, July 29. Tickets:
1-800-841-2787 or online at appsummer.appstate.edu.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Asheville, N.C. _ The Craft Fair of the Southern Highlands is
Thursday through Sunday at the Asheville Civic Center. The fair
showcases works by the 700-member Southern Highland Craft Guild and
presents demonstrations in various media as well as live mountain
music and storytelling. 828-298-7928.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Asheville, N.C. _ The Southern Highland Craft Guild presents
``Buck-Os and Lady Misses,'' a dramatic musical presentation of
stories about life in the Blue Ridge Mountains by North Carolina
poet laureate Fred Chappell, at the Folk Art Center: 7:30 p.m.
Friday-Saturday; 3:30 p.m. Sunday. $10; under 10 free.
828-298-7928.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Highlands, N.C. _ The Highlands Playhouse presents the farce
``Cash on Delivery'' through Sunday, the musical ``Crazy for You''
July 21-Aug. 8 and the comedy ``Take This Man'' Aug. 11-22.
828-526-2695.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Cartersville, Ga. _ The 16th annual Bartow County Saddle Club
Championship Rodeo Friday and Saturday features traditional rodeo
events plus pony rides and a petting zoo at the Saddle Club Arena
off Burnt Hickory Road. 706-602-2234.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Thomasville, Ga. _ The Thomasville Cultural Center presents
its 10th annual Summer Showcase, a juried show featuring 67 works
by artists living within a 275-mile radius of Thomasville. Also,
works by Dick Inman, whose oil paintings depict people and animals
from faraway places. Through July 25. 912-226-0588 or
www.tccarts.org.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Young Harris, Ga. _ The 11th season of the state's official
historical drama, ``The Reach of Song,'' continues through Aug. 22
and features local musicians and cast members in a celebration of
the Appalachian spirit and a tribute to mountain poet Byron Herbert
Reece. 1-800-262-7664.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Madison _ Madison Fest '99 July 22-25 combines the 18th annual
Madison Theatre Festival, focusing on the works of author C.S.
Lewis, and the Madison Fest Arts and Crafts Show, a jured show
(July 24 only). Also performances, home tours, carriage rides,
food, music, classic car cruises and novelty car and tractor
displays. 1-800-709-7406.
</P>
<P>
   _Paula Crouch Thrasher writes for the Atlanta
Journal-Constitution.
</P>
