<SLUG> BC-MULES18-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    The slide rules during dog days
 &HT;    EDS: Embargoed for Sunday, July 18.
 &HT;    By Alma E. Hill
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Dog days got you sniffing around for a way to cool your heels
this summer? Then consider the stylishness and simplicity of the
hottest and coolest trend in footwear: the mule.
</P>
<P>
   The toe can be open or closed, the heel high or low, the look
sporty or comfy. This backless shoe that slides on your foot is
turning up in every style, color and fabric imaginable.
</P>
<P>
   Women have worn mules for decades. But the shoe came back on the
scene in the 1970s when Candies slides were popular and re-emerged
again in the 1990s. Now men have joined the mule team by sporting
versions that are masculine enough for a guy and sexy enough to
merit a double take.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no question it's a hot summer look,'' said Susan
Forehand, fashion and public relations director at Saks Fifth
Avenue in Phipps Plaza. ``A person who buys that shoe has a high
awareness of what's happening in fashion.''
</P>
<P>
   To look good in mules, obey a few crucial rules:
</P>
<P>
   Never wear them with hose or socks, and don't put them on crusty
feet that are begging for a pedicure. (At the very least, buff your
heels and trim your toenails.)
</P>
<P>
   Women can slide them on with capri pants or cropped slacks,
ankle-length skirts and dresses, or laid-back beachwear.
</P>
<P>
   Men's mules go well with cargo pants, walking shorts or
pleatless slacks.
</P>
<P>
   ``What makes the shoe look new this season is the pant you put
with it,'' Forehand says. ``That makes the statement.''
</P>
<P>
   But fashion experts say there's one place the versatile mule
doesn't belong _ in the boardroom.
</P>
<P>
   ``For a dress down Friday situation it's certainly appropriate.
But for more traditional businesses, there are other
alternatives,'' advises Jill Hinson, fashion director for Nordstrom
stores.
</P>
<P>
   Alma E. Hill writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
