</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-LONDON-THEATER18-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Rub elbows with past and present in the city rich with
theatrical secrets, characters and scenes around every corner
 &HT;    Eds: Embargoed for Sunday, July 18.
 &HT;    By Dan Hulbert
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON _ When the theater lover makes a pilgrimage to this most
stage-struck metropolis, it's a two-for-one deal. Enjoy an exciting
present _ bask in a glorious past.
</P>
<P>
   Even more than painting is to Paris, or music to Vienna, theater
is the steady flame of London's spirit, burning as bright today as
it did 100 or 400 years ago. With just a few breaks in the action,
the torch has passed proudly from Shakespeare to Congreve to
Garrick to Kean to Shaw to Olivier to the current galaxy of Michael
Gambon, Judi Dench, Anthony Sher, Trevor Nunn, Fiona Shaw. ... The
only problem is trying to decide how much time you should spend in
a theater seat and how much on your feet, taking in the great
open-air show of venerable playhouses, smoke-cured pubs, benevolent
theater ghosts (don't laugh _ there are still sightings) and mossy
monuments to artists of yore.
</P>
<P>
   Ah, so many centuries, so little time.
</P>
<P>
   You can always, though, experience past and present in a single
stroke.
</P>
<P>
   Let's say you're at the 1903 Albery Theatre watching ``Plenty,''
David Hare's still-scathing 1978 play about an England spiritually
numbed by affluence, starring the stunning Cate Blanchett, who
shone onscreen as young queen ``Elizabeth.'' Your eye wanders up
past the chandelier to the carving of a lyre held by angels over
the stage, and you recall that Sir John Gielgud called it one of
the most ``poetic'' bits of decor in London. It was in this house,
then called the New Theatre, that Gielgud in 1935 famously
alternated the roles of Romeo and Mercutio with Laurence Olivier,
and Gielgud grew quite jealous of the more dashing actor.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking of friendly rivalries, let's say you step across the
alley to Salisbury's pub. In the mellow ambience of red plush and
frosted glass, you're debating the provocative ``Plenty'' with your
companion when you notice an empty corner booth. Two ghosts come
slowly into focus: Olivier and Ralph Richardson, deep in
conversation. The old pals, who called each other Larry and Cocky,
lunched here often during their stewardship of the Old Vic troupe,
which had a legendary residence at the New when the Vic playhouse
suffered bomb damage during World War II.
</P>
<P>
   Olivier recalled one of those Salisbury lunches as tense but
funny. He had signed up to play Lear for the same reason Richardson
claimed dibs on Cyrano: as a pre-emptive strike. Each grabbed the
role that he knew the other man craved, and would surely play
triumphantly. Larry kept needling, Cocky refused to ``swap.''
Reviews suggest that Richardson got the better end of the gambit.
</P>
<P>
   Such are the scenes that, with a little imagination, play out
among the streets, lobbies and courtyards of London's theater
land.Dan Hulbert writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
