<HEADER>
A1815 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SIBLEY-COLUMN16-COX     07-15 0533
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SIBLEY-COLUMN16-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Bounty of gifts helps you walk away from pain
 &HT;    By Celestine Sibley
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   We had a family emergency. My daughter, who should have been
hoeing the garden or washing the dog, was busy having a stroke _
the kind of something or other that goes whindering off to your
brain, scaring you to death.
</P>
<P>
   We packed up nightgowns and books and television tapes and
hurried to the hospital. She had no business being in precarious
health, I told her. It was my time. So we decided to go in tandem,
me in one room, her just down the hall.
</P>
<P>
   She couldn't move parts of her body, paralysis, they said. I
could move everything, and when I got home, I found I had been
endowed with a splendid collection of treasures. My kitchen table
held a See Rock City birdhouse, a spirit lifter if there ever was
one. My hands lifted it, my heart soared.
</P>
<P>
   But best of all, there was this marvelous walking stick. No, I
don't want a walking stick. I pride myself on using my own two feet
and such legs as they are. But they have acted funny lately,
catching on carpet, stumbling on small, innocuous blades of grass,
kicking my dog in his sleeping side.
</P>
<P>
   So my friend, former Gov. Ernest Vandiver, decided to take
matters in hand. I saw Ernie and Betty at the Capitol party for
Pete Wheeler of Veterans Services fame. Ernie was carrying a
splendid wood walking stick with an artfully shaped marble handle.
</P>
<P>
   ``Send you one,'' he said. And he did.
</P>
<P>
   It's as fine a walking stick as I ever saw, built in the
mountains in 1850, I think, and shaped and very comfortable to hold
on to. I had acquired a couple of other sticks recently. One had a
lithesome body curved around it _ just like a snake, though my
friend Nan said it was a vine, not a snake. (I saw a head and a
mouth and didn't believe her.)
</P>
<P>
   The other is a copper metal number, which my grandson said he
picked up at a yard sale, knowing I would value it more than
something store-bought. It happened that he did get a store-bought
one and charged it to me. But it can't hold a candle to the
beautiful mountain marble one, and I fully expect to outwalk
everybody going and coming with this one.
</P>
<P>
   The good thing about a sudden onset of unexpected illness, as
most Southerners know, is the bounty that seems to grow on your
kitchen table in your absence. Birdhouse, walking stick, ham,
beans, cake, a beautiful spill of the prettiest tomatoes of the
season, even muffins and breakfast bread. Even bottles of the
finest beer to drink.
</P>
<P>
   It's a bit like all-day-sing-with-dinner-on-the-ground, although
we miss the singing and the preaching. I suppose the habit of
gift-giving is one of the imperishable graces of our society.
</P>
<P>
   I hope it is, because with illness striking families
unexpectedly, it's lovely to have ease and surprise strike too. I
think my daughter's health is going to be all right; I certainly
plan not to be talked into anything worse than slow walking. How
could I, with such a splendid marble-topped helper?
</P>
<P>
   Celestine Sibley writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
