<P>
   For Friday:
</P>
<P>
   POLITICAL NEWS (``p'' category)
</P>
<P>
   BUSH-2000 (Waterloo, Iowa) _ Texas Gov. George W. Bush says he
will forgo federal matching funds for his presidential campaign.
That means he can ignore spending limits in bellwether states like
Iowa and New Hampshire. Bush raised more than $37 million in four
months, swamping rivals in both the Republican and Democratic
parties. By CRAGG HINES.
</P>
<P>
   BUSH-MONEY (Austin, Texas) _ Texas Gov. George W. Bush has
raised so much money for his White House campaign that the rules
just don't apply to him anymore. His opponents and others worried
about democracy are gnashing teeth over what they see as a
perversion of the process. By R.G. RATCLIFFE.
</P>
<P>
   HILLARY-CLINTON (Washington) _ First Lady Hillary Clinton,
vowing to ``learn how I can be helpful'' in the Middle East peace
process, joins President Clinton in hosting an intimate dinner for
Israeli Prime Minister Ehud Barak at Camp David. The get-together
could prove useful in her New York Senate campaign. By STEWART M.
POWELL. (Also filed in the ``w'' category.)
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON NEWS (``w'' category)
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-BARAK (Washington) _ President Clinton and new Israeli
Prime Minister Ehud Barak promise to breathe new life into the
Mideast peace process. By NANCY MATHIS.
</P>
<P>
   BOMBING-PUERTO-RICO (Washington) _ The Navy and the Marine Corps
launch a campaign to persuade President Clinton to permit
resumption of live-fire training on Puerto Rico's island of
Vieques. The training was stopped three months ago after Marine
pilots killed a Puerto Rican civilian in a bombing mishap.
Meanwhile, some lawmakers are urging the Pentagon to end the
exercises permanently. By STEWART M. POWELL. (Already filed.)
</P>
<P>
   PATIENTS-RIGHTS (Washington) _ Senate Republicans reject a
Democratic proposal to allow patients the right to sue if they are
harmed by the decisions of managed care providers. The GOP moves
toward passage of its own measures. By GREG McDONALD.
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-GUNS (Washington) _ Colorado students, including several
from Columbine High School in Littleton, meet with President
Clinton and lobby members of Congress for tougher controls on guns.
By BENNETT ROTH.
</P>
<P>
   IMMIGRATION-AGENCY (Washington) _ House members of both parties
introduce a bill to abolish the embattled Immigration and
Naturalization Service and divide its service and enforcement into
two separate agencies. By MARK HELM. (Already filed.)
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL NEWS (``a'' category)
</P>
<P>
   SERIAL-KILLER (Houston) _ The lawyer representing Angel Maturino
Resendez says his client hopes for help from the Mexican
government, which might share the suspected serial killer's
apparent distress over facing a possible death sentence if he is
convicted of murder in Texas. By STEVE BREWER and MARIA LUISA
PEREZ.
</P>
<P>
   SERIAL-KILLER-FEDS (Houston) _ Details emerging from the efforts
to capture suspected serial killer Angel Maturino Resendez indicate
that federal agents tripped up a few times, threatening the tenuous
relationship with the suspect's family, who ultimately convinced
the fugitive to surrender. ``I think it just boils down to the fact
that the FBI got beat and they can't stand it,'' says a
high-ranking official with the Texas Department of Public Safety.
By ARMANDO VILLAFRANCA and JAMES PINKERTON.
</P>
<P>
   NASA-CHANDRA (Houston) _ NASA's Chandra X-ray Observatory, a
$1.55 billion, 45-foot-long, assembly of precision-ground optics
and science instruments, promises at least a 10-fold improvement in
previous celestial telescopes of its type. If successfully launched
by the crew of the shuttle Columbia next week, the Chandra will
open new doors for a relatively new breed of scientists, the X-ray
astronomers. By MARK CARREAU.
</P>
<P>
   Y2K-CITIES (Washington) _ Only two of the nation's 21 largest
cities _ Boston and Dallas _ are fully prepared to deal with
anticipated year 2000 computer glitches, according to the General
Accounting Office of Congress. By JOHN C. HENRY. (Already filed.)
</P>
<P>
   COMMENTARY (``k'' category)
</P>
<P>
   MEANS-COLUMN (Washington) _ In trying to fight pornography on
the Internet, Congress is moving to require libraries to block from
their computer screens ``offensive'' words and pictures so that
children will not be exposed to them. But librarians contend they
can do a better job of controlling pornography than any machine and
point out that the existing software blocks innocent words. By
MARIANNE MEANS. (Already filed.)
</P>
<P>
   SPORTS (``s'' category)
</P>
<P>
   BBN-DIERKER (Houston) _ A little more than a month after
suffering a seizure and undergoing brain surgery, Houston Astros
manager Larry Dierker returns to the dugout as the Astros open the
second half of the season against the Detroit Tigers. By NEIL
HOHLFELD.
</P>
<P>
   BBN-ASTROS (Houston) _ Pitcher Shane Reynolds will be seeking
his 11th victory of the season as the Houston Astros open their
longest homestand of the season with a game against the Detroit
Tigers. By JOSEPH DUARTE.
</P>
<P>
   With: BBN-LOPEZ-COLUMN
</P>
<P>
   GLF-BRITISH (Carnoustie, Scotland) _ Only one player in the
entire field is under par after the first round of the British Open
golf tournament, and scores are expected to soar even higher as the
tournament progresses into the weekend. By EDDIE SEFKO.
</P>
<P>
   For Sunday:
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON NEWS (``w'' category)
</P>
<P>
   GOD-BILLBOARDS (Washington) _ God is speaking to commuters from
billboards across the country. With Madison Avenue cleverness, the
Lord is delivering brief messages designed to amuse _ and prod the
fallen back to their pews. One message in Florida, cast in large
white letters against a stark field of black, asks, ``You think
it's hot here?'' and is signed ``God.'' By ERIC ROSENBERG. (Filed
Thursday.)
</P>
<P>
   TEACHING-HOSPITALS (Washington) _ With a boost from Hillary
Clinton, the plight of the nation's 400 teaching hospitals is
becoming a hot-button issue not only in her New York campaign for
the Senate but also in the nation's capital as Congress debates the
future of Medicare. By DAN FREEDMAN. (Filed Thursday.)
</P>
