<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-BARAK-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BARAK VOWS TO `INJECT NEW MOMENTUM' INTO MIDEAST TALKS 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By NANCY MATHIS 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Israeli Prime Minister Ehud Barak pledged Thursday
to ``inject new momentum'' into stalled Middle East talks and
declared the region at a decisive ``moment of truth'' in its quest
for a lasting peace.
</P>
<P>
   In his first official meeting with President Clinton, Barak also
declared that he was ready to meet with the Syrians to open another
peace track and stated that while he would not dismantle any
Israeli settlements in occupied lands, neither would he open new
ones.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton, who has made no secret of wanting the Middle East
conflict resolved on his watch, reiterated his promise that the
United States will help in any way possible to bring lasting peace
to the region.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is our intention to inject new momentum into the peace
process and to put it back on all tracks,'' Barak said as he and
Clinton appeared before reporters in the Rose Garden.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton and Barak retired to a nearly three hour meeting in the
more relaxed confines of the Yellow Oval Room in the White House's
residential quarters. The two, accompanied by their wives, later
flew for dinner to Camp David, site of the historic 1978 peace
agreement between Israel and Egypt.
</P>
<P>
   An Israeli official reported Barak told Clinton that the Middle
East had reached a ``moment of truth,'' and he was ready for
compromise.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Middle East has suffered long enough,'' the Israeli
official said, describing Barak's talks with Clinton. ``We are
ready. This is the moment of truth. It's a fateful moment. There
are dangers, but we are ready to try to reduce them.''
</P>
<P>
   Barak will spend six days in the United States. He will return
to Washington on Sunday for a more official dinner at the White
House and will hold a second round of meetings with Clinton on
Monday. The amount of time spent with the president greatly exceeds
that of most world leaders.
</P>
<P>
   ``As Israel again walks bravely down the path of peace, America
will walk with you, ready to help in any way we can,'' Clinton told
Barak in the Rose Garden.
</P>
<P>
   Barak said his Washington trip follows several meeting with Arab
leaders where he ``assured them that we would work as partners,
with mutual trust, in order to overcome all challenges and
complications that are still awaiting us down the street. We agreed
that we needed to abide by the previous agreements signed by all
parties, including the Wye accords.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked by reporters if a meeting with Syrian President Hafez
Assad was possible, Barak said, ``We still wait to see when the
time comes, but I hope we'll be able to meet. It takes two to
tango. I am ready, the arena is ready, maybe the dancing instructor
is ready. We have to find opportunity and begin.''
</P>
<P>
   Barak reportedly told Clinton during their private session that
he was prepared for a ``painful compromise'' that would return the
captured Golan Heights to Syria.
</P>
<P>
   Barak also addressed the delicate issue of Jewish settlements in
occupied territories. ``I'm not going to build new ones, I'm not
going to dismantle any one of them. Israeli citizens are living in
them.'' Barak told reporters.
</P>
<P>
   But he also told Clinton in private that the settlements would
remain under Israeli sovereignty and he had no intention of
returning Israel to its borders as they existed before the 1967
war. Israel expanded its territory to the West Bank, Gaza Strip and
the Golan Heights after that conflict with its Arab neighbors.
</P>
<P>
   Barak's openness toward peace negotiations received a hearty
welcome at the White House where the administration wrangled for
years with Barak's hard-line predecessor, Benjamin Netanyahu.
</P>
<P>
   Barak defeated Netanyahu in a landslide election in May,
following the collapse of the conservative government. Netanyahu
lost support from key coalition allies after he signed the Wye
River Memorandum.
</P>
<P>
   The Wye River accord called on Israeli to return to the the
Palestinian Authority an additional 13 percent of the occupied West
Bank in return for security pledges. The pact was brokered by
Clinton after around-the-clock sessions at the secluded Maryland
estate between Netanyahu and Palestinian President Yasser Arafat.
</P>
<P>
   Barak also expanded on previous comments in which he suggested
that instead of exhausting his domestic political capital trying to
implement the Wye River pact, the Israelis and Palestinians should
move go directly to final status talks and try to resolve the most
sensitive remaining issues _ the question of Palestinian statehood
and the status of Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
   Barak said his government would abide by the Wye requirements to
withdraw, but suggested it be done in combination with the opening
of final status negotiations.
</P>
<P>
   However, he said any changes would be implemented ``only through
an agreement with Arafat after mutual, open, frank and direct
discussions.''
</P>
<P>
   Barak also reiterated statements he made to U.S. newspapers
earlier this week that the United States should play a lesser role
in the peace process than it has been.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think that the United States can contribute to the process
more as facilitator than as a kind of policeman, judge and
arbitrator at the same time,'' Barak said.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton said he agreed, saying the United States only took a
greater role when it appeared the peace process was on the verge of
collapse.
</P>
<P>
   ``We did what was necessary to keep it going,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The president also restated the administration's position that
the issue of Jerusalem as the capital of Israel should be left to
the final status talks. Last week, first lady Hillary Rodham
Clinton, pondering a race for the Senate from New York, sent a
letter to Jewish leaders there declaring Jerusalem the eternal
capital of Israel.
</P>
<P>
   ``We should be doing nothing to prejudge the final status
issues,'' Clinton said, when asked about moving the U.S. Embassy
from Tel Aviv to Jerusalem. Clinton last month signed a wavier
delaying moving of the American Embassy.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every individual member of Congress can express a personal
opinion, but because of the waiver, the United States does not have
to prejudge the final status issue. That's good,'' he said,
referring to the first lady.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton also found himself explaining a comment he made earlier
this week when he described feeling like ``a kid with a new toy''
at the prospect of Barak's visit. The remarked prompted a
controversy in Israel where the media viewed it as a patronizing
remark.
</P>
<P>
   ``In American English it means, `I'm very excited about the
prospect of the rejuvenation of the peace process,' and that's all
it means,'' Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
   Barak, Israel's most decorated soldier, said the flap made him
feel like ``someone who got the mission of defusing a time bomb.''
He chastised the Israeli press for its ``tricky interpretation of
innocent favorable statements.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-15-99 2008EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
