<HEADLINE>
S.F.-BORN ASTRONAUT DESERVES HIS DUE
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Eds: This story also moved in the ``a'' national news file)  
 By LEAH GARCHIK  
 c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle
<TEXT>
<P>
   Tuesday being the 30th anniversary of the first moon walk, space
buff  &UR; Ken Winans &LR;  of Mill Valley has been trying to get someone in
California _ he wrote to Gov.  &UR; Gray Davis &LR; , San Francisco Mayor
 &UR; Willie Brown &LR;  and all of the San Francisco supervisors _ to honor
 &UR; John Young &LR; , the astronaut born in San Francisco. Young, who is 69
years old and lives in Houston nowadays, is the most traveled man
in space; he was the ninth man to walk on the moon.
</P>
<P>
   Brown expressed to Winans his enthusiasm for some kind of
homage, noting that the California Academy of Sciences is
considering a proper tribute.  &UR; Meagan Levitin &LR;  at the academy says
discussions are under way, spurred by the mayor and Supervisors
 &UR; Tom Ammiano &LR;  and  &UR; Leslie Katz &LR; .
</P>
<P>
   Winans says he has no ulterior motive but has been a lifelong
admirer of the Apollo program. He realized during a trip to Houston
that while Young was honored with a stand-alone tribute there,
there is no citation of his accomplishments in the Bay Area.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; THE DEMS LINE UP &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Celebrities who have lined up behind the presidential candidacy
of  &UR; Bill Bradley &LR; , as listed in the New York Daily News:
 &UR; Harrison Ford &LR; ,  &UR; Quincy Jones &LR; ,  &UR; Sting &LR; ,  &UR; Olympia Dukakis &LR; ,
 &UR; Dustin &LR; 
 &UR; Hoffman &LR; ,  &UR; Robert Redford &LR; ,  &UR; Spike Lee &LR; ,  &UR; Michael Jordan &LR; ,  &UR; Barry &LR; 
 &UR; Diller &LR; ,  &UR; Michael Eisner &LR; ,  &UR; Sydney Pollack &LR;  and  &UR; Bruce Hornsby &LR; .
</P>
<P>
   Celebrities who have lined up behind  &UR; Al Gore &LR; :  &UR; Barbra &LR; 
 &UR; Streisand &LR; ,  &UR; Steven Spielberg &LR; ,  &UR; Tom Hanks &LR; ,  &UR; David Geffen &LR; ,
 &UR; Sheryl &LR; 
 &UR; Crow &LR;  and  &UR; James Taylor &LR; .
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; TALES OF NEWT &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Newt Gingrich &LR;  is hawking ``Newt's Age of Possibilities,'' a
90-second taped radio message that will be sent to stations by his
syndicate, Premiere Radio Networks, five days a week. Gingrich says
he'll be ``the same kind of direct, uncensored, unedited guy''
we've come to know and love.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the Washington Post is reporting that Gingrich is
negotiating a financial settlement that will end his 18-year
marriage.
</P>
<P>
   A friend of his told the Post that he didn't want to go public
with this news because his soon-to-be former wife is occupied right
now helping her mother recover from cancer surgery. Newt-watchers
will remember that he told his first wife that their marriage was
over while she was being treated for cancer.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FLASH &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; _ Prentice Steffen &LR; , team physician for the Mercury
Professional Cycling Team, points to the Web site of  &UR; Paul &LR; 
 &UR; McCartney &LR; 's bicycle racing team, which is sponsored by Paul
through his wife's vegetarian food company. The site says that all
current team members are vegetarians, records good results in
English races last weekend and mentions the team's goal of
participating in the Tour de France. They aren't in this year's
race, writes Steffen, because ``they aren't that good yet.''
</P>
<P>
   _ PMK, the public relations company representing  &UR; Tom Cruise &LR; ,
asked members of the press covering him at previews of ``Eyes Wide
Shut'' to agree that ``the interview and the program will not show
the artist in a negative or derogatory manner.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Having paid $8,000 for the privilege at a children's charity
auction in New York,  &UR; Evander Holyfield &LR;  is an extra in ``Summer of
Sam,'' reports People magazine.
</P>
<P>
   _ Environmental alert:  &UR; Bud Arnold &LR;  forwards an Atherton police
report in the Palo Alto Daily News of  &LR; July 12:  &LR; ``Resident called
police after discovering a piece of art was leaking mercury in the
garage. Officers found no problem.''
</P>
<P>
   _  &UR; La Verne Frizell &LR;  writes that her boyfriend, born on a
commune in Oregon, is named  &UR; Huckleberry Sundance &LR;  (berries seem to
have been particularly popular). And  &UR; Cody Gates &LR;  remembers
schoolmates  &UR; Sunshine &LR;  and  &UR; Star Bright &LR; ;  &UR; Maureen Forys &LR;  remembers
classmates  &UR; Tuesday &LR;  and  &UR; Sunday &LR;  and just plain  &UR; A &LR; .
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; THE SIGNS OF ENGLAND &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Inspired by Monday's item about English road signs warning of
humps,  &UR; Jon Ahlberg &LR;  reports that he's seen the following in his
own travels to Great Britain:
</P>
<P>
   ``Sleeping Policemen'' (means speed bumps are present); ``Humped
Zebra Crossing'' and ``Humped Pedestrian Crossing'' (warnings of
pedestrian walkways); ``Cats Eyes Removed'' (reflective markers
have been taken off road); and ``Changed Priorities Ahead''
(right-of-way changes).
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
