<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-15 20:11 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1829 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-YUGOSLAVIA-ARMY-947&AMP;A     07-15 1034
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-YUGOSLAVIA-ARMY-947&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SERBIAN RAGE BEING REDIRECTED TOWARD RUSSIA 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Graphic of locator map is being sent to NYT graphic
clients. Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
(888) 603-1036.) 
(yn) 
 By CHRIS HEDGES   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   VRANJE, Yugoslavia _ Yugoslavian generals, touring the country
to stanch protests and dismantle roadblocks set up by angry army
reservists owed money for duty in Kosovo, are dousing one
rebellious fire after another.
</P>
<P>
   At least for now, the generals have apparently succeeded in
redirecting some of the popular rage from President Slobodan
Milosevic of Yugoslavia toward the latest enemy of Serbia: Russia.
</P>
<P>
   Army reservists in Vranje, as in other cities in southern
Serbia, took down street barricades after Gen. Nebojsa Pavkovic,
the commander in southern Serbia, promised that back salaries would
be paid in two weeks. But the general also perpetuated for his
former soldiers the newest myth taking root in Serbia. The country
was not defeated by NATO bombs, he said, but was betrayed and sold
out by Russia, a country now as perfidious as the United States.
</P>
<P>
   ``We wanted to reach a peaceful settlement,'' the general told
some 100 reservists in Vranje, ``but this was not accepted. We
approached the Russians, who were our friends, and made a plan. The
Russians accepted the plan. We would leave the Pristina corps and
our special Ministry of Interior police in Kosovo and the U.N.
forces would be allowed to enter. Everything would be all right.''
</P>
<P>
   ``But the Russians then came back and said we had to accept the
Western plan, that we had to take it or leave it,'' he said. ``We
were told that if we refused the plan, every city in Serbia would
be razed to the ground. The bridges in Belgrade would be destroyed.
The crops would all be burned. Everyone would die. Look at the
Russians. They have not helped us.''
</P>
<P>
   So, once again, begins the flight from reality that has plagued
the Serbs during the wars in the former Yugoslavia, one that pins
the defeat not on the leadership of Milosevic and Serbian
nationalism, but on nefarious outside forces arrayed to crush the
Serbs.
</P>
<P>
   While many soldiers and reservists remain critical of the
Yugoslav president, many also seem ready to accept this version of
events. There is little atonement for Kosovo, or for Serbian
attacks in Bosnia or Croatia.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were betrayed in Kosovo,'' said Ivica Mladenovic, 23, who
served in Kosovo and took part in the road blockages. ``Our fight
has been useless. I wait for the day when we are ordered to take
Kosovo back. I will be the first to volunteer. Now the Kosovo
Liberation Army holds Kosovo. The Serbs are being driven out. The
grandfather of my friend had his eyes gouged out four days ago and
his body mutilated.''
</P>
<P>
   Soldiers and some of this region's 20,000 newly discharged
reservists, all with closely cropped hair, linger in Vranje's
street cafes and freely acknowledge that Kosovo Albanians died in
droves during the campaign, yet seem unable to ascribe blame for
the killings.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Ministry of Interior police had the job to punish those
who were connected with the Kosovo Liberation Army,'' Mladenovic
said. ``The Albanians were not afraid of the army. They were afraid
of the police.''
</P>
<P>
   The atrocities committed by Serbian forces are viewed by many as
an inevitable consequence of war, somehow beyond human
responsibility. Special police and members of Serbian paramilitary
units stationed in Kosovo show photos of Kosovo Albanians, their
hands tied behind their backs, kneeling in rows awaiting execution,
several army soldiers said.
</P>
<P>
   War stories by men decked out in gold chains and expensive
watches, part of the loot from the province, are told with a moral
numbness, these soldiers said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most Serbs know what happened in Kosovo before NATO came,''
said Vuk Obradovic, the editor of Vranjske Novine, a weekly
independent paper. ``They know what crimes were committed, because
the people who come here from Kosovo, the soldiers and the
refugees, tell us what happened. My Serb friend from Kosovo said,
`I must escape. Evil has been done here and I can't stay.' He's not
the only one saying this. People know what the Serbs have done.''
</P>
<P>
   But this acknowledgment is not made in public. The paper, after
this week interviewing a Serbian refugee who said he understood why
the Kosovo Albanians wanted to exact revenge, was asked by the
refugee not to print the statement because he feared reprisals.
</P>
<P>
   ``During the last 10 years, the regime has created a situation
where Albanians are no longer seen as equals,'' Obradovic said.
``Because of this, no one feels guilty for what happened.''
</P>
<P>
   The combustible mixture of defeat, anger and denial is one that
Milosevic has played to his advantage in the past, and may use
again, despite rising rage at his policies and Yugoslavia's
poverty.
</P>
<P>
   Besides redirecting reservists' rage toward the Russians, Gen.
Pavkovic also tried to spook the malcontents, warning that once the
last pockets of Serbs were driven from Kosovo, NATO forces would
move to occupy Vranje and Leskovac, another southern Serbian town
where there have been daily protests against Milosevic.
</P>
<P>
   Any respite from the protests may, however, prove temporary. The
general admitted that the promised back pay _ totaling $100 million
_ may have to come in the form of coupons for utilities and food
rather than currency. A government official in Belgrade, worried
that the army would not be able to pay by its self-imposed deadline
of July 28, said the reservists' barricades may go back up.
</P>
<P>
   ``God knows what will happen then,'' he said, asking not to be
named. ``It may just be anarchic violence.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The trees, walls and lamp posts in Vranje are covered with paper
death notices, most with the grainy black and white photos of
soldiers and police killed during the war. The clusters of young
men who walk past the notices often comment quietly on those they
knew.
</P>
<P>
   ``They have to have died for something,'' said Zoran Stankovic,
24. ``We just don't yet know what it was.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
