<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-15 20:16 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1836 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-IRELAND-PEACE-BOS &LR;      07-15 1144
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IRELAND-PEACE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ULSTER ASSEMBLY DISINTEGRATES AMID RECRIMINATION, FARCE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KEVIN CULLEN AND JOHN O'FARRELL  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BELFAST _ A year after it was inaugurated as the future for a
place held back by the past, the 108-member Northern Ireland
Assembly collapsed Thursday amid a sea of recrimination,
resignation and farce.
</P>
<P>
   While the British and Irish governments insisted that the
failure to form a local power-sharing government was only a
temporary setback, and that they had ordered a review of the
inability of the parties in Northern Ireland to implement the Good
Friday Agreement of 1998, the scenes on the assembly floor did not
bode well for its future or the peace process.
</P>
<P>
   British Prime Minister Tony Blair and his Irish counterpart,
Bertie Ahern, are scheduled to meet Tuesday to chart a course out
of the dead end the peace process has run into. But privately,
British and Irish diplomats were admitting that the assembly would
not sit for at least six weeks, and that the peace process had been
set back even further.
</P>
<P>
   As has been expected for several weeks, efforts to revive the
stalled peace process collapsed because of a dispute between the
Ulster Unionists, who represent middle-class Protestants in
Northern Ireland, and Sinn Fein, which is allied with the Irish
Republican Army. The unionists refuse to form a local government
with Sinn Fein until the IRA begins disarming, while Sinn Fein
accuses the unionists of trying to rewrite the Good Friday
Agreement, which made no linkage between the formation of a local
government and IRA disarming.
</P>
<P>
   It is seldom, if ever, that Sinn Fein President Gerry Adams and
the fundamentalist Protestant preacher-politician Rev. Ian Paisley
agree on anything, but both described the events on the assembly
floor at Stormont as farce. But despite seeing eye to eye on that
matter, Paisley's members heckled Adams mercilessly as Adams
appealed for compromise.
</P>
<P>
   The Ulster Unionists, the largest party in Northern Ireland, and
its leader David Trimble boycotted the session. Fifteen minutes
before the assembly sat, Trimble and his party leaders held a press
conference outside their headquarters in downtown Belfast to
announce they would not nominate the three candidates they were due
on a 10-member cabinet that would oversee the assembly's work.
</P>
<P>
   After Paisley's party refused to put forward candidates, and the
Alliance Party, which draws members from both the Catholic
nationalist and Protestant unionist communities, also refused,
Catholic nationalist members of the assembly from Sinn Fein and the
Social Democratic and Labor Party eventually accounted for all 10
seats.
</P>
<P>
   But because the cabinet can by law only be formed with
cross-community representation, the nominations were invalidated
and British Secretary of State Mo Mowlam ordered the assembly
adjourned.
</P>
<P>
   In the most farcical scene of the day, the assembly speaker,
John Alderdice, turned to Trimble's empty chair and asked the
absent assembly leader to nominate his party's ministers for the
cabinet. Alderdice dutifully waited the five alloted minutes before
moving onto the next party.
</P>
<P>
   In the day's most dramatic scene, Seamus Mallon, the deputy
leader of the assembly, resigned, saying he was disgusted that Sinn
Fein's efforts to compromise on the arms dispute had been dismissed
by the Ulster Unionists.
</P>
<P>
   ``Regrettably, and I say this more in sorrow than in anger,
those efforts have not just been spurned, they have been scorned,''
said Mallon, deputy leader of the Social Democratic and Labor Party
who accused the unionists of using ``this crisis to bleed more
concessions out of the governments.''
</P>
<P>
   It was an extraordinary verbal attack by Mallon, the
gentlemanly, stoic politician from South Armagh who seldom uses the
melodramatic rhetoric so common here. But as Mallon sat down and
fought to control his emotions, it was obvious that even he was
overwhelmed by the sense that things were slipping away just 15
months after the euphoria of signing the Good Friday Agreement.
</P>
<P>
   Mallon called on Trimble to resign also, and unionist sources
said Trimble may do so Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Trimble, who resisted an all-out press by Blair to accept a
compromise that would have seen formation of the government first
and IRA disarming second, said his party would not sit in
government with a party ``inextricably linked'' to the IRA, saying
to do so would make a mockery out of the democratic process.
</P>
<P>
   There was little respite for the democratic process. When Adams
nominated Martin McGuinness, Sinn Fein's chief negotiator and a
former IRA chief of staff, as the minister for agriculture,
hecklers from Paisley's party shouted ``fertilizer, fertilizer,'' a
reference to the IRA's use of fertilizer bombs.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking in Washington, President Clinton seemed to capture the
bewilderment of the outside world, which sees the stalemate as one
easily resolved.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton said unionists and republicans ``are having a fight over
who goes first and acting today as if the whole thing could be
abandoned over that. That cannot be allowed to happen.''
</P>
<P>
   Speaking in London, Blair agreed, saying, ``a summer break for
dialogue and time to consider the deal will help.''
</P>
<P>
   George Mitchell, the former US Senate majority leader who
chaired the negotiations that led to last year's Good Friday
Agreement, agreed that a break until September would do the peace
process good. Mitchell was in London to receive an award from Queen
Elizabeth for his work in Northern Ireland.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking in Dublin, Ahern asked that the parties refrain from
recrimination, and said only the building of trust between the
parties would allow the process to move forward.
</P>
<P>
   Addressing the House of Commons, a downcast Mowlam insisted the
setback was only temporary and refused to apportion blame.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't want to indulge in blame and recrimination,'' she
said. ``Today is not the day. The last thing the people of Northern
Ireland need is a breakout of recrimination.''
</P>
<P>
   Only Paisley dared to call Thursday a ``good day for Northern
Ireland.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Democracy has triumphed,'' the fiery orator thundered, ``and
there are no IRA men in the government of Northern Ireland.''
</P>
<P>
   But Adams warned unionists that their intransigence came with a
price. While the institutions created by the Good Friday Agreement
have been put on hold, Adams noted, other aspects that unionists
abhor have not, including the release of paramilitary prisoners and
the creation of equality measures to address systematic
discrimination against Catholics.
</P>
<P>
   Adams called on Blair to stand up to the unionists and move the
process forward.
</P>
<P>
   ``The question is whether the Good Friday Agreement prevails, or
the unionist veto prevails,'' Adams said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
