</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-VACCINE-SUSPEND-700&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HEALTH OFFICIALS SUSPEND USE OF VACCINE TO PREVENT INFANT
DIARRHEA 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ga., Calif., Minn.)  (th) 
 By LAWRENCE K. ALTMAN    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Federal health officials called Thursday for the immediate
suspension of a vaccine recently recommended for all infants to
protect against rotavirus, the most common cause of severe diarrhea
in infants and young children.
</P>
<P>
   The Centers for Disease Control and Prevention said it took the
extraordinary action because a program to monitor side effects
suggested a link between the vaccine, licensed last year, and 20
nonfatal cases of a painful blockage of the bowel called
intussusception.
</P>
<P>
   Although there is no conclusive evidence that the vaccine causes
the bowel condition, CDC officials said the data are strongly
suggestive. They said they considered it prudent to halt rotavirus
vaccinations until at least November. The bowel condition seems to
develop about one to three weeks after rotavirus vaccination.
</P>
<P>
   ``No one should now be giving rotavirus vaccine to anyone,''
said Barbara Reynolds, a spokeswoman for CDC.
</P>
<P>
   The vaccine was developed at the National Institutes of Health
and is licensed to Wyeth-Ayerst of St. Davids, Pa., a division of
American Home Products Corp., which sells it as RotaShield. One
million infants have received the vaccine, a spokesman for
Wyeth-Ayerst said, and the company is cooperating with federal
officials.
</P>
<P>
   The vaccine has been approved for use in 13 European countries,
but has not been marketed there because Wyeth-Ayerst lacked a
sufficient supply, a spokesman for the drug company said. He said
the company will not market the vaccine in Europe until the bowel
condition problem is clarified.
</P>
<P>
   Cases of bowel obstruction were noted in experimental trials
that were required before the vaccine was approved for licensing,
but not in unusual numbers. The FDA required studies to monitor the
incidence of the condition among infants who received the vaccine.
Information collected in those studies led the CDC to recommend a
halt to rotavirus vaccinations.
</P>
<P>
   By November, the CDC expects to clarify what role, if any, the
vaccine plays in the development of bowel obstruction. The federal
agency, based in Atlanta, has undertaken a study of the vaccine
with health officials in 15 states.
</P>
<P>
   ``The vaccine is still licensed by the Food and Drug
Administration,'' Dr. Melinda Wharton, a CDC epidemiologist and
expert on childhood vaccines, said Thursday in an interview.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is a highly effective vaccine, and we don't want to take
this disease prevention tool away from practitioners in the United
States unless there is a real good reason to do that,'' Dr. Wharton
said.
</P>
<P>
   Rotavirus vaccine is injected three times _ at 2, 4 and 6 months
of age. Infants who have already received one or two shots should
not receive another, CDC officials said in their weekly report.
</P>
<P>
   Intussusception is rare and of unknown cause, although some
studies have hinted at a link to other viruses. The condition
occurred long before Aug. 31, 1998, when the FDA licensed the first
vaccine against rotavirus, which is the biggest killer from
diarrheal illness among children around the world.
</P>
<P>
   The condition results when one part of the bowel slides inward,
like a telescope, into another part of the bowel. In severe cases,
a previously healthy infant suddenly screams in paroxysms of pain.
The screaming can last for several minutes, then abate, only to
recur and become cyclical.
</P>
<P>
   Other symptoms include persistent vomiting and a bowel movement
that contains blood or appears black. In examining the abdomen, a
doctor often can feel a knot from the telescoped bowel and make a
tentative diagnosis. A barium enema and X-rays are used to confirm
the condition.
</P>
<P>
   In some cases the enema can straighten out the telescoped bowel.
But in others, surgery is required. Of the first 15 cases
investigated, eight infants underwent surgery to repair the bowel
and one had a piece of bowel removed.
</P>
<P>
   Parents and caretakers should immediately call a doctor if a
child develops such symptoms, the CDC said. The agency also alerted
doctors to consider the possibility of bowel obstruction in an
infant that had recently received rotavirus vaccination.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Concern about the vaccine arose about four weeks ago when an
epidemiologist noticed an unusual number of intussusception cases
in seven states involved in the monitoring system that the CDC and
the FDA use, Dr. Wharton said.
</P>
<P>
   The reports came from doctors, Wyeth-Ayerst and parents. After
sorting out duplicate reports and confirming that the cases were
intussusception, the CDC team began to see a consistent pattern in
the timing of the bowel condition following vaccination, Dr.
Wharton said.
</P>
<P>
   Two additional reports strongly influenced the decision, Dr.
Wharton said.
</P>
<P>
   One report came from officials of the Minnesota Health
Department. The other came from doctors at Northern California
Kaiser Permanente who are conducting a post-licensing safety study
for Wyeth-Ayerst. But both studies suggested an increased risk,
although they involved small numbers of infants.
</P>
<P>
   The CDC then joined with health officials in 15 states to
conduct a study involving more than 2,000 infants. That study is
expected to be completed by October when a committee on
immunizations holds its next regular meeting.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was the consistency of the findings that raised concerns to
the point that we felt a postponement was the prudent thing to
do,'' Dr. Wharton said.
</P>
<P>
   The November suspension date is a reflection of the seasonal
nature of rotavirus infection, which usually occurs in the winter
and spring. Each year, rotavirus infection causes diarrhea in about
3.5 million American children, sends 50,000 to the hospital and
kills 20.
</P>
<P>
   The suspension of the RotaShield vaccine is the latest in a
string of misfortunes for Wyeth-Ayerst and its parent, American
Home Products. Aside from its two failed merger attempts last year,
the company recently withdrew several of its drugs from the market
over health concerns and announced last month that its
second-quarter earnings would not meet analysts' expectations.
</P>
<P>
   The possible demise of the RotaShield vaccine should not dent
American Home Products' overall performance. The drug was projected
by analysts to be a small seller _ just $100 million in sales this
year and $200 million in 2000. Some analysts said Thursday that
they did not expect RotaShield to ever return to the market, and if
it did, nervous doctors would be likely to shun it.
</P>
<P>
   It was unclear how investors would react, given that American
Home Products made an announcement about the vaccine after the New
York Stock Exchange had closed Thursday. Shares of American Home
Products, which is based in Madison, N.J., closed Thursday at
$54.875, down 12.5 cents.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
