<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHINA-NUKE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ADMINISTRATION TRIES TO PLAY DOWN TIMING OF CHINA'S ANNOUNCEMENT 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Calif., Fla., N.J., N.Y.) (rk) 
 By ERIC SCHMITT   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Seeking to contain a budding crisis in Asia, the
Clinton administration tried Thursday to play down the timing and
significance of China's declaration that it was capable of making
neutron bombs and miniaturized nuclear weapons.
</P>
<P>
   But congressional Republicans said Beijing's assertion validated
a congressional inquiry that accused China of stealing U.S. nuclear
secrets, and was timed precisely to intimidate Taiwan.
</P>
<P>
   ``This shows the Cox report was hard-hitting and has caused the
Chinese some angst,'' said Rep. Porter Goss, R-Fla., who heads the
House Intelligence Committee and who served on the special House
panel headed by Rep. Christopher Cox, R-Calif.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now the Chinese are saying to Taiwan, `Pay attention, we've
got this,''' Goss said. ``It's a very dangerous situation.''
</P>
<P>
   Tensions between Taiwan and China rose after Taiwan's president,
Lee Teng-hui, said over the weekend that his government would no
longer adhere to the principle that the Chinese mainland and Taiwan
were two parts of the same country. The announcement stunned and
angered China, which has always reserved the right to use military
force, if necessary, to fulfill its goal of reunification with
Taiwan.
</P>
<P>
   The United States has staked out a muted position since the war
of words erupted, not wanting to inflame the debate. At the White
House and State Department Thursday, administration spokesmen
refused to draw the conclusion that China's announcement of its
nuclear-bomb building ability was intended to intimidate Taiwan.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't see the connection,'' said State Department spokesman
James Rubin. ``I don't think it's any secret to the people of the
world that China has a very small nuclear capability.''
</P>
<P>
   But under repeated questioning from reporters, Rubin
acknowledged that the administration was troubled by the heated
dispute. ``We are concerned,'' he said. ``We regard the statements
and the reaction to the statements both as unhelpful to the people
concerned and to the region.''
</P>
<P>
   Rubin said that under the Taiwan Relations Act, ``any effort to
determine the future of Taiwan by other than peaceful means would
be a threat to the peace and security of the Western Pacific area
and of grave concern to the United States.''
</P>
<P>
   At the same, Rubin said the saber-rattling was, so far, just
that. ``We haven't seen any change in posture that would indicate
an escalation of this situation,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   On Capitol Hill, Republicans and some Democrats expressed little
doubt that China's announcement was carefully calculated to
frighten Taiwan.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was meant as a threat to the democratic island of Taiwan,''
said Rep. Benjamin Gilman, R-N.Y., chairman of the House
International Relations Committee. ``I do not think we can dismiss
the possibility that China could use the neutron bomb _ a weapon
that has never been used _ against Taiwan.''
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Robert Torricelli, D-N.J., who just returned from a trip to
China and North Korea, said, ``There's no doubt that the choosing
of this moment to announce they have the neutron bomb is not
coincidental.''
</P>
<P>
   Even so, many lawmakers said China's assertions, while
worrisome, were unlikely by themselves to alter the congressional
debate later this summer on extending China's trade status with the
United States.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is ham-fisted and clumsy, but unless it lasts for more than
a few days, it will ultimately be ignored,'' Cox said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   The Cox Committee accused China of having stolen information on
the designs of the neutron bomb, which kills people with enhanced
radiation while leaving buildings intact, and the W-88, the most
advanced miniaturized nuclear warhead.
</P>
<P>
   While there is a debate within U.S. intelligence officials as to
how much the U.S. information contributed to China developing its
own nuclear weapons, there is no disagreement that Beijing obtained
classified data that accelerated its own programs. China has denied
committing espionage.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
