<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUSH-2000-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSH REFUSES FEDERAL CAMPAIGN FUNDS 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By CRAGG HINES 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WATERLOO, Iowa _ Gov. George W. Bush, sitting on the fattest
presidential primary war chest in history, said Thursday he would
forgo federal campaign funds and the spending limits attached to
them as he seeks the Republican nomination.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've got too many people counting on me to put myself in a box
_ to get boxed in by the rules that affected our nominee in 1996,
and I intend to win,'' said Bush, reflecting on the funding
problems faced three years ago by losing Republican nominee Bob
Dole.
</P>
<P>
   The announcement came as Bush formally reported $37 million in
contributions through June 30, with $30 million still on hand _ a
huge lead over all of his competitors.
</P>
<P>
   He predicted the massive bankroll could get him past unforeseen
campaign problems: ``I think with $30 million in the bank, I've got
pretty good staying power.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush said he would skip the federal payments in the primary
because he wanted to maintain ``strategic flexibility'' as he
battles through early-voting Iowa and New Hampshire against the
largely self-financed campaign of multimillionaire publisher Steve
Forbes. Bush also said that if he becomes the presumptive GOP
nominee he wants to be able to mount a vigorous campaign from the
spring of 2000 until the Republican National Convention that
summer.
</P>
<P>
   Under the matching fund system, the federal government matches
up to $250 of each individual contribution. But accepting the funds
means Bush or any other candidate must abide by state-by-state
spending limits and an overall primary-season expenditure of $33.3
million. Bush's decision to skip federal funds in the primary would
not affect his ability later, if he is the Republican nominee, to
claim an estimated $66 million in general-election campaign funds
from the federal Treasury.
</P>
<P>
   Bush recalled that Dole was damaged by Forbes' early lavish
spending _ especially on attack ads _ and by the inability to
answer Democratic slams in the months between the primaries and the
convention.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to be in a position to respond,'' Bush told reporters
after a rally here with about 250 people. ``I want to be in a
position to plan. I want to be in a position to budget according to
need.''
</P>
<P>
   In the short term, Bush and his advisers see a threat in Forbes,
who spent $36 million of his own money in the 1996 campaign and who
has already contributed $6.6 million of his own to his 2000
campaign account _ if only because of his seemingly unlimited
willingness to bankroll his campaign.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm competing in the primary against somebody who can write
one check, and I'm mindful of what happened in 1996,'' Bush said.
``And I'm not going to let it happen to me''
</P>
<P>
   The lack of spending limits could be important not only in Iowa
and New Hampshire but also in the newly important and always
expensive New York and California primaries, which have been moved
up in the calendar and could be decisive.
</P>
<P>
   The Bush team is also concerned that the campaign could be
hamstrung in the run-up to the convention. Three years ago,
President Clinton established general-election campaign themes and
Democrats painted an uncomplimentary portrait of Dole that he could
not fully answer because he was out of funds and had hit the
federal spending limit.
</P>
<P>
   Looking ahead to a similar pre-convention shootout with Vice
President Al Gore, Bush said:
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a chance I'll be running against somebody who'll be
able to jump on a government airplane and travel all over the
country making promises, and I want to be able to respond. The best
thing for me to do is not accept taxpayers' money.''
</P>
<P>
   Besides setting a fund-raising record, Bush's $30 million cash
on hand is particularly stunning when compared to the 1996
Republican field.
</P>
<P>
   Forbes is Bush's nearest competitor at $9.5 million, but $6.6
million of that is his own money.
</P>
<P>
   Elizabeth Dole reported raising $3.5 million so far, with $1.8
million cash on hand. Dole noted that 43 percent of her
contributions of $200 or more came from women, who she said usually
make up only 25 percent of high-dollar donations.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. John McCain of Arizona has raised $4.3 million since the
first of the year and transferred $1.9 million from his Senate
committee. He closed the period with $2.6 million in cash.
</P>
<P>
   Among the Democrats, Vice President Al Gore has about $18.5
million, while former Sen. Bill Bradley has raised about $11.7
million.
</P>
<P>
   Bush's campaign bragged that he had 74,000 contributors and that
98 percent of his contributions came from individuals. The average
contribution was $466.69, the campaign said.
</P>
<P>
   Bush's report said he had raised $36.2 million from individuals
and $804,941 from political action committees
</P>
<P>
   Only two major-party contenders, both Republicans, have refused
to accept federal matching funds in the primaries since the program
was instituted as one of the post-Watergate campaign financing
reforms. They were former Texas Gov. John B. Connally in 1980 and
Forbes in 1996. The ultimate failures of their campaigns have left
politicians and their handlers wary of not following the more
trodden financing path.
</P>
<P>
   By skipping the federal funds, Bush runs the risk of drawing
attention to his financial prowess and charges, such as Forbes has
already made, that the Texas governor is all political technique
and no heartfelt beliefs _ an allegation Bush heartily rejects.
</P>
<P>
   Bush sought to picture his move as a boon for the candidates who
will dip into matching funds: ``I guess I'm doing the system a
favor,'' he deadpanned.
</P>
<P>
   Bush's announcement came as he started his second campaign swing
through Iowa, which not only holds the first major test of
candidate support next year but plans a Republicans presidential
straw poll next month.
</P>
<P>
   With both events in mind, Bush launched what a local political
analyst called ``an agri-pander'' aimed at the state's important
farming interests.
</P>
<P>
   Bush, touring farm country on a bus, faulted the Clinton
administration for not striking a deal with China on admitting the
giant communist nation to the World Trade Organization _ a move
that would make agricultural commerce easier.
</P>
<P>
   Bush also promised in a speech in Waterloo never, if elected, to
``use food as a sanction'' in diplomatic disputes. Later, speaking
to reporters, he said that pledge was good for ``any country in the
world.''
</P>
<P>
   Although the latest agricultural crisis has been caused by
marketing disruption _ primarily a product of the Asian economic
crisis _ as opposed to natural disasters, Bush said farmers merited
a federal bailout.
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe disaster is disaster,'' Bush said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
