<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-ANDERSON-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: THE UMPIRES DEFY LABOR'S RULE BOOK
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 By DAVE ANDERSON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ In baseball's medieval times, when umpires projected
nobility instead of defiance, it was raining steadily when the
Pittsburgh Pirates' manager, Frank Frisch, confronted Jocko Conlan,
one of history's feistiest umpires. After arguing, loudly, that the
weather was too soggy to play baseball, Frisch questioned Conlan's
intestinal fortitude.
</P>
<P>
   ``You haven't got the guts to call it,'' Frisch growled.
</P>
<P>
   ``You haven't got the guts to play it,'' Conlan barked. ``Why
don't you stop crying and try to win the game.''
</P>
<P>
   Today's umpires ought to heed Jocko Conlan's advice.
</P>
<P>
   By announcing their resignation, effective Sept. 2, in order to
threaten the remainder of the season as well as the league playoffs
and the World Series, at least 57 of the 66 major league umpires
have shown they don't have the intestinal fortitude to play through
their union contract with Major League Baseball, which expires Dec.
31.
</P>
<P>
   To paraphrase Conlan, who once traded kicks to the shin with Leo
Durocher, the umpires should stop crying, work through the World
Series and then try to negotiate a new labor contract.
</P>
<P>
   With an agreement that includes a no-strike clause, the umpires'
intention to ``resign'' is merely semantics. For all practical
purposes, they've called a wildcat strike for Sept. 2.
</P>
<P>
   If that wildcat strike happens, the games will go on; the
National and American leagues will hire ``replacement'' umpires as
they did during other labor disputes. The replacements won't be as
good. Bad calls will occur that could affect the identity of the
World Series winner.
</P>
<P>
   But bad calls have always occurred. Remember all those wide
strike-zone calls in last year's post-season games? Maybe the
replacements would have more consistent strike zones.
</P>
<P>
   You would think that the umpires, of all the people in baseball,
would be more ethical in their labor dealings. Umpires uphold
baseball's ethics, its rule book. When the now-retired Doug Harvey,
known as God, was a young umpire, his mentor, Hall of Famer Al
Barlick, told him:
</P>
<P>
   ``If you're going to preach the game, you better know the
bible.''
</P>
<P>
   Barlick meant the umpires' bible, the rule book. If a manager or
a player tried to defy that rule book, an umpire would eject him.
And an umpire, theoretically, would never call a pitch a strike if
it wasn't a strike. But now the umpires are calling what amounts to
an illegal strike.
</P>
<P>
   In their devious decision to resign on Sept. 2, the umpires are
defying their own rule book, the labor agreement negotiated by
Richie Phillips, their union leader. Then again, Phillips' judgment
is open to question. He pretends that all umpires resemble a batch
of cookies.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have a pool of 64 marvelous umpires,'' Phillips said during
last year's post-season problems. ``Very little distinguishes them
from one another in ability.''
</P>
<P>
   You would think that the best umpires would resent being lumped
with the worst umpires. But to Phillips, all umpires are the same
in order to justify the annual post-season rotation of umpires,
good and bad.
</P>
<P>
   Ideally, the most efficient umpires should be assigned to call
the most important games.
</P>
<P>
   In explaining the umpires' resignations, Phillips cited such
grievances as umpires' accountability and threats by the league
offices of dismissal, as if umpires were somehow exempt from
situations that exist in any other profession.
</P>
<P>
   More and more in recent years, baseball umpires have developed a
more aggressive, if not arrogant, attitude in on-the-field disputes
that has negated any sympathy for their problems.
</P>
<P>
   By resigning, the 57 umpires will be eligible for a total of
more than $15 million in termination pay, the first shot in
Phillips' approaching battle for a new labor contract.
</P>
<P>
   But with the umpires forming Umpires Inc., a new organization,
Major League Baseball might go to court over that termination pay.
Whatever develops, umpires have lost their sense of the rule book,
if not their sense of humor that even the legendary Bill Klem had
when an irate lady spectator disagreed with one of his calls.
</P>
<P>
   ``Klem,'' she shouted, ``if you were my husband, I'd put poison
in your coffee.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Lady,'' yelled Klem, staring at her, ``if I was your husband,
I'd drink it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
