u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-COURT-SETTLEMENTS-2TA     07-15 1026
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COURT-SETTLEMENTS-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STATE COURTS STRIKING DOWN LAWS THAT LIMIT LIABILITY 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ill., N.H., Ky., Ind., Ore., Wis., Alaska, Colo., Ohio)  (mk) 
 By WILLIAM GLABERSON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   More than a decade after states began enacting laws to cut back
big jury awards and curtail injury lawsuits, state courts across
the country are overturning one measure after another, concluding
that Americans have a powerful right to settle their disputes in
court.
</P>
<P>
   Top courts in states like Illinois, New Hampshire, Kentucky and,
most recently, Indiana on July 8 and Oregon on Thursday, have
relied on provisions of state constitutions like guarantees of fair
access to the courts to strike down all or part of the new laws
that were passed under the banner of ``tort reform.'' The new
liability laws make it more difficult to bring some suits and seek
to limit how much people can collect in accident, malpractice and
other injury cases.
</P>
<P>
   The highest courts of at least seven states have struck down all
or part of new liability laws in the last three years. Dozens of
new challenges to such laws are working their way toward state
supreme courts across the country, including in Wisconsin, Alaska
and Colorado, and a major decision is expected soon from the
Supreme Court in Ohio, which enacted a sweeping new liability law
two years ago. The cases focus on such state constitutional
guarantees of ``open courts'' or the right to a jury trial.
</P>
<P>
   In this rancorous second phase of the battle over the liability
system, at least 87 decisions by state courts at all levels have
found flaws with laws that have been enacted since the mid-1980s.
</P>
<P>
   ``The state courts are invalidating huge parts of the tort
reform legislation to the consternation of supporters of tort
reform,'' said professor Mark Geistfeld of New York University Law
School. ``There is much more judicial hostility to this kind of
legislation than anyone was expecting.''
</P>
<P>
   The laws have also been upheld by lower courts across the
country, with judges taking sides in one of the country's fiercest
but least noted legal wars. In a decision this January, the
Virginia Supreme Court, one of the few top state courts to affirm
the new laws recently, said a law limiting damages in malpractice
cases passed muster under that state's constitution. But legal
experts on both sides of the issue say the momentum is clearly on
the side of the critics of the new laws.
</P>
<P>
   In its decision Thursday striking down a law limiting to
$500,000 the amount of damages injured people can recover for pain
and suffering, the Oregon Supreme Court said that state's
constitution ``prohibits the legislature from interfering with the
full effect of a jury's assessment.''
</P>
<P>
   The decision came in a case involving a man who was brain
damaged and partly paralyzed when a pneumatic nail gun
malfunctioned, sending a 3-inch nail into his skull. A jury had
awarded the man and his wife more than $2.8 million in damages for
pain and suffering on top of more than $7 million in other
compensatory and punitive damages.
</P>
<P>
   The new liability laws, enacted in waves across the country
after intense lobbying by business groups, have tried various
approaches to limit what critics call frivolous suits that
unnecessarily tie up the courts and lead to outlandish awards.
</P>
<P>
   Business groups typically say limits are justified because of
what they call irrational verdicts, like the 1994 case of the
McDonald's customer who won a verdict of $2.9 million, later
reduced to $600,000, after she spilled scalding coffee on herself,
or the $4.9 billion verdict against General Motors last week in the
case of a fuel tank explosion.
</P>
<P>
   Business, professional, medical and other groups that have been
remarkably successful in pressing for liability law changes in the
legislatures of most states are incensed at the reversal of course.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is only recently that the state courts have begun
second-guessing state legislatures,'' said Richard Willard, a
Washington lawyer who represented Union Pacific Railroad in the
Illinois case that struck down that state's broad law.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is really no basis for it,'' Willard continued, ``other
than an assertion of raw power by the courts to overturn the will
of the popularly elected legislatures.''
</P>
<P>
   Consumer advocates and trial lawyers say the business lawyers
are simply being forced to contend with the reality that the laws
stripped consumers of fundamental rights.
</P>
<P>
   Robert Peck, legal director of the Association of Trial Lawyers
of America, who is coordinating several of the attacks on the laws,
said business groups had used political contributions to
effectively buy laws that immunized them from damage suits.
</P>
<P>
   ``The problem they are having now,'' Peck said, ``is that these
laws frequently violate fundamental state constitutional principles
and the courts are saying so.''
</P>
<P>
   Because the legislatures in the New York region have been far
less aggressive in enacting new liability laws than most other
states, the significant court battles are not now in the courts in
New York, Connecticut and New Jersey.
</P>
<P>
   Business lawyers said the national trend of decisions
invalidating the laws simply represents judges' coming to the aid
of the trial lawyers, who often use campaign contributions and
political clout to press their cause. Victor Schwartz, a Washington
lawyer who is one of the chief legal strategists for business
groups on liability issues, said the reversals in state courts were
the biggest threat in decades to what he calls liability reform.
</P>
<P>
   ``The trial lawyers' strategy,'' Schwartz said, ``is to find
obscure provisions of state constitutions or provisions of state
constitutions that have more rubber than Goodyear has in a tire to
allow a court to do whatever it wants to nullify the intent of the
legislature.''
</P>
<P>
   The state courts are relying on provisions of state
constitutions like those giving citizens the ``right to a remedy''
in more than 35 state constitutions. Legal experts say many of the
provisions have received little judicial interpretation before.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Some of the provisions have no parallel in the U.S.
Constitution. But even where there is similar language, like the
guarantee that citizens have a right to equal protection of the
laws, many of the decisions have been made on the state
constitutional grounds alone. As a result, state supreme court
decisions cannot be appealed.
</P>
<P>
   When striking down the liability laws, some courts use language
suggesting that they are offended by the legislation. In the 1997
Illinois decision, one of the most influential, the court said the
Legislature disregarded a century-long tradition concerning the
role of juries and the courts when it enacted a 1995 law, which,
among other provisions, limited damages to $500,000 to compensate
injured people for pain and suffering.
</P>
<P>
   In a case brought by the family of a 20-year-old truck driver
who had been killed when a train smashed into his truck at a
railroad crossing, the court said the $500,000 limit violated the
Illinois constitution.
</P>
<P>
   The ruling by Justice Mary Ann McMorrow said the law
``arbitrarily and automatically reduces the jury's award for a
lifetime of pain and disability, without regard to whether the
verdict, before reduction, was reasonable and fair.''
</P>
<P>
   Some judges have expressed equally strong sentiments in
upholding the laws. In its decision in January, the Virginia
Supreme Court rejected the argument that a law limiting damages in
medical malpractice cases to $1 million violated the state
constitution's guarantee of a right to trial by jury.
</P>
<P>
   In that case, the husband of a woman who died after she was
treated in an emergency room sued, claiming her condition had been
misdiagnosed. The jury agreed and set damages at $2.04 million. The
judge reduced the award to $1 million and the husband appealed.
</P>
<P>
   In a decision written by the state's chief justice, Harry
Carrico, the court upheld the law, saying the husband had had a
jury trial. ``It is not the role of the jury but of the legislature
to determine the legal consequences of the jury's factual
findings,'' Carrico said, concluding that there was no violation of
the right to a jury trial merely because a plaintiff did not
receive the full amount the jury had awarded.
</P>
<P>
   In 1997, Schwartz, who is the general counsel of the American
Tort Reform Association, a group pressing for liability limits,
wrote a scholarly article that was one of the first to identify the
trend of ``judicial nullification'' of the new liability laws.
</P>
<P>
   Schwartz, a former law school dean, said in an interview this
week that he had counted 87 decisions by state courts at all levels
that had declared all or part of new liability laws invalid in
recent years.
</P>
<P>
   His article, published by the conservative Washington Legal
Foundation, has received wide circulation among business lawyers as
a harbinger of what some of them see as a kind of stealth attack on
the new laws.
</P>
<P>
   The article also identified more than 100 decisions upholding
the laws since the era of so-called tort reform began in 1983. But
Schwartz and other lawyers for business say the momentum is toward
declaring the new limits on lawsuits unconstitutional, with more
high-level state courts striking down more significant liability
laws recently.
</P>
<P>
   In a decision on July 8, the Indiana Supreme Court was presented
with a doctor's claim that a malpractice suit filed by a woman
suffering from breast cancer should be dismissed because it was not
filed within a new time limit of two years after the alleged
malpractice had occurred.
</P>
<P>
   But as the court pointed out, in an opinion by Justice Myra
Selby, the heart of the suit was that the woman claimed the doctor
had misdiagnosed her condition. As a result, she said, she had not
discovered she had breast cancer until three years after she saw
the doctor.
</P>
<P>
   To enforce the law, the court said, would have meant the woman
would have been barred from court because she did not file her
malpractice suit at a time when she thought she was healthy. The
court said it would be unconstitutional to apply the law in that
case. Any other decision, Selby said, ``would be boarding the bus
to topsy-turvy land.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-15-99 2032EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990715.0375 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-15 20:33 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1848 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FLEET-BANKS-BOS &LR;      07-15 0894
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FLEET-BANKS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOREIGN INVESORS EYEING FLEET-BANKBOSTON BRANCH SALE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By LYNNLEY BROWNING  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON -- While the country's biggest banks have so far shied
away from the largest bank divestiture in US history, community
institutions and even foreign financial companies are gaining
momentum to try to use Fleet-BankBoston's mammoth branch sale to
expand in New England.
</P>
<P>
   None of the nation's household-name banks has jumped at the
chance to buy the nearly $15 billion in assets that Fleet Financial
Group Inc. is selling as part of its historic merger with
BankBoston Corp., according to sources close to the sale.
</P>
<P>
   ``Are any of the top 10 banks pursuing the opportunity to buy
these assets? The answer is `no,' '' a source involved in the sale
said Thursday. Bidding for the assets closed last month.
</P>
<P>
   Reports of a lack of interest from leading players like Bank of
America, Chase Manhattan, and First Union come as Fleet is
earmarking around 15 percent of the branches and deposits for sale
to community banks.
</P>
<P>
   In recent weeks, Masssachusetts congressmen and Governor Paul
Cellucci have lobbied fiercely for smaller banks to be allowed a
shot at some of the assets. The Department of Justice, which must
approve the $16-billion merger, bowed to political pressure last
month to include smaller banks in the divestiture process.
</P>
<P>
   Cellucci said Thursday that Fleet's chief executive, Terrence
Murray, told him in a telephone call that Fleet would invite a
dozen community banks in next week to discuss which Massachusetts
branches they want to buy.
</P>
<P>
   ``They will need some bigger bidders as competitors, but the
community banks are good competitors too,'' Cellucci said.
</P>
<P>
   The Justice Department and Federal Reserve Board, which must
also approve the merger, are said to want a large competitor to
acquire most of the assets to provide a strong competitor to the
new Fleet.
</P>
<P>
   But regulators have a loose definition of large, banking
analysts and consultants said, and have historically approved
divestiture sales in which mid-sized banks emerge as the main
winners.
</P>
<P>
   The lack of giant bidders is likely to please Fleet, which is
keen to avoid having to compete against a strong retail bank based
outside the region. ``Fleet doesn't want a First Union or a Bank of
America coming in,'' said Gerard Cassidy, a banking analyst at
Tucker Cleary.
</P>
<P>
   Industry observers see several reasons for the lack of interest
from big banks.
</P>
<P>
   In a rapidly consolidating industry that has created a handful
of giant institutions with hundreds of billions of dollars in
assets, big banks are too busy digesting recent acquisitions to
make plays for more.
</P>
<P>
   Some of those deals have stumbled. First Union Corp, the
Charlotte, N.C.-based bank that has gobbled up other banks, is
struggling to regain investor confidence after months of declining
profits. The acquisitive bank, the nation's sixth largest, has
become a cautionary tale for other banks seeking to grow.
</P>
<P>
   Another barrier is the size of Fleet-BankBoston's divested
assets. The lot is only a fraction of the size of the new company,
which will be the nation's eighth-largest bank, with over $160
billion in assets. Major banks, some with global operations, may
see little point in trying to gain a minor foothold in New England.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nobody in banking has really expected the truly big,
out-of-state banks to be interested,'' said Arnold Danielson, a
banking consultant in Rockville, Md. ``If you're a $250 billion
bank, buying the assets and getting a third position in the Boston
area without any ready-made infrastructure could hurt your earnings
for the next three to four years.''
</P>
<P>
   Most of the assets being sold are in Massachusetts, where Fleet
is selling nearly its entire franchise, or 197 branches with $8.7
billion in deposits and $1 billion in loans. BankBoston is selling
assets in Connecticut and Rhode Island. The two banks expect to
announce winning bidders in coming weeks and to close their merger
later this year.
</P>
<P>
   The two banks, which must sell the branches and deposits to meet
antitrust requirements, have received more than 50 bids, with over
40 coming from community banks, according to banking sources.
</P>
<P>
   An industry source said Fleet had winnowed the bidders to eight
to 10 banks, not including the community banks. Fleet declined
Thursday to confirm or deny a Boston Herald report saying that the
list included Citizens Financial Group of Providence; Charter One
Financial Inc. of Cleveland; Sovereign Bancorp of Wyomissing,
Penn., and one global banking giant, London-based HSBC Holdings.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is certainly no final list, because this is a fluid
process,'' said Fleet spokesman James Mahoney.
</P>
<P>
   The banks all have assets in the $25 billion to $40 billion
range, save for HSBC, a financial services behemoth with $483
billion in assets. ``Each of those names is acquisitive and has an
interest in the Northeast,'' said analyst Thomas Theurkauf of
Keefe, Bruyette &AMP; Woods.
</P>
<P>
   Cassidy said he thought that two Canadian banks _ Scotia Bank
and Canadian Imperial _ were also on the list. Scotia acquired some
of the failed Bank of New England's assets earlier this decade,
while Canadian Imperial owns New York-based stock brokerage CIBC
Oppenheimer.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
