<DOCNO> NYT19990715.0378 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-15 20:36 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1851 &Cx1f; tad-z
u p &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BUSH-MONEY16-COX     07-15 1027
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUSH-MONEY16-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Bush bounty draws criticism
 &HT;    By Ken Herman and Scott S. Greenberger
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Gov. George W. Bush's high-speed political cash
machine has bought him front-runner status, freedom from campaign
spending limits and blistering rebuke from critics who say he is
single-handedly undoing reforms aimed at separating money from
politics.
</P>
<P>
   Bush, who on Thursday filed a federal report showing he has
collected more than $37 million for his presidential campaign,
announced in Iowa that he has enough money in the bank to skip
federal matching funds for the primaries and the spending limits
they bring.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to be in a position to respond,'' said Bush, who will
be free to go dollar-for-dollar with the deep pockets of GOP foe
Steve Forbes, who will not take the federal money.
</P>
<P>
   Bush also wants to avoid the fate of 1996 GOP nominee Bob Dole,
who ran out of money after the primaries and had to moth-ball his
campaign until federal funds flowed after the Republican National
Convention in August.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm mindful of what happened in 1996 and I'm not going to let
it happen to me,'' said Bush. ``I'm going to win.''
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a chance I'll be running against somebody who will be
able to jump in a government airplane and travel the country making
promises,'' Bush said of Vice President Al Gore. ``I want to be
able to respond. The best way to do that is to not take taxpayer
dollars.''
</P>
<P>
   But nonpartisan groups that monitor campaign finance said a
candidate who doesn't need the federal cash is too heavy on the
root of all political evil. Common Cause's top man said Bush's
unprecedented four-month cash harvest will turn the clock back on
campaign-finance reforms of the 1970s. ``I think the decision means
that he's turning his back on the principal post-Watergate reform
that was intended to take the White House off the auction block,''
said Don Simon, Common Cause's acting president. ``His decision
signals the 2000 presidential election may well be the most
expensive ever, and that the fund raising and potential corruption
is going to be out of control.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush said his money will allow him to maintain ``strategic
flexibility.''
</P>
<P>
   Simon called it something else.
</P>
<P>
   ``The flexibility he claims he's seeking is being purchased at
the expense of laws designed to preserve the integrity of the
elections process,'' said Simon. ``That's a poor bargain for the
American people.''
</P>
<P>
   Sheila Krumholz of the Washington-based Center for Responsive
Politics, a nonprofit group that tracks political money, said the
volume of money moving Bush's way makes it more important to see
where it's coming from.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a watershed event. This is not unlike Watergate and
the reforms that it spawned,'' she said. ``This is a real blow to
the partial public funding system, a system that's already
beleaguered by not having enough funding.''
</P>
<P>
   Krumholz said Bush should release the list of ``pioneers,''
friends and allies who have agreed to raise $100,000 each for the
race.
</P>
<P>
   ``People who bring in dozens of donors are far more important
than a person who makes one donation,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Bush has declined to release the list or say how many pioneers
he has. Bush spokeswoman Mindy Tucker said pioneers are merely
``people talking to their friends and family about Governor Bush's
message of compassionate conservatism.''
</P>
<P>
   She also said Bush's massive fund raising is a result of ``the
democratic process of people being able to express their opinion
about a candidate.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush, who has called for instant disclosure of campaign
contributions, still will have to play by federal rules that cap
individual contributions at $1,000 and political action committee
donations at $5,000.
</P>
<P>
   Bush's desire to skip the federal funds was driven by Steve
Forbes, the wealthy publisher who did not take the federal money
and spent $37.5 million of his own money in 1996 in a failed bid
for the GOP nomination. Though it did not help him win the
nomination, not having to follow spending rules helped Forbes,
previously a political unknown, buy near-instant credibility in
1996.
</P>
<P>
   The federal government matches the first $250 of each
individual's contributions to a candidate. Federal Election
Commission preliminary numbers show that candidates who take the
federal money for the primaries would be limited to spending $39.6
million.
</P>
<P>
   In the general election, all major-party candidates accept
federal money and agree not to raise additional money. However,
that money is supplemented by so-called ``soft money'' raised by
the political parties. Federal Election Commission preliminary
estimates show that each major-party candidate will get $66.1
million for their post-convention campaigns.
</P>
<P>
   Primary candidates who took the federal money in 1996 were
limited to spending about $1 million in Iowa and $600,000 in New
Hampshire. Forbes, unfettered by limits, spent almost $10 million
in Iowa and $5 million in New Hampshire.
</P>
<P>
   Forbes has not said how deep he will be willing to dip into his
pockets this time around. His report filed Thursday indicates he
plans on being generous to himself. Of the $9.5 million he raised
this year, $6.6 million came from himself.
</P>
<P>
   Forbes' spokeswoman Juleanna Glover Weiss said her candidate is
pleased that Bush is skipping the federal matching money. But she
questioned his motive.
</P>
<P>
   ``Steve made his decision not to accept federal funds because he
believes it is wrong,'' she said. ``Bush made the decision not to
accept it because he wants to win.''
</P>
<P>
   Arizona Sen. John McCain, a GOP presidential contender, said
Bush may be ``unintentionally adding to the already widespread
cynicism of the American people regarding the influence of special
interest money in politics.''
</P>
<P>
   Brian Kennedy, spokesman for GOP contender Lamar Alexander,
said, ``What's clearly is going on here is that Governor Bush is
trying to buy the nomination. He doesn't want to compete on a level
playing field. He wants to buy his way there.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
