A1859 &Cx1f; tad-z
u p &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CAMPAIGN-200016-COX     07-15 0765
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAMPAIGN-200016-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Bush won't take federal matching funds
 &HT;    By Mark Sherman
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Gov. George W. Bush of Texas said Thursday that his
eye-popping $37 million in campaign contributions for the first
half of 1999 will allow him to forgo federal matching funds for the
2000 primaries.
</P>
<P>
   Bush's report with the Federal Election Commission, filed
Thursday, shows that he has more than $30 million in available
cash.
</P>
<P>
   Campaigning in Iowa, the candidate said he would not accept
federal money and the state-by-state spending limits that go with
it to preserve ``strategic flexibility'' in his campaign.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to be in a position to respond and plan according to
needs, especially in key early states such as Iowa and New
Hampshire,'' Bush said.
</P>
<P>
   At this point, the only Republican whose campaign cash would
even approach that of Bush would be magazine publisher Steve
Forbes.
</P>
<P>
   He reported contributing $6.6 million from his personal fortune
so far in 1999 and raising an additional $2.9 million from others.
</P>
<P>
   Forbes has indicated he, too, will not take federal money. His
1996 presidential campaign was virtually self-financed.
</P>
<P>
   Forbes' main contribution three years ago was that his
aggressive advertising forced Bob Dole, the Republican front-runner
and eventual nominee, to spend heavily to counteract Forbes' ads.
</P>
<P>
   While Dole won the battle, he exhausted his money supply months
before the Republican convention.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton, meanwhile, faced no opposition for the
Democratic nomination and waged an expensive advertising campaign
through the spring and early summer that both Democrats and
Republicans believe seriously damaged Dole's candidacy.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm mindful of what happened in 1996, and I'm not going to let
it happen to me,'' Bush said. ``I'm going to win.''
</P>
<P>
   He also said he wants to have money available to compete with
Vice President Al Gore in the months before the party conventions,
at which nominees are formally chosen and become eligible for
millions of dollars in federal funds for the general election
campaign.
</P>
<P>
   ``I may be facing a Democratic candidate who may attempt to
travel around the country handing out expensive promises at
government expense,'' Bush said.
</P>
<P>
   GEORGIANS AIM TO RAISE BIG BUCKS FOR BUSH
</P>
<P>
   So how does a candidate like Bush raise that kind of cash? One
way is to find a lot of wealthy supporters who agree to lean on
their friends.
</P>
<P>
   Thirteen Georgians have agreed to raise $100,000 each for Bush,
and 90 more are on board for at least $10,000 each, according to
Eric Tanenblatt, Bush's campaign manager in Georgia. The commitment
from this group of 103 is a minimum of $2.2 million.
</P>
<P>
   One of the 13 in the $100,000 club is Krishna Srinivasa of
Dallas, Ga. He has been a significant source of Republican campaign
funds in Georgia since he first wowed the Bush team when he was the
leading ticket-seller for President George Bush at a campaign event
in suburban Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   Other experienced and generous hands include Virgil Williams,
the Gwinnett County business tycoon who helped Democrat Zell Miller
raise millions for his run for governor in 1990; Julian LeCraw, an
Atlanta real estate executive; Amos McMullian, chairman and chief
executive of the baking concern Flowers Industries; and Joe Rogers,
Waffle House chief executive.
</P>
<P>
   The rest of the 13 are: Charles Ackerman, an Atlanta developer;
John Carswell, a Savannah insurance and financial services
executive; James Franklin, a lawyer in Statesboro; Winnie LeClercq,
whose family owns Cub Foods and an interest in Food Lion; James B.
Miller, president of the Fidelity National banking company; Parker
H. ``Pete'' Petit, a Cobb County health care executive; Stephen
Wakefield, general counsel for the Southern Co.; and Joel Williams,
a lawyer with Powell, Goldstein, Frazier &AMP; Murphy in Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   Candidates to visit Atlanta today
</P>
<P>
   Former Red Cross President and Cabinet Secretary Elizabeth Dole
and conservative activist Gary Bauer are both expected in Atlanta
today.
</P>
<P>
   Dole will hold a news conference outside the main Fulton County
library downtown to talk about shielding library users from
pornography on the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   She plans to lunch at the Varsity, then talk to Chick-Fil-A
employees. Dole and Chick-Fil-A founder Truett Cathy believe they
are distant relations.
</P>
<P>
   Bauer is scheduled to hold a news conference outside Ft.
McPherson to talk about defense spending.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
