<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-15 20:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1864 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-R-WARNER-BROTHERS-ART     07-15 1025
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-R-WARNER-BROTHERS-ART-960(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STARTLING DEPARTURE AT THE TOP OF WARNER BROTHERS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Eds.: Repeating to add graphics note; no other changes.) 
(ATTN: Calif., N.Y.)  (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036.) 
(jw) 
 By BERNARD WEINRAUB and GERALDINE FABRIKANT   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   In a move that stunned the entertainment business, Robert Daly
and Terry Semel, the co-chairmen of Warner Brothers, announced
their resignations Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Daly and Semel, whose nearly 20-year partnership was one of the
most stable and successful in Hollywood history, have endured a
string of box-office flops in recent years as well as a luckluster
music record. But they said their decision was unrelated to that.
</P>
<P>
   They had been considering leaving for several months, they said,
and had discussed the idea informally with Gerald Levin, chairman
of the studio's parent company, Time Warner. They told Levin of
their decision late Wednesday in New York, on the eve of Time
Warner's board meeting.
</P>
<P>
   The resignations came after Time Warner reported
better-than-expected second-quarter earnings Thursday, on the eve
of Warner Brothers' highly anticipated release of ``Eyes Wide
Shut,'' starring Tom Cruise and Nicole Kidman, the last movie made
by Stanley Kubrick, who died in March.
</P>
<P>
   Daly, 62, and Semel, 55, said they told Levin they wanted to
join forces as entertainment entrepreneurs. ``If I was ever to
pursue another challenge in my life, I felt the time was now,''
Semel said.
</P>
<P>
   The decision immediately cast the normally stable Warner
Brothers studios in turmoil. As to possible replacements,
speculation centered on, among others, Barry Meyer, executive vice
president and chief operating officer, who is popular on Wall
Street; Jeff Bewkes, chairman and chief executive of Home Box
Office, who is close to Ted Turner, vice chairman and 11 percent
owner of Time Warner; Joe Roth, chairman of Walt Disney Studios;
Jeffrey Katzenberg, a partner at Dreamworks SKG; Peter Chernin,
president and chief operating officer of News Corp., which owns
20th Century Fox, and Leslie Moonves, a former head of Warner
Brothers television and now president and chief executive of CBS
television.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking for Time Warner, Levin said he was saddened by the
decision. ``There is never a good time to lose this kind of
talent,'' he said, ``but our film, TV and music businesses, and our
company as a whole, are in excellent shape, and there is tremendous
depth of management throughout our organization.''
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a deeply personal decision,'' he added. ``What they
decided to do was something very human.'' He said the two had come
to a point in their lives ``where they can think about
themselves.'' Levin said Daly and Semel would play a central role
in creating a new team, but made it clear he would make the final
decision.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am the CEO,'' he said. ``I will think this through.''
</P>
<P>
   Privately, top Hollywood agents said that even though Daly and
Semel in recent months had made known their interest in leaving,
they had been wavering. One agent said preliminary talks with Time
Warner indicated that the company wanted to wrest the troubled
music division away from the pair. It was, the agent said, a factor
in the final decision. The music division, run by Daly and Semel,
has fared poorly.
</P>
<P>
   Once the most successful music company in the industry, Warner
music has been mired in management turmoil. After the controversial
departure of its longtime management team several years ago, Levin
turned first to Michael Fuchs, the former chairman of HBO, and then
to Daly and Semel. By all accounts, the team was relatively
inexperienced in the music business, and the division was only
lately starting to recover.
</P>
<P>
   According to Soundscan, which tracks industry performance,
Warner Music was fourth in album sales after Universal, BMG and
Sony. In total domestic share, including catalog sales, Warner has
remained second after Universal, but its market share has slipped.
</P>
<P>
   Daly and Semel _ as well as Levin _ insisted that no contract
talks had begun, and that the decision was simply based on their
yearning to create and own their own ventures. But there was
speculation by several top Hollywood executives that the two _ who
were unaccustomed to criticism in the media _ had simply grown
thin-skinned and weary over attacks on their film record.
</P>
<P>
   Their most recent big-budget film, ``Wild, Wild West,'' while
No. 1 at the box office last week, was poorly received by critics
and may barely earn a profit, if at all. The film cost an estimated
$180 million, rivals and agents say, but Warner Brothers said it
was much lower.
</P>
<P>
   The decision by Daly and Semel to leave at the end of the year
marked the end of an enduring partnership, involving two stolid,
tough and unflashy businessmen. Their films included the lucrative
``Batman'' and ``Lethal Weapon'' franchises. Even more important,
Warner Brothers was just about the only studio in town to develop a
reputation for stability _ even during bleak periods it avoided
bloodletting and nurtured a loyalty among its well-paid employees.
</P>
<P>
   Even by Hollywood standards, the two executives are enormously
wealthy. Their yearly compensation is believed to be as high as $25
million each. Semel's accumulated wealth is estimated as high as
$500 million, largely because of soaring Time Warner stock. Daly's
is said to be less, perhaps $300 million, because of a divorce
settlement. The two men declined to discuss their incomes.
</P>
<P>
   Hollywood moguls said they were amazed at the departures. Roth,
of Disney, was awakened by a phone call from a reporter this
morning with the news. ``I'm as shocked as you are,'' he said, and
denied having any discussions about a top job there. Katzenberg
heard about it in the restaurant of the Four Seasons Hotel in New
York.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a breathtaker,'' he said, adding: ``These two guys are
the Mark McGwire and Sammy Sosa of the movie business.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   As to his moving to Warner Brothers, Katzenberg said, ``There's
no chance. It's not in the world of possibilities.''
</P>
<P>
   Daly and Semel made it plain that in some ways they were seeking
to kick off their new careers by emulating Barry Diller, now
chairman and chief executive of USA Networks and its largest
shareholder.
</P>
<P>
   In recent months, the two have held private discussions with
Diller to discuss the pitfalls of striking out on one's own. ``I
always envied what Barry Diller did,'' Daly said.
</P>
<P>
   Diller said he had been speaking privately for more than a year
with Daly and Semel. ``They want a third act,'' Diller said. ``The
difference for them, as opposed to most people, is that they're
sitting on a big empire. And, as I told them, choosing independence
over empire is very scary to do, the longer you let it go.''
</P>
<P>
   Diller said he was convinced that Time Warner wanted to renew
the contracts of Semel and Daly. ``There's no question of that,''
Diller said. ``Bob and Terry just wanted to choose independence.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
