<HEADLINE>
NEW YORK TIMES CORRECTIONS FOR FRIDAY, JULY 16
</HEADLINE>
 Eds.: These corrections will appear in The New York Times on
Friday. Days and dates refer to the original article's transmission
by the New York Times News Service, and may need to be adjusted by
NYT clients.)  
(gc) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BC-CONGRESS-FAMILIES-ADS-NYT (moved on Monday, July 12)
</P>
<P>
   A New York Times News Service article sent on Monday, July 12,
about an arrangement by the National Association of Broadcasters to
televise the wives of Congressmen in public service advertisements
referred incorrectly to the main legislation sought by the
broadcasters. It would let satellite companies carry over-the-air
broadcasts from local television stations but prohibit them from
carrying distant signals if an adequate local broadcast was
available. It would not prohibit them altogether from carrying
over-the-air signals.
</P>
<P>
   BC-REPUBS-TAX-NYT (moved on Friday, July 9)
</P>
<P>
   A New York Times News Service article sent on Friday, July 9,
about the Republican tax proposal in the Senate referred
incorrectly to the current rates. The 15 percent bracket applies to
taxable income up to $25,750 for single people and $43,050 for
married couples filing jointly, not to adjusted gross income _ that
is, income before the standard or itemized deductions.
</P>
<P>
   BC-TAX-CUTS-NYT (moved on Tuesday, July 13)
</P>
<P>
   A New York Times News Service article sent on Tuesday, July 13,
about the effect of potential tax cuts on the economy misstated the
proposal of Senator Connie Mack, Republican of Florida. His plan
calls for $766 billion in cuts over 10 years, with $137 billion of
that amount coming in the first five years, not a total of $137
billion for the decade.
</P>
<P>
   BC-OBIT-O'BRIEN-NYT (moved on Saturday, July 10)
</P>
<P>
   The obituary of Mark O'Brien, sent by the New York Times News
Service on Saturday, July 10, referred incorrectly to an editor for
whom he worked. The editor, Sandy Close, is a woman.
</P>
<P>
   BC-OBIT-TRUMP-NYT (moved on Friday, June 25)
</P>
<P>
   The obituary of Fred C. Trump sent by the New York Times News
Service on Friday, June 25, misstated the location of the White
Horse Restaurant and Inn where his father supplied food and lumber
to miners in the gold rush. It was in the Yukon Territory, not in
Alaska.
</P>
</TEXT>
