<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COCACOLA-EARNINGS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COCA-COLA'S 2D QUARTER PROFITS FALL 21 PERCENT 
 (DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By CONSTANCE L. HAYS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   In part because it had to pull millions of soft drinks off the
market in Europe last month, the Coca-Cola Co.'s second-quarter
profit fell 21 percent, the company said on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   In the quarter ended June 30, net income dropped to $942
million, or 38 cents a diluted share, compared with $1.19 billion,
or 48 cents a share, in the quarter a year earlier.
</P>
<P>
   Worldwide sales volume, measured in cases of finished drinks,
fell 2 percent, compared with a 10 percent increase in the period a
year earlier. The company appears to be spending heavily on
marketing even as volume declines. It reported that revenue rose 4
percent, to $5.38 billion from $5.15 billion, but that sales,
administrative and general expenses increased 10 percent.
</P>
<P>
   The volume and earnings were about what Wall Street had
expected, and Coke shares rose $2.125, closing at $64.
</P>
<P>
   It was the fourth consecutive quarter in which Coke reported a
decline in earnings, but analysts seemed to take the results in
stride.
</P>
<P>
   ``The good news is, there's no incremental bad news,'' said
Jennifer Solomon, a beverage analyst with Salomon Smith Barney.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, Coca-Cola's top management, including its chairman
and chief executive, M. Douglas Ivester, has scheduled an unusual
meeting with analysts and investors in New York for next Thursday.
Topics on the agenda include the recall in Europe, global business
conditions and Coke's growth outlook.
</P>
<P>
   In a statement on Thursday, the company said the recall, which
began in Belgium on June 14 with hundreds of people saying they
became ill after drinking Coke products and spread to France,
Luxembourg and the Netherlands, was a factor in its performance.
About 17 million cases of Coke products had to be recalled and
destroyed.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, two plants in Belgium and a third in France were
shut down while Coca-Cola sought to determine what had made people
ill. The company concluded that a flawed batch of carbon dioxide,
used to carbonate its soft drinks, from a Belgian plant may have
caused a bad smell in one set of products and that a phenol
compound used to protect shipping crates in the French plant may
have done the same thing. But in both cases, Coca-Cola maintained
that the substances it detected were present in amounts too tiny to
have made anyone ill.
</P>
<P>
   The recall's effect on Coca-Cola's earnings was 2 to 3 cents a
share, the company said.
</P>
<P>
   While volume fell 6 percent in European markets, it declined in
many other places, as well. In China, volume dropped 9 percent, a
decline the company attributed to severe flooding in the eastern
part of the country last month and to the fallout from the bombing
by the United States of the Chinese Embassy in Belgrade,
Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
   In India, volume rose 2 percent, far less than in the second
quarter of 1998, when it grew 33 percent. Again, the weather was at
fault, Coca-Cola said, noting that the early monsoons decreased
sales near the end of the quarter. Over all, volume fell 2 percent
in the Middle East and East Asian division.
</P>
<P>
   Volume was flat in Latin America, compared with a 12 percent
increase in the second quarter last year, and sales in countries
like Venezuela and Colombia continued to slide. In Africa, volume
fell 1 percent, mostly in the southern part of the continent, where
the company said unrest in Zimbabwe and economic weakness in South
Africa drove down demand.
</P>
<P>
   In the United States, volume fell 1 percent, compared with an 8
percent increase in the period a year earlier.
</P>
<P>
   In Japan, one of Coke's largest markets, volume grew 6 percent,
a turnaround from a 3 percent decline in the second quarter last
year.
</P>
<P>
   Equity income, from bottlers in which Coca-Cola holds a stake,
has fallen 83 percent so far this year, the company said. That pace
is ahead of last year's, when equity income decreased 79 percent, a
reflection of the sales slowdowns that bottlers are encountering.
</P>
<P>
   ``The equity-income line was supposed to be a nice contributor
to earnings growth,'' said Emanuel Goldman, a global consumer
products analyst for Merrill Lynch. ``It's backward now.''
</P>
<P>
   Of the quarter as a whole, he added: ``It's like Zeus was
hurling thunderbolts at them, and Zeus worked for Pepsi.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
