<DOCNO> NYT19990715.0393 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-15 20:51 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1869 &Cx1f; taf-z
s f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BIZ-FOR-ME-$ADV18-NYT     07-15 0870
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIZ-FOR-ME-$ADV18-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THIS BROKER REALLY TAKES A LONG VIEW  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, JULY 18) 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Tenn., S.C.)   (af)  
 By LAURA PEDERSEN-PIETERSEN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   I can't see what all the fuss is about,'' said Frank W.
Fletcher, 95, a stockbroker. ``My father was pushing a hand mower
well into his 90s.''
</P>
<P>
   And the way things are going in the workplace, there may soon be
no fuss whatsoever about people toiling into their 90s _ or even
their 100s. Not only are Americans living and working longer, but
in some fields, older workers are even being sought out.
</P>
<P>
   Consider the investment business, where a stampeding bull market
has produced legions of silver-haired millionaires-next-door. Many
older investors prefer to work with a broker of their own
generation, said David W. Wiley III, 44, who is Fletcher's boss at
Wiley Bros./Aintree Capital, a brokerage firm in Nashville.
</P>
<P>
   Recruiting the elderly is not just a brokerage-business
phenomenon. Seventy-something models are hired to appear in glossy
ads for makeup for the great-grandmother on the go, and 60-year-old
engineers are being hauled out of retirement by the
cruise-ship-full to work on Year 2000 problems. (After all, they
installed the stuff.) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Fletcher was born on Oct. 3, 1903, four months after an engineer
named Henry formed the Ford Motor Co. and 10 weeks before Orville
Wright made that famous flight. And when folks muttered about ``the
Depression'' back then, they meant the four years after the Panic
of 1893.
</P>
<P>
   In 1920, when Fletcher was a teen-ager, the market crashed
again, leaving four million people out of work. ``A dress rehearsal
for the big one,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The big crash, in 1929, came just four weeks after he married _
and the very week that he and his bride, Mary, visited the New York
Stock Exchange. ``The government did all the wrong things back then
_ we needed Alan Greenspan,'' said Fletcher, an unabashed admirer
of the current Federal Reserve chairman.
</P>
<P>
   After graduating from Vanderbilt University in 1925, Fletcher
joined his family's wholesale food business, soon becoming
president and staying until the company was sold in 1954.
</P>
<P>
   That year, at 51, Fletcher embarked on his second career,
joining the Eisenhower administration as deputy director of the
Agency for International Development. His first overseas posting,
in Amman, Jordan, coincided with the Suez crisis. ``It wasn't
exactly the time or place to be wearing an `I like Ike' button,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   In 1959, he returned to Nashville, to work on the presidential
campaign of Richard M. Nixon. But after John F. Kennedy's
inauguration in 1961, he again had to decide what to do with the
rest of his life. Some friends were ready to pull out the golf
clubs, but retirement at 58 held no appeal for him.
</P>
<P>
   He became an insurance salesman. ``I gave it a year,'' he
recalled, ``but selling insurance just didn't fit my personality.''
A friend suggested the investment business and invited him to join
Aintree Capital.
</P>
<P>
   There, in 1962, he began his fourth career. ``I loved this
business from the start,'' he said. ``And the good thing about it
is that you can be a broker while you play golf. In fact, people
here expect it of you.''
</P>
<P>
   He not only dispenses investment advice _ his current favorites
are Lincoln National Life, Lucent Technologies and BellSouth _ but
also career advice. To the young (anyone under 90), he says, ``Do
something you enjoy and you'll probably be successful.''
</P>
<P>
   Fletcher is his own best example. ``Every day something new is
happening with the markets,'' he said, ``so it's always exciting to
me, never boring.''
</P>
<P>
   His son, Frank Jr., 56, a stockbroker in Greenville, S.C.,
offers another perspective. ``When you're married to a Nashville
social queen, as he's been for decades, you'd better find a job to
go to every day,'' he said. Whatever the reason, he has clearly had
a successful marriage. He and Mrs. Fletcher, now 91, will celebrate
their 70th anniversary this fall.
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, there's work to be done. And it's not always a
cakewalk.
</P>
<P>
   Fletcher said that, as a broker, there are disadvantages to
getting old. ``Customers have died or turned their affairs over to
banks and investment companies,'' he said. ``And the young people
coming up want to deal with people in their own social circle.''
</P>
<P>
   But Wiley, Fletcher's boss, sees many pluses. ``Frank has a
great sense of humor,'' he said, ``and he's as mentally effective
as any 40-year-old, and sometimes more so.'' Wiley said older
workers add continuity and a much-needed long-term perspective
about the markets.
</P>
<P>
   A co-worker, J. Anthony Curcio, said: ``He's a voracious
consumer of financial commentary. Every morning he reads the
business papers with a four-inch magnifying glass, and if he sees
an article that would be of interest to another broker he takes it
right to them.''
</P>
<P>
   Fletcher has no plans to retire, but he acknowledges that there
are some things outside the office that he can no longer manage.
``I can't play golf anymore, I can't drink as much as I'd like and
there's one other thing I can't do but I can't remember what it is
so I guess it doesn't matter.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
