<SLUG> BC-OBIT-WYNDER-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DR. ERNST LUDWIG WYNDER, 77, HELPED LINK TOBACCO TO CANCERS 
</HEADLINE>
  (yn) 
 By WOLFGANG SAXON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Dr. Ernst Ludwig Wynder, who was the founding
president of the American Health Foundation and who posted early
warnings of cancers lurking in the environment, particularly for
smokers, died on Wednesday at the Memorial Sloan-Kettering Cancer
Center in Manhattan. He was 77 and had lived in Manhattan and in
Westport, Conn.
</P>
<P>
   The cause was cancer of the thyroid, said the foundation, a
nonprofit research organization that Wynder formed in 1969 and
guided at his death.
</P>
<P>
   Under the leadership of Wynder (pronounced WIN-der), the
foundation became one of the country's foremost private research
centers for preventive medicine and health maintenance, supported
largely by grants and contracts from the National Cancer Institute.
</P>
<P>
   The foundation has a staff of about 200 researchers, whose
specialties include epidemiology, synthetic chemistry,
biochemistry, nutrition sciences, experimental oncology, molecular
biology and the behavioral sciences.
</P>
<P>
   Much of the work is carried out in laboratories that Wynder
built on the grounds of the Westchester Medical Center in Valhalla,
N.Y. Additional research is done in Manhattan and elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
   Wynder himself was credited with furnishing biological proof
that tobacco smoke contained a cancer-producing substance. As a
researcher associated with Sloan-Kettering, he subsequently linked
excessive tobacco use with cancers of the oral cavity, esophagus,
larynx, pancreas and bladder.
</P>
<P>
   Working alone and in collaboration with others, he provided
chemical proof of the carcinogenic potential of tobacco smoke and
tobacco itself. The work effectively closed the circle of evidence
and tied cigarette smoking to an array of cancers.
</P>
<P>
   Ernst Wynder was born in Herford, Germany, in 1922 and came to
the United States in 1938. He graduated from New York University in
1943, the year he received his citizenship, and was a U.S. Army
intelligence officer in World War II.
</P>
<P>
   In 1950, he earned both a B.S. in medical science and his M.D.
at Washington University in St. Louis. While still a student there,
he began cancer research with his professor and mentor, Evarts A.
Graham.
</P>
<P>
   In one particular study of 605 men who had developed lung
cancer, the two men determined that smoking was a common factor. Of
those patients, 97 percent were heavy smokers while only 2 percent
were nonsmokers.
</P>
<P>
   Their work was generally regarded as the first major study to
make that link, and the American Medical Association hailed it in
1985 as landmark research.
</P>
<P>
   Wynder followed with a paper at Sloan-Kettering in 1953 in which
he presented evidence that condensate made from cigarette smoke,
painted onto the backs of mice, caused malignant tumors. Four years
later, the Surgeon General's office posted its first official
warning that excessive smoking may cause lung cancer.
</P>
<P>
   But the debate continued. As recently as 1994, the heads of the
major tobacco companies in the United States swore before a
Congressional subcommittee that nicotine was not addictive and
might not be a cause of cancer after all.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to research on tobacco-related cancers, Wynder led
studies comparing the incidence of various types of cancer with
demographic and clinical data in foreign countries.
</P>
<P>
   For instance, the role of poor nutrition in cancers of the upper
alimentary tract were highlighted in research that Wynder conducted
in collaboration with Swedish colleagues. They identified iron
deficiency as a key factor in Plummer-Vinson syndrome, a painful
disorder afflicting some middle-aged women. As a result, an iron
supplement was added to flour, ending the sickness in Sweden.
</P>
<P>
   Wynder wrote or contributed to more than 700 papers and received
many honors in this country and in Europe. He was a principal
author of ``Environmental Aspects of Cancer: The Role of Macro and
Minor Components of Food'' (1988, Food and Nutrition Press).
</P>
<P>
   He started his work at the Sloan-Kettering Institute for Cancer
Research in 1952 as an assistant researcher and rose to chief of
epidemiology. After he created the American Health Foundation, he
continued his association with Sloan-Kettering as an associate
scientist into the 1980s.
</P>
<P>
   Wynder is survived by his wife, Sandra Miller Wynder, and a
sister, Lore Levinson of Springfield, N.J.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
