<SLUG> BC-FBC-BIGWEST-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLOCK TICKING FOR CAL STATE NORTHRIDGE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By LEE BARNATHAN  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ From his office in Ogden, Utah, Big Sky Conference
commissioner Doug Fullerton sadly watches the events unfold around
the Cal State Northridge football team and knows time is running
out.
</P>
<P>
   Northridge remains a member of the Big Sky for now, but who
knows for how much longer?
</P>
<P>
   Northridge's inability to build the larger football stadium
required by the Big Sky continues to frustrate Fullerton. He sees
Sacramento State's intent to comply and would like to see
Northridge follow.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're down to `You need to do something now,' '' Fullerton
said. ``We would love to have them have an on-campus stadium.''
</P>
<P>
   There's also talk of Northridge one day joining the Big West
Conference, which is in a state of flux. The nonfootball members
such as Cal State Fullerton and Long Beach State would like to
reconfigure into an all-California conference without football.
Football members such as Boise State, Idaho and Utah State are
being courted by several conferences, including the Big Sky.
</P>
<P>
   Long Beach State athletic director Bill Shumard said Northridge
would be considered for Big West membership should an
all-California conference become reality. A source also said
Northridge interim president Louanne Kennedy has informally
mentioned to her colleagues she would be interested in the Big
West.
</P>
<P>
   However, this is all just talk. Northridge athletic director
Dick Dull said neither he nor anyone else within the department has
contacted anyone about the Big West. Besides, first must come the
resolution of the ongoing investigation into possible violations
within the football program. Offensive coordinator Rob Phenicie has
already resigned, and findings could be released today.
</P>
<P>
   Northridge has been granted an extension to build the stadium.
Dull said he expects to receive guidelines next week when the Big
Sky ADs meet in Park City, Utah.
</P>
<P>
   Dull also agreed this is a time of conference reconfiguration
and any institution, including Northridge, should keep its options
open.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have not initiated anything,'' Dull said. ``We are members
in the Big Sky Conference. We value our membership in the Big
Sky.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, commissioner Fullerton wonders about Northridge.
</P>
<P>
   `` `Snakebit' is a good word,'' Fullerton said. ``I feel bad
they haven't gotten everything under control. It seems it's one
thing after another.''
</P>
</TEXT>
