<SLUG> BC-BUSH-MONEY-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSH'S DECISION TO FORGO FEDERAL MATCHING FUNDS DRAWS CRITICISM 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By R.G. RATCLIFFE 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Gov. George W. Bush's victory in the checkbook
primary of the Republican presidential contest and his decision
Thursday to forgo federal matching funds may have cost him some
moral high ground in the presidential race.
</P>
<P>
   His opponents are claiming that his massive fund-raising
operation, which has raised $37 million, has essentially corrupted
the democratic process by marginalizing lesser-funded candidates.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some in our party don't want the voters to have a say in
picking our nominee,'' Republican candidate Lamar Alexander said.
</P>
<P>
   ``They want to hold an auction on the White House lawn and sell
the presidency to the highest bidder,'' said Alexander, the former
Tennessee governor and U.S. education secretary. ``These moneyed
interests contend the so-called money primary matters more than the
Iowa caucuses or the New Hampshire primary.''
</P>
<P>
   Sen. John McCain, R-Arizona, who has made campaign finance
reform a cornerstone of his Senate terms and his campaign, said
Bush's decision to pass on matching funds and required spending
limits sends the wrong signal.
</P>
<P>
   ``By refusing to abide by the accepted guidelines, Governor Bush
may be unintentionally adding to the already widespread cynicism of
the American people regarding the influence of special interest
money in politics,'' McCain said.
</P>
<P>
   Bush has raised almost twice as much money as all of his
Republican opponents combined.
</P>
<P>
   Such a daunting prospect led in part to the decision by Sen. Bob
Smith, R-N.H., to drop out of the race and leave the Republican
Party earlier this week. And Rep. John Kasich, R-Ohio, dropped out
of the race and endorsed Bush.
</P>
<P>
   Other candidates have been complaining about Bush's
record-setting fund-raising.
</P>
<P>
   Former Vice President Dan Quayle last week said, ``Message, not
money, is what counts in 2000.''
</P>
<P>
   Alan Keyes called Bush the ``virtual reality'' candidate
fabricated by the ``money bosses and the media.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Each of the dollars he gets is a shackle tying him to the
interests of the monied establishment of this country that has
shown a willingness to sell out our conscience,'' Keyes said.
</P>
<P>
   Bush has not been criticized on the money issue by Steve Forbes,
who spent $36 million of his own money on an unsuccessful
presidential bid in 1996. Bush cited Forbes' candidacy this time as
the main reason he is rejecting the federal matching funds, which
contain spending limits.
</P>
<P>
   Forbes has already contributed $6.6 million of his own money to
the $2.7 million he raised from potential voters.
</P>
<P>
   Elizabeth Dole, whose husband Bob set the previous campaign
fund-raising record of about $31.3 million in the first half of
1995, also has not specifically criticized Bush's fund-raising.
</P>
<P>
   But Dole has noted that ``there are a number of other Texans who
raised huge amounts of money but did not carry the ball across the
finish line.''
</P>
<P>
   Former Texas Gov. John Connally spent $13 million in 1980 in an
unsuccessful presidential bid.
</P>
<P>
   Ellen Miller, executive director of Public Campaign, a campaign
finance reform group, said Bush ``has thumbed his nose at the
voters' sense of fair play'' by rejecting the federal matching
funds spending limits.
</P>
<P>
   ``The governor is now free to blow other candidates out of the
political water well before the voters of this country even get
their say,'' Miller said.
</P>
<P>
   Bush said his campaign fund-raising does not violate the spirit
of democracy because he has raised money from more than 70,000
people across the country and lived within the $1,000-per-person
contribution limits.
</P>
<P>
   Bush also has proposed campaign finance reform, including:
</P>
<P>
   _ Banning soft money to political parties from unions and
corporations.
</P>
<P>
   _ Instant disclosure of contributions on the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   _ Raising individual contributions limits to more than the
current $1,000 to allow greater financing of all candidates.
</P>
<P>
   Dole has said she would support raising the individual limit to
$5,000 a person. She noted that the current limit was set in 1974.
</P>
<P>
   ``It doesn't even reflect the rate of inflation,'' Dole said.
</P>
<P>
   Alexander wants to remove the limit altogether, but require
instant disclosure as Bush wants.
</P>
<P>
   However, removing the limits might not help other candidates.
Several people who could only give Bush $1,000 for his presidential
race could give him contributions akin to the $100,000 they each
gave him for his gubernatorial races in Texas where there are no
contribution limits.
</P>
<P>
   Alexander also has called on a moratorium on public opinion
polls by news organizations because he feels they influence who
receives contributions.
</P>
<P>
   McCain has made a ban on all soft money to political parties his
campaign mantra. He has described the contributions as a back-door
way to influence presidents and Congress. However, McCain also
could support raising the individual contribution limits to
presidential candidates if certain other reforms also passed, he
says.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
