<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-15 20:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1875 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ARRINGTON16-COX     07-15 1402
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ARRINGTON16-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Racial issues part of mixed legacy of Birmingham mayor
 &HT;    By Marlon Manuel
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   BIRMINGHAM, Ala. _ Finance and health care have replaced steel
and coal as the economic muscle of this town. But other aspects are
harder to change. Political vision, for instance, remains tinted in
black and white.
</P>
<P>
   And so it is with the legacy of Richard Arrington.
</P>
<P>
   The son of sharecroppers, the first black man elected mayor of
Alabama's largest city, Arrington retires today after a 20-year
tenure.
</P>
<P>
   How he will be remembered, his oldest critics say, is a matter
of race. Ardent supporters, several of them white business leaders,
contend history will look favorably on Arrington's two decades.
</P>
<P>
   Social changes abound. The city council has a black majority
thanks to Arrington's political machine. City contracts with black
firms over the years total in the millions, after amounting to less
than $1,000 in 1976.
</P>
<P>
   The Civil Rights Institute, supported by city tax money, stands
as a memorial and tourist attraction erected on Birmingham's
confrontational past. Arrington worked to eliminate police
brutality from the white-dominated police force he inherited, a
group then only 16 years removed from the head-cracking days of
police commissioner Eugene ``Bull'' Connor, who used dogs to attack
civil rights demonstrators.
</P>
<P>
   ``You probably had exaggerated black expectations and
exaggerated white anxiety, neither of which was justified,'' said
Maynard Jackson, Atlanta's first black mayor, who was midway
through his second term when Arrington was elected in 1979.
</P>
<P>
   ``But you had to manage that politically,'' Jackson said. ``He
had to do it; I had to do it. Eventually, you get past that. You
have to manage change and manage these expectations. ... He's been
an outstanding transition mayor from the old Birmingham to the new
Birmingham.''
</P>
<P>
   Normally dressed in tailored suits, Arrington spent Thursday
cleaning out his office in agolf shirt, blue jeans and sandals. His
staff helped him take down 20 years' worth of memorabilia _ a
football from the World League, soccer balls from the Olympic
tournament the city hosted.
</P>
<P>
   During one of Arrington's final interviews, the dark
cherry-colored walls of his office already were almost bare, except
for a large portrait of Nelson Mandela, South Africa's former
president and civil rights leader.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like a death,'' said receptionist Willease Burts, who has
known Arrington since she was a child.
</P>
<P>
   Among those mourning are many of the city's business leaders.
The mayor pushed for several annexations to encourage commercial
development that increased the city's tax base. The University of
Alabama at Birmingham medical college cranks out doctors and
nurses. An hour west of town, Mercedes builds upscale sport utility
vehicles. An hour to the east, Honda will crank up an assembly line
in two years.
</P>
<P>
   Arrington, a 64-year-old biologist with a doctorate in
invertebrate zoology from the University of Oklahoma, is leaving
office, he says, because it's time. A special election will be held
Oct. 12. City Council President William Bell, who is black and an
Arrington loyalist, will preside as interim mayor, giving him an
edge, critics say, in the race to succeed Arrington.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been 20 years,'' said Arrington, who dreamed about
becoming a college president. ``The city needs an injection of new
leadership.''
</P>
<P>
   But saying unequivocally that Birmingham is better off because
of Arrington perturbs critics.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's a matter of color,'' said Nina Miglionico, who is white
and served on the city council with Arrington before he was elected
mayor. She started on the council in 1963, the year a bomb blast at
the 16th Street Baptist Church killed four girls during Sunday
school class. A civil rights activist, Miglionico did not seek
re-election in 1985 in the face of Arrington's powerful Jefferson
County Citizens Coalition, which still controls the city's
majority-black voting bloc.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you're black, it's worked out beautifully because he calls
all the shots,'' Miglionico said, ``but the whites felt left out.''
</P>
<P>
   Downtown Birmingham faces the same troubles as many urban hubs:
crime and poor education, which drive affluent residents of all
races to the suburbs. Birmingham has lost nearly 11 percent of its
population since 1980. Nearly seven of every 10 city residents are
black. Most of the suburbs have a white majority.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps feeling especially left out are low- and middle-income
whites who in decades past worked for U.S. Steel and voted for
George Wallace. More recently, they've voted for Fob James for
governor. In last year's GOP gubernatorial runoff, Arrington
endorsed moderate white challenger Winton Blount. The threat of
black crossover votes in the GOP nomination turned out thousands of
conservative whites and led to Blount's defeat.
</P>
<P>
   ``Richard Arrington does not get high marks for building bridges
with average white voters,'' said Natalie Davis, an Arrington
supporter and political scientist at Birmingham Southern College.
``In Birmingham they feel a sense of powerlessness, so he's been a
target in that sense.''
</P>
<P>
   Even before he took office, Arrington aligned himself with
corporate Birmingham. He built consensus, and that helped him push
his agenda of affirmative-action hiring in the city and reform in
the police department.
</P>
<P>
   ``He has made that a priority,'' said Alabama Power CEO Elmer
Harris, a major force in Arrington's small inner circle. ``The
mayor has been a very positive force for the city of Birmingham and
taken this city to new heights.''
</P>
<P>
   Arrington, Harris and the Rev. John T. Porter developed a
partnership that began revitalizing part of downtown. A modern
early learning center and a facility for senior citizens have been
constructed.
</P>
<P>
   Harris said future generations will ``be able to see the
achievements of his administration without race connotations. If it
were a white man, it would be the same thing. I don't think his
race has anything to do with how people will look back upon him.
</P>
<P>
   ``He has been a very successful mayor. He has worked with
whites, he has worked with blacks. He's moved this city forward.''
</P>
<P>
   Among Arrington's biggest steps backward was the two-year
federal investigation of city hall corruption. Though he wasn't
charged, Arrington calls it the low point of his administration. In
1992, he spent a day in jail after refusing to give his personal
appointment records to a federal judge, complaining the U.S.
attorney singled him out because he was a black officeholder.
</P>
<P>
   Arrington protested by symbolically chaining himself to
protesters, awakening images Birmingham long had tried to put
behind it. An old chasm opened between blacks and whites.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's one of the few times the corporate community got its
back up,'' said Davis, the political analyst. ``They complained it
reinforced a stereotype. People were very upset at him for that.''
</P>
<P>
   Said Harris, the power company executive, ``Anybody that is
faced with an aggressive prosecutor has to attack that in any
manner that he sees as successful. I supported the mayor in the
past, I supported him at that time, and I support him today.''
</P>
<P>
   This week, during Arrington's final City Council meeting, most
members gave him a standing ovation. Councilman Jimmy Blake, one of
Arrington's most outspoken critics, sat unmoved. He blames
Arrington for the city's dwindling population but gives the mayor
an A-plus for politicking.
</P>
<P>
   ``The older blacks saw him as a messiah figure,'' said Blake,
who is white and running to replace Arrington. ``He was very
popular among the white establishment _ and always has been
_because they made a lot of money off him. He has played both sides
of the race fence beautifully.''
</P>
<P>
   Frank Parsons, the white lawyer Arrington defeated in a runoff
in 1979, shares some of those sentiments.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Parsons credits Arrington with bringing private
enterprise and federal assistance to Birmingham at a level Parsons
might not have achieved. White business leaders cultivated
relationships with Arrington because, Parsons said, they wanted to
be counted as progressives.
</P>
<P>
   ``He made some inroads,'' Parsons said. ``And, let's face it,
that's what politics are all about.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
