u v &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SUNDAY-FINAL-BUDGET-N     07-15 1977
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SUNDAY-FINAL-BUDGET-NYT </SLUG>
  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The New York Times News Service will move the following
entertainment/arts articles this week for release Sunday, July 18,
1999. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ENTERTAINMENT &AMP; ARTS (Moved in `e' category) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FEATURE story &LR;
</P>
<P>
   KUBRICK-FILMS (Undated) _ In ``The Killing'' (1956), one of
Stanley Kubrick's earliest feature films, a man talking about his
cronies in a racetrack heist remarks: ``None of these men are
criminals in the usual sense. They've all got jobs and they all
live seemingly normal, decent lives, but they've got their problems
and they've all got a little larceny in them.'' Change ``a little
larceny'' to varying degrees of ``a lot'' and you've got a pretty
good description of Kubrick's entire body of work. Kubrick's new
movie, ``Eyes Wide Shut,'' a lugubrious, strangely static work that
he completed shortly before his death in March, is no exception.
The movie stars Tom Cruise and Nicole Kidman as a wealthy New York
couple who imperil their cushy, bourgeois lives by yielding to the
dark side of their natures. By Michiko Kakutani. &UR;  &LR; (Moved).
</P>
<P>
   CUNNINGHAM-DANCE (Undated) _ Talking about Merce Cunningham's
choreography can lead to an attack of the nonlinear. Words like
possibility, multiplicity and flexibility burst out like the
unexpected movements in his dances. As Lincoln Center Festival '99
prepares to honor Cunningham with an 80th-birthday celebration this
week, he is, as always, exploring new ways of moving in new
contexts. Theories that explain the premises behind his work
abound. Yet the cerebral and the fantastic have never been at odds
in his half-century of experiments. Once heckled as the high priest
of the dance avant-garde and now acclaimed for the same reason, he
has never failed to show that even the most fully plotted cosmos
can reveal surprising secrets. By Anna Kisselgoff. (Moved). Photo.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FILM AND VIDEO &LR;
</P>
<P>
   BELGIAN-FILMS (Undated) _ This year marked the triumph of the
realist strain in Belgian film, as ``Rosetta,'' directed by Luc and
Jean-Pierre Dardenne (brothers whose previous films include ``La
Promesse'') captured top honors, including the Palme d'Or, at the
Cannes International Film Festival. (While across town ``The
Carriers are Waiting,'' a comedy about a working-class family by a
firsttime Belgian director, Benoit Mariage, played to packed houses
at the Director's Fortnight, a sidebar to the main festival.)
``Rosetta,'' which will open here in the fall, uses a hand-held
camera and a cinema verite style to tell an intense moral fable
about an impoverished young girl's struggle to hold down a menial
job while maintaining shreds of dignity. By Leslie Camhi. (Moved).
Photo.
</P>
<P>
   CABARET-BALKAN-FILM (Paris) _ It is not an easy time for a
Serbian filmmaker to be releasing a new movie in the United States,
even for a veteran director like Goran Paskaljevic, who has long
opposed Slobodan Milosevic's regime, who has expressed his shame
over the atrocities committed by Serbian forces in Bosnia and
Kosovo, who has been denounced as a traitor by the official press
in Belgrade. For all that, he remains a Serb, and, as such, he is
expected to throw light on the collective madness that has gripped
a good many of his fellow Serbs of late. As it happens, this was
his objective when he began shooting ``Cabaret Balkan,'' his 11th
feature film, in Belgrade in the early spring of 1998. It was still
a year before NATO launched its aerial war against Yugoslavia in
the name of saving Kosovo, but Paskaljevic was already convinced
that Milosevic was leading his nation to disaster. His movie is
about people, not politics, but nonetheless about people driven to
violence and despair by politics. By Alan Riding. (Moved). Photo.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; THEATER &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   SOLITUDE-THEATER (London) _ ``Fair enough then. So we're
alone.'' When Dame Judi Dench, playing a grieving veteran theater
actress, speaks the final line of ``Amy's View'' Sunday on Broadway
during the last performance at the Ethel Barrymore Theater of David
Hare's play, the remark may make theatergoers sit up with a start.
Part of the frisson comes from the elegant visualization of those
closing moments, in which cascading sheets of silk prompt a far
more real emotive response than any musical's mechanized scenery
ever could. For that, credit Richard Eyre, the director, and Bob
Crowley, the designer, alongside that rare performer, Dame Judi,
who is never more moving than when she is being most
matter-of-fact. But beyond the simplicity of a scene that works
simultaneously as baptism and requiem, is the stark, declarative
nature of the concluding remarks of Dame Judi's character, Esme
Allen. In just those six unsentimental words, Esme gives voice to a
condition that has been dramatized of late with varying degrees of
urgency and pathos on New York and London stages. By Matt Wolf.
(Moved).
</P>
<P>
   &UR; CLASSICAL MUSIC &LR;
</P>
<P>
   GEORGE-BENJAMIN-MUSIC (Undated) _ Some artists bloom young;
others do not find themselves until they are a decade or two into
adult life. George Benjamin, 3, the English composer who is in
residence at the Tanglewood Music Center Festival of Contemporary
Music, beginning on Thursday in Lenox, Mass., where his music will
be featured, has followed both patterns. In his late teens and
early 20s Benjamin produced a quick succession of bold and
beautiful works, full of energy and color, and remarkable also for
their technical finish. Then the flow almost stopped until, as he
entered his 30s in 1990, he emerged again as an even stronger
creative presence, with the same keen ear but a weightier mind. The
Tanglewood programs include pieces from both the youthful
flourishing and later. By Paul Griffiths. (Moved). &QL;
</P>
<P>
   CENTRAL-PARK-OPERAS (Undated) _ A new operatic project could
hardly receive a more auspicious introduction than that to be
accorded over the next five months to ``Central Park,'' a trilogy
of one-act operas by three American composer-librettist teams.
That's why the flak that the project has stirred up among many
people concerned about the future of American opera, especially
American composers, has been so noteworthy. The short operas that
make up the trilogy are linked thematically only in that each story
is set in New York's most famous park. ``Central Park'' will have
its premiere on Saturday evening at the Glimmerglass Opera in
Cooperstown, N.Y. By Anthony Tommasini. (Moved).
</P>
<P>
   BAROQUE-MUSIC (Undated) _ Celine Dion singing ``My Heart Will Go
On'' and a Locatelli violin concerto send me to the radio's ``off''
button with equal velocity. A decision about Ms. Dion took about 45
seconds, Locatelli more like 30 years. But the two are annoying for
similar reasons. Ms. Dion makes it easy. The disposable charms of a
momentarily famous pop singer are brief by nature. Yet how has a
love affair with the Italian Baroque _ born of the postwar
long-playing record boom _ gone so wrong? Those of us raised on the
big pieces of the 19th century, a lot of Mozart and a little Haydn
raced to the record stores to hear the latest Torelli and Corelli
from chamber orchestras like I Musici or I Virtuosi di Roma. We
were charmed by the elegance and the certitude. We liked the
absence of bigness for its own sake and the clarity of small string
ensembles in synchrony. With exceptions (Vivaldi is one), I find
this music increasingly difficult to listen to. Saturation?
Perhaps. Near-symmetry, often repeated, numbs the spirit; the
frictionless paradoxically becomes an irritant. This civilizing of
human passions runs like a current beneath the great musical events
of the 18th century, although the best composers, refusing to be so
easily tamed, fought against the tide. By Bernard Holland. (Moved).
</P>
<P>
   CONDUCTORS-MUSIC (Undated) _ At a time when so many orchestras
and conductors are changing partners, it is good to be reminded of
the artistic benefits of retaining a long-term maestro. One such
reminder comes in the form of a Sony Classical reissue of two
classic recordings by the Cleveland Orchestra under the direction
of George Szell: Prokofiev's Fifth Symphony, recorded in 1959, and
Bartok's Concerto for Orchestra, recorded in 1965. These
performances may not induce discophiles to part with their version
of the Prokofiev by Herbert von Karajan or of the Bartok by Fritz
Reiner, but both offer orchestral playing of breathtaking
refinement while challenging the notion that Szell was a dour
taskmaster and an interpretive literalist. By David Schiff.
(Moved).
</P>
<P>
   &UR; POP MUSIC &LR;
</P>
<P>
   ONLINE-MUSIC (Undated) _ Most of the recent controversy about
on-line music has been over how it is going to change the
experience of selling and purchasing music, but much more
interesting is the question of how it is changing our experience of
listening to and handling the music. Listening to music on the
Internet is not simply a novel alternative to CD players or a way
to use the computer as a separate but equal stereo system. Nor is
it an opportunity to level the playing field _ as utopians like to
dream _ and allow all musicians, great and small, access to all
listeners mainstream and marginal. It is a key to unlocking the
restrictions that all audio storage media before them have posed to
musicians and fans. The CD was a medium similar enough to a record
that one could still call it an album without being corrected. But
with the Internet, the idea of the album is dead. By Neil Strauss.
(Moved).
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ART &LR;
</P>
<P>
   JAPANESE-ARTISTS (Annandale-On-Hudson, N.Y.) _ Since the late
1980s, a number of younger Japanese artists have emerged on the
international scene to challenge the old notion that all modern art
from Japan is merely a pale imitation of modern art from the West.
Among them are Yasumasa Morimura, Tatsuo Miyajima, Mariko Mori and
Takashi Murakami, whose goofy, glossy work has found an avid
audience outside Japan. Rooted in Japanese popular culture,
Murakami's art communicates across borders in a media-driven era of
global pop to which fashion, animation, music and electronic
gadgetry from Japan have all contributed. It is now the focus of
``The Meaning of the Nonsense of the Meaning,'' a
mini-retrospective on view here at the Center for Curatorial
Studies Museum at Bard College through Sept. 12. By Edward M.
Gomez. (Moved).
</P>
<P>
   &UR; TELEVISION &LR;
</P>
<P>
   TV-BONANNO (Undated) _ Joseph Bonanno, the long-retired Mafia
boss (he prefers ``father'') widely known as Joe Bananas, who is
now, at 94, is truly the Really Absolutely Very Last Don.
``Bonanno: A Godfather's Story,'' a two-part film being shown next
Sunday and Monday on Showtime, may well be the highest-level mob
memoir and tutorial (``Mafia is a process, not a thing'') to find
its way to the screen. It is quite certainly the only one ever to
list another acknowledged Mafioso _ Bonanno's son Salvatore, known
as Bill _ as an executive producer. By Ralph Blumenthal. (Moved).
</P>
<P>
   BESTSELLERS (Undated) (Moved.)
