<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NYTIMESCO-EARNINGS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE NEW YORK TIMES CO. REPORTS 9.5% INCREASE IN PROFITS  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Mass.)   By FELICITY BARRINGER    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The New York Times Co. said Thursday that its
second-quarter profit from operations rose 9.5 percent, lifted by
strong growth in advertising revenue at the company's flagship
newspaper.
</P>
<P>
   In a separate announcement, the company said that it was buying
Abuzz Technologies Inc., its first acquisition since it
consolidated its numerous Internet properties into one division,
Times Co. Digital, eight weeks ago.
</P>
<P>
   For the second quarter, the Times Co. had an operating profit of
$158.9 million, or 48 cents a diluted share, compared with $145.1
million, or 40 cents a share, in the period a year earlier.
</P>
<P>
   Revenue increased 4 percent, to $779.4 million from $749.2
million, while costs rose 3.4 percent, to $624.5 million from
$604.1 million.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts had expected the company to earn 45 cents a share,
according to the First Call Corp., which tracks company earnings.
</P>
<P>
   The Times Co. did not disclose the terms of the acquisition of
Abuzz, which is based in Cambridge, Mass. It is a three-year-old
company that has developed a product called Beehive, which culls
information from various sources and connects people who have
questions with people or places that have answers. This tool, which
effectively creates individual card indexes fine-tuned to a user's
information needs, is intended to enhance what Martin A.
Nisenholtz, the chief executive of Times Co. Digital, described as
a strategy ``to capture the premium audience on line.''
</P>
<P>
   Nathaniel Palmer, an analyst with the Digital Group, a research
firm in Boston, said: ``Today on the Internet you can find someone
who claims knowledge in a particular area. But is there a trusted
peer review of that individual?'' Abuzz's technology, he said,
permits a higher level of reliability and refines the concept of
electronic communities.
</P>
<P>
   But despite the favorable earnings report and the acquisition,
shares of the Times Co. fell 25 cents on Thursday, to $39.
</P>
<P>
   ``The results were very strong _ clearly above expectations,''
said Steven N. Barlow, an analyst with Credit Suisse First Boston.
Douglas M. Arthur, an analyst with Morgan Stanley Dean Witter,
agreed, saying that the Gannett Co. experienced a similar stock
price dip when it reported strong second-quarter earnings, only to
see the price rebound days later.
</P>
<P>
   Both Barlow and Arthur said that the strong earnings numbers at
the Times Co., like those recently reported by Dow Jones and
Gannett, were related to the depressed price of newsprint, which is
one of the biggest costs for newspaper companies. The low newsprint
prices are expected to continue for at least another quarter, the
two said.
</P>
<P>
   At the Times Co.'s other large newspaper, The Boston Globe,
advertising revenue rose 1.4 percent after two consecutive quarters
of declining revenue. Operating profit for the company's newspaper
group as a whole increased 14.2 percent, to $147.8 million.
</P>
<P>
   ``The important thing was that the ad revenue trend in the
newspaper group was better than expected and accelerating as the
quarter ended,'' Arthur said.
</P>
<P>
   As for the new acquisition, Arthur said: ``It certainly
represents a more aggressive stance in terms of really building
this Internet business beyond the news site and registered users.
They want to build something greater. This is going in new
directions for The New York Times.''
</P>
<P>
   He added, ``It could also suggest that the company's future use
of excess cash flow is going to be potentially less focused on
traditional media and more focused on building new media.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
