<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-15 21:02 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1883 &Cx1f; tta-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ISRAEL-U.S.-ART-1000&AMP;     07-15 1331
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ISRAEL-U.S.-ART-1000&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BARAK SAYS ISRAEL WILL PURSUE AN AGREEMENT WITH SYRIA 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photos are being sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(mk) 
 By JOHN M. BRODER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Prime Minister Ehud Barak told President Clinton on
Thursday that Israel would embark on a ``serious effort'' in the
next several weeks to restart negotiations with Syria, which is
still formally at war with Israel.
</P>
<P>
   In a private meeting with the president at the White House that
lasted two and a half hours, Barak laid down several conditions
that he would demand as the price of peace with Syria, according to
a senior Israeli official who spoke with Barak after the session.
</P>
<P>
   The prime minister told Clinton that Israel was prepared for
``painful compromises and difficult decisions'' to reach agreement
with Syria, if it offers concessions in turn, the official said.
Israel is willing to partly pull its troops back from the Golan
Heights on the Israel-Syria border if the two countries can reach
agreement on the status of Lebanon, terrorism, borders, water
rights and normalization of diplomatic relations.
</P>
<P>
   Barak told Clinton that Israel would never agree to return to
the borders that existed before the 1967 war, the official said.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday's meeting was the first of a series of discussions the
new Israeli prime minister will have with the president and other
top American officials over the next five days. The Washington
talks come barely a week after he was sworn in as prime minister
and are intended to dramatize his commitment to rapid progress
toward political reconciliation.
</P>
<P>
   Barak also told the president that he would continue the
withdrawal of Israeli forces from the West Bank under terms of a
deal reached with Palestinians at the Wye Plantation in Maryland
late last year, but that ``most'' Israeli settlers would remain in
the communities they have established there.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are at the moment of truth,'' Barak told Clinton, according
to the Israeli official. ``Our generation must find a way to solve
this conflict. We will leave no stone unturned to reach peace
agreements that will enhance the security of Israel.''
</P>
<P>
   After the meeting with Clinton, Barak met briefly with Vice
President Al Gore, and then Clinton and first lady Hillary Rodham
Clinton and Barak and his wife, Nava, flew by helicopter to Camp
David to dine privately and spend the night.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking to reporters in the Rose Garden in an appearance with
Clinton before their meeting, Barak said he planned a vigorous
effort to resume discussions with all of Israel's neighbors and
with the Palestinians. He asked for the president's support, but at
the same time expressed a desire for the United States to play a
less prominent role in negotiations and in enforcing any ultimate
agreements.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton publicly agreed that the United States had become overly
intrusive in the Middle East dialogue in the last several years. He
said Washington should serve merely as a ``facilitator'' of talks
involving Israel, its Arab neighbors and the Palestinians, not as
an active participant.
</P>
<P>
   ``We should not be in a patronizing role. We should be in a
supportive role,'' Clinton said in his public appearance with the
prime minister. It was the first time Clinton had responded to
Barak's complaint this week that the United States had been too
deeply enmeshed in Middle East negotiations.
</P>
<P>
   The president said the United States had intervened only when it
appeared that progress toward peace had halted.
</P>
<P>
   ``We took a more active role, in effect as a mediator, when the
bonds of trust and the lines of communication had become so frayed
that we were in danger of losing the peace process,'' Clinton said.
``And I did not want that to happen.''
</P>
<P>
   He said it was far preferable for the parties to talk directly
to one another without American intercession, as Barak said he
intended to do.
</P>
<P>
   The prime minister said that he did not want the United States
to serve as ``policeman, judge and arbitrator'' of relations
between Israel and the Arabs. Barak seemed to be referring in part
to the CIA's involvement in security issues with the Palestinians,
a role that was established at the Wye accords and one that some
critics say supplanted the chances of direct contact between the
Israelis and the Palestinians on those issues.
</P>
<P>
   Barak did emphasize Thursday that restarting the Middle East
dialogue would require ``American leadership and support all along
the way.''
</P>
<P>
   Barak said that he would abide by all agreements signed by
previous Israeli governments, including the Wye accords reached
last fall. He said he intended to try to reach agreement on ``all
tracks'' of regional peace talks, including a comprehensive accord
with Syria.
</P>
<P>
   However, he said he felt as if he had ``got the mission of
defusing a time bomb'' by taking office after a three-year period
in which Israel's relations with its neighbors, the Palestinians
and the United States were badly strained by the cantankerous
posture of the Likud government of Prime Minister Benjamin
Netanyahu.
</P>
<P>
   Barak, who was sworn in just last week after winning a landslide
victory over Netanyahu in May, has already met with Yasser Arafat,
the Palestinian leader, King Abdullah of Jordan and President Hosni
Mubarak of Egypt.
</P>
<P>
   He said Thursday that he was prepared to sit down with Hafez
al-Assad, the president of Syria, to discuss peace with Syria and
an Israeli withdrawal from Lebanon, which Syria essentially
controls.
</P>
<P>
   ``It takes two to tango,'' Barak said. ``I am ready, the arena
is ready, maybe the dancing instructor is ready. We have to find an
opportunity and begin.''
</P>
<P>
   Secretary of State Madeleine Albright is expected to travel to
Syria in the next several weeks to sound out officials there on
what conditions they will require for normalization of relations
with Israel.
</P>
<P>
   Assad has insisted that Israel withdraw all of its forces from
southern Lebanon and return land on the Golan Heights seized during
the 1967 war. He also wants a permanent international observer
force stationed in the Golan to insure that Israel lives up to its
commitments.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Assad would also like the lifting of economic sanctions the
United States imposed because of the American determination that
Syria sponsors international terrorism.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton said he had not meant to signal a shift in American
policy toward Palestinian refugees or to prejudge the outcome of
so-called final status talks when he said two weeks ago that the
refugees should be able to settle ``wherever they want to live.''
</P>
<P>
   The remark touched off a wave of criticism in Israel, where the
``right of return'' of hundreds of thousands of Palestinians
scattered around the Middle East to territory now occupied by
Israel is one of the most emotional issues still to be resolved
with Palestinian leaders.
</P>
<P>
   The refugee issue is one to be negotiated in the permanent
status talks between Israel and the Palestinians, Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The United States, as a sponsor of the peace process, has
asked the parties to do nothing to prejudge the final status
issues,'' the president said. ``We certainly should be doing
nothing to prejudge the final status issues.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton gave a similar answer in response to a question arising
from Mrs. Clinton's statement last week that Jerusalem was the
capital of Israel and that the United States should move its
Embassy to Jerusalem from Tel Aviv. Her statement is at odds with
administration policy, which is that the status of Jerusalem has
yet to be decided and that the U.S. Embassy will remain in Tel Aviv
until it is.
</P>
<P>
   For his part, Barak said he would like embassies from all
nations to be in Jerusalem, which both Israel and the Palestinians
claim as their historic capitals.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
