<HEADER>
A1884 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NUCLEAR-PAYOUT16-COX     07-15 0753
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NUCLEAR-PAYOUT16-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    U.S. to pay workers sickened in bomb plants
 &HT;    By Charles Seabrook
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The government acknowledged for the first time
Thursday that thousands of workers were made sick while making
nuclear bombs, and it announced a proposal to compensate many of
them for their maladies.
</P>
<P>
   Congress still must approve the proposal outlined in Washington
by Energy Secretary Bill Richardson. The compensation would end
years of litigation over claims by the workers that they became
sick while employed by private contractors at federal nuclear
facilities during the Cold War.
</P>
<P>
   The White House's plan initially would limit compensation to
workers suffering from exposure to beryllium, a chemical element
that was used as a strengthening alloy in atomic weapons. The cost
of such compensation was estimated at $13 million a year over 10
years.
</P>
<P>
   Although the 310-square-mile Savannah River Site in South
Carolina near the Georgia border at Augusta played a key role in
developing the nation's nuclear arsenal, a plant spokesman said
Thursday that the kind of beryllium that may have caused illness
among nuclear workers was never used there. The main mission of
SRS, which was built in the early 1950s, was the production of
plutonium and tritium, the explosive ingredients of nuclear
weapons.
</P>
<P>
   The Department of Energy said that most of the workers with
chronic beryllium disease were employed at Rocky Flats in Colorado,
the Oak Ridge weapons complex in Tennessee, the Hanford reservation
in Washington state, Los Alamos National Laboratory in New Mexico
and the Argonne Laboratory in Chicago. Many also worked for private
vendors in Pennsylvania and Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the workers eligible to file claims worked at plants
that date from the Manhattan Project, the World War II effort to
build a nuclear bomb.
</P>
<P>
   ``The U.S. government is acknowledging that we made a mistake.
... We need to right this wrong,'' said Richardson, who noted that
for a long time the government had rejected such claims.
</P>
<P>
   The workers and their unions and other advocates have argued for
years that they suffered from lung disease or cancers of exposure
to mercury, uranium, asbestos and various radioactive substances.
</P>
<P>
   Richardson said the proposal announced Thursday also calls for
the president's National Economic Council to examine compensation
for other occupational illnesses related to the nuclear weapons
program, including asbestosis and radiation-induced cancers. A
report is expected next March.
</P>
<P>
   If those illnesses are included, the program probably would
include workers at the Savannah River Site.
</P>
<P>
   A five-year DOE-funded program to screen thousands of former
workers for illnesses they may have acquired from exposure to
dangerous materials at the plant began in January in Augusta.
``There are 50,000 to 60,000 people who worked here since the early
1950s,'' said Tommy Yarbrough of the Augusta Building Trades group
that represents 14 building trade unions at SRS. The screening is
taking place at the organization's building in Augusta.
</P>
<P>
   During the initial screening that lasts more than an hour, the
former workers are asked whether they handled or were exposed to
one of several toxic or radioactive materials and how long they may
have been exposed. The computerized information then is reviewed by
medical experts under contract for the program.
</P>
<P>
   The medical reviewers determine from the questionnaire whether a
worker should be referred to doctors for exams. Yarbrough said it
is ``quite likely'' that the program will turn up a number of
former workers suffering from exposure to dangerous materials while
working at SRS.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are trying to reach as many former workers in these as
possible to undergo this screening,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Under the administration's plan, workers found to be eligible
for compensation would be reimbursed for medical costs, compensated
for lost wages and given vocational assistance. In cases in which
the worker has died, survivors' benefits would be provided, DOE
officials said.
</P>
<P>
   Union officials representing the workers and others have claimed
for years that the DOE and its predecessor, the Atomic Energy
Commission, failed to provide proper safeguards to protect workers
in the production, manufacture and assembly of nuclear materials
and weapons.
</P>
<P>
   The Associated Press contributed to this article.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
