<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-15 21:06 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1885 &Cx1f; tta-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HEALTH-CARE-ART-2TAKE     07-15 0924
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HEALTH-CARE-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SENATE APPROVES REPUBLICAN PLAN TO REGULATE HEALTH INSURERS 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Nonsubscribers
can make individual purchase by calling 1-888-603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) (th) 
 By ALISON MITCHELL    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ In the final hours of a bitter and sharply partisan
debate over health care, the Senate killed a Democratic effort to
expand the ability of patients to sue managed care providers and
then, in a near party-line vote Thursday night, approved a
Republican plan to regulate the companies that provide health
insurance for most Americans.
</P>
<P>
   The bill, designed to grapple with the health care revolution
that has shifted most Americans into managed care, passed by a
53-47 vote. Two Republicans, John Chafee of Rhode Island and Peter
Fitzgerald of Illinois, broke ranks with their party to oppose the
bill. The measure would provide $13 billion in new tax breaks for
health care and give an array of rights to consumers, most
significantly creating an appeal process for 124 million Americans
in employer-sponsored health plans.
</P>
<P>
   The extent of the other new protections _ including consumer
information, the right to a hospital stay after a mastectomy if
recommended by a doctor and access to an emergency room outside a
managed care network _ would vary according to the nature and
source of a person's insurance coverage.
</P>
<P>
   Many of the new rights would apply only to the 48 million people
in self-funded plans offered by large companies. In many cases
these are not the more restrictive insurance plans that have caused
the most consumer concern because they channel access to care
through a ``gatekeeper'' physician.
</P>
<P>
   The Democrats had tried unsuccessfully across four days of
impassioned debate to push through a more comprehensive plan that
would have applied to all 161 million Americans with private health
insurance.
</P>
<P>
   As the marathon Senate struggle over the issue drew to a close
Thursday night, Senate Majority Leader Trent Lott, R-Miss.,
espoused the Republican philosophy of regulation in moderation and
criticized the Democrats' efforts to expand the right to sue.
</P>
<P>
   ``Congress should not imperil the continuing transformation of
American medicine,'' he said. ``It's not our job to dictate or
control that transformation.''
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Tom Daschle, D-S.D., the Senate minority leader, harshly
criticized the Republican bill as a fraud. ``The Senate has missed
a golden opportunity to pass a real Patient's Bill of Rights,'' he
said. ``Instead the Republican majority is handing the insurance
industry its version of HMO reform _ half measures only.''
</P>
<P>
   With Republicans and Democrats sharply divided over an issue
they expect to resonate with the public, Vice President Al Gore
vowed that President Clinton would veto the Republican bill, making
it likely that the parties' different approaches to health care
will become an issue in the next election.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nobody should be under any illusions,'' said Gore, who came to
the Senate in the late afternoon in the unlikely event that he
would be called upon to cast a tie-breaking vote. ``If the
Republican leadership insists on going through a charade and
insists on passing that bill of goods they've been trying to
promote, President Clinton will veto it in a minute. It has zero
chance of going past his desk, because it's a fraud. And what
happens then? We will come right back here, and we'll start all
over again.''
</P>
<P>
   Republicans who favored less federal regulation than the
Democrats charged that the Democrats' rival plan would raise
premiums and force more Americans into the ranks of the uninsured.
Of the veto threat, Sen. Don Nickles, the majority whip from
Oklahoma, said, ``We are going to find out if the White House is
interested in increasing quality health care or just wants to make
politics.''
</P>
<P>
   A handful of Democrats and Republicans tried but failed in the
final hours of debate to find common ground in an attempt to head
off the impasse. ``If this gamesmanship continues the only winner
will be the status quo,'' said Sen. Bob Graham, D-Fla.
</P>
<P>
   The Senate plan would have implications for doctors, insurers,
businesses and consumers. The American Medical Association on
Thursday night sharply condemned the final bill, saying, ``In a
highly regrettable action, the Senate has bowed to the insurance
industry dictate that says their profits come first and patients
come last.''
</P>
<P>
   The managed care industry by contrast praised the outcome. ``I
think it means that all patients will have a guarantee of
independent review that's a very important aspect of providing
trust and confidence,'' said Karen M. Ignagni, the president of the
American Association of Health Plans.
</P>
<P>
   The most significant provision of the Republican bill would
allow people in employer-sponsored health plans to appeal decisions
denying them coverage for a specific treatment or type of care.
Patients could appeal to an independent medical reviewer if a
health plan refused to pay for care.
</P>
<P>
   The bill enforces a decision against a health plan by allowing a
patient to obtain treatment outside a health network if treatment
does not begin in the time frame recommended by the reviewer. The
plan would be held liable for the charges and for a $10,000 fine.
And the plan may be assessed another fine of up to $10,000 if it
fails to comply with time frames for review.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   During the two years that managed care has been a major issue in
Congress, the most hard-fought question has been whether to go
further and expand a patient's right to sue in cases of
malpractice. Currently most patients suing over decisions in
managed care must do so in federal court, where they can typically
collect the value of the care denied but not punitive damages.
</P>
<P>
   Time and again Thursday afternoon, Republicans charged that the
Democrats' proposal to give consumers the right to sue for punitive
damages in state court would drive up health care costs and serve
as a boon to trial lawyers, an important Democratic constituency.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Pete Domenici, R-N.M., called it ``lunacy'' to expect the
courts to solve health care problems. ``I am convinced that if you
let the trial lawyers solve a medical problem it is borderline
useless,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The Democrats countered that they were trying to insure that the
insurance companies that deny certain health care treatments can be
held to account through the courts in the same way other businesses
are.
</P>
<P>
   Protesting a Republican amendment to strip the right to sue out
of the Democratic plan, Sen. Barbara Boxer, D-Calif., said, ``If
this amendment passes and the HMOs cannot be held accountable in
court of law, what it means is if they kill you, if they maim you,
if they hurt you or your family or your children due to callous or
uncaring bureaucrats they cannot be held accountable.''
</P>
<P>
   By a 53-47 vote, the Senate went on to kill the Democrats'
liability provision before beginning the final debate.
</P>
<P>
   Beyond the grievance procedures the Republican plan provides
certain protections available to different groups of people
depending on the source of their health care.
</P>
<P>
   Under the plan all women with private health insurance would be
able to stay in a hospital after a mastectomy if their doctor
recommends it. The measure was a response to the emotional issue of
so-called ``drive-by mastectomies in which some insurance companies
had required the operation for breast cancer to be handled as an
out-patient procedure.
</P>
<P>
   An array of other protections were granted to 48 million people
covered by self-funded employer plans, which encompass both
old-style fee-for-service programs and managed care, but are
frequently no the kinds of restrictive HMO plans that have drawn
the most consumer complaints.
</P>
<P>
   These protections include access to emergency rooms outside a
provider network for services related to stabilizing an emergency
condition. It requires health plans to coordinate transfers or
discharges within an hour after being contacted by the
out-of-service hospital.
</P>
<P>
   The bill grants women in these kinds of health plans direct
access to an obstetrician for pregnancy and child delivery but
direct access to a gynecologist for ``routine'' care.
</P>
<P>
   And for these 48 million people the bill requires ``timely''
access to medical specialists, but only those inside a health
plan's network. For patients, among the 48 million, with cancers
best treated through clinical trials, the plan would require
payment of routine patient costs associated with approved cancer
clinical trials sponsored by the National Institutes of Health, the
department of Veterans Affairs and the Department of Defense.
</P>
<P>
   In each of these areas the Democrats had argued for protections
that were often broader and that would apply to all 161 million
Americans with private health insurance.
</P>
<P>
   The Republican bill would create $13 billion in new tax breaks,
allowing full deduction of health insurance premiums, the full
deduction of long-term care insurance that is not subsidized by an
employer and an expansion of medical savings accounts, _ tax-free
savings accounts for health care.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats object to the medical savings accounts because they
say the accounts provide an incentive for the healthy and the
affluent to drop out of the general insurance pool.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-15-99 2106EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
