<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-BARAK16-COX </SLUG>

<TEXT>
<P>
   CLINTON HOPES BARAK CAN ADVANCE MIDEAST PEACE PROCESS
</P>
<P>
   919. Moving in international and washington categories.
</P>
<P>
   W/PHOTOS
</P>
<P>
   By Bob Deans
</P>
<P>
   Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON Embracing Israel's new leader as the last hope for
the ``rejuvenation,'' of the long-stalled Mideast peace process on
his watch, President Clinton welcomed Israeli Prime Minister Ehud
Barak to the White House on Thursday for substantive, yet cordial,
talks.
</P>
<P>
   After a private conversation lasting 2.5 hours, the leaders
traveled by helicopter to the Camp David presidential retreat,
where they and their wives had dinner and spent the night.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am very excited about the prospect of the rejuvenation of
the peace process,'' Clinton told reporters in the sun-splashed
Rose Garden, just before his first meeting with Barak since the
Israeli took office last week, vowing to move the peace process
forward.
</P>
<P>
   ``He has put peace at the top of his agenda,'' said Clinton,
adding to Barak that ``America will help you as you move forward.''
</P>
<P>
   Barak reciprocated the optimistic sentiment. ``It is our
intention to inject new momentum into the peace process,'' he said,
attributing the victory of his Labor Party in May parliamentary
elections to Israelis' desire for peace with security.
</P>
<P>
   ``They expect us to provide them with a better and safer
future,'' said Barak. ``We cannot let their hopes down.''
</P>
<P>
   Barak later told Clinton he was prepared to make ``painful
compromises,'' in order to make peace with Palestinians, Syrians
and Lebanese, an Israeli official told reporters.
</P>
<P>
   Amid the show of good faith and high expectations, however,
there were signs of the difficulties and risks that must be
overcome to end five decades of bloodshed and enmity between
Israelis and Arabs.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton pressed Barak to make the first move toward
jump-starting the long-stalled Mideast peace process by fulfilling
his country's pledge to hand over additional territory to
Palestinian control.
</P>
<P>
   Barak said he would honor Israel's agreement, brokered by
Clinton last fall, to turn over an additional 13.1 percent of
Israeli-occupied land in the West Bank to the Palestinians. He said
he would do so, however, only as part of a broader effort to reach
a comprehensive peace accord.
</P>
<P>
   Barak further stressed that he would not permit Washington to
dictate the terms or the tempo of the peace process and that
Clinton's role as peace-broker should be limited.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think that the United States can contribute to the process
more as facilitator,'' said Barak, `` than as a kind of policeman,
judge and arbitrator at the same time.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton, nodding as Barak spoke, said he agreed. But Clinton
also made clear the enormous stake the United States, and he as its
leader, has in the Mideast peace process.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have done what we could, consistently, for more than 20
years now, through all kinds of administrations, to try to advance
the peace process,'' said Clinton. ``I have probably spent more
time on it than anyone has, and certainly I've spent a lot of time
on it.''
</P>
<P>
   During his first year in office, Clinton hosted former Israeli
Prime Minister Yitzhak Rabin and Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat
for a South Lawn signing of an historic peace accord. Over the past
two years, however, progress on steps outlined in that accord
stalled amid mutual recriminations. The accord is a blueprint for
handing over certain Israeli-occupied land to Palestinian control
in exchange for Palestinian efforts to combat anti-Israeli
terrorism.
</P>
<P>
   Hoping to restart the process, Clinton spent several days last
October in negotiations between Arafat and then-Israeli Prime
Minister Benjamin Netanyahu at the Wye River resort in rural
Maryland. The result was an agreement that quickly ran aground, as
Netanyahu charged Arafat with failing to take strong enough
measures against anti-Israeli terrorists. And Arafat countered that
Netanyahu had bargained in bad faith.
</P>
<P>
   Barak said Thursday he would honor the Wye agreement, which
calls on Israel to relinquish to the Palestinians additional land
on the West Bank.
</P>
<P>
   ``But there is a need to combine the implementation of Wye with
the moving forward of the permanent status agreement,'' Barak said.
</P>
<P>
   Permanent status issues, including the question of Palestinian
statehood and the future of Jerusalem, are regarded as among the
most contentious issues between Israel and the Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
   A May deadline for the resolution of those issues was missed,
and Clinton has said he would hope the permanent status talks can
begin soon and be completed within a year.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday's meeting was designed as a first step toward building
confidence between the two men and, according to senior Israeli and
American officials, it achieved those goals.
</P>
<P>
   Barak, a career soldier who also serves as Israel's Defense
Minister, was scheduled to meet Friday with Secretary of Defense
William Cohen and Secretary of State Madeleine Albright.
</P>
<P>
   Barak is to spend the weekend meeting with representatives from
the U.S. Jewish community in New York, before returning to the
White House for a state dinner Sunday night and further meetings
with Clinton on Monday.
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday, the two leaders met by themselves, without the
aides and notetakers that customarily accompany heads of state in
such meetings. And the venue was the Treaty Room in the White House
residence, deemed a more intimate setting than the businesslike
Oval Office, where Clinton ordinarily receives official guests.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
