</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAMPAIGN-FINANCE-700(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSH ANNOUNCES HE WON'T ACCEPT FEDERAL MATCHING FUNDS 
</HEADLINE>
  (rk) 
 By DON VAN NATTA Jr.   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Gov. George W. Bush declared Thursday that he would
not accept federal matching funds because of his enormous $37
million campaign war chest, giving him the capacity to far outspend
his Republican presidential rivals in the 2000 election, especially
in early and pivotal primaries and caucuses.
</P>
<P>
   With Bush, the governor of Texas, and another Republican
candidate, multimillionaire publisher Steve Forbes, both forgoing
federal matching funds, one of the bulwarks of the post-Watergate
campaign finance system has been weakened.
</P>
<P>
   By refusing to accept $16.5 million in matching funds from
taxpayers, Bush, with more than $30 million in cash reserves, will
not be restricted by a spending limit of nearly $40 million that
applies to candidates who accept matching funds in the primaries.
</P>
<P>
   More important, Bush's chief Democratic rivals, Vice President
Al Gore and former New Jersey Sen. Bill Bradley, who are both
accepting matching funds, will both likely reach the spending limit
by the spring of 2000. But Bush would still have ample money left
to spend through the summer conventions. The Republican and
Democratic presidential nominees would then receive about $66
million each in public funds for the general election.
</P>
<P>
   ``After looking at the numbers, cash on hand of $30 million,
I've decided not to accept federal matching funds during the course
of this campaign,'' Bush said Thursday in a campaign appearance in
Waterloo, Iowa.
</P>
<P>
   Bush decided to announce his intentions on the day that all the
candidates were required to report their quarterly fund-raising
totals to the Federal Election Commission.
</P>
<P>
   By not being hamstrung by spending limits, Bush said that his
campaign would be able to respond to ``attack ads'' broadcast by a
wealthy Republican rival, presumably a reference to Forbes.
</P>
<P>
   Forbes has already announced that he would not accept federal
matching funds for the 2000 primary season. Forbes is raising money
and also intends to spend tens of millions of his own money on his
campaign, as he did in 1996 when he spent $37 million. Other
wealthy candidates in years past like Ross Perot, have refused to
accept the subsidies financed by taxpayers, choosing to spend
millions of their own money on their campaigns.
</P>
<P>
   ``You've got limits that constrain a candidate,'' Bush said. ``I
want to be in a position to respond.''
</P>
<P>
   Campaign reform advocates, as well as some political
strategists, harshly criticized Bush's decision and predicted that
it might backfire with voters.
</P>
<P>
   ``This system was set up in part to prevent a candidate from
drowning everyone else out by accumulating huge amounts of money,''
said Fred Wertheimer, the president of Democracy 21, a public
policy organization. ``But by rejecting public funds, Governor Bush
is basically taking an approach to try to use political money to
try to drown everyone else out of the race.''
</P>
<P>
   Pressed about why Bush was refusing to abide by the spending
limits that will apply to most of his rivals, Mindy Tucker, a
spokeswoman for the Bush campaign, said, ``I think Governor Bush
feels that this is part of the democratic process that people can
contribute to a campaign to express their opinion. There are 74,000
who have heard his message and to convey their opinion they have
made a contribution in the sum ranging from $5 to $1000.''
</P>
<P>
   She also stressed that Bush ``understands the need for campaign
finance reform.'' Bush has called for several reforms, including
the banning of so-called soft money from corporations and unions
when the members or shareholders are not consulted about how the
money is spent.
</P>
<P>
   On the Democratic side, Gore reported that he has raised a total
of $19.5 million in the first half of the year, but he has only
$9.4 million in the bank that can be spent during the primaries.
The vice president has two million more in cash on hand than his
only Democratic challenger, Bradley.
</P>
<P>
   Campaign strategists said that the relatively close disparity in
each campaign's cash reserves demonstrates that Gore may be even
more vulnerable to a lengthy campaign by Bradley through most of
the state primaries next year.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   The federal matching funds program was enacted in 1974 as part
of a legislative overhaul of the federal election laws after the
Watergate scandal. The goal of the 1974 law was to cleanse the
campaign finance system and provide some public funding for
presidential candidates after the campaign finance scandal that
surrounded President Richard Nixon's 1972 re-election.
</P>
<P>
   Under the matching funds system, candidates receive $250 in
federal funds for every $1,000 they raise. Qualifying candidates
can receive as much as $16.5 million in matching funds during the
primaries. In return, they must abide by an overall spending
ceiling of nearly $40 million during the primaries including the
matching funds. There are strict state-by-state spending limits.
For instance, each candidate who accepts matching funds can only
spend $1.13 million in Iowa and $661,200 in New Hampshire. But Bush
can ignore all these limits, although he must still adhere to
contribution limits of $1,000 for individuals.
</P>
<P>
   Bush's dominant lead in cash-on-hand creates an even wider
disparity between him and the other candidates in the field. His
commanding lead in cash and in national polls has already chased
two candidates out of the Republican race. Rep. John Kasich, who
had trouble raising money, dropped out of the campaign on Wednesday
and endorsed Bush. And Sen. Robert Smith of New Hampshire announced
he was leaving the Republican Party and would run for president as
an independent.
</P>
<P>
   In just four months, Bush raised $37.03 million, a sum even
higher than his campaign's estimate of $36.3 million in early July,
according to figures that the Bush campaign reported Thursday to
the Federal Election Commission.
</P>
<P>
   The Texas governor received $1,000 from both his father, the
former president, and Barbara Bush, the former first lady. George
H.W. Bush of Houston's occupation was listed as ``retired,'' and
the contribution was reported to have been given on June 30, the
last day of the second quarter. Mrs. Bush's occupation was listed
as ``homemaker.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush also received $1,000 checks from other celebrities,
including actors Chuck Norris and Pat Boone, and Dallas Cowboys
quarterback Troy Aikman. Former Bush spokesperson David Beckwith,
who was dismissed by the campaign earlier this week, also
contributed $1,000. Bush's campaign reported that the average
contribution was $466.69.
</P>
<P>
   Bush acknowledged Thursday that his decision not to accept
matching funds was inspired in part by a lesson he said he learned
from Bob Dole's 1996 campaign for president. Dole, who accepted
matching funds after setting his own fund-raising records in 1995,
hit the spending ceiling in April 1996 after being forced to spend
millions to keep pace with Forbes' advertising blitzes.
</P>
<P>
   During the summer of 1996 and in the weeks leading up to the
election, the Republican Party had to prop up Dole's candidacy by
spending millions of dollars on issue advertising that prominently
featured the former Kansas senator. By then, President Clinton had
widened a big lead.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm mindful of what happened in 1996 and I'm not going to let
it happen to me,'' Bush said Thursday. ``I'm going to win.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush said he would also have to spend more to keep pace with
Gore, his probable Democratic foe. ``There's a chance I'll be
running against somebody who will be able to jump in a government
airplane and travel the country making promises,'' Bush said. ``I
want to be able to respond. The best way to do that is to not take
taxpayer dollars.''
</P>
<P>
   Elizabeth Dole, who now ranks a distant second to Bush in most
presidential opinion polls, reported raising $3.5 million during
the first half of the year, including $2.8 million between April 1
and June 30. Mrs. Dole also said she has $1.8 million in the bank.
Mrs. Dole's campaign reported that 43 percent of individuals that
gave her at least $200 were women.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our campaign is gaining strength and momentum,'' Mrs. Dole
said Thursday. ``This campaign is on its way to making history.''
</P>
<P>
   Duane Andreas, the chairman of the Archer Daniels Midland Co.,
and his wife each gave $1,000 to Mrs. Dole. Archer Daniels is the
nation's largest producer of ethanol, and Andreas has been a
long-time supporter of the Republican Party and Dole.
</P>
<P>
   Forbes' campaign is in debt as of June 30, according to his
report. Forbes gave his campaign $6 million of his own money in the
last quarter, while also managing to raise $2.7 million from
supporters. During the first half of this year, Forbes took in a
total of $9.5 million, including $6.6 million of his own money.
</P>
<P>
   But by the end of June, Forbes had just $1.2 million in his bank
account, but his debts totalled $1.4 million, leaving his campaign
with a debt of $200,000.
</P>
<P>
   Dan Quayle, the former vice president, has raised nearly $3.5
million in the first six months of the year, a sum he had hoped to
raise by April 1. But as of June 30, he had only $128,750 in the
bank.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
