<SLUG> BC-MEDICARE-ART-NYT </SLUG>
  
 HMOs TO DROP 327,000 MEDICARE PATIENTS  (jw) 
 By ROBERT PEAR   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The Clinton administration said Thursday that
327,000 Medicare beneficiaries would be dropped next year by health
maintenance organizations that are pulling out of the Medicare
program or reducing the areas they serve.
</P>
<P>
   The number is higher than initial estimates by spokesmen for the
managed care industry, who said two weeks ago that at least 250,000
people would be dropped.
</P>
<P>
   The actual numbers, reported Thursday by the Department of
Health and Human Services, show thousands of people forced out of
Medicare HMOs in various states, including 39,000 in New York,
31,000 in Arizona, 29,000 in Florida, 34,000 in Louisiana and
32,000 in Texas. About 9,000 people in Connecticut and 6,000 in New
Jersey will also be affected.
</P>
<P>
   While many of these people may be able to join other HMOs, the
experience of being dropped by a health plan can be unnerving for
elderly and disabled people, who must hastily figure out how to
meet their medical needs.
</P>
<P>
   The government data indicate that more than 10 percent of all
Medicare beneficiaries in HMOs have been or will be dropped by
their health plans in 1999 or 2000.
</P>
<P>
   About 407,000 beneficiaries were forced out of Medicare HMOs
this year, because of decisions announced by managed care plans in
late 1998. Thus, in two years, 734,000 people will have been
dropped.
</P>
<P>
   Of the people dropped from private health plans last year, 44
percent enrolled in another HMO, 44 percent voluntarily decided to
go into Medicare's traditional fee-for-service program and 12
percent went into the fee-for-service program because they had no
other option.
</P>
<P>
   About 6.2 million of the 39 million Medicare beneficiaries are
in HMOs. They join because they are generally protected against
catastrophic costs and they usually receive extra benefits, like
prescription drugs. Many HMOs said earlier this month that they
intended to increase premiums or cut benefits for elderly
subscribers next year.
</P>
<P>
   When an HMO pulls out of Medicare, it is normally barred from
the program for five years. Forty-one of the 305 Medicare HMOs are
pulling out of the program next year, and 58 will reduce their
service areas.
</P>
<P>
   People dropped from Medicare HMOs can buy certain types of
private health insurance to fill gaps in the original
fee-for-service program. But Michael Hash, deputy administrator of
the Health Care Financing Administration, which runs Medicare, said
there was no guarantee that they could get insurance covering
prescription drugs.
</P>
<P>
   Of the 327,000 people being dropped by HMOs next year, 79,000
live where no other managed care plans are available to them.
</P>
<P>
   Hash rejected the argument of HMOs that say they are not paid
enough by Medicare. He said the administration would oppose efforts
in Congress to restore some of the Medicare money cut from HMOs
under a 1997 law.
</P>
<P>
   Karen Ignagni, president of the American Association of Health
Plans, which represents HMOs, said that Thursday's announcement
confirmed that Medicare's managed care program was ``in crisis.''
HMOs want to continue serving Medicare beneficiaries, Ms. Ignagni,
said, but often find that they cannot afford to do so.
</P>
<P>
   Hash said some health plans were trying to scare beneficiaries
by talking about a crisis in Medicare's HMO program.
</P>
<P>
   Susan Pisano, a spokeswoman for the American Association of
Health Plans, said: ``I don't know what the scare tactics are. If
people believe that disruption to the lives of 700,000 people is
not a crisis, we don't know what it takes.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
