<HEADLINE>
BELGIAN RIDER MAKES A MOVE  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Belgium, France, Russia, Kazakstan, Spain)   c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ST. ETIENNE, France _ Ludo Dierckxsen of Belgium and the Lampre
team won the 11th stage of the Tour de France, a 123.3-mile stretch
through darkly wooded hills from Le Bourg d'Oisans to St. Etienne,
by 1 minute 26 seconds Thursday over Dmitri Konyshev of Russia and
Alexander Vinokourov of Kazakstan, and he finished 22:18 ahead of
the pack.
</P>
<P>
   But nothing changed at the top of the standing, where Lance
Armstrong of the U.S. Postal Service team remained ahead of Abraham
Olano, a Spaniard with ONCE, by 7:42, with Alex Zuelle 5 seconds
back. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Dierckxsen, the Belgian national champion, pulled away about 20
kilometers from the finish and sped to victory.
</P>
<P>
   He rose from 77th place to 52nd, nearly 52 minutes behind
Armstrong.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
