</P>
<P>
   ``I think that the United States can contribute to the process
more as facilitator,'' said Barak, `` than as a kind of policeman,
judge and arbitrator at the same time.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton, nodding as Barak spoke, said he agreed. But Clinton
also made clear the enormous stake the United States, and he as its
leader, has in the Mideast peace process.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have done what we could, consistently, for more than 20
years now, through all kinds of administrations, to try to advance
the peace process,'' said Clinton. ``I have probably spent more
time on it than anyone has, and certainly I've spent a lot of time
on it.''
</P>
<P>
   During his first year in office, Clinton hosted former Israeli
Prime Minister Yitzhak Rabin and Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat
for a South Lawn signing of an historic peace accord. Over the past
