</P>
<P>
   Barak said Thursday he would honor the Wye agreement, which
calls on Israel to relinquish to the Palestinians additional land
on the West Bank.
</P>
<P>
   ``But there is a need to combine the implementation of Wye with
the moving forward of the permanent status agreement,'' Barak said.
</P>
<P>
   Permanent status issues, including the question of Palestinian
statehood and the future of Jerusalem, are regarded as among the
most contentious issues between Israel and the Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
   A May deadline for the resolution of those issues was missed,
and Clinton has said he would hope the permanent status talks can
begin soon and be completed within a year.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday's meeting was designed as a first step toward building
confidence between the two men and, according to senior Israeli and
American officials, it achieved those goals.
</P>
<P>
   Barak, a career soldier who also serves as Israel's Defense
Minister, was scheduled to meet Friday with Secretary of Defense
William Cohen and Secretary of State Madeleine Albright.
</P>
<P>
   Barak is to spend the weekend meeting with representatives from
the U.S. Jewish community in New York, before returning to the
White House for a state dinner Sunday night and further meetings
with Clinton on Monday.
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday, the two leaders met by themselves, without the
aides and notetakers that customarily accompany heads of state in
such meetings. And the venue was the Treaty Room in the White House
residence, deemed a more intimate setting than the businesslike
Oval Office, where Clinton ordinarily receives official guests.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
