<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIZ-DIARY-$ADV18-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SHORT ITEMS ON SURVEYS, RESEARCH AND NEW PRODUCTS  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, JULY 18) 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: N.Y.)   (af)  
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Cold Comfort For Migraines &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Drug companies have spent millions of dollars researching new
treatments to relieve migraine headaches. Now comes a simple new
product called Migraine Ice from the Mentholatum Co. _ essentially,
an instant ice pack with adhesive backing to affix to the forehead,
temples or back of the neck for immediate pain relief.
</P>
<P>
   Funny to look at, yes. But cold therapy is a long-accepted
method for reducing migraine pain, according to Dr. Lawrence
Newman, director of the Headache Institute at St. Luke's-Roosevelt
Hospital in New York and head of the Pain Management Council, a
promotional group sponsored by Mentholatum.
</P>
<P>
   Mentholatum's Japanese parent was looking to develop new
products based on a technology used in Japan to reduce fever: a
water-based gel that stays cold for up to four hours. Mentholatum
researchers concluded that migraine sufferers _ compared with
people with ankle sprains or joint pain, for example _ had the
greatest need for convenient cold therapy, if only to relieve the
pain between the time a migraine strikes and when pain medication
takes effect, said Marty Cohen, vice president of sales and
marketing at the company in Orchard Park, N.Y.
</P>
<P>
   Each treatment costs about $2.50 _ more, of course, than
wrapping a few ice cubes in a washcloth. But Mentholatum is
promoting the relative convenience of its new product. ``It was one
of those V-8 moments,'' Cohen said of the idea.
</P>
<P>
   Migraine sufferers, though, are unlikely to slap their foreheads
at the thought. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Patricia Winters Lauro &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
