<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COMPUWARE-VIASOFT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMPUWARE SET TO BUY VIASOFT
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ariz., Mich.)  (rk) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Compuware Corp., a provider of business software and
technology support services, will acquire Viasoft Inc., a leading
vendor of software tools for fixing year 2000 computer problems,
for $164 million, the companies said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Viasoft, based in Phoenix, reached a market value of more than
$1 billion in 1997, its stock rising to more than $65 a share, as
investors anticipated soaring demand for its Year 2000 products.
But the company later became a prime example of the problems facing
year 2000 companies as the business wound down.
</P>
<P>
   With investors pessimistic about its future, Viasoft's shares
spent much of the year below $4 before climbing recently to $6.3438
on Wednesday. Viasoft rose $2.25 Thursday, to $8.5938. Shares of
Compuware edged up 50 cents, to $35.
</P>
<P>
   The price for Viasoft comes to $9 a share, a 42 percent premium
to Wednesday's closing price.
</P>
<P>
   Compuware, a more diversified company based in Farmington Hills,
Mich., began reducing its reliance on year 2000 revenue early last
year. Viasoft waited until this year to shift its focus to products
and services that could sell well after the year 2000 transition is
over. Compuware said it was particularly attracted to Viasoft's
tools to link existing mainframe computer systems to e-commerce and
for making improvements in old software.
</P>
</TEXT>
