<HEADER>
A1898 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SERIAL-KILLER-FEDS-HN     07-15 1240
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SERIAL-KILLER-FEDS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DETAILS REVEAL INTERAGENCY RIVALRY IN HUNT FOR SUSPECT IN SERIAL
KILLINGS 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By ARMANDO VILLAFRANCA 
and JAMES PINKERTON 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ Emerging details about efforts to track down and
arrest a suspected serial killer indicate that federal agents
tripped up on at least two critical occasions, threatening the
fragile relationship with the suspect's family, who ultimately
brokered the surrender of Angel Maturino Resendez.
</P>
<P>
   The first misstep occurred in early June, according to a
law-enforcement source close to the investigation, when an FBI
agent offended the fugitive's sister just as a Texas Ranger was
developing a relationship with her. The agent was acting at the
request of Don K. Clark, head of the FBI's Houston office, said the
source, who asked not to be identified.
</P>
<P>
   According to a second source, a high-ranking Texas
law-enforcement official, Clark then frustrated Rangers and the
suspect's wife a week ago with his aggressive effort to put her on
television to appeal to Maturino Resendez to surrender. Maturino
Resendez also went by the alias Rafael Resendez-Ramirez.
</P>
<P>
   The final blow came when the FBI announced the suspect's arrest
Tuesday, again slighting the Rangers, who had pulled off the
dramatic surrender earlier that morning on an international bridge
in El Paso.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it just boils down to the fact that the FBI got beat
and they can't stand it,'' said the second source, who also asked
not to be identified. ``And then the FBI struggles to understand
why they are so disrespected and can't develop relationships with
other agencies. They want it to be a one-way street, all for
them.''
</P>
<P>
   Ultimately, the differences were set aside.
</P>
<P>
   The sister, Manuela Maturino, came to trust the Ranger, Sgt.
Drew Carter. Her brother came out of hiding in Mexico and
peacefully surrendered in Texas. He now is in the Harris County
Jail in Houston, a suspect in at least nine slayings since 1997.
</P>
<P>
   But these new details are significant in the implication that
interagency rivalry may have jeopardized one of the largest
manhunts in recent U.S. history.
</P>
<P>
   According to the first source, Clark apparently tried to
undercut Carter several weeks ago by asking the FBI office in
Albuquerque, N.M., to dispatch an agent to Maturino's home in that
city _ before Carter could arrive for an interview he had already
scheduled.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, Carter got a chilly reception from the woman.
Details of the meeting are unclear, but Maturino shut down talks
with investigators afterward.
</P>
<P>
   ``The word I got was she was offended by the way she got
approached by the FBI,'' said the source. ``The initial contact on
her was not good, and that was the FBI. (Carter) had to re-initiate
contact.''
</P>
<P>
   The incident caused a riff because the Rangers were not told
ahead of time about the Albuquerque visit initiated by the FBI in
Houston. Shortly afterward, representatives of the multiagency task
force investigating the serial crimes held a meeting to defuse the
animosity and prevent future breakdowns in communication.
</P>
<P>
   Carter, a 32-year-old rookie in the elite Rangers corps who has
assumed folk-hero status for his work on the case, was reluctant
this week to discuss the incident because he must work with the FBI
in future investigations.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know what happened, I know, and I just don't know that
that's a wound that needs to be addressed,'' he said. ``To bring
that up, I think we're digging up a wound that I don't want to
open. I don't think that will be positive.''
</P>
<P>
   At the time, though, it was Carter who smoothed things over.
</P>
<P>
   Carter had been assigned to the investigation of the Dec. 17
slaying of a Houston-area physician and had been one of the first
to suspect it was linked to another brutal killing in Weimar in
May. When he heard about Manuela Maturino, he telephoned to set up
an interview. After the rocky start, the two bonded.
</P>
<P>
   ``We established a trust in that we both sensed sincerity in the
other individual's questions and in their answers and in their
concerns,'' Carter said. ``I think Manuela and their family are
good people. They were legitimately concerned for the safety of
their brother, but at the same time they did not approve of the
crimes that were being committed.''
</P>
<P>
   The federal officials assented, telling Maturino that Carter was
the point man in their discussions. In the six weeks he worked with
Maturino, Carter said, he flew to Albuquerque three times and
talked to her frequently by telephone.
</P>
<P>
   The major break in the case came last Sunday, when Maturino
called Carter on his cellular phone to report that her brother was
ready to give himself up.
</P>
<P>
   Maturino's pastor in Albuquerque, Troy Robinson, however,
downplays any impression that there was ever any tension between
the woman and any law-enforcement officials.
</P>
<P>
   ``In every meeting there was a Texas Ranger, a U.S. marshal and
an FBI agent. All of them were very considerate to her,'' he said.
Three formal meetings were held, beginning in mid-June, he said.
</P>
<P>
   The second source has a harsher view.
</P>
<P>
   ``I firmly believe that had those folks treated that lady
properly ... had shown the respect and compassion that Drew Carter
did, she would have picked up the cell phone and made the call to
them,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Later in the investigations, authorities convinced Maturino
Resendez's common-law wife, Julieta Dominguez Reyes, to fly to
Houston from her home in Mexico to talk with two FBI experts who
were crafting a psychological profile of the fugitive.
</P>
<P>
   ``The deal we cut with the FBI was that we would let two FBI
profilers in the hotel to interview her,'' the second source said.
Clark told one of his profilers that he wanted to bring her over to
the task force office and have her publicly plead for her husband
to surrender.
</P>
<P>
   Dominguez refused, the Mexican assistant attorney general who
was with her refused and the Rangers didn't like it either.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hell, we had homicide cases we had to talk to her about,'' the
official said.
</P>
<P>
   Clark wound up making the appeal himself.
</P>
<P>
   The final straw was on the day of the surrender. The Rangers
were planning to announce Maturino Resendez's arrest. But word got
back immediately to the FBI, and the announcement was made directly
from Washington, with FBI Director Louis Freeh announcing the
arrest during a congressional hearing.
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday, Clark defended his actions.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't regret having made any decisions that I had to make in
this case,'' said Clark. ``If we made some calls somewhere along
the line that may have appeared to upset or do something else, then
we live with those and we go ahead on. The end result is what
counts.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't want to look back at adverse things in this
investigation because I think there's a lot of hard work by a lot
of people here on a very complex investigation and a whole team it
took to put this together, not one agency, not one person, not one
anything.''
</P>
<P>
   Clark said several factors contributed to the Maturino
Resendez's surrender, including placing the suspect on the FBI's 10
Most Wanted list, generating nationwide publicity on the case and
getting the suspect's wife to beg her husband to surrender himself.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Chronicle staff writer Patty Reinert contributed to this report
from Albuquerque, N.M.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
