<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-15 21:20 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1900 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-RUGOVA-NYT &LR;      07-15 0785
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-RUGOVA-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ETHNIC ALBANIAN LEADER RETURNS TO KOSOVO AMID CHEERS 
</HEADLINE>
  (yn) 
 By JOHN KIFNER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PRISTINA, Yugoslavia _ Ibrahim Rugova, leader of a decade of
principled, but largely futile, nonviolent resistance to Serbian
domination, returned here Thursday to a political landscape that
was at once transformed and confused.
</P>
<P>
   He has been criticized for appearing on television with Slobodan
Milosevic, the Yugoslav president, in the midst of the brutal
campaign to drive Albanians out of Kosovo. He has also faced
criticism for failing to visit refugee camps and refusing to
actively support the Kosovo Liberation Army's armed rebellion. But
he received a warm welcome Thursday from a cheering crowd as he
arrived at the new U.N. headquarters here, accompanied by American
diplomats.
</P>
<P>
   Even as Rugova held a crowded, sweaty and enigmatic news
conference for a crush of foreign journalists Thursday afternoon,
the man who _ if all goes according to plan _ will really run
Kosovo came to town with considerably less fanfare.
</P>
<P>
   The man is Bernard Kouchner, the former French government
minister and leader of Doctors Without Borders, who is to be the
chief civil administrator of the war-torn province, with the title
of special representative of the secretary general.
</P>
<P>
   ``The priority is law and order, order and law,'' Kouchner said
in a brief meeting with reporters.
</P>
<P>
   It is a daunting task. His predecessor, Sergio Vieira de Mello,
ended his brief tour in office by issuing a statement decrying
Kosovo's postwar slide toward chaos despite the presence of more
than 32,000 NATO peacekeeping troops.
</P>
<P>
   ``Killings, kidnapping, forced expulsions, house burnings and
looting are a daily occurrence'' directed at members of minority
groups, the statement said. ``These are criminal acts. They cannot
be excused by the suffering that has been inflicted in the past.
Kosovo's future must be built on justice, not vengeance.''
</P>
<P>
   There are simply no Kosovo government institutions left. Kosovo,
treasured in Serbian history and folklore, was the key to
Milosevic's plan to seize power by unleashing Serbian nationalism.
In 1990, Milosevic ended Kosovo's constitutional autonomy,
effectively firing the parliament and dismissing Albanians from
jobs in government and state enterprises.
</P>
<P>
   Under Rugova's leadership, Albanians resisted with a nonviolent
``parallel society,'' holding school classes and even elections for
a powerless parliament and president _ Rugova _ in their homes.
</P>
<P>
   Milosevic loyalists and nationalists were the mayors and police
chiefs for the most part, but these Serbs were swept away by the
arrival of NATO troops a month ago. Kosovo Albanians, out of work
for a decade, now want their old jobs back.
</P>
<P>
   In this void have come the United Nations and other
international agencies like the Organization for Security and
Cooperation in Europe, which is supposed to concentrate on
developing democratic institutions; the European Union, focusing on
physical rebuilding, and a host of lesser aid groups. So many
hundreds of millions of dollars of aid have been pledged that
senior international officials worry privately that the money
cannot be effectively absorbed.
</P>
<P>
   The U.N. operation here, which is carrying out the mandate of
the Security Council, says it will determine what the law is,
mostly old Yugoslav law except where that conflicts with European
norms.
</P>
<P>
   There are at least two other claims to a government. One is from
Rugova, who drew an 80 percent turnout as the sole candidate in an
underground election in March 1998, which was boycotted by his
critics. The other is from his rival, Hashim Thaci, the rebel army
leader who dominated the Albanian delegation at the Rambouillet
peace conference in France, and who calls himself the president of
the ``provisional government.''
</P>
<P>
   As the rebel army gained popular support because of killings by
Serbs, Rugova's stature here is believed to have declined. In
recent weeks, however, the rebel force has appeared to be splitting
into factions.
</P>
<P>
   U.N. officials believe it will be about a year before elections
can be held.
</P>
<P>
   The United Nations is attempting to form a Kosovo Transitional
Council of about a dozen people _ its final membership is still
uncertain _ from various political parties and factions. Rugova and
Thaci have both said they would join.
</P>
<P>
   ``We will cooperate with everybody and we will be represented on
the international forums together,'' Rugova said.
</P>
<P>
   Asked about his appearance with Milosevic during the war and
rumors that he might have been drugged, Rugova replied, ``That was
not cooperation and it's over now.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
