<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    CompuServe, AltaVista keep free deals coming
 &HT;    By Frances Katz
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Want to get on the information superhighway on the
cheap? Online service CompuServe continues to offer rebates on
certain makes of IBM computers if users sign up for three years of
the service at the $21.95 monthly price tag.
</P>
<P>
   Then after you get your computer, you can sign up with search
engine AltaVista, which may have come up with the Internet service
provider's worst nightmare: free dial-up Internet service. Both
deals are designed to draw more users and more advertising dollars
to the respective services.
</P>
<P>
   AltaVista's free Internet access is made possible through a deal
with a small Silicon Valley start-up called 1stUP.com. The company
claims to be the first to provide the technology for Web
businesses, e-commerce players and any Web site to offer Internet
access.
</P>
<P>
   As with Juno's free e-mail and Internet service, users will have
to look at constantly rotating advertising banners in exchange for
free access to the Net.
</P>
<P>
   The service should be available sometime next week. Consumers
who decide to use AltaVista's free ISP service will download the
software from the AltaVista Web site (www.altavista.com), although
AltaVista may eventually offer the software on a CD.
</P>
<P>
   As with Juno and other free online services, subscribers will
complete a registration questionnaire and they'll receive ads for
products they are interested in. 1stUp says that access will be
available from almost anywhere in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   The AltaVista ISP will have an online advertising window framing
banner ads as well as an AltaVista search window.
</P>
<P>
   1stUp co-founder and Vice President Jonah Steinhart says the
company's mission is to ``be the leading technology provider for
ad-supported Internet access. We want to enable our partners to
build even stronger relationships with their customers.''
</P>
<P>
   1stUp hopes to join with other major Internet companies and
offers a wide range of solutions along with dial-up Internet
access, including e-mail and customer support. The type of service
will vary by what each individual partner needs. In the case of
AltaVista, the search engine has its own free e-mail service and
doesn't need 1stUp's e-mail component.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
