<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COKE-EARNINGS16-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Coca-Cola's profit down, but optimism up
 &HT;    By Henry Unger
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Coca-Cola's stock rose more than 3 percent Thursday
after the company reported a sharp drop in second-quarter earnings
but indicated the worst may be over.
</P>
<P>
   Hurt by a European health scare and troubled economies overseas,
Coca-Cola said Thursday its second-quarter profits fell 21 percent
from a year ago. The recall of its products last month in Belgium
and France was responsible for about 25 percent of the profit
decline.
</P>
<P>
   But while the first half of the year has been disappointing for
the company, Chairman and Chief Executive Officer M. Douglas
Ivester and industry analysts are expecting the rest of the year to
be kinder.
</P>
<P>
   Most analysts predict the company will be able to earn more in
the second half of 1999 than it did in 1998. For the first six
months of this year, Coca-Cola's earnings have fallen 18 percent
from a year ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are now starting to see stabilization in many markets and
gradual economic improvements in others,'' Ivester said.
</P>
<P>
   In the second quarter, however, the company earned $942 million,
or 38 cents a share. That was down from $1.19 billion, or 48 cents
a share, a year ago.
</P>
<P>
   Of the 10 cents-a-share decline, the company attributed 2 cents
to 3 cents to the recall of its products that caused full or
partial sales bans in several key European markets.
</P>
<P>
   The company also experienced increased marketing expenses as it
tried to reinvigorate its brands once the recalls were lifted.
</P>
<P>
   Globally, Coca-Cola saw a 2 percent drop in quarterly case sales
_ only the second time that has happened in more than a decade.
</P>
<P>
   ``This past year can be characterized as a period of volatility
and uncertainty in the global economic environment,'' Ivester said
in a statement. ``Looking back, the depth of the economic downturns
in many markets has been greater than we had originally
anticipated.''
</P>
<P>
   In Europe, case volume dropped 6 percent. That compared with a
10 percent gain a year ago. In addition to the recall, sales were
hurt by ``continued difficult economic conditions in Germany,
Russia and parts of Eastern Europe which were influenced by the
recent war in Kosovo,'' the company said.
</P>
<P>
   Case sales _ the number of 24 eight-ounce servings shipped to
retailers _ fell in virtually every part of the world, except in
Latin America, where volume was flat. Mexico, Central America and
the Caribbean saw gains, but Brazil, Chile, Venezuela and Colombia
posted declines.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are ongoing problems with Coke's international
operations, which dominate the company's earnings stream,'' said
Roy Burry, an analyst with Brown Brothers Harriman &AMP; Co.
</P>
<P>
   Volume was down 9 percent in China, which is a major contributor
to results in Coca-Cola's Middle and Far East group. Although the
company blamed poor weather and a backlash to U.S. products
following the bombing of the Chinese Embassy in Belgrade,
Yugoslavia, Wall Street expected better results.
</P>
<P>
   Even in North America, which has not been hit by a recall or
economic turmoil, case sales fell 1 percent. This time the culprit
was recent price increases that crimped consumer demand. Partly
because of price increases, company revenue rose 4 percent to $5.38
billion in the quarter.
</P>
<P>
   Going forward, the forecast is for Coca-Cola to earn 37 cents a
share in the third quarter, compared with 35 cents a year ago, and
about 33 cents in the fourth quarter, against 24 cents in the 1998
period.
</P>
<P>
   While Credit Suisse First Boston analyst Martin Romm predicts a
moderate improvement in the third quarter, he expects the company
will still feel the effects of the European recall.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know the ongoing expense in the third quarter _
getting back the consumer and the shelf space and market share _
but I think all those things will come at a price,'' Romm said.
</P>
<P>
   Company executives, including Ivester, are scheduled to talk to
industry analysts at a meeting next Thursday in New York.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
