<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COKE-SUIT16-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Class-action part of Coca-Cola suit is not dismissed
 &HT;    By Henry Unger
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Coca-Cola Co. failed Thursday in its bid to get the
class-action portion of a racial discrimination suit dismissed.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. District Judge Richard Story said it would be ``premature''
and a ``disservice'' to both sides to throw out the class-action
allegations at such an early stage in the case. The information
gathering, or ``discovery,'' process has just begun, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of the grave concerns I have is a lack of knowledge,''
Story said during the two-hour hearing in Atlanta. As a result, he
wants both sides to spend the next few months accumulating and
exchanging information, analyzing documents and taking depositions.
</P>
<P>
   Story pointed out that his ruling does not mean the plaintiffs
have succeeded in gaining class-action status. That could only come
after the discovery process is completed, and only if the judge is
convinced the case is appropriate for a class action.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are still significant legal and management issues to be
resolved,'' Story said.
</P>
<P>
   While announcing his ruling, the judge said he must take
employment discrimination cases very seriously. Story quoted from a
Court of Appeals case saying the legal system has ``consistently
recognized that discrimination in employment is one of the most
deplorable forms of discrimination known to our society.''
</P>
<P>
   One former and four current Coca-Cola employees have sued the
company, alleging discrimination against African-American employees
in pay, promotions and performance evaluations. They seek
class-action status so they can represent another 1,500 black,
salaried Coke employees in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Coca-Cola denies it has discriminated against African-Americans.
</P>
<P>
   But the company unsuccessfully argued Thursday that there are
too many individual facts and circumstances among existing and
prospective plaintiffs for the case to ever be handled as a
class-action suit. Company attorney William Clineburg Jr. argued
that it would break down into 1,500 mini-trials.
</P>
<P>
   ``Having 1,500 jury trials is not going to result in any benefit
for the class as a whole,'' Clineburg told the judge.
</P>
<P>
   Story, however, remained unconvinced. He said it might be more
efficient to have one case and 1,500 trials than 1,500 cases and
1,500 trials.
</P>
<P>
   But that decision, the judge said, needs to be made after more
facts are known. The company just recently handed over to the
plaintiffs some 13,000 pages of documents that need to be read and
analyzed.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're disappointed with this ruling,'' said Coca-Cola
spokesman Robert Baskin. ``But it's the first step in a long
process. ... After it's over, we're confident it will be determined
that Coca-Cola does not discriminate.''
</P>
<P>
   Plaintiffs' attorneys Cyrus Mehri and Pamela Coukos said they
were delighted with the ruling.
</P>
<P>
   ``The most powerful institution in the South tried to turn back
the clock,'' Mehri said, referring to the company's attempt to get
the class-action claims dismissed. But, he added, a ``courageous
judge'' stopped it.
</P>
<P>
   ``This isn't the time to do a victory lap,'' Mehri added. ``This
is the time to roll up our sleeves and get to work.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
