u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GA-GASDEREG16-COX     07-15 0721
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GA-GASDEREG16-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Marketers rush to land deals with apartment units
 &HT;    By Matthew C. Quinn
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Competition is fast and furious for the natural gas
accounts of apartment managers and residents.
</P>
<P>
   Shell Energy, one of Georgia's 20 certified gas marketers, and
Lane Co., one of Atlanta's largest property management companies,
announced a deal this week designating Shell as the ``preferred
natural gas provider'' for Lane's rental units. Lane owns and
manages between 20,000 and 25,000 Georgia apartments, 30 percent of
which use natural gas.
</P>
<P>
   Post Properties chose SCANA Energy this year for its 16,000
units. Julian LeCraw &AMP; Co. also chose the South Carolina-based
natural gas supplier to serve 5,000 to 6,000 of its apartments.
</P>
<P>
   Gables Residential signed up with Peachtree Natural Gas for more
than 7,000 units. The gas supplier also counts a number of public
housing authorities among its customers.
</P>
<P>
   According to the Georgia Apartment Association, there are about
500,000 apartment units in the state. About 60 percent are
all-electric, and 40 percent use natural gas.
</P>
<P>
   Landlords typically negotiate ``continuous service'' agreements
that ensure the gas flow will continue when apartments are vacant,
avoiding such problems as frozen pipes during the winter. The
agreements also pre-empt $25 disconnect and reconnect fees to
landlords from AGL, which will remain a distribution company even
after deregulation.
</P>
<P>
   When tenants move out, they notify marketers and are billed for
their usage. The gas flow to the apartment then goes on landlords'
accounts until a new tenant moves in.
</P>
<P>
   But most tenants are winding up with less choice than homeowners
when it comes to selecting a marketer. Landlords are rewriting
leases en masse to make clear that they _ and not tenants _ have
the right to choose gas suppliers. Many have asked tenants to sign
over those rights until their current leases expire.
</P>
<P>
   John Slattery, president of the apartment association, estimated
that 85 percent to 90 percent of residents have agreed, though they
are giving up the right to choose their own suppliers.
</P>
<P>
   Spokesmen for the Public Service Commission and the Governor's
Office of Consumer Affairs both said the practice is permissible,
so long as tenants give proper authorization.
</P>
<P>
   Several marketers said they charge landlords the same prices
that tenants pay. Other financial inducements offered the landlords
have been kept confidential. AGL has offered ``continuous service''
agreements for years as a monopoly supplier, and marketers are
rushing to fill the void that will be created when the utility
exits the sales business this fall.
</P>
<P>
   A. Clifton Payne, vice president for marketing at Georgia
Natural Gas, said agreements with apartment managers are highly
sought.
</P>
<P>
   ``They give us a block of meters we know will remain ours
although people are turning over in the apartments,'' said Payne,
whose company claims 30,000 units. The turnover rate in Georgia
apartments is estimated at 60 percent to 70 percent a year.
</P>
<P>
   Deborah Latham, president of Peachtree Natural Gas, said her
company has ``cut every kind of imaginable deal you can think of''
to secure such agreements, from supplying gas grills for pools to
``sales development fees'' paid directly to landlords or to upgrade
units for energy efficiency.
</P>
<P>
   Linda Joyce-Menk, director of cooperative programs and services
at Lane Co., said her company was offered sign-up bonuses but
declined to accept them.
</P>
<P>
   ``We did not see deregulation as a moneymaker,'' she said.
``This is not something you get greedy over.'' But she added that
Lane is seeking to recoup more than $30,000 it has spent to figure
out deregulation through its deal with Shell.
</P>
<P>
   SCANA said its customers in apartments have received all the
benefits extended to other customers, including SCANA's $50 free
gas offer that expired in April. SCANA distributed $50 grocery gift
certificates to Post residents displaced by a recent Atlanta
apartment fire.
</P>
<P>
   Latham said Peachtree's offer of free gas during the summer is
going to tenants in apartment houses it serves.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are treating tenants just like everybody else,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
