<DOCNO> NYT19990715.0424 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-15 21:24 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1912 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-AFFIRMATIVE-ACTION-NY     07-15 0948
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AFFIRMATIVE-ACTION-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ATLANTA'S MAYOR DEFIES THREAT TO END AFFIRMATIVE ACTION 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Leaning over four floors of balconies and surrounding
a stage at City Hall, hundreds of black Atlantans let loose their
``amens'' Thursday at a rally called by the mayor in defiance of
the threat of a lawsuit to end the city's affirmative action
program.
</P>
<P>
   Even as the courts in recent years have chipped away at similar
race-based benefit programs across the country, the mayor, Bill
Campbell, has said he refuses to allow the same thing to happen in
Atlanta, which is more than two-thirds black and is known as the
cradle of the civil rights movement.
</P>
<P>
   A conservative public interest legal group, the Southeastern
Legal Foundation, gave the city 30 days' notice on June 14 that if
its affirmative action program was not abolished voluntarily, the
foundation would file a lawsuit. The foundation, led by its
president, Matthew Glavin, has said that the program violates the
Fourteenth Amendment and that it will file suit by the first week
of August.
</P>
<P>
   Campbell, who in 1960 was the only black child to integrate the
school system in Raleigh, N.C., told the rally that Atlanta must
not let outside forces push back the gains of the civil rights
movement.
</P>
<P>
   ``They want us to be able to dunk, to dance and to run, but not
to run our own businesses,'' the mayor said.
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta's affirmative action program was started in 1975 by its
first black mayor, Maynard Jackson, when minority-owned companies
received less than 1 percent of the money from city contracts. The
program got the attention of business when Jackson held up airport
construction because, he said, there were not enough minority
companies involved.
</P>
<P>
   Today the city, which is home to the nation's largest
black-owned contractor, H.J. Russell &AMP; Co., requires that 35
percent of its contracts be handled by minority-owned companies. In
1997 Atlanta awarded $109 million to about 800 companies registered
as minority-owned enterprises.
</P>
<P>
   In the previous year the private corporation established by city
officials to run the 1996 Summer Olympics, the Atlanta Committee
for the Olympic Games, awarded almost a third of its $387 million
in construction and vending contracts to companies owned primarily
by minorities and women. One of the main beneficiaries was H.J.
Russell, which won a 29 percent share of the $207 million spent to
build the Centennial Olympic Stadium, the main arena of the event.
</P>
<P>
   The program has been the focus of controversy outside of the
general debate over affirmative action. A series of articles in The
Atlanta Journal and Constitution this year detailed several abuses
in the system, including an incident in which a city employee
certified a business as eligible to bid as a minority-owned company
and then left to become head of that company, which later received
a $3 million contract from the city.
</P>
<P>
   There have been instances in which both white and minority
business people have said the program amounts to a patronage
system, where friends of city leaders receive big contracts. In
particular, there is a small core of Atlanta developers who have
over the years won bids on most of the city's biggest contracts,
including part of a $283 million renovation of the city's biggest
hospital and a $142 million project at the city's Underground
Atlanta shopping center.
</P>
<P>
   In a telephone interview Thursday morning, Campbell said that
Atlanta must remain a mecca for black businesses and that he would
go to jail before he sees the city stop its affirmative action
program. Losing, he said, is ``not an option.''
</P>
<P>
   If the foundation follows through with its threat of a lawsuit _
and it seems likely that it will _ Campbell and the city's
minority-owned contractors will face a coalition of lawyers that
has won a series of victories in this decade in shutting down
race-based preference programs in the South. The foundation,
through lawsuits and threats, has effectively drawn an
ever-constricting ring of affirmative-action defeats around
Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   In June the foundation successfully sued Fulton County, of which
Atlanta is the county seat, to discontinue its affirmative action
program. In his decision, a judge in U.S. District Court here said
that the data supplied by Fulton County officials could not show a
clear pattern of discrimination by the county against
minority-owned companies there. Atlanta uses the same set of data
as Fulton County to justify its program.
</P>
<P>
   The foundation ended affirmative action in Jacksonville, Fla.,
in 1991, in the Atlanta public schools in 1996 and in DeKalb
County, which adjoins Fulton County, in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   In the last year, letters from the group led DeKalb County's
public schools to stop its minority-to-majority busing program, and
the school board in Nashville to cease using race as a factor in
its magnet school program.
</P>
<P>
   But Campbell says that he remembers being that little boy in a
sea of white in the 1960 school year and that he is not intimidated
by the foundation's track record.
</P>
<P>
   ``We will fight to the death,'' Campbell said. ``There will be
no compromise, no capitulation whatsoever. There will be no judge
browbeating us into submission. Just because these right-wing hate
groups dress themselves in suits instead of robes doesn't mean it's
not still racism.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We will fight to the death,'' he said. ``There will be no
compromise, no capitulation whatsoever. There will be no judge
browbeating us into submission. Just because these right-wing hate
groups dress themselves in suits instead of robes doesn't mean it's
not still racism.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
