<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-15 21:28 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1917 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MANAGED-CARE16-COX     07-15 0851
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MANAGED-CARE16-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    SENATE APPROVES REPUBLICAN BILL ON MANAGED CARE
 &HT;    By LARRY LIPMAN
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ After four days of rancorous debate over competing
proposals to give patients more power over their managed care
health plans, the Senate voted along party lines late Thursday for
a Republican bill that the White House said would be vetoed.
</P>
<P>
   The final 53-47 vote vote seemed preordained early in the week
as Republicans, who hold a 10-seat majority, were able to hold all
but two or three members on every vote.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats remained united throughout the week, but lost on a
dozen amendments aimed at broadening the bill's coverage and giving
both patients and doctors greater influence over health care
decisions.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans John Chafee of Rhode Island and Peter Fitzgerald of
Illinois joined the unanimous Democrats in opposing the final bill.
</P>
<P>
   The issue has not been voted on in the House. But Vice President
Al Gore, who joined key Democratic senators in the Capitol a few
hours before the final Senate vote, said that ``if the Republican
leadership insists on going through this charade and passing a bill
of goods they've been trying to promote, President Clinton will
veto it in a minute.''
</P>
<P>
   Senate Majority Leader Trent Lott, R-Miss., urged senators not
to be swayed by a veto threat. Lott noted the administration had
indicated it would veto several bills that were later signed into
law after a House-Senate conference.
</P>
<P>
   ``To the president and to those who have not supported the
Republican position on the 'Patients' Bill of Rights Plus', work
with us,'' Lott said. ``Let's make it happen.''
</P>
<P>
   The Republican-sponsored bill would cost the federal government
$13.4 billion over five years. Among its major components:
</P>
<P>
   _ Patient protections: It covers 48 million people in employer
self-financed insurance plans, prohibits managed care plans from
charging patients more for using emergency rooms outside of the
plan, gives women direct access to gynecologists and allows
obstetricians and gynecologists to serve as primary care providers,
requires access to specialty care ``in a timely manner,'' covers
clinical trials for cancer patients only, and requires all managed
care plans to allow mastectomy patients to remain in a hospital as
long as determined necessary by a doctor.
</P>
<P>
   _ Appeals: The bill covers 124 million people in most managed
care plans, creates an internal and external appeals process in
cases of denial of treatment, and would impose a $10,000 fine for
managed care plans that do not comply with the ruling of the
external appeals panel.
</P>
<P>
   _ Tax provisions: It allows full tax deduction of health
insurance for the self-employed, the creation of tax-free medical
savings accounts to pay for health care, and full deduction of
long-term care insurance that is not employer-subsidized.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier in the day, Clinton blamed the power of the insurance
lobby for a 53-47 rejection of a key Democratic amendment that
would have allowed patients to sue their health maintenance
organization.
</P>
<P>
   ``The health insurers won't let them do it,'' Clinton said.
``It's a sad day for health care in America, but we're not done
yet, and this won't die.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore predicted the patients' rights issue could play a major
role in next year's elections.
</P>
<P>
   ``If they don't do the right thing on this, I think it will be a
major topic of debate all over the country this year, next year and
until this bill is passed,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Responding to Democratic criticisms that the GOP would leave
about 113 million people without adequate protection, Republicans
argued that their bill covered 48 million people in federally
regulated plans without usurping existing state regulations.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans also argued that if the Democratic proposal was
approved, insurance premiums would rise by more than 6 percent and
the number of uninsured Americans would increase by 1.8 million
people.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Bill Frist, R-Tenn., the only physician in the Senate, said
he was convinced the GOP bill ``keeps the patient at the center of
this debate.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our bill takes medical decisions out of the hand of the huge
bureaucracy of HMOs,'' he said, ``and puts them back in the hands
of the doctors.''
</P>
<P>
   But Sen. Tom Daschle, D-S.D., the Senate minority leader, said
the ``HMO'' in the Republican HMO reform bill stood for ``half
measures only.''
</P>
<P>
   The final action came after Lott objected to a request by Sen.
Bob Graham, D-Fla., that would have allowed a bipartisan group of
moderate senators to offer a compromise plan that included many of
the Democratic provisions and a scaled-back right to sue HMOs for
damages.
</P>
<P>
   After Lott's objection, Graham said the group would ``continue
the effort to fashion a reasonable, bipartisan plan.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is not the last chapter of this debate,'' Graham said.
Referring to the veto threat, he said, ``We don't want an issue. We
want a result that will help American families.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
