<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-15 21:30 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1921 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-AMOCO-EXPENSES-NYT &LR;      07-15 0815
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AMOCO-EXPENSES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BP AMOCO TO CUT $4 BILLION IN COSTS AND SELL $10 BILLION IN ASSETS 
 (DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By ALAN COWELL   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON _ BP Amoco PLC, the newly formed petroleum giant,
announced ambitious plans Thursday to cut annual costs by $4
billion over the next three years _ double the previous target _
and shed $10 billion of assets, including low-profit oil fields and
refineries.
</P>
<P>
   The magnitude of the cuts was a surprise and went far beyond
reductions the company first envisioned when the $55 billion merger
of British Petroleum and Amoco was completed six months ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``We thought that is was going to be hard for them to do
anything beyond the promises they had already made,'' said Adam
Sieminski, an oil analyst with Deutsche Banc Alex. Brown.
</P>
<P>
   The cuts almost certainly mean that the company will exceed its
previously announced goal of cutting 10,000 jobs from the
98,000-employee work force. Many of the jobs it already eliminated
were in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   BP Amoco officials would not specify how many additional jobs
might be cut, but said one of the first refining assets to be
divested would be its large Alliance Refinery in Louisiana. It
employs about 800 workers.
</P>
<P>
   Sir John Browne, the chief executive of the company, told
securities analysts at a meeting in London that the steps were
aimed at achieving a ``very significant improvement in underlying
performance.''
</P>
<P>
   The company also announced it had discovered one of the biggest
untapped pools of oil in the Gulf of Mexico and said it would
sharply increase capital spending to total $26 billion by 2002.
</P>
<P>
   British Petroleum shook the oil industry last year with its
acquisition of the Chicago-based Amoco, setting off a chain of
mergers that reflected the impact of weak oil prices.
</P>
<P>
   Many large oil companies have concluded that the only way to
remain profitable is to combine. The Exxon Corp. and The Mobil
Corp. announced an $87 billion merger deal in December, which would
create the world's largest oil company. BP Amoco itself announced a
$27 billion deal to buy the Atlantic Richfield Co. in March. Just
last week, Total Fina SA of France began a $43 billion hostile
takeover offer for another big French petroleum business, Elf
Aquitaine SA.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, oil prices were languishing at $10 per barrel.
Although they have since nearly doubled to $19 a barrel, the
measures BP Amoco announced Thursday were aimed partly at preparing
the company for any new shocks. Browne told analysts that the cost
reductions were designed to make BP Amoco ``robust at $11 a
barrel.''
</P>
<P>
   He also said the planned savings by the end of 2001 would take
effect before any other cost-saving from the pending acquisition of
Atlantic Richfield.
</P>
<P>
   The BP Amoco news pushed up its shares by 2.6 percent to 1,292
pence in London, or about $20, valuing the company at more than
$195 billion and adding 11 points to the blue-chip FTSE 100 index,
where it has the biggest weighting.
</P>
<P>
   At the time of the BP Amoco merger, Browne forecast annual cost
savings of $2 billion by the end of 2000, but said Thursday those
savings would be achieved more than one year ahead of schedule.
</P>
<P>
   Browne said the $10 billion in planned disposals included $4
billion from exploration and production, $3 billion from sales of
refineries and $2.5 billion in chemicals, where the company intends
to abandon low-growth activities and focus on fast-growing markets
in China, Korea and Malaysia.
</P>
<P>
   Specifically, Brown said, BP Amoco will move ahead with shedding
its Canadian oil interests, which are already on the market, and
its 64 percent stake in Altura Energy, an oil and gas producer in
Texas and New Mexico. But the biggest cuts are in refining.
</P>
<P>
   ``With worldwide refining capacity continuing to grow faster
than demand, our expectation is that the global refining margin
will average little more than $1 a barrel over the medium term,''
Browne said. ``Our aim, therefore, is to reduce our refining
coverage by around a third.''
</P>
<P>
   The reduction would drop BP Amoco's ranking among the world's
oil refiners from fourth place to eighth, according to figures from
Arthur Andersen consultants. The size of the cuts in refining was
the most surprising element in the cost-savings plan.
</P>
<P>
   The steep cutbacks also come at time when refining capacity in
the United States has become tight and has helped oil companies
strengthen their earnings. Frederick P. Leuffer, an oil analyst for
Bear Stearns, said that selling major assets like refineries would
allow competitors to pick up assets for low prices.
</P>
<P>
   Browne appeared to be unfazed by such concerns.
</P>
<P>
   ``We only wish to be involved in the refining business when we
cannot buy the supplies we need for our own marketing network at
reasonable prices,'' Browne said. ``We now have more refining
capacity than we need.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
