<HEADLINE>
CLINTON TELLS COLORADO YOUTHS HE'LL STAND FAST ON GUN CONTROL
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Colo., Mo.)   (jw) 
 By KATHARINE Q. SEELYE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ President Clinton said Thursday that he would veto
the juvenile justice bill if it emerged from Congress with
provisions that weakened existing gun controls.
</P>
<P>
   ``I will not in any way, shape or form countenance a weakening
of the law,'' Clinton declared at the White House, standing in
front of 90 students from Colorado _ six of them from Columbine
High School in Littleton _ who are in Washington to lobby Congress
for gun controls that the Senate version of the bill would add.
</P>
<P>
   The president noted that the Senate legislation also included a
weakening provision, eliminating background checks on people who
retrieve their guns from pawnshops. Even as he issued his veto
threat, though, Clinton said that he was not fully aware of what
else was in the bill and that ``the attorney general has to give me
a briefing on it before I can make a final decision.''
</P>
<P>
   The president spoke after meeting privately with the students at
the White House. The students, organized by a gun-control group
that was formed in Colorado after the killings at Columbine in
April, have proved to be an unusual lobbying force.
</P>
<P>
   Most lobbyists come to Washington begging for a moment with
lawmakers, which both sides generally like to keep private. In this
case, these students have been sought out by politicians. Vice
President Al Gore went to the Capitol Thursday afternoon where he
and Rep. Dick Gephardt, D-Mo., his party's leader, posed with them
after the president met with them at the White House.
</P>
<P>
   The students also met with the six-member Colorado delegation in
the House, the state's two senators and more than two dozen other
lawmakers they had identified as possible swing votes on gun
control.
</P>
<P>
   Some students acknowledged that they were being used as
political props but said that they were also accomplishing their
goals.
</P>
<P>
   ``When they get a group of kids who are as impassioned as we
are, it generates media,'' said Jared O'Brien, a 17-year-old from
Denver.
</P>
<P>
   Jody Gold, 28, an Internet consultant and one of the chaperones
of the group, said that the students discussed with Clinton how to
keep Congress focused on gun control now that Columbine has faded
from the news. He said the president's advice to the students was
to expand their numbers in Colorado, create similar groups in other
states and return next year.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was teaching,'' Gold said. ``He was explaining that
legislation is like turning an aircraft carrier, slow, saying we
need to be persistent and ask for the right kind of reforms.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite pessimism about the bill, Clinton said it was not too
late for Congress to heed the students' message. ``Don't forget
Littleton,'' Clinton urged Congress. ``Don't allow the victims of
Columbine to have died in vain. Don't forget the 13 children who
die every day from gun violence. Many, many, many of them can be
saved. We must not lose the urgency of our mission.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
