<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-GUNS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COLORADO STUDENTS IN CAPITOL URGE TIGHTER GUN CONTROL 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By BENNETT ROTH 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ President Clinton and Congressional Democrats got
some help Thursday in their push for stricter gun control as
Colorado students, including several from Columbine High School,
descended on the Capitol to lobby lawmakers.
</P>
<P>
   After meeting with the student group at the White House, Clinton
said lawmakers should put aside partisan differences and pass
legislation that would, among other things, force background checks
on those who purchase firearms at gun shows.
</P>
<P>
   ``For the past three months the gun lobby has been calling the
shots on Capitol Hill, now it's time for Congress to listen to the
lobbyists who truly matter _ our children, the people who will be
most affected by what is or is not done by Congress,'' Clinton said
after meeting with the Denver-area student group.
</P>
<P>
   The latest push for gun control was prompted by the massacre
April 20 at Columbine High School outside Denver, which resulted in
the deaths of 15 people, including a teacher and the two gunmen.
</P>
<P>
   But last month the House defeated gun legislation approved by
the Senate because of opposition by most Republicans and some
Democrats to a provision giving authorities three days to conduct
the background check. Republicans want to give authorities one day
to conduct the check.
</P>
<P>
   House Republican leaders said they expect some gun-control
measures, such as safety locks on guns, to emerge from compromise
legislation that will eventually be hammered out by the House and
Senate.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton said he would reject any legislation that weakens
current laws but would not say how he would react to compromise
legislation that may emerge.
</P>
<P>
   The 90 Colorado students, who visited with Democratic House
leaders and with lawmakers of both parties, said Congress needs to
stop dawdling.
</P>
<P>
   ``The leaders are not leading, and the representatives are not
representing,'' said David Winkler, a leader of the student group
called Colorado SAFE (Sane Alternatives to Firearms Epidemic).
</P>
<P>
   The students met later with House Minority Leader Richard
Gephardt, D-Mo., and Vice President Al Gore and urged them to use
their bully pulpit to ensure the passage of stricter gun laws.
</P>
<P>
   Gore noted that he has spoken out frequently about the need for
gun control and took an indirect swipe at GOP presidential
contender Texas Gov. George W. Bush.
</P>
<P>
   ``I agree that anyone in a position of leadership who has a
chance to change the way people think about an issue like this has
an obligation to do so,'' Gore said. ``And if you have that chance
you need to do that for the right purposes and not the wrong
purposes. We don't need new protections for the gun industry. We
need new protections for families. We don't need more concealed
weapons, we need more gun safety laws and strict access to those
weapons.''
</P>
<P>
   As governor, Bush signed laws allowing concealed handguns and
prohibiting municipal suits against gun manufacturers.
</P>
<P>
   The students did not meet with the key Republican leaders who
control the agenda in the House, including Speaker Dennis Hastert,
R-Ill., and House Majority Whip Tom DeLay, R-Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Hastert spokesman John Feehery said that no one asked his boss
for a meeting. Feehery said he expected that a compromise gun
measure would be part of legislation fashioned by House and Senate
negotiators. However, Hastert has yet to appoint House members to
the committee that must iron out differences with the Senate.
</P>
<P>
   In a written statement, Hastert blamed Democrats for the lack of
any gun legislation.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is appropriate that these students are meeting with the
minority leader (Gephardt). Hopefully they can convince him to put
aside the partisanship and work with us to pass good legislation,''
Hastert said.
</P>
<P>
   The students, six of them from Columbine, were not afraid to
confront lawmakers who did not share their views on guns.
</P>
<P>
   During a meeting with Colorado Republican Rep. Scott McInnis,
several disputed his contentions that it was important to protect
Second Amendment rights and that guns were needed for protection.
</P>
<P>
   One student told the congressman, ``if there weren't violent
people with guns you wouldn't have to protect yourself.''
</P>
<P>
   Daniel Kurtz-Phelan said the session ``turned a bit
confrontational.''
</P>
<P>
   ``He came into the speech intending to blow us off,'' said
Kurtz-Phelan, 18, who just graduated from George Washington High
School in Denver.
</P>
<P>
   Kurtz-Phelan said this lobbying experience has ``been a sobering
experience.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's hard not to see the influence of special interest groups,
especially money,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
