<HEADER>
A1929 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MA-LOTTERY-AUDIT-BOS &LR;      07-15 1139
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MA-LOTTERY-AUDIT-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LOTTERY VICTIMIZED BY SCAM ARTISTS, AUDITOR SAYS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BRIAN MACQUARRIE  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON -- Scam artists, cashing in on the state Lottery's lack
of financial controls, appear to have collected millions of dollars
in fraudulent winnings, according to a scathing report released
Thursday by state Auditor A. Joseph DeNucci.
</P>
<P>
   The audit portrayed a carelessly managed system in which many
scratch tickets were cashed by people using fake identification.
Lottery staffers often did not ask winners for identification _ as
required _ and did not pursue suspicions about winners who cashed
tickets dozens of times in a year, auditors said.
</P>
<P>
   In one case, 319 winning tickets worth $412,000 were cashed in a
year, all by a person, or people, using the name Clarence Jones.
</P>
<P>
   The top 10 most frequent winners cashed in 842 times for a total
of $1.8 million in 1998, DeNucci said. Five of those winners were
found to have used fraudulent names.
</P>
<P>
   Auditors suspect that professional ticket cashers, using the
bogus names, were cashing tickets for others so the real winners
could avoid paying taxes or other obligations like child support.
The ticket cashers would then receive a cut of the winnings,
usually 10 or 15 percent.
</P>
<P>
   DeNucci said the audit provides ``very, very strong''
indications that scam artists were aided by Lottery employees and
referred the report to Attorney General Thomas F. Reilly, for
possible criminal prosecution.
</P>
<P>
   . ``There is a strong possibility that there is some collusion
involved here, a strong possibility that there is an inside gimmick
going on,'' DeNucci said.
</P>
<P>
   The findings have been passed to Treasurer Shannon P. O'Brien,
who has trying to impose new, strict controls at the Lottery, which
generates $3.2 billion in annual revenue - two-thirds of it from
scratch tickets.
</P>
<P>
   ``We will not tolerate fraud. We will not tolerate abuse,'' said
O'Brien, who noted that operations in the state Lottery's regional
offices have been under scrutiny since she took office in January.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to suspicious multiple winners, DeNucci said the
audit found that:
</P>
<P>
   -- $7 million in withholding taxes from Lottery winnings is due
the state from 1,800 people who gave the Lottery ``undeliverable''
addresses when cashing in tickets.
</P>
<P>
   -- $2.2 million in 1998 winnings went to people with suspicious
identification, including fake names, Social Security numbers and
addresses. Some of the names included ``Chris Mis,'' ``Joe
Bellone,'' Dave Mograss,'' ``Nu Bank,'' and ``Kris Kristofferson,''
yet Lottery workers apparently never reported anything amiss.
</P>
<P>
   -- $15 million is owed the state by Lottery sales agents.
</P>
<P>
   -- Dozens of sales agents, owing millions of dollars, are
estimated to have moved to unknown addresses.
</P>
<P>
   -- Internal records for 29,000 winning Instant Game tickets
worth more than $600 each are incomplete, raising the possibility
of theft or abuse.
</P>
<P>
   -- Unsecured bundles of active scratch tickets were left
unattended in locations easily accessible to employees at Lottery
headquarters in Braintree.
</P>
<P>
   The audit, awaited since March and covering 1998, further dents
the already damaged reputation of former Treasurer Joseph D.
Malone.
</P>
<P>
   Early this year, two Treasury managers were accused in the theft
of $8.9 million from the Unpaid Check Fund during Malone's tenure.
In addition, O'Brien last month fired a staffer in the Boston
Lottery office who allegedly stole $24,000 in scratch tickets. Two
employees are serving suspensions in that incident.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is an attitude problem in an entrenched bureaucracy,''
Deputy Auditor Robert Powilatis said. ``This is going to take a
long time to fix. It's like turning around the Queen Mary in the
Charles River.''
</P>
<P>
   DeNucci, a Democrat, blamed the administration of Malone, a
Republican, for the problems. Malone, who served from 1991 until
this year, oversaw a complacent office that ignored directives to
improve management, DeNucci said.
</P>
<P>
   Malone could not be reached Thursday night.
</P>
<P>
   DeNucci said that Lottery staffers at offices that cash scratch
tickets must use a consistent, rigorous method of verifying the
identities of winners. Lottery staffers are required to ask for a
photo ID that shows a Social Security number. Although Lottery
managers were aware of the requirement, auditors said, employees in
the field appeared ignorant of it.
</P>
<P>
   In some cases, said auditor spokesman Glenn Briere, winners were
not asked for any identification.
</P>
<P>
   The question of employee collusion must be investigated by
another agency, DeNucci said. In the most suspicious example, that
of 319-time winner Clarance Jones, the bulk of his tickets were
cashed at a Woburn office where only three employees regularly
handle claims.
</P>
<P>
   In the case of Clarence Jones of Lynn, auditors said, the name
could have been used by as many as 20 different people who cashed
tickets in the Woburn office. Briere said that Jones' name was
traced to a post office box in Lynn, had a matching Social Security
number, and had even been used to apply for credit. Any criminal
investigation, which would determine if such a person exists, would
be handled by the attorney general's office, they said.
</P>
<P>
   State auditors, who said they conducted the review with computer
technology installed in 1997, focused the study on scratch tickets
that paid between $600 and $5,000. In this range, tickets can be
cashed at one of the regional Lottery offices, and taxes do not
have to be deducted at the time.
</P>
<P>
   For winnings above $5,000, taxes are deducted from the tickets
before they are cashed at Lottery headquarters.
</P>
<P>
   DeNucci also blasted collection procedures at the Lottery, which
he said allows sales agents at stores throughout the state to
withhold payment for months at a time. When Lottery officials
visited one store in Taunton, they discovered no inventory for
$234,000 in scratch tickets and ordered him to repay the amount in
two days to retain his license.
</P>
<P>
   Powilatis said that the loss of millions of dollars in taxes
should be a major impetus for streamlining the agency. ``You need
to reengineer their minds to do their jobs,'' Powilatis said of
Lottery employees.
</P>
<P>
   DeNucci said that lax controls at Lottery sales offices became
apparent two years ago after his office was notified of a $597
theft at Braintree headquarters, where residents can buy tickets.
Further review has shown that $129,344 is unaccounted for in
Braintree, DeNucci said.
</P>
<P>
   O'Brien has also commissioned an independent audit of the
Lottery by the KPMG Peat Marwick accounting firm. The results of
that study have not been received, but preliminary findings led to
the discovery of the $24,000 in stolen scratch tickets.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
