<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-15 21:36 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1930 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RAC-MODESTI-COLUMN-LA     07-15 1121
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RAC-MODESTI-COLUMN-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MOSTLY A RELIEF
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KEVIN MODESTI  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   INGLEWOOD, Calif. _ The way R.D. Hubbard tells it now, he had no
intention of becoming the boss of Hollywood Park when he bought
stock in the track in 1990.
</P>
<P>
   He didn't plan to become the most influential figure in
California racing _ perhaps in all of American racing _ in the
tumultuous decade.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not a job I went after,'' Hubbard said Thursday on the
phone from a golf course in Park City, Utah. ``It just escalated.''
</P>
<P>
   That's one reason, Hubbard said, that his overwhelming emotion
is not sadness but relief as his 8{ years as Hollywood Park's
chairman and CEO end with the close of the track's spring-summer
meet on Monday. The 61-year-old facility will be operated by
Churchill Downs after the $140 million purchase announced in May
becomes final in August or September.
</P>
<P>
   ``The first couple of years were a lot of fun,'' said Hubbard,
64, the Kansas-born glass manufacturer who led the takeover of
Hollywood Park from Marjorie Everett in February 1991. ``But the
last few were frustrating. I came in thinking there were lots of
changes we could make, and then we ran up against (opposition). It
seemed like one thing would work, and something else we'd get a lot
of criticism for.''
</P>
<P>
   Swaggering, fun-loving and imaginative, Hubbard and his staff
did make lots of changes at the run-down track he believes was
heading out of business. They spruced up every corner of the 380
acres, beat back horsemen's protest to build the nation's first
trackside casino, breathed life into Friday-night racing and made
the Autumn Turf Festival a reason to attend the November-December
meet.
</P>
<P>
   Attendance went up 11 percent in 1991 _ before suffering the
same slide as the rest of the racing industry. Company earnings
tripled in '92.
</P>
<P>
   When Hollywood Park hosted the best-run Breeders' Cup in 1997,
it showed the world ``The Track of Lakes and Flowers'' was back in
bloom.
</P>
<P>
   Hubbard's experimentation also produced forgettable failures
like the EZQ, the short-lived wager that required fans to merely
pick two of the top three finishers in a race, and unfulfilled
plans for a football stadium, music arena and police station on
track property.
</P>
<P>
   Other near-misses frustrated Hubbard.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think there was a lot more we could have done (with tracks)
working together,'' he said. ``Every time there's legislation that
would be good for racing overall, the greed factor kicked in.''
</P>
<P>
   Hubbard worries about the rapid changes at Santa Anita under
chairman Frank Stronach.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think they're going to be facing a lot of tough times and
criticism,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   He worries about the potential for fights over racing dates as
Stronach battles Churchill Downs management in California and
Florida.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would hope cooler heads prevail,'' Hubbard said.
</P>
<P>
   He'd like to see changes in the California-breds incentive
program. He's optimistic about the sport's future, though.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel that as we go into the 21st century, there are more
positive things going on for racing than there have been in 25
years,'' including the consolidation of track ownership and the
spread of home wagering through telephone and online accounts,
Hubbard said.
</P>
<P>
   He thinks that if California permitted slot machines at
racetracks, as many states do, ``purse money could easily be
doubled or tripled.''
</P>
<P>
   Hubbard isn't getting out of racing. He controls Turf Paradise
in Phoenix and Ruidoso (N.M.) Downs. And he owns more than 400 head
of racing and breeding stock after buying into 200 horses earlier
this month with Rio Claro Thoroughbreds, the South American outfit
best known for 1996 Hollywood Gold Cup winner Siphon.
</P>
<P>
   So Hubbard will remain visible at Hollywood Park. Only he'll be
seen in the saddling paddock and not the executive wing.
</P>
<P>
   ``Overall,'' Hubbard said, ``I think it's been a good ride.''
</P>
<P>
   __ The weekend: General Challenge will try to become the fifth
favorite in a row to win the Swaps Stakes for 3-year-olds on
Sunday, the second-to-last day of the Hollywood Park season.
</P>
<P>
   The Cal-bred lowered his odds Tuesday by working 6 furlongs in
1:09 4/5 at Santa Anita _ 2 3/5 seconds faster than the morning's
next-best drills at the distance.
</P>
<P>
   ``For any other horse, I would say it was too fast, but not for
him,'' trainer Bob Baffert said of the Santa Anita Derby winner.
``He does things I've never had any other horse do.''
</P>
<P>
   General Challenge (a troubled 11th in the Kentucky Derby) will
be ridden by David Flores in the 1[-mile Swaps when he faces Cat
Thief (third) and Pat Day, Desert Hero (13th) and Jerry Bailey, and
Walk That Walk and a jockey to be announced.
</P>
<P>
   __ Other highlights of closing weekend: Saturday's Hollywood
Oaks for 3-year-old fillies (including Excellent Meeting), and
``Super Sunday's'' Sunset Handicap on turf (River Bay, Lazy Lode)
and Hollywood Juvenile Championship for 2-year-olds (D. Wayne
Lukas-trained Exchange Rate, Richard Mandella-trained Dixie Union).
</P>
<P>
   Del Mar opens Thursday for 42 days.
</P>
<P>
   __ Turf war: Hollywood Park has affirmed its commitment to TVG,
the interactive racing network, by terminating its agreement with
Youbet.com, the online wagering service. Youbet took its last
Hollywood bets last Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Hubbard said the $21,000 wagered daily through Youbet was
``extremely disappointing'' and said TVG ``offers a far superior
platform for our product.''
</P>
<P>
   But Youbet executive vice president and CEO Ron Luniewski noted
that the $1.1 million wagered on Hollywood races this season would
rank in the top 40 percent of the track's simulcast outlets.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were surprised,'' Luniewski said of Hollywood's
announcement. ``In the last five years, nobody has canceled a
simulcast contract through a press release.''
</P>
<P>
   Youbet began its marketing effort in January and claims 6,000
subscribers. TVG was launched Thursday and is available to C-band
satellite customers on GEI, transponder 23.
</P>
<P>
   __ Building suspense: Plans to add an entertainment arena and
dining complex to Santa Anita's Paddock Gardens following the
1999-2000 season will be revealed this morning in Arcadia.
</P>
<P>
   Work is underway on phase one of Stronach's changes, putting a
575-seat restaurant, 215-foot bar and dance floor in the clubhouse;
adding terraces to the track apron; enlarging the winner's circle
and installing a huge TV screen in the infield.
</P>
<P>
   Stronach calmed traditionalists in April when he said the
paddock and walking ring won't be moved, and the unique hillside
turf course will remain.
</P>
<P>
   New Santa Anita general manager Lonnie Powell took office on
Thursday.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
