<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-15 21:40 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1936 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BIZGLANCE-NYT     07-15 0587
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIZGLANCE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSINESS AT A GLANCE
</HEADLINE>
 (af) 
c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   TINY COMPUTER COMPONENTS PROMISE BIG STEPS IN SPEED
</P>
<P>
   Researchers from Hewlett Packard and the University of
California at Los Angeles have fashioned simple computing
components no thicker than a single molecule that they say could be
a step toward computers 100 billion times faster than today's most
powerful personal computers.
</P>
<P>
   And they envision a world in which supercomputing power is so
pervasive and cheap that it literally becomes an integral part of
every manmade object.
</P>
<P>
   NO INDICATION OF INFLATION IN JUNE
</P>
<P>
   The Consumer Price Index _ which measures changes in the price
of everything that American households buy, from candy bars to
health care _ remained unchanged in June for the second
consecutive, indicating no inflation, the Labor Department
reported.
</P>
<P>
   COKE POSTS 21 PERCENT DECREASE IN PROFIT
</P>
<P>
   Coca-Cola's second-quarter profit fell 21 percent, in part
because it had to pull millions of soft drinks off the market in
Europe last month. Worldwide sales volume, measured in cases of
finished drinks, fell 2 percent, compared with a 10 percent
increase in the period a year earlier. The volume and earnings were
about what Wall Street had expected, and Coke shares rose $2.125,
to $64.
</P>
<P>
   NASDAQ AND S&AMP;P SET RECORDS
</P>
<P>
   Stocks rose in response to news the consumer price index showed
no inflation and to strong corporate earnings. The Dow Jones
industrial average rose 38.31 points, to 11,186.41. The NASDAQ
composite index rose 21.24 points, to a record 2,839.37. The
Standard &AMP; Poor's 500-stock index also set a new high, rising 11.45
points, to 1,409.62.
</P>
<P>
   Bond investors quickly bought up a $1.6 billion Southern
California tax-exempt issue, and Nassau County, N.Y., offered $138
million in bonds. The yield of the 30-year Treasury remained at
5.91 percent.
</P>
<P>
   BP AMOCO PLANS $4 BILLION IN CUTS
</P>
<P>
   BP Amoco, the newly formed petroleum giant, surprised analysts
with ambitious plans to cut annual costs by $4 billion in the next
three years _ double the previous target _ and shed $10 billion of
assets.
</P>
<P>
   BOEING EARNINGS BEAT EXPECTATIONS
</P>
<P>
   Boeing delivered stronger-than-expected earnings for the second
consecutive quarter and raised its estimates of future profits,
giving its beleaguered investors new hope after two years of
disappointments.
</P>
<P>
   FOR ARDEN, A NEW CAMPAIGN
</P>
<P>
   Responding to a consumer study that found disparaging attitudes
toward the beauty industry, the Elizabeth Arden Co. is seeking to
redefine its image in an unconventional campaign from J. Walter
Thompson. One aspect is unretouched black and white photographs
showing women of various ages and ethnic groups, with headlines
like ``I am the leader of my own free world.'' Advertising.
</P>
<P>
   DRUG EXECUTIVES CRITICIZE PROPOSAL
</P>
<P>
   Top pharmaceutical executives said they shared President
Clinton's goal of increasing Medicare beneficiaries' access to
prescription drugs, but for the first time criticized specific
features of his proposal.
</P>
<P>
   INDEX FUNDS ARE LOSING FAVOR
</P>
<P>
   Although investors have increasingly favored mutual funds that
track stock market indexes, the performance of competing funds has
improved, and investors have begun throttling back on index funds.
Market Place.
</P>
<P>
   TOUGHER POLICY HINTED IN EUROPE
</P>
<P>
   The head of the European Central Bank, Wim Duisenberg, signaled
that it might soon toughen monetary policy.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
