<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-UPR-CHAIRMAN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UPR CHAIRMAN ANNOUNCES RETIREMENT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service Clients) 
By DAN PILLER 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ Jack Messman, who oversaw an aggressive
expansion at Union Pacific Resources Group, took the energy company
public, and led its unsuccessful bid to acquire Pennzoil, announced
his retirement on Thursday from the oil and gas exploration
company.
</P>
<P>
   Messman, 59, said he will become the chief executive of a
high-tech company in the northeastern United States, but he gave no
other details. Messman has a history in technology; he was
co-founder of Novell _ the Utah software company _ in the early
1980s.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the time for me, and the opportunity came out of
nowhere,'' Messman said just hours after UPR's directors had
accepted his resignation.
</P>
<P>
   Messman's departure comes as the company's fortunes have turned,
thanks to a recent rise in the price of crude oil. During his eight
years at the helm, revenues nearly doubled to $1.8 billion, making
it one of Tarrant County's 10 largest companies. UPR stumbled last
year, losing nearly $900 million due to a big writedown of assets
as oil prices dropped.
</P>
<P>
   But as prices recovered, UPR rebounded, posting a first-quarter
profit this year of $42.3 million from continuing operations.
</P>
<P>
   ``Things are going pretty well for UPR, and this is a rather
surprising time for someone to leave,'' said analyst Kevin Boone of
the Bear, Stearns investment firm in New York.
</P>
<P>
   UPR immediately named UPR President George Lindahl III to
succeed Messman as chairman and chief executive. Lindahl, who also
will retain the president's title, has been with UPR since 1987.
</P>
<P>
   The change came as a surprise to the energy and investment
communities, even to Messman himself.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just moved into a new house last month, and now we'll move
again,'' Messman said of the Fort Worth home he shares with his
wife, Maggie.
</P>
<P>
   The stock market took the news calmly. UPR stock closed on the
New York Stock Exchange up 62 cents, at $16.06.
</P>
<P>
   ``There hadn't been any indication or advance warning that Jack
was about to make a change, but the appointment of George Lindahl
looks like a pretty normal progression,'' said analyst David
Garcia, of the Everen Securities investment firm in Houston.
</P>
<P>
   Messman is not a lifetime oilman. He came to UPR in 1991,
succeeding Bill Adams, from USPCI, the hazardous waste subsidiary
of Union Pacific Corp. UP at the time owned Union Pacific
Resources.
</P>
<P>
   Messman is a native of West Virginia, and was educated at the
University of Delaware and Harvard University's business school. He
was trained as a chemical engineer and has worked for Union
Carbide, the Somerset House publishing company, and Warner Amex
Cable in New York.
</P>
<P>
   At UPR, Messman pursued what he referred to as ``manufacturing
approach'' to energy, which essentially meant laying numerous wells
over formations for fast, voluminous extractions.
</P>
<P>
   The aggressive strategy, particularly in the Austin Chalk
formation of South Texas where UPR pioneered the use of horizontal
drilling, increased UPR's production by an average of 17 percent
annually during Messman's years and made the company the largest
independent driller in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   In 1995, Messman oversaw the separation of UPR from parent Union
Pacific corp., owner of the railroad of the same name, into an
independent company.
</P>
<P>
   With the company now under his own control in 1996, Messman set
about to reshape the corporation's culture.
</P>
<P>
   In 1998, the company moved from its headquarters to another
downtown Fort Worth location, and shifted from a traditional,
mahogany wall environment to an open, workstation arrangement.
</P>
<P>
   By then Messman already had adopted Friday casual dresscodes for
the 1,200 workers (a number reduced by about 400 when falling
energy prices forced a layoff late last year). Messman now allowed
casual dress each day of the week and jeans on Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Messman also began new performance review systems, where
employees were rated not only by their superiors, but also by their
peers and by those under them.
</P>
<P>
   He also worked to impart more of a marketing approach to a
company whose industry long has been commodity-based.
</P>
<P>
   ``I tried to persuade people that we do have customers, instead
of just commodity users,'' Messman said.
</P>
<P>
   In part because of those efforts, UPR was named one of
``America's Best Companies to Work For'' by Fortune magazine in
1998. It also received a commendation from Working Mother magazine
for his programs for women employees.
</P>
<P>
   Union Pacific Resources was a steady profit earner through
Messman's era until the price of crude oil plunged beginning late
in 1997 through earlier this year.
</P>
<P>
   ``It frustrated me that the price of my company's product was
set by three or four people in the Middle East,'' Messman said of
OPEC, the oil producers' cartel that still exerts the largest
single influence over worldwide oil prices.
</P>
<P>
   From the beginning of his time at UPR, Messman was put on notice
by Wall Street of the need to expand the company's resources beyond
its traditonal base in Wyoming and Colorado and Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Messman tried to buy Pennzoil of Houston in 1997, but his
unfriendly takeover bid of $84 per share was rejected. UPR then
paid $3.5 billion for Norcen Energy Co. of Calgary, Canada. The
purchase almost doubled UPR's resources base and made it a major
player in Canada, the offshore Gulf of Mexico, Guatemala and
Venezuela.
</P>
<P>
   But it also laid heavy debt upon UPR at a time when revenues
began to erode because of the falling prices. For the last year,
UPR has had to spend more than $2 billion of its cash flow to pare
down debt.
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
