<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-BARAK-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: BARAK COMES TO WASHINGTON 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times says in an editorial Friday, July 16: &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Ehud Barak winds up his first diplomatic tour as Israel's prime
minister with a long weekend of meetings with President Clinton
that began Thursday. The mood in Washington is upbeat and
encouraging, as it was during Barak's earlier meetings with Arab
leaders. Clinton welcomes Barak's aspiration to complete peace
agreements with the Palestinians and Syria. The two men will also
explore how America can help.
</P>
<P>
   Barak would prefer less direct U.S. participation in negotiating
and carrying out peace agreements. He wants Washington to return to
its former, less intrusive role while Israelis and Arabs find their
own way to peace. That is fine. America's involvement increased
under Barak's predecessor, Benjamin Netanyahu, when a long and
dangerous stalemate imperiled carrying out the Oslo peace
agreements. With Israelis and Palestinians unable to work out their
problems and unwilling to trust each other's promises, both needed
American help.
</P>
<P>
   At last year's Wye River meeting, the White House helped devise
the formula for Israeli troop withdrawals from a further 13 percent
of the West Bank in exchange for Palestinian security guarantees.
The CIA also agreed to monitor Palestinian performance against
terrorism, including the handling of terrorist suspects by
Palestinian courts and prisons. Barak now wants the CIA to reduce
this monitoring role. That, too, is reasonable, though Israelis and
Palestinians should put new mechanisms in place to assure that this
chronically troublesome issue does not lead to renewed crises.
</P>
<P>
   Barak would also like to skip some withdrawals agreed to at Wye
and move directly to talks on a final settlement. Yasser Arafat is
reluctant to enter those talks with less than the 40 percent of the
West Bank the Palestinians would get under Wye. Barak, for his
part, hopes to avoid clashes with Jewish settlers over the Wye
pullbacks that could brake the current momentum toward peace. Both
arguments have merit. It would be best to carry out the withdrawals
unless Arafat agrees to bypass them. Debating how to move ahead is
a welcome change from trading blame for delaying peace. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
