<P>
   ATTENTION EDITORS: The following photos are part of tonight's
New York Times Photo Package, moving Thursday, 07/15/99. Photo
clients will automatically receive these photos via AP's
PhotoExpress or may download them from either the Wieck Photo
Database in Dallas at 972-392-0888 or from NYTPhotos on Newscom at
305-448-8411. Non-clients can make individual purchases by calling
(888) 603-1036 or 212-556-4204.
</P>
<P>
   (NYT34) WASHINGTON -- July 15, 1999 -- HEALTH-CARE-4, 07-15 --
Sen. Edward Kennedy addresses a group outside the U.S. Capitol
about the need to pass a Democratic form of the Patients Bill of
Rights on Thursday as healthcare activist Justin Dart looks on at
left. Turning to one of the most contentious issues in the weeklong
debate over health maintenance organizations, the Senate on
Thursday killed a Democratic provision that would have enabled
patients to sue their health plans. (Shana Raab/New York Times
Photo) LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT33) EAST RUTHERFORD, N.J. -- July 15, 1999 --
SPRINGSTEEN-CONCERT, 07-15 -- Bruce Springsteen fans from left,
Mary Decicoccio, Marilyn Kirby and Gina Garflied in the parking lot
of Continental Airlines Arena on Thursday. The women were partying
before entering the arena for Bruce Springsteen's concert Thursday
night. (Keith Meyers/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT32) WASHINGTON -- July 15, 1999 -- ISRAEL-U.S.-4, 07-15 --
President Clinton, his wife Hillary Rodham Clinton, Israeli Prime
Minister Ehud Barak and his wife Nava Barak board Marine One for a
filght to Camp David on Thursday. Buoyed almost to the point of
ebullience by the prospect of fresh momentum, Barak, Clinton and
his foreign policy advisers hope that his visit will be the opening
chapter of a comprehensive Middle East peace settlement that will
culminate near the end of Clinton's term. (Paul Hosefros/New York
Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT31) NEW YORK -- July 15, 1999 -- TIGER-THEATER-REVIEW, 07-15
-- Silas Weir Mitchell and Shae D'lyn in ``Tiger Tail,'' Tennessee
Williams' stage reduction of ``Baby Doll.'' It is unlikely that
Williams ever thought of ``Tiger Tail'' as a viable theatrical
work, and the production mounted at the Harold Clurman Theater
suggests it isn't. (Nicole Bengiveno/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT30) ATLANTA -- July 15, 1999 -- AFFIRMATIVE-ACTION, 07-15 --
Atlanta Mayor Bill Campbell, left at microphone, addresses a crowd
at City Hall on Thursday on affirmative action. Hundreds of black
Atlantans let loose their ``amens'' at the rally called by Campbell
in defiance of the threat of a lawsuit to end the city's
affirmative action program. (Alan S. Weiner/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT29) WASHINGTON -- July 15, 1999 -- ISRAEL-U.S.-3, 07-15 --
President Clinton and his wife Hillary Rodham Clinton accompany
Israeli Prime Minister Ehud Barak and his wife Nava Barak towards
Marine One for a filght to Camp David on Thursday. Buoyed almost to
the point of ebullience by the prospect of fresh momentum, Barak,
Clinton and his foreign policy advisers hope that his visit will be
the opening chapter of a comprehensive Middle East peace settlement
that will culminate near the end of Clinton's term. (Paul
Hosefros/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT28) NEW YORK -- July 15, 1999 -- WHITNEY-MUSIC-REVIEW, 07-15
-- Whitney Houston at the Theater at Madison Square Garden on
Wednesday. For a contemporary rhythm-and-blues show, where backup
tapes and the faithful replication of studio singles are usually de
rigueur, Ms. Houston's two-hour performance here was remarkably
unscripted. (Billy Smith II/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT27) LITHONIA, Ga. -- July 15, 1999 -- LAWN-FETISH16-2-COX,
07-15 -- Westley Levy closely examines his lawn for any weed that
might be trying to hide there. Every seven days, the retired
carpenter spends about five hours mowing, edging and mulching his
Bermuda grass. ``He also sits on a bench and pulls the roots of
weeds up, one by one, using (the claw of) a hammer,'' his wife,
Carmen, says. (William Berry/Atlanta Journal-Constitution Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT26) ALPHARETTA, Ga. -- July 15, 1999 -- LAWN-FETISH16-1-COX,
07-15 -- Pat Apps examining some blades of grass at his Alpharetta
home Thursday morning. ``It takes a lot of work, but I like the
exercise and getting outside, especially in the evenings,'' says
Apps, a product engineer. ``I try to mow and edge mine every five
days, but that's hard to do.'' (William Berry/Atlanta
Journal-Constitution Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT25) WASHINGTON -- July 15, 1999 -- HOUSE-RELIGION, 07-15--
Rep. Charles Canady, R-Fla., the main sponsor of the Religious
Liberty Protection Act, in his office on Capitol Hill, Wednesday.
Divided mainly along party lines, the House debated at length on
Thursday as to whether religious liberty or civil rights should
take precedence when the two principles come into conflict.
Religion, which the Republicans favored, came out on top.(Justin
Lane/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT24) WASHINGTON -- July 15, 1999 -- HEALTH-CARE-3, 07-15 --
Vice President Al Gore, left, talks to reporters about healthcare
legislation before the Senate as Senate Minority Leader Tom
Daschle, D-S.D., right, and Sen. Edward Kennedy, D-Mass., look on,
Thursday on Capitol Hill. Turning to one of the most contentious
issues in the weeklong debate over health maintenance
organizations, the Senate on Thursday killed a Democratic provision
that would have enabled patients to sue their health plans. (Shana
Raab/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT23) WASHINGTON -- July 15, 1999 -- HEALTH-CARE-2, 07-15 --
Sen. John Chafee, R-R.I., is joined by colleagues, from left, Sens.
Bob Gramm, D-Fla., Chuck Robb, R-Virg., Max Baucus, D-Mont., Arlen
Spector, R-Pa., Joe Lieberman, D-Conn., and Blanche Lincoln,
D-Ariz., during a news conference, Thursday on Capitol Hill. The
legislators were offering an alternative to both the Democratic and
Republican versions of Patients Bill of Rights. (Shana Raab/New
York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT22) BROOKLINE, Mass. -- July 15, 1999 -- WOMEN-MARRIAGE-BOS,
07-15 -- Bride-to-be Patty Hudson gets help from Yulia Eydinov at
La Reine in Brookline. According to a report, ``The State of Our
Unions,'' issued this month by Rutgers University's National
Marriage Project, 70 percent of graduating high school girls said
it was possible to have a full life without marriage, compared with
61 percent in 1980. (Wendy Maeda/Boston Globe Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT21) WESTON, Mass. -- July 15, 1999 -- AUTHOR-CHAPLIN-BOS,
07-15 -- Gordon Chaplin, author of ``Dark Wind: A Survivor's Tale
of Love and Loss,'' detailing a sailing accident that resulted in
the death of his partner, Susan Atkinson. Chaplin and Atkinson
elected to ride out a typhoon in a Marshall Island lagoon aboard
their 36-foot sailboat, but the boat was ultimately driven aground
and splintered by the pounding surf. ``I felt a compulsion to tell
people who cared about Susan what really happened,'' he says.
(Frank O'Brien/Boston Globe Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT20) PALO ALTO, Calif. -- July 15, 1999 -- FASTER-COMPUTERS,
07-15 --Philip Kuekes, a researcher at Hewlett Packard, holds the
HP-UCLA Molecular Electronics Digital Logic Chip that was jointly
developed by Hewlett Packard and UCLA. Plunging deeply into the
microscopic world that promises ultrafast, low-power computers, the
Hewlett Packard/UCLA team have for the first time fashioned simple
computing components no thicker than a single molecule. (Peter
DaSilva/New York Times Photo) LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT19) NEW YORK -- July 15, 1999 -- ADV. FOR SUN., JULY 18 --
SOLITUDE-THEATER, 07-15 -- Polly Draper and Ciaran Hinds on the
hunt for intimacy in Patrick Marber's ``Closer.'' Although the 1987
Stephen Sondheim-James Lapine musical ``Into the Woods'' went to
great lengths to reassure us and the show's battered fairy tale
folk that ``no one is alone,'' a number of provocative recent plays
- ``Closer'' among them - have decided the opposite. (Sara
Krulwich/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT18) NEW YORK -- July 15, 1999 -- SOC-WEBBER-PROFILE, 07-15
-- Saskia Webber, a goalkeeper on the U.S. women's soccer team,
during an interview earlier this week. Webber did not play even
one-half of a match in the Women's World Cup, which the team won on
Saturday. Instead, she spent the entire, excruciatingly thrilling
tournament on the bench, her hair spray-painted red, white and
blue, cheering her team and watching Briana Scurry, the starting
keeper. Webber's story is about persistence and defeat, three times
over, and finally, victory: being chosen second best. (Ozier
Muhammad/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT17) NEW YORK -- July 15, 1999 -- ADV. FOR SUN., JULY 18 --
CABARET-BALKAN-FILM, 07-15 -- Goran Paskaljevic, the director of
``Cabaret Balkan,'' a film about people driven to violence and
despair by politics. Paskaljevic, who has long opposed Slobodan
Milosevic's regime and has expressed shame over the atrocities
committed by Serbian forces in Bosnia and Kosovo, still remains a
Serb, and, as such, he is expected to throw light on the collective
madness that has gripped a good many of his fellow Serbs of late.
(Sara Krulwich/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT16) WASHINGTON -- July 15, 1999 -- CLINTON-BARAK-COX, 07-15
-- President Clinton looks on as Israeli Prime Minister Ehud Barak
speaks to reporters at the White House on Thursday. Clinton and
Barak met for three hours at the White House before going off to
Camp David. (Rick McKay/Cox News Service Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT15) NEW YORK -- July 15, 1999 -- ADV. FOR SUN., JULY 18 --
BELGIAN-FILMS, 07-15 -- Patrice Toye, the director of ``Rosie,'' a
sensitive and provocative debut feature focusing on the inner life
of a 13-year-old girl. ``I didn't want to tell an ABC story,'' says
says Ms. Toye who, at 32, is the first woman to make a feature film
in Flemish. ``You know, the kind of film where you watch the first
five minutes, and you can already tell what's going to happen.''
(Jeffery A. Salter/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT14) NEW YORK -- July 15, 1999 -- ADV. FOR SUN., JULY 18 --
CUNNINGHAM-DANCE, 07-15 -- The dancer and choreographer Merce
Cunningham at his dance studio earlier this month. As Lincoln
Center Festival '99 prepares to honor Cunningham with an
80th-birthday celebration this week, he is, as always, exploring
new ways of moving in new contexts. Once heckled as the high priest
of the dance avant-garde and now acclaimed for the same reason, he
has never failed to show that even the most fully plotted cosmos
can reveal surprising secrets. (Jeffery A. Salter/New York Times
Photo) LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT13) PROVIDENCE, R.I. -- July 15, 1999 -- RECYCLED-CLOTHES-2,
07-15 -- Captain Thomas Taylor, the administrator of the Salvation
Army's Providence center where workers sort donated clothes. The
center is one of the busiest of the organization's 119 across the
country. Nearly a decade of rising prosperity has shaken the ways
that Americans view and use clothing. The glut is a boon to the
many charities like the Salvation Army that sort and sell old
clothes. (Keith Meyers/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT12) PROVIDENCE, R.I. -- July 15, 1999 -- RECYCLED-CLOTHES-1,
07-15 -- Tracy Alexander sorts through clothes at the Salvation
Army warehouse. Nearly a decade of rising prosperity has shaken the
ways that Americans view and use clothing. The glut is a boon to
the many charities like the Salvation Army that sort and sell old
clothes. (Keith Meyers/New York Times Photo) LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT11) ROCKVILLE, Md. -- July 15, 1999 -- CARS-SAFETY-2, 07-15
-- A Ford Explorer spared the bumper of Matthew L. Wald's Mercury
Sable wagon almost entirely by striking above it. But the insurance
company said repairs would cost a bit more than $5,000, which was
the approximate value of the car, which had 80,000 miles on the
odometer. (Matthew L. Wald/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT10) ROCKVILLE, Md. -- July 15, 1999 -- CARS-SAFETY-1, 07-15
-- Matthew L. Wald's Mercury Sable wagon after being rear-ended by
a Ford Explorer on a residential street in Rockville. It wasn't
bumper-to-bumper, but bumper-to-taillight, as the Explorer spared
the wagon's bumper almost entirely by striking above it. As a
result of the mismatch, the left rear corner of the car ended up
moving one foot toward the hood. (Matthew L. Wald/New York Times
Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT9) LOS ANGELES -- July 15, 1999 -- ART-NOTES, 07-15 --
``Initial C: David Playing Bells'' from the Avranches Psalter,
which the Getty recently bought, reportedly for about $7 million.
The 334-page work, which is 12 inches tall and has nine
illustrations inspired by the Book of Psalms, was something the
Getty had had its eye on for years. (J. Paul Getty Museum/New York
Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT8) NEW YORK -- July 15, 1999 -- NY-VIDEO-FESTIVAL, 07-15 --
The actress Kate Valk giving pointers to an 8th grade video
production class at I.S. 131. As the title character in the Wooster
Group's video production of Eugene O'Neill's play ``The Emperor
Jones,'' Ms. Valk wears blackface and a Kabuki costume, rolling her
eyes and writhing like a voodoo apparition in Asian theatrical
drag, the Caucasian actress adopting a cartoonishly oratorical
drawl to intone the character's ravingly paranoid dialogue.
(Barbara Alper/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT7) LONDON -- July 15, 1999 -- THEATER-NOTES, 07-15 --
``Mamma Mia,'' featuring Abba songs, is drawing London crowds. The
$4.5 million all-Abba musical - which has sold out its 1,650-seat
theater through Sept. 11, with tickets on sale through March 2000 -
was developed by Benny Andersson and Bjorn Ulvaeus, former members
of the group, with a book by Catherine Johnson. ``I don't think
anybody anticipated how well we would be received,'' says Judy
Craymer, the show's producer. (Jonathan Player/New York Times
Photo) LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT6) WASHINGTON -- July 15, 1999 -- ISRAEL-U.S.-2, 07-15 --
President Clinton walks with Israeli Prime Minister Ehud Barak
towards the podium to deliver comments to the waiting press corps
at the White House on Thursday. Clinton and Barak met for three
hours at the White House before going off to Camp David. (Paul
Hosefros/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT5) WASHINGTON -- July 15, 1999 -- ISRAEL-U.S., 07-15 --
President Clinton talks to reporters as visiting Israeli Prime
Minister Ehud Barak looks on at the White House on Thursday.
Clinton and Barak met for three hours at the White House before
going off to Camp David. (Paul Hosefros/New York Times Photo) LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT4) DENVER -- July 15, 1999 -- DENVER-INTERNATIONALIZE-3,
07-15 -- People take part in a Greek folkloric dance during a
festival earlier this month. Experts say the rapid
internationalization of this city, 1,000 miles from the nearest
seaport, is perhaps the highest profile example of a larger trend:
the increasing integration of the nation's interior into the world
economy. (Kevin Moloney/New York Times Photo) LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT3) DENVER -- July 15, 1999 -- DENVER-INTERNATIONALIZE-2,
07-15 -- In a scene not usually identified with taking place in the
West, Tibetan protesters try to set alight a Chinese flag to
protest the arrival of Chinese Premier Zhu Rongji in April. Experts
say the rapid internationalization of this city, 1,000 miles from
the nearest seaport, is perhaps the highest profile example of a
larger trend: the increasing integration of the nation's interior
into the world economy. (Kevin Moloney/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT2) DENVER -- July 15, 1999 -- DENVER-INTERNATIONALIZE-1,
07-15 -- A visitor to the Denver Art Museum looks up at ``The
Battle of Lowestoft'' by Adriaen van Diest, circa 1670, in January
during the exhibit, ``600 years of British Art.'' Experts say the
rapid internationalization of this city, 1,000 miles from the
nearest seaport, is perhaps the highest profile example of a larger
trend: the increasing integration of the nation's interior into the
world economy. (Kevin Moloney/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT1) WASHINGTON -- July 15, 1999 -- HEALTH-CARE, 07-15 --
President Clinton comments about pending health care legislation
after an event at the White House supporting gun control laws on
Thursday. A Senate vote is expected late Thursday on the Republican
version of the Patients' Bill of rights. (Paul Hosefros/New York
Times Photo)
</P>
