<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEN-DAVIS-CUP-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DAVIS CUP LINEUPS HAVE SAMPRAS ONLY IN DOUBLES 
</HEADLINE>
  (rk) 
 By ROBIN FINN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHESTNUT HILL, Mass. _ History was in the air Thursday at the
Longwood Cricket Club, site of the first Davis Cup competition in
1900 and of a centenary quarterfinal between the United States and
Australia this weekend.
</P>
<P>
   But Pete Sampras, now a six-time Wimbledon champion and arguably
the greatest player in tennis history, will apparently not take a
singles role in the encounter between Davis Cup's two superpowers,
despite speculation that the United States had a secret weapon
waiting in the wings.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't drag someone out on the singles court,'' said Tom
Gullikson, the U.S. captain. ``He wouldn't have come back on the
team if he felt like he was taking a singles spot away from one of
our other guys.''
</P>
<P>
   Gullikson admitted that the decision to leave Sampras on the
singles sideline could end up backfiring.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we win, nobody will care,'' Gullikson said. ``If we lose,
everybody thinks I'm nuts and I get my head chopped off. But it's
better to have Pete Sampras back in the fold, even if just to play
doubles. It's better than nothing.''
</P>
<P>
   Barring a sudden injury to Todd Martin or Jim Courier, the
anchormen of the United States' first-round upset of Great Britain,
Sampras' role will be limited to doubles. According to Sampras,
Martin and Courier ``deserve to play singles'' because of their
sustained commitment to Davis Cup.
</P>
<P>
   ``I haven't been in the same boat,'' said Sampras, who ignored
Davis Cup last year to concentrate on his ranking and on the Grand
Slams. He only decided to join the 1999 squad after Martin and
Courier's first-round coup rekindled his team spirit.
</P>
<P>
   At a brief noontime draw ceremony on the Longwood veranda, the
lineups of both teams, along with the schedule for the four singles
matches and one doubles match, were disclosed. In the opener on
Friday, Martin, playing the top singles slot for the United States,
will face 18-year-old Lleyton Hewitt, a replacement for the injured
Mark Philippoussis.
</P>
<P>
   The second singles match features Patrick Rafter, the two-time
defending U.S. Open champion, and Courier, the veteran scrapper who
pulled off pivotal upsets of Tim Henman and Greg Rusedski in very
hostile territory in the opening round at Birmingham, England, this
year. The singles pairings reverse on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   The best player on the podium, and the only one with a winning
record against Rafter, was not mentioned until it was time for the
doubles pairings for Saturday. Sampras will join Alex O'Brien
against another impromptu doubles tandem: Sandon Stolle, like
Hewitt a Davis Cup neophyte, and Mark Woodforde, a 33-year-old Cup
fixture whose usual partner, Todd Woodbridge, begged off because of
what John Newcombe, Australia's captain, called a confidence
problem.
</P>
<P>
   Gullikson said he was not averse to using Sampras in singles.
But he said he had failed to convince Sampras that he could play
singles without slighting Martin, who indicated he would give up
his singles spot if Gullikson asked him to, and Courier, who made
it clear he felt he and Martin had earned the roles.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of ``jumping on the bandwagon and carrying the flag''
after an acrimonious year's hiatus from Davis Cup duty, Sampras
stuck to his plan of tiptoeing back into the good graces of the
team's stalwarts.
</P>
<P>
   But Sampras had no qualms about returning to the top singles
role if the American squad reaches the semifinals. ``If we advance,
I would think I've showed Todd and Jim and the rest of the guys
that I am committed to Davis Cup,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
