<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WORKING-COLUMN-$ADV18-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE REIGN OF TERROR  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, JULY 18) 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Pa.)   (af)  
 By MICHELLE COTTLE 
  
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q. (italics)The director of the small nonprofit organization
where I work is absolutely impossible. She is controlling and has
poor management skills, and her mood swings result in unpredictable
tirades. As a result, we have high turnover at all levels. Our
board members are aware of the situation, but their attitude seems
to be that, as long as the work gets done, it doesn't matter how
the office is run. Any advice?(end italics) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. Ouch. Since you presumably aren't in a position to play
therapist to your boss, or to give her a swift kick in the pants,
it's time to gather your co-workers to talk about your options _
keeping in mind, of course, that any action could leave you without
a job.
</P>
<P>
   You should discuss your perceptions of the problem, potential
strategies for solving it and possible fallout. ``You need to
operate as a support group for one another,'' said Daniel K.
Oestreich, co-author of ``Driving Fear Out of the Workplace''
(Jossey-Bass).
</P>
<P>
   But don't let the discussions degenerate into pointless
complaining, warned Renee Magid, president of Initiatives Inc., a
consulting firm in Fort Washington, Pa., that helps companies
balance employees' work and personal issues. ``Often, the biggest
problem is that everybody is very good at moaning and groaning,''
she said, but when it comes to doing something, they back off.
</P>
<P>
   Start documenting your boss's behavior, Ms. Magid said. ``Keep a
log so you have actual facts,'' she advised.
</P>
<P>
   Stanley Foster Reed, author of ``The Toxic Executive'' (Random
House, 1994), agreed that the complaints must be specific. ``You've
got to know when the person said this or did this. No
generalizations.''
</P>
<P>
   The hard part, however, is deciding who is going to approach the
boss or the board. Everyone should be involved in the decision,
Oestreich said. ``There's the possibility that one person speaking
up will affect others,'' he explained. ``You need to be talking in
a candid way about who's going to do what.''
</P>
<P>
   In meeting with the boss, your emissary should make it clear
that he or she represents the entire group, Ms. Magid advised.
``You have a much better chance with a group involved,'' she said,
``because it can't be that everyone's crazy.''
</P>
<P>
   Keep the conversation professional, about business rather than
hurt feelings. Explain how certain actions are undermining
productivity. ``The idea is not necessarily to be accusing as much
as to say how this is impacting the organization and its people,''
Ms. Magid said.
</P>
<P>
   If the boss does not seems receptive, it's time to repeat your
presentation for the board members.
</P>
<P>
   The board may well have an incomplete picture of the situation,
Oestreich said. Outline for them the precise costs of your boss's
leadership failures.
</P>
<P>
   No matter how delicately you handle the issue, however, heads
may roll. So your best recourse may be to abandon ship. But if you
and your colleagues are committed to the organization and believe
in its future, your actions _ rational and organized _ may be worth
the risk. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Michelle Cottle is a Washington writer. Each week, she responds
to readers' questions about career and workplace issues. Send them
by e-mail to working(AT)nytimes.com or by mail to Working, Money &AMP;
Business, The New York Times, 229 West 43d Street, New York, N.Y.
10036. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
