</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-BRITISH-OPEN-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHEN THE GOING GETS TOUGH, IT'S THE BRITISH OPEN WHERE PAR TAKES
THE LEAD  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By CLIFTON BROWN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   CARNOUSTIE, Scotland _ When the day mercifully ended, nobody who
had played Thursday could remember enduring a tougher first round
in the British Open.
</P>
<P>
   One hundred fifty-six of the world's best golfers teed off.
Nobody finished under par, and only one player, Rodney Pampling of
Australia, shot even par. The average score was 78.3 on a par-71
course. Fifty-five players finished in the 80s, while two finished
in the 90s.
</P>
<P>
   The highest winning British Open score of the last 50 years was
Gary Player's 289, also at Carnoustie in 1968, but that mark is in
jeopardy. The last time that no golfer was able to shoot under par
during a round of the British Open occurred in 1986, at Turnberry,
Scotland, in both the first and third rounds. In the United States
since World War II, there has never been a round in the Masters and
the PGA Championship in which a golfer has failed to break par. In
the more difficult U.S. Open, it has happened 11 times since World
War II, with the last instance coming at Winged Foot in New York in
1974.
</P>
<P>
   All the pre-tournament talk about Carnoustie's being one of the
world's most difficult courses rang true, especially because the
7,361-yard bunker-laden course has been toughened for the Open. The
fairways are narrow, some only 15 to 20 yards wide, and from the
tee box they look as narrow as a hallway. And all of the fairways
are framed by thick, knee-high rough, deep enough to make a golf
ball disappear, along with any chance for victory.
</P>
<P>
   Weekend amateurs could relate to the inflated scores. Many of
the world's best players could not.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the average player had to play out there, he'd probably
quit the game _ a lot of pros, too,'' said David Duval, the world's
No. 2-ranked player, who shot an 8-over-par 79. ``When the guys
said 300 would be the winning score, everyone thought they were
crazy. You never know.''
</P>
<P>
   With the wind averaging around 20 miles an hour and gusting up
to 30, all the ingredients were in place to make players fall to
their knees.
</P>
<P>
   Mark O'Meara, the defending champion, shot an 83. Sergio
Garcia's first major as a professional became a major disaster as
he triple-bogeyed the first hole, finished with an embarrassing 89,
declined to comment before leaving the course, and bravely returned
several hours later to answer questions.
</P>
<P>
   The later it got, the wilder it got. Tiger Woods, who shot a 74,
was surprised on his final hole by a scantily clad woman who ran on
the green and gave him a kiss while he was trying to line up a
putt. Woods would rather have had a birdie than a kiss, but he took
the incident in stride.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had just put my ball down, all of a sudden I see these
feet,'' Woods said. ``I looked up, there she was.''
</P>
<P>
   Almost lost in the chaos was the competition. Even the leader
board was bizarre. Playing in his first Open, Pampling shot a 71
and led by one stroke over Bernhard Langer and Scott Dunlap. Seven
players were tied for fourth place at 73: Justin Leonard, the 1997
British Open champion; Hal Sutton; Dudley Hart; Paul Lawrie of
Scotland; Len Mattiace; Mark McNulty of Zimbabwe, and Steve Pate.
</P>
<P>
   Pampling and Langer took advantage of their early tee times
(7:25 a.m.), as did Dunlap (8:05 a.m.), finishing some holes before
the wind was at its worst.
</P>
<P>
   Pampling, a 27-year-old native of Queensland, started the week
having to introduce himself to many players. He ended the day
leading them. Who would have thought? But it was that kind of day.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a lot of fun,'' said Pampling, a 30-year-old who has
won just once on the Australasian Tour, where he plays regularly.
``I was enjoying the moment.''
</P>
<P>
   Many others did not. All of these formidable players finished at
79: Duval; the reigning U.S. Open champion Payne Stewart; the 1995
PGA Championship winner Steve Elkington, and this year's U.S. Open
runner-up, Phil Mickelson.
</P>
<P>
   The par-4, 474-yard No. 9 was the most difficult hole today,
with an average score of 4.73. There were four birdies on the hole,
62 pars, and 90 double-bogeys or worse. Jim Furyk, who shot a 78,
double-bogeyed No. 9, as did Garcia.
</P>
<P>
   Choosing the right club to hit was an adventure. How much of a
factor was the wind? On the par-5, 515-yard No. 14, which played
downwind, Woods hit a 4-iron off the tee, then reached the green
with a 7-iron. Think about that.
</P>
<P>
   But playing into the wind on the par-4, 459-yard No. 17, Woods
hit a 2-iron off the tee, and when he followed that shot with a
3-wood from the fairway, the ball landed well short of the green.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, any trip into the rough was a possible ball-searching
expedition. ``You might find a few players with injured wrists at
the end of the week,'' said Colin Montgomerie, who shot a 74.
</P>
<P>
   Davis Love III (74) double-bogeyed No. 12, when he took a mighty
swing at a ball buried in deep rough, and the ball moved about
three inches.
</P>
<P>
   Having won two U.S. Opens, Stewart is not one to complain about
courses. He complained about this one. ``I do not think these
conditions will recognize the best player,'' Stewart said. ``The
landing area where you have to lay up on No. 6 is 11 yards.
</P>
<P>
   ``What are we trying to do here? It's a great championship, it
means a lot to me, but I'm just sorry everybody is coming off the
golf course having these opinions. This is a wonderful golf course
played a little bit wider. You know you're going to have wind, so I
don't understand it. It could actually be a place where people wish
they'd missed the cut.''
</P>
<P>
   Stewart might. But Thursday's game plan was to avoid shooting
oneself out of the tournament. Players like Duval and Stewart
seriously hurt their chances. Anyone who shot 75 or better had a
strong day.
</P>
<P>
   They will do it again Friday, and with the wind not expected to
die down, expect more of the same. Somebody will ultimately win,
but their scorecard will look ugly.
</P>
<P>
   Montgomerie, recalling this year's U.S. Open, said: ``It was
only 30 days ago that we were saying Pinehurst was the hardest
course we ever played. We're all changing our opinion.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
