<SLUG> BC-EURO-271&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BANK CHIEF HINTS AT POSSIBLE BOOST FOR EURO 
</HEADLINE>
  (yn) 
 By EDMUND L. ANDREWS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   FRANKFURT, Germany _ In a move that helped push up the sagging
value of the euro against the dollar, the head of the European
Central Bank signaled Thursday that it might toughen monetary
policy in the not-too-distant future.
</P>
<P>
   Wim Duisenberg, president of the central bank, said the bank
might tilt toward an increase in interest rates if the supply of
credit and money in Europe continues to expand robustly.
</P>
<P>
   Though he stopped well short of announcing a change in policy,
Duisenberg said that ``a bias may be creeping into our
considerations'' and that ``a reassessment might be appropriate.''
</P>
<P>
   The remarks helped nudge the euro up about a half-cent against
the dollar, reaching $1.024 in European trading Thursday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   The remarks marked a small but significant shift by the bank,
which has been watching Europe's new single currency sink about 13
percent against the dollar since it was introduced on Jan. 4.
</P>
<P>
   The currency's weakness has become a source of embarrassment and
concern among the 11 nations that adopted the single currency.
There had been widespread expectations that it would strengthen in
value fairly quickly.
</P>
<P>
   But Duisenberg and other European central bankers have
repeatedly refused to do anything to prop up the value of the euro,
even as it has drifted down from nearly $1.18 at its introduction
to nearly a one-to-one parity with the dollar last week.
</P>
<P>
   Though Duisenberg said nothing new about the euro's exchange
rate Thursday, higher interest rates would represent a tightening
of the monetary spigots and would put upward pressure on the euro's
value.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The comments on Thursday marked a new turn in the central bank's
delicate dance between promoting the euro's credibility in world
markets and promoting a recovery in Europe's sluggish economy.
</P>
<P>
   Alarmed by the sharp slowdown in industrial production and
exports toward the end of last year, the bank reduced its baseline
interest rates on April 8 to 2.5 percent from 3 percent. That
reduction followed an earlier cut imposed simultaneously by all the
individual banks in the 11-nation euro-zone last December, just
before the euro came into formal existence.
</P>
<P>
   The euro was hovering around $1.02 before Duisenberg spoke this
afternoon after a meeting of the bank's board of governors.
</P>
<P>
   For months, bank officials have publicly asserted that they were
not concerned about the euro's decline, because it merely reflected
Europe's slower economic growth and still had considerable
``potential'' for moving higher.
</P>
<P>
   Duisenberg reiterated that line Thursday. ``We believe that the
euro is firmly based on internal price stability and therefore has
potential for a stronger external value,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   He repeated conclusions in the bank's July monthly bulletin,
saying the signs of economic recovery have become more numerous.
</P>
<P>
   ``While signs of recovery are still modest and are not yet
reflected in labor market developments, recent data appear to
confirm the outlook for a continued improvement in the course of
the year,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Duisenberg said the new ``bias'' toward higher rates reflects
strong growth in the money supply and in the volume of new credit.
</P>
<P>
   ``If money and credit growth increase further, a reassessment
may be appropriate,'' Duisenberg said. But, he added, he had no
regrets about the last decision to cut rates.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
