<HEADER>
A1957 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CRUISE16-COX     07-15 1191
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CRUISE16-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Cruise plays latest risky role with eyes wide open
 &HT;    By Dave Larsen
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ Tom Cruise has enjoyed a seemingly charmed
career. The two-time Oscar nominee has more than $1 billion in
box-office receipts to his credit and commands $20 million per
film, making him one of Hollywood's top guns. He produced the
blockbuster ``Mission: Impossible,'' in which he starred, as well
as last year's ``Without Limits,'' the critically acclaimed film
biography of Olympic runner Steve Prefontaine.
</P>
<P>
   The latter title could easily apply to Cruise himself. The
37-year-old actor surmounted a difficult childhood and a brief
association with Hollywood's ``Brat Pack'' to become a superstar.
In 1990, he married beautiful Australian actress Nicole Kidman, his
frequent co-star, with whom he has two adopted children, Isabella
and Connor.
</P>
<P>
   There have been a few stumbles, such as the fantasy flop
``Legend'' and the meandering immigrant saga ``Far and Away,'' but
Cruise appears to have made all the right moves. Like Prefontaine,
he's confident, disciplined and driven by a strong personal
commitment to excellence.
</P>
<P>
   ``You do have to believe in yourself,'' Cruise said at a press
conference in September at the Toronto Film Festival, where
``Without Limits'' premiered. He was discussing whether he ever
faced self-doubt. ``Things seem like they can't get any worse _ I
say, `Well, things can't get any worse, so let's keep going.' It's
got to get better at some point.''
</P>
<P>
   Cruise's best performances usually have involved the greatest
risk, like when he abandoned his cocksure screen persona to play
paralyzed Vietnam veteran Ron Kovic in Oliver Stone's ``Born on the
Fourth of July,'' which earned Cruise his first Academy Award
nomination. Author Anne Rice denounced his casting as the cruel and
seductive Lestat in ``Interview With the Vampire,'' only to take
out a full-page ad in ``Variety'' to rave about Cruise's
performance after she screened the film.
</P>
<P>
   The biggest chance of his career _ Stanley Kubrick's highly
anticipated psychosexual thriller, ``Eyes Wide Shut'' _ emerges
today from under a shroud of secrecy. Cruise refused to discuss the
production at the Toronto press conference, except to say that
``filming `Eyes Wide Shut' was an extraordinary experience.''
</P>
<P>
   The film is Kubrick's first since 1987's ``Full Metal Jacket,''
as well the last from the legendary director of such films as
``2001: A Space Odyssey,'' ``Dr. Strangelove'' and ``A Clockwork
Orange''; he died in March at age 70. The plot, which was
deliberately withheld from the media per Kubrick's instructions,
was inspired by Arthur Schnitzler's 1926 novella, ``Dream Story.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Eyes Wide Shut'' also sees Cruise resurface for the first time
since his Oscar-nominated turn in 1996's ``Jerry Maguire.'' The $65
million film's scheduled 18-week shoot mushroomed into 52 weeks
over 15 months, during which Cruise, who had reduced his usual
salary to work with Kubrick, passed on a number of other projects
and reportedly developed an ulcer.
</P>
<P>
   His health problems might be attributed to the emotional demands
of his character, a wealthy New York physician who explores the
dark side of his sexual nature after learning that his wife, played
by Kidman, was once strongly tempted to have an extramarital
affair.
</P>
<P>
   Kubrick presented ``Eyes Wide Shut'' to Cruise, Kidman and
Warner Bros. executives Bob Daly and Terry Semel five days before
his death. The director's contract gave him final cut, but the
Motion Picture Association of America insisted on a ``digital
adjustment'' before it would issue an R rating, according to
Variety. To skirt an NC-17, digital characters have been
strategically imposed over the action in a large-scale orgy scene.
</P>
<P>
   Such a depraved setting is probably the last place one would
expect to find Cruise, whose All-American good looks,
million-dollar smile and earnest demeanor portray him as a fairly
regular guy to whom audiences can easily relate.
</P>
<P>
   He was born Thomas Cruise Mapother IV on July 3, 1962 in
Syracuse, N.Y. As a boy he suffered from dyslexia and from the
breakup of his nomadic family. His father, an itinerant electrical
engineer, dragged Tom, his mother and his three sisters to at least
a dozen different cities _ including Cincinnati, where Tom attended
a Franciscan seminary. He settled in Glen Ridge, N.J., after his
mother remarried.
</P>
<P>
   Cruise used his athletic ability as a means to fit in and didn't
discover acting until a knee injury forced him to quit his
high-school wrestling team. He dropped out during his senior year
to move to New York City, where he struggled through auditions and
night classes while barely supporting himself as a busboy and
maintenance worker.
</P>
<P>
   He made his film debut in 1981 with a fleeting role as an
arson-prone teen-ager in ``Endless Love,'' followed by his
appearance the same year as a trigger-happy cadet in ``Taps.''
Cruise would establish himself in coming-of-age movies such as
``Risky Business'' and solidify his star status in escapist action
fare such as ``Top Gun.''
</P>
<P>
   His rich characterization of an arrogant young pool player in
Martin Scorsese's ``The Color of Money'' proved him to be a serious
actor who could hold his own alongside screen legend Paul Newman.
He did the same with Dustin Hoffman in ``Rain Man'' and Jack
Nicholson in ``A Few Good Men,'' consolidating his credentials.
</P>
<P>
   Cruise's weaker films, such as ``Cocktail'' and ``Days of
Thunder,'' have often presented little more than slight variations
on his cocky persona. It's when he has dug deep under the surface
of such characters, as in ``Jerry Maguire,'' that Cruise has
shined.
</P>
<P>
   Having completed ``Eyes Wide Shut,'' Cruise will return to
theaters with a vengeance. He recently wrapped production on
``Magnolia,'' the new film by ``Boogie Nights'' director Paul
Thomas Anderson, due in December. Cruise signed this week to star
in ``Death Race 3000,'' Anderson's remake of ``Death Race 2000,'' a
1975 Roger Corman film about race-car drivers who get points for
running down pedestrians.
</P>
<P>
   For ``Mission: Impossible 2,'' he will reprise his role as Ethan
Hunt, who must recapture and destroy a deadly German-manufactured
virus before it falls into the wrong hands. Cruise produced the
action thriller, which is being shot in Australia by John Woo and
is due Dec. 17.
</P>
<P>
   Next summer Cruise will star in ``Minority Report,'' a sci-fi
action thriller directed by Steven Spielberg. Mark your calendar
for June 30, 2000.
</P>
<P>
   ``I love movies, plain and simple,'' Cruise said in Toronto. ``I
enjoy making them. The process of it can be very difficult. Every
day is different. And working with the people that I've had the
opportunity to work with, I feel that I've learned a lot from them.
</P>
<P>
   ``The one thing that I've realized that I could do in my
situation is that whatever amount power and responsibility I carry
is to channel them in a way that allows me to hopefully make good
films. That's always been my goal.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
