<HEADER>
A1958 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NUTS&AMP;BOLTS16-COX     07-15 1024
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NUTS&AMP;BOLTS16-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Low-voltage, solar lighting easy to install
 &HT;    By James Cummings
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ There are few projects that can be done quickly
and inexpensively that have as much impact around the house as
installing outdoor lighting.
</P>
<P>
   By working a few hours and spending less than $100, you can
dramatically change the look of your property and improve its
security at the same time. It costs a bit more to step up from
basic plastic light fixtures to sturdier designer models, but the
time investment still will be low.
</P>
<P>
   The most common landscape lights are low voltage and are a snap
to wire. And for a little more money, you can have solar-powered
lights that require no wiring at all.
</P>
<P>
   Low-voltage lights
</P>
<P>
   While your inside lights run on 120-volt circuits, outside
accent lights typically function on 12 volts. Low-voltage lighting
systems consume less energy and are safer and easier for a
do-it-yourselfer to install and maintain.
</P>
<P>
   Among the fixtures that can run on 12 volts are floodlights to
light large areas and spotlights to illuminate individual objects
or architectural features, as well as lights for paths, ponds and
steps. A trip to a lighting or home-improvement store will give you
an idea of your options.
</P>
<P>
   Decide where you want the lights to go, what type you'll need
and where the power supply will be. Draw a simple map of your
planned layout and measure distances to determine how much power
cord you'll need.
</P>
<P>
   The main component of a low-voltage light system is a
transformer. This device attaches to the main house current and
converts it to the lower voltage.
</P>
<P>
   Like all outdoor-lighting components, transformers come in a
wide range of prices. But because it is the heart of a lighting
system, it doesn't pay to skimp on a cheap transformer. And, of
course, the more lights you plan to use, the more power capacity
you need in the transformer.
</P>
<P>
   If your needs are basic, you can buy an inexpensive kit that
comes with a transformer, light fixtures and wiring. You can find
kits with eight to 10 lights for less than $50.
</P>
<P>
   Or you can build a custom system by buying individual accent
lights and a transformer. Prices for individual lights vary, but
they start at around $20.
</P>
<P>
   Marc Johannes, an electrical specialist at the Lowe's store near
the Dayton Mall, said the best way to install low-voltage lights is
to position all the lights and run the wiring to connect them.
Don't bury the wires yet.
</P>
<P>
   Attaching fixtures to the power supply is very simple. Most
fixtures come with clamps that have electrical contacts that
automatically punch through the coating on the power supply wire.
You ordinarily don't have to do any cutting and splicing.
</P>
<P>
   Wait until dark to see how the lights look, Johannes said. If
you're satisfied with the arrangement, come back the next day and
conceal the wires. Low-voltage wires don't have to be deeply buried
like 120-volt lines do. A one-inch-deep furrow or a layer of mulch
is all it takes.
</P>
<P>
   If the wires are accidentally cut (such as by a hoe or lawn
mower), they may deliver a mild shock but nothing dangerous.
</P>
<P>
   To protect the wires, you may want to run them close to the
foundation of your house.
</P>
<P>
   They also can be tucked against the edge of a sidewalk or
driveway.
</P>
<P>
   Solar-powered lights
</P>
<P>
   In the past, solar-powered lights tended to be dim and
unreliable. With advances in technology, they've become brighter,
more dependable and relatively cheap.
</P>
<P>
   Solar-powered lights also have become easy to find. Both
Wal-Mart and Lowe's, for instance, carry at least one brand that
can be attached to a wall or driven into the ground with a stake.
</P>
<P>
   Solar-powered landscape lights collect energy from the sun
during the day and release current at night to illuminate a bulb.
The ones I've seen for sale locally use LED (light-emitting diode)
technology.
</P>
<P>
   The length of time the light stays lit depends on the brightness
of the sun. But even on an overcast day, solar-powered lights store
enough power to stay bright through the evening.
</P>
<P>
   A basic solar-powered light costs about $20, which is
considerably more than a basic low-voltage light in a kit.
Low-voltage lights don't use much electricity, so they're
inexpensive to run. Solar-powered lights don't cost anything at all
to run.
</P>
<P>
   The major advantage of solar-powered lights, though, is that
they don't require any wiring; each light fixture is self-contained
and doesn't need to be connected to a power source.
</P>
<P>
   That means you can easily place a set of solar-powered lights at
the far corner of your property where it would be impractical to
run a power line.
</P>
<P>
   Another outdoor-lighting project that will improve the security
of your home is replacing an outdoor fixture, such as one on a back
porch or garage, with a motion- or light-sensor fixture.
</P>
<P>
   A traditional porch or garage light is only on when you turn it
on, so it provides no security if you forget to turn it on every
night.
</P>
<P>
   A motion-sensor fixture turns the light on when it detects
motion nearby, such as an intruder approaching the porch. A light
sensor turns the light on at dusk and off at dawn. You can find
either kind starting at around $20.
</P>
<P>
   To replace a light fixture, start by cutting power to the
circuit. Go to your house's main service panel or fuse box and turn
off the circuit breaker or remove the fuse corresponding to the
room or garage where the light switch is located.
</P>
<P>
   Go back to the light fixture and carefully take off removable
shades and light bulbs. The fixture should be held to the wall with
screws. Remove the screws and pull the fixture a few inches from
its bracket.
</P>
<P>
   Use a circuit tester to confirm power has been cut to the
fixture before using a screwdriver to disconnect the electrical
leads.
</P>
<P>
   Keeping the electrical leads separated, attach them to the new
fixture in the same way they were attached to the old one. The
replacement light fixture will have screws and other hardware to
hold it in place.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
