<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-REFINISH16-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Refinishing can be hefty job
 &HT;    By James Cummings
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ So you've stumbled across a gorgeous old coffee
table being used to display knickknacks at a neighbor's garage
sale.
</P>
<P>
   Or maybe the chest of drawers Grandma Schwartz left you is
starting to show its age.
</P>
<P>
   ``Not to worry,'' you think. ``I'll just refinish it.''
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, refinishing is rarely an easy or simple process.
It's messy, complicated, sweaty work.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most people don't realize how much elbow grease this is going
to take,'' said Ralph Swigart Jr. of Swigart Refinishing Co. in
Dayton.
</P>
<P>
   If you're determined to make an old piece of wooden furniture as
attractive, valuable and useful as possible, you should take a
research trip to the library or bookstore and interview people who
have done it before.
</P>
<P>
   The Dayton Daily News talked to Elma Hyatt and Mike Cole, who
run American Heritage Furniture Stripping and Refinishing in
Dayton, and Ralph Swigart Sr. and Ralph Swigart Jr. of Swigart
Refinishing, to gather insights on what the job entails.
</P>
<P>
   Heritage refinished a 150-year-old oak writing table Hyatt found
at a yard sale to demonstrate techniques the company uses, and the
Swigarts showed us the work they did on a client's dining room
chair that probably is about 50 years old.
</P>
<P>
   And the word is ``sanding.'' Expect to do a lot of it.
</P>
<P>
   To strip or not to strip
</P>
<P>
   ``If you're thinking of reselling a piece at some point and you
think it might have the original finish on it, you definitely
should not strip it,'' said Ralph Swigart Jr. Retaining the
original finish on an antique generally enhances its value. Do what
you can to maintain the finish without removing it.
</P>
<P>
   Cole pointed out that some pieces were painted over an original
finish while some other pieces were painted directly on the bare
wood. In cases where the bare wood was painted, stripping will not
remove color that has seeped into the wood itself. You won't be
able to use a clear finish after stripping, but you can repaint to
give an attractive new surface.
</P>
<P>
   Stripping
</P>
<P>
   The Swigarts use a stripper the consistency of a light paste
that sticks to surfaces as it is applied. Similar thick-bodied
strippers are available where refinishing supplies are sold. They
apply the paste with brushes, monitor the project closely to see
when the old finish loosens, then work off the old finish with
burlap rags. ``A common mistake people make is applying stripper
then walking away to wait while it works,'' said Ralph Swigart Jr.
``You have to keep right on top of it or the stripper can stay on
too long and streak the wood.'' Swigart workers use tools to
carefully work the finish out of crevices. Fine steel wool followed
by burlap bags help remove stubborn finishes. Sometimes more than
one application of stripper is needed. After the stripper, the
piece is cleaned with denatured alcohol.
</P>
<P>
   At American Heritage, furniture is stripped in a continuous
stream of liquid stripper. A pump pushes the stripping solution
containing methylene chloride through a hose and it comes out
through the bristles of a brush that is used to rub until the
finish loosens. As in home applications of stripper, the liquid is
collected after use to be used again.
</P>
<P>
   Strippers are generally harsh, somewhat caustic chemicals. Wear
gloves, use them in a well-ventilated area and follow other label
precautions.
</P>
<P>
   Sanding
</P>
<P>
   As wood becomes wet in the stripping process, the fibers absorb
water and the grain opens, Cole said. Sanding closes and smooths
the grain. He starts with a 120 grit sandpaper if the wood is
roughened or scratched and advances to a finer 320 grit to finish.
</P>
<P>
   Ralph Swigart Jr. said it's OK to use an orbital sander on flat
areas, but he said it's best to do most of the sanding by hand.
</P>
<P>
   Repair
</P>
<P>
   If the piece has loose joints or legs that don't sit solidly on
the floor, remove the screws or other hardware holding the piece
together and gently tap the joints apart with a soft mallet. ``Mark
each piece carefully so you'll know where it goes when you put
things back together,'' Swigart said. Fill small cracks with wood
filler that matches or is slightly lighter than the surrounding
wood. It's easier to darken a light-colored filler with a stain to
match its surrounding than it is to lighten a dark-colored filler.
Cole also had to replace a piece of missing wood veneer on the
writing table. Carefully glue and clamp broken pieces. Consult a
furniture repair book on techniques for clamping and strapping
furniture to hide repairs and make it sturdy. Sand again to smooth
repaired surfaces and remove any stray glue. Vacuum the piece and
use a tack cloth to remove sawdust residue.
</P>
<P>
   Color
</P>
<P>
   To see what the piece will look like without color, wipe it a
damp cloth, Cole suggests. If you're satisfied with the wood's
natural color, you can skip ahead to sealing.
</P>
<P>
   The dining room chair done by the Swigarts was stained with a
traditional red-brown mahogany stain. They use an oil-pigmented
wiping stain applied with rags and small brushes to reach into
crevices. ``Apply it and wipe it out evenly with clean rags,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Sealing
</P>
<P>
   The next step is to seal the wood to protect the wood and the
stained color. To get a rich color, a deep glow and a smooth
surface, you'll probably need to apply several coats of sealer,
sanding between each coat. ``The more porous the wood, the more
sealer you'll need to apply,'' Cole said. ``Oak might take three or
four coats while maple may seal nicely with one or two.'' Both
Swigart and American Heritage apply sealer using fine-mist spray
equipment, but nonprofessionals can get good results with a paint
brush and clear shellac or varnish. A 2-inch brush for broad
surfaces and a 1-inch brush to reach smaller areas are common.
</P>
<P>
   Sealers come in a variety of compositions with various
properties of durability, shine, water resistance and so on. Spend
some time with a knowledgeable salesperson in a paint or furniture
refinishing retailer and read cans carefully to pick the sealer
that best suits your needs.
</P>
<P>
   After applying each coat of sealer, you must let it dry then
sand it smooth with very fine sandpaper. The amount of times needed
for drying depends on the sealer you use, the ventilation in your
work area, humidity and other factors. Both American Heritage and
the Swigarts use 400 or 600 grit sandpaper at this point. After
sanding each coat of sealer, wipe the piece down with a tack cloth
to remove sawdust.
</P>
<P>
   Final coat
</P>
<P>
   The sealer coats typically will dry to a high gloss, but most
people prefer a softer glow for their old wood furniture. ``They
don't want an antique to look like they just bought it at Elder
Beerman,'' Cole said. The finishers use products that have been
designed as final coats with satin or semigloss shines, and you
should be able to find similar products at your refinishing supply
retailer. Before applying the muted sheen coat, make sure the
shinier sealer coats are perfectly smooth. A light rubdown with
0000 steel wool followed by a tack cloth is not a bad idea. Then
apply the finish coat. Some people will apply two or even three
layers of finish coat, drying and sanding between coats.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
