<HEADER>
A1964 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-DUPRI-JAIL16-COX     07-15 0350
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DUPRI-JAIL16-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Legal note: Dupri tries to beat the rap
 &HT;    By Ralph Ellis
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ A Fayette County judge wants to lock up a millionaire
rap music star for dodging jury duty.
</P>
<P>
   Superior Court Judge Chris Edwards found Jermaine Dupri in
criminal contempt of court and sentenced him to three days in jail.
Dupri, whose legal last name is Maudlin, remains free while
appealing the conviction.
</P>
<P>
   Both the judge and the rapper declined comment Thursday, but
Edwards expressed himself with vigor in a May 13 hearing.
</P>
<P>
   ``It doesn't matter to me if Mr. Maudlin was a brain surgeon or
whatever he does. If somebody doesn't show up for jury duty then
everybody is deprived of justice,'' the judge said.
</P>
<P>
   Dupri's lawyer, Michael W. Tyler, said the rapper made an
innocent mistake.
</P>
<P>
   Dupri showed up for the first day of jury duty March 1 and was
excused for March 2 with the rest of the jury pool. Dupri, assuming
Edwards would grant him a waiver from the rest of jury duty, left
town to perform March 3 at the Meadowlands in New Jersey, Tyler
said.
</P>
<P>
   Fayette judges granted Dupri waivers three times previously,
Tyler said. But Assistant District Attorney Jim Hardin said Dupri's
lawyers were told in August, when the last waiver was granted, not
to ask for any more.
</P>
<P>
   It's unusual for judges to put jury no-shows in jail. Usually a
judge sends a deputy out to find the missing juror, said Fayette
District Attorney Bill McBroom.
</P>
<P>
   Dupri, 26, lives in the northern tip of Fayette County, where he
shares a neighborhood with heavyweight boxing champion Evander
Holyfield, Chris Kelly of Kris Kross, singer/songwriter Kandi
Burruss of R&AMP;B quartet Xscape and LaFace Records executive/producer
Tony Mercedes.
</P>
<P>
   Dupri made his first million before he turned 21 as the producer
of Kris Kross, a preteen rap duo. He has since written
million-sellers for Mariah Carey (``Always Be My Baby''), Usher
(``You Make Me Wanna'') and himself (``Money Ain't a Thing'').
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
