<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIZ-DIARY-PERSONAL-$ADV18-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SHORT ITEMS ON PERSONAL BUSINESS  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, JULY 18) 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   A Way to Give It Before You've Got It &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Last year, Chris Evans sold Accipiter, a 22-month-old maker of
software that manages banner ads on the Internet, to CMG
Information Services for $55 million and joined the ranks of
Americans with enough cash to become philanthropists. Now Evans,
33, has invented a way to help other entrepreneurs get into giving
while their companies are young.
</P>
<P>
   They will be able to give some private shares in their start-ups
to the Entrepreneurs Venture Fund, advised by Evans and others and
associated with the Triangle Community Foundation in the Raleigh,
N.C., area.
</P>
<P>
   Then other donors, called ``investors,'' will lend some of their
money to the fund, linking it to the value of the shares. The
start-up owners will choose the causes that get the money.
</P>
<P>
   Later, when start-up companies are sold or go public, the fund
will turn its shares into cash, presumably at a profit. First the
fund will pay back the investors, who must use the money for other
giving. Any profit will go to the fund or to the start-up owners'
favorite charities.
</P>
<P>
   So what's in it for the investors? Not profit; the money they
get back will be pledged to charity. They will invest in the idea
of philanthropy itself by helping to recruit new givers.
</P>
<P>
   Todd Cohen &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Working for the Fun of It &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Neuberger Berman, the investment company, calls it
``surprising'' that the more money people make, the less likely
they were to say in a survey it sponsored last spring that they
would quit their jobs if they received a windfall inheritance.
</P>
<P>
   Among earners of less than $125,000 a year, 54 percent said
they'd quit, while only 28 percent of those making $250,000 or more
would. But if job satisfaction rises as one climbs the ladder, it's
hardly surprising that those with high earnings are more likely to
love what they do. Or perhaps the result confirms what many at
drone level suspect: that the more money you make, the more fun it
is to go to work.
</P>
<P>
   Barbara Ireland
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
