A1969 &Cx1f; taf-z
s f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CAR-SMART-ROADSTER-$A     07-15 0724
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAR-SMART-ROADSTER-$ADV18-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INSTANT ALLURE FOR THE PHYSICALLY AND FINANCIALLY FIT  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, JULY 18) 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By PETER PASSELL   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``The AIV Roadster is a purist's car, meant for one thing:
driving,'' Danny Panoz warned, obviously anxious that a test driver
might write critically about his baby's lack of creature comforts.
</P>
<P>
   The $62,500 Roadster is, indeed, ill-suited for a night at the
opera _ or, for that matter, a trip to the market. It takes some
practice to climb over the door sill and plop into one of the low,
low bucket seats without looking like an idiot.
</P>
<P>
   The vestigial doors are too fragile to use for leverage. And the
seats are too narrow for comfort, unless you have the general
physique of Ally McBeal.
</P>
<P>
   While we're on the subject of convenience, the Roadster has no
room for a glove compartment; the only place to store a map or an
insurance card is the Velcro-fastened door pocket. And then there
are the windows _ or, rather, the lack thereof.
</P>
<P>
   The Roadster is designed to be driven without top or windows. A
cloth and plastic contraption, rather like a pup tent, is stored in
a duffel bag in the diminutive trunk and can be used to cover the
occupants in a hailstorm.
</P>
<P>
   The Roadster comes with both air-conditioning and a sound system
with a CD player. But without a roof (or a muffler that can quiet
the engine below a roar) their presence is largely symbolic.
</P>
<P>
   All that said, Panoz need not have worried. For anyone who likes
fierce acceleration; quick, precise steering, and the glorious
thunder of a 305-horsepower V8 will love the Panoz Roadster. You
may care less that this car can go from zero to 60 in 4.5 seconds _
faster than an Acura NSX, a BMW M coupe, a Corvette or a Porsche
911 Carrera.
</P>
<P>
   But almost anyone with a pulse will get a kick out of its
appearance, a playful yet polished cross between a 1930s
Mercedes-Benz racer and a 1950s dragstrip bad boy. In my
experience, no vehicle has attracted more oohs and aahs from
attractive members of the opposite sex. Well, maybe the gull-winged
Lamborghini Diablo, which costs almost four times as much.
</P>
<P>
   Up close and personal, there is much more to the Roadster than
an oversized engine and a pretty face. The superrigid chassis is
made largely of aluminum (AIV stands for ``aluminum intensive
vehicle''), a first for an American car.
</P>
<P>
   The five-speed stick shift from Borg-Warner is as slick and
precise as the transmission on a BMW. And the engine, a
dual-overhead-cam, 4.6-liter V8 from Ford, with an aluminum block
and 32 valves, is proof that Detroit can still come up with the
right stuff.
</P>
<P>
   The real fun begins when you turn the key. The engine rumbles
(but doesn't vibrate) like a racing machine's. Shove the shifter
into first, ease off the clutch and the car explodes off the line.
Shift to second and before you can blink, the Roadster is howling
at 50 mph near the red line. Amazing what 300 foot-pounds of torque
can do in a vehicle that weighs just 2,570 pounds.
</P>
<P>
   The handling, with slightly excessive power steering, requires a
little getting used to. But it never disappoints. In fact the car's
exceptionally wide track, light weight, low center of gravity and
superwide tires on 18-inch wheels create a feeling of omnipotence,
a somewhat dangerous impression that the Roadster can take any
curve at any speed.
</P>
<P>
   The disk brakes, with their oversized vented rotors, are a
proper counterpoint to the explosive acceleration. Thus, while this
delightful beast is probably no match for a 12-cylinder Ferrari at
three-digit speeds, I expect it could hold its own on a mountain
road with any street-legal car in the world.
</P>
<P>
   Beefs? Apart from the limited amenities, just a handful. The car
lacks air bags and antilock brakes, taking purism a step too far.
And the cockpit is so narrow that the only way to hold the wheel
properly is to rest your elbow on the door. This could prove
awkward in an emergency.
</P>
<P>
   On the other side of the ledger, the Roadster offers one perk
that is exceptional in a car this exotic: In a pinch, virtually any
Ford dealer can repair the drivetrain. And with proven, durable
parts largely derived from high-end Mustangs, maintenance should be
reasonably cheap. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   INSIDE TRACK: On the short list of ultimate adult toys. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-15-99 2203EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
