<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-15 22:08 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1975 &Cx1f; tta-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SPRINGSTEEN-CONCERT-A     07-15 0788
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SPRINGSTEEN-CONCERT-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ALL'S WELL IN NEW JERSEY AS SPRINGSTEEN RETURNS 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds: More to be filed by 10:30 ET) 
(ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(mk) 
 By DAVID W. CHEN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   EAST RUTHERFORD, N.J. _ Every step of the way, it seems, Bruce
Springsteen has managed to produce the perfect songs and perfect
lyrics for the soundtrack to Matt Facendo's life.
</P>
<P>
   Facendo, 39, grew up in Hazlet, a Jersey guy like Springsteen.
His dad worked in a factory; so, too, did Springsteen's. He
escorted his younger brother, Doug, to his first Bruce Springsteen
concert, in Pittsburgh, when Doug was 12. He became a father just
as Springsteen was writing lyrics about the wonders of fatherhood.
And Facendo went through a bitter divorce _ just as Springsteen did
_ scathed, but full of appreciation for the small and precious
things in life.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can identify with him so much,'' said Facendo, a salesman
for Sears. ``He was writing songs about the emotional distress he
was going through, and you can identify with that. He's not better
than you when it comes to emotional or psychological problems.''
</P>
<P>
   Facendo wasn't the only one who was identifying with Springsteen
on Thursday. In fact, there were thousands of people who descended
upon the Continental Airlines Arena, right in the heart of the
swamps of Jersey, to absorb the first of 15 sold-out Springsteen
shows and, presumably, to make the kind of intimate connection with
Springsteen that few performers can hope to achieve in a big-arena
setting.
</P>
<P>
   For the sake of statistical posterity, of course, it should be
noted that there are many things about the 15-show stint from
Springsteen and the E Street Band that can be described as big, as
mind-boggling.
</P>
<P>
   For one thing, he will surpass the Grateful Dead as the leading
draw in the history of the arena. The 15-night run will be the
longest by a single artist, eclipsing Springsteen's own record of
11 shows in 1992. And the show figures to be one of the
biggest-grossing concerts of the summer, if not in recent years.
</P>
<P>
   But these were not the kinds of conversational tidbits that
could be heard in the parking lot of the arena Thursday afternoon,
the kinds of things that attracted people of different generations.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, with Springsteen songs oozing from every other car,
there was the distinct sense that this was more, perhaps, than just
a concert: It was about appreciating the good times, waxing
nostalgic and sharing wistful thoughts about how Springsteen _ and
by extension, everyone in the crowd who aged with him _ had changed
over years, and that nothing, nothing, should be taken for granted.
</P>
<P>
   It has been more than a decade, after all, since Springsteen
toured with the E Street Band, and there is no telling when, if
ever, they will perform together again on such a tour. Springsteen,
who turns 50 in September, has not had a big hit in many years; he
has not even released an album with new material in quite some
time. And he has written about changes in his life with the kind of
sharp details that a painter could appreciate.
</P>
<P>
   ``Essentially, Springsteen's fans understand mortality in a way
that they didn't when they were 19,'' said Charles Cross, editor of
The Rocket, a music magazine based in Seattle, and author of book
about Springsteen called ``Backstreets'' (Harmony Books, 1989).
``They find an appreciation for the moments where you can transcend
your life. There are a lot of pressures in life, so any time you
can have escapism in its purest form, people savor that.''
</P>
<P>
   The New Jersey Sports and Exposition Authority, which runs the
Meadowlands sports complex, set up a mini-boardwalk in the parking
lot before Thursday night's show, with volleyball courts, carnival
games, food stands and a deejay.
</P>
<P>
   ``We like to think that we brought a little bit of the Jersey
shore here to the Meadowlands,'' Helen Strus, a spokeswoman for the
New Jersey Sports and Exposition Authority, told The Associated
Press. Springsteen first made his name playing in Asbury Park and
other places along the New Jersey shore.
</P>
<P>
   Fans snatched up 308,000 tickets for the East Rutherford shows,
from Thursday through Aug. 12. After he finishes this run at the
arena, Springsteen will become the No. 1 selling artist at the
Meadowlands, selling more than 1 million tickets for all his shows
since he opened the arena in 1981.
</P>
<P>
   Springsteen and his band arrived after wrapping up a 17-city
European tour. After they finish the New Jersey shows, they'll move
on to Detroit, Boston, Washington, D.C., and Philadelphia.
</P>
<P>
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
