<HEADER>
A1977 &Cx1f; tta-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SCI-VACCINE-SUSPEND-1     07-15 1131
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-VACCINE-SUSPEND-1STLD-725&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HEALTH OFFICIALS SUSPEND USE OF VACCINE TO PREVENT INFANT
DIARRHEA 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (EDS: Subs for complete writethru to recast, add that drug maker is
suspending drug shipments. No pickup.)  (th) 
 By LAWRENCE K. ALTMAN    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Federal health officials Thursday recommended that doctors
immediately stop using a vaccine recently recommended for all
infants to protect against rotavirus, the most common cause of
severe diarrhea in infants and young children.
</P>
<P>
   The federal Centers for Disease Control and Prevention said it
took the extraordinary action because a program that monitors
vaccine side-effects suggested a link between the drug, licensed
last year, and 20 cases of a painful blockage of the bowel called
intussusception. The disease, which can in rare cases be fatal,
affects an estimated 3.5 million children in the United States a
year.
</P>
<P>
   American Home Products Corp. told Reuters Thursday that it had
temporarily suspended shipments of vaccine, RotaShield, which is
made by a subsidiary, Wyeth-Ayerst of St. Davids, Pa. American Home
Products also said it had sent letters to doctors informing them of
the CDC report.
</P>
<P>
   Although there is no conclusive evidence that the vaccine causes
the bowel condition, CDC officials said the data are so strongly
suggestive of a link that they considered it prudent to advise
halting rotavirus vaccinations at least until November, by which
time a new study of the vaccine will be completed.
</P>
<P>
   ``No one should now be giving rotavirus vaccine to anyone,''
said Barbara Reynolds, a spokeswoman for the centers.
</P>
<P>
   The CDC has no enforcement power, and its call for a suspension
is only a recommendation. But doctors generally follow such
warnings.
</P>
<P>
   The vaccine was developed at the National Institutes of Health.
One million infants have received the vaccine, Douglas Petkus, a
spokesman for Wyeth-Ayerst, said Thursday. He said the company was
cooperating with the federal officials looking into the vaccine.
</P>
<P>
   Rotavirus vaccine is injected three times: at 2, 4 and 6 months
of age. Infants who have already received one or two shots should
not receive another, CDC officials said.
</P>
<P>
   The Food and Drug Administration licensed the product on Aug.
31, 1998, as the first vaccine against rotavirus, which is said to
be the biggest diarrheal killer of children around the world.
</P>
<P>
   Cases of bowel obstruction were noted in the experimental trials
that were required for the vaccine to be approved, but not in
unusual numbers. As part of the approval, the FDA required further
studies to monitor the incidence of blockages among the infants who
received the vaccine. The CDC used information from those studies
in deciding to recommend a halt to the rotavirus vaccinations.
</P>
<P>
   Officials at the CDC said they hoped to better understand how
much risk is posed by the vaccine through a study the agency, based
in Atlanta, has undertaken with health officials in 15 states.
</P>
<P>
   ``The vaccine is still licensed by the Food and Drug
Administration,'' Dr. Melinda Wharton, a CDC epidemiologist and
expert on childhood vaccines, noted in an interview. ``It is a
highly effective vaccine, and we don't want to take this disease
prevention tool away from practitioners in the United States unless
there is a real good reason to do that.''
</P>
<P>
   The vaccine has also been approved for use in most European
countries but has not been marketed there because Wyeth-Ayerst
lacked a sufficient supply, Petkus said. He said the company would
now postpone marketing the vaccine there until the risk was
clarified.
</P>
<P>
   Intussusception is rare and of unknown cause, although some
studies have hinted at a link to other viruses. The condition
results when a portion of bowel slides inward, like a telescope,
into another part of the bowel. In severe cases, a previously
healthy infant suddenly screams in paroxysms of pain.
</P>
<P>
   Other symptoms include persistent vomiting and a bowel movement
that contains blood or appears black. A doctor often can feel a
knot from the telescoped bowel and make a tentative diagnosis.
Confirmation comes from giving a child a barium enema and then
taking X-rays of the region.
</P>
<P>
   In some cases the enema itself can straighten out the telescoped
bowel. But in others, surgery is required. Of the first 15 cases
investigated, eight infants underwent surgery to repair the bowel.
</P>
<P>
   Parents should immediately call a doctor if a child develops
symptoms of the disease, CDC officials said. The agency also
alerted doctors to consider the possibility of bowel obstruction in
an infant who has recently received rotavirus vaccination.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Concern about the rotavirus vaccine arose about four weeks ago,
when an epidemiologist noticed an unusual number of intussusception
cases in seven states, Dr. Wharton said.
</P>
<P>
   The reports came from doctors, Wyeth-Ayerst and parents. After
sorting out duplicate reports and confirming that the cases were
intussusception, a CDC team began to see a consistent pattern in
the timing of the bowel condition in relation to the vaccination,
Dr. Wharton said. The bowel condition seems to develop about one to
three weeks after the vaccination is given.
</P>
<P>
   Two other reports also stirred concern, one from officials of
the Minnesota Health Department, the other from doctors at Northern
California Kaiser Permanente who are conducting a post-licensing
safety study for Wyeth-Ayerst, Dr. Wharton said. Those reports also
suggested an increased risk of bowel blockages.
</P>
<P>
   The CDC then joined with health officials in 15 states to
undertake a study involving more than 2,000 infants. The study is
expected to be completed by October, when a committee on
immunizations that advises the CDC holds its next regular meeting.
</P>
<P>
   The advice to suspend use of the vaccine until November reflects
the seasonal nature of rotavirus infection, which usually occurs in
the winter and spring. Each year, rotavirus sends 50,000 American
children to the hospital and kills 20.
</P>
<P>
   The withdrawal of the RotaShield vaccine is the latest in a
string of misfortunes for Wyeth-Ayerst and American Home Products.
The company, the subject of two failed merger attempts last year,
recently pulled several other of its drugs from the market after
health concerns were raised. And last month it announced that its
second-quarter earnings would not meet analysts' expectations.
</P>
<P>
   It was unclear how investors would react, given that American
Home Products made its announcement about the vaccine after the New
York Stock Exchange had closed Thursday. Shares of American Home
Products, which is based in Madison, N.J., closed Thursday at
$54.875, down 12.5 cents.
</P>
</TEXT>
