A1979 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SERIAL-KILLER-HNS &LR;      07-15 1266
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SERIAL-KILLER-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SUSPECT'S FAMILY SAYS LAWMEN TRICKED THEM 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By STEVE BREWER 
and MARIA LUISA PEREZ 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ The mother, sister and brother of accused serial
killer Angel Maturino Resendez said Thursday that U.S. lawmen
``betrayed'' them because they thought there was an understanding
that he would not face the death penalty in Texas if he
surrendered.
</P>
<P>
   But the written agreement that led to the surrender says nothing
about capital punishment, and even Mexican government officials
were dubious of Maturino Resendez's claim that he thought he would
not face the death penalty if he surrendered on Texas soil.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were upset and crying,'' said Allen Tanner, who
represents Maturino Resendez, 39, and talked with his family
members before they visited him in jail. ``They feel like they have
been betrayed. They're going to the Mexican Consulate and will try
to convince them to help convince the district attorney's office
not to seek the death penalty.''
</P>
<P>
   Previously known as Rafael Resendez-Ramirez, he told a judge
Wednesday that his real name is Angel Maturino Resendez.
</P>
<P>
   Family members helped broker the deal with Texas Rangers that
led to Maturino Resendez's surrender Tuesday in El Paso. He is
charged in Harris County with the burglary of the home of Dr.
Claudia Benton, but is expected to be charged soon with her murder.
</P>
<P>
   The rail-riding fugitive has been charged with one murder in
Hughes Springs, Texas, is a suspect in five others in the state,
including two in Harris County, and has also been linked to
killings in Illinois and Kentucky.
</P>
<P>
   Tanner and his co-counsel, Rudy Duarte, met Thursday with
Maturino Resendez's brother, Florentino Resendez, a pastor; Manuela
Maturino Resendez, the sister credited with helping to negotiate
his surrender; and his mother, Virginia Resendez Ramirez.
</P>
<P>
   Tanner said all three think they were tricked into convincing
Maturino Resendez to surrender.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were totally convinced he would be treated `humanely' and
they don't think that includes the death penalty,'' Tanner said.
</P>
<P>
   But a copy of the written agreement shown to the family does not
include the word `humanely' or mention capital punishment.
</P>
<P>
   The two-paragraph document, which was faxed to the Texas Rangers
who were dealing with the family, mentions only that Maturino
Resendez can have two visitors at a time while in jail and will be
given a psychological exam. It is signed by Harris County District
Attorney John B. Holmes Jr., dated July 12 and is conditioned on
his surrender to Texas authorities within 72 hours.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier Thursday, the 5-foot-7 Maturino Resendez appeared
briefly before James V. Garrett Jr., a senior criminal law hearing
officer, who advised him that the 1963 Vienna Convention gave him
the right to contact Mexican authorities about his case.
</P>
<P>
   Officials later confirmed that Maturino Resendez had been
advised of that right while in El Paso, but lead prosecutor Devon
Anderson said she wanted to make sure it was on the record.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to cross every `t' and dot every `i' with this guy,''
Anderson said.
</P>
<P>
   Maturino Resendez remained silent while Garrett told him of the
right, and he signed a form acknowledging it. He reportedly added a
small star alongside his signature.
</P>
<P>
   Rodulfo Figueroa, the Mexican Consul General in Houston, said
Thursday they had not heard from or contacted Maturino Resendez.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was asked in El Paso, Texas, if he wanted to contact the
Consulate there and he gave a negative answer,'' Figueroa said.
``This was confirmed to me by Armando Ortiz Rocha, the Consul
General in that city.''
</P>
<P>
   Figueroa said consulates do not generally intervene in the U.S.
legal system unless the defendant asks for help, which can take
several forms.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes the lawyers call us asking for help to bring
witness, family or friends from Mexico,'' Figueroa said. ``Other
times they just need some documents. It is up to the defense to
establish which kind of help would they ask from the Consulate.''
</P>
<P>
   Tanner said he hopes that Mexico will present legal or
diplomatic arguments to help Maturino Resendez
</P>
<P>
   Figueroa said Mexico has stated many times that it does not
agree with the death penalty but respects the laws of the United
States.
</P>
<P>
   But Figueroa said, ``In different times, each time an execution
is imminent, Mexico has expressed its disagreement with the death
penalty. But the United States law is the one that rules here.''
</P>
<P>
   Figueroa also expressed disbelief that Maturino Resendez did not
know he could be exposed to the death penalty if convicted in
Texas.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody knows that one of the consequences, when a capital
murder is proved, is that the suspect can receive the death
penalty,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Figueroa said he didn't know why Maturino Resendez surrendered
on U.S. soil, and he declined to speculate about what kind of legal
dilemma could have developed if he had been captured or surrendered
in Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, Maturino Resendez was charged with capital murder
in Cass County for the October slaying of Leafie Mason in the East
Texas town of Hughes Springs.
</P>
<P>
   Harris County is holding him on the Dec. 17 burglary of the West
University Place home of Benton, who was stabbed, raped and beaten
to death. West University is an affluent enclave of Houston.
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors are not going to charge him with capital murder in
that case until they receive DNA test results, though Anderson has
said that fingerprints have already placed him at at the scene.
</P>
<P>
   The DNA tests could also link Maturino Resendez to another
Harris County murder _ that of Noemi Dominguez, 26, who was killed
in her Houston home in June. Prosecutors could also file capital
murder charges in that case, but the evidence is more likely to be
used in the punishment phase of a trial for Benton's death,
assuming there's a conviction.
</P>
<P>
   Harris County sends more killers to death row than any other
county in the nation.
</P>
<P>
   According to the Texas prison system, there are now 468 people
on death row _ 460 men and eight women. Of those, 143 _ 140 men and
three women _ were convicted in Harris County.
</P>
<P>
   There are 165 men white men on death row, five white females,
192 black males, three black females, 99 Hispanic males, including
13 Mexican nationals, and four who list their origins as ``other,''
officials say.
</P>
<P>
   Since capital punishment was declared constitutional again in
1976, Texas has executed 180 people, more than any other state,
said prison spokesman Larry Fitzgerald. Most of those were from
Harris County, which has sent more killers to death row than any
state, except, of course, Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Harris County Sheriff Tommy Thomas said jailers have given
Maturino Resendez a Bible to replace the one that was taken away
when he was booked.
</P>
<P>
   Thomas said Maturino Resendez was immediately provided with a
Bible from the jail when he asked for one and that it was standard
procedure to take an inmate's possessions at booking.
</P>
<P>
   Maturino Resendez could have gotten his own Bible back if it had
been checked and he had asked for it.
</P>
<P>
   The defendant is currently in what's called ``administrative
segregation'' or ``lockdown.'' When he's not in court, he is in a
cell by himself 23 hours a day and is watched constantly by a
jailer.
</P>
<P>
   For one hour each day, he is allowed out to exercise under
supervision, Thomas said. Constant supervision will continue at
least until a psychological evaluation on him is complete.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
