<HEADER>
A1980 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBO-UMPIRES-NYT &LR;      07-15 1040
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-UMPIRES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UMPIRES CALCULATE THEIR RISK, AND SAY BASEBALL'S IS BIGGER  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By MURRAY CHASS    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ They saw a fight coming and decided that they, and
not their employers, would pick the time and place to start it. Now
baseball's major league umpires, whose letters of resignation,
effective Sept. 2, were sent by fax to the league offices Thursday,
will wait to learn if they have taken too great a risk.
</P>
<P>
   ``I live in Orlando,'' Rocky Roe, an American League umpire,
said Thursday in St. Petersburg, Fla., before the Mets-Devil Rays
game. ``There's always the possibility I could be at Disney World
looking for a job. Sure, there's an inherent risk.''
</P>
<P>
   Major League Baseball officials were silent Thursday on the
umpires' unexpected action, saying only that they were reviewing
the situation. But some are known to welcome the resignations,
because they feel they would be able to start over with new umpires
and regain the control they feel they have lost.
</P>
<P>
   Like Roe, Richie Phillips, head of the umpires union,
acknowledged the risk in the umpires' action. But, he said, if
baseball hired replacement umpires, it would be taking a much
bigger risk.
</P>
<P>
   ``They risk having 25 years of inferior umpiring ahead of
them,'' Phillips said in a telephone interview, ``in a game in
which they will be presenting a very, very watered down product.
That's a real risk.''
</P>
<P>
   The labor agreement between the umpires and the National and
American leagues expires Dec. 31. Negotiations for a new deal were
going to be confrontational because the two sides have been headed
for a fight for more than a year, and the tension has been
especially high since the beginning of this year. The fight is just
starting earlier than expected.
</P>
<P>
   The umpires, who are barred by the labor contract from striking,
decided to adopt the resignation strategy because they will receive
$15.5 million in termination pay. The severance ranges from
$150,000 for a 10-year umpire to $400,000 for one who has 20 or
more years in the majors.
</P>
<P>
   About a dozen and a half umpires out of the 66-member union do
not qualify for severance, but those who do have agreed to share a
percentage of their termination pay with the younger umpires.
Phillips said resignation letters of 63 umpires were faxed
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   The umpires acted before they could be acted upon. They believed
management planned to try to induce lower-rated umpires to leave,
telling them they could resign and receive severance or be fired
and get nothing. Rather than have severance used as a weapon
against them, the umpires opted to have it work for them.
</P>
<P>
   In that way, the fight is economic. But it is also about
respect. ``A lot of times we feel that we're not appreciated,''
said Roe, a 20-year veteran.
</P>
<P>
   The umpires chose a resignation date seven weeks away, figuring
there would be time for the two sides to achieve an agreement that
would prompt them to rescind their resignations.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hopefully,'' Roe said, ``the parties will be able to get
together and negotiate in good faith and get a deal done.''
</P>
<P>
   The players pursued a similar strategy in 1994, figuring the
owners would rush to an agreement to salvage the post-season. But
the owners, for the first time, held firm, then congratulated
themselves on their ability to do that as the World Series was
canceled.
</P>
<P>
   In previous work stoppages involving umpires, the leagues hired
replacements, but they turned out to be inadequate and prompted
players and fans alike to clamor for the return of the regular
umpires. Fans at various parks booed umpires when they walked onto
the field last night, but Phillips recalled different scenes.
</P>
<P>
   ``What Bud Selig and his errand boys don't understand,'' the
Philadelphia lawyer said, referring to the commissioner, ``is that
in 1979, when the umpires returned May 19, they received standing
ovations at every park in America. In 1984, in San Diego, when they
returned for the fifth game of the Padres-Cubs series, the umpires
got a standing ovation. After the 1995 lockout, upon their return,
they received standing ovations.''
</P>
<P>
   But a different dynamic could come into play this time. While
the umpires are gambling that the major leagues cannot do without
them, management could decide to let them resign, then go out and
hire permanent replacements. By hiring umpires on a permanent
basis, they may be able to recruit more capable men than they have
been able to lure for previous, temporary work stoppages.
</P>
<P>
   Even some of the major league umpires could change their minds
if they are faced with permanent loss of their jobs, which,
including a $25,000 year-end bonus, pay from $95,000 to $262,500.
</P>
<P>
   Not all of the union umpires are enamored of Phillips'
leadership. Last spring about a dozen umpires approached Ron
Shapiro, a noted player agent, and asked if he would be interested
in representing the umpires. They told him they were concerned with
Phillips' confrontational stance. But nothing developed, and an
overwhelming majority of umpires continued to support Phillips,
voting him a new five-year contract. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The possibility of the commissioner's office hiring an entirely
new crew of umpires contains an unusual element. New umpires would
be represented by the same bargaining unit, the Major League
Umpires Association. The old members of the union would go away,
but not the union. The head of the union is Phillips, and he would
continue under his five-year contract.
</P>
<P>
   Asked Thursday what he thought would happen next, Phillips said,
``I expect that in keeping with their attitude of smugness and
typical management arrogance, they will start recruiting their
amateur umpire force in order to intimidate the umpires.''
</P>
<P>
   One large group of umpires may not be available. With 220 of the
228 minor league umpires voting for it and the other 8 abstaining,
a new union of minor league umpires has been formed. It has yet to
be recognized by the minor league group that hires umpires, but the
umpires are represented by Phillips and he said they support the
major league umpires.
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, the lure of lucrative major league jobs, if
offered, could be difficult to resist.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
