<HEADER>
A1982 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-INSURANCE-FRAUD-NYT &LR;      07-15 0671
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INSURANCE-FRAUD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AUTHORITIES SAY INSURANCE SUSPECT MAY BE IN ITALY 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Calif., Conn., N.J.)  (rk) 
 By JOSEPH KAHN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Federal authorities on the trail of suspected insurance swindler
Martin R. Frankel have tracked wire transfers of nearly half a
million dollars to Rome and are focusing on the possibility that he
is hiding in Italy, a country integral to his complex financial
dealings.
</P>
<P>
   Several FBI agents, including Joseph P. Dooley, the lead agent
tracking Frankel, have flown to Italy in recent days in what one
person interviewed by the FBI called ``hot pursuit'' of the man
wanted for absconding with several hundred million dollars he
managed on behalf of Southern insurance companies.
</P>
<P>
   Authorities have also followed up leads suggesting that Frankel
might have joined a Catholic monastery in Assisi, the home of the
saint after whom he named a charitable foundation involved in his
suspected fraud. Officials at the monastery in Assisi said in
recent interviews that no one matching Frankel's description had
become a monk.
</P>
<P>
   Word of Frankel's likely whereabouts adds a fresh dash of the
unexpected to the case. Though notes rescued from smoldering
documents at his home in Greenwich, Conn., suggested that Frankel
had studied countries from which the United States might have
difficulty extraditing him, including Brazil, he appears to have
traveled to a country where he would seem to be decidedly insecure.
</P>
<P>
   Experts in international crime consider it highly unlikely that
Italy would shelter Frankel from charges he faces in the United
States, and the FBI has worked closely in the past with Italian law
enforcement authorities.
</P>
<P>
   Yet he and an entourage that associates say included several
women who lived in his Greenwich homes have eluded police, at least
so far. There are suggestions he has a financial cushion that could
allow him to live in hiding in luxury.
</P>
<P>
   As previously reported, Frankel purchased $10 million in
diamonds just before fleeing the United States. And although the
FBI has frozen many of Frankel's bank accounts around the world, he
almost certainly has access to cash as well.
</P>
<P>
   The wholesale dealer who arranged Frankel's huge last-minute
diamond purchase said Thursday that he had wired $455,000 to an
Italian bank account in the name of a woman who is said to be
traveling with Frankel. It could not be learned whether Frankel had
withdrawn the money before American authorities found out about the
payment last month.
</P>
<P>
   Robert A. Wiener of the Worldwide Diamond Co., which arranged
the sale, said the money had been withheld from the $10 million
Frankel paid for diamonds to settle California sales taxes. But
because the diamonds were delivered to Frankel's representatives at
an airport in New Jersey, the California tax withholding was
unnecessary and needed to be refunded, Wiener said.
</P>
<P>
   On May 13, well after Frankel is thought to have fled the
country, he telephoned Richard Teel, another merchant involved in
the diamond sale, to inquire about the refund. Frankel phoned again
on May 21. This time, he instructed the diamond dealers to wire the
funds to an account at Rome's Banca Popolare di Brescia. The
transfer was made May 21, Wiener said. That was two weeks after
firefighters discovered documents ablaze at Frankel's mansion.
</P>
<P>
   Wiener said at the time that he had no knowledge of Frankel's
whereabouts. Teel's lawyer said his client also did not know at the
time that Frankel had left the country.
</P>
<P>
   Frankel has friends in Rome. Just before leaving the United
States, he wired $3 million to an account controlled by Fausto
Fausti, an Italian business consultant who had earlier helped
Frankel try to recruit a Catholic charity as a partner for
Frankel's business dealings. The transfer to Fausti's account was
mentioned in an affidavit prepared by the Internal Revenue Service,
according to people who have seen the affidavit.
</P>
<P>
   Fausti could not be reached for comment.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
