<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SHEEN-AWARD16-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Actor Martin Sheen to accept peace award
 &HT;    By Kathy Whyde Jesse
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ Actor and Dayton native Martin Sheen will receive
the 1999 Pope Paul VI Teacher of Peace Award from Pax Christi USA,
a national Catholic peace movement.
</P>
<P>
   Sheen, 58, who has almost made a second career of advocating for
such causes as environmentalism and the homeless, and against
capital punishment, oppression in Central America and the nuclear
arms race, will receive the award today in Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   Nancy Small, Pax Christi USA national coordinator, said Sheen
``is an actor who integrates his faith and deep convictions with
his life's work.''
</P>
<P>
   He was nominated by several Pax Christi members, including John
Dear, executive director of the Fellowship of Reconciliation, an
interfaith organization committed to seeking peace and justice.
Dear called Sheen ``a teacher of peace to the whole mainstream
culture.''
</P>
<P>
   Sheen, a 1958 graduate of Chaminade High School, is the first
actor to win the award. Past winners have included Dorothy Day,
co-founder of the Catholic Workers, a social reform organization;
author Joan Chittester; Dom Helder Camara, a Brazilian bishop;
Helen Prejean, author of ``Dead Man Walking,'' and Maura Clarke,
Ita Ford, Dorothy Kazel and Jean Donovan, the three nuns and a
social worker who were murdered in 1980 while working with the poor
in El Salvador.
</P>
<P>
   Sheen is perhaps best known for his role as the narrator in the
war film ``Apocalypse Now,'' as well as for roles in ``Gandhi'' and
``Wall Street.''
</P>
<P>
   More recently, he narrated ``An Act of Conscience,'' a
documentary about Randy Kehler and Betsy Corner, who refused to pay
federal income taxes as a protest against government military
spending.
</P>
<P>
   He will star this fall in the NBC television drama ``The West
Wing,'' about the inner workings of the White House Oval Office.
</P>
<P>
   Sheen, born Ramon Estevez, was one of 10 children born to
Francisco Estevez, a Spanish immigrant, and Mary Ann Phelan, an
Irish immigrant. He left Dayton for an acting career in New York
after high school graduation.
</P>
<P>
   Although he was raised Roman Catholic, he said in a 1995
National Press Club speech that as a young adult, he let his
``Catholic faith kind of slide.'' He didn't rediscover it, he said,
until he was about 40, when he traveled to India and met Mother
Teresa while filming ``Gandhi.''
</P>
<P>
   That experience, he said, led him to ``the real faith of
activism.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
