A1984 &Cx1f; taf-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-COAL-POLLUTION-NYT &LR;      07-15 0790
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COAL-POLLUTION-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EPA ACCUSES SOME UTILITIES OF VIOLATING RULES ON COAL USAGE  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ohio)   By MATTHEW L. WALD   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The Environmental Protection Agency has found that
several electric companies have violated the terms under which
their coal plants were ``grandfathered'' under the Clean Air Act,
by making major changes to produce more power without installing
the required pollution controls, according to federal officials.
</P>
<P>
   Inspectors have completed field audits of six plants, and were
preparing to complete work on 22 more, the officials said. No
action has been taken against the plants yet, as investigators
continue reviewing the data. The EPA could require the companies to
install equipment to control their emissions and fine them.
</P>
<P>
   ``They have been making what we believe are major capital
improvements, not routine maintenance,'' said one federal official,
who asked not to be further identified because the investigation is
still under way. The improvements included new boilers, burners,
and blowers for moving coal, all of higher capacity than the old
ones. In some cases, the official said, the ability of the plants
to produce power had been increased ``dramatically.''
</P>
<P>
   The Clean Air Act set strict pollution standards for new sources
but much looser ones for existing power plants and factories. Under
the grandfather clause, the old sources could continue to operate
with minor improvements as long as their owners did not undertake
major renovations.
</P>
<P>
   Demand for power from coal-fired plants has risen in the last
few years, as de-regulation of the utility industry has allowed
electric companies with old, paid-for plants consuming cheap fuel
to sell their electricity profitably across state lines, into
higher-priced eastern markets.
</P>
<P>
   But the nitrogen oxides they produce add to smog in the east,
according to the EPA and air pollution officials in the eastern
states. Smog, or ground-level ozone, is produced by the action of
sunlight on nitrogen oxides, which come from cars and power plants,
with hydrocarbons, which come from cars, oil refineries and other
sources.
</P>
<P>
   The allegations against the power companies, most of them in the
Ohio Valley, are only the latest dispute about the plants;
officials in Northeastern states have long complained that their
pollution travels hundreds of miles to create smog from Washington
to Boston.
</P>
<P>
   But people in the industry said that they were under a legal
obligation to keep their plants in top condition, and had done
nothing that would require stricter pollution controls.
</P>
<P>
   About 100 EPA investigators are looking at records and hardware
in the plants, according to federal officials, who say the EPA
first made its discovery by comparing computerized databases
assembled for other purposes. One database, created for the control
of the sulfur dioxide emissions that cause acid rain, shows power
generation and coal consumption. Another shows investments in new
equipment. Matching the two, investigators said they found evidence
of major improvements, the kind that should have required stricter
pollution controls.
</P>
<P>
   But Henry V. Nickel, a lawyer who represents the Utility Air
Regulatory Group, an industry coalition, said, ``They're looking at
things that everyone in industry has had to do, to keep their
plants running.''
</P>
<P>
   Nickel said that in some cases the EPA had looked at production
in the year that work was done on a plant, and production in the
year after, and found an increase. But that, he said, was ``a
perfectly fulfilling prophecy,'' because, he said, ``when you shut
down a facility to do a repair project, it's going to operate less
in that year than in next year, when you don't have to shut down
for repairs.''
</P>
<P>
   Nickel said improvements that allowed a plant to produce more
kilowatt-hours from a fixed amount of fuel would not require better
pollution controls, because by definition, such improvements meant
a decline in pollution per unit of electricity produced.
</P>
<P>
   At American Electric Power, a coal-based utility that generates
and distributes power in seven states, Pat Hemlepp, a spokesman,
said, ``We've known for a long time that EPA has wanted to pursue
an emissions reduction strategy through enforcement initiatives.''
Hemlepp said his company's investments in its plants had been
obvious over the years. ``There's not much that electric utilities
do that's private,'' he said, because of regulatory requirements.
</P>
<P>
   In a filing with the Securities and Exchange Commission this
spring, American Electric Power said the EPA had requested
documents from the company related to its coal plant investments
and power output.
</P>
</TEXT>
