<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SWI-USCSWIM-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ON PATH TO GOLD?
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MATTHEW KREDELL  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Elite swimmers from around the country are
competing this weekend at the Janet Evans Invitational at USC's
McDonald's Swim Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   Among the top competitors is USC alumnus Lenny Krayzelburg, the
reigning world backstroke champion and American record-holder in
the 200-meter event.
</P>
<P>
   A favorite for the 2000 Olympics in Sydney, Krayzelburg, 23, is
setting his sights on besting his own meet record of 1:59.82 in the
200 backstroke set in 1997. The race starts at 5 p.m. today.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am used to training in this stadium and this weather,''
Krayzelburg said. ``I know what I need to do and have my own
strategy. I don't expect anyone else to be faster than two minutes,
and I think I can do a legitimate 1:58. On the other hand, I can't
control what other competitors do.''
</P>
<P>
   Krayzelburg is making a charge at the world record in the 200
backstroke. He has broken the American record three times in the
past two years, most recently lowering it to 1:56.95 at the U.S.
Swimming Championships at Long Island, N.Y., earlier this year. The
time was just 0.38 seconds off the world record set in 1991.
</P>
<P>
   Others are eager for a chance to see Krayzelburg further his
assault on the world record.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of people in the swimming community are excited to see
what Lenny will do at the Janet Evans Invitational after his
showing in the past year,'' said Paul Davidson, a coach for the
Conejo/Simi Aquatics Club who has swimmers competing at the meet.
</P>
<P>
   Krayzelburg doesn't expect to break the world record this
weekend, but it is definitely among his goals for the next few
months.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't train as hard prior to this event as we do for the
top events in the world,'' Krayzelburg said. ``The big competition
I am shooting for is the Pan Pacific Games in five weeks at Sydney,
Australia, the site of next year's Olympics.''
</P>
<P>
   Krayzelburg burst into national prominence by winning three gold
medals at the '97 Pan Pacifics. He went on to become the first man
in 10 years to sweep the 100- and 200-meter backstroke at the '98
World Championships in Perth, Australia, where he also won a silver
medal in the 400-meter medley relay.
</P>
<P>
   Born in Ukraine, Krayzelburg moved to the United States with his
family in 1989 in order to have a better life and more
opportunities. He became a U.S. citizen in 1995.
</P>
<P>
   Krayzelburg finished his stellar career at USC with the
fourth-fastest time in history in 200-yard backstroke at the NCAA
Championships in 1997. He graduated from USC last December with a
degree in finance.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to the 200-meter backstroke, Krayzelburg will
compete in four more events at the Janet Evans Invitational, today
in the 100 freestyle, Saturday in the 200 and 50 freestyle, and
Sunday in the 100 backstroke.
</P>
<P>
   The event also includes competition for juniors.
</P>
<P>
   Tickets can be purchased at McDonald's Swim Stadium. Prices
range from $2 to $5.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
