<HEADER>
A1994 &Cx1f; taf-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-EDIT-PATIENT-RIGHTS-N     07-15 0496
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-PATIENT-RIGHTS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: PATIENT RIGHTS AND WRONGS 
</HEADLINE>
   (af) 
c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times says in an editorial Friday, July 16: &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   With impressive but wrongheaded discipline, Senate Republicans
have rejected a series of attempts to protect the rights of
patients enrolled in managed-care health programs. Despite reams of
opinion surveys suggesting that the public wants reform in this
area, the Republicans chose to protect insurers, health maintenance
organizations and businesses at the expense of patients.
</P>
<P>
   After sweeping health-care legislation failed in 1994, the word
in Washington was that incremental reform might be possible. The
Clinton administration had some success with smaller steps. But
this week the Senate effortlessly swatted down a series of
incremental measures to prevent abuses by HMOs.
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday it rejected the right of patients to redress
grievances in court for denial of care. Earlier it rejected greater
access to specialists for patients and the right of doctors to
determine what is ``medically necessary'' for their patients. The
Senate could not even bring itself to expand basic protections from
the 48 million Americans in fancy ``self-insured'' health plans to
more than 100 million in employer-provided plans, state and local
government plans and plans for people who buy their own insurance.
</P>
<P>
   There is no mystery here. Campaign money is dictating medical
policy in the Senate. The political system, and especially the
Republican Party, is awash in money from the health-care industry.
As President Clinton said Thursday, GOP senators could not support
the patients' bill of rights because ``the health insurers won't
let them do it.''
</P>
<P>
   There are, of course, legitimate concerns about the costs of
reform. But these basic protections can be enacted without pushing
up health insurance premiums, as opponents charge. Another empty
Republican point is the insistence that these protections are best
regulated by the states. Health care _ like civil rights and
environmental protection _ is one of those areas where Americans
want broad, consistent national policy.
</P>
<P>
   What the Senate did this week was weaken legislation even beyond
what is being considered in the House, where many Republican
members say they plan to support some patient protections,
including the right to sue health maintenance organizations. Those
in the health-care industry who support these protections should
now speak up, especially the doctors in the American Medical
Association, who have already begun lobbying for some of these
provisions and who recently announced plans to form unions to
counterbalance the power of HMOs.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans in the House seem to understand better than their
Senate colleagues that the issue of health care will be hot in
2000. By then, campaign money from the industry may not be enough
to protect Republicans from the public desire for relief from HMO
abuses. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-15-99 2224EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990715.0478 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-15 22:24 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1996 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TEN-DAVISCUP-HNS &LR;      07-15 1728
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEN-DAVISCUP-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JODY GOLDSTEIN  
 c. 1999, Houston Chronicle  
BOSTON _ It was conceived in the United States in 1900 as a way to
bring together countries to enjoy the sport. Now, the Davis Cup is
being credited with the resurgence of interest in men's tennis in
this country.
<TEXT>
<P>
   U.S. Davis Cup ace Jim Courier breathed life into a competition
that no longer held the interest of many of the top Americans. Pete
Sampras had opted out for personal reasons. Andre Agassi denounced
the team for political reasons. And Michael Chang had played
sparingly.
</P>
<P>
   But Courier, a member of 13 teams, all victorious, scratched and
clawed for more than eight hours to help lead a second-tier U.S.
squad past Britain's best to force a quarterfinal showdown against
Australia. Courier outlasted Tim Henman, then Greg Rusedski to keep
alive the U.S. team's hopes of returning the Cup to its native
shores.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was one of the best Davis Cup moments I've seen in a long
time,'' said Cup veteran John McEnroe. ``When I saw Jim win the
fifth match and he nodded for his teammates to come out and they
got in that circle and started dancing, that's when I really missed
it.''
</P>
<P>
   That likely was what Dwight Filley Davis envisioned when he
created the competition in 1900. A 21-year-old recent Harvard
graduate and a leading American player who later would become
President Calvin Coolidge's secretary of war, Davis envisioned a
yearly tournament that would advance friendship and good will
internationally as the men traveled to one another's countries for
matches.
</P>
<P>
   That first tournament, which consisted solely of the United
States and Great Britain, was held at the Longwood Cricket Club in
Boston, site of today's Davis Cup quarterfinal between the United
States and Australia. The U.S. won that first Davis Cup 3-0.
</P>
<P>
   The United States would go on to win 30 more Davis Cups, more
than any other nation. Australia is second with 26. In all, 100
countries have participated but only nine have won.
</P>
<P>
   The Davis Cup competition included only the two countries until
1904, when Belgium, Austria and France joined. Great Britain
emerged victorious, sweeping Belgium 5-0.
</P>
<P>
   The United States played its first Davis Cup matches on foreign
soil the following year, defeating France and Australasia
(Australia and New Zealand) at Queen's Club in London. The United
States won the right to play Britain in the challenge round but
lost 5-0 at Wimbledon.
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't until 1913 that the trophy returned to America for the
first time since 1902. Richard Norris Williams, a survivor of the
sinking of the Titanic the year before, was the star of the U.S.
team that beat Britain 3-2. Williams, whose father died in the
disaster, registered a 6-1 record in singles in the four victories
by the U.S. team.
</P>
<P>
   By the next year, the event had become so popular that 12,000
fans poured into the West Side Tennis Club in Forest Hills, N.Y.,
to watch the final between the United States and Australasia.The
United States was narrowly defeated 3-2. It would be the last Davis
Cup match until 1919 because of World War I.
</P>
<P>
   Bill Tilden of the United States popularized the competition in
the 1920s. With a flashy style and solid results, Tilden helped
lead his team to victories over France, Britain and Australasia
with a 7-0 mark in 1920. He played another 10 years, accumulating
25 singles wins. The United States won seven consecutive trophies
beginning with his rookie campaign. He holds the U.S. record for
most appearances in a final with a 21-7 record.
</P>
<P>
   That streak was halted in 1927 by the Four Musketeers _ the
French team of Rene Lacoste, Jean Borotra, Henri Cochet and Jacques
Brugnon. The United States and France forged a rivalry through six
consecutive challenge rounds, which they split.
</P>
<P>
   The next great U.S. Davis Cup figure was Don Budge, who in 1937
helped lead the United States to its first Davis Cup victory since
1926. Budge and Gottfried von Cramm of Germany played one of the
most dramatic matches in the event's history. According to legend,
the phone rang in the locker room before the match. Von Cramm was
called to find Adolf Hitler on the other end offering words of
encouragement. And though he led Budge 4-1 in a decisive fifth set,
the American pulled it out.
</P>
<P>
   Budge played Davis Cup for only four years but achieved a 25-4
record in 11 ties and twice helped lead the United States to the
trophy.
</P>
<P>
   Nearly every great player has participated at one time. Nikki
Pietrangeli of Italy holds the honor of being the most prolific
player of all time, having participated in the most Davis Cup
matches (164) and the most Cup ties (66). He led Italy to its only
Davis Cup (over Chile) in 1976.
</P>
<P>
   The 1950s and '60s belonged to Australia, which won the Davis
Cup 15 times between 1950 and 1967 with such talented players as
Frank Sedgman, Ken McGregor, Mervyn Rose, Neale Fraser, Mal
Anderson, Ashley Cooper, Rod Laver, John Newcombe, Tony Roche, Fred
Stolle and John Alexander. Newcombe has remained involved as the
current captain for Australia.
</P>
<P>
   In 1968, Davis Cup opened itself to registered professionals but
not contract pros, who signed guaranteed contracts with independent
promoters. The competition was opened to everyone in 1973, which
became the decade that McEnroe began asserting his Davis Cup
dominance.
</P>
<P>
   As a 19-year-old rookie in 1978, McEnroe helped the United
States to its 25th Davis Cup title. McEnroe lost only 10 games in
his two singles matches over John Lloyd and Chris Mottram as the
U.S. team beat Britain 4-1 in the final.
</P>
<P>
   McEnroe didn't lose a set in Davis Cup singles or doubles until
1980 and went on to become the most successful American Davis Cup
player ever, setting U.S. records for years on the team (12), team
matches (30), singles matches (49), singles victories (41), total
matches (69) and total wins (59).
</P>
<P>
   ``This is part of being a team,'' McEnroe said. ``It's the only
chance, aside from doubles, when we have the chance to root for the
other guy and be part of a team. It's important in different ways.
You can't compare it. It's an honor and responsibility to play
Davis Cup.''
</P>
<P>
   He was joined by Connors in 1984, a pairing that gave the
Americans the Nos. 1 and 2 players in the world. But the United
States was shocked by Sweden 4-1.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've played under a lot of circumstances,'' Connors said.
``You play for yourself, but you've got 200 million people behind
you when the United States creeps into it.''
</P>
<P>
   McEnroe has been involved in some of the Cup's most memorable
matches. He and Mats Wilander were locked in a 6-hour, 32-minute
quarterfinal duel in 1982, the longest in Davis Cup history.
McEnroe emerged victorious 9-7, 6-2, 15-17, 3-6, 8-6 to clinch the
3-2 win over Sweden.
</P>
<P>
   One of the best U.S. victories of recent Davis Cup action was in
1992 when the United States fielded its ``Dream Team'' of then-No.
1 Courier, Wimbledon champion Agassi, Sampras and McEnroe. Together
they knocked off Sweden 4-1 in the semis, then defeated Switzerland
3-1 in the final.
</P>
<P>
   ``Davis Cup is the perfect platform for the better competitors
to shine,'' Agassi said. ``The intensity is there, so in-your-face.
I go in like it's the end of the world. It's a lot more dramatic
winning or losing when your country is counting on you than when
the fans are counting on you and yourself is counting on you. What
a platform that is to show what you're made of.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite all his great moments, which include five of the United
States' 31 victories, that 1992 tie is the one McEnroe is most
proud of.
</P>
<P>
   ``The '92 tie where I played just doubles,'' he said. ``Being
part of what I consider to be a legendary team with Pete, Andre and
Jim, and going through the divorce (from former wife Tatum O'Neal),
I was feeling emotionally not really capable of playing. I think
perhaps that that could be maybe my greatest emotional moment, to
be able to be part of that squad.''
</P>
<P>
   The United States has won only once since (1995), edging Russia
3-2 in an emotional final in which Sampras was dramatically dragged
off the court after beating Andrei Chesnokov, suffering severe
cramps. He returned the next day to play doubles and won a second
singles match.
</P>
<P>
   Since then, the Americans have struggled. A team of Todd Martin,
MaliVai Washington and Chang lost to the Czechs in '96. Sampras
tore a calf muscle, then watched his teammates get swept by Sweden
in '97. Last year, it was Italy pulling off the stunner, beating
the Americans 4-1 in the semifinals.
</P>
<P>
   ``The emotional roller coaster we ride during Davis Cup is a
little bigger than the average roller coaster,'' Martin said. ``I
realize now how much more important the Davis Cup is than the other
tournaments we play.''
</P>
<P>
   Sampras hasn't played Davis Cup since '97. Agassi split from the
team this year. And there have been rumblings the event would be
more attractive if played only every two years, a recommendation
recently vetoed by the International Tennis Federation.
</P>
<P>
   But just when attitudes seemingly were at an all-time low,
Courier's actions sparked patriotism and the Americans are ready to
wave their flags.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think from my perspective as Davis Cup captain and director
of coaching for the USTA, we have to keep the momentum going,''
American captain Tom Gullikson said. ``I think it's important for
us to win this tie and keep the tennis momentum in this country
going.''
</P>
<P>
   Tickets for the quarterfinal tie sold out a record 81 minutes
after going on sale.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think that the thing that's kind of gratifying is that you
guys (the media) are here, and it's Monday. And that hasn't
happened in a Davis Cup tie in America that I've ever been a part
of,'' Courier said. ``So that, for me, is a gratifying part.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Davis Cup is getting back to being a front-page story. I
think that's what makes it gratifying to me _ an event of this
stature is trying to get a little more recognition in America. I
played a small part in that, and that makes me sleep better.''
</P>
<P>
   Courier has played a big part in America's quest to return the
Davis Cup to its soil 99 years after Davis' dream became a reality.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Davis Cup and Grand Slams are the two reasons I get up
every morning and strap on my shoes and practice,'' Courier said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
