<SLUG> BC-18TH-VINE-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JAZZ MUSEUM TURNS TO INTERNET FOR PROMOTION AND SALES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID HAYES  
 c. 1997 The Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The 18th and Vine Authority plans to use the Internet to
generate cash for the American Jazz Museum and spread the word
about Kansas City jazz worldwide.
</P>
<P>
   The authority has hired an Overland Park, Kan., Internet company
to build an online storefront for the Jazz Museum's Swing Shop,
which sells jazz posters, museum souvenirs, and music by current
and past Kansas City jazz artists.
</P>
<P>
   NetSales, which operates online storefronts for more than 1,500
businesses worldwide, will design an e-commerce Web site for the
museum and handle transactions and delivery.
</P>
<P>
   The authority's board hopes the online store will be the first
step in establishing the museum's Web site as a central site for
jazz online.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some of the biggest, most enduring names in jazz got their
start or made their mark in Kansas City, and the American Jazz
Museum highlights our area's illustrious contributions to the art
form,'' said Emanuel Cleaver, chairman of the 18th and Vine
Authority.
</P>
<P>
   The authority approved the contract with NetSales this week. The
store will be up and running within 90 days, said James E. Coleman,
the authority's chief financial officer.
</P>
<P>
   NetSales will design and serve as host for the commerce site for
a percentage of the sales. The museum's Web site can be reached
through www.kcmo.org.
</P>
<P>
   ``The reason the board was so excited by this is that it's not
costing us anything,'' Coleman said. ``This gives us a chance to
get into e-commerce for effectively no cost.''
</P>
<P>
   Cleaver said the deal would help the museum pay for itself.
</P>
<P>
   ``This represents a significant step toward self-sufficiency
while also helping to promote the historic 18th and Vine District
to an international audience of jazz aficionados,'' Cleaver said.
</P>
<P>
   Initially, the store will sell CDs of current Kansas City jazz
musicians and of past jazz masters, Coleman said. It also will sell
T-shirts, caps, jackets and other museum souvenirs.
</P>
<P>
   Eventually, Coleman said, the online store may be expanded to
include videos from past jazz performances and other jazz
memorabilia.
</P>
<P>
   The American Jazz Museum hopes to broadcast live performances
over the Internet from the museum's Blue Room.
</P>
<P>
   The museum and Swing Shop opened in September 1997, part of a
50,000-square-foot complex that features Kansas City jazz and
baseball heritage.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
