<SLUG> BC-NY-NIGERIA-SLAVE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHILD ABUSE INVESTIGATOR IN SLAVERY CASE FACED COMPLAINT IN 1988
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 By MICHAEL COOPER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ A New York City child-abuse investigator accused of
forcing a Nigerian girl into servitude and repeatedly beating her
was the subject of a 1988 complaint that she had neglected another
Nigerian girl living in her home, officials said on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   The investigator, Ifeoma Ezeonu Udogwu, and her husband, Prosper
Udogwu, were charged on Wednesday with keeping Beatrice Okezie, a
native of Nigeria who is now 23, in forced servitude in their Bronx
home for nine years and beating her. During most of that time, Ms.
Udogwu was a caseworker for the city's Administration for
Children's Services; she became a supervisor with the agency last
year.
</P>
<P>
   But as far back as August 1988 _ just a month after she began
working for the city _ Ms. Udogwu was named in a complaint for a
case of possible child abuse in her home, law enforcement officials
said. That complaint was phoned to a state child abuse line by fire
marshals who were investigating a fire believed to have been set in
her home by another Nigerian girl, said Chief Brian Dixon, a Fire
Department spokesman.
</P>
<P>
   The marshals were concerned that the girl, who was not charged
because she was a juvenile, was not properly supervised and had not
been enrolled in school, Dixon said.
</P>
<P>
   Investigators had said on Wednesday that the girl, who they said
was 11 or 12, had returned to Africa after being sexually assaulted
by Ms. Udogwu's brother, but they said Thursday that that account
is now unclear.
</P>
<P>
   Officials at the Administration for Children's Services said
Thursday that they were going through old paperwork in warehouses
to see if the neglect complaint against Ms. Udogwu was ever
forwarded to them and, if so, whether any action was taken on it.
The agency, which suspended Ms. Udogwu without pay after she was
indicted this week, is also preparing disciplinary proceedings
against her and is auditing the cases she handled.
</P>
<P>
   ``If these charges are true, it is about as outrageous a piece
of alleged conduct against any of our people as I've heard,'' said
Nicholas Scoppetta, the agency's Commissioner.
</P>
<P>
   The Udogwus are accused of luring Miss Okezie into the country
from Nigeria in 1989, when she was 13, by promising to send her to
trade school, only to force her to work as their unpaid, live-in
maid, according to a complaint filed on Wednesday in U.S. District
Court in Manhattan. Miss Okezie was beaten into submission and was
unable to leave because the Udogwus confiscated her passport and
other identification papers, the complaint says.
</P>
<P>
   Lawyers for the Udogwus deny the charges. Jerry Tritz, a lawyer
for Udogwu, said that his client brought Miss Okezie to America
because he was tricked into believing that she was his daughter by
a woman he had had an affair with. ``He found out that this was a
lie and terminated the relationship,'' he said. ``This is
payback.''
</P>
<P>
   During the time she is said to have lived with the Udogwus as an
indentured servant, Miss Okezie attended Evander Childs High School
in the Bronx. Margie Feinberg, a Board of Education spokeswoman,
said that her records indicate that Miss Okezie graduated in 1994
with an attendance record of better than 90 percent and grade
average of 81.5.
</P>
<P>
   Joel S. Cohen, a lawyer for Ms. Udogwu, said that Miss Okezie's
record at Evander Childs undermines some of the accusations against
his client. ``I think it completely belies the accusation in the
complaint,'' he said. ``You certainly don't get the impression that
she had enough freedom of movement to attend high school in the
complaint.''
</P>
<P>
   But Susan M. Beschta of Catholic Charities of the Archdiocese of
New York, who is one of several lawyers from a number of groups
representing Miss Okezie in a civil suit she had filed against the
Udogwus, said that the girl was simply too frightened to ask school
officials for help. ``She was too intimidated to talk to anybody,''
Ms. Beschta said. ``And as far as I know, nobody at the school
noticed anything.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
