<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AMC-STOCK-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DURWOOD'S STOCK IN AMC EVENTUALLY WILL BENEFIT CHARITY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JENNIFER MANN  
 c. 1997 The Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Any income from movie theater magnate Stan Durwood's stock in
AMC Entertainment Inc. will be used to fund charitable causes.
</P>
<P>
   Durwood, who died Wednesday at age 78, was co-chairman and chief
executive officer of the fourth-largest movie exhibition company in
the world. He owned a large majority of AMC's class B stock, which
has 10 votes for every one vote of common stock.
</P>
<P>
   Through his supervoting stock, Durwood controlled almost 70
percent of Kansas City-based AMC. The value of that stock is
unclear because the class B shares are not publicly traded.
</P>
<P>
   The stock will soon be transferred to a trust controlled by two
longtime lawyer friends, with the eventual beneficiary being the
Stanley H. Durwood Foundation, a charitable trust.
</P>
<P>
   While speculation has swirled for months that the company would
be sold upon Durwood's death, the way his estate is set up makes
that less likely, or at least much more difficult than previously
expected.
</P>
<P>
   In keeping with the company's succession plan, Peter Brown,
previously co-chairman of AMC with Durwood, on Thursday became
chairman and chief executive officer. Philip M. Singleton continues
as president and chief operating officer of American Multi-Cinema
Inc., a subsidiary that has responsibility for all AMC operations
worldwide.
</P>
<P>
   ``Stan's vision created the pre-eminent company in our
industry,'' Brown said. ``He prepared the company well for its
future, leaving a strong foundation for continued growth and
leadership.''
</P>
<P>
   Though not the largest movie exhibition company in the world,
AMC is one of the most highly regarded, mostly because of its large
number of megaplexes, which account for more than half of its 2,729
screens.
</P>
<P>
   Raymond F. Beagle Jr., one of the two trustees, said Durwood's
estate and succession plan had two purposes _ to create stability
for the company and its employees and to create stability for the
holders of 19.4 million shares of common stock.
</P>
<P>
   ``He didn't want the wonderful management team and the employees
to feel like the company was going to be sold out from under
them,'' said Beagle, a longtime friend of Durwood's.
</P>
<P>
   The other trustee is Charles J. Egan Jr., who is also a director
of the company.
</P>
<P>
   When it was disclosed in January 1997 that Durwood had cancer,
Wall Street started speculating that the company would be sold.
</P>
<P>
   Those rumored to be interested in the company are the investment
firms of Kohlberg Kravis Roberts &AMP; Co. and Hicks Muse Tate &AMP; Furst,
which owns Regal Cinemas Inc. Another name that's been mentioned is
Loews Cineplex Entertainment Corp., which is largely owned by the
Sony Corp.
</P>
<P>
   Spencer Wang, an analyst with Solomon Smith Barney in New York,
said several factors would make AMC an attractive takeover
candidate, including its large concentration of megaplexes.
</P>
<P>
   Wang also said Durwood had long been reluctant to raise ticket
prices.
</P>
<P>
   ``So somebody could come in and buy the company and immediately
jack up the ticket prices, and a lot of that flows to the bottom
line,'' Wang said.
</P>
<P>
   The company's cost structure also is a bit bloated, he said, so
an acquirer ``could immediately cut costs to improve financial
performance.''
</P>
<P>
   Wang estimates the company's current buyout value to be between
$28 and $30 a share.
</P>
<P>
   Another possibility, according to some analysts, would be
obtaining financing and taking the company private.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Beagle said any income generated by the stock in the
trust, whether from dividends or the sale of some or all of the
stock, would be disbursed to various charities through the Kansas
City Community Foundation.
</P>
<P>
   Brown said anyone could approach the company with an offer to
buy AMC.
</P>
<P>
   ``As with any public company, that could happen at any given
time, but that doesn't mean it would be a credible offer,'' Brown
said. ``Besides, the one place that we're different is that there
is tight control over the B shares.''
</P>
<P>
   In other words, the trustees, Brown and Singleton, control AMC
as tightly as Durwood did.
</P>
<P>
   ``Stan always viewed the company as family, and he was a loving,
family-oriented person and would like to see the family stay
together,'' Brown said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
