<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-15 22:28 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2003 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MOVIE-SEASON16-COX     07-15 0362
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIE-SEASON16-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Film sketches paint portrait of Saigon
 &HT;    By Hap Erstein
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ Vietnam. For years, the name was
synonymous with an unwinnable war on the other side of the world.
Now, with ``Three Seasons,'' Tony Bui's delicate series of parallel
character sketches, we glimpse the natural beauty, urban squalor
and have-and-have-nots economy that is modern-day Saigon.
</P>
<P>
   This Sundance Grand Jury Prize winner, the first American
production shot in post-war Vietnam, looks likely to have a
substantial art house life if viewers can accept its elliptical,
enigmatic stories for their fragile merits.
</P>
<P>
   Director-writer Bui shows Saigon through the yearnings of three
groups of desperate searchers and peddlers. We first meet Kien An,
who toils in exquisitely photographed ponds of white lotuses, which
she and others then harvest and hawk on the street. One day she is
summoned to the adjacent house of Teacher Dao, a leprosy-ravaged
man who asks her to transcribe his poems before he dies. They forge
an ephemeral bond.
</P>
<P>
   Next is cyclo-taxi driver Hai, who becomes obsessed with a call
girl servicing the tourists in the upscale hotels most Vietnamese
never see inside. With a windfall, Hai buys a night with Lan, whom
he watches as she sleeps, untouched. Their union is both moving and
sad, and their story narrowly escapes its inherent cliches.
</P>
<P>
   The cast of ``Three Seasons'' is Vietnamese, except for
executive producer Harvey Keitel, who plays a war veteran named
James Hager in search of the love child he never met. He encounters
a street urchin peddling trinkets and gum from a wooden case, which
he loses in one of the city's frequent blackouts. The urchin scours
the city for Hager, suspecting him of stealing the case, while
Hager searches for his daughter.
</P>
<P>
   Each story is a variation on attempts at making connections. The
film's lack of traditional structure or dramatic resolution can be
frustrating, but that should not get in the way of appreciating its
delicate texture and intriguing visuals.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
