<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-15 22:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2006 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BABY-SELLING-NYT &LR;      07-15 0526
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BABY-SELLING-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WOMEN PLEAD GUILTY IN BABY SMUGGLING CASE  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ariz.)   By JOSEPH P. FRIED   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Two Long Island women accused of being part of an
adoption ring that smuggled babies from Mexico pleaded guilty
Thursday to conspiracy charges.
</P>
<P>
   The women, Arlene Lieberman and Arlene Reingold, who federal
prosecutors said had worked with an Arizona lawyer to sell at least
17 children to unwitting adoptive parents in the New York area,
pleaded guilty to conspiring to transport illegal immigrants _ the
children _ within the United States and conceal them from detection
after they were smuggled into Arizona.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the children were infants, some only a few days old, but
one child was 9, according to a prosecutor in U.S. District Court
in Brooklyn, where the women entered their pleas Thursday, seven
weeks after they were arrested. Under federal sentencing
guidelines, they could each receive terms of 21 to 27 months in
prison. The women, who will be sentenced at a date that hasn't been
set, remained free on $150,000 bail each.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to the prison terms, the women face fines of up to
$250,000 each and, under their plea agreements, each is to pay
$43,500 in restitution to the adoptive parents involved.
</P>
<P>
   Timothy Macht, an assistant U.S. attorney in Brooklyn, declined
to say how much each set of parents would receive.
</P>
<P>
   In return for the pleas, federal prosecutors agreed to dismiss
seven other charges against the women, including conspiring to
defraud adoptive parents, who prosecutors said had been falsely
assured that the children were legitimately in the United States
and that it was legal to take custody of them.
</P>
<P>
   The authorities said that the parents, who generally paid fees
of $20,000 or more for the adoptions, did not know that the lawyer
with whom the women worked _ Mario Manuel Reyes Burgueno, who lives
in Douglas, Ariz., and practices law just across the border, in
Agua Prieta, Mexico _ had used faked birth certificates and
adoption-consent forms, had bribed Mexican officials and had
arranged for the children to be brought across the border by women
posing as their mothers.
</P>
<P>
   Once the 17 children were in the New York area, prosecutors
said, they were turned over to the adoptive parents without the
visas, passports or required documents from the U.S. Immigration
and Naturalization Service. The two women's clients, who were often
desperate to adopt children, were falsely told that they could
apply for the necessary approvals from immigration officials later.
</P>
<P>
   All the charges that Ms. Lieberman and Ms. Reingold had
originally faced are still pending against Reyes, who, his lawyer
said Thursday, ``wants to go to trial'' because he believes he has
committed no crimes.
</P>
<P>
   The lawyer, Stephen P. Scaring, said he was surprised that Ms.
Lieberman, 48, and Ms. Reingold, 46, who live near each other in
Medford, had pleaded guilty. ``We haven't approached the U.S.
Attorney at all,'' Scaring said of possible plea negotiations for
his client, who is free on $1 million bond and is due to return to
court on Aug. 13.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
