<SLUG> BC-DURWOOD-OBIT-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STAN DURWOOD, INVENTOR OF MULTIPLEX MOVIE THEATER, DIES AT 78 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JENNIFER MANN  
 c. 1997 The Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Stanley H. Durwood, inventor of the multiplex movie theater and
head of AMC Entertainment Inc., died Wednesday night after a long
battle with esophageal cancer. He was 78.
</P>
<P>
   Durwood opened the nation's first multiplex theater in 1962 at
Kansas City's Ward Parkway Shopping Center. Later, he doggedly
pushed various plans to revitalize downtown, his most recent vision
being the proposed $454 million Power &AMP; Light District.
</P>
<P>
   ``Stan Durwood was a true legend of the theatrical exhibition
industry as well as one of the great entrepreneurs of all time,''
said AMC executive Peter Brown, who became chairman and chief
executive officer of the Kansas City-based company upon Durwood's
death.
</P>
<P>
   AMC officials said Thursday that the succession plan ensured
that the nation's fourth-largest movie exhibition company could
remain independent, even as the stock surged amid renewed takeover
speculation. Backers of the Power &AMP; Light District said the project
would proceed.
</P>
<P>
   Durwood was described by one Hollywood executive as being to the
exhibition side of the movie industry what Louis B. Mayer, Jack
Warner and Darryl F. Zanuck were to the production side.
</P>
<P>
   ``The only way to look at it is that the industry has lost a
mogul,'' said Tom Sherak, chairman of 20th Century Fox Domestic
Film Group. ``He was an icon to those of us growing up in the
business. To us he was a legend, and his legend will not stop.''
</P>
<P>
   Hollywood was in Durwood's blood. His father, Edward Dubinsky,
and an uncle, Maurice Dubinsky, crisscrossed the Midwest near the
turn of the century performing melodramas in tent shows.
</P>
<P>
   The Dubinsky brothers eventually settled in Kansas City and
bought a movie theater. Within a decade, they owned more than a
dozen theaters.
</P>
<P>
   When his father died in 1960, Stan Durwood took over the
business and continued running the theaters, all located downtown.
</P>
<P>
   Durwood invented the multiplex when he hung a velvet curtain to
divide a movie theater and played two movies on the same screen.
</P>
<P>
   His first deliberate multiscreen theater was created at Ward
Parkway in 1962 when the mall's owner, John Kroh, decided to
enclose it and add a second level.
</P>
<P>
   Durwood wanted to build a movie house there, which would have
been one of the first suburban theaters in the area. But Kroh said
because of the support beams, it couldn't be done. It then dawned
on Durwood to create two smaller theaters, and the multiplex was
born.
</P>
<P>
   He didn't have the multiplex appeal quite figured out. Both new
theaters at Ward Parkway opened with the same movie, ``The Great
Escape.''
</P>
<P>
   But soon, Durwood figured out the formula, and the company
opened its first four-plex in 1966. In 1969, AMC opened a six-plex,
with each screen playing a different movie.
</P>
<P>
   The complexes kept getting bigger. The Grand 24 opened in Dallas
in 1995 to rave reviews and huge crowds. Later, AMC built
megaplexes with as many as 30 screens.
</P>
<P>
   Durwood always was an innovator, said Sherak, who teaches a
graduate class at the University of California-Los Angeles on film
exhibition and distribution.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of the most important things I teach my students about is
Stan Durwood and how he changed this industry,'' Sherak said. ``He
always put his money and expertise where he believed the industry
was going, and he was right many more times than he was wrong. But
he wasn't afraid to admit when he was wrong, and that's just part
of what made him a very special man.''
</P>
<P>
   Durwood reveled in some of his quirky traits, such as his
uncanny ability to remember the birth dates of virtually everyone
he ever met and his ability, even in his 70s, to do one-handed
push-ups, a la Jack Palance at the 1992 Academy Awards.
</P>
<P>
   Durwood propelled what eventually became AMC Entertainment Inc.
into one of the largest movie exhibition companies in the world.
Today it has 218 movie theater complexes with 2,729 screens in 23
states and Washington D.C. AMC also has complexes in Japan, Hong
Kong, Spain, Portugal and Canada.
</P>
<P>
   Besides building movie houses packed with amenities, including
high-back tilting chairs, retractable armrests with built-in cup
holders and tiered stadium seating, Durwood also had a passion for
saving urban areas. The one closest to his heart was the heart of
Kansas City.
</P>
<P>
   The impetus for that effort came from Ruben Bergendoff of the
architectural firm Howard Needles Tammen &AMP; Bergendoff. Bergendoff
gathered a group of businessmen in the early 1960s, put them on a
bus and gave them a tour of the soon-to-open highway system in and
around Kansas City.
</P>
<P>
   Durwood was impressed. But later, in a private conversation,
Bergendoff pointed out to Durwood that the highway system ran both
ways _ if downtown was allowed to deteriorate, people would quit
coming, and the heart of the city would die.
</P>
<P>
   From that point on, Durwood pushed to try to revitalize the core
of Kansas City. His efforts weren't always successful.
</P>
<P>
   In a 1996 interview, he said: ``The heart of the city is losing
blood; it's losing function and is just down to a handful of office
buildings. It can function as a much bigger thing.''
</P>
<P>
   But by the time of his death, the dream of the Power &AMP; Light
District was closer to becoming a reality. On Wednesday, project
leaders announced some changes to the plans, including constructing
more of it during the first phase and turning the Power &AMP; Light
Building, where AMC has headquarters, into apartments.
</P>
<P>
   City officials mourned Durwood's death but were confident the
project would continue in his absence.
</P>
<P>
   Durwood was born Aug. 5, 1920, in Kansas City. He was a graduate
of Harvard University, where he competed on the football and
wrestling teams, and was a former U.S. Air Force lieutenant.
</P>
<P>
   Durwood received many civic and industry awards, including the
1994 University of Missouri-Kansas City Chancellor's Medal, the
1995 Foundation of the Motion Picture Pioneers ``Pioneer of the
Year'' award and the 1996 National Association of Theater Owners
Robert W. Selig ``ShoWester of the Year'' award.
</P>
<P>
   Durwood is survived by his wife, Pamela Durwood; six children by
his first wife; and 13 grandchildren. Services are pending.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
