<SLUG> BC-SOUTHTRUST16-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    SouthTrust pays for annoying you
 &HT;    By Jeff Ostrowski
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ Bank customers love to hate fees.
</P>
<P>
   But one bank that does business in South Florida is turning the
tables. SouthTrust of Birmingham, Ala., is coughing up cash when it
annoys customers.
</P>
<P>
   Rewards include $10 for a mistake or misspelling on a statement,
$5 if the bank doesn't return a customer's phone call by the end of
the day and $1 if a customer has to wait in line for a teller for
more than 5 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   ``Truthfully, I don't think anyone is standing there with a
stopwatch,'' said Eris Sandler, senior vice president of
SouthTrust's South Florida operations. ``It's our way of saying we
care about quality service.''
</P>
<P>
   SouthTrust also reimburses customers who find a SouthTrust ATM
isn't working and are forced to pay fees when they use other banks'
ATMs.
</P>
<P>
   Sandler said she isn't sure how much the bank has paid out in
South Florida, but she said the number is in ``the thousands.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We know it costs a lot more money to attract a new customer
than to retain existing customers,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
