<HEADLINE>
JUDGMENT AGAINST GM DESERVES A REASSESSMENT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JERRY HEASTER  
 c. 1997 The Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The most striking aspect of last week's $4.9 billion judgment
against General Motors was the jurors' apparent failure to consider
the millions of blameless individuals who depend on GM for their
livelihoods.
</P>
<P>
   It goes without saying that the plaintiffs' suffering has been
horrific beyond imagining. Could any juror hear the details of
their story and not be moved to a sympathetic response? Probably
not, but it also goes without saying that those charged with making
judgments about economic justice should do so with a sense of
proportion.
</P>
<P>
   The jurors were said to have reacted to allegations that GM cut
corners on safety to save a few dollars. The result was what is
considered the largest personal-injury award in history: $107.6
million in compensatory damages and $4.8 billion in punitive
damages.
</P>
<P>
   In making such an award, the jury essentially reduced the entire
GM operation to a relative few company executives it thought should
be taught a lesson no business manager would ever forget. If the
judgment is allowed to stand, which most legal analysts doubt, it
would amount to far more than GM's earnings last year.
</P>
<P>
   Before anyone says it serves them right, however, General Motors
should be evaluated in its context as a source of economic
sustenance for millions of people not only in America but also
throughout the world. These are the employees, retirees, those
supplying GM with myriad goods and services, those with nest eggs
invested in GM stock, and all their families.
</P>
<P>
   The corporate entity known as General Motors and a small coterie
of its executives may be blameworthy in this case. The jury in Los
Angeles certainly thought so, but whether those charged with
reviewing the case on appeal will agree with the jury remains to be
seen.
</P>
<P>
   Regardless of what happens, however, where is the justice of a
penalty that would severely cripple an enterprise on which millions
have an economic dependency ranging from significant to critical?
</P>
<P>
   Does a juror making such a judgment ever think beyond the narrow
confines in which the case is presented? Certainly the jurors in
this case share economic dependencies similar to those whose
fortunes are tied to General Motors. Did they ever stop to think
how they might be affected if another jury made a judgment that
jeopardized their economic survival?
</P>
<P>
   It's not as though the plaintiffs didn't deserve relief. The
most obvious liability, it seems, should have been borne by the
drunken driver who rear-ended the plaintiffs at a speed estimated
at 50 to 70 mph. Reasonable minds may disagree on the structural
integrity of the GM car that became an inferno in the crash.
Nevertheless, it's asking a lot to build a vehicle that provides
reasonable protection when it's hit while standing still by another
vehicle hurtling forward at 50 to 70 mph.
</P>
<P>
   A main point of contention in the recent debate over tightening
medical-coverage regulation has been whether to make it easier to
sue managed-care plans and expand the liability parameters.
Proponents say it would make the plans more responsive.
</P>
<P>
   Many damage awards in recent years, however, indicate that such
a move would do more to spur lotterylike lawsuits than enhance the
quality of health care.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-15-99 2230EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
