u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-WTO-DIRECTOR-NYT &LR;      07-15 0262
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WTO-DIRECTOR-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DEAL SUGGESTED FOR TRADE GROUP POST
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 By ELIZABETH OLSON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   GENEVA, Switzerland _ A solution to end the deadlock over the
next head of the World Trade Organization appeared closer Thursday
when a compromise proposal was introduced that would allow the two
contenders to split one term.
</P>
<P>
   The proposal, circulated at a meeting of the trade group's
decision-making General Assembly, came two weeks before it adjourns
for August, and there were widespread expectations that the 134
member nations would try to reach a final decision before then.
</P>
<P>
   The divisive process of choosing between Mike Moore, a former
New Zealand prime minister, and Supachai Panitchpakdi, Thailand's
deputy prime minister, has undermined trust among the member
nations of the Geneva-based group, which sets the rules of global
commerce.
</P>
<P>
   The proposal to divide the director-general's tenure into two
equal parts was introduced by Bangladesh and Australia.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   It would allow one person to serve as director-general for three
years, from Sept. 1, 1999, to the end of August 2002. The second
three-year term would run from Sept. 1, 2002, to the end of August
2005.
</P>
<P>
   Both Moore and Supachai have indicated publicly that they would
accept such an arrangement. However, some members have criticized
the proposal and it remains unclear how the members would decide
which contender serves first.
</P>
<P>
   The trade organization has been leaderless since Renato Ruggiero
left when his four-year term expired at the end of April.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
