<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-15 22:33 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2015 &Cx1f; tta-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SPRINGSTEEN-CONCERT-A     07-15 0437
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SPRINGSTEEN-CONCERT-ART-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 EAST RUTHERFORD, N.J.: and Philadelphia.   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Thursday night, Springsteen opened with ``My Love Will Not Let
You Down'' and ``Promised Land.''
</P>
<P>
   For weeks, people had been gearing up for the return of
Springsteen, E Street band in tow, giving the event all the
attention worthy of a Super Bowl. There were scads of Internet
sites; detailed reports about dress rehearsals in small New Jersey
clubs, and preparations for the boardwalk-like festival of food
concessions and a beach volleyball court complete with sand hauled
in from, yes, the Jersey shore.
</P>
<P>
   There was even a full-page advertisement Thursday in The
Star-Ledger newspaper, of Newark, N.J., from New Jersey Online,
which said in part: ``We partied to you. We danced in the dark to
you. We hit the parkway to you,'' and ended, ``We have a local hero
thanks to you. Welcome home.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, in dozens of interviews in the Meadowlands parking lot
Thursday, many people seemed, for a day at least, to exult in the
fact that they, too, were from New Jersey, and could readily
identify with Springsteen and his songs about working-class life,
yearning and frustration.
</P>
<P>
   ``Glory Days'' played to the left. ``Thunder Road,'' coming from
a sports-utility vehicle, played to the right. ``Jungleland,'' all
around.
</P>
<P>
   In the section of the parking lot coded C23, Keith Wells was
sipping a drink with his friend Pete Mooney. Two decades ago, Wells
spent hour after ear-pounding hour worshiping Bruce Springsteen and
the E Street Band on the radio, at his home by the Jersey shore or,
as often as possible, in concert. And when he became an adult, he
said, he took his son Greg, then 9, to his first concert: Bruce, of
course.
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday, it was Greg's turn: He had bought a ticket for his
dad as a Father's Day gift.
</P>
<P>
   ``Listening to his songs is like talking to an old friend,''
beamed Wells, 51, a computer consultant who lives in Little Silver,
N.J. He was blasting what he said confidently was ``the best
bootleg collection'' of Springsteen songs _ ever _ from the windows
of his green BMW.
</P>
<P>
   A few rows away, Mary Anne Gross was proudly displaying her
``Jersey Girl'' T-shirt, which she said she bought about a dozen
years ago, as a reminder of her devotion to that song and to
Springsteen. Three years ago, she married Alex Tannucilli, who was
her equal as a Springsteen fanatic.
</P>
<P>
   ``He speaks for the entire Jersey experience. The entire
experience of being born between two megalopolises,'' said
Tannucilli, who, like his wife, is 56. ``He's the poet king, and he
gives back to his fans.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
