A2016 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PBS-DONORS-BOS &LR;      07-15 1266
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PBS-DONORS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REPUBLICANS SEEK PROBE OF PUBLIC BROADCASTING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ANNE E. KORNBLUT AND DON AUCOIN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Amid growing evidence that public television
stations in several cities have shared their donor lists with both
political parties, House Republicans Thursday night considered
holding hearings to determine whether any wrongdoing had occurred.
</P>
<P>
   As disclosures that Boston's WGBH-TV shared donors' names with
the Democratic Party touched off a furor on Capitol Hill, two major
public stations, WNET in New York and WETA in Washington, D.C.,
admitted to a similar practice.
</P>
<P>
   Several House Republicans said they suspect numerous other
stations were involved, although at least two members said the WGBH
controversy was reason enough for an ``oversight'' hearing, the
congressional equivalent of an investigation.
</P>
<P>
   Representative Christopher Cox, a California Republican, said
the ``proper response to the WGBH illegal activity is oversight
hearings,'' although he could not say which laws might have been
broken.
</P>
<P>
   And Representative W.J. ``Billy'' Tauzin, the Louisiana
Republican who chairs the House subcommittee that oversees funding
for public broadcasting nationwide, was convinced the three
incidents were ``just the tip of the iceberg.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We are going to call the Corporation for Public Broadcasting
on the carpet and grill them about the process,'' said Ken Johnson,
a spokesman for Tauzin.
</P>
<P>
   The subcommittee had planned to call WGBH officials to a hearing
Tuesday to question them on the list swap. But  &UR; last night &LR; , on a
lawyer's advice, Tauzin changed his mind.
</P>
<P>
   ``They may be facing some legal consequences as a result of
their actions, and so we've decided not to call them,'' Johnson
said.
</P>
<P>
   But with the Corporation for Public Broadcasting under scrutiny,
the revelation that both parties might have benefited from list
swaps will probably not defuse the issue among Republicans, who
traditionally have been hostile to public broadcasting.
</P>
<P>
   The admission by two more stations that they were involved in
list-swapping with political parties rocked the national
Corporation for Public Broadcasting, the umbrella organization that
receives and distributes federal funding for the country's public
television and radio stations, including the Public Broadcasting
Service.
</P>
<P>
   Days earlier, public broadcasting had been optimistic about
receiving a significant increase in federal funds, but that now
appears to be in jeopardy.
</P>
<P>
   Robert Coonrod, president of the Corporation for Public
Broadcasting, condemned even the appearance of wrongdoing among
member stations, saying he was committed to ferreting out the
problem.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't condone this practice,'' Coonrod said Thursday. ``We
will work with the Congress as appropriate to make sure it doesn't
continue. Even if stations are in compliance with IRS regulations,
if they are swapping lists with partisan institutions, that could
reasonably be perceived by their viewers as having a partisan slant
to it.''
</P>
<P>
   It remained unclear whether any of the stations had violated the
law. According to Internal Revenue Service regulations, tax-exempt
organizations _ otherwise known as 501(c)(3)s _ are allowed to sell
or rent their mailing lists to a political organization or
candidate as long as the lists are ``available to all other
candidates.''
</P>
<P>
   But the definition of ``available'' is undefined. According to
an IRS guide, tax-exempt groups must prove ``that all candidates
were afforded a reasonable opportunity to acquire the list.''
</P>
<P>
   Representative Edward J. Markey of Malden, the top Democrat on
the telecommunications subcommittee, insisted the list-sharing was
nonpartisan. ``Across the PBS system many stations viewed Democrats
and Republicans as being potentially valuable sources of income,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, the corporation launched its own investigation
after learning the list-sharing was not an isolated incident as it
first seemed.
</P>
<P>
   WGBH had initially said its swap with the Democratic Party was a
onetime occurrence and a mistake, before the Democratic National
Committee revealed the sharing involved thousands of donor names
and had gone on for years.
</P>
<P>
   Cecily Van Praagh, a spokeswoman for WETA-TV in Washington,
acknowledged that the station also traded donor lists with the DNC
and other political organizations, ``both conservative and
liberal.''
</P>
<P>
   Van Praagh said the station had not considered that practice a
problem, but will now reevaluate it ``in view of the concern that's
come up with WGBH.''
</P>
<P>
   At a third television station, WNET in New York, dismayed
executives said they discovered Thursday that a ``list broker''
working for the station had shared the names of donors with the
Democratic and Republican parties.
</P>
<P>
   The executives said the broker had acted without the station's
knowledge and in violation of company policy against making mailing
lists available to political organizations.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is very upsetting,'' said Paula Kerger, WNET vice
president of development. She said the station launched an internal
examination in response to the WGBH controversy.
</P>
<P>
   Coonrod, learning of the additional stations engaged in the
practice, said: ``I guess this is especially disappointing because
it came as such a surprise. Until today, this seemed like an
isolated incident that happened some time ago.''
</P>
<P>
   At the Republican National Committee, spokesman Michael Collins
said, ``To the best of our knowledge, we have never leased any
public TV station donor list.'' He said he could not rule out the
possibility that the RNC leased a tax-deductible organization's
list, but said the party always used ``a list broker and paid
market price for the lists.''
</P>
<P>
   All three stations and the DNC also said they used outside list
brokers for their transactions, reducing their knowledge of which
organizations they were dealing with.
</P>
<P>
   WGBH was scrambling to contain the damage. The station contacted
all 350 PBS stations across the country via e-mail, explaining how
the snafu occurred and expressed regret. Station officials also
fielded scores of calls and e-mails from donors and viewers.
</P>
<P>
   At the station's headquarters on Western Avenue in Allston, WGBH
general manager Jonathan Abbott insisted it ``was not a political
conspiracy, not a political collaboration.''
</P>
<P>
   Chief among the errors, he said, was that the station gave what
the DNC says were 12,000 names to the party in 1996. That was a
full two years after the station had prohibited exchanges with
political organizations after discovering a previous arrangement
with the DNC.
</P>
<P>
   Abbott and Jeanne M. Hopkins, vice president for communications,
said the 1994 and 1996 violations were committed by staffers within
the development, or fund-raising, office. They said the lists of
donors' names were supplied to the DNC without the knowledge of
senior management.
</P>
<P>
   David Liroff, who was WGBH station manager in 1994, and Steven
Bass, who was station manager in 1996, told the Globe they were not
aware of the sharing of mailing lists with the DNC.
</P>
<P>
   The harsh spotlight on WGBH's fund-raising practices falls at an
awkward time for station, which recently launched a $33 million
capital campaign. Part of that would help with the costly
transition to digital broadcasting mandated by the federal
government. Now WGBH has to explain to donors why some of their
names were supplied to a political party for fund-raising purposes.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
