<SLUG> BC-NY-MRSCLINTON-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FIRST LADY IS PLEDGED $25 MILLION FOR RACE 
</HEADLINE>
  (yn) 
 By ADAM NAGOURNEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Settling in for what is shaping up to be the
costliest congressional contest in the nation's history, 75 New
York Democrats sat down for breakfast with Hillary Rodham Clinton
Thursday and pledged to raise $25 million to finance her expected
race for senator from New York.
</P>
<P>
   If they succeed, the Clinton campaign would set a new record:
raising more from contributors than any other non-incumbent Senate
candidate.
</P>
<P>
   As the lawyers, media executives and business leaders made their
pledges at a midtown law office, the first lady also mailed more
than 1 million appeals to prospective Democratic contributors
across the nation, her associates said. The size of the mailing
dwarfed anything attempted in any congressional campaign in recent
memory, Democrats said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   ``Over the years I have written to you on behalf of Democratic
candidates and causes,'' Mrs. Clinton wrote in her two-page letter.
``Today, I am writing to make a more personal request.'' She went
on to say, ``For three decades I have been a strong advocate for
the causes I believe in, and I believe I can be a strong advocate
for New York.''
</P>
<P>
   Taken together, the letter and the fund-raising plan leave
little doubt that the race to succeed Daniel Patrick Moynihan could
shatter campaign financing records.
</P>
<P>
   If Mrs. Clinton meets the $25 million goal _ and Democrats and
Republicans Thursday predicted that she would _ her campaign would
surpass the record set by Oliver L. North in 1994, when he raised
$20.7 million for his unsuccessful Senate bid in Virginia.
</P>
<P>
   And if Mayor Rudolph W. Giuliani of New York City or another
Republican candidate comes close to matching Mrs. Clinton's success
in raising funds _ and Democrats and Republicans Thursday predicted
that some Republican would _ the race could break the $44 million
spending record set in the California Senate race of 1994, when
Michael Huffington spent $30 million, most of it out of his own
pocket, in his unsuccessful campaign against Sen. Diane Feinstein.
The second most-expensive race was in New York last year, when
Charles E. Schumer, a Democrat, defeated Sen. Alfonse M. D'Amato, a
Republican. Spending in that contest reached about $40.1 million.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike most first-time candidates, Mrs. Clinton will not have to
spend any money to introduce herself to voters. However, her
supporters said Thursday, the first lady expects to spend large
sums to address, presumably with television advertisements,
unfavorable perceptions among a good portion of the New York
electorate.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, Republicans across the nation have begun making
their own requests for money to help finance an effort to defeat
Mrs. Clinton, adding to the pressure Mrs. Clinton's supporters said
they felt to raise money in the months ahead.
</P>
<P>
   Aides to Giuliani said they were unconcerned about Mrs.
Clinton's fund-raising intentions. ``We will match the Democratic
candidate for the Senate in fund raising,'' said John H. Gross, the
mayor's treasurer.
</P>
<P>
   Still, before Giuliani reaches the point of matching Mrs.
Clinton, he has to get past a well-financed challenge to the
nomination within his own party. Giuliani now has less money on
hand for a Senate run than Rep. Rick A. Lazio of Long Island, his
relatively unknown rival for the Republican nomination, aides to
both men said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   In federal campaign filings to be released at the end of the
month, Giuliani is expected to report having about $2.6 million on
hand, compared with more than $3 million for Lazio.
</P>
<P>
   However, Giuliani has been raising money in recent months at a
far faster clip than Lazio, whose total is bolstered by more than
$1.8 million carried over from his Congressional campaign
committees in previous years.
</P>
<P>
   The first lady's fund-raising meeting was held in a conference
room at the New York law firm of Skadden, Arps, Slate, Meagher &AMP;
Flom, at the invitation of a partner, Morris N. Kaplan.
</P>
<P>
   The session was led by Alan J. Patricof, the New York venture
capitalist who has been one of the president's most loyal
supporters, and by Terence McAuliffe, a close friend of Clinton who
raised $27 million for the Clinton-Gore campaign in just seven
months in 1995.
</P>
<P>
   According to participants, it was Patricof who set the $25
million goal. That figure was embraced by the participants, who
agreed to meet monthly.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
