<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SENATE-CARE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SENATE CLEARS GOP'S SCALED-DOWN HEALTH BILL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB HOHLER  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The Senate's Republican majority Thursday night
approved new protections for 48 million members of employer-run
health plans after defeating Democratic efforts to guarantee far
broader rights to 161 million health-care consumers.
</P>
<P>
   In the final act of a four-day drama whose epilogue will
probably include a presidential veto and political skirmishes in
the 2000 elections, Senate Republicans passed their scaled-down
version of The Patients' Bill of Rights Act, 53-47. Only two GOP
members, Senators John H. Chafee of Rhode Island and Peter G.
Fitzgerald of Illinois, joined the unified Democratic minority in
opposition.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans never sustained more than three defections as they
narrowly prevailed in more than a dozen votes over four days of a
wide range of patient protection issues. They effectively gutted
and cast aside the Democratic package before adopting their own.
</P>
<P>
   ``We came up with a very good package, a very defensible
package, one that's proven not only to have the votes but one that
I think will make positive contributions for making affordable
quality health care for all Americans,'' said the assistant
majority leader, Don Nickles of Oklahoma, who spearheaded the
Republican initiative.
</P>
<P>
   The White House, consumer groups, and medical organizations
assailed the GOP measure as a passel of meager regulations crafted
to appease the health insurance industry, which spent millions of
dollars fighting the Democratic proposal with lobbyists and
advertising campaigns.
</P>
<P>
   The industry is poised to exert similar pressure as the
legislation moves to the Republican-controlled House, where its
passage is less certain than it was in the Senate.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a sad day for health care in America,'' Clinton said
before the final vote. ``But we're not done yet and this won't
die.''
</P>
<P>
   Vice President Al Gore, in a last-minute plea for the Democratic
plan in a news conference outside the Senate chamber, reiterated
Clinton's threat to veto the GOP measure and keep the issue alive
for the coming elections. ``It has zero chance of going past his
desk because it's a fraud,'' Gore said.
</P>
<P>
   Senator Edward M. Kennedy, the chief architect of the Democratic
plan, held out hope that Senate Democrats had cast the debate
favorably enough to create momentum for broader health insurance
regulations in the House. ``This is a Pyrrhic victory for the
Republicans,'' Kennedy said. ``If they keep taking marching orders
from the HMOs, they'll keep losing public support.''
</P>
<P>
   The Republican plan provides greater access to emergency rooms,
specialists, medications, and clinical trials for cancer patients.
The measure requires health insurers to provide inpatient treatment
for mastectomy patients if their doctors deem it necessary,
effectively preventing ``drive-by mastectomies'' that are peformed
on an outpatient basis.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, the GOP bill provides an array of tax provisions
aimed at increasing access to health coverage for 43 million
uninsured consumers. The provisions include permitting the
self-employed to fully deduct their health insurance and allowing
company employees to fully deduct long-term care insurance that is
not subsidized by their employers.
</P>
<P>
   The measures would reduce federal tax revenues by $3.5 billion
over five years, and Republican leaders were not clear about how
they would offset the loss.
</P>
<P>
   A key element of the GOP bill would permit patients to appeal
decisions by their insurance companies to review boards staffed by
physicians. The appeals process contrasts with the Democratic
proposal to permit patients to sue their insurers in federal or
state courts.
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe 10 years from now, when our proposal is in effect,
that the American people are going to believe that this was a very
important bill we adopted in the Senate tonight,'' said Senator
Phil Gramm, a Texas Republican and leading foe of the Democratic
plan. ``It is going to mean better health care, it's going to mean
greater access to health care, it's going to mean more freedom. And
it's going to mean that when you're sick, you're going to get an
opportunity to see a doctor, not an opportunity to suffer some
permanent injury and then get to see a lawyer and file a lawsuit.''
</P>
<P>
   Democrats, citing myriad horror stories involving patients who
had suffered dire consequences, including deaths, because of
alleged abuses by their insurers, decried the GOP move to prevent
patients from suing their insurers. ``Patients should not have to
play a game of Russian roulette to the health care they need and
deserve,'' Kennedy said.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats also criticized the Republican plan for generally
protecting only the 48 million members of self-funded health plans
that are run by the employees's companies rather than the insurance
industry. The Democratic plan would have extended federal
protections to 75 million consumers whose employers pay an
insurance company or HMO to provide coverage, 23 million state and
local employees, and 15 million individuals who pay for insurance
on their own.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Senate has missed a golden opportunity to pass a real
Patients' Bill of Rights,'' said the minority leader, Thomas A.
Daschle. ``Instead, the Republican majority is handing the
insurance industry its version of HMO reform: Half Measures Only.''
</P>
<P>
   Republicans countered that the Democratic plan would have raised
insurance premiums 6 percent over five years, forcing 1.8 million
individuals off the insurance rolls. The GOP plan would increase
premiums an estimated 1 percent.
</P>
<P>
   An attempt by Chafee to broker a last-minute, bipartisan
compromise failed when he was unable to secure the 51 votes he
needed to force a vote on the measure. One of Chafee's top
Democratic allies, Senator Bob Graham of Florida, said the
bipartisan measure's death ``doomed 161 million Americans to yet
another year of inadequate managed care coverage.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
