u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOEING-EARNINGS-450&AMP;A     07-15 0760
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOEING-EARNINGS-450&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
55 PERCENT RISE IN BOEING PROFITS FAR EXCEEDS PREDICTIONS
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 By LAURENCE ZUCKERMAN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Boeing Co. delivered stronger-than-expected earnings for the
second consecutive quarter Thursday and raised its estimates of
future profits, giving its beleaguered investors new hope after two
years of disappointments.
</P>
<P>
   Boeing, the world's largest aerospace company and the nation's
largest exporter, said its profits rose 55 percent during the
quarter, easily surpassing Wall Street's estimates. Executives
attributed the strong results to the improved efficiency of
Boeing's commercial airplane business and a reduction in research
and development costs.
</P>
<P>
   Boeing earned $701 million, or 75 cents a diluted share,
compared with $258 million, or 26 cents a share, in the quarter a
year earlier. Revenue rose 13 percent, to $15.1 billion from $13.4
billion.
</P>
<P>
   Excluding a $181 million gain from a tax settlement, Boeing
earned 56 cents a share during the quarter. Analysts had expected
the company to earn 48 cents a share, according to the First Call
Corp., which tracks company earnings.
</P>
<P>
   Shares of Boeing, which had risen sharply this week, fell 87.5
cents, to $46.75.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is very positive news,'' said Joseph F. Campbell, a
managing director at Lehman Brothers, ``but it does need to be kept
in the context of where we are coming from and where we need to
go.''
</P>
<P>
   Two years ago, Boeing had racked up record sales of its
jetliners. Analysts predicted that the company would earn as much
as $5 a share in 2000. But production difficulties and other
setbacks forced the company to take $4 billion in charges, causing
its stock price to plunge. The consensus profit estimate for 2000
compiled by First Call was $1.81 a share Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Over the last year, Boeing installed new management to run its
commercial airplane division and began improving its performance.
Led largely by a turnaround in the commercial airplane unit, net
profit margins for the company during the second quarter were 4.6
percent, up from 1.9 percent the same time last year.
</P>
<P>
   Boeing said Thursday that it had raised its estimates of profit
margins for the full year to between 5 percent and 5.5 percent from
a previous estimate of 4 percent to 5 percent. Next year's estimate
was also raised to between 5 percent and 6 percent, up from 4
percent to 5 percent.
</P>
<P>
   But the company still faces a decline in earnings next year when
revenue is expected to fall by $10 billion as deliveries of
jetliners decline to 480 from a record 620 this year. Deborah
Hopkins, Boeing's new chief financial officer, said Thursday that
the company would try to cushion investors by maintaining flat
earnings in 2000 despite the big drop in revenue.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's aggressive but it is not a goal we shouldn't go for,''
she said.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Thursday, the company also released four measures _ what it
called a ``value scorecard'' _ as part of its effort to regain
credibility with investors.
</P>
<P>
   The measures are part of a broader, company-wide effort led by
Ms. Hopkins to get all of Boeing's disparate operations to focus on
improving their financial performance. The four measures that will
be provided to the public each quarter include annual inventory
turnover, the size of Boeing's real estate, its number of suppliers
and the amount by which it has reduced its expenses.
</P>
<P>
   To give investors a way to measure the company's progress, Ms.
Hopkins Thursday revealed both short-term and long-term goals in
each category. She also said that the company intended to achieve
double-digit profit margins in the next three to five years.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to operational improvements, Boeing also seems to be
encouraged by a faster than expected turnaround in Asia, where some
of its most important customers were forced to retrench after the
severe economic downturn in the region in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am slightly more optimistic about Asia today than I was
three months ago,'' said Philip M. Condit, Boeing's chairman and
chief executive, speaking to reporters. He cited improvements in
Korea as well as ``some positive signs'' in Japan.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, Boeing said that it would decrease production of its
747 jumbo jet to one a month next year because of declining demand
in Asia. Now, the company is hinting that it may be able to sustain
production of the 747, which is its most profitable airplane, at
two a month. A final decision will be made in August.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
