<SLUG> BC-OBIT-MARCHAND-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LESLIE ALEXIS MARCHAND, LEADING BIOGRAPHER OF BYRON, DIES AT 99  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: N.J., Fla., Wash.)   c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Leslie Alexis Marchand, considered the leading authority on the
poet Lord Byron, died on Sunday at his home in Englewood, Fla. He
was 99.
</P>
<P>
   Marchand's lifelong pursuit of Byron, an elusive figure who
described himself as ``being everything by turns and nothing
long,'' began in 1935 while he researched his dissertation, ``The
Athenaeum: A Mirror of Victorian Culture,'' a historical study of
the British independent literary magazine for which he received a
doctorate from Columbia University in 1940.
</P>
<P>
   While teaching a course in Romanticism at Rutgers University,
whose faculty he had joined in 1937, Marchand recognized the need
for a first-rate biography of Byron. In 1947, he embarked on what
he called his ``Byron pilgrimage,'' journeying from the London
offices of Sir John Murray, a descendant of Byron's publisher to
Missolonghi in Greece, where Byron died in 1824, to Jannina, on the
Albanian frontier, where Byron and his friend J.C. Hobhouse had
visited the Turkish ruler Ali Pasha.
</P>
<P>
   ``Byron: A Biography'' was published in three volumes by Alfred
A. Knopf in 1957. The result of more than a decade of research, the
work totaled 1,264 pages, exclusive of notes and index.
</P>
<P>
   Louis Simpson of the Hudson Review called the work ``a triumph
of scholarship, thorough, intelligent and impartial.'' W.H. Auden
also praised it, writing in The New Yorker, ``the meticulous
scholarship is there, all right, but Marchand has digested it, and
despite an occasional ponderous phrase like ``his natatorial
skill,'' his three volumes . . . are as fascinating to read as they
are informative, and, as a biography of the poet, as nearly
definitive as any such book can be.''
</P>
<P>
   The son of a French-speaking homesteader and his wife, Marchand
was born in the small town of Bridgeport, Wash., near the Columbia
River. He attended the University of Washington in Seattle, where
he studied journalism. He enrolled at Columbia University in 1929.
</P>
<P>
   After retiring from Rutgers in 1966, Marchand set out to create
a comprehensive collection of Byron's personal writings, to
``reproduce Byron's letters as they were written,'' he later wrote.
This endeavor occupied him from 1968 to 1982 and resulted in the
12-volume ``Byron's Letters and Journals.''
</P>
<P>
   His collection included about 1,700 previously unpublished
letters by Byron _ some 100 of which Marchand discovered _ and
whenever possible supplied the passages that previous collections
had deleted and corrected countless errors in dating. Moreover,
after comparing more than 80 percent of the letters against their
original manuscript versions, Marchand restored Byron's often
idiosyncratic punctuation, spelling and capitalization.
</P>
<P>
   Marchand received two significant awards for his work, the James
Russell Lowell Prize of the Modern Language Association in 1973 and
the Ivan Sandrof Award of the National Book Critics Circle in 1982.
The latter had been awarded only once before, to Flannery O'Connor.
</P>
<P>
   In 1994, Marchand published ``What Comes Uppermost,'' a
supplemental volume of ``Byron's Letters and Journals'' that
contained letters discovered since the completion of the original
12 volumes in 1982.
</P>
<P>
   He is survived by his wife, Marion, of Englewood, Fla.
</P>
<P>
   Asked in the 1980s what had aroused his interest in Byron and
sustained his studies for more than 40 years, Marchand replied:
``Byron is a fascinating character and I have never found him dull.
I can read over his `Don Juan' and his letters dozens of times
without yawning. He was a superb letter writer, spontaneous, frank,
self-honest and witty, and his sane and humane and tolerant view of
the world is refreshing, when contrasted with so much cant and
dishonesty and pretension. Byron speaks with the voice of the
disillusioned modern world more than with that of the 19th
century.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-15-99 2238EDT &QL; 
