<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEN-GRAF-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GRAF, FEELING ILL, BOWS OUT OF THIRD SET WITH CAPRIATI  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By GERALD ESKENAZI    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MAHWAH, N.J. _ Steffi Graf had moved Jennifer Capriati all over
the court Thursday night at the A.&AMP;P. Tennis Classic, her wicked
backhands delivered with the crushing swing of a samurai sword.
</P>
<P>
   Then, suddenly, at match point, leading by 40-0 and 5-3 in the
second set, it unraveled for Graf, the defending champion and a
six-time winner of the event.
</P>
<P>
   Capriati, on the comeback trail in more ways than one, went on
to win the second set and take the first game of the third set. She
had lost the opening set by 7-5 and had survived five match points.
</P>
<P>
   The crowd, which had rooted for Graf, then turned to Capriati,
who has not won this tournament since 1993, when personal and legal
problems began for her.
</P>
<P>
   But after losing that first game of the final set, Graf went to
the sideline and told the umpire that she could not continue. She
``retired'' in tennis parlance. But just for the night, presumably.
</P>
<P>
   An official said later that Graf had told him she became ill
from a medication she was taking for the bronchitis. It caused her
to bow out of her scheduled semifinal mixed doubles match with John
McEnroe at Wimbledon earlier this month.
</P>
<P>
   Graf went on to play in the singles championship and lost to
Lindsay Davenport. This was her first match since Wimbledon. In
subsequent interviews, she has sent mixed signals about her plans
to retire completely sometime soon.
</P>
<P>
   For Capriati, who appeared to be overmatched midway through
Thursday night's second set, this was the first time she had
defeated Graf since the 1992 Olympics.
</P>
<P>
   Capriati advanced to Saturday's semifinals, where she will face
the winner of Friday's match between Nicole Pratt and Erica deLone.
</P>
<P>
   But Thursday night, it was a thrill-a-minute for 95 minutes of
action before Graf quit. Capriati vainly tried to bring her newly
acquired style of rushing the net into the match.
</P>
<P>
   ``But it's very hard against Steffi Graf,'' Capriati said later.
</P>
<P>
   She is barely ranked in the top 50 and in Graf she was facing a
player ranked third in the world. Capriati valiantly returned shot
after shot from between the baselines, but the pounding forced her
into too many errors.
</P>
<P>
   She seemed a goner, in fact, as Graf, winning seven of the last
nine games, surged to the 5-3 lead and match point.
</P>
<P>
   ``As the match went on I got a little loose,'' Capriati said.
</P>
<P>
   At age 23, once a famous teen-age pro, she is now a year into
her comeback. ``All the players are younger now,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Tournament organizers presented the 30-year-old Graf with
several gifts before the match, which presumably is leading to her
permanent retirement, perhaps after the U.S. Open in September. The
gifts included a rocking chair inscribed with her major victories.
</P>
<P>
   She could watch next year's French Open, which she won in June,
sitting in the chair, she was told. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
