<SLUG> BC-OBIT-DURWOOD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STANLEY DURWOOD, INVENTOR OF MULTIPLEX, DIES AT 78  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Kan., Conn., Mass., Calif.)   By DIANA B. HENRIQUES   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Stanley H. Durwood, an entertainment industry executive who is
credited with inventing the multiplex movie theater, died Wednesday
night at his Kansas City, Mo., home after a two-year illness. He
was 78.
</P>
<P>
   The cause was esophageal cancer, according to a statement from
AMC Entertainment, the international movie theater chain Durwood
built from a family business founded in 1920.
</P>
<P>
   Durwood's version of how he first got the notion of combining
multiple screening rooms into a single theater has entered into
Hollywood folklore. The inspiration first hit in the early 1950s,
after his family theater chain had acquired the 600-seat Roxy
Theater in downtown Kansas City.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was standing in the lobby the third week after we took over
the theater, and we were running an Abbott and Costello picture,''
he recalled in a 1998 profile for Variety. The film was doing so
poorly that he had closed the balcony to avoid having to place an
usher there. ``I thought, `If we could just run another so-so
picture up in the balcony, we'd double our gross.'''
</P>
<P>
   By the late 1950s, with television emptying out the grand movie
palaces that had sprung up in the 1930s, he had acquired several
giant Kansas City theaters and cut them into several small movie
theaters. Then, in 1963, he built the first theater originally
designed as a multiplex, in the Ward Parkway shopping center in
south Kansas City.
</P>
<P>
   In 1966, Durwood's company built its first four-screen complex;
a six-screen complex followed in 1969. The rest, as they say in
Hollywood, was history. The concept ``echoes all around the
world,'' a Metro-Golden-Mayer executive told Daily Variety in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was like punching a hole in the floor of your living room
and oil coming out,'' Durwood later recalled. ``I figured I had
about five years to run with the ball before the big guys would
overtake me.''
</P>
<P>
   His innovations have been widely credited by the motion picture
industry with helping to rescue the business from the onslaughts of
both television and the videocassette recorder. In 1993, the
Foundation of Motion Picture Pioneers honored him as Pioneer of the
Year, an honor which had previously gone to such household names as
Darryl F. Zanuck and Cecil B. De Mille.
</P>
<P>
   The multiplex was not Durwood's only innovative contribution to
the moviegoing public: he also is credited with inventing the
arm-rest cup holder, whose introduction reflected his determination
to make a night at the movies so pleasant it would pull people away
from their television sets and into his theaters.
</P>
<P>
   More recently, he began to see his multiple-screen theater
concept as a magnet that could also pull people out of the suburbs
and into the center cities. Under his guidance as chief executive,
AMC has begun to develop huge theater entertainment centers in
once-rundown urban neighborhoods, from Times Square in New York
City to ``beautiful downtown Burbank'' in California, once the butt
of television talk-show jokes.
</P>
<P>
   Durwood was born Aug. 5, 1920, in Kansas City. He was the son of
Edward Dubinsky, a silver-haired actor-turned-entrepreneur who
built a small chain of about a dozen movie houses and drive-in
theaters. The business prospered, as did the family, which later
changed its name to Durwood.
</P>
<P>
   Durwood was educated at Harvard. After serving as a navigator in
the Army Air Forces during World War II, he returned to his
birthplace in 1945 and joined the family business. After his
father's death in 1960, he began to steer the company toward the
pursuit of worldwide growth. In 1968 he changed the company's name
to American Multi-Cinema, which has become today's AMC
Entertainment.
</P>
<P>
   Durwood is survived by his wife, Pamela Yax Durwood of Kansas
City; a sister, Marjorie Durwood Grant, also of Kansas City; a
brother, Richard Durwood, of Mission Hills, Kan.; and six children,
Carol Journagan, of Blue Springs, Mo.; Edward D. Durwood, of
Shawnee Mission, Kan.; Thomas A. Durwood, of Rancho Santa Fe,
Calif.; Brian D. Durwood, of Corte Madera, Calif.; Elissa Grodin,
of Wilton, Conn., and Peter J. Durwood, of New York City. He is
also survived by 13 grandchildren.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-15-99 2240EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990715.0501 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-15 22:43 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2026 &Cx1f; taf-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HEALTHCARE-TEXT-2TAKE     07-15 1221
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HEALTHCARE-TEXT-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
 
EXCERPTS FROM DEBATE ON LAWSUITS OVER HEALTH CARE  (rk) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Following are excerpts from remarks by Democratic
Senators Harry Reid of Nevada and Richard J. Durbin of Illinois and
Republicans Slade Gorton of Washington and Rick Santorum of
Pennsylvania in Thursday's debate on a patients' bill of rights as
transcribed by The New York Times.
</P>
<P>
   Reid: There are basically two groups of people who can't be
sued: foreign diplomats and HMOs. That isn't the way it should be.
...
</P>
<P>
   And HMOs ... if they've been involved directly in dictating,
denying or delaying care for a patient, it can use a loophole in
what we call Erisa, the Employee Retirement Income Security Act, to
avoid any responsibility for the consequences of its actions. The
American people simply do not support that.
</P>
<P>
   Erisa was designed to protect employees when they lose pension
benefits due to fraud, mismanagement and employer bankruptcies,
which occurred so often during the '60s. The law now has the effect
of allowing an HMO to deny or delay care with no effective remedy
for patients. What they're trying to do is strike a provision from
our bill which simply insures that HMOs can be held accountable for
their actions, a responsibility owed by every other industry to
consumers. ...
</P>
<P>
   All we wanted to do is make the law apply to HMOs like everyone
else. ...
</P>
<P>
   Durbin:
</P>
<P>
   This is the heart of the debate. This is what the patients' bill
of rights is all about. The insurance companies hate the idea of
being sued in court like the devil hates holy water. They don't
want to be held accountable for their actions. They want to be
protected so that they can make the wrong decision when it comes to
medical care for American families and never, never be held
accountable.
</P>
<P>
   The amendment being offered on the Republican side is an effort
to take away from 123 million Americans the right to hold
health-insurance companies accountable. That is the bottom line,
123 million Americans will be denied an opportunity to go to court
when the health-insurance company makes a decision which costs them
their health or their life. Most people are stunned to know that
you can't take a health-insurance company to court.
</P>
<P>
   Since 1974, a federal law has protected health-insurance
companies from being sued. And what does that mean? When your
doctor wants a certain procedure, a certain medicine, a certain
specialist for your good or the good of your family, and that
doctor is overruled by a health company, health-insurance company
bureaucrat, the doctor is the only one who will be taken to court,
not the health-insurance company.
</P>
<P>
   If we pass nothing else in this patients' bill of rights but
this section which said that health-insurance companies will be
held accountable in court, I would tell you it will be a major
victory for America. I trust the judgment of 12 citizens of this
country in a jury box to decide the fairness and legality of an
issue. ...
</P>
<P>
   For the last two days Senator Kennedy, Senator Reid and all of
my colleagues have brought stories to the floor, chilling,
heart-breaking stories. Here's one: Florence Corcoran. Let me quote
Florence Corcoran. ``They let a clerk thousands of miles away make
a life-threatening decision about my life and my baby's life
without even seeing me and overruled five of my doctors. They don't
get held accountable, and that's what appalls me. I relive that all
the time. Insurance companies don't answer to nobody,'' Florence
Corcoran says. ...
</P>
<P>
   Well if you're listening to this debate you think, well surely
there must be a long roster of companies in America that receive
the same kind of immunity from liability, that can't be brought to
court. No. This is it, folks. This is the only sector of the
American economy, maybe the only sector in America that is going to
be allowed to be held above the law. The Republican majority and
the health-insurance industry is determined to protect their
immunity from a lawsuit so that Florence Corcoran whose life and
the life of her baby was threatened by a decision by a
health-insurance company cannot even take that health-insurance
company to court. ...
</P>
<P>
   The state of Texas passed a patients' bill of rights. Said you
could take the health-insurance company in court for certain
insured people in Texas. Well you would think from the arguments
from the Republican side that the sky fell on Texas two years ago.
It didn't happen. You know how many lawsuits have been filed since
this law was enacted? A law which Governor Bush vetoed and the
legislature overrode his veto on? Three lawsuits. Three lawsuits in
two years. Does that sound like we're flooding the courts? But I'll
tell you something, in that state for those who are protected by
that law, I'll bet you there's been a change in the way that they
do business.
</P>
<P>
   Gorton:
</P>
<P>
   President, nothing could more dramatically illustrate the
difference in general attitudes and attitudes toward health care
between the senator from Massachusetts and the members on this side
than his statement that his bill was preferable to ours because it
would only cost the American people $7 billion while ours would
cost the American people $13 billion.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, of course, overwhelmingly, the costs of his bill will
be evidenced in higher taxes on the American people. His so-called
costs of our bill are in fact the reduction of taxes on the
American people so that they can use their own money to make more
of their own health-care costs. But to the senator from
Massachusetts, it's the same thing. More taxes or less taxes. We do
not think that that is the same thing by any stretch of the
imagination. In addition, of course, he ignores entirely as costs
the costs imposed on the American people by paying higher
health-insurance premiums. Those, presumably, are irrelevant.
</P>
<P>
   But the subject before us primarily is lawsuits. There is
widespread agreement, even in this body and across the United
States, that the medical malpractice system is simply broken; that
it comes too late, that it costs so much, that less than half of
the dollars that it costs ever get to victims and the rest are
consumed by lawyers and by the administration of the system itself.
The problem is, of course, we have never come up with a majority
for a way in which to fix that medical malpractice system. But the
proposition that it is broken is very, very widely held.
</P>
<P>
   It is into that broken system that the Democrats' plan pours
another element of our health-care system and says, oh, the system
may be broken but the only solution is to make it worse, is to make
it more widespread, pouring good wine into a broken bottle. With
what impact? Better health care? No. We know that the medical
malpractice system doesn't create more and better health care. More
lawsuits? Clearly, yes. One aspect of that broken system, of
course, is that the cost gets not into providing better health care
for the people of the country but into the system itself. But the
patients, ultimately, the people who buy insurance, the people who
consume health care, pay the entire bill, including all of the
bills for the lawyers. What impact? Higher costs for everyone who
is insured. And therefore fewer insured.
</P>
<P>
   Santorum: A lot has been said about you can't sue your HMO. Here
are three Federal Circuit Court cases and 12 Federal District Court
cases who said that Erisa does not pre-empt state law when you want
to sue your HMO for malpractice. ...
</P>
<P>
   So the issue is not whether you can sue your HMO. That's not why
we're so adamantly against the provision in the Kennedy bill. It is
not to be able to sue your HMO. I don't have any problem with you
being able to sue your HMO. What I do have a problem with is what
this bill does is allow you to sue your employer ... for a decision
made by an HMO, by an insurance company. What will that mean? ...
</P>
<P>
   I've talked to dozens, dozens of employers who said if you are
going to open up the books of my corporation, and I make widgets,
or I make steel, or I make desks, or I make pencils, and you're
going to open up my books for my employees to sue me for a decision
my insurance company that I hired made, I can't afford, I'm not in
the business of health care. I'm not managing these health-care
decisions. I hired someone to do that, but I'm going to get sued
for their decision.
</P>
<P>
   Sorry, as much as I'd love to provide group health insurance to
you, I can't allow our corporation, our effort to be jeopardized by
a decision that someone outside of what I do made. I can't let it
happen. ...
</P>
<P>
   Who would be the first person, once these employers drop their
insurance as a result of this bill, who would be the first person
to run to the Senate floor and say these nasty employers, look at
them they're dropping their insurance. We need the government to
take over the health-care system. Yes, the senator from
Massachusetts would be the first person here on the Senate floor
calling for a government health-care system.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-15-99 2243EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
