<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-15 22:45 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2028 &Cx1f; tth-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PIPELINE-SPI &LR;      07-15 0988
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PIPELINE-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CONGRESSMAN DEMANDS INQUIRY OF PIPELINE SAFETY AFTER ACCIDENT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By MICHAEL PAULSON  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Pointing to the deaths of three people when an oil
pipeline exploded in Bellingham last month, a top member of
Congress on Thursday demanded a wide-ranging congressional
investigation into the federal government's regulation of pipeline
safety.
</P>
<P>
   The demand by Rep. John Dingell, D-Mich., came on the same day
that Sen. Patty Murray, D-Wash., summoned Transportation Secretary
Rodney Slater to her office seeking stepped-up inspections of
pipelines in Washington state and assurances that there would be no
rush to reopen the Bellingham pipeline, about 90 miles north of
Seattle.
</P>
<P>
   Slater, whose department is responsible for pipeline safety,
pledged not to allow Olympic Pipe Line to reopen the pipe until he
can guarantee its safety, and promised to consider Murray's request
that he permanently station a federal pipeline inspector in
Washington state.
</P>
<P>
   But Slater also defended the administration's handling of
pipeline safety, and rejected suggestions that his department's
Office of Pipeline Safety is too close to the oil and gas industry
it is supposed to regulate.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is an administration guided by a president and a vice
president that say we're going to put the American people first,''
Slater said after meeting with Murray.
</P>
<P>
   ``That doesn't mean that we're not going to work in partnership
with industry and with safety advocates, but I can assure you that
our meeting today has been focused on the people who are involved
here, and that's what our commitment is. We will work with
industry; we will regulate industry in a way that protects the
American people.''
</P>
<P>
   The actions by Dingell and Murray mark the first public steps
members of Congress have taken in response to the June 10 explosion
in Bellingham, when Olympic's 16-inch pipeline ruptured, sending
hundreds of thousands of gallons of gasoline into Whatcom Creek.
Gasoline vapor ignited, burning two 10-year-old boys to death. A
teenager died after he was overcome by fumes, fell in the creek and
drowned.
</P>
<P>
   The explosion is likely to be explored in depth by Congress,
which has just begun debating the renewal of the nation's pipeline
safety laws, which expire next year.
</P>
<P>
   Murray, who toured the Bellingham site last Friday, pledged to
play an active role in the debate over renewal of pipeline safety
laws, even though she does not sit on a committee with jurisdiction
over the office. She said she pushed Slater not to reopen the
Olympic pipeline too quickly, to station an inspector permanently
in Washington state and to support right-to-know actions that would
alert communities to potential pipeline safety problems.
</P>
<P>
   ``I expressed to him my desire to work with him to make sure
that we do everything we can to make sure this community is safe
before the pipeline reopens, and also to prospectively do
everything we can to make sure this doesn't happen anywhere
again,'' Murray said. ``I intend to be working on the pipeline
reauthorization bill to make sure we are doing everything we can
... and I will be looking at whether or not we should improve the
standards, or the reporting requirements, or the community's right
to know about any anomalies that exist in the pipeline or any
safety conditions that exist in their neighborhoods.''
</P>
<P>
   Slater said Olympic Pipe Line will have to take numerous
corrective actions before being allowed to reopen.
</P>
<P>
   ``We do not plan to reopen this pipeline until the standards
have been met, until we can ensure the safety of the pipeline for
the people there in Bellingham,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   As for Murray's request that he station an inspector in
Washington, Slater said, ``we will consider that.''
</P>
<P>
   There are 55 federal inspectors responsible for inspecting all
interstate pipelines in the United States, and states employ
another 250 inspectors to handle intrastate pipelines. Of the 55
federal inspectors, 10 are responsible for the Western United
States, including eight in Denver and two in Alaska.
</P>
<P>
   Dingell, the longest-serving member of the House, is a longtime
critic of pipeline safety and the top Democrat on the House
Commerce Committee, which has jurisdiction over the Office of
Pipeline Safety. Late Thursday he sent a detailed letter to the
General Accounting Office, the investigative arm of Congress,
seeking a broad investigation of the Office of Pipeline Safety.
</P>
<P>
   Dingell cited not only the June 10 Bellingham accident, but also
a 1994 pipeline explosion in New Jersey that destroyed an apartment
complex and a 1993 leak in Virginia that caused environmental and
property damage.
</P>
<P>
   ``While the effectiveness of current law remains unclear, so too
does the effectiveness of the agency charged with administering
that law, the Department of Transportation's Office of Pipeline
Safety,'' Dingell wrote. ``Congress, for its part, must try to
ensure that our pipeline safety laws and the agency charged with
enforcing those laws are working in a manner that protects the
public and the environment.''
</P>
<P>
   Dingell asked the GAO to review virtually every allegation made
by the numerous critics of the Office of Pipeline Safety. He also
asked the GAO to determine the validity of accusations that the
Office of Pipeline Safety has ignored directives from Congress and
recommendations of the National Transportation Safety Board.
</P>
<P>
   Dingell also called upon the GAO to determine whether there were
actions the Office of Pipeline Safety could have taken to prevent
the Bellingham accident, and to supply a list of all key
recommendations to strengthen pipeline safety efforts.
</P>
<P>
   Although Dingell cannot order the GAO to conduct an
investigation, the agency is certain to do so in response to a
request from such a senior member of Congress.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
