<DOCNO> NYT19990715.0504 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-15 22:49 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2030 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SPORTS-BRA16-COX     07-15 0827
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SPORTS-BRA16-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Tempest in a B cup?
 &HT;    By Lillian Lee Kim
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Raise your hand if you were truly upset by the sight
of Brandi Chastain's sports bra.
</P>
<P>
   Thought so.
</P>
<P>
   Depending on who you listen to, Chastain's act of whipping off
her soccer jersey at the World Cup, thereby uncovering her black
Nike sports bra, was everything from brazen exhibitionism, to a
calculated ploy for an endorsement contract with Nike, to an
Amazonian roar of female athletic empowerment.
</P>
<P>
   People. Isn't this a sports bra we're talking about?
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't see what the big deal is at all,'' said Lynn Leonard,
34, who wore a navy Adidas sports top while running along the
Chattahoochee River on a recent afternoon. ``It's really a matter
of comfort. Especially in Atlanta, where it's so hot all the
time.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Good for her,'' cheered 54-year-old Cheryl May as she pushed a
jogging stroller containing her granddaughter. ``I thought it was
terrific.''
</P>
<P>
   Many people seem to share Leonard's indifference or May's
enthusiasm. But a vocal minority, many of whom apparently belong to
the media, seemed to read more into it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hey, her name is Chastain, not Chaste,'' quipped Time
magazine. The Atlanta Journal's editorial board scolded Chastain
for scoring ``no points as a role model and hero.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought it was tacky and cheesy, another example of the
masculinization of women,'' said WGST radio host Kim Peterson, who
devoted most of his Monday call-in show to the Brandi Bra Moment.
``If it's OK for women to rip off their shirts and walk around in
their sports bras, men should be able to rip off their pants and
walk around in their jockstraps.''
</P>
<P>
   Well, no, not really, says Rose Getch, spokeswoman for Champion
JogBra, which leads the $415 million sports bra industry.
(Ironically, the first sports bra consisted of two jockstraps
stitched together _ and was an undergarment.)
</P>
<P>
   See, most modern sports bras are designed to be worn as
outerwear. They come in solids and patterns, sometimes with
matching shorts. In addition to traditional athletic wear
manufacturers such as Champion, Danskin and Nike, couturiers
including Ralph Lauren, Tommy Hilfiger and Donna Karan now make
them.
</P>
<P>
   Jockstraps, by contrast, do not come in designer prints and are
never meant to see the light of day.
</P>
<P>
   ``What Brandi was wearing was an outerwear sports bra,'' Getch
said. ``It is perfectly acceptable to wear those outside. People do
every day.''
</P>
<P>
   On a summer day in Atlanta, chances are that one in every two or
three women exercising outdoors is wearing a sports bra without a
T-shirt or other cover-up.
</P>
<P>
   But those disturbed by the Bra Moment say they aren't generally
offended by the sight of women wearing sports bras in public. The
problem apparently is a temporal one: Chastain spent the whole game
in a shirt, then took it off.
</P>
<P>
   ``I bet it was the act of taking off her shirt that bothered
people,'' Leonard mused.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was the act of doing it itself that really bothered me,''
Peterson said.
</P>
<P>
   Even some of those who didn't mind said they initially were
startled when Chastain tore off her shirt.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was shocked just at first,'' said Atlantan Jay Lown, 29,
clad in a rainbow-hued biking jersey.
</P>
<P>
   Chastain's champions point out that male soccer players
regularly strip off their jerseys in victorious glee. They
challenge her detractors to go outside at lunchtime and jog for,
say, 90 minutes, the duration of a soccer game, and then see how
they feel about layered clothing.
</P>
<P>
   ``No one would have said anything if a man had done it,'' said
Barbara Harris, editor in chief of Shape, a leading women's fitness
magazine, which first featured a model in a sports bra on its cover
in November 1992. ``I just couldn't even believe there were
negative comments made. Women are being held to a different
standard of behavior than male athletes.''
</P>
<P>
   Peterson puts it slightly differently: ``Just because men are
pigs doesn't mean women have to be,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   That's a common bias, says Sarah Mahoney, editor in chief of
Fitness magazine, another popular women's fitness periodical.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some people are against women being flamboyant in sports,''
said Mahoney, who watched the World Cup with her 7-year-old
soccer-playing daughter. ``Men have their whole little dances. They
even have names for them.''
</P>
<P>
   Dirty Bird, anyone?
</P>
<P>
   For the record, Nike did pay Chastain for helping design the bra
over a year ago but says it won't be giving her any ``additional
compensation'' for the, uh, product exposure. The model will arrive
in stores July 25, with a price tag of $40.
</P>
<P>
   All this fuss over a basic item of sports equipment. In
Chastain's case, a sweaty one. Not sexy. Not titillating.
</P>
<P>
   ``Like Freud said, sometimes a cigar is just a cigar,'' Mahoney
said.
</P>
<P>
   Not these days, it isn't.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-15-99 2249EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990715.0505 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-15 22:49 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2031 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-INTEL-INTEL_SFCHRON &LR;      07-15 0666
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INTEL-INTEL </SLUG>
 _ SF CHRON  
 Intel to Sell Devices Giving Speedy Access to the Internet  &HT;     By Henry Norr 
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
In the latest move to diversify its business, Intel yesterday
announced plans to sell devices that give home and small-business
users high-speed access to the Internet.
<P>
   The first of the new products will be modems for use on DSL
(Digital Subscriber Line) connections, which provide speedy access
to the Net over standard phone wires. The move is part of Intel's
effort to expand beyond its role as the dominant supplier of chips
for personal computers. The Santa Clara company, spokesman Michael
Sullivan said, aims to be a ``building-block supplier to the
Internet economy.''
</P>
<P>
   In recent months, Intel has acquired several networking
companies and announced plans to set up ``server farms'' hosting
Web sites for other businesses. Just yesterday, the company
announced a reorganization of its growing portfolio of networking
initiatives, including creation of a new Communications Products
Group.
</P>
<P>
   The new Intel modems, which are slated to begin shipping this
fall, initially will be distributed by the telecommunications
companies that provide DSL service. But in a few years, once
standards have matured, the company expects to sell them through PC
manufacturers and even retail outlets, according to Mark
Christensen, vice president and general manager of the company's
Network Communications Group.
</P>
<P>
   As part of the new product plan, Intel's Broadband Access
Operation signed a technology agreement with Cisco Systems, the
leader in the Internet networking equipment market. Cisco already
offers DSL modems. The deal will help Intel get its version to
market quickly and ensure its compatibility with the Cisco DSL
equipment used in many telecommunications switching offices.
</P>
<P>
   The Intel modems will be based on two new international
standards, G.lite and G.DMT, that are intended to simplify DSL
setup and ensure that products from different vendors work smoothly
together.
</P>
<P>
   Current DSL products, however, don't always work together, and
even though the new standards were ratified last month by the
International Telecommunications Union, industry observers expect
it could be several years before all systems are fully compatible.
</P>
<P>
   DSL runs over the same copper phone lines used for voice
traffic. G.lite, the standard intended for consumers, provides
speeds of 1.5 megabits per second, more than 25 times the speed of
the fastest analog modems.
</P>
<P>
   Regional phone companies as well as several startups
specializing in the technology are promoting it as their high-speed
Internet access solution for home users and small businesses. In
the United States, the number of DSL lines installed lags far
behind the total for cable modems, an alternative technology for
high-speed Net access promoted by cable TV providers and now by
telecom giant AT&AMP;T.
</P>
<P>
   In the Bay Area, however, DSL is off to an early lead. The
service is offered by Pacific Bell and through many Internet
service providers. By contrast, TCI, the region's dominant cable
provider, has stumbled repeatedly in its efforts to deploy cable
modems here.
</P>
<P>
   Worldwide, there are currently fewer than 900,000 DSL lines
installed, according to Cahners In-Stat Group, a technology
research group. But next year, In-Stat predicts, the total will
climb by more than 150 percent, passing the 2 million mark, and by
2003 it is expected to exceed 8.5 million.
</P>
<P>
   Intel has been active in development and standardization of
several broadband technologies, including cable modems and
satellite data transmission as well as DSL.
</P>
<P>
   Sullivan refused to say whether the company will eventually
supplement its DSL modem line with cable or satellite products, but
he noted that the Intel group in charge has the generic term
``broadband,'' not ``DSL,'' in its names. ``It was chosen very
deliberately,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service Clients) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
