<HEADER>
A2033 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-WORKWAYS-WORKWAYS_SFC     07-15 0895
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WORKWAYS-WORKWAYS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WORKWAYS/ILANA DEBARE 
</HEADLINE>
 _ SF CHRON   Mouthing Off Can Get You Fired 
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
Q: Yesterday, I was fired from my job as a classified ad taker at a
nonunion newspaper. The official reason was ``insubordination.''
Here's what happened: The company suddenly cut our monthly
commission rates in half.
<P>
   My boss wouldn't give me a clear reason why, so I started
talking to the other sales reps about our pay. My boss then
demanded to know what I had been talking to them about. I said it
was none of his business, and when he insisted that it was, I told
him that was bull_. He then informed me that I was suspended.
</P>
<P>
   As I got up to leave, I said, ``Heil Hitler.'' (I thought it was
amusing.) The next day, I was fired for reasons that included
``using Nazi references, which creates a hostile work
environment.'' At no time did anyone ask for my side of the story.
Do I have any legal recourse?
</P>
<P>
   A: There's more than enough blame to go around on both sides
here. This company sounds like it does a crummy job of
communicating with its employees. Your boss should realize he's not
going to inspire loyalty by ordering people to disclose their
private conversations; if anything, he'll just make them more
defensive or angry.
</P>
<P>
   But using profanity with your boss is no way to respond to bad
management.
</P>
<P>
   And comments like ``Heil Hitler'' may sound witty when recounted
in a bar at 2 a.m., but they don't belong in a workplace.
</P>
<P>
   The upshot? The company probably had the right to fire you
unless you were covered by a union contract guaranteeing you
additional warnings before termination.
</P>
<P>
   ``This person acted unprofessionally and was insubordinate and
fresh,'' said Barbara Lawless, a San Francisco lawyer who
represents workers in employment disputes. ``I wouldn't take that
case, not with a 10-foot pole.''
</P>
<P>
   This company should take a hard look at its management policies
and figure out a way to inspire more trust and open communication.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, you need to figure out whether you want to
succeed in future jobs _ and if so, adjust your attitude.
</P>
<P>
   Anywhere you work, you'll find occasional dumb policies,
irritating co-workers or bad bosses. Mouthing off isn't the answer.
Instead, try keeping your cool, doing your job and offering
criticism in a level-headed manner.
</P>
<P>
   You won't be able to solve the problems of truly dysfunctional
workplaces, but you can at least emerge with a reputation as a
professional and dependable team player.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Retrieving Personal Items
</P>
<P>
   Q: I have worked for a company for 18 years. I had a lot of
personal items on my computer at the time. Is there any way I can
get copies of the items on my computer so that I can transfer them
to my computer at home?
</P>
<P>
   A: From the wording of your question, I'm assuming that you no
longer work for the company _ or no longer use the particular PC
where your personal documents were stored.
</P>
<P>
   You really have no legal right to those documents. The computer
and all the files stored on it are property of the company.
</P>
<P>
   So your only choice is simply to ask the company for permission
to retrieve your personal files.
</P>
<P>
   Most companies wouldn't have a problem with such a request from
a longtime employee who left on good terms. However, managers may
be worried about your taking confidential business files off their
computer. If so, you could offer to let someone from the firm look
over your shoulder while you copy your files to a floppy disk.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Short Notice
</P>
<P>
   Q: A co-worker gave two weeks' notice. Our boss then informed
him that he would only need to work one week. Is he eligible to be
paid for the entire two weeks?
</P>
<P>
   A: Nope. Unless your colleague was covered by a union contract
or individual employment contract, he most likely was an at-will
employee.
</P>
<P>
   And at-will employment means that either the worker or the
company can terminate the relationship at any time, for any reason.
</P>
<P>
   Your colleague did the ethical, courteous thing by giving two
weeks' notice before leaving. It would have been nice if the
company had thanked him for the advance notice rather than
terminating him even earlier.
</P>
<P>
   But nice or not, his dismissal is still probably legal.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Car-Phone Quandry
</P>
<P>
   Last week, I wrote that injuries from car crashes while
commuting to work generally are not covered by workers'
compensation. One reader posed an interesting question: What if the
accident occurs while you're holding a work-related conversation on
your car phone?
</P>
<P>
   Ron Christensen, spokesman for the State Compensation Insurance
Fund, said there's not yet any clear legal precedent that would
cover all such cases. ``If work conversations on the car phone were
a normal part of the employee's routine, they could probably file a
claim,'' said Christensen. ``Judges would probably decide it on a
case-by-case basis.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Farewell Note
</P>
<P>
   After two years writing Workways, I'm moving on to a new
challenge _ writing a book and being a visiting scholar at Mills
College. Many thanks to all my expert sources for sharing their
knowledge of human resources and employment law. And thanks to you,
readers, for sharing your questions and conundrums about the work
world. I've learned a lot and hope I've managed to help some of
you, too.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service Clients) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
