<SLUG> BC-NY-LAWYERS-CODE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BAR CLARIFIES CONDUCT RULES FOR LAWYERS IN NEW YORK
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 By ANTHONY RAMIREZ   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The New York State Bar Association Thursday announced
changes in its code of conduct, clarifying rules on how
aggressively lawyers can solicit clients, barring lawyers from
coercing sex from clients, and liberalizing the restrictions on
when lawyers can talk to the press.
</P>
<P>
   Roy D. Simon, who teaches legal ethics at Hofstra University
School of Law, said the changes were important, as they made
explicit what was once assumed. ``The new rules say that
transactions between lawyers and clients have to be fair and
reasonable to the client,'' he said. ``The old rules did not
specifically demand fairness or reasonableness.''
</P>
<P>
   Mary C. Daly, who teaches legal ethics at Fordham University
School of Law, said the revisions ``bring New York into the 21st
century.''
</P>
<P>
   Violations of the 70-page Lawyer's Code of Professional
Responsibility can lead to censure, suspension or loss of license
to practice. New York has 120,000 lawyers, second only to
California, said Steven C. Krane, chairman of an eight-member state
bar committee that revised the rules. In 1997, the latest year for
which data is available, 231 New York lawyers were disciplined,
including 79 who were disbarred.
</P>
<P>
   The code was last revised in 1990.
</P>
<P>
   ``The hot issues were mainly advertising and solicitation,''
said Krane, a lawyer who represents the NBA and the NHL.
</P>
<P>
   The previous code barred all forms of solicitation by lawyers,
but recent U.S. Supreme Court decisions allow virtually all forms
of advertising and solicitation as long as they are not false and
misleading. Under the new state rules, lawyers can send
solicitations, but not to victims of disasters like plane crashes.
``Sending letters to hospitals or to people who are bereaved means
that they cannot make an informed judgment,'' Krane said.
</P>
<P>
   Lawyers can also claim in advertisements that they specialize in
a particular form of law, like immigration, but only if they are
certified by a group approved by the American Bar Association.
``They also have to put in a disclaimer that this doesn't
necessarily mean that they are better lawyers than anyone else,''
Krane said.
</P>
<P>
   There has always been an almost complete ban on divorce lawyers
having sex with their clients, said Krane, but the new rules expand
the prohibition to all lawyers. The new rules apply only to lawyers
who ``enter into'' sexual relations with clients, Krane said. They
do not apply to previous, continuing sexual relationships.
</P>
<P>
   The new rules ban the coercion of sexual favors from a client or
``a third party,'' like a relative. Previous versions of the code
alluded only to ``conduct prejudicial to the administration of
justice'' and did not define sexual relations, which the revised
code does.
</P>
<P>
   The old code discouraged most lawyers' statements to the press,
but now allows a right of rebuttal if opposing counsel states
something that may prejudice the trial. The new rules say a lawyer
may make a press statement if it is ``necessary to mitigate the
recent adverse publicity.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Daly, the Fordham professor, said: ``It's an eye-for-an-eye
and a tooth-for-a-tooth proposition. If the prosecution says your
client flunked a lie-detector test, which isn't admissible in
court, you can answer back.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
