 &UR; FOR SAN FRANCISCO CHRONICLE PAGE ONE &QL;  &LR; 
CHEVRON _ Chevron is asking for a waiver to sell gas that doesn't
meet California environmental standards because 70% of its plant
capacity in Richmond was knocked out by a gas explosion last
weekend. By Rebecca Smith
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FOR CHRONICLE BUSINESS SECTION &QL;  &LR; 
 &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR; TEMPS _ Microsoft's long-term temporary employees have already
challenged a key pillar of high-tech business practices, by filing
a landmark lawsuit aimed at getting some of the same benefits as
permanent employees. Now Microsoft ``permatemps'' are trying
another kind of tactic to improve their status at the company _
they are asking the company to recognize them as a union and
bargain over wages and working conditions. Last month about 20
MBAs, accountants and lawyers who are writing code and content for
an MS financial-software project signed a petition asking a local
union to represent them. By Ilana DeBare
</P>
<P>
   TEMPSIDE _ Seattle isn't the only area where labor unions are
trying to make inroads into high-tech. In Silicon Valley, labor is
trying an unusual strategy to improve the lot of temporary clerical
workers at high-tech firms. The local labor council has started its
own (nonprofit) temp staffing firm, aimed at ratcheting up wages
and benefits for valley temps. By Ilana DeBare
</P>
