<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-15 22:53 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2038 &Cx1f; kan-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HOGS-LAWSUIT-KAN &LR;      07-15 0753
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOGS-LAWSUIT-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SETTLEMENT APPEARS NEAR IN MISSOURI LAWSUIT AGAINST HOG PRODUCER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL MANSUR  
 c. 1997 The Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The state of Missouri may be close to settling a pollution
lawsuit against Premium Standard Farms, the state's largest hog
producer. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Any settlement will require the company to install equipment to
treat large volumes of hog wastes, Attorney General Jay Nixon
said. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``If I do settle,'' Nixon said, ``I would only do so if it
includes the company installing the next generation of waste
treatment technology.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In January, Nixon sued Kansas City-based Premium Standard Farms
in Jackson County Circuit Court, accusing the company of repeated
hog-waste spills, failure to report past spills and excessive
spraying of wastes on farm fields. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The suit asked for $10,000 a day in fines for each violation. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Environmental groups and Nixon want corporate hog farms to be
treated more like industries and cities, whose collected wastes
must be treated to reduce pollutants before being discharged onto
land or into streams and rivers. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Ozark chapter of the Sierra Club said Thursday that it had
obtained a copy of a draft settlement between Nixon's office and
Premium Standard Farms. The group declined to release a copy,
saying it might tip off the source of the draft. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   But the group said the draft settlement included these terms: &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The company would pay $1 million in fines, $650,000 of it up
front. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The company would install up to $25 million worth of equipment
in the next five years to treat its hog wastes. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   If it installed that equipment and complied with other
requirements, the company could avoid paying the $350,000 balance
of the fine. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In return, the company would be exempt from new lawsuits by
Missouri. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Not everyone is happy with the proposed settlement. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd call it a sellout of the environment and family farms,''
said Ken Midkiff, the Sierra Club's program director. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The proposal is too weak and doesn't require set limits for the
treated wastewater, Midkiff said. It also would seem to allow the
company to pay the balance of its fine _ the $350,000 _ rather than
install all of the treatment equipment, Midkiff said. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``What kind of businessman wouldn't spend $350,000 to save $25
million?'' Midkiff said. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   What's more, Midkiff said, the settlement would preclude future
lawsuits against the company. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``The enforcement provisions are absent,'' he said. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Premium Standard Farms spokesman Charlie Arnot and Nixon
declined to say whether the settlement included a $1 million
penalty or requirements for $25 million in new treatment
equipment. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't comment at all on anything that's part of the
settlement,'' Arnot said. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   But he said his company hoped it could strike a deal that would
benefit it and the state of Missouri. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Arnot declined to say how much such equipment would cost for an
operation as large as Premium Standard's in north Missouri, where
the company produces more than 2 million hogs a year. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Sierra Club contends that north Missouri has the nation's
largest concentration of hogs and hog wastes, although a newer
operation in Utah may rival it. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Nixon said he thought a settlement could be completed in a week
to 10 days. He said he had been involved in the negotiations. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Nixon was in Kansas City on Thursday to address a workshop on
regulating concentrated animal feeding operations for the National
Association of Attorneys General. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Nixon urged attorneys general in other states to regulate the
large farms. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Missouri family farms have a system of accountability in
place,'' Nixon said. ``It's called being a good neighbor. These new
neighbors, the large pork factories, do not have a good neighbor
policy. Their policy is the bottom line.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Hundreds of north Missouri residents were expected to meet
Thursday night in Trenton to address Premium Standard Farms' newest
plans. The company has asked for new permits to spray hog wastes on
nearly 25,000 acres in north Missouri. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Sierra Club contends that although the terms of the permits
have been strengthened since last year, they are not tough enough. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Current state permits allow the company to spray about 750
million gallons of hog wastes over 45,000 acres of north Missouri.
The company has said it isn't expanding operations, but gaining
permission to spray wastes on new lands. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
