<HEADLINE>
JEWISH SETTLEMENTS IN OCCUPIED TERRITORIES QUICKLY RULED ILLEGAL  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   GENEVA, Switzerland _ Less than one hour after it began, a
conference on whether Jewish settlements in territories occupied by
Israel violate international law adjourned Thursday after declaring
that the settlements are illegal.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The closed session, ordered by the U.N. General Assembly last
February, was held over objections by both Israel and the United
States. The Palestinians, who had been pressing for the gathering,
said they were satisfied with the conference. They said they had
wanted to send a message but not disrupt the peace efforts of
Israel's new prime minister, Ehud Barak.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our drive to get the conference coincided with a total change
in Israeli politics,'' said Nabil Shaath, the top Palestinian
official at the meeting. ``We hope that there won't be a need for
another conference like this,'' he added.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Noting the ``improved atmosphere in the Middle East as a
whole,'' the resolution approved by the conference stated that it
had adjourned ``on the understanding that it will convene again in
the light of consultations on the development of the humanitarian
situation in the field.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   At issue is whether the settlements violate the Fourth Geneva
Convention, which forbids transferring populations in occupied
territories.  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
