<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-15 22:54 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2040 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PATIENT-RIGHTS-HNS &LR;      07-15 1130
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PATIENT-RIGHTS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GOP PULLS PLUG ON DEMOCRATS' HEALTH BILL 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By GREG McDONALD 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Republican senators delivered a death blow to the
Democrats' managed care bill Thursday by defeating a crucial
amendment that would have allowed people to sue their health
maintenance organizations and by passing their own more moderate
patients' protection measure that would cover fewer people.
</P>
<P>
   The lawsuit amendment, which was modeled after laws in Georgia
and Texas, was rejected along party lines by a vote of 53-47, with
only two Republicans _ Sens. Arlen Specter of Pennsylvania and John
Chaffee of Rhode Island _ joining all 45 Senate Democrats to
support it.
</P>
<P>
   The measure, offered by Sen. Richard Durbin, D-Ill., was at the
heart of the Democrats' so-called patients' bill-of-rights plan,
which was aimed at strengthening regulations governing the managed
care systems. The proposed legislation was prompted by a
proliferation of complaints in recent years against HMOs as they
have grown to become the only choice available to many employers
and Americans in search of affordable health insurance.
</P>
<P>
   Senate Majority Leader Trent Lott, R-Miss., said most
Republicans rejected the Durbin measure because it would place
``the scalpels of litigation in trial lawyers' hands and invite
them to carve up the nation's health care system.''
</P>
<P>
   The Republicans also ensured the death of the Democratic bill by
killing two other key amendments that would have expanded access to
specialists and emergency services for all 161 million of the
nation's privately insured, and which would have allowed doctors
instead of insurers to make final decisions on the medical
necessity of treatments.
</P>
<P>
   One of the biggest complaints against HMOs has come from doctors
and patients who believe that insurers, motivated by cost concerns,
often deny treatments or other services that may be medically
necessary.
</P>
<P>
   Throughout the politically-charged and often rancorous four-day
debate, Republicans repeatedly accused the Democrats of trying to
revive President Clinton's universal health care proposal, which
failed in 1994, and which they referred to as ``socialized''
medicine. They said the Democratic patients' protection bill would
have amounted to new government mandates on states and would have
drastically increased the costs of average health care plans for
most Americans.
</P>
<P>
   After dismantling the Democratic plan piece by piece, the
Republicans voted 53-47 late Thursday to pass their own, less
expansive managed care proposal, which would cover about one-third
of the 161 million privately insured Americans who would have
benefited from the Democrats' proposal.
</P>
<P>
   Although Republicans insisted that some provisions in their bill
_ such as providing longer hospital stays for women who have
mastectomies _ would apply to a larger number of insured women, the
GOP alternative was crafted primarily to address the 48 million
Americans who are covered through large employer self-funded health
care plans that do not fall under state regulations.
</P>
<P>
   The Democrats charged that most of the provisions in the GOP
bill do not address HMO problems at all and are weighted in favor
of the insurer over the patient.
</P>
<P>
   In an appearance at the White House, Clinton denounced the
Republican plan as short-sighted and suggested that it was designed
to protect the profits of the nation's huge $320 billion health
insurance industry.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a sad day for health care in America,'' Clinton said of
the Republicans' rejection of the broader Democratic proposal
</P>
<P>
   ``But we're not done yet and this won't die,'' he added,
suggesting that the issue of patient protections would likely play
a prominent role in next year's election.
</P>
<P>
   At a news conference on Capitol Hill, Vice President Al Gore
took Clinton's comments one step further. He called the GOP
alternative ``a fraud'' and declared that Clinton would veto it
``in a minute'' if it reaches his desk.
</P>
<P>
   Durbin went even further. In a floor speech after Republicans
rejected his amendment to allow lawsuits against HMOs, he accused
them of working with the insurance industry to reject any
Democrat-sponsored plan designed to put patient interests ahead of
the insurers.
</P>
<P>
   Under the Republican-adopted measure, the health insurance
companies ``won't be answerable to the law and they won't have to
provide the kind of health care that every American counts on,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Despite losing their two-year battle to pass a managed care
bill, the Democrats did at least succeed in putting Republicans on
the record in opposing some popular initiatives aimed at giving
Americans more control over coverage decisions made by their health
plans, particularly HMOs. This, they said, could help Democratic
candidates in close elections.
</P>
<P>
   But Republicans said they were confident that passage of their
own bill, even if it never becomes law, will help deflect
Democratic criticism in races next year.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think there's been a political downside for us passing
this legislation,'' said Sen. Don Nickles, R-Okla.
</P>
<P>
   He challenged Clinton to accept the Republican bill and work to
ensure its passage in the House, which may consider several managed
care proposals later in the year.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope the president decides not to play politics. I hope that
he will work with us to pass legislation that improves health care
quality for all Americans,'' Nickles said.
</P>
<P>
   He and other Republicans insisted that their version of a
patients protection bill strikes a ``critical balance'' in holding
down costs and holding the nation's health care system accountable.
</P>
<P>
   ``Protecting quality and access, that's what its all about,''
said Sen. Susan Collins, R-Maine, who offered a number of
amendments during the debate that were similar to Democratic
proposals, but which did not cover as many people.
</P>
<P>
   Still, at least one Republican disagreed, admonishing his
colleagues that despite their claims to the contrary, the
GOP-sponsored legislation will not cover ``all insured Americans.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The Republican legislation will not do that,'' said Chaffee,
one of three Republicans to vote against the GOP bill.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we ought to give patients the right to sue and we will
not do that,'' he added.
</P>
<P>
   Chaffee joined with Sen. Bob Graham, D-Fla., in scolding his
colleagues for letting the American people down, as he put it, by
not considering compromise legislation the two had tried to offer
that would have combined some of the best provisions of both bills.
</P>
<P>
   Chaffee said that once again Republicans and Democrats had
allowed politics to drive the debate ``to the benefit of no one.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
