u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GLF-SERGIO-GARCIA-ART     07-15 0532
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-SERGIO-GARCIA-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOR YOUNG STAR, RUDE AWAKENING IN DEBUT AS PRO 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(af) 
 By CLIFTON BROWN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   CARNOUSTIE, Scotland _ Even in a nightmare, Sergio Garcia would
probably not have imagined Thursday's events. Garcia entered the
British Open as a 19-year-old sensation, coming off his first
professional victory earlier this month, and he was expected to
play well.
</P>
<P>
   But Thursday he was humbled by a score of 18-over-par 89 on the
demonic Carnoustie layout, and he will remember his first round as
a professional at the British Open for all the wrong reasons.
</P>
<P>
   Garcia came ready to battle Carnoustie, but the course easily
won. Garcia started with a triple-bogey on No. 1, and his day kept
getting worse.
</P>
<P>
   ``I couldn't do anything,'' said Garcia, who returned to answer
questions several hours after he dejectedly left the course. ``The
wind wasn't as hard in practice.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't put pressure on myself or set my goals too high. It's
part of the learning experience. Every single Open has been
difficult, but this year is too tough. But I am young. I will start
again tomorrow.''
</P>
<P>
   Garcia will almost surely miss the cut Friday, no matter how
high it is. But he was glad that he did not quit.
</P>
<P>
   ``It does cross your mind at times that you'd like to walk
off,'' Garcia said. ``At the end, I left because I wanted to be
alone with my family after the day I had. I think it's better to
speak now that I'm calm.''
</P>
<P>
   Mark O'Meara will need a miracle to repeat as the British Open
champion after his opening-round 83. And he admitted that
Thursday's round hurt his pride.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm a professional golfer,'' said O'Meara, who had three
double-bogeys and one triple-bogey. ``I'm not looking forward to
shooting in the 80s, but I felt I got the score I deserved. I drove
the ball pretty badly. I just didn't do very well.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't make a lot of putts. I've seen the weather more
trying, but I've never seen a more difficult or demanding golf
course. Tomorrow, all I can do is try to play better and restore
some of my pride.''
</P>
<P>
   Tom Watson was the last person to win consecutive British Opens,
in 1982 and 1983.
</P>
<P>
   The championship committee of the Royal and Ancient Golf Club
took plenty of criticism from players about the course setup at
Carnoustie.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's an unfair golf course from the standpoint that the
fairways are too narrow,'' said Watson, who has won five British
Opens. ``But Bobby Jones said it wasn't meant to be a fair game.''
</P>
<P>
   Ernie Els, who was only three strokes off the lead after his 74,
was not pleased.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm trying to do the best in a bad situation,'' he said. ``I
don't think anybody has played a golf course like this. Sure they
wanted us to play on a challenging course. I think we've all agreed
they've gone over the top.''
</P>
<P>
   Sandy Lyle who shot an 85, said he could see trouble coming.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were fertilizing the rough and watering it when I was
here playing about two weeks ago,'' Lyle said. ``I think it's just
a joke now.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
