<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOX-FITEFEAT-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MIDDLEWEIGHT VARGAS ISN'T LOOKING FOR FRIENDS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MICHAEL ROSENTHAL  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Get to know IBF junior middleweight champion
Fernando Vargas and you'll probably like him. He's warm, gracious
and his love for his family _ especially his toddler son, Fernando
Jr. _ is touching.
</P>
<P>
   The problem is few become acquainted with a man in his position.
</P>
<P>
   All but those close to the Oxnard, Calif., resident are left to
judge him primarily on sound bites, which more often than not
reveal a brashness that is reminiscent of Muhammad Ali but much
less playful.
</P>
<P>
   Big talent, big mouth.
</P>
<P>
   That about covers Vargas in the opinion of even casual boxing
fans, many of whom are turned on by his immense ability and turned
off by what they perceive to be his arrogance.
</P>
<P>
   ``Man, I'd like to see him lose,'' one disgusted fan said.
</P>
<P>
   Most celebrated of his running commentary is his baiting of
Oscar De La Hoya, the WBC welterweight champion. Vargas doesn't
like his rival and hasn't hesitated to say so.
</P>
<P>
   He has been almost cruel in his analysis of Raul Marquez, a
former Olympian against whom he defends his title on Saturday in
Lake Tahoe: ``Usually, (left-handers) are intelligent, hard to hit.
Raul isn't,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   And, when De La Hoya and Marquez _ who are friends _ dared to
show up at a promotional event near his Big Bear training camp at
which he was the featured guest, he challenged Marquez to take his
championship belt then and there.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's being kind of childish, really,'' said Marquez, 27.
``He's a kid; he talks a lot.''
</P>
<P>
   That might explain part of it.
</P>
<P>
   Vargas !ital!is only 21, an age when most young men are far from
mature. Add to that the fact he's a sudden millionaire and the
focus of immense attention and you get a precarious situation.
</P>
<P>
   His manager and close friend, Rolando Arellano, also admits the
fighter comes from a ``dysfunctional environment'' _ his father
abandoned the family when he was a child _ that has left him with
an aggressive personality.
</P>
<P>
   However, the ``cocky'' label doesn't sit well with Arellano, who
typically jumps in to defend his fighter when that word comes up
during interviews or casual conversations.
</P>
<P>
   To him, Vargas is merely expressing confidence.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to believe you're the best and believe you'll beat
the best. If you don't, you're not going to,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Miller Brewing Co., which recently signed Vargas to a
promotional contract in its ``Think When You Drink'' campaign,
isn't concerned.
</P>
<P>
   Spokesman Marc Spiegel, whose company was enamored with Vargas'
boxing ability, name-recognition in Southern California and the
fact he's Latino, is aware of his reputation for brashness but
dismisses it as typical boxing hype.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Main Events, Vargas' promotional firm, !ital!embraces
its client's proclivity to talk.
</P>
<P>
   Trainer/manager Lou Duva, the patriarch of Main Events, has been
known to be chatty himself. He understands the value of
self-promotion. Positive or negative, it doesn't matter: The idea
is to get people talking about you.
</P>
<P>
   And, like Arellano, he sees it as an expression of confidence.
</P>
<P>
   ``I like a little cockiness in a fighter,'' Duva said.
``Sometimes, fighters who are laid back make the wrong moves
because they're uncertain of themselves. Fernando's certain of
himself.''
</P>
<P>
   Vargas' interpretation? He makes no apologies or excuses.
</P>
<P>
   He doesn't believe the criticism is fair. Those who don't know
him, he said, have no right to judge him.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, he said he'll continue to speak his mind.
</P>
<P>
   For Vargas, it all comes down to respect, a philosophy born of
his experience on Oxnard's tough streets. That, and the lingering
animosity over the fact his father abandoned the family, has left
him with an indelible don't-mess-with-me mentality.
</P>
<P>
   His motto: You can love me or hate me but never disrespect me.
</P>
<P>
   The De La Hoya situation? When he was 14, Vargas and other
teen-age amateurs visited De La Hoya _ whom he idolized _ at his
Big Bear training camp. Apparently, Vargas slipped and fell during
a training run and De La Hoya laughed at him.
</P>
<P>
   Vargas has never forgiven him.
</P>
<P>
   The Marquez situation? Vargas was on a conference call with
reporters when Marquez broke in and questioned Vargas' choice of
opponents _ in hopes of luring him into the ring.
</P>
<P>
   That, as well as the incident at the Big Bear promotional event,
led to Vargas' nasty comments.
</P>
<P>
   Vargas is also feuding with Spanish-language Telemundo. As the
story goes, the television network nicknamed Vargas ``Chico Fresa''
_ Strawberry Kid _ a reference to the abundance of strawberry
fields in Oxnard, according to broadcaster Mario Solis.
</P>
<P>
   Vargas took offense, failed to show up for a scheduled interview
and now refuses to do business with Telemundo.
</P>
<P>
   The point is this: Disrespect me and I'll disrespect you.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's the way I've been since I was a kid,'' Vargas said.
``Growing up, I was always in the streets, always in trouble. If
anybody said anything about me, I never said nothing. I would just
start fighting.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you don't like me, fine. But respect me. If you grew up the
way I did, you'd understand.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
