<HEADER>
A2043 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBO-UMPS-Q&AMP;A16-COX     07-15 0830
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-UMPS-Q&AMP;A16-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Umps demand baseball's respect
 &HT;    By Thomas Stinson
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ With play resuming Thursday, baseball has 48 days
before when the umpires say they'll resign over a series of
dissatisfactions with Major League Baseball. As of now, the
questions outnumber the answers.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Where is this situation headed?
</P>
<P>
   A: Apparently Armageddon. Major League Baseball is determined to
take more control of its umpires, from scheduling to strike-zone
definition to job perfomance. The Major League Umpires Association
is seeking more autonomy. Both sides have a miserable record at the
negotiating table.
</P>
<P>
   Q: What's the big issue? No one has mentioned money or working
conditions.
</P>
<P>
   A: Money is not a primary concern. The issue is the resistance
of the umpires to yielding any control to MLB. They correctly see
any change as a threat to their jobs. But deeper, this is also
about respect. Although the umps are far from blameless, relations
between players and managers and the umpires cannot get much worse.
The umpires have felt slighted since Roberto Alomar received just a
five-day suspension for spitting on John Hirschbeck in 1996. Tom
Hallion's suspension for bumping a player apparently was the last
straw. The umps think their support from the presidents' and
commissioner's offices has weakened.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Why not give them that ``respect?''
</P>
<P>
   A: It's not that simple. The umps' basic work agreement expires
at the end of this season. MLB has been on record all year as
wanting more authority over the umpires to demand better job
performance. The ground hardly is solid for compromise, much less
for making a bunch of crusty men feel loved.
</P>
<P>
   Q: If the umps, as they have stated, start their own new
corporation, which would contract with MLB for future services,
what's so bad about that?
</P>
<P>
   A: Nothing, except little indicates that the level of umpiring
has improved in baseball this year. If anything, it has declined,
and with an ironclad work agreement that makes the umpires
essentially immune to firing, granting them even stronger job
security seems a strange way to improve on-field performance.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Who will call the games if they walk off the job?
</P>
<P>
   A: If union chief Richie Phillips succeeds in his efforts to
gain the support of minor-league umpires, replacement umpires
probably would come from colleges and amateur associations.
</P>
<P>
   Q: And what's wrong with that?
</P>
<P>
   A: Usually, those guys are down the totem pole because they're
not suited for the big leagues. Short memories neglect the 1995
umpire lockout, in which replacements worked the season's first 86
games. It was near calamity. When the ML umpires made it back to
the field, ovations came from both leagues.
</P>
<P>
   Q: What is this going to cost baseball?
</P>
<P>
   A: In dignity, plenty. From the pocketbook, Phillips says, the
total in severance payments will come to $15 million, to cover all
68 full-time umpires. It sounds like a lot, but when divided among
30 major-league teams, it comes down to $500,000. That's the
equivalent of the contract for an experienced reserve infielder.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Are the umpires having that bad a year?
</P>
<P>
   A: Probably no better or worse than usual, with a few
exceptions. Hallion's clash with the San Diego Padres was an
embarrassment. And the idea that Frank Pulli, completely on his
own, went against written regulations to use a video replay to make
a home-run call boggles the mind. But given the strife over the
bogus new strike zone, it also has been a difficult season to be an
ump.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Who is Richie Phillips?
</P>
<P>
   A: A tough-guy lawyer from Philadelphia _ and a former agent _
who took a powerless group of umpires and made them just as
formidable a labor organization as the player association. He is
bombastic and confrontational and can be a disruptive presence at
the negotiating table. He also is testing his allegiances within
his union. The umps voted unanimously to resign, but all of them
can't be as sure about where their action is headed as Phillips
seems to be.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Where has commissioner Bud Selig been? And who is Sandy
Alderson?
</P>
<P>
   A: Selig hired Alderson last year for just such issues.
Alderson, Princeton-educated with a military background, was
general manager of the Oakland A's dating back to the Bash Brothers
clubs and has seen baseball's ugly underbelly. It was Alderson, at
Selig's bidding, who wrote the new strike-zone ultimatum, and it
was Alderson who requested that clubs monitor the performance of
plate umps and send the written reports to him. He is shrewd and
capable.
</P>
<P>
   Q: How does the timing work?
</P>
<P>
   A: By walking out in early September, the union hopes its
replacements will make such a mess of the games in the ensuing
weeks that management will be ready to give in to get the real umps
back for the postseason. Severance pay would not be due until
winter.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
