<DOCNO> NYT19990715.0518 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-15 22:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2045 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RADAR-AIR-CONTROL-NYT     07-15 1265
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RADAR-AIR-CONTROL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TEST ALOFT GIVES PILOTS GLIMPSE OF TOMORROW 
</HEADLINE>
  (yn) 
 By MATTHEW L. WALD   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WILMINGTON, Ohio _ Five thousand feet over the rolling farm
country of southern Ohio, it was obvious to the test pilot of the
Federal Aviation Administration's biggest research plane that the
airborne experiment under way could change the nature of air
traffic control.
</P>
<P>
   Two dozen planes from around the nation swarmed through the air,
each carrying a new technology that could replace radar and give
pilots aloft detailed information that is now available only to the
controller on the ground: the precise location and identity of
other planes, their speed, direction and altitude, their rate of
climb or descent, even their planned route.
</P>
<P>
   The technology, called ADS-B, is a radical new approach to tasks
that have been done for almost 60 years with radar, and it has a
radical pedigree: its development was sponsored in partnership with
the airlines rather than by the F.A.A. alone. (The government and
the private sector each put up about $25 million.) It also promises
to reduce the risk of collision, both in the air and on the ground.
And while many of its component parts are not yet commercially
available, nothing less than adoption by the entire aviation
industry is envisioned.
</P>
<P>
   In the first few minutes of the experiment performed here
Saturday, it was clear that all the new information was making the
participating pilots act differently.
</P>
<P>
   As Larry Van Hoy, captain of the F.A.A. research plane, listened
from the cockpit of his Boeing 727, a controller in Dayton issued a
standard order to a plane approaching the Wilmington airport,
telling its crew to follow a United Parcel Service 727 to the
runway.
</P>
<P>
   But the pilot, answering the controller, did not give the
standard response, ``Traffic in sight.'' Instead, he included a
jaw-dropping fact, the flight number of the plane he had been told
to follow. ``I have U.P.S. 550 in sight,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Cool,'' said Van Hoy. His first officer, Fred Karl, laughed.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're cheating already,'' Karl observed. Pilots are supposed
to give the standard response, but the rules do not mention citing
the plane's call sign. (The people who wrote the rules surely never
contemplated that it would be possible.) The next step could be
air-to-air traffic negotiations among planes.
</P>
<P>
   The F.A.A. plane and 24 others here, including several 727's and
DC-9's from Federal Express, U.P.S. and Airborne Express, a Boeing
757 belonging to NASA, a P-3 submarine hunter sent by the Navy and
several smaller craft, were part of the first large-scale test of a
program that combines several innovations to pinpoint everything in
the sky, and on the ground, too. In the airport's vicinity
Saturday, an on-board screen on every plane equipped with the new
system showed where every other plane was. With a little more work,
experts say, the planes will soon be able to see fuel trucks,
tractors, other equipment, even people.
</P>
<P>
   That is one reason the cargo airlines are so interested in the
system. The Wilmington airport, formerly a base for the Strategic
Air Command, is a busy center for cargo planes, and at night the
bustling apron here is covered with vehicles and planes ``like
ants,'' said David A. Marcontell, director of engineering at
Airborne Express, which owns the airport and was host to the test.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have vehicles that have run into airplanes, we have
airplanes that have run into airplanes,'' Marcontell said.
</P>
<P>
   The system has other benefits as well. Sitting in the cockpit of
his parked 727, Tom Ewing, a U.P.S. captain, watched two freighters
descend toward the runway closer together than standard technology
would permit. A U.P.S. 727 was coming in at 140 knots, and behind
it was an Airborne DC-9 at 226 knots, closing the gap rapidly. If
quick-sequence landings like Ewing was witnessing could be made
routine, they would increase the runway's capacity and cut delays
during an airport's busiest hours.
</P>
<P>
   But a pilot with only the human eye to estimate distances would
not be able to bring his plane that close to the craft he was
following. Often, Ewing said, he is instructed by a controller to
follow another plane to the ground. He tries to maintain a safe
distance, but even in daylight the task is difficult, and ``at
night, if you're cleared for a visual approach and all you see is a
blinking light out there, well, you do the best you can.''
</P>
<P>
   With the new system, in contrast, the pilot always knows the
range to the plane ahead.
</P>
<P>
   The cargo airlines hope the new system will be ready for wide
use early next year. Passenger airlines, too, are interested in it.
When the cloud layer descends to 3,000 feet in San Francisco,
hardly ``bad weather'' for that area, planes cannot conduct
simultaneous landings on the airport's two runways, which are just
750 feet apart. If ADS-B gave each pilot a clear picture of where
the other plane was while both were still in the clouds, such
landings might be possible, said Rocky Stone, a captain for United
Airlines.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, flight routes over the Atlantic, far from radar,
are separated by 60 miles laterally because no one can be quite
sure exactly where the planes are, and experts say ADS-B could cut
that distance.
</P>
<P>
   ADS-B could someday be an inexpensive replacement for radar,
which works by bouncing radio waves off passing objects to
calculate their position.
</P>
<P>
   Radar is ``independent surveillance'' _ that is, it does not
rely on action by the plane. Over the oceans, in contrast, where
there is no radar, planes are equipped with automatic dependent
surveillance, or ADS. In ADS, the plane automatically radios its
position, and the receiving station, often a satellite, is
``dependent'' on the plane to send the data.
</P>
<P>
   In the new technology, the addition to ADS is the ``B,'' for
broadcast, in which the planes send their information directly to
other aircraft.
</P>
<P>
   There are some problems, participants in the experiment here
agreed. ADS-B would take over navigation, surveillance and
communications functions now spread among four separate sets of
equipment, thus raising the stakes if the system failed.
</P>
<P>
   Bill Blackmer, the director for safety and technology at the
National Air Traffic Controllers Association, said ADS-B could be
very useful but was not ``a miracle cure.'' Humans on the ground,
not the pilots of competing airlines in the sky, will still have to
decide who goes first, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``My belief,'' Blackmer said, ``is that we cannot be automated
out of existence, although I don't put it past anybody to try.''
</P>
<P>
   The system outperforms radar in several ways. The planes know
their own positions by use of the satellite-based Global
Positioning System, which is more accurate than radar. And the
on-board computer on which the whole system depends combines the
data and recalculates once a second; radar, in contrast, updates
the screen only as often as the radar dish completes a sweep, often
once every six seconds. And while planes can be below the radar,
they are never below GPS and ADS-B.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, the system has an effective range of 160 miles, and
sometimes picks up targets much farther away. The conventional
anticollision system now on all passenger airliners is always
accurate only to 14 miles, though sometimes to 40 _ distances that
are not large when two planes are converging head on at 16 miles a
minute.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm sold,'' Ewing, a nine-year veteran of U.P.S., said of the
new system. ``I'm absolutely convinced.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
