<SLUG> BC-BBN-BRAVES-NOTES16-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Lopez is DH, catches Saturday
 &HT;    By Carroll Rogers
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Javy Lopez returned to action Thursday night as the
Braves' designated hitter for the opener of this three-game series
against the Yankees.
</P>
<P>
   He singled in his first at-bat.
</P>
<P>
   Lopez, who missed 20 games with a sprained right knee, was
activated from the disabled list and Pascual Matos was optioned
back to AAA Richmond.
</P>
<P>
   Manager Bobby Cox is planning to use Lopez as the designated
hitter for the first two games and then have him catch for the
first time Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   ``If they gave me a few more days it would be less pressure on
my knee, but if they need me I'm ready to catch,'' Lopez said.
</P>
<P>
   Lopez said before the game he had no fears about being limited
in any way when he's hitting. He's wearing a brace on his right
knee but said it's mainly for support when he catches.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hitting-wise I don't have to wear the brace on my knee,''
Lopez said. ``I don't even have to put pressure on my knee when I'm
hitting. Hitting is not the problem, catching is. It's just going
to be uncomfortable. ...The way I'm going to go up there is like I
haven't missed any games, just like I did when my mom died. I came
to Chicago and started, went along like nothing happened.''
</P>
<P>
   Quiet about umpires
</P>
<P>
   The Braves reacted quietly to the surprise news that
major-league umpires had resigned effective Sept. 2..
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not commenting on the situation,'' said Tom Glavine, the
Braves' player representative. ``We don't stand to gain much by
commenting. We wouldn't talk about (the strike-zone change) in
spring training, why would we talk about it now?''
</P>
<P>
   Cox said he was shocked by the news.
</P>
<P>
   ``It caught me off guard,'' Cox said, adding he would like to
see Major League Baseball and the umpires union work out their
differences quickly.
</P>
<P>
   ``(September) is when pennant races really get going,'' Cox
said. ``You don't want them to be breaking in new umpires then.
Smoltz outing in AA
</P>
<P>
   John Smoltz returned to the mound to test out his elbow Thursday
night for the AA Greenville Braves. He pitched two scoreless
innings in Jacksonville, throwing 27 pitches and striking out the
side in the third inning. He finished with four strikeouts.
</P>
<P>
   ``It went all right,'' Smoltz said. ``I don't know how it's
going to be the next day or so, but it went as good as it could.
I'm sure it'll be a little sore tomorrow. Saturday will be a big
day. I'll take the day off (today), see how it feels and try to do
the same thing again Saturday. I've got a few more hurdles.''
</P>
<P>
   Cox is hoping to use Smoltz in one game of the doubleheader on
Friday, July 23 in Philadelphia
</P>
<P>
   Millwood's big night out
</P>
<P>
   Kevin Millwood's scoreless inning in his first All-Star Game was
a nice touch in what he said was an overall great experience.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was awesome,'' Millwood said. ``Probably one of the best
times I've ever had in baseball, getting to hang out with all the
guys. ``Sitting in the bullpen I was a little nervous,'' Millwood
said. ``Once I got on the field it felt like it was just another
game. Rotation adjustment
</P>
<P>
   Cox shifted Millwood's next start from Saturday to Sunday, the
first game of the series in Toronto, and will have rookie Odalis
Perez start on Saturday. Bruce Chen will pitch Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
