<HEADER>
A2047 &Cx1f; tth-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MOONWALK-ANNIVERSARY-     07-15 1721
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOONWALK-ANNIVERSARY-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LOOKING BACK AT AN UNPARALLELED ADVENTURE, 30 YEARS AGO 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JAMES WALLACE  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Florida day dawned hot and humid.
</P>
<P>
   Outside Kennedy Space Center, more than a million people crowded
roads, parks and beaches to witness the start of a great adventure,
a perilous journey of exploration unlike any other.
</P>
<P>
   July 16, 1969. Thirty years ago Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Hundreds of millions followed anxiously on television. Three
minutes and 10 seconds before the scheduled launch of Apollo 11, a
30-year-old Boeing engineer named Charles Lehtinen pressed a button
that began the firing sequence.
</P>
<P>
   At 9:32 a.m. Eastern Daylight Time, the monster Saturn 5 rocket,
carrying astronauts Neil Armstrong, Edwin ``Buzz'' Aldrin and
Michael Collins, roared away into the heavens from Launch Pad 39A,
leaving an 800-foot-long trail of flame.
</P>
<P>
   Four days later, America's decade-long quest was realized. Man
had landed on the moon.
</P>
<P>
   Some 13,000 Boeing employees were among the tens of thousands
from NASA, McDonnell Douglas, North American, Grumman and hundreds
of smaller companies who made it happen.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were all just a bunch of kids,'' recalled John Winch, who
was in his late 20s when he went to work for Boeing in 1966 in
Huntsville, Ala., as chief engineer for Saturn 5 booster
integration. He was responsible for making sure the first, second
and third stages of the rocket went together and worked the way
they should.
</P>
<P>
   ``We just did it,'' Winch said. ``We didn't know we couldn't.
...''
</P>
<P>
   In May 1961, President John F. Kennedy set the nation on a trail
Boeing workers would eventually help to blaze.
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe,'' Kennedy said, ``that this nation should commit
itself to achieving the goal, before the decade is out, of landing
a man on the moon and returning him safely to Earth.''
</P>
<P>
   NASA selected Boeing that December to build the first stage of
the moon rocket.
</P>
<P>
   Work already was under way in Huntsville on the design of a
super rocket that could launch astronauts to the moon. The Saturn
5, as it became known, was the brainchild of Wernher von Braun and
his team of German scientists.
</P>
<P>
   ``The size of the hardware was mind boggling,'' said Denton
Hanford, 24, and just out of college when he joined Boeing in
Seattle in 1961. A year later, he and his wife moved to Huntsville.
His job was to make propulsion performance predictions for the
Saturn 5 first stage.
</P>
<P>
   Doug Tilden also arrived in Huntsville, with his wife and three
children, in 1962. It was his first job with Boeing. He was working
in Houston, as a structural analysis engineer for an oil company,
when he was recruited by Boeing and Lockheed Martin. He chose
Boeing.
</P>
<P>
   Tilden initially helped on a NASA project to develop the giant
crawler that would transport the 364-foot-tall Saturn 5 from the
Vehicle Assembly Building to its launch pad some three miles away.
He later worked on Saturn 5.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had no idea what I was getting into,'' Tilden said. ``I was
challenged every day for the next 10 or 12 years. It was a great
experience. People were working together for a purpose, for
something they believed it. It was a unique effort. I've never seen
that same kind of atmosphere since.''
</P>
<P>
   Boeing built 15 of the first-stage booster rockets, but only the
first two in Huntsville. The manufacturing operation was moved to
the Michoud Ordinance plant in New Orleans.
</P>
<P>
   The plant, in a swamp, had not been occupied since 1945.
</P>
<P>
   Hanford and other members of Boeing's first-stage team in
Huntsville, along with about 1,500 Boeing engineers from Seattle,
were sent to the Michoud plant once it had been refurbished. Few
welcomed the forced relocation.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was hot, it was humid,'' Winch said.
</P>
<P>
   They prevailed, though. And the giant Saturn rocket would be
ready for its first test flight in 1967, a year that began with
tragedy.
</P>
<P>
   On the evening of Jan. 27, 1967, astronauts Gus Grissom, Ed
White and Roger Chaffee died when an electrical fire swept through
their Apollo spacecraft during a launch pad test.
</P>
<P>
   In the aftermath of the investigation, NASA handed Boeing a
bigger role: Overall responsibility for Apollo and Saturn 5
programs.
</P>
<P>
   ``We needed to have some new faces in there in order to convince
Congress we were doing something different,'' said George Mueller,
NASA's chief of manned spaceflight for most of the 1960s.
</P>
<P>
   Mueller, who turns 81 this month, still has his sights on the
moon and beyond. He is chief executive officer of Kistler Aerospace
in Kirkland, Wash., where he leads a team, many of them veterans of
NASA, who next year plan to launch the world's first reusable
rocket. On the wall of Mueller's office at Carillon Point, next to
a photo of a Saturn 5 being transported to the launch pad, is the
original NASA schedule that Mueller, von Braun and others signed
off on back in 1963. It charts various program milestones that had
to be met to land a man on the moon before the end of the decade.
The schedule, dated Dec. 17, 1963, set the first moon landing in
April 1969.
</P>
<P>
   Key to meeting Kennedy's challenge, Mueller said, was creating
an organization with a can-do team spirit that could overcome any
obstacles. On Nov. 1, 1963, Mueller ordered that instead of testing
each stage of the Saturn 5 individually, all three stages would be
connected for the first flight. The ``all-up testing'' edict proved
crucial.
</P>
<P>
   Four years later, on Nov. 9, 1967, the Saturn 5 was ready for
that maiden flight.
</P>
<P>
   Winch was standing outside the Vehicle Assembly Building. His
chest shook from the low frequency assault of noise. But Winch was
absolutely certain the rocket would work.
</P>
<P>
   A second unmanned Saturn 5 test flight a few months later did
not go as well. Boeing's first stage developed what became known as
the ``pogo effect,'' a dangerous modulation that caused the booster
to violently shake up and down for a full half minute after
liftoff. Next, two of the five second-stage engines quit. Had this
Saturn 5 carried astronauts, they would have had to abort the moon
mission.
</P>
<P>
   ``We spent a lot of time on pogo, trying to figure out how to
correct it before the next flight,'' Tilden said. They did.
</P>
<P>
   The crew of Apollo 8 orbited the moon on Christmas Eve 1968.
Apollo 9 soon followed. Then Apollo 10's lunar module came within
50,000 feet of the moon.
</P>
<P>
   The stage was set for Apollo 11.
</P>
<P>
   On July 20, 1969, at 4:17 p.m. Eastern Daylight Time, four days
after the spectacular Saturn 5 liftoff from Kennedy Space Center,
the lunar lander Eagle with Armstrong and Aldrin, 15 seconds from
running out of fuel, its on-board computer overloaded with data and
sounding alarms, gently touched down on the Sea of Tranquility.
</P>
<P>
   History held its breath.
</P>
<P>
   Then came Armstrong's first words: ``Houston, Tranquility base
here. The Eagle has landed.''
</P>
<P>
   As he watched on television those first steps on the moon,
Hanford remembered the visit that Neil Armstrong made to the
Michoud plant a couple years earlier. Hanford had briefed and
escorted the astronaut who would become the first man to set foot
on the moon.
</P>
<P>
   Armstrong and Aldrin spent more than two hours hopping over the
moon's surface in bulky space suits.
</P>
<P>
   Boeing engineers were then at work designing a unique vehicle
that could carry future astronauts across the moon miles from their
landing site. Three months after Apollo 11, Boeing signed a
contract with NASA to develop what would be called the Lunar Roving
Vehicle. Within 17 months, Boeing delivered four flight-ready
rovers and several more for test and training.
</P>
<P>
   Winch was program manager for the Boeing moon buggy team in
Huntsville. Final assembly was in Kent. The Boeing plant south of
Seattle had manufacturing capability that Huntsville lacked.
</P>
<P>
   Tilden also worked on the project, and manned one of the mission
control consoles in Huntsville in August 1971 when Apollo 15
astronauts Dave Scott and Jim Irwin spent three days exploring the
Alpennine Mountains in the first moon buggy.
</P>
<P>
   After the rover project ended, Tilden was transferred to
Seattle. After retiring in 1994, he helped restore one of the
original rover test vehicles for Boeing's Museum of Flight.
</P>
<P>
   Hanford had returned to Seattle at the end of 1969, but later
became general manager of Boeing's helicopter division in
Philadelphia. He retired last year.
</P>
<P>
   Winch would spent 13 years in Seattle.
</P>
<P>
   Today, all his engineering skills are being put to the test on
the National Missile Defense project, for which Boeing is prime
contractor.
</P>
<P>
   But nothing can compare with the moon program, Winch said.
</P>
<P>
   ``So many things we were doing for the very first time then,''
he said. ``We went at it with enthusiasm, with excitement, with a
spirit of working together. You could meet with your friends, talk
with anyone about it. It wasn't classified. It was inspirational.
Supply any adjective you want. That was it.''
</P>
<P>
   But Hanford feels disappointment on the 30th anniversary of the
moon landing.
</P>
<P>
   ``What struck me is how difficult it would be today to go back
to the moon,'' he said. ``It's very disappointing that we could do
it then, but we could not do it today. ... The commitment just
isn't there. We could never find the motivation.''
</P>
<P>
   Mueller, the ex-NASA boss for manned spaceflight, echoes him.
</P>
<P>
   On July 24, 1969, the day Apollo 11 splashed down in the Pacific
Ocean, Mueller issued a statement that read, in part:
</P>
<P>
   `` ... These trips are only the first step. There remains for
mankind the task of deciding the next step: Will we press forward
to explore other planets, or will we deny the opportunities of the
future. ... The organization that brought men to the moon stands
ready for that next step.''
</P>
<P>
   That next step never came, Mueller said Wednesday as he sat in
his Kirkland office looking distantly at the space photos on his
wall.
</P>
<P>
   ``To me, the most disappointing thing is that having landed on
the moon a few times, we essentially retreated. ... If we had
focused our efforts, if someone had the vision, like President
Kennedy, to say `This is what we are going to do,' we would by now
have a colony on Mars. We would have taken the first couple of
steps in the exploration of the solar system.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
