<HEADLINE>
LOOKING BACK AT AN UNPARALLELED ADVENTURE, 30 YEARS AGO 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JAMES WALLACE  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Florida day dawned hot and humid.
</P>
<P>
   Outside Kennedy Space Center, more than a million people crowded
roads, parks and beaches to witness the start of a great adventure,
a perilous journey of exploration unlike any other.
</P>
<P>
   July 16, 1969. Thirty years ago Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Hundreds of millions followed anxiously on television. Three
minutes and 10 seconds before the scheduled launch of Apollo 11, a
30-year-old Boeing engineer named Charles Lehtinen pressed a button
that began the firing sequence.
</P>
<P>
   At 9:32 a.m. Eastern Daylight Time, the monster Saturn 5 rocket,
carrying astronauts Neil Armstrong, Edwin ``Buzz'' Aldrin and
Michael Collins, roared away into the heavens from Launch Pad 39A,
leaving an 800-foot-long trail of flame.
</P>
<P>
   Four days later, America's decade-long quest was realized. Man
had landed on the moon.
</P>
