<SLUG> BC-BOEING-EARNINGS-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SECOND-QUARTER EARNINGS A GOOD SIGN FOR RESURGENT BOEING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By PAUL NYHAN  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ The Boeing Co. painted a picture of a resurgent
company Thursday, reporting a jump in earnings in the second
quarter fueled in part by a more productive and efficient
commercial airplane division.
</P>
<P>
   The increase represents another step in Boeing's effort to
improve operations and restore investors' confidence. The company
drove profits up partially by squeezing more work out of its
commercial airlines group with fewer workers and lower expenses.
That group recorded $435 million in second-quarter operating
earnings, compared with a loss of a year ago, with 17 percent fewer
employees.
</P>
<P>
   Overall, Boeing posted $701 million in net income in the second
quarter, including a one-time windfall of $181 million tied to a
federal tax settlement. The company earned $258 million a year ago,
although that number was cut by $78 million in one-time costs.
Overall, the report represents the fourth consecutive quarterly
increase in earnings from the aerospace giant.
</P>
<P>
   ``Clearly, this is a turnaround story, (it's) a very good
indication it's on track,'' said Bill Fiala, an analyst at
Missouri-based Edward Jones Investments.
</P>
<P>
   The profits also translate into 75 cents earnings per share
including the tax payment, in the second quarter, compared with 26
cents a share in the second quarter of 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Boeing also rolled out a new measurement tool Thursday. The
so-called value scorecard includes targets and goals designed to
give investors, executives and employees a clearer picture of the
company's progress.
</P>
<P>
   The scorecard also sets financial targets for executives at the
world's largest airplane manufacturer. For example, Boeing hopes to
cut $1.6 billion in overhead by the end of 2000, while trimming its
base of suppliers from 31,000 to 25,000.
</P>
<P>
   The scorecard is part of a broader effort to review the
company's operations, services and products. While Boeing has shed
some divisions, it plans to focus more of its time on improving
lines that merit repair, according to Chief Executive Officer Phil
Condit.
</P>
<P>
   Some analysts say that's good news for Boeing's new 717 airplane
that the company is hawking to airlines.
</P>
<P>
   ``It appears that (they) are committing to the 717,'' Fiala
said.
</P>
<P>
   While analysts hailed the company's profits, they added that
investors shouldn't expect Boeing to continue to report dramatic
increases in the coming months.
</P>
<P>
   ``Given that Boeing is facing an environment of declining
revenue, this kind of profitability level probably remains somewhat
flat over the next year or two,'' said Peter Jacobs, a
Seattle-based analyst for Ragen MacKenzie.
</P>
<P>
   Other observers warned that Boeing will also be challenged to
boost growth in the face of fierce price competition from rival
Airbus Industrie and a downturn in airplane orders.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the more challenging work is in front of them,'' said
James Kawai, an analyst who tracks Boeing for Neuberger &AMP; Berman.
</P>
<P>
   The company admits the second quarter likely represents the high
mark for revenue in 1999. Overall, the company expects to have
revenues of $58 billion this year, while delivering 620 airplanes.
So far, it's on track to meet the target; the company delivered 313
airplanes in the first six months.
</P>
<P>
   In 2000, revenue is projected to drop $10 billion to $48
billion, the result of a downturn in demand and the impact of
Asia's economic troubles moving from Boeing's order book to
production, according to Boeing executives.
</P>
<P>
   However, the company expects to squeeze even more out of its
commercial airplane wing next year. The company expects operating
margins of 3.5 percent to 4.5 percent from the group this year and
4.5 to 5.5. percent next year.
</P>
<P>
   But it will take several years for Boeing to achieve its goal of
joining the top quartile of companies in the S&AMP;P 500, Jacobs said.
Those companies routinely produce 10 percent margins, he added.
</P>
<P>
   Boeing's Condit said he was ``a little more optimistic'' about
prospects in Asia. The Asian economies are key elements in
establishing production goals for the 747 airplane.
</P>
<P>
   Condit noted recent positive developments in Japan and said the
company plans to review the production targets for the 747.
</P>
<P>
   Condit added that Boeing has no current plans to announce
additional layoffs beyond the target already announced of trimming
between 48,000 and 53,000 jobs through the year 2000.
</P>
<P>
   The company had little choice but to announce some job cuts as
part of its effort to become more efficient and to attract capital
from the financial markets, according to Condit.
</P>
<P>
   Boeing is also embroiled in negotiations with 49,000 Machinists
over a new contract. Condit said he was optimistic of an agreement.
</P>
<P>
   Boeing shares actually fell seven-eighths to close at 46 and
three-quarters in trading Thursday. However, the stock price has
been rising in recent days in anticipation of a healthy financial
report. Overall, Boeing's stock price is up 43 percent since the
end of last year.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
