<SLUG> BC-NY-BLACKOUT-SUIT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CITY HALL SUES UTILITY OVER 18-HOUR BLACKOUT 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By ALAN FINDER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Accusing Consolidated Edison of gross negligence, the
administration of Mayor Rudolph Giuliani sued the utility on
Thursday, contending that blackouts in upper Manhattan last week
were caused by Con Edison's failure to properly design and maintain
its network of cables that distribute electricity.
</P>
<P>
   The city did not ask for a specific amount in damages in the
lawsuit, which Giuliani had been threatening to file starting late
last week. But the mayor said in a news conference that he hoped to
recoup ``multiple millions of dollars'' for the extra cost of
police officers, firefighters, emergency medical workers and other
city employees during the power failures that crippled the
Manhattan neighborhoods of Washington Heights and Inwood for 18
hours on July 6 and 7.
</P>
<P>
   The lawsuit, filed in state Supreme Court in Manhattan, also
sought several unusual remedies that city officials said would make
it less likely that New Yorkers would have to endure similar
blackouts in the future. The city asked the courts to order Con
Edison to develop a new plan for the design, installation and
maintenance of its power distribution system to prevent blackouts.
It also asked the courts to appoint a special master who would
oversee Con Edison's new plan.
</P>
<P>
   The city also asked the courts to establish a special procedure
to enable city residents, along with government officials and the
city's Board of Education, to present their claims against Con
Edison and be compensated quickly for losses caused by the
blackouts.
</P>
<P>
   The chairman of Con Edison, Eugene McGrath, declined to speak
about the suit Thursday. ``I've never dealt with a lawsuit from the
city, so I can't comment,'' McGrath said, shortly after he had
finished testifying before a State Assembly hearing in Manhattan on
the power failures.
</P>
<P>
   More than 200,000 people in the Washington Heights and Inwood
sections of upper Manhattan lost power at the height of an intense
heat wave last week, when underground power lines from substations
to the neighborhoods failed and then several power lines caught
fire. Con Edison said that it was forced to shut off all
electricity north of 155th Street in Manhattan.
</P>
<P>
   Officials of the state Public Service Commission, which
regulates utilities, have said that in studies of rates of power
failures, Con Edison's performance has been the best among New York
state's power companies. But Giuliani contends that Con Edison must
upgrade its distribution system so that there are never any
blackouts, and he has repeatedly accused the company's executives
of setting low expectations by trying to explain away power
failures as all but inevitable.
</P>
<P>
   It remains unclear whether the power failures last week, which
also affected the Lower East Side, were caused by the huge demand
for power because of record-setting temperatures and humidity, or
whether they reflected more fundamental problems with the design
and condition of Con Edison's vast network of cables that transmit
electricity from generating stations to homes and offices.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-15-99 2311EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
