<HEADER>
A2187 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FOREIGN-BRIEFS-NYT &LR;      07-15 0621
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FOREIGN-BRIEFS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WORLD NEWS IN BRIEF 
</HEADLINE>
  (rk) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   THE AMERICAS
</P>
<P>
   Venezuela: Colombia Trucks Barred
</P>
<P>
   Defying a ruling by the Andean customs union, President Hugo
Chavez of Venezuela has closed his country's border to all
commercial vehicles from Colombia. He took the action, reportedly
causing chaos at border crossings, after complaining that
Venezuelan truckers are unable to travel safely in Colombia because
of guerrilla activity there and recalling his ambassador to Bogota
in retaliation for remarks a Colombian Cabinet member made
criticizing Venezuela's position on the issue.
</P>
<P>
   Venezuela: Chavez Fined Over Vote
</P>
<P>
   With voters set to pick a constitutional assembly on July 25,
the National Electoral Council has ordered President Hugo Chavez to
stop attending rallies of candidates he favors and to suspend his
weekly radio and television programs on state-run channels, saying
those activities violate the nonpartisan character of the election.
Chavez, who was also fined $10,000, said ``they'll have to put me
in jail'' to prevent him from lobbying for candidates who support
his proposal to write a new constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Mexico: Finance Aide Accused
</P>
<P>
   The opposition parties in Congress sent a formal complaint to
President Ernesto Zedillo accusing his finance minister, Jose Angel
Gurria, of withholding information from an auditor who is examining
the government's $85 billion bank bailout. The auditor is seeking
records from a bank that belonged to Carlos Cabal Peniche, a
financier who is in jail in Australia and has said he made illegal
donations to Zedillo's 1994 campaign.
</P>
<P>
   ASIA
</P>
<P>
   Japan: Nuclear Leak
</P>
<P>
   The authorities acknowledged that a radiation leak at a nuclear
power plant on Monday had exceeded safety limits by 11,500 times.
The operator of the plant, in Tsuruga, 200 miles west of Tokyo,
said no radiation had escaped. But the leak is likely to add to
public doubt about Japan's nuclear power program.
</P>
<P>
   Macao: Gang Warfare Flares
</P>
<P>
   Six months before it is scheduled to revert to Chinese rule,
Macao was hit by new street violence. The police said gang members
were suspected of using gasoline bombs to set fire to six
government cars. The attacks came after an accused gang leader was
sentenced to six years in prison.
</P>
<P>
   AFRICA
</P>
<P>
   South Africa: Botha Tied To Killings
</P>
<P>
   Former President P.W. Botha could be headed for more problems
with the Truth and Reconciliation Commission, which he has called
``a circus'' and to which he has refused to testify. The panel has
told him he will be implicated by former security officers asking
for amnesty in the 1985 killing of eight anti-apartheid activists.
The activists were given ``zero-timed'' grenades that exploded as
soon as they tried to use them.
</P>
<P>
   EUROPE
</P>
<P>
   Russia: Yeltsin Aide Denies Swiss Charges
</P>
<P>
   Pavel Borodin, the Kremlin administration chief named in a Swiss
money-laundering investigation, denied that he had engaged ``in
commercial or any other activities in Switzerland,'' and called the
inquiry a political attack on President Boris Yeltsin. But his
lawyer was more reserved, saying that ``generally speaking''
Borodin was not active in Switzerland and had violated no Swiss
laws. Swiss accounts in his name could be forgeries, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Middle East
</P>
<P>
   Israel: Apology for Crusades
</P>
<P>
   Several hundred members of a Christian group apologized for the
Crusades, delivering framed copies of their apologies to religious
leaders in Jerusalem. Nine hundred years after the mass killings of
Jews, Muslims and Byzantine Christians, Israel's chief rabbi,
Yisrael Meir Lau, thanked them, saying, ``Better late than never.''
</P>
</TEXT>
