<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-15 23:11 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2074 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GLF-BROPEN-ROUND116-C     07-15 0727
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-BROPEN-ROUND116-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    British scores soar
 &HT;    By Glenn Sheeley
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   CARNOUSTIE, Scotland _ Day 2 of the Carnage at Carnoustie is
scheduled to begin this morning _ if golfers in the British Open
decide to return. It has become the Brutish Open, where the world's
greatest players are starting to feel as though they've been
dragged for five hours tied to the bumper of a rental car.
</P>
<P>
   With shin-high rough, the 128th British Open promised to be no
picnic in calm conditions. Add 25-mph winds, and the first round of
the tournament evolved into an epic that could have drawn an R
rating for violence.
</P>
<P>
   Strange things happened Thursday, when winds allowed players to
smack 200-yard 9-irons with it or beat drivers 220 yards against
it. The leader is a 30-year-old Australian named Rodney Pampling,
whose previous claim to fame was a victory in the Canon Challenge
on the Australasian Tour. Pampling was the only player to match par
71.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't mind the wind,'' said Pampling, who eagled the par-5
14th hole with a 1-iron, 6-iron and a 25-foot putt. ``It's a
challenge. It makes you think a lot harder out on the golf
course.''
</P>
<P>
   Thinking isn't what hurt. The real pain came in the scoring
tent, where the Royal &AMP; Ancient Golf Club officials might have been
wise to dispense calculators. Germany's Bernhard Langer and
Alpharetta's Scott Dunlap are one shot back, and Americans Steve
Pate, Justin Leonard, Hal Sutton and Len Mattiace are at 2-over 73.
But most of the scores were much higher.
</P>
<P>
   With fairways tighter than the hallway of a Scottish boarding
house, the scoring average for the first round was 78.31 strokes.
Of the 155 players, 57 shot 80 or worse. Spain's Sergio Garcia shot
an 89. Defending champion Mark O'Meara shot 83. U.S. Open champion
Payne Stewart and runner-up Phil Mickelson recorded matching 79s.
</P>
<P>
   While pre-tournament favorite Tiger Woods is in fine shape at
3-over 74, even he could not emerge without a bizarre event. A
scantily clad woman appeared on the 18th green and planted a kiss
on him. On a day this bizarre, the incident was like an
afterthought.
</P>
<P>
   ``I mean, if the average player had to get out here and play,
he'd probably quit,'' said David Duval after recording his 79,
``and I think a lot of the pros are pretty close to that, too.''
</P>
<P>
   ``If a 15-handicapper came out and played here today,'' said Hal
Sutton, who had a 73, ``a good number would be 120.''
</P>
<P>
   Derrick Cooper, who owns a sandwich shop in Warrington, England,
spent most of the day atop the leaderboard with Pampling, but he
triple-bogeyed the 17th to finish at 74.
</P>
<P>
   Sea Island's Davis Love III also had a 74, undone by a
double-bogey at the 12th hole, where he drove into the high grass
and moved his second shot about two feet with a sand wedge. Also
among those at 74 are Scotland's Colin Montgomerie, 10 shots over
his course-record score, and Ernie Els of South Africa.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just let it get away from me a little,'' Love said. ``I
didn't get what I wanted, but I survived. Everyone's got to play
the golf course. They're not going to call the tournament off
because it's too hard.''
</P>
<P>
   After complaints during practice rounds about narrow fairways
and high rough, the whining heightened when winds made both facets
difficult.
</P>
<P>
   ``The R&AMP;A said it's not the way they wanted to set it up,''
Duval said, ``but that it was some out-of-control greens-keeper,
and you know that's not the case. Let them go play it and see how
many of them start crying.''
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta's Billy Andrade, four shots off the lead, called his 75
``my par.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's ridiculous,'' Andrade said. ``I'm very happy with 75....
We were walking down the 18th fairway and (playing partner) Miguel
Angel Jimenez saw Sergio Garcia and said, `This is ridiculous. This
is a young man who won the Irish Open and almost won Loch Lomond,
and he's going down the 17th hole 15-over par.'''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's one thing when you have bad shots that turn out really
bad,'' said Atlanta's Stewart Cink after an 82. ``It's another
thing when you have dang good shots that turn out really bad.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I think your (pride is hurt) a little bit when you shoot in
the 80s,'' O'Meara said. ``I mean, I'm a professional golfer _ but
I tried on every shot.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
