<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Gordon, Stewart apologize for incidents at Loudon
 &HT;    By Mark Schlabach
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ This weekend's off-date should give NASCAR drivers a
chance to cool down after last week's emotional race at New
Hampshire International Speedway.
</P>
<P>
   Two-time defending Winston Cup champion Jeff Gordon, who bumped
and passed points leader Dale Jarrett in the final lap of the Jiffy
Lube 300, apologized to Jarrett this week. Rookie Tony Stewart, who
lost the event when he ran out of fuel with fewer than three laps
left, also apologized for his behavior in Loudon, N.H.
</P>
<P>
   Stewart, 28, led 100 of the final 103 laps before his No. 20
Pontiac stalled on lap 297. After refueling, Stewart tangled with
the No. 36 Pontiac of Ernie Irvan. Stewart then stormed away from
the garage area, refusing to answer reporters' questions.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was so consumed with emotion,'' Stewart said, ``(but) there
was a lack of maturity there. It's not going to happen again.''
</P>
<P>
   Stewart, the 1997 Indy Racing League champion, says he spoke to
owner Joe Gibbs about his post-race behavior.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was inexcusable,'' Stewart said. ``Hopefully, people will
forgive me.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Gordon and Jarrett were involved in a heated
post-race confrontation in the garage. The pair stood toe-to-toe
and exchanged heated words. As Jarrett walked back to his No. 88
Ford, he screamed at Gordon, ``If you want to turn this into a war,
it's on. We can make it one.''
</P>
<P>
   Gordon, who finished third in the race, seemed diplomatic in his
post-race news conference, but Jarrett says Gordon apologized
before leaving the speedway. At this week's Ford testing at
Indianapolis Motor Speedway, Jarrett said he isn't angry with
Gordon, who trails Jarrett by 389 points.
</P>
<P>
   ``It took a lot for (Gordon) to walk over to someone who is a
lot bigger than he is,'' Jarrett told the Indianapolis
Star-Tribune. ``I don't regret anything. It was racing and, as far
as I'm concerned, it's over.''
</P>
<P>
   Driver change
</P>
<P>
   Sixteen races remain on this year's Winston Cup schedule, but
the sport's ``Silly Season'' apparently already has started. Jerry
Nadeau, a second-year driver in Melling Racing's No. 9 Ford, will
replace Wally Dallenbach next season in the No. 25 Chevrolet of
Hendrick Motorsports, according to published reports.
</P>
<P>
   The change and a sponsorship announcement for Hendrick's third
car is expected Monday at the team's headquarters in Concord, N.C.
</P>
<P>
   Dallenbach, 36, a road-course specialist, has only two top-10
finishes in 18 starts this season and is 20th in points. Nadeau's
finishes are actually worse, as he's 33rd in points with only one
top-10 effort.
</P>
<P>
   Melling Racing is expected to continue its Winston Cup
operation, and the search for Nadeau's replacement is underway.
</P>
<P>
   Indy testing
</P>
<P>
   Jarrett had the fastest lap in Ford's two-day testing at
Indianapolis, covering the 2.5-mile oval in 50.236 seconds, an
average speed of 179.154 mph. He was followed by Jeff Burton
(178.260), Mark Martin (178.218), Jeremy Mayfield (177.925) and
Kenny Irwin Jr. (177.736).
</P>
<P>
   Chevrolets and Pontiacs are scheduled to test at Indy on Monday
and Tuesday for the Aug. 7 Brickyard 400.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
