<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Garcia can't get going, shoots 89
 &HT;    By Glenn Sheeley
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   CARNOUSTIE, Scotland _ In retrospect, Sergio Garcia probably
should have waited a day for his declaration of terms. On
Wednesday, Garcia announced to the media a preference to be called
``Sergio.'' On Thursday, in the first round of the 128th British
Open, Garcia shot an 18-over-par 89.
</P>
<P>
   True, everyone fought for their professional lives Thursday in
the 25-mph winds, but only two players on the board posted higher
numbers than the 19-year-old Spaniard.
</P>
<P>
   ``Perhaps another day,'' Garcia said to a mob of reporters,
moving to the clubhouse. ``I'm not in the mood.''
</P>
<P>
   Later, after cooling off, he said, ``It does cross your mind
sometimes that you'd like to walk off, but my caddie said, `Come
on, let's go and see if I could shoot 80.' But I had two doubles in
a row (on 9 and 10), and it was an impossibility of getting it
going.... It's part of the learning experience.''
</P>
<P>
   Jerry Higginbotham, Garcia's talkative caddie, said, ``Well, at
least we broke 90.''
</P>
<P>
   Playing in his third British Open, Garcia started with a
triple-bogey on the first hole and began a nightmare that never
ended. He made a birdie, six bogeys, five double-bogeys and a
triple-bogey. It was a brutal contrast to the last two weeks, when
Garcia won the Irish Open and finished second at Loch Lomond.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yes, I was suffering,'' he said. ``I couldn't do anything....
I don't see this test as very fair. It's too difficult.... I left
(earlier) because I wanted to be alone for two hours with my family
after the day I had. I wanted to take a little time out, because I
think it's better to speak now that I am calm.... Today is
forgotten. I will try again to play well tomorrow.''
</P>
<P>
   Woods stunned at the 18th
</P>
<P>
   A woman wearing a thong and bikini top appeared on the 18th
green to plant a kiss on Tiger Woods. ``When she first came up, I
was kind of surprised by that,'' Woods said. ``I wondered what Ian
(Woosnam, his playing partner), was laughing at. She came up as I
was walking up toward my ball. I had spikes on, so I didn't want to
step on her feet because she was barefoot. After she did what she
did, she ran off. I tried to get my focus back, focus on the job at
hand, and that was to bury that putt. Unfortunately, I just left it
right in the middle of the hole short.''... Leader Rodney Pampling
was using an 18-degree driving iron, hitting it about 180 yards
into the wind and 290 downwind.
</P>
<P>
   Open-ing the menu
</P>
<P>
   A restaurant in Monifeith just down the road is advertising
appropriate lunch specials for the week _ the Seve Salad, the Greg
Egg, the Tiger Burger and the Full Monty.... Asked what the hardest
thing was to accomplish in Thursday's first round, Payne Stewart,
the U.S. Open champion, said, ``Trying not to injure yourself out
there.... Seventy-nine? Well, it beats 80. I was really working
hard to break the `snowman.'''... Scot Colin Montgomerie on the
windy conditions: ``This is a breezy summer's day here, nothing
more than that.''... On the toughness of Carnoustie, Monty
reminded, ``Thirty days ago, we were saying Pinehurst was the
hardest course we've ever played. We're all changing our opinion
coming here. There's a lot of good players that have been blown
away today. They will be tomorrow, too, and they will be Saturday
and Sunday, if it remains this way.''... There were 23
double-bogeys made on the 412-yard 7th hole.... Len Mattiace, two
shots back with a 73, made birdies on the two toughest holes
Thursday _ the 9th and the 17th.... Sam Torrance of Scotland
withdrew because of a shoulder injury.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
