<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-THRASHERS-TRADES16-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Thrashers acquire Botterill, Prochazka; trade Pushor
 &HT;    By Guy Curtright
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The Atlanta Thrashers finally have a coach and a
schedule. But the roster, just like Philips Arena, is still under
construction.
</P>
<P>
   General manager Don Waddell made two trades Thursday, the most
significant of which was the acquisition of left wing Jason
Botterill, a former first-round draft pick, from Dallas for
defenseman Jamie Pushor.
</P>
<P>
   The Thrashers also obtained right wing Martin Prochazka from
Toronto for a sixth-round draft pick in 2001.
</P>
<P>
   Botterill, 23, was the 20th overall selection in 1994 and scored
104 goals in four years at the University of Michigan. He split
last season between Dallas and the IHL Michigan K-Wings.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are very pleased to add a forward of Jason's caliber,''
Waddell said. ``He is young, talented and physical.''
</P>
<P>
   Botterill, who is 6 feet 4, 220 pounds, had no points and 23
penalty minutes in 17 games with Dallas last year. He had 13 goals
and 25 assists in 56 games in the IHL.
</P>
<P>
   Pushor, 26, was expected to be used in a trade when he was
selected by the Thrashers from Anaheim in the expansion draft, but
a deal with Phoenix fell through. The rugged defenseman started his
career with Detroit and was traded to the Mighty Ducks during the
1997-98 season. He had three points and 112 penalty minutes in 70
games last season. Prochazka, 27, played for the Czech Republic
when it won the Olympic gold medal in 1998. He played in his native
country last season after being with the Maple Leafs in 1997. A
restricted free agent, Prochazka reached contract terms with the
Thrashers after the trade.
</P>
<P>
   Karlsson signs contract
</P>
<P>
   Center Andreas Karlsson, 23, signed his first NHL contract after
playing in his native Sweden. The Thrashers obtained the rights to
Karlsson from Calgary on the day of the expansion draft. He was
drafted in 1993 but never signed with the Flames. In 49 games last
season, Karlsson had 18 goals and 15 assists in the Swedish Elite
League.
</P>
<P>
   Preseason schedule
</P>
<P>
   The Thrashers' eight-game preseason schedule will begin
Saturday, Sept. 11 in Columbus with a 7:30 p.m. game against
Nashville. Training camp will be in Orlando, with players reporting
Sept. 4. The Thrashers will play Carolina in Greenville, S.C., on
Sept. 15, and in Charleston, S.C., on Sept. 24. Atlanta will play
the Blues in Grand Rapids, Mich., on Sept. 12, and St. Louis on
Sept. 14. Two games will be at Philips Arena _ the New York Rangers
7 p.m. Sept. 18 and the New Jersey Devils 3 p.m. Sept. 19.
</P>
<P>
   National TV exposure
</P>
<P>
   The Thrashers' second game of the season, Oct. 7 against Detroit
at Philips Arena, will be televised by ESPN2 at 8 p.m. Thrashers
weeknight games normally will begin at 7:30 p.m. ESPN2 will carry
102 games this season, up from 75. ESPN will show 27, beginning
with Pittsburgh at Dallas on Oct. 1. ABC, which takes over hockey
from Fox this season under a five-year, $600 million deal, will
show regional telecasts the last four weeks of the season, along
with the NHL All-Star Game on Feb. 6 in Toronto.
</P>
<P>
   Schedule odds and ends
</P>
<P>
   The Flames, the South's first NHL team, return to Atlanta on
Oct. 26. The Flames played eight years in Atlanta before being sold
and moved to Calgary in western Canada after the 1979-80 season.
... Atlanta will face its Southeast Division rivals _ Carolina,
Florida, Tampa Bay and Washington _ five times each. The Thrashers
have four games against each of the remaining Eastern Conference
teams, except Toronto, which they will face three times. ...
Carolina will play its first nine games on the road because of
construction delays on its new arena in Raleigh. ... The Thrashers
have two games against Western Conference teams, except for
Anaheim, Chicago and Vancouver, which they are set to meet only one
time each. The Mighty Ducks are the only team that won't visit
Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
