u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TEN-DAVISCUP-ADVANCE1     07-15 0672
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEN-DAVISCUP-ADVANCE16-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Courier's job: U.S. team's closer
 &HT;    By Todd Holcomb
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   BROOKLINE, Mass. _ Jim Courier, who knocked out England with a
five-set triumph of will over Greg Rusedski in the first round of
Davis Cup in April, is situated to deliver again Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Courier will play world No. 2 Patrick Rafter in today's second
match, but he is paired to play Australian teenager Lleyton Hewitt
for the fifth point Sunday if this Davis Cup quarterfinal is still
at issue.
</P>
<P>
   But Courier wasn't always this cool. Though now regarded as one
of the best Davis Cup closers, he remembers what nerves are. Making
his debut in 1991 in Mexico City, Courier was the lead singles
player in the United States' 3-2 victory, thanks mostly to two wins
by Brad Gilbert.
</P>
<P>
   ``Otherwise, it was a nightmare,'' said Courier, who was
trounced twice, by jouneymen Luis Herrera and Leonardo Lavalle. ``I
couldn't handle the altitude, the way the balls flew and the rookie
pressure.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're up 2-1, and there I was choking in the dressing room as
Brad struggled against Herrera. He came through, finally, in five
sets. I was a nervous wreck.''
</P>
<P>
   Eight years later, the U.S. Davis Cup team is 13-0 when Courier
plays, and he has won the clinching point in five of them. Rod
Laver's presence in 11 consecutive Australian victories, 1959-73,
is the next-best recent feat of its kind.
</P>
<P>
   Courier has toiled in the heat of a fifth match for the deciding
point three times, winning them all, including the 6-4, 6-7, 6-3,
1-6, 8-6 triumph over Rusedski, which came two days after another
five-set win, over Tim Henman. The effort did more to rekindle U.S.
Davis Cup pride than any match this decade.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ever since I was a kid, I've always wanted the ball at the end
of the game,'' Courier said. ``If it was kickball or baseball or
whatever, I always wanted to be involved at the end. Tennis is no
different. I enjoy being out there when the stakes are high.''
</P>
<P>
   Courier's loyalty to the Davis Cup and his history of performing
under duress assured his place on this team, despite his world
ranking, still foundering at No. 41, fifth among American players.
</P>
<P>
   ``Rankings don't mean anything in Davis Cup,'' Gullikson said.
``Jim has been a champion. He's been No. 1, he's a Grand Slam
winner. ... And the one thing that's impressive about Jim is his
preparation for Davis Cup. The week before the match, I can count
on the fact he's hitting twice a day. He's prepared for battle.''
</P>
<P>
   Courier has been the modern-day warrior for U.S. Davis Cup
efforts.
</P>
<P>
   In 1994, he won two matches each in India and the Netherlands
and clinched against Holland in the fifth match, beating Jacco
Eltingh. Two days before, he had upset the Dutch No. 1, Richard
Krajicek. But when the semifinals came, Courier was passed over for
Sampras and Martin.
</P>
<P>
   In 1996, Courier went to Brazil for a first-round match and
survived Fernando Meligeni in five sets in front of the most vile
crowd he had ever seen. Later, he clinched the match by beating
Gustavo Kuerten, on clay. Yet when the semifinals came, Gullikson
passed the baton to Sampras and Michael Chang to play the
Australians in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, with his victory over Russia's Marat Safin at Stone
Mountain Park, after trailing 6-0, 4-1, Courier became only the
fourth American in a century of the Davis Cup to win the fifth set
of a meaningful fifth match. Against Rusedski this year, Courier
became the first American to do it twice.
</P>
<P>
   This time, he won't be passed over. Although not revered on tour
as the same player who won four Grand Slam titles and rose to No. 1
in the early '90s, Courier has become America's closer.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some guys deal with the pressure of Davis Cup consistently
very well, and Jim is one of those,'' Rafter said. ``He loves the
whole thing of Davis Cup, and he's someone who's been able to
handle that better than anyone else.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
