</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-NASDAQ-TIMESSQUARE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STOCK EXCHANGES ABANDON PLANS TO RELOCATE TO TIMES SQUARE 
</HEADLINE>
  (yn) 
 By CHARLES V. BAGLI   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Nearly a year after Nasdaq and the American Stock
Exchange created a stir in New York with grand plans to move to a
new 40-story skyscraper near Times Square, the two financial
markets have reversed course and now appear ready to stay in lower
Manhattan.
</P>
<P>
   The decision amounts to a retreat for Frank G. Zarb, the
chairman of the National Association of Securities Dealers, which
owns both Nasdaq and the American Stock Exchange. Zarb had planned
to move to Times Square, a telegenic international crossroads, as a
step in building a world financial market to rival the New York
Stock Exchange. But Zarb has since discovered that building a new
headquarters in midtown, or even in lower Manhattan, can be
expensive.
</P>
<P>
   In a letter sent to city officials Thursday, Nasdaq said the two
stock markets were now considering an expanded trading floor at the
American Stock Exchange, at 86 Trinity Pl., and leasing 290,000
square feet at either 1 Liberty Plaza or 1 World Financial Center
for Nasdaq. City officials and real estate executives say they
still expect the NASD to move to New York from Washington.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, Nasdaq resurrected a threat to move its
operations to Jersey City, N.J., if it does not get large tax
breaks from New York, though real estate executives on both sides
of the Hudson River say they doubt that the exchanges would leave
Manhattan.
</P>
<P>
   ``The city's goal was to bring Nasdaq to New York,'' said Randy
L. Levine, deputy mayor for economic development. ``We always left
the exact location up to them. We'll continue to work with them to
try and find a suitable home.''
</P>
<P>
   Last November, Nasdaq signed an agreement with the state and the
city to build a new headquarters at 42nd Street and the Avenue of
the Americas, or a similar site, with a $200 million package of tax
breaks and cash. Levine said Thursday that it was unlikely that
Nasdaq would get that amount now.
</P>
<P>
   ``The $200 million deal was for a new building,'' Levine said.
``We usually grant a lower level of incentives when you're only
leasing space.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite signing the agreement with New York on Nov. 3, Michael
Jones, chief administrative officer for the NASD, said the
association had made it clear that the exchanges were still
examining their options. Because of several expiring leases, he
said the association could not wait five years for a building to be
constructed.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
