<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-15 23:13 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2194 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MASSACRE-FUNERAL16-CO     07-15 0407
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MASSACRE-FUNERAL16-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Funeral filled with prayers for surviving boy
 &HT;    By Gita M. Smith
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Atlanta wrapped compassionate arms around a grieving
family Thursday night and, with gospel music, prayers and poems,
said goodbye to six murder victims.
</P>
<P>
   More than 1,000 attended the emotional, standing-room-only
memorial for Deleane Briskey; four of her children, Torsha and
Craig DeCarlo Briskey; and David Antonio and Antione DeAndre Lucas;
and her sister Essie Jo Huguley.
</P>
<P>
   Inside St. Paul AME Church, along with thoughts of the dead,
were special prayers for survivor Santonio Lucas, 11, the boy who
witnessed the massacre of his family at dawn Monday. Many inside
the sanctuary and outside on the lawn of the church spoke of
Santonio as a child who may be more wounded in his psyche than in
his body.
</P>
<P>
   ``Lord, thank you for leaving him behind to tell the story,''
prayed the Rev. A.W. Motley. ``Lord, settle his mind. Don't let him
suffer psychologically.''
</P>
<P>
   Others voiced their hope that Santonio, still hospitalized
Thursday night, will recover with the help of his remaining family.
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta Mayor Bill Campbell took up that refrain.
</P>
<P>
   ``I visited young Tony Lucas in the hospital. We've got to pray
for this boy and ... bind his wounds,'' Campbell said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our children should be swimming and playing and going to
movies, having boyfriends and girlfriends,'' he said. ''Instead, we
are burying them.''
</P>
<P>
   Speaking for the four children's teachers, Atlanta Public
Schools Superintendent Beverly Hall described their memories of
Deleane Briskey's children.
</P>
<P>
   ``Antione, a sweet boy. David, an affectionate boy who would hug
the principal in the cafeteria. Carlos, outgoing and full of life.
Torsha, an outstanding honor student,'' Hall said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Please also remember Jalisa (Lucas) and Santonio, the
survivors. They have been victimized, but it need not be
lifelong,'' Hall said.
</P>
<P>
   A special poem for Torsha by ``best friend'' Alicia Copeland
painted a picture of a girl on the brink of life with tremendous
intellectual promise.
</P>
<P>
   And Antonio Bailey, an uncle of Santonio and Jalisa, sent out
this reminder: ``Get together with your loved ones when you get
home tonight. Tell them you love them, because when you go out the
door, you don't know if you'll see them again.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
