<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-15 23:21 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2196 &Cx1f; tth-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-OFFICER-KILLED-SPI &LR;      07-15 0900
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OFFICER-KILLED-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FREAK NATURE OF YOUNG OFFICER'S DEATH STUNS DEPARTMENT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By REBEKAH DENN  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   EVERETT, Wash. _ The rituals are unfamiliar at the somber police
department offices here: The flag at half-staff for one of their
own, the bagpipers preparing to pay tribute to a fallen officer,
the counselors trying to ease the pain of a colleague's death.
</P>
<P>
   Officer Brian M. Dibucci, who suffered a fatal fall after a high
speed chase Thursday, was the first person to die in the line of
duty in the Everett department in 79 years.
</P>
<P>
   The freak nature of his death _ falling 100 feet from a trestle
as he tried to assist his fellow officers _ made the shock even
worse, said Deputy Chief Pat Slack. Police are conscious that they
risk their lives every day, Slack said, but they fear shootings or
stabbings _ ``not something like this.''
</P>
<P>
   With Dibucci's death, the department lost a man who had ``a
wonderful future to look forward to,'' Chief Jim Scharf said.
</P>
<P>
   Not only was Dibucci considered an up-and-coming patrolman, but
he had just announced his engagement to Margaret Erb, a fellow
Everett officer. The couple, who started dating shortly after
Dibucci joined the department in January of 1998, was planning a
February wedding.
</P>
<P>
   After Dibucci and Erb were to finish working their 5 p.m. to 5
a.m. shift Thursday, they had planned to visit Erb's mother and let
her know the good news.
</P>
<P>
   They were a ``wonderful'' couple, said Dibucci's stepfather,
Thurston County Commissioner Kevin O'Sullivan, who had welcomed
their engagement along with Dibucci's mother, Donna O'Sullivan.
``They loved each other with sincerity and passion.''
</P>
<P>
   The driver of the car involved in the traffic stop is being
investigated for suspicion of second-degree murder, possession of
stolen property _ the car was stolen _ and felony eluding. A
district court judge Thursday set his bail at $100,000.
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors couldn't be immediately reached Thursday, but
Woodall said he expected they would file murder charges against the
driver rather than a lesser charge such as manslaughter. He said
the man was not being treated any more harshly because an officer
had died.
</P>
<P>
   ``The elements are very clear on murder two,'' Woodall said.
``He committed a felony, and someone died as a result.''
</P>
<P>
   Dibucci's stepfather, himself a former police officer, said he
considered murder charges ``absolutely appropriate.''
</P>
<P>
   Dibucci was a backup policeman in Thursday's pursuit, one of at
least three officers chasing a driver who had tried to outrun
police after he was spotted driving erratically. The pursuit
proceeded from the downtown streets to the trestle on state Route 2
heading out of the city.
</P>
<P>
   Officers had slowed as they approached a sharp S-curve at the
east end of the trestle, Woodall said, but the driver sped on, lost
control, and crashed. The officers ran to the car, guns drawn, and
arrested the unharmed man and his passenger.
</P>
<P>
   The case seemed to be closed.
</P>
<P>
   Then they noticed the empty patrol car.
</P>
<P>
   The officers tried to raise Dibucci on his radio, then saw that
he had fallen over the thigh-high barrier to the grass and brush
100 feet below.
</P>
<P>
   The road split into three ramps at that spot of the accident,
and Dibucci had parked at an adjacent overpass about 15 feet from
the stolen car.
</P>
<P>
   Investigators are still trying to figure out what happened.
Everett police said Dibucci was apparently trying to cover the
other officers as they made the arrest, and likely either slipped
or leaned too far as he rushed from his car to the barrier.
</P>
<P>
   The Snohomish County Medical Examiner's Office ruled the death
an accident.
</P>
<P>
   For Dibucci's stepfather, the way Dibucci died was in line with
the way he served his community every day. ``He fell to his death
running to help another officer,'' O'Sullivan said.
</P>
<P>
   Dibucci, 30, was ``a great kid,'' said Scharf, sad and weary as
he spoke in the same office where he had interviewed the young man
with glowing references a year and a half before.
</P>
<P>
   Smart, dedicated, professional and compassionate, Dibucci had
wanted to be a police officer from the time he was a boy, family
and friends said.
</P>
<P>
   He was inspired by the example set by his stepfather, who was
the latest in a family line of police officers, and by the
opportunity to serve the public.
</P>
<P>
   Dibucci saw ``the excitement of being on the road, being a part
of the community, seeing what you can do as an individual to
improve the community,'' said former Tenino (Wash.) Police Chief
Derek Stansbury, who worked with Dibucci as a 911 dispatcher in
Thurston County and recruited him as a Tenino officer in 1995.
</P>
<P>
   ``He had the biggest smile and just the biggest heart ... I
don't think I've ever seen Brian have a harsh word for anybody,
ever,'' said dispatcher Gay Nell Bare.
</P>
<P>
   At Tenino ``his mind was always going 120 miles an hour,''
Stansbury said, establishing an especially close rapport with
children, starting up a bicycle cop patrol, and always thinking
about how to improve the department.
</P>
<P>
   Besides his mother and stepfather, of West Olympia, Dibucci is
survived by his father, John Dibucci of Pennsylvania, and his
grandmother, Mary Hill of Lacey.
</P>
<P>
   The last time an Everett officer died was in 1920, when
Detective John Fox was shot by a robber.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
