A2197 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GILLETTE-EARNINGS-NYT     07-15 0281
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GILLETTE-EARNINGS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GILLETTE REPORTS 19 PERCENT DROP IN NET INCOME 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 By DANA CANEDY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Gillette Co., reeling from weakness in its international
business and the dismal performance of some product lines, reported
second-quarter earnings on Thursday that matched Wall Street's
previously lowered expectations.
</P>
<P>
   Gillette, the maker of razors and blades, posted a 19 percent
decline in net income to $300 million, or 26 cents a share, from
$372 million, or 33 cents a year earlier. Gillette's revenue rose
3.8 percent to $2.41 billion. Analysts polled by First Call had
initially expected Gillette to earn 29 cents a share, but after an
earnings warning from the company, the estimate was lowered to 26
cents.
</P>
<P>
   Although earnings were announced after the market closed,
investors anticipated the company would hit the revised estimates
and its stock rose $1.25, to $44.75.
</P>
<P>
   The company, though, has only recently begun to get back on
investors' good side. The stock is far off its 52-week high of
$64.375, reached on March 23.
</P>
<P>
   While Gillette's overall business is stumbling, the core
business has never been stronger. The company's Mach3
premium-priced, three-blade shaving system has snagged a 17 percent
share of the market since it was introduced in April 1998. At the
same time, Gillette continues to pick up share in the $7 billion
worldwide razor and blade business, which it dominates with 72
percent of the market. The company's Duracell battery business also
remains strong.
</P>
<P>
   Gillette said its results were also hurt by increased marketing
and advertising spending and divestiture of a cosmetics unit.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
