 &QL; 
NOTARO-COLUMN (Phoenix) - I saw that something was wrong when my
cousin Anthony and his wife, Linda, arrived at my sister's house
just as we were turning on the grill for our 4th of July barbecue.
I gasped when I saw him. Even though he and Linda had moved from
New York earlier this year, his ``new resident'' status could not
excuse what I saw. He had a tan. Not just any tan but a deep,
bronze, tan like he was the sun child of George Hamilton and Jackie
Stallone. ``Are you crazy?'' I yelled to him. ``I told you not to
go outside!'' By LAURI NOTARO. Story moved in the ``L'' category. &QL; 
 &QL; 
COX (Phoenix) - Cox Communications has severely reduced the upload
speed of its high-speed Internet service in the Phoenix metro area
in an effort to thwart the abuse of an estimated 1 percent of its
subscribers. The slowdown is aimed at preventing subscribers from
using the $44.95-per-month service to host pornographic Web sites
and Web/mail servers, The company discovered the abuses during
routine monitoring of the network to make sure people aren't using
the residential service for business purposes, a company spokesman
said. By MAX JARMAN. Story will move in the ``A`` category. &QL; 
 &QL; 
MOON (Undated) - It's regarded as the defining moment of the
century, perhaps of all history. It's the moment human beings
shucked their Earthbound destiny, rocketed into the black vastness
of the cosmos and set foot upon another celestial body. The Apollo
moon landing 30 years ago this Monday lasted just under 22 hours.
And although public fascination with space has waned, it remains a
technological feat that altered forever the way humans view the
universe and their place in it. By KERRY FEHR-SNYDER. Story will
move in the ``A`` category.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
