<SLUG> BC-BBO-YANKS-BRAVES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FANS BOO CLEMENS AS YANKEES FALL TO BRAVES 
</HEADLINE>
  (rk) 
 By BUSTER OLNEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ New York Yankees fans have waited a half season for
Roger Clemens to pitch like someone destined for the Hall of Fame.
They have waited for Clemens to respond to big moments, in the way
David Wells responded before being traded for Clemens.
</P>
<P>
   But Clemens has been as maddeningly erratic as the subways, and
it appears as if he is officially on probation with fans at Yankee
Stadium, who booed Clemens Thursday night for the first time after
was knocked out and lost, 6-2, to the Tom Glavine and the Atlanta
Braves.
</P>
<P>
   Clemens (8-4) was charged with six runs on six hits and five
walks. Although questionable umpiring calls cost him a couple of
runs, he pitched far below his own standards. When Clemens is at
his best, he has great stuff and command, but once again, Clemens
lacked command. Of the 116 pitches he threw, only 63 were for
strikes.
</P>
<P>
   Wells has not had a good season with Toronto, either, and there
is probably not a member of the Yankees front office who would
second-guess the decision to swap the petulant Wells for a
five-time Cy Young Award winner dedicated to excellence.
</P>
<P>
   But Wells almost always pitched well in games particularly
important to the Yankees _ games against rivals, games against
contenders. Clemens has had two starts against Baltimore, two
against the Mets, three versus Texas, one each against Cleveland
and Boston, and Thursday night, he faced the Braves in what was
viewed as a possible World Series preview. Clemens' record in those
10 starts is 3-4, with a 7.33 ERA.
</P>
<P>
   His lack of control haunted him Thursday night. A two-out walk
in the first inning led to a run. He allowed back-to-back walks to
open the fifth inning, in which the Braves scored a run and assumed
a 4-1 lead. The five walks matched his season high.
</P>
<P>
   A day after the umpires announced their intention to resign
Sept. 2 as part of their labor battle with baseball, first base
umpire Jim Evans made two arguable calls that cost the Yankees one
run and led to another.
</P>
<P>
   Andruw Jones, the Braves' speedy center fielder, pulled a
two-out double to left off Clemens in the fourth inning. Randall
Simon then smacked a grounder up the middle, where second baseman
Chuck Knoblauch intercepted the ball and made an off-balance throw
to first base, the ball reaching Tino Martinez on a bounce. Clemens
pumped a fist, signaling for an out. Evans waved two hands, palms
down, parallel to the ground: Safe.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees, taken aback by Evans' call, reacted slowly after
realizing Jones had rounded third and was sprinting home. Martinez
hesitated ever-so-briefly before throwing home, and catcher Jorge
Posada was not in position to block the plate or to receive the
throw. In any event, Martinez's relay was too late.
</P>
<P>
   Joe Torre, the Yankees' manager, bounced out of the dugout and
questioned Evans. Replays appeared to show that Simon was out by a
half-step.
</P>
<P>
   The call probably would not have drawn so much attention if
Evans had not made another controversial one the next inning. With
Atlanta runners on first and second and nobody out, Chipper Jones
hit a grounder to the right field side of second base. Knoblauch
made a diving stop, flipped the ball to Derek Jeter for the
forceout and Jeter threw to first for an apparent double play. But
Evans ruled Jones safe at first, and Martinez and the other Yankee
infielders were incredulous.
</P>
<P>
   Torre argued, to no avail, and replays again indicated that the
call was wrong. Subsequently, Scott Brosius rushed to turn a
grounder to third into a double play and kicked the ball as another
Atlanta run crossed.
</P>
<P>
   But Evans' calls would not have mattered much if Clemens had
pitched more effectively. When Bret Boone singled sharply to start
the seventh, then Andruw Jones walked and Brian Jordan grounded a
hit through the left side, scoring Boone, Clemens was finished.
</P>
<P>
   As he handed the ball to Torre and walked off the mound, he was
met by booing from the crowd of 49,087 _ mild nastiness by Yankee
Stadium standards, but the first real booing Clemens has heard at
Yankee Stadium.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
