<SLUG> BC-MOON-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FIRST MOON LANDING MARKING 30TH ANNIVERSARY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By KERRY FEHR-SNYDER  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   (Undated) It's regarded as the defining moment of the century,
perhaps of all history.
</P>
<P>
   It's the moment human beings shucked their Earthbound destiny,
rocketed into the black vastness of the cosmos and set foot upon
another celestial body.
</P>
<P>
   The Apollo moon landing 30 years ago this Monday lasted just
under 22 hours. And although public fascination with space has
waned, it remains a technological feat that altered forever the way
humans view the universe and their place in it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Apollo changed the world. Anybody that doesn't understand that
doesn't have a clue,'' said James Schefter, a veteran space
reporter and author who covered the Apollo program.
</P>
<P>
   ``It changed how people think.''
</P>
<P>
   Landing on the moon altered how we viewed the Earth (fragile),
what America can do when it sets its mind to it (beat the
Russians), and where it ultimately sees itself headed (distant
planets).
</P>
<P>
   ``The really important thing is that it reminds us that, as a
species, we're explorers,'' Schefter said.
</P>
<P>
   ``From the earliest days as cavemen to the opening of the West,
we have always wanted to know what's over the next hill.''
</P>
<P>
   The Apollo 11 moonwalk mission was the outcome of the Cold War
challenge issued by President Kennedy in May 1961, four years after
the Russians launched Sputnik I.
</P>
<P>
   But it was by no means a fait accompli. It required coordination
by thousands of scientists and the creation of a host of new
technologies, including those that developed fire-retardant
clothing and heart-monitoring equipment now routinely used in
hospitals.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we were just going to prove America's technical
superiority, there's no question that we did that,'' said Claude
Canizares, director of the Center for Space Research at the
Massachusetts Institute of Technology.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was an unbelievable technical triumph to put people on the
moon.''
</P>
<P>
   Arizona played a significant role in the mission. The U.S.
Geological Survey, headed by the late Gene Shoemaker, trained these
and later astronauts in the new field of ``astrogeology'' at Meteor
Crater, a geological cousin to the moon, as well as at Sunset
Crater and the Grand Canyon.
</P>
<P>
   The USGS also helped map the moon and pick landing sites, and it
monitored the astronauts' geological work as they explored the Sea
of Tranquility.
</P>
<P>
   The University of Arizona's Lunar and Planetary Lab also helped
map geological sites, determine exactly where the astronauts were
and advise where to place various instruments and where to collect
lunar rock samples.
</P>
<P>
   At Arizona State University, a geologist analyzed moon rocks for
carbon content, a key ingredient for life. The samples were so
valuable that they were kept in a locked safe and checked nightly
by campus security.
</P>
<P>
   Private industry in Arizona was also involved. Motorola designed
and manufactured communications equipment, including the radio
``transponder'' Neil Armstrong used to speak his memorable ``one
giant step for mankind'' line.
</P>
<P>
   But the public's fascination with this unprecedented
breakthrough was short-lived. By the time Apollo 12 took off four
months later, considerably fewer Americans were watching. Interest
in manned spaceflight continued to wane until John Glenn's recent
return to space, and even that was considered a gimmick by many.
</P>
<P>
   ``After Apollo 11, the missions piled on, and the public lost
interest,'' MIT's Canizares said. ``It's like an Olympic athlete
winning a gold medal the first year out; what do you do after
that?''
</P>
<P>
   The loss in interest was reflected in the popular lament: ``If
they can send a man to the moon, why can't they (fill in the
blank)?''
</P>
<P>
   Some observers say NASA became a victim of its own success. In
an effort to bring space to the people, NASA may have made
spaceflight look too easy and, therefore, not worthy of the
public's short attention span.
</P>
<P>
   ``The American psyche, unfortunately, has gotten saturated with
the 24-hour news cycle,'' space reporter Schefter said. ``There's
always something new. It's hard to get excited for more than 15
minutes about anything.''
</P>
<P>
   It would take an outside threat, Schefter said, to rally support
for another manned space mission of Apollos' magnitude.
</P>
<P>
   Although a manned trip to Mars is on the horizon, experts say
the rocket-fuel technology needed to get there is still far away.
Without the pressure of the Cold War, such a mission is remote.
</P>
<P>
   Even if landing on Mars is attainable, there was something
uniquely American about the race to the moon. In 1969, the country
was torn apart by the Vietnam War, yet it rallied around the goal
of being first to the moon.
</P>
<P>
   And because Apollo 11 was mostly about flexing America's
technological muscles, science was secondary.
</P>
<P>
   ``Kennedy didn't say go to the moon for the sake of science,''
said Andrew Chaikin, author of ``A Man on the Moon,'' an account of
the Apollo program. ``He (wanted) to show the world that the free
(market) system is better than the communist way.''
</P>
<P>
   But by the time Kennedy spoke to Rice University students a
little more than a year after his 1961 challenge, Chaikin notes in
his book, ``Kennedy was already widening his view from simply a
Cold War chess move to something that would have great impact on a
number of fronts, including scientific fronts.''
</P>
<P>
   Chief among them was learning something about the makeup of the
moon, how it was formed and whether it eventually could be
colonized.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone knew that even if they (the astronauts) came back
with one bag of moon dirt, it would be priceless,'' Chaikin said.
``Even if they had just gotten out of the lander and scooped up
some dirt and gotten back, they would have made a huge advance in
the terms of science and astronomy.''
</P>
<P>
   But some scientists, including the prominent Flagstaff
astrogeologist Shoemaker, pushed for more. They wanted the
astronauts to venture farther from the lunar rover and to explore
the geology of the moon. But NASA was insistent that the astronauts
focus on getting to the moon and back.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was a lot of pressure to just accomplish the landing and
get back safely in front of the eyes of the world and not screw
up,'' Chaikin said.
</P>
<P>
   Although today marks the 30th anniversary of the launch, the
Apollo 11 moonwalk cannot be viewed in a vacuum. It was, of course,
preceded by the Mercury, Gemini and other Apollo missions, which
included both tragedy and triumph.
</P>
<P>
   The darkest hour came in 1967 when three astronauts were killed
in a fire on the launch pad during a training session for Apollo 1.
One of the brightest moments came with Apollo 8, which gave the
world the famous photographs of the Earth as a blue-and-white gem
rising beyond the moon in a sea of blackness on Christmas Eve 1968.
</P>
<P>
   Apollo 11 was followed by Missions 12 through 17. The
white-knuckle mission was Apollo 13, when a ruptured oxygen tank
crippled the astronauts' spacecraft.
</P>
<P>
   Taken together, the Apollo missions represented the highest
achievement of mankind's ingenuity only decades after it developed
atomic weapons.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the 20th century, human beings developed the means to
destroy themselves and the planet,'' Chaikin said. ``In the same
century, they also developed the means to leave their planet and
become immortal.''
</P>
<P>
   The irony isn't lost on Chaikin.
</P>
<P>
   ``Americans, in particular, believed that they could do
anything,'' he said. ``That's part of the nostalgia.
</P>
<P>
   ``But it's about a moment of human achievement, human evolution,
and that has to have philosophical, spiritual implications,'' he
added. ``To look at the moon and say, wow, people have walked
there.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
