<HEADLINE>
COX SLOWS INTERNET SERVICE TO THWART BUSINESS USERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By MAX JARMAN  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - Cox Communications has severely reduced the upload
speed of its high-speed Internet service in the Valley in an effort
to thwart the abuse of an estimated 1 percent of its subscribers.
</P>
<P>
   To prevent subscribers from using the $44.95-per-month service
to host pornographic Web sites and Web/mail servers, Cox has
slashed the upload speed of the product to 128 kilobits per second,
or kbps, from 3 to 5 megabits per second, or mbps.
</P>
<P>
   ``That makes it about eight times slower than before,'' Cox
sales manager Dennis Kienlen said.
</P>
<P>
   The download speed is unaffected and still runs 3 to 5 mbps, he
said.
</P>
<P>
   The company discovered the abuses during routine monitoring of
the network to make sure people aren't using the residential
service for business purposes, company spokesman Andy Horwitz said.
</P>
<P>
   He said that, although hosting pornography sites is not
permitted on either its residential or business systems, many of
the residential abuses, such as Web site hosting, is allowed with
the business service.
</P>
<P>
   ``These people think they can save $55 per month by signing up
for residential service and using it for business purposes,''
Horwitz said.
</P>
<P>
   Businesses pay over twice the residential fee, at least $100 per
month, for Cox(at)Work, which is essentially the same product,
Kienlen said.
</P>
<P>
   Cox officials say their company's monitoring of subscribers is
not an invasion of privacy because of contractual arrangements.
</P>
<P>
   Kienlen explained that when customers sign up for the service,
they agree to Cox's ``appropriate use'' policy, which prohibits
using the system for commercial purposes such as hosting Web sites
and servers.
</P>
<P>
   The policy gives Cox the authority to monitor the network for
violations.
</P>
<P>
   ``We scan the network looking for Internet protocol addresses
that have server ports open,'' Kienlen said. ``When we find one, we
log on and see what they are doing. If they are posting
inappropriate materials, it's pretty obvious.''
</P>
<P>
   Kienlen acknowledged the slowdown has angered some of the
service subscribers. But he noted that most of those people
affected by the change were abusing the system.
</P>
<P>
   ``They had a very inexpensive business connection,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Kienlen said that avid players of Internet computer games will
have their fun curtailed as a consequence of other users'
inappropriate behavior.
</P>
<P>
   Cox would not say how many people have signed up for the
Cox(at)Home service, but noted it will be available to 580,000
Phoenix-area homes by the end of the year.
</P>
<P>
   The company estimates that only about 1 percent of the
subscribers were abusing the service, but that their inappropriate
use was threatening to slow the entire network down.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were constantly working on the network to keep it moving at
an even level,'' Kienlen said.
</P>
<P>
   He said the pornography sites were particularly troublesome
because they upload pictures which takes up a lot of bandwidth on
the system.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you upload pictures, you're sending very large data files
that take up a lot of the system's capacity,'' he said. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
