</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-METS-DEVILRAYS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
METS DEFEAT DEVIL RAYS, 8-7 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 By JASON DIAMOS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ST. PETERSBURG, Fla. _ Armando Benitez, it turns out, is not the
perfect closer.
</P>
<P>
   The hard-throwing Benitez blew a save opportunity on Thursday
night for the first time in four outings since inheriting the
closer's role from the injured John Franco. But he got the victory
as the New York Mets edged the Tampa Bay Devil Rays, 8-7, in 10
innings.
</P>
<P>
   Benitez entered in the ninth inning with the Mets leading by
7-4, but squandered all of the lead, yielding two runs on Fred
McGriff's single and the tying run on a single by Bubba Trammell.
He then struck out Paul Sorrento on a full-count slider with the
winning run on third base.
</P>
<P>
   Roger Cedeno, who earlier had driven in a pair of runs in a
four-run seventh-inning rally, doubled home Benny Agbayani with the
tie-breaking run off Norm Charlton in the top of the 10th inning.
And then Benitez (1-2) redeemed himself by pitching a perfect 10th.
</P>
<P>
   ``I said to Bobby I want to go back out,'' Benitez said,
relaying what he told Manager Bobby Valentine after the ninth
inning. ``I said, `Don't take me out. If I have to lose, I have to
lose, but I want to win. I had to show I can come back when I make
a mistake.''
</P>
<P>
   ``He showed me a lot with that,'' Valentine said. ``It was
impressive.''
</P>
<P>
   For a while, it looked as if Matt Franco would be the Mets' hero
for the second time in the last three games. But Franco could also
have been the goat because of a baserunning gaffe.
</P>
<P>
   Representing the go-ahead run at second base in the seventh
inning of a sloppy contest that the Mets were trailing, 3-2, Franco
ran through the third-base coach Cookie Rojas' stop sign on
Cedeno's single to center.
</P>
<P>
   Cedeno's line drive easily scored Brian McRae from third with
the tying run. The slow-footed Franco was going to need a break to
score from second, however.
</P>
<P>
   When McGriff, the Tampa Bay first baseman, cut off center
fielder Randy Winn's off-line throw, Franco found himself in
no-man's land, halfway down the third-base line. But McGriff
inexplicably did not throw home from the left of the pitcher's
mound. And to complete the bizarre sequence, Franco slid home even
though Rickey Henderson was motioning for him to stand up, giving
Cedeno a gift run batted in and the Mets the lead in their
game-winning four-run rally.
</P>
<P>
   With the designated-hitter rule in effect in the American League
park, Franco, the Mets' No. 1 pinch-hitter, was being rewarded with
a rare start. He had provided the most dramatic moment of the
season's first half last Saturday at Shea Stadium when his
bases-loaded, two-out, two-strike, two-run single off Mariano
Rivera gave the Mets a wild 9-8 victory over the Yankees.
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday night, Franco went 0 for 1. But he walked twice and
scored both times. And the Mets (51-39) improved to a major
league-best 24-11 since June 6, the day they ended an eight-game
losing streak.
</P>
<P>
   In the seventh, McRae and Franco had both drawn full-count walks
off Esteban Yan to open the inning, before they were sacrificed to
second and third by Rey Ordonez. Cedeno followed with his two-run
single, the Mets' first hit in six at-bats with runners in scoring
position. Cedeno stole second, his second swipe of the game and
major-league leading 48th of the season. Henderson drew a walk
against Albie Lopez. Edgardo Alfonzo then singled in a run and John
Olerud hit a sacrifice fly to make it 7-3.
</P>
<P>
   Al Leiter rebounded from a shaky start and looked like a winner
until Benitez blew the save.
</P>
<P>
   The Tampa Bay right-hander Rolando Arrojo, who made his first
start since May 24, had struggled to a 2-5 record and a 7.32 earned
run average before going on the disabled list with shoulder
inflammation. But on Thursday night, the Cuban-born Arrojo
displayed the form that enabled him to win 14 games for an
expansion club last season and be selected to the American League
All-Star team.
</P>
<P>
   Arrojo allowed just a pair of bloop singles in his five-inning
outing. He left after 78 pitches with a 3-2 lead, both runs
unearned, as the Mets scored twice in the fifth without a hit.
</P>
<P>
   When Jose Canseco, who had 31 home runs, went on the disabled
list last week, deciding to have back surgery, it seemed that the
Devil Rays were going to have to find ways to score runs other than
via the home run.
</P>
<P>
   Not on Thursday night.
</P>
<P>
   Not with Leiter struggling with full-count pitches.
</P>
<P>
   Bubba Trammell deposited one of them over the left-field fence
leading off the second for a 1-0 Tampa Bay lead. And when Paul
Sorrento drilled a full-count offering off the right-field foul
pole, two batters after John Flaherty had walked on a 3-2 pitch to
open the fourth, the Devil Rays were up by 3-0.
</P>
<P>
   The Mets scratched back against Arrojo, who hurt his own cause
by walking two of the first three batters he faced in the fifth.
McGriff made a nice play at first, going down on his knee for the
second out to prevent a Franco grounder from scoring a run.
</P>
<P>
   Cedeno then beat what looked like a harmless grounder into the
Tropicana Field carpet. The former Mets infielder Aaron Ledesma
easily fielded the two-hopper in front of third, but
double-clutched and threw off the wrong foot. Cedeno beat the
throw, Robin Ventura scored from third and it was 3-1.
</P>
<P>
   With runners on first and third, Cedeno took off for second on a
2-0 pitch. Now it was the catcher Flaherty's turn for a gaffe.
Instead of conceding second to the fleet Cedeno, he rushed his
throw from behind the plate. It sailed to the right of second and
into the outfield. Franco scored, Cedeno scampered to third and it
was 3-2.
</P>
<P>
   Henderson, though, grounded out to leave Cedeno on third, and
Arrojo, in his first start in nearly two months, departed with the
lead.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
