<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-15 23:52 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2218 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-REUTERS-INQUIRY-NYT &LR;      07-15 0302
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-REUTERS-INQUIRY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REUTERS SAYS IT WON'T FACE FEDERAL CHARGES
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 By SHOLNN FREEMAN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Federal prosecutors will not charge Reuters Holdings
PLC with improperly obtaining information from a big competitor,
Bloomberg LP, Reuters said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   A federal grand jury in New York has been investigating the
relationship between a Reuters subsidiary, Reuters Analytics, and
Cyberspace Research Associates Inc., a New York company set up by a
former Bloomberg employee.
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors were looking into whether Cyberspace Research
assisted Reuters Analytics Inc. in obtaining information about
Bloomberg's operating code.
</P>
<P>
   Reuters said the U.S. attorney told the company that prosecutors
had closed the investigation. The U.S. attorney's office in
Manhattan declined to comment.
</P>
<P>
   At issue was the relationship between Reuters Analytics and
Cyberspace Research _ for example, whether it served as an
independent contractor or had a closer affiliation with the unit.
The government wanted to know whether Reuters Analytics
commissioned Cyberspace Research to steal Bloomberg data.
</P>
<P>
   Cyberspace Research, a Bloomberg customer, obtained the data
directly from a computer terminal Bloomberg distributes to its
clients. People close to the investigation have said prosecutors
obtained written communications between Reuters Analytics and
Cyberspace Research requesting that Cyberspace Research obtain
detailed information about technical programs, these people have
said.
</P>
<P>
   The data was passed to Reuters, these people said. Prosecutors
were said to have also obtained those responses. Turning the data
over to Reuters would have violated Cyberspace Research's agreement
with Bloomberg and could have constituted criminal fraud, lawyers
said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
