<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-NFL-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RIVAL GROUPS BACK NEW COLISEUM PLAN
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By STEVE DILBECK  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ The compromise Coliseum design-and-site plan has
been agreed upon by the two groups competing for an NFL franchise
and is scheduled to be revealed at a press conference July 23.
</P>
<P>
   Bill Chadwick _ whom Gov. Gray Davis asked last month to bring
the franchise rivals, Michael Ovitz/Ron Burkle and Eli Broad/Ed
Roski Jr., together _said Thursday he hopes to present the plan to
the various groups involved in the Exposition Park site over the
next week. Its public unveiling comes before the latest Coliseum
plans are presented to NFL owners in Chicago on July 28.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm sure I'll have a whole bunch of changes here and there
between now and the end of next week. I just hope they're not so
fundamental I have to go back to the drawing board,'' Chadwick
said. ``I mean, nobody is going to look at it and say, `Perfect,
Bill, you're wonderful.'
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody's got something. Everybody's got a different venue
to protect or interest to protect or vision of their own. It's not
like everybody in L.A. has the same dream. What we're trying to do
here is come up with something that works pretty well for
everybody.''
</P>
<P>
   Chadwick, a lawyer and investment banker, has quickly been able
to unify the separate stadium and site designs, though only one
group is ultimately expected to be selected the franchise owner.
</P>
<P>
   The latest Coliseum design is expected to be modeled more
closely to the Ovitz plan, which included a large multideck parking
garage with a park on top, but Chadwick would not reveal details on
the compromise.
</P>
<P>
   Chadwick returned Wednesday from two days of meetings with NFL
executives in New York, which included a video conference call that
previewed the new plans with the rival groups, league officials and
Carolina owner Jerry Richardson, co-chairman of the expansion
committee.
</P>
<P>
   A key area of concern for the NFL has been the parking around
the Coliseum. The league originally asked for 25,000 spaces, which
the Ovitz plan provided with five garages. The Broad proposal made
to owners in Atlanta last May called for one 7,000-space garage.
</P>
<P>
   Chadwick denied a report that the compromise parking plan
required 20,000 spaces, although the final design is expected to be
much closer to the Ovitz scheme.
</P>
<P>
   Still to be determined, however, is how the garages will be
financed. Davis has already voiced opposition to public funding,
although if Chadwick can demonstrate benefit to the various other
groups at the state-owned park, the league and prospective owners
are hopeful some public assistance can be justified.
</P>
<P>
   Chadwick said he is finalizing the unified plan's financing.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's my weekend piece,'' he said. ``I have a meeting (this)
afternoon with all my various financial consultants and advisors _
and I certainly have a lot of them _ to try and pull that
together.''
</P>
</TEXT>
